<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAXCUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BAD TAX CUTS INSIDE GOOD BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 12:
</P>
<P>
   Congress is trying to push through unfair, damaging tax
provisions by attaching them to two popular bills, one designed to
raise the minimum wage, the other to protect patients in managed
care. The bills have passed both Senate and House and are headed
for conference. None of the tax provisions deserve to survive.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the patients' bill of rights legislation for
managed-care plans, the Republicans attached a provision to create
a universal right to put tax-free money into medical savings
accounts. Individuals would first have to purchase a
high-deductible insurance policy that would cover medical bills
only after they exceed a large annual amount, say $3,000. The
tax-free medical savings account would cover the costs under
$3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Because the accounts are expected to appeal to people who can
afford to make large tax-free deposits, the provision amounts to a
large tax cut for wealthy savers. Worse, medical savings accounts
that are available to everyone would also hurt the chronically ill.
Catastrophic policies attract people who do not expect to run up
many medical bills and therefore can expect the money they deposit
into the medical savings accounts to accumulate on a tax-free
basis. But that leaves less healthy people to buy ordinary medical
insurance, driving up the premiums for such coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Similar problems afflict ill-designed tax provisions that were
attached to minimum-wage legislation. These would raise the amounts
that highly paid workers can put into tax-deductible pension
accounts, giving wealthy employees a big tax break.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bills, the maximum pension contribution would rise
from $30,000 to $40,000, a break that only the top tier of
executives could afford. The maximum payout from defined-benefit
plans upon retirement would rise from $135,000 to $160,000, another
break only the wealthy could tap. Current law permits companies to
provide tax-deductible pensions only if they extend comparable
percentage contributions to low-paid workers. But under the House
and Senate bills, these protections for low-income workers would be
weakened. Pension experts warn that the pension provisions taken in
their entirety could encourage companies to reduce the pension
payments they now make on behalf of low- and moderate-income
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The unfairness of the tax provisions would be reason enough to
reject them. The threat to insurance premiums and the pension
rights of low-paid workers makes them truly offensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
