<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO MAGIC LEFT IN STARS-OILERS SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Cary Grant would have put it, they've got to stop meeting
like this.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and the Edmonton Oilers have got to. They're no good
for one another.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, they break each other's heart. Invariably, one of
them walks away and sends the other one home.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't have to be this way this time, though. The Stars and
Oilers, it has been roundly reported, figured they were finished
with one another. Splitsville. Nothing was going to be left but the
memories, the frequent-flier miles and a few R-rated Ron Low
quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton thought its NHL playoff destiny rested in St. Louis.
The Blues have the league's most imposing record, but what the hey
_ at least they weren't the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, on the other hand, once seemed resigned to the fact
that they would open their Stanley Cup playoff defense against the
worrisome San Jose Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Call it destiny. Call them cousins. Call me when it's over.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, there could have been more electric first-round
matchups. The typical Stars fan has only a vague recollection that
Edmonton was once the epicenter of the NHL universe. They have no
idea how passionate the kind people of Edmonton are about their
Oilers. They've never seen the giant banners _ the young Wayne
Gretzky, two stories tall _ hanging from the Edmonton rafters.
</P>
<P>
   The one flashpoint that could have really ignited the rivalry _
Bryan Marchment, the cowardly thug _ was traded away.
</P>
<P>
   You call this electricity? For the four meetings between the
teams this season, the Stars totaled nine goals and the Oilers
scored six, which means the average score was something like 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Just as a reminder, we're talking hockey here, not curling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our hockey club comes out and plays the way we can play,''
said Oilers winger Todd Marchant, ``we're capable of beating the
Dallas Stars, and I think they know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, whatever, but few teams over the past two postseasons have
been able to come out and dictate the script against coach Ken
Hitchcock's Stars. On the contrary, it's been the defending champs
who have shown a penchant for dragging the game down to their
level.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose would have confronted the Stars with somewhat younger
legs, combined with conspicuously less conscience. It loomed as a
much more physical series. And there would have been that
Marchment, watch-your-kneecaps factor.
</P>
<P>
   But lest anyone from Edmonton think that the Stars had written
them off, consider that general manager Bob Gainey himself scouted
the Oilers during the season's final week.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw was apparently a desperate hockey team, trying to
salvage a roller-coaster season, forced to earn its playoff ticket
on the road. The Oilers did so by winning a 5-4 overtime crapshoot
in Vancouver, knocking the Canucks out.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most confident I've felt in the time I've been in
Edmonton,'' center and team leader Doug Weight said. ``I feel
really confident with our game plan, with the coaching and with the
guys we're putting on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to give Dallas a good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there is some history here. Since Marchant muted the
Reunion Arena crowd with his series-deciding overtime goal three
years ago, the Oilers have beaten the Stars exactly two of 21
times.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton goaltender Tommy Salo, moreover, is 0-7-1 lifetime
against the Stars and a dank 0-4 against them in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if it comes down to the goalies _ and don't all NHL
playoff series, sooner or later, come down to the goalies? _ the
Stars and Ed Belfour figure to have a significant edge. Weight
dismissed that yesterday by suggesting that it was the other 18
guys who are going to have to outplay Belfour, not Salo.
</P>
<P>
   Well, whatever, but there is a feeling here that under new coach
Kevin Lowe and with their pulse-rousing finish, the Oilers might
have peaked emotionally one weekend too soon. The Stars, on the
other hand, have been waiting for this night, this first night of
the postseason, since October.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it looked as if it would never get here. How fitting
that the Oilers, who indirectly launched last year's magical Stars
run, are back to audition for the role again.
</P>
<P>
   You guys have got to stop meeting like this. Really.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
