<HEADER>
A4216 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-SEQUEL-TEX     04-12 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SEQUEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Stars need Stanley Cup sequel equal to last year's production 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Yes, critics and audiences alike raved over the Stars'
first Stanley Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Everything fans could possibly want, Dallas' 23-game, eight-week
playoff pursuit of Lord Stanley's Cup provided. Action. Emotion.
Suspense. Controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, from the same people who brought you The Cup, comes The Cup
2: Return to Paradise. Bigger. Better. Bolder. And Uncut.
</P>
<P>
   And it's opening Wednesday at an arena near you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big fan of sequels,'' Stars leading man Joe
Nieuwendyk admitted. ``Do you ever think sequels are as good as the
original? Neither do I.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has Caddyshack II. Hockey has the 1996 New Jersey
Devils. Both sequels bombed.
</P>
<P>
   Seems creating a sequel worthy of the original is more difficult
than finding redeeming value in ``Major League II'' If Hollywood
finds it hard to produce a good sequel, imagine sports guys trying
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say a good sequel can't be done.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 Pittsburgh Penguins did it. So did the 1998 Detroit Red
Wings. Hey, lots of folks say ``The Godfather II'' was better than
``The Godfather''. So, it has been done. But, there are rules. It's
the Stars job to observe the rules of the sports sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1 _ The expectations are bigger, way bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock opened a door for a sequel in June
when he stood before a packed Reunion Arena crowd, Cup in tow,
saying: ``As long as we got one of these, why not make it two.
Hell, let's make it three.''
</P>
<P>
   Roll credits. End of season. Audience eagerly anticipates No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   So, for two short vacation months and one interminable regular
season, they waited for tonight. The premiere.
</P>
<P>
   While the original was about finally shaking the specter of
never having won a Stanley Cup, the sequel is about surviving the
expectations created when they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, you don't have: `You haven't done this or you
only got this far or you only did this,' '' Hitchcock said. ``We're
only carrying the expectations of wanting to win again.''
</P>
<P>
   Only trailers from this season have teased to a Stars bunch
riddled with injuries, steadied by sheer will, besieged by slumps
only to be buoyed by play from Derian Hatcher, Ed Belfour and Mike
Modano.
</P>
<P>
   And reviews have been equally mixed. Based on the regular-season
trailer, the Stars certainly aren't the favorite to do it again.
St. Louis, Detroit and Colorado all grabbed critics and audiences
attention _ the Blues by winning the Presidents' Trophy, the Red
Wings by being themselves and the Avalanche by bringing in
defenseman Ray Bourque and his power-play prowess from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly seems like we're not the favorite again this year
to win it,'' Stars forward Guy Carbonneau said. ``What we have to
guard against is \Rthe idea that\S because it went well last year,
we just have to show up and do it again. We have to start at
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Only their hard core audience expects the heroes to pick up
where they left off. You see the problem with the sequel isn't that
it isn't as good, but instead that it has something to be compared
to.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams in the last 12 seasons have been able to make a
sequel as good as the original.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars felt a Stanley-Cup-or-bust pressure last season
because of a Presidents' Trophy, home-ice advantage and signees
such as Brett Hull. They delivered. Now, they have to make a second
one as good as the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``However difficult it is, however successful it is,'' Stars
general manager Bob Gainey said, it will be different than last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 2 _ The games are always much more elaborate, much more
intense, with longer overtimes and more scoring. Your core audience
expects it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hull scored his Cup-clinching goal in not the first, not the
second but the third overtime in Game 6. Don't be surprised if it
takes them four overtimes and a Game 7 this time.
</P>
<P>
   Ask anybody who has actually been in a sports sequel, and
they'll tell you the second one is much harder to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the playoffs start, you are the favorite,'' Red Wings
defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom said. ``I found it pretty tough that
second time around, when the playoffs started. Once the playoffs
started, you knew that you were nearing the end of the line towards
winning the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we got past that first round, you're just eager to get
going and win some more.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the plot thickens right there. The Western Conference
lends itself to more elaborate scenes because there are so many
tough teams with not a lot separating them.
</P>
<P>
   The villain standing in the way of the Stars as they try to get
out of the first round is a familiar one, the Edmonton Oilers. The
Stars and Oilers have met in the playoffs for four consecutive
years, three of those meetings coming in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   And it only gets harder. The Stars have a likely second-round
date with Colorado. If the Stars get past the Avalanche, the Blues
or Red Wings are likely to be waiting in the Western Conference
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, there is two teams on one side better than any one team
on the other side,'' San Jose coach Darryl Sutter said. ``Dallas
and Detroit are two great hockey clubs, and, unfortunately, one is
not going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 3 _ If you want your sequel to be a franchise, never, ever
repeat the same story. You have to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Failure to comply is why most sequels aren't as good as the
originals, Stars winger Grant Marshall says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the excitement of the original,'' he said. ``Whenever you
see the sequel, you are going to get the same thing but different.
The first ``Austin Powers'' was awesome. No. 2 was great, but you
know it's the same comedy, same drama.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars can't expect anything to happen exactly like it did in
the original.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk isn't likely to score 11 goals. He could score less.
He could score more. Belfour isn't likely to have a personal-best
1.67 goals-against average. He could go lower. He could go higher.
</P>
<P>
   No, the feat of repeating isn't for your Nick-at-Night rerun
types.
</P>
<P>
   The repeaters need to break some new ground.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, Nieuwendyk and Belfour carrying the team to a Cup?
Forget it. That's been done.
</P>
<P>
   Who else do they have?
</P>
<P>
   The cast has grown to include a promising rookie, Brenden
Morrow, a winger in need of a second chance, Scott Thornton, and a
winger desperately craving another chance at a Cup, Kirk Muller.
They join audience favorites such as Nieuwendyk and Hull and Modano
and Belfour and Hatcher and ...
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, we've got a hell of a team,'' Morrow said. ``We're
going to make a good sequel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 4 _ Be sure to have a
``This-could-be-the-start-of-a-beautiful-friendship''-like
ending.''
</P>
<P>
   ``''Empire Strikes Back,'''' Stars captain Derian Hatcher
responded when asked to name a sequel that surpassed an original.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't worry about making it better,'' Hatcher continued.
``What's the difference, if you win? It should be just as good if
you win.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
