<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PLAYERS IRKED BY YANKEES' EARLY DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Outfielder Gabe Kapler walked into the Rangers'
clubhouse here yesterday and said aloud what was on most of his
teammates' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have played today, real easy,'' Kapler said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't play yesterday because of the New York
Yankees' decision on Monday to postpone their home opener until
today. The Yankees were concerned about weather forecasts that
called for a 90 percent chance of rain and possible snow.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers weren't happy that the decision to postpone the game
was made Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is you should at least wait and see if it rains,''
pitcher Rick Helling said. ``I've never been a big fan of calling
it just because you think it's going to rain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' ire was reinforced when] it didn't rain much in the
Bronx yesterday. At game time _ 12:05 p.m. _ there was light rain
falling, but it stopped within minutes and never picked up again.
The temperature was in the 40s but with no wind. The Rangers'
pitchers were able to do their daily throwing in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was premature that they \Rcalled\S the game 18-22 hours
before, basing it all on a forecast,'' pitcher Tim Crabtree said.
``They could have easily waited until this morning to call it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree, the Rangers' player representative, said the Players
Association tried on Monday to convince Yankees owner George
Steinbrenner to wait until yesterday before making a decision. But,
according to Crabtree, Steinbrenner told the union he was concerned
about fans traveling to the game in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why weather is a concern,'' Crabtree said.
``People have to travel to the Bronx every night. They should be
more concerned about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody was upset. Rangers manager Johnny Oates defended
Steinbrenner's decision to call the game early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough decision and somebody's got to make it,'' Oates
said. ``Some of us can't second-guess, we have to make decisions
beforehand. It's easy to say we could have played. Whether it's
just or not, the guy had to make a tough decision \R Monday\S.
You've got to make the call. You should have been in his shoes
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will be made up when the Rangers return to New York in
August. The Rangers and the Yankees have a day off on Monday, Aug.
21, before beginning a three-game series on Aug. 22. But the
Rangers must vote to approve playing on Aug. 21, because it would
mean they would have a stretch of 31 games without a day off. That
goes against the labor contract.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree said his recommendation would be to play a day-night
doubleheader on Aug. 22. Oates, who hates doubleheaders, wants to
play on the day off. The Yankees players, who would be returning
from a West Coast road trip, also must approve playing on August
21, and the issue was undecided yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro, however, said it will be better for the Rangers
playing an extra game in August rather than yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not, the weather will be nicer,'' Palmeiro said. ``The
weather will be nice and the team will be rolling by then. I think
it will be a positive for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The postponement prompted both managers to adjust their
rotations. Darren Oliver (today) and Kenny Rogers (tomorrow) are
scheduled to pitch for the Rangers. Esteban Loaiza, who had a touch
of the flu over the weekend, has been pushed back to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are planning to go with David Cone today and Orlando
Hernandez tomorrow. Andy Pettitte, originally scheduled to pitch
today, has been pushed back because of a bad back.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
