<HEADLINE>
USC VS. BOSTON COLLEGE A POSSIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC is talking to Boston College about a proposed
home-and-home series for the 2001 and 2002 football seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have been looking for an opponent to fill two open
dates, and Kansas recently was unable to reach an agreement. USC
had also tried to schedule Kansas State, before Wildcats coach Bill
Snyder killed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Virginia backed out of a home-and-home agreement. USC
would like to play Boston College at the Coliseum on Sept. 12,
2001, and travel to Boston College on Sept. 19, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary shuffle: There's almost no way to tell who is starting
at safety for the Trojans, especially the free-safety position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have (a starter),'' secondary coach Dennis Thurman
said. ``If we had to start the season today, I don't know who it
would be.''
</P>
<P>
   The free safeties are Ife Ohalete, Kevin Arbet and Frank Strong.
DeShaun Hill, who played safety in last Saturday's scrimmage, is
moving to cornerback. At strong safety, the candidates are Ohalete,
Troy Polamalu and incoming freshman Matt Grootegoed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first game, don't be surprised if we have two totally
different units out there,'' Thurman said.
</P>
<P>
   One decision has been made in the secondary. Kris Richard will
remain at cornerback. There was some debate about moving him to
free safety, but he will not have to make a position switch.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan out: Reserve free safety John Morgan suffered what is
believed to be a season-ending knee injury during Saturday's
scrimmage. Results of a magnetic-resonance imaging test should be
known by today.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly could run: Wide receiver Kareem Kelly, who is academically
ineligible for the remainder of spring practices, might run track
and compete in the Pac-10 and NCAA championships, because USC's
spring semester ends before those events take place.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker John Cousins is not ineligible but has missed more
than a week to concentrate on academics. He might return before
spring practice concludes Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 0010EDT &QL; 
