<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON GETS LONG-AWAITED CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM - Put yourself in the shoes of Angels' infielder Keith
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has played in 816 games in eight different cities
without ever receiving a promotion to a major league club.
</P>
<P>
   So after sitting out both ends of a Triple-A doubleheader in
Edmonton on Monday, Johnson picked up his ringing hotel room phone.
It was the call that all minor leaguers dream about, his call to
the big club.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson answered the phone, coupled with the fact he was a
non-performer in two games earlier that day, one might understand
his hesitation to believe the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me 10 minutes to believe what they were saying,'' said
Johnson, who will turn 29 next week. ``It's funny. I was watching
Monday's game on television and I didn't even know (shortstop Gary)
DiSarcina was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who spent seven years in the Dodgers' organization
before playing in the Arizona Diamondbacks system last season,
moved up when DiSarcina was placed on the disabled list with a
thumb injury.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia, familiar with the former Dodger
farmhand during his days as a coach in the organization, says
Johnson can play four positions, if need be - shortstop, second
base, third base, and left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a guy that fills a need right now,'' Scioscia said. ``We
needed a guy with experience playing shortstop. (And) everybody in
the organization was very confident that Keith was the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Between Double-A and Triple-A last season, Johnson hit .289 with
15 home runs and 61 in 124 games.
</P>
<P>
   While Toronto manager Jim Fregosi's name is quite familiar with
Angels' fans, so too are a number of his coaches. Longtime Angels'
base coach Bobby Knoop is coaching first base with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Three former big league managers - Terry Bevington (Chicago
White Sox), Cito Gaston (the Jays' most successful manager in team
history) and Lee Elia (Chicago Cubs), also make up part of
Fregosi's staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels close out their season-opening nine-game homestand
tonight when they take on the Blue Jays in the third game of the
series. Anaheim has gotten off to a decent start against the three
Eastern Division teams that have come through town (New York and
Boston being the other two). The Angels were 20-36 versus the East
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Was it that long ago?: Ten years ago Tuesday, Mark Langston and
Mike Witt combined to pitch a no-hitter against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's pitching matchup: The Angels will throw right-hander
Jason Dickson (1-0, 2.70 ERA) while Toronto will send out veteran
righty Frank Castillo (0-1, 15.00).
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS vs. TORONTO
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 p.m., Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: No TV; KLAC-AM (570), XPRS-AM (1090)
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Right-hander Jason Dickson (1-0, 2.70 ERA) looks to
make his second consecutive solid start for the Angels. Toronto
will counter with right-hander Frank Castillo (0-1, 15.00). The
Angels entered Tuesday's game with their starting pitchers
(Dickson, Ken Hill, Kent Bottenfield, and Scott Schoeneweis)
leading the majors in earned-run average (3.02) and opponent
batting average (.210, 33 for 157). As a staff, Anaheim's ERA of
3.86 ranks No.4 in the majors and second in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   -Frank Welch
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
