<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-BULLS-NYT &LR;      04-12 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS DEFEAT NEWS, 100-93 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman have
been gone for two seasons. Even Toni Kukoc has left the building.
No one of consequence from the Chicago Bulls' glorious championship
run continues to play home games at the United Center. Yet the New
Jersey Nets still cannot win here.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls defeated their downtrodden guests by 100-93. It was
the Nets' 12th straight loss at the United Center, where they
haven't won since Dec. 5, 1994, the night they played their first
game at the six-year-old arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets (31-47) also equaled their season high for consecutive
losses at seven. With Stephon Marbury, Kerry Kittles and Evan
Eschmeyer _ none of whom played on Tuesday night _ likely to miss
the rest of the season, the lifeless Nets could easily lose their
final four games.
</P>
<P>
   Such a finish would give the Nets a 2-14 record over the last
month of the season and place pathetic bookends on a season that
began with only two victories in the first 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll get back on the winning track sooner or later,''
said Kendall Gill, who scored 19 points. ``And it better be sooner
because we only have four games left.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, whose lone standout player is Elton Brand (22 points,
15 rebounds, 7 assists, rookie of the year candidate), did not just
beat the Nets. They put on a performance for their
highlight-starved fans.
</P>
<P>
   In scoring 17 points, the former Net Chris Carr mimicked Jordan
by throwing down a thunderous windmill dunk over Keith Van Horn (15
points, 10 rebounds) and ferociously swatting a shot by Gill. A
character named Michael Ruffin, a rookie out of Tulsa, skied above
a collection of Nets to slam in a Bulls miss, and Matt Maloney (19
points) hit 3-pointers (5 of 6) as if he were shooting alone in his
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Defying its ignominious 17-60 record, Chicago, which outscored
the Nets by 57-45 over the second and third quarters to take
control, won the season series by 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   While Marbury and Kittles, who both will be examined by doctors
on Wednesday, could perhaps help the Nets grind out at least one
more victory, neither seems likely to return. Kittles (sore right
knee) was vague about his plans, but Marbury said he was probably
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I doubt if I come back,'' said Marbury, who sat
out their fourth straight game with tendinitis in his left knee.
``I'm just trying to get my knee healthy. The doctors have told me
that it's best to stay off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a magnetic resonance imaging exam last Thursday,
Marbury was told that he might be able to play in a week. That
would have enabled him to compete in the last three games of the
season. With Marbury's intense drive to play in as many games as
possible, it seemed likely that he would fight off anyone who might
try to keep him out of Friday's home game against Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets officials, none of whom want Marbury risk another
injury, have gotten their star point guard to consider his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the organization wants me to stay off of it,''
said Marbury, who averaged 22.2 points and 8.4 assists this season.
``I don't want to say it's not worth it because we're out of the
playoffs because it's always worth it to play basketball. But the
people in our organization know that next year is more important.
It makes me feel real good to know that they care about me for next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of too many performances like Tuesday night's, next year
is all that matters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
