<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-WALK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITYWALK NEW LOOK ROCKS TO L.A. BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As if Universal CityWalk _ a virtual downtown
within an artificial city _ needed any more reality distortions.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty new venues open Thursday with such mind-bending
attractions as a virtual reality NASCAR speedway and a virtual
bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new attractions in CityWalk's second phase in a
sense distill the L.A. experience into its highlights: a Latin
dance club and surf-clothing shop; a skateboarding half-pipe and a
sci-fi movie memorabilia shop; a Mexican-food joint and a Tommy's
Hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   CityWalk architect Jon Jerde said he sees it as a model for
reviving downtowns in Los Angeles and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``CityWalk has become globally famous. We work all over the
globe and everywhere we go, people say, Let's CityWalk the place,''
Jerde said. ``People use it as a verb, which means bringing
vitality, light and excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new venues have opened already, and on Tuesday
tourists and locals strolled around gaping at the new sights and
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outstanding area. I think this thing is going to be
packed,'' said John Rice, 45, a firefighter visiting from
Oceanside, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 10 million people visit the Universal Studios/CityWalk
complex every year, and officials expect that number to shoot up
with the expansion, plus the June opening of the Red Line subway in
North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're offering what is arguably the best full-day
entertainment experience in Southern California,'' boasted
Universal Studios Hollywood President Larry Kurzweil.
</P>
<P>
   Since CityWalk opened in 1993, it has not only complemented the
studio theme park, but filled a need for pedestrian-oriented
entertainment districts in a car-crazy city.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jerde, downtown Los Angeles especially is in need
of a pedestrian-oriented retail/restaurant zone and he has begun
talking to developers within the last month with that goal in mind.
</P>
<P>
   CityWalk's 93,000-square-foot expansion includes more than a
dozen new eateries, including a quick-service food court with menus
distilled from full-service restaurants throughout Los Angeles.
Jerry's Famous Deli and the Gaucho Grill, both full-service
restaurants in the San Fernando Valley, are opening quick-bite
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other venues are: the Rumba Room, a Latin dance club
with live salsa, merengue and Latin jazz; The Wound &AMP; Wound Toy
Co., featuring wind-up toys; Buca di Beppo Italian restaurant; Cafe
Tu Tu Tango, a Barcelona-style tapas bar; and a six-story IMAX
movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   Jillian's Hi Life Lanes features a virtual bowling game called
Hyperbowl, which involves 10-foot-high video screens projecting
city scenes, such as a futuristic San Francisco. Using a stationary
bowling ball set up like a computer track ball, the player has to
maneuver the virtual ball around the city, dodging street cars,
pedestrians and then struggling uphill to knock down pins at the
end of the street.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs at Jillian's, a real bowling alley features a nightclub
atmosphere with glow-in-the-dark balls and huge screens showing
music videos.
</P>
<P>
   Another CityWalk addition is a series of uniquely L.A.
billboards commissioned from local artists. One tongue-in-cheek
piece titled ``L.A. Angst'' depicts a comic strip-drawn woman
crying on a man's shoulder and exclaiming: ``Oh Andy ... The hot
tub overflowed and ruined my cell phone. Then the cappuccino maker
exploded and the top on the convertible is stuck shut ... Again!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
