<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-LINEBACKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEBACKER FROM BYU PLAYS, LIVES AT FULL THROTTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brigham Young linebacker Rob Morris plays the game of life with
the same reckless abandon that he plays the game of football.
Morris has jumped out of a fifth-floor apartment into a swimming
pool, eaten out of a dog dish, done some car surfing, had his
picture taken with an alligator and painted his toenails.
</P>
<P>
   Has Morris had one too many blows to the head?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't go so far as to say I'm crazy,'' he said. ``Maybe a
little free-spirited. I just enjoy having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, the NFL draft's top-rated inside linebacker, is a
throwback. His dogs are named Butkus and Bronko. His nickname is
``Freight Train.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A reporter asked me once what it was like hitting a
quarterback,'' Morris said. ``I said it was like a freight train
hitting a Yugo. They took off with that. Made all these
train-whistle sounds. I can't get rid of it. I like it. Freight
train is an old, reliable thing. It hits hard. Nobody wants to get
hit by a freight train.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, an Eagle Scout, spent 1994 and '95 on a Mormon mission
in Toronto. He redshirted in '96 before posting 333 tackles, 341/2
tackles for losses, one interception and 13 sacks over the past
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He will be a 25-year-old NFL rookie, but he doesn't promise to
grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who watches tapes of Chuck Bednarik, Sam Huff, Ray
Nitschke and Dick Butkus, plays the game like the alligator that
almost tamed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a slugger,'' Morris said. ``I pride myself on being the
old school-type linebacker. I've been known to snort and growl. If
you're a middle linebacker and you don't have some blood on your
elbows and snot running down your face, you're not a true middle
linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tait, a former BYU lineman who was a first-round choice of
the Kansas City Chiefs last season, enticed Morris to get within
four feet of the 7-foot alligator for a picture. Morris escaped
without becoming gator bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was misinformed about alligators, about how fast they could
travel on land,'' Morris said. ``When I finally found out the
truth, well, I guess it wasn't a smart decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who has been compared to his role model, Chris Spielman,
is rumored to bite the heads off chickens, too. He is an urban
legend before his pro career has started.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Linebackers Name School Height Weight 40 time Comment
1. LaVar Arrington Penn State 6-3 250 4.50 The next Lawrence
Taylor? 2. Brian Urlacher New Mexico 6-31/2 255 4.52 An athletic
two-way player for Lobos. 3. Rob Morris BYU 6-11/2 250 4.68 Mature
25-year-old rookie. 4. Keith Bulluck Syracuse 6-3 244 4.47 Former
safety can play MLB/OLB. 5. Julian Peterson Michigan State 6-3 235
4.60 Can he learn a pro defense? \Nsubheds:Sleeper Dhani Jones
Michigan 6-1 238 4.60 Always where he's supposed to be.
\Nsubheds:Stock falling Na'il Diggs Ohio State 6-31/2 231 4.55
Up-and-down '99 season casts doubts. \Nsubheds:Texas ties Antonio
