<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX BOOM LEFT INDIGENT IN ITS DUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On one side rises the shiny new cityscape of downtown Phoenix's
rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   On the other looms the lustrous copper dome of the Arizona State
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   In between _ squeezed ever smaller _ squats a dirty little
corner of hell.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly compressed mixture of mentally ill homeless and
criminal predators has turned the area between Seventh and 15th
avenues, Harrison to Jefferson streets into a ghetto of misery and
violence, city officials and homeless advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is so bad that Phoenix Police Chief Harold Hurtt
has urged the city to rectify ``years of neglect'' that have
allowed the area to slide into ``unchallenged disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   In a memo written last week, Hurtt recommended that his officers
step up their presence in the area to protect the homeless and
arrest those preying upon them.
</P>
<P>
   He and others say the crisis _ brewing for decades _ represents
the grim downside of Phoenix's celebrated renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a crisis in that area, but it's coming should be no
surprise,'' said Louisa Stark of the non-profit Community Housing
Partnership. ``Not so long ago, a lot of mentally ill people were
living in old hotels in the downtown,'' she said. ``Then we tore
them down for revitalization. The result was people lost their
housing and were pushed into the area where they are now.''
</P>
<P>
   An area that's evolved from merely seedy to downright dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criminal element within the homeless population has taken
over the area, (which has) become a drug marketplace with high
criminal activity and neighborhood blight,'' Hurtt wrote in a
council report. ``Users from all over the city come to this area to
buy and sell illegal drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Negrete heartily agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real dangerous down here now, worse than before, since
everybody is all cracked-out,'' said Negrete, who with friend,
Arthur Magana, live there and collect cans and discarded clothing
in the neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of mean, mean drug dealers, and the crazy people getting
ripped off and beat up and their disability money stolen from
them,'' he said. ``Bad. Bad.''
</P>
<P>
   About 400 people call the Central Area Shelter Services building
at 12th Avenue and Madison Street home. Another estimated 450 sleep
in nearby vacant lots and streets. &QL; 
_Changing nature of population More than half of them suffer from
mental problems, estimates CASS Director Mark Halloran.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of jobs out there now, and most of the homeless
who had the capacity to work are working,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's left are some very seriously ill people. And we have
about 900 of them right here.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Vincent de Paul Society serves a hot lunch to hundreds
of homeless people a block from CASS. Spokesman John Feit agreed
that ``well over half, maybe 70 percent of these folks, have mental
health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many can't fend for themselves,'' Feit said. ``Most are in
pitiful shape. Hundreds need help and few are getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the area's homeless are people who were _ or would have
been _ treated in hospitals or other residential settings, Halloran
said. But court decisions and state laws have forced the nation's
mental hospitals to discharge many patients and admit far fewer
than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The CASS shelter, and the area around it, ``is being used as an
area to contain the mentally ill,'' Halloran said. ``The state
doesn't have the money, they say, to help these people.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, lawmakers and Gov. Jane Hull agreed to fund a new
mental hospital at 24th and Roosevelt streets. On the other hand,
state Sen. Sue Grace, R-north Phoenix, introduced a bill to
increase mental health spending by $33 million, but the bill is
stalled in the House. &QL; 
_Signs of progress? The shuffling of the indigent west of Central
Avenue began in the 1970s, when the old downtown ``Deuce'' area was
demolished and replaced by Phoenix Civic Plaza and Patriots Square.
With the Deuce went the many old hotels where the poor could stay
for as little as $1.50 a night.
</P>
<P>
   As downtown redevelopment progressed, the homeless have been
pushed westward from the downtown core and into a smaller and
smaller area. With the coming completion of Phoenix City Court at
Fifth Avenue, and the new federal court building at Sixth Avenue,
Seventh Avenue has become the line between downtown on the east and
the homeless area on the west.
</P>
<P>
   The State Capitol at 17th Avenue and government buildings that
extend to 15th Avenue mark the western boundary for the homeless, a
boundary bolstered by residential redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtt said special training will be given to officers who soon
will conduct stepped-up patrols in the area. Drug dealers and
muggers will be targeted, he said. But the mentally ill ``will be
another story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many mentally ill people to deal with, arrests can't
be the only answer,'' Hurtt said.
</P>
<P>
   Commander Emmett Quill of the South Mountain Precinct said
psychiatrist Glenn Lippman will train officers to assess people
with behavioral health problems. Quill said plans now call for
space being made available in a state mental health facility for
people involved in incidents in the area who also seem to be
suffering from mental problems.
</P>
<P>
   People who live and work in the area say they applaud police
efforts, but doubt anything short of drastic action will solve the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Bosse, president of the Capitol Mall Association, a
non-profit group revitalizing that area, agreed: ``There are
hundreds of hard-core mentally ill people in those few blocks,''
she said. ``Until they are dealt with, the problem won't be
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurtt expressed no illusions that his officers alone could solve
it. ``When we are judged in the future on how we took care of the
weak and helpless among us,'' he said, ``I'm afraid that judgment
will be a harsh one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
