<SLUG> BC-BKN-CUBAN-MAVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA APPROVES CUBAN AS MAVERICKS OWNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Cuban arrived for his anointing as the
Mavericks' new owner dressed in black slacks, a black pullover
shirt, a black belt, black shoes, black socks, and a black leather
jacket adorned with the Mavericks logo. In essence, Mark Cuban was
being Mark Cuban _ nothing pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   After his bid to purchase a majority interest in the Mavericks
was approved yesterday by the NBA Board of Governors, Cuban said
his first order of business was to ``take a nap.'' He was fatigued
from dealing with lawyers and the sale transfer. He also made plans
to watch last night's Portland-Mavericks game on TV in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Today it's back to work for the man determined to turn the
Mavericks into a winner, and there's much work to be done. The
Mavericks have missed the playoffs for 10 consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone \R26-18\S since I first met the players,'' Cuban
said. ``Now the goal, the challenge, is to take that farther and
make sure that everybody realizes that we're a playoff team, and
work with the players to get them excited about working on their
skills and their game over the summer so we can hit the ground
running'' next season.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban has invigorated the Mavericks since signing a letter of
intent Jan. 3 to purchase controlling interest in the franchise
from Ross Perot Jr. for an NBA-record $280 million. He has created
a new buzz around the team, and also higher expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz has also hit the NBA, which is counting on Cuban and
his Internet connections to help a league with a $2.64 billion
television contract reach new revenue heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be proactive. And I don't think I've met anyone
who's more proactive than Mark, and that's very good,'' NBA
commissioner David Stern said. ``And he's going to stub his toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's better than just sort of sitting back and sort of
accepting status quo if you think you can make improvements. I
think that's what the fans want, and I think that's what we're
looking for from Mark now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban might have stubbed his toe by signing Dennis Rodman in
February, when the Mavericks appeared ready to make playoff run.
Cuban also acknowledged, when he released the 38-year-old power
forward March 9, that signing Rodman might have been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Cuban's efforts to improve the team earned the
admiration of players and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's high maintenance but good, and I mean that sincerely. He
is in a class by himself, but that's good,'' Stern said. ``He's
young and enthusiastic. I think it's terrific. I think the owners
are looking forward to that kind of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the moves Cuban has made since taking over operations
from Perot, Cuban said he still held back. Now he plans to throw
his full energy and resources into reshaping the franchise,
starting with the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are approximately $6 million over the projected
salary cap for next season, which handcuffs Cuban in signing free
agents this summer. But Cuban said some owners don't want to pay
the NBA's new escrow tax, which kicks in if the average league
salary is over the tax threshold. Unlike some owners, the
Mavericks' billionaire owner said he wouldn't be discouraged from
signing a premier free agent to a big contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those \Rtaxes\S will have an impact on player decisions for
some organizations,'' Cuban said. ``So we'll try to take advantage
of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be really, really interesting to see how all of
the dynamics play out with the salary cap. We're going to be as
opportunistic as we possibly can be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks also will have a lottery draft pick, assuming
coach/general manager Don Nelson doesn't trade it.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said yesterday he plans to hire a new coach. He wants
Nelson to return as general manager, and Nelson has said this will
be his final season as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban also said he's ``thrilled with the job'' by Terdema
Ussery, the Mavericks' president and chief executive officer, and
wants him back next season. He also said he plans no more changes
among his senior-level employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will dramatically expand our sales force in the ticket
end of the sponsorship area,'' Cuban said. ``We want to be able to
reach our season ticket goals, which I'm not going to tell you what
they are because I haven't even told the staff yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just leveraging up on the excitement that's building for
the Mavs in Dallas. The response has been great, and I just want to
take it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, 41, is the third owner in the Mavericks' 20-year history.
He also is the franchise's most flamboyant owner _ a guy willing to
sign Rodman, and also willing to hire a 10-man coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Stern acknowledges that Cuban has ``raised eyebrows'' among the
owners with some of his dealings, including two ugly shouting
matches directed at referee David Jones. But all was apparently
forgotten yesterday, as the 28 other NBA owners opened their
fraternity to the ambitious Pittsburgh native.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, we have had a number of owners over the years who
have done a lot,'' Stern said. ``Some well-documented and some not,
because we got to them fast and told them to cut it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think if you get to know \RCuban\S and talk to him, you
realize that he's exceedingly good-natured and very competitive and
very bright and hard working.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than saying ``little shackles'' have been removed from his
feet, Cuban said he doesn't feel any differently now that the
Mavericks are officially his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm looking for other franchises, or I'm looking
to build a sports empire,'' he said. ``I just love basketball, I
love Mavericks, and I love Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not just have fun with it? It doesn't have to be anything
beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:CUBAN'S TEAM  &LR; agatea:Mark Cuban officially became owner
of the Mavericks yesterday in New York, but he has been running the
franchise since Januray, when he made an offer to buy a controlling
interest of the team from Ross Perot Jr. The major moves Cuban has
made:
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 13: Fired Reunion Arena announcer Kevin McCarthy and
replaced him with radio personality ``Humble'' Billy Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31: Hired Derek Harper as vice president of business
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 3: Signed forward Dennis Rodman to a contract for the
remainder of the season. Also leased his guest house to Rodman
until the NBA told Cuban that was a violation of the league's
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 21: Hired George Prokos as director of new revenue and
sales.
</P>
<P>
   March 9: Waived Rodman the day after Rodman criticized Cuban for
``hanging on the players'' and compared him to Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   March 13: Hired Del Harris as defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   March 14: Hired Brad Davis as defensive assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   March 15: Hired Gar Heard as defensive assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   March 23: Said he wants team president Terdema Ussery, general
manager Don Nelson and Nelson's son Donnie to return next season.
</P>
<P>
   April 3: Hired Matt Fitzgerald as senior vice president of
marketing and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday: Approved by NBA Board of Governors as the Mavericks'
owner, the third in franchise history.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 0105EDT &QL; 
