<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN-JERRY-TAKEOVER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN &AMP; JERRY'S HOMEMADE AGREES TO $256 MILLION TAKEOVER BY
UNILEVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to qualify lede graf)  By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than two weeks after saying it was considering a plan to be
taken private, Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade has appeared to have reached
an agreement to be sold to Unilever PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which was described by people close to the
takeover talks, was apparently reached late Tuesday, during a
lengthy meeting of the Ben &AMP; Jerry's board in New York.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant to Ben &AMP; Jerry's chief financial officer, Frances
Rathke, would not comment Tuesday night. Unilever's spokesman and
the company's investment banker did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever has agreed to pay about $42 a share for Ben &AMP; Jerry's,
making the deal worth about $256 million, the people said. It is a
significant premium on Ben &AMP; Jerry's share price, which despite
rising to a 52-week high of $35.625 in Tuesday's trading, closed at
$34.9375.
</P>
<P>
   It is also about $4 more a share than the leveraged buyout plan
that Ben &AMP; Jerry's said it was considering on March 29. That plan
would have divided the company between one of its founders, Ben
Cohen; a venture-capital firm called Meadowbrook Lane Capital that
describes itself as socially responsible; and Unilever. Unilever
would have controlled about 28 percent of the company under that
plan, while Cohen and Meadowbrook Lane Capital would have held 36
percent apiece.
</P>
<P>
   As in the earlier plan, Jerry Greenfield, the other founder and
namesake of Ben &AMP; Jerry's, would relinquish his role in the
company. It was not clear Tuesday what led to the revised offer,
nor what Cohen's role would be once Unilever took control. Cohen
and Greenfield issued a statement last month saying that they
remained close friends.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief issues facing Ben &AMP; Jerry's is its distribution
system in the United States, where it sells most of its flavors
like Cherry Garcia and Wavy Gravy. Until 1998, most of Ben &AMP;
Jerry's ice cream was distributed by Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream, an
Oakland, Calif.-based company that has a large share of the market.
Ben &AMP; Jerry's broke off the arrangement, which began in 1987, and
replaced with one that relied on Haagen-Dazs, another big
competitor, as well as Dreyer's and some company-owned
distributors. All in all, it was seen as a less-than-ideal solution
by many analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly not a negative for Unilever,'' said Jeffrey
G. Kanter, a food stocks analyst for Prudential Securities.
``Whether or not it becomes a home run remains to be seen. Unilever
is obviously looking at this for the long term. It's a fair price
for an asset with strong brand equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's, which had received takeover offers in the past,
issued an unusual statement in early December in which it said it
had received ``indications of interest'' and would be evaluating
them. The stock has risen since then from about $17 a share, and
people involved with the company, including several owners of
franchised ice-cream shops, said Ben &AMP; Jerry's appeared to be
taking the offers more seriously than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   A big concern of the franchise owners has been whether a new
owner would preserve the unusual aspects of Ben &AMP; Jerry's,
particularly its commitment to social causes like helping the
homeless and conserving the environment. Unilever maintains on its
corporate Web site that it is working to preserve clean water
resources and is involved with other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer's made an offer of $31 a share in February, according to
a copy of documents submitted with the offer. Two days later,
Meadowbrook Lane Capital submitted an offer of $32 a share. Both
were lower than the $40 a share that Unilever bid around the same
time, said a person familiar with the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A Dreyer's spokesman had little comment when contacted Tuesday,
and refused to confirm reports that Dreyer's had raised its bid
this week to $38 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything we would do on any kind of company would be on a
friendly basis, and we would only do things that are accretive to
our shareholders,'' said the spokesman, Tyler Johnston. ``Outside
of that, I can't comment on what's swirling out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
