<SLUG> BC-HKN-BELFOUR-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Ed Belfour ready if called on to carry Stars in playoffs (For use
by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mac Engel 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram Ed Belfour ready if called on to carry Stars in playoffs
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ The question invariably was going to come up with the
playoffs starting: How important is goalie Ed Belfour to the Stars'
repeating as Stanley Cup champions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid question,'' defenseman Richard Matvichuk said. ``What
was it? Four of the last five Stanley Cup champions had good
goaltending.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's think ... Martin Brodeur for New Jersey, Patrick Roy for
Colorado, Mike Vernon for Detroit and, most recently, Belfour for
the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   It took him 11 seasons, but Belfour finally got the ring that
usually adorns the fingers of the NHL's top goalies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the last couple of years Eddie was trying to find
himself and maybe drop the monkey off his back,'' forward Guy
Carbonneau said. ``And I think he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there a monkey?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Belfour said.
</P>
<P>
   With the weight of said primate on someone else's back (i.e.
Dominik Hasek), the player who often carried the Stars during the
regular-season now has the luxury of playing his first playoffs
minus the never-won-a-Cup pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure, instead, comes from himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I feel the same motivation,'' Belfour said, ``just
a little more relaxed. I don't think of it any different.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after a year in which Belfour posted the league's top save
percentage (.919) and was arguably the NHL's top goalie, players
like Roy, Roman Turek and Olaf Kolzig enjoyed most of the
attention.
</P>
<P>
   But Belfour played, and won, with nearly the same consistency as
the aforementioned trio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Eddie's had an antagonistic personality for most of
his career, other than the last couple of years, so people love to
hate him,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``For other teams and
other players, he's well respected. They know he can win games.''
</P>
<P>
   But Belfour winning games isn't extraordinary. This was his
third consecutive 30-win season. What's different is the way he's
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a hot-tempered guy in the past, but when it comes to
the big game, Eddie just stands still and he's the man,'' Edmonton
center Doug Weight said. ``We talked about him \Ron Monday\S, that
you've got to get him. He doesn't falter, he doesn't get rattled.''
</P>
<P>
   At no time this season could the Stars afford for him to be. In
a season where his teammates typically limped off or were carried
off the ice, Belfour's consistency was singular, not only because
he never got hurt, but because he made the saves that won games for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about \RMike\S Modano \Ras an MVP candidate\S, you
have to look at Eddie, too,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher said.
``For a while there, Eddie was the only reason we were winning, to
be honest. He might be the biggest reason we won it last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But, there are no Master Card commercials. There wasn't even an
All-Star invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Does he care?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how people view me,'' Belfour said. ``I care
about how my teammates view me and how I think of myself. I don't
think that's changed. I know how I can play, I know what I have
done in the past, and it doesn't bother me. I think I have played
well my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is a guy who won game No. 300 of his career this
season, becoming only the 16th goalie in NHL history to hit that
mark. How did he do it? In a typical 2-1 fashion, this time against
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best season Belfour's ever had for us,'' Hitchcock
said. ``He's won us points, he's got us games as a team we didn't
deserve to get points from.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't last year's team where we outplayed teams and the
goalies' job was to not lose games. He's had to go out and win us
games, and he's done it.''
</P>
<P>
   As he was riding a regular-season crest came his much-publicized
arrest after a hotel scuffle] March 8.
</P>
<P>
   The doubts began to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Was Belfour going to be the same?
</P>
<P>
   Was this going to be the same player that carried the Stars for
so much of the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't missed a beat,'' Hitchcock said. ``The time that he
spent away was hard on him and hard on us. If it did anything it
made him realize how important hockey is to his life and his
family. What that man's been through, this is all window dressing.
To me, coming back to our team was the easiest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything's a little easier when you've already won a Stanley
Cup.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
