<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTIZ KEEPS ANGELS ROLLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- To this point - and yes, it is still very, very early
- seemingly every question concerning the 2000 Angels has met with
a positive response.
</P>
<P>
   Our pitchers Ken Hill and Jason Dickson healthy? Check and
check. Is Scott Schoeneweis ready to become a big league starter?
Check. Can Darin Erstad rebound from a sub-par 1999? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to add pitcher Ramon Ortiz and backup shortstop Benji
Gil to the Angels' feel good check list.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, who says his right shoulder is stronger than at any time
last season, did nothing to disprove his claim as he went five
quality innings as the Angels beat the Toronto Blue Jays 5-4 in
front of a Tuesday night crowd of only 15,229 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Gil, who is replacing injured shortstop Gary DiSarcina, had a
single and a double while hitting out of the No. 9 slot in the
order.
</P>
<P>
   Gil's second inning single with two outs proved to perhaps be
the most timely hit for the Angels. Catcher Bengie Molina, another
Angel off to solid start, walked prior to Gil's single.
</P>
<P>
   Gil's base hit and Molina's walk kept the inning alive for the
red-hot Erstad, who promptly followed his first inning infield
single with a three-run homer to right to give Anaheim a 4-0 lead.
Erstad's homer gave him 17 hits in his first 33 at bats to start
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson opened four-run second with a double, the 176th
of his career, tying him for No. 7 on the all-time Angels list with
Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus put the Angels up 1-0 when Toronto shortstop Alex
Gonzalez couldn't quite keep Glaus' ground ball up the middle from
slipping far enough into center to allow Anderson to slide home
ahead of center fielder Jose Cruz Jr.'s throw home.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went up 5-0 when cleanup hitter Mo Vaughn, with no
homers and three RBI when he stepped to the plate, hit a harmless
looking fly ball down the left field line that eventually landed in
the seats for a solo homer. Vaughn's 338-foot opposite field job
was hardly the kind fans are used to seeing from the team's
high-priced slugger.
</P>
<P>
   While Ortiz bobbed and weaved through troubled spots in the
third and fourth innings, Toronto finally seemed to solve the
Angels' 24-year-old right-hander in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, who has a slight tear of his labrum (shoulder) went five
innings and gave up eight hits and four walks, but just two runs.
He also struck out four while throwing 83 pitches (43 strikes).
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz took a shutout into the fifth after striking out both Raul
Mondesi and Carlos Delgado, the third and fourth hitters in the
Blue Jays' lineup, with runners at second and third.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Ortiz, whose fastball was consistently clocked in
the low 90's, got Cruz Jr., to line softly to second base for an
inning-ending double play, Earlier in the inning, Vaughn fielded
Darrin Fletcher's soft ground ball and threw out Brad Fullmer at
home.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Toronto cut it to 5-2 when Mondesi, the former
Dodger who heard boos here and there, atoned for his earlier strike
out with a two-run homer to left, his first of the year and just
his second and third RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado followed with a double, but Ortiz was bailed out of the
fifth when Molina picked Delgado off of second base. Molina also
cut down leadoff man Shannon Stewart with a perfect throw to second
base on a first inning stolen base attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi scored on a Lou Pote wild pitch in the seventh inning
and Stewart's RBI single cashed in Cruz Jr., who opened the eighth
with a triple down the right field line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
