<HEADLINE>
DALLAS' LEADING MAN MIKE MODANO BOUNCES BACK FROM STRIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mike Modano's problems began with the greatest moment
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He had just won the Stanley Cup, giving him everything he
wanted. He had a six-year, $43.5 million contract, builders ready
to break ground on his dream house and, by summer's end, an
engagement to his high-school sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   So why then wasn't he happy? Modano asked himself that exact
same question as he lay by his pool last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of things going on, on my plate,'' Modano
admitted. ``Planning a house, planning a wedding and still having
to play hockey and concentrate on that. It just seemed to be too
much at one time. Yeah, I was buried by it.''
</P>
<P>
   He needed to simplify. By February, he had fired his agent,
called off his engagement, sold the land on which he was going to
build the house, and, somewhere along the way, he became arguably
the best player in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   He has 22 goals and 24 assists since Jan. 20 _ numbers that only
Colorado's Joe Sakic has bested _ turning a lackluster beginning
into a MVP-type season.
</P>
<P>
   And the season looks even better when you consider all the
changes in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what people on the outside forget a lot. We're human
just like everybody else, and we have personal problems,'' Stars
forward Guy Carbonneau said. ``Whether it's your mom or parents,
wife or kids, there are difficult things in our lives that for a
fan they don't see. For a human being, it's draining. This is the
stuff that is more important than the game.'' \Nsubheds:THE BIG
FALL Modano should've been happy. He was coming off maybe the best
hockey of his life.
</P>
<P>
   What he did in the Stanley Cup Finals, while not largely noticed
or noted, was be probably the Stars best player. Not only did he
once and for all shed his image as ``soft'' by taking injections so
he'd be able to play with a broken bone in his wrist, but he proved
himself worthy of Conn Smythe consideration as playoff MVP and
inclusion among the best players in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a thing that Mo was a changed player,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Yeah, but it's like `OK, you're a
changed player.' But when it is on the line, are you a changed
player? Or do you revert back to old form?
</P>
<P>
   ``And he was a changed player.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a player more committed to winning than to stats, more
about substance than style. If winning the Cup was his belated
coming-out party, this season was supposed to be his chance to
flaunt it. He began talking of possibly breaking the 100-point
barrier.
</P>
<P>
   He broke his nose instead. He was lucky the broken nose, a mild
concussion and strained neck ligaments were all he suffered after a
scary collision with the end boards. It was only the second game of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, on the same night that his engagement to longtime
girlfriend Kerri Nelson was announced on the Jumbotron, his life
seemed to be spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   It could've been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   As he was being wheeled from the ice on Oct. 2, he remembers
thinking it was. Would I walk again? Should I play again?
</P>
<P>
   He eventually decided yes, returning three games later. But this
wasn't the same Mike Modano as before the injury. The injury
combined with lethargy from a long playoff run caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as you want to say it doesn't effect you, it does,''
Stars winger Brett Hull said. ``I'm not going to blame anyone for
it, but I know for a fact that looking at him and playing with him
and him looking at me and him playing with me, that here's two guys
that just there wasn't a lot of enthusiasm at the start of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   You could see it on the ice. The Stars struggled. Modano
couldn't score.
</P>
<P>
   And Modano probably would've skated along in this funk all
season had it not been for Derian Hatcher's injury Dec. 17. Hatcher
would miss six to eight weeks. The Stars needed a new captain. With
Nieuwendyk hurt, too, Modano was the only choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably came at a good time,'' Modano said. ``Everything
was spinning out of control, and I think that kind of gave me a
little direction.'' \Nsubheds:THE HAPPY ENDING Of course, the
Hollywood version would have Modano's comeback beginning as soon as
he became captain. But he was consistent, not spectacular. So
Hitchcock sat him down in January and they talked.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard talk in which things were said that maybe people
don't want to hear. It was one of many hard discussions Modano has
had to have recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was figuring out what I should be doing and who I should be
with, building houses and getting rid of agents and getting rid of
investors. I'm not really one to upset people,'' Modano said. ``I
try to keep people happy all the time and please everybody, and
then it all of a sudden comes back to haunt me. I finally had to do
something. It was out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   His last, and probably hardest, talk was with Nelson. He had to
tell someone he cared very much about that he just wasn't ready to
get married.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't my time,'' Modano said. ``That's what we talked
about. I needed some time to think about if this is what I want to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the buildup to it, to get the nerve to say that or
mention what you are going to do, to explain it to somebody that
you don't want them to work for you anymore, you don't want to
spend your life with that somebody any more. It took me days to
build up the courage.''
</P>
<P>
   He finally did. He moved out of his house into a hotel in
Dallas. He's closed on a house in Highland Park. He's taken a
more-active role in the handling of his finances. He's simplified.
</P>
<P>
   And his happiness started to fall into place during the worst
season of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken me 11 years to get the right people around me,''
Modano said. ``Everybody has a great idea. Everybody has a
bullet-proof plan as far as what to do with your money and how you
should run your life, but nobody can tell you. You have to figure
it out for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He has, too. Because for the first time in a long time, he can
honestly say he's happy.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
