<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-BLAZERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' DEFENSE STUNS TRAIL BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks' Mark Cuban era began triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban received the NBA's seal of approval yesterday in New York,
and the Mavericks rewarded their new owner by beating the NBA's
second-best team last night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks stunned the Portland Trail Blazers, 92-81, despite
being outrebounded, 59-37, and dazed general manager/coach Don
Nelson in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we're winning some of these games,'' Nelson
said after the Mavericks' fifth consecutive victory. ``How do you
get outrebounded by 20 in this league and win? I have no idea, but
we've done it all season long. It amazes me, but our defense was
strong enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' defensive effort stymied the Trail Blazers, who
entered the contest as the league's best-shooting team. The Trail
Blazers connected on 34.6 percent of their field-goal attempts
(28-of-81) and further hurt their cause by misfiring on 14 of their
33 free-throw attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' defensive improvement can be traced to the recent
hiring of Del Harris as their defensive coordinator, but ``a lot of
it was us deciding to work harder on the defensive end,'' point
guard Steve Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks center Shawn Bradley played a role in Portland's
offensive meltdown. The 7-foot-6 center blocked five shots and
altered many others during his 29 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley played the second half with a tender left knee after
straining it with 1:22 remaining in the first half. Bradley
returned during the third period and made an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad he was able to play the second half,'' Nelson
said. ``The fact that he came back after his injury and played well
was a factor in a lot of their missed shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks began the third quarter with a four-point
advantage and extended it to 15 with 9:57 remaining. Portland's
Greg Anthony fouled Bradley on a layup, and the center completed
the 3-point play with the ensuing free throw that gave the
Mavericks a 71-56 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, though, answered with Bonzi Wells, who scored all 11
of his points during the final period. The Trail Blazers twice
pulled within six points, but the Mavericks' Michael Finley never
allowed the visitors closer.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who scored a game-high 24 points, nailed a 3-pointer
with 4:51 remaining, and his 20-foot jumper as the shot clock
expired with 2:35 remaining sealed the Trail Blazers' fate.
</P>
<P>
   Nash continued to serve as the Mavericks' catalyst. The 6-foot-3
guard scored all of his nine points during the second half and
finished with six assists and no turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Steve Nash's line, and it's not very impressive,''
Nelson said. ``Yet, he's the main reason we won. He made every
right play, defended and ran a great game. His line doesn't look
all that good, but he was the guy tonight. There's no question
about it.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly The Mavericks established a season
high with their fifth consecutive victory and remain unbeaten this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Trail Blazers center Rasheed Wallace earned his NBA-leading 36th
technical foul. Mavericks forward Dirk Nowitzki drew an offensive
foul from Wallace with 3:51 remaining in the third quarter.
Obviously, Wallace disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' 81 points marked the fewest scored against the
Mavericks this season. The Bulls scored 83 during the Mavericks'
12-point victory Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was the Blazers' first player to score in double figures
with his 10th and 11th points with 7:35 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' 36 victories matched the 1994-95 team's total for
the ninth-most in franchise history.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
