<SLUG> BC-TECHNICOLOR-ACQUIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNICOLOR BUYS CANADA'S ASTRALTECH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMARILLO, Calif. _ Technicolor Inc., the world's largest film
print, videocassette and DVD production and distribution company,
said Tuesday that it will buy AstralTech, Canada's second-largest
duplicator of videocassettes, for $17.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition helps Technicolor solidify its presence in the
growing Canadian market and gives the company increased capacity to
produce digital video discs, which are gaining popularity as a home
video format.
</P>
<P>
   ``AstralTech already has a well-established retail direct
distribution infrastructure,'' said Quentin Lilly, president of
Technicolor Video Media Services.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's video market is growing at a steady pace, Lilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Technicolor, a subsidiary of the British conglomerate Carlton
Communications, has a DVD plant in Camarillo with the capacity to
produce 18 million discs per year. That is expected to double by
the end of this year because of an expansion at the plant, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   The AstralTech acquisition gives Technicolor facilities in
Montreal and Toronto, into which Technicolor plans to consolidate
its own existing duplication and distribution operations.
</P>
<P>
   AstralTech will become part of Technicolor's Packaged Media
Group _ the company's largest division, comprised of video
manufacturing, optical manufacturing and distribution operations.
</P>
<P>
   All of AstralTech's 360-plus video duplication and distribution
employees are being offered positions with Technicolor, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   Technicolor's Canadian operation will have the capacity to
produce more than 45 million videocassette units a year.
</P>
<P>
   The move also better positions Technicolor to become one of
Canada's leading DVD packaged media manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   AstralTech's regional strength in Canada should meld well with
Technicolor's global leadership, AstralTech General Manager Andre
Pagotto said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is geared mostly for videocassette production,
AstralTech's existing infrastructure can support expansion into
DVD, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has the capacity this year to produce in excess of
800 million videocassettes, 150 million DVDs and 500 million CDs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to video duplication and distribution, Technicolor
also processes film and produces release prints of films for
distribution. The company also is working on developing a digital
distribution system for movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
