<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS DISPOSE OF CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers double-dared the Sports Illustrated
jinx Tuesday by losing for the 63rd time in 77 games.
</P>
<P>
   It was their first public appearance since this week's magazine
cover declared Donald T. Sterling's franchise the worst in sports
history. But with six seasons of 60-plus defeats in the bank since
moving north from San Diego, the Clippers should be immune from the
historically bad karma invited by an SI cover.
</P>
<P>
   Jinx? Bring it on.
</P>
<P>
   So, with no fear of going even lower to deter them, the Clips
were beaten, 95-88, by the Phoenix Suns before 14,724 at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd be approaching games not to be
embarrassed,'' said Clipper rookie Lamar Odom, who roared out of a
two-week funk by providing 26 points, 15 rebounds and 6 assists,
``but that's where we are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling was elsewhere Tuesday, and his was occupied by actor
George Segal, whose sitcom ``Just Shoot Me,'' was not inspired by
the Clipper owner.
</P>
<P>
   That title also had nothing to do with Phoenix management, which
is dealing with catastrophic injuries to Jason Kidd and Tom
Gugliotta. Cliff Robinson continued picking up the slack by scoring
22 points to lead the playoff-prepping Suns (50-27).
</P>
<P>
   Another celebrity to preview this Clipper fall was University of
Cincinnati forward Kenyon Martin, winner of the John Wooden Award
and lead suspect as the Clips' drive to earn the first pick in the
NBA Draft. The Clippers' 13th consecutive loss also included the
season's first recorded sighting of a paper bag hiding the face of
a Clipper fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious hits us in the face sometimes,'' said interim
coach Jim Todd, addressing his team's all-too-familiar story line
of solid start, rotten finish.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a 12-point effort from Derek Anderson, they led, 22-15,
after Tuesday's first quarter. Anderson, an aspiring free agent who
may think this situation is too bad to come back for an encore,
almost decided his back was too bad to compete vs. the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   But he mustered up enough grit to punch in 25 points. Anderson
fired in 18 of those by intermission, but a 28-18 second-quarter by
Phoenix had the Suns up, 43-40, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Odom had an equal split of 14 third-quarter points,
as the home team entered the fourth quarter tied at 65.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter was typically smelly for the Clips. Thirteen
seconds after a 19-foot jumper by Penny Hardaway gave Phoenix the
lead for good (74-72) at 7:36, Anderson retired with lower back
spasms.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs got week, so I shut it down,'' said Anderson, who
didn't make the trip to Salt Lake City for tonight's game with the
Utah Jazz and is expected to miss Friday's game at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Another question mark is forward Maurice Taylor, who aggravated
his left-ankle injury, while finishing with 8 points on 4-of-12
shooting. He also aggravated Todd with a couple of untimely shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like it's getting worse,'' said Taylor, presumably
referring to his bad wheel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
