<HEADER>
A4269 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ACADEMIC-DECATHLON-LA     04-12 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMIC-DECATHLON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECATHLON HIT BY LOCAL COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL O'DONOGHUE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the eve of the prestigious National Academic
Decathlon competition, a coalition of decathlon coaches _ including
those from former U.S. champs El Camino Real and Moorpark high
schools _ accused the sponsor of plagiarism and inaccuracy in its
test materials.
</P>
<P>
   The one-page letter sent last month by 42 decathlon coaches from
the Los Angeles Unified School District says the test materials,
which help students prepare for the grueling annual competition in
10 subjects, are ``replete with errors, often plagiarized and are
sold for an exorbitant cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, a copy of which was obtained Tuesday by the Daily
News, demands an overhaul of the board's study preparation process,
as well as the tests and the competition itself. The coaches said
they are prepared to withdraw from of the national competition and
form their own contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not happy with the direction USAD is heading,''
said Jim Hatem, who has coached Los Angeles High School teams for
the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the issues will be addressed later this week, when the
national competition kicks off in San Antonio, Texas, with Simi
Valley High School representing California. The USAD board is
slated Friday to review the recommendations of a task force set up
to address the coaches' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview from San Antonio, USAD Executive Director
James Alvino refused to release the proposed recommendations.
However, he acknowledged that the study guides, which cost $495 per
set and contain booklets on seven of the 10 subjects, had many
errors.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the errors _ such as incorrect figures for the
population of China and the wrong dates for construction of the
Suez Canal _ on a contractor hired to write the study guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some of the materials this year, there were an inordinate
amount of errors,'' Alvino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired a contractor who let us down in a big way and we
didn't discover this until the materials were printed and
distributed. However, whenever we did get an allegation of a
mistake, we thoroughly assessed it ... and if we could verify it,
then all corrections were were posted on the Web site as errata and
sent it out to the (coaches).''
</P>
<P>
   Alvino emphasized that most of the errors occurred in the Social
Science book and said USAD will increase its reviews of future
study guides to detect errors.
</P>
<P>
   In response to coaches' complaints of widespread plagiarism in
the study guides, Alvino said material was used from other sources,
but was used legally and cited appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were materials ... lifted from other sources and, in
some cases, certain paragraphs in a row lifted verbally from other
sources and we were concerned about this. And we had our attorneys
look at this issue, and their opinion was that, given the
legitimacy of the sources from which the material was taken and the
small amount taken from the sources and put in our guides, we were
covered by the fair-use part of the copyright laws,'' said Alvino.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in San Antonio, Simi Valley Coach Ken Hibbitts said he,
too, had concerns about errors in the study materials, but had not
written or signed any letter of complaint. While he would like
improvements made, he said he wants to see the national program
continue intact.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Jones, the coach of last year's national champion
Moorpark High School team, and other coaches have sent letters of
complaint to USAD.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has taken issue with what he considers the exorbitant cost
of study guides and accused USAD of trying to make money despite
its nonprofit status.
</P>
<P>
   But Alvino rejected those arguments, saying that USAD offers
bulk discounts and is a nonprofit organization with no objectives
of making large amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Michelle Bergman, this year's Moorpark High coach and
an assistant coach of last year's national winners, also have
expressed similar concerns. Both also said they would join with the
Los Angeles coaches' threat to break away from USAD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would help anyone to get a grass-roots competition going,
and our students are aware of this, too,'' Bergman said. ``There
could be secession because we feel like they're really going away
from the students' education and it's kind of money-driven now is
the feeling we all have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     04-12 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTIZ KEEPS ANGELS ROLLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- To this point - and yes, it is still very, very early
- seemingly every question concerning the 2000 Angels has met with
a positive response.
</P>
<P>
   Our pitchers Ken Hill and Jason Dickson healthy? Check and
check. Is Scott Schoeneweis ready to become a big league starter?
Check. Can Darin Erstad rebound from a sub-par 1999? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to add pitcher Ramon Ortiz and backup shortstop Benji
Gil to the Angels' feel good check list.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, who says his right shoulder is stronger now than at any
time last season, did nothing to disprove his claim as he went five
quality innings to pick up the win as the Angels defeated the
Toronto Blue Jays 5-4 in front of a Tuesday night crowd of only
15,229 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Gil, who is replacing injured shortstop Gary DiSarcina, had a
single and a double while hitting out of the No. 9 slot in the
order.
</P>
<P>
   Gil's second inning single with two outs proved to perhaps be
the most timely hit for the Angels. Catcher Bengie Molina, another
Angel off to solid start, walked prior to Gil's single.
</P>
<P>
   Gil's base hit and Molina's walk kept the inning alive for the
red-hot Erstad, who promptly followed his first inning infield
single with a three-run homer to right to give Anaheim a 4-0 lead.
Erstad's homer gave him 17 hits in his first 33 at bats to start
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson opened four-run second with a double, the 167th
of his career, tying him for No. 7 on the all-time Angels list with
Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus' RBI single cashed in Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went up 5-0 when Mo Vaughn, with no homers and three
RBI when he stepped to the plate, hit a harmless looking fly ball
down the left field line that eventually landed in the seats for a
solo homer.
</P>
<P>
   While Ortiz bobbed and weaved through troubled spots in the
third and fourth innings, Toronto finally seemed to solve the
Angels' 24-year-old right-hander in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, who has a slight tear of his labrum (shoulder) went five
innings and gave up seven hits and four walks, but just two runs.
He also struck out four while throwing 83 pitches -43 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleased with his velocity and he still had good stuff
into the fifth,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``When push
came to shove, he made some tremendous pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz took a shutout into the fifth after striking out both Raul
Mondesi and Carlos Delgado with runners at second and third to end
the third.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Ortiz, whose fastball was consistently clocked in
the low 90's, got Jose Cruz Jr., to line softly to second base for
an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Toronto cut it to 5-2 when Mondesi, the former
Dodger who heard boos here and there, atoned for his earlier strike
out with a two-run homer to left, his first of the year and just
his second and third RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado followed with a double, but Ortiz was bailed out of the
fifth when Molina picked Delgado off of second base. Molina also
cut down leadoff man Shannon Stewart with a perfect throw to second
base on a first inning stolen base attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi scored on a Lou Pote wild pitch in the seventh inning
and Stewart's RBI single cashed in Cruz Jr., who opened the eighth
with a triple down the right field line.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Troy Percival blew the Blue Jays away in the ninth,
striking out the side the included Mondesi, Delgado (with a 97 mph
fastball), and Brad Fullmer to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy Percival definitely stepped it up a notch tonight,''
Scioscia said. ``He was throwing well before, but tonight was a
different story. That pitch he threw to Delgado was nasty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
