<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, April 12.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-NAP-GUIDE (United Nations) _ Diplomacy is an exhausting
business, so where to catch a midday nap? At the U.N. Secretariat,
a building made mostly of glass, there would seem to be no place to
hide. Wrong! says Alain Dejammet, who has just returned to Paris
after four years as France's ambassador to the United Nations. He
has ``published'' a guide to napping, ``Dormir aux Nations Unies.''
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT27) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   UNIONS-GLOBAL-ECONOMY (Washington) _ Why are U.S. labor unions
so anti-trade? A big union rally planned for Wednesday to protest
the U.S.-China trade deal has become a focal point for
anti-globalization forces planning to protest during the IMF and
World Bank meetings this weekend. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-FAMILIES (Seoul, South Korea) _ Divided families are
joyful over the prospect of a North-South summit: ``My parents
would probably be over 100 years old now, so I must assume they are
no longer living,'' said Park Byoung Gul. ``But even if I can't see
them, it would mean the world to me to hear from my sisters.'' By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-SYRIA (Beirut) _ The Syria-Lebanon relationship has
undergone changes from both sides in the last few years, with the
Syrians more subtle in their management and the Lebanese more open
in their desire to define its terms. But it is still a lopsided
arrangement. A Lebanese clan leader says: ``If you want to weaken
your opponent, you go to Syria. If you want to help someone, you go
to Syria. If you want a service from the judiciary, you go to
Syria.'' By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-IV (Gloucester, Mass.) _ The father of a slain
college student and the young man's killer try to understand the
senseless crime. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT14,15) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI (Miami) _ Non-Cuban Miamians don't support the
Cuban community in this case but some understand their actions.
Some older blacks hear echoes of the civil rights movement and
Latin Americans from repressive countries understand the Cubans. By
Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-FATHER (Bethesda, Md.) _ A hotel doorman from Cuba has
a sendoff meeting with Castro, rides a private jet, meets Janet
Reno, sees snow for the first time in the yard of his home away
from home in a well-to-do Washington suburb, meets Jesse Jackson,
sees his son on TV every day, meets Jose Serrano, receives a
present of Wisconsin cheese, gives copies of family photos to Reno,
Serrano, the cheese lady and probably to Jackson. And all the while
a crowd of photographers watches him, speculating that he might
defect at any time. Life in America for Juan Miquel Gonzalez isn't
just a spring walk past the cherry blossoms. By Randal C.
Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-PROSTITUTES (Chicago) _ Shrouded in darkness on the tough
streets of the city's South Side, a Roman Catholic priest, Michael
Pfleger, looks for prostitutes. Pfleger, 50, the pastor of St.
Sabina Church, pays cash, ranging from $10 to $50, and then uses
the time to talk to the women about escaping the indignities and
dangers of selling their bodies. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFTER-HOURS _ A white house memo: It is after hours,
away from the White House, that Bill Clinton loosens up. With no
prepared text before him, his words flow more freely than during
daylight. He talks of frivolous things (Pokemon cards and movie
plots) and serious matters (how he almost lost his job as
president). He abandons the cautious verbiage he uses from 9 to 5,
lashing out at political opponents as though he were still a
candidate. It is a side of Clinton that has been prominent at other
times, but in the twilight of his presidency, with fewer and fewer
big policy events and more and more fund-raisers, it is a side that
is becoming more dominant. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SPY-SATELLITES - The U.S. government's ability to keep track of
looming international threats was drastically curtailed last year
because of a prolonged computer breakdown at the Pentagon agency
that collects and analyzes photographs from spy satellites, several
federal intelligence officials said. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PATENT (Undated) _ The University of Rochester said on
Tuesday that it had been awarded a broad patent covering the use of
a new type of painkiller that has become the pharmaceutical
industry's fastest-selling new product. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   SPONSORS-MOTIVATE (Atlanta) _ When the Olympic Games open in
Australia this summer, about 30 athletes will represent Egypt.
Sixty will make up the contingent from Turkey. And nearly 100 will
make up the delegation from Home Depot. The company's orange logo
will not appear on the the Olympic athletes' uniforms, of course,
and television commentators probably won't even mention the giant
retailer's name. But in cities and towns around North America,
thousands of Home Depot employees will stay up late to root for the
athletes on TV and get up the next morning to devour the accounts
of their exploits in the sports pages. That, it turns out, is the
audience Home Depot executives are trying to reach. When a company
employs 210,000 people in an industry with one of the highest
turnover rates in the country _ in the midst of one of the tightest
job markets in more than three decades _ it does what it has to do
to hold onto every last one of them. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OPERATION-SMILE (Undated) _ Acknowledging for the first time
that its organization lacked proper oversight, Operation Smile
notified its chapters last week that it was enacting sweeping
reforms at the suggestion of an outside lawyer retained by the
organization to review its conduct. The reforms are aimed at
addressing serious criticism that arose last year, following two
articles published by the New York Times, over the charity's
management and the quality of its medical care. The charity, which
helps thousands of underprivileged children overseas obtain plastic
surgery but has had some patients die, said it would be stepping up
efforts to hire a new chief executive officer and adding the
position of chief medical officer. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OMNICOM-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ In another step to expand an
already extensive interactive empire, the Omnicom Group is
investing in an innovative agency that specializes in creating
offline campaigns for online marketers. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   RITEAID-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Rite Aid, having failed to find
buyers for its PCS Health Systems subsidiary, has announced a plan
to refinance its debt for more than two years, giving it access to
more than $640 million in additional funds. The deal came at a cost
of higher interest rates on some of its borrowings and substantial
dilution for its stockholders. Shares of Rite Aid rose $1.625, to
$7.3125. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   SPONSORS-MOTIVATE (Atlanta) _ When the Olympic Games open in
Australia this year, 55 athletes will be representing Thailand.
Seventy-five will make up the contingent from Argentina. Ninety
will run, jump, swim, and play for France. And approximately 100
will make up the delegation from the Home Depot Corp. Of course,
Home Depot's orange logo won't appear on the Olympic athletes'
uniforms, and television viewers are unlikely to hear much about
their connection to the giant retailer. But in cities and towns
across the United States, Canada and Puerto Rico, thousands of the
company's employees will be staying up late to watch them on TV and
scanning the next morning's newspapers to root for them. That, Home
Depot's executives say, is precisely the reason the company has
spent several million dollars hiring dozens more Olympic athletes
than any other company. The Olympic program is part of a broader
effort to use traditional marketing strategies, like sponsorships,
as a management tool. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   CORNELIUS-CASINO (Undated) _ Neil M. Cornelius Jr., general
manager, Treasure Island Resort and Casino.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Copenhagen,'' the
endlessly fascinating play by Michael Frayn, opened in New York on
Tuesday night. Who would ever have thought that three dead,
long-winded people talking about atomic physics would be such
electrifying companions? Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT21) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TEENAGE-GERMAN-NOVELIST (New York) _ Benjamin Lebert is 18, and
his first novel ``Crazy,'' written when he was 16, is a runaway
best seller in his native Germany. There are 200,000 copies in
print, the rights have been sold in 26 countries. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ARISTA-DAVIS (Los Angeles) _ Clive Davis, the beleaguered chief
executive of Arista Records, celebrated the 25th anniversary of the
label he founded with performances by some of its best-known acts
on Monday night at the Shrine Auditorium here. Among those
performing at the ceremony, which stretched from three hours to an
audience-wearying six so that it could be taped properly for
broadcast May 15 on NBC, were Santana, Sarah McLachlan, Toni
Braxton, Puff Daddy, Barry Manilow, Alan Jackson, Patti Smith and
Whitney Houston. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   ALBEE-BABY (Houston) _ In Edward Albee's new play, ``The Play
About the Baby,'' which opens on Wednesday at the Alley Theater
here, a young married couple have a baby and soon find themselves
bedeviled by two strangers, an older man and woman. Eventually the
child disappears. Truth? Illusion? What happened to the baby? As
usual, Albee leaves it to the audience, except to say, yes, there
was a real baby. When the play was first presented at the Almeida
Theater in London in 1998, as directed by Howard Davies, the
reviews were sharply divided. After a possible New York production
was postponed, Albee decided to do it at the Alley, a familiar
regional theater that allows him complete artistic freedom. By Mel
Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIALIST-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Specialist,'' a
documentary about Adolf Eichmann directed by Eyal Sivan. (In
English, Hebrew, German and French) Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLIPS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Mr. Phillips,'' by John
Lanchester (Putnam). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SOPRANOS (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: ``The Sopranos''
ends another successful season. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
