<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4277 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LA     04-12 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WUSA'S PLAN MAKES LITTLE SENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Women's United Soccer Association (WUSA) made a bold
announcement Monday, indicating that it plans to launch its new
league in April of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The plan of the WUSA to go head-to-head with Major League Soccer
doesn't make a lot of sense. Why not compete in a different season,
a shorter season, so that soccer fans aren't asked to choose
allegiances?
</P>
<P>
   There is room for both professional leagues, but competing
against each other, especially with pro soccer at such a sensitive
stage in its development in this country, isn't the smartest move
on the WUSA's part.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters more complicated, the MLS recently submitted its
own plan to start a women's professional league, hoping to use
league resources, offices and stadiums to piggy-back the women's
game with the men's game.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck. This will never happen. MLS submitted its plan hoping
to discourage the WUSA.
</P>
<P>
   At least Discovery Communications founder John Hendricks seems
to have a credible plan to get the WUSA off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   He has plenty of financial support and an ambitious television
package to challenge the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks announced that he has raised $40 million, mostly from
television, to start WUSA's league.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Cablevision, Cox Enterprises, Cox Communications and
Time Warner Cable agreed to a four-year cable contract with Time
Warner that calls for 22 games to be broadcast nationally by either
TNT of CNN/SI.
</P>
<P>
   The WUSA has named New York, Atlanta, Boston, Philadelphia, San
Diego, San Francisco, Washington D.C. and Orlando as the eight
cities that will have teams. The WUSA also has support from the
entire U.S. Women's National Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting all the elements together for a successful
league and we are very optimistic and confident we will not be
disadvantaged in any way,'' Hendricks said. ``Our investment group
is fully capable of getting this league going and running.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS commissioner Don Garber released a statement indicating that
MLS hasn't given up the idea of having its own women's league next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are great believers in women's soccer,'' Garber said. ``We
have the experience, resources and operational expertise to
effectively create and manage a professional women's soccer
league.''
</P>
<P>
   For the good of the game, the MLS and WUSA need to sit down and
work out a plan that benefits everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Temple City High and Stanford graduate Erin Martin is one
keeping close tabs on the new women's leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Martin set the CIF state career scoring record at Temple City
with 286 goals before graduating in 1993. After graduating from
Stanford, Martin played professionally in Japan with the Fujita
Mercury. She played professionally last season in Sweden. Last
week, she left for New Zealand to try yet another professional
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a great time, it's been awesome to live in
different parts of the world,'' said Martin. ``The level of soccer
could be better, but the experience of different cultures is
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who played for the U.S. Under 20 National Team, was
never called to the full U.S. National Team but has played with or
against nearly every member of the U.S. Women's World Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of facing U.S. National Team players again, in the
U.S., and against some of the best female players in the world,
certainly interests her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing abroad, but I would probably play here if a pro
league works out,'' said Martin. ``Not because I feel I have
anything to prove; I'm happy with how my career worked out. But it
would be nice to play in front of family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy midfielders Sasha Victorine, Peter Vagenas and defender
Dan Califf were named to the final 18-player pool for CONCACAF'S
2000 Olympic qualifying in Hershey, Pa., later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Victorine, who is an early candidate for MLS rookie of the year,
was asked how he felt about his newfound stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, I still go out and nobody recognizes me,'' joked
Victorine. ``I deposited a check the other day and the bank teller
asked if I worked for Adidas since I had an Adidas sponsored check
to deposit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I play for the Galaxy.' The teller said, `Come on, I
don't recognize you, all you guys say you play pro soccer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's humbling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 0254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
