<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOCKS-PAIN-GAIN-OPED-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES AND ADVERSITY: DRAMA QUEENS, KINGS REIGN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy 625-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' general news and ``s'' sports news files.)  
  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month ago, a young and well-liked Australian swimmer named
Lori Munz was badly hurt in an automobile crash near Sydney. The
collision left her with a concussion, a shattered kneecap which
required reconstructive surgery and other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, she returned to the pool with her right leg in
a brace and did a few cautious laps with every intention of
competing in the Australian Olympic swimming trials in May.
</P>
<P>
   It is an inspirational story: ``Promising athlete with a chance
of winning a medal in a relay in her hometown Olympics battles the
odds and the ticking clock to keep her dreams afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is so inspirational that when Munz returned to the
pool, she already had signed exclusive agreements to tell her tale
to an Australian TV network and the newspaper consortium News Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Good for her, most of us would instinctively say. The
unfortunate young woman deserves every scrap of support _ both
emotional and financial _ she can get.
</P>
<P>
   Though I have never met Munz, I would be inclined to agree. A
shattered kneecap is a painful thing, but there is a part of me
that does not like the way the sports business _ and it is ever
more a business _ is evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Deals like the one Munz has signed underscore the fact that
misfortune is now just another selling point, along with
nationality and personality and _ lest we overlook the point of
this whole sweaty endeavor _ athletic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   If I were an unscrupulous, attention-hungry athlete with every
hope of qualifying for the Olympics but little hope of actually
winning something, I would not resort to taking
performance-enhancing drugs. I would instead attempt to make myself
into a great story.
</P>
<P>
   Option One: Find an equally unscrupulous physician to act as
co-conspirator _ why not ask around in cycling circles? _ and feign
a serious injury or illness several months before the Games begin.
</P>
<P>
   The injury or illness should be unusual and preferably one that
cannot be easily distinguished by observers. How about sudden
blindness, or chronic fatigue syndrome? Several months would allow
plenty of time for a dramatic yet plausible recovery; plenty of
time for sponsorship deals and plenty of time for interviews with
the media to build public awareness and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of this option is that it is result-proof. All that
matters is making it to the Games. Even elimination in the heats
would be seen as a form of triumph and would also forestall too
many nosy follow-up questions.
</P>
<P>
   Option Two: Experience misfortune at the Games themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Redmond, a British runner, pulled up lame at the Barcelona
Olympics. After he began hopping toward the line, his father leaped
out of the stands and helped his tearful son finish his race and
become a fixture on highlight programs.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond was legitimately injured, but that need not be the case.
A big idea will be required, however. Remember, there are only 16
days and 32 American news cycles from opening ceremony to closing
ceremony (Americans are particularly susceptible to human interest
stories) and much of that time will be devoted to the actual medal
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Those who choose to exercise one of these options should be
aware that there are risks. The possibility of being found out and
humiliated is real, although being unmasked would certainly help
the plotter's name recognition more than finishing seventh in the
men's hurdles or women's individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   The other potential problem is that, however creative and
inventive the ruse, it risks being overshadowed by reality.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Some listing, lutzing soul might hire a hit man to
break a rival's leg. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 625-word commentary from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
