<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA: GOLDEN ECONOMIC PRIZE, OR RISING MENACE? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA-DEMYSTIFIED-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The West cannot quite make up its mind about how it wants to
deal with China. In America, big business lobbies Congress to treat
China as a normal trading nation, while Congress urges the Clinton
administration to sell more weapons to Taiwan, as defense against
Communist Chinese threats. Golden economic prize (2.6 billion
armpits to deodorize) or rising international menace (those ugly
threats)? Is China one or the other? Both or neither? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,025 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPAN NEEDS A NEW PRIME MINISTER WITH A MANDATE, SOON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POST-OBUCHI-JAPAN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Keizo Obuchi's stroke last weekend, Japan has had to find
a new prime minister. No one, however, seems to be looking for any
other change; that, most Japanese seem to think, can wait until
after the general election, due sometime before autumn. Alas, Japan
cannot afford to be so relaxed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOENIX: THE NEXT SILICON VALLEY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOT.COM-PHOENIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's arid Southwest is attracting people faster than any
other part of the country. Maintaining quality of life, while
continuing to attract the firms that will provide the jobs to
sustain population growth at almost three times the national rate,
is a balancing act. For Phoenix, the answer may be the Internet.
After all, an industry that doesn't need too much space, and brings
in a lot of money and not too many people, seems like a good
prospect for a city that wants to slow down a bit. Could Phoenix be
the next Silicon Valley? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Arizona) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JACK E., OH...: IT'S A SINNERS' RACE FOR TEDDY'S SEAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOSTON-BADBOYS-SENATE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in the age of negative politics, there is something a
little extraordinary, even admirable, about Jack E. Robinson III's
run for the Senate seat that comes up for election in Massachusetts
this year. In his nine-page ``Robinson's Report,'' he reveals every
skeleton in his political closet, and is now challenging his
notoriously inhibited opponent, Sen. Ted Kennedy, to do the same. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Massachusetts) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE KU KLUX KLAN: STILL RIDING, WITH A BIGGER AGENDA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KKK-ARKANSAS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Half a century or so ago, the Ku Klux Klan was remembered for
its nocturnal cross burnings, its bombing of black churches, its
occasional murders. Now, in a new century, it has picked up the
trappings of modernity. It has an Internet address for the
``Invisible Empire.'' And now Klansmen leave their rallies in
minivans and SUVs, not on horseback. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Little Rock, Ark.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
