 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOES DOLLARIZATION MAKE CENTS FOR EL SALVADOR? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOLLARIZE-ELSALVADOR?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will El Salvador be the next Latin American country to adopt the
dollar as its currency? On paper, at least, El Salvador is a far
more promising candidate for dollarization that, say, Ecuador,
which recently adopted the greenback out of desperation with its
own, sliding, currency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-MAIL, SANS REGRETS: BEFORE YOU HIT THE `SEND' BUTTON... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EMAIL-`WHOOPS!'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who has not banged out an angry reply to an apparently brusque
e-mail message, hit the send button _ and then regretted it? Surely
no technology has led to so many rifts and fractured friendships
(not to mention subpoenas) as electronic mail. But nowhere is
e-mail more perilous than in negotiations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAKISTAN'S SOCCER-BALL INDUSTRY MENDS ITS TATTERED IMAGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KIDS-LABOR-PAKISTAN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ending child labor in Pakistan can have unexpected consequences.
In the mid-1990s, Pakistani soccer-ball manufacturers were under
attack when the western press discovered that they were employing
children for 80-hour-a-week shifts, working for pennies in near
darkness. The industry hastily made profound changes and, three
years later, child labor in Sialkot's soccer industry is mostly
history. The effects, though, have been double-edged. Like soccer
itself, getting rid of child labor is not always a win-win game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 350; 1,375 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE FORBIDDEN `SECRET ROOMS' OF PORNOGRAPHIC POMPEII &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EROTIC-POMPEII-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half centuries after the excavation which brought the
ancient, destroyed cities of Pompeii and Herculaneum to light, a
collection of ``obscene objects,'' long kept behind closed doors,
is about to be opened again to the general public. A preview of the
erotic material in Naples reveals more than anything that they are
far above the standards _ as art as well as entertainment _ of what
passes for pornography today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 200; 950 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
