<P>
   &UR; PROPERTY RIGHTS _ AND WRONGS _ IN A WIRED WORLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO-OWNS-IDEAS?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Thomas Jefferson's inspiring vision, there are no barriers to
the acquisition of knowledge. Nobody owns it, everybody partakes of
it _ and the world becomes richer. Two centuries later, when
knowledge has taken over much of the economy, Jefferson's words
seem to take on a new power. These days, ideas are capital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 825 words; 900 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAK IT UP, BOYS: `WINDOWS' OF OPPORTUNITY FOR MICROSOFT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIXING-MICROSOFT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may have come as a shock to the markets, but few others can
have been surprised that Microsoft was this week found guilty. A
bolder and more imaginative Bill Gates would now consider
restructuring his company himself, as a better and more creative
alternative to the terrifying legal lottery that he appears to have
chosen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEST'S MACHIAVELLI IS NO BETTER THAN IRAQ'S HUSSEIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RETHINK-SADDAM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If, year in, year out, the United Nations were systematically
killing Iraqi children by air strikes, western governments would
declare it intolerable, no matter how noble its intention. They
should find their existing policy toward Iraq just as unacceptable.
In democracies, the end does not justify the means. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZIMBABWE ON A KNIFE-EDGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZIMBABWE-FOLLY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe is in crisis. The blame lies almost entirely with
President Robert Mugabe and his ZANU-PF, the party that has ruled
the country since it gained independence from Britain in 1980.
Mugabe has always swung between emotion and reason. Conceivably,
reason may regain the upper hand and he will allow next month's
election to be free and fair. But some nudging will almost
certainly be needed. If not, disaster will surely ensue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
