A4397 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-GAMER11-COX     04-12 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot Shots Golf 2 livens up solemn sportBy Shaun Conlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   What Tiger Woods does for the game of golf, invigorating and
broadening the appeal of ``a nice walk in the woods, spoiled (Mark
Twain),'' Sony does with its video game version of a day on the
links. Decidedly cartoonish characters bang around fictional golf
courses with simple but clever caricature animations making the art
of the duff forgiving and fun. As a sequel, Hot Shots Golf 2 ($40;
www.playstation.com; for the PSX) offers little more than a few
tweaks to its predecessor, with new characters, modes, sounds, etc.
Nevertheless, this version of the stuffy greenery game is riddled
with engaging features such as optionally quick and easy play,
where a good many tasks are automated; spectacular replay features
that give a high-tech, arcade feel to an otherwise somber sport,
plus equipment upgrades and long-term tourneys for the avid fan.
Great appeal to both golfers and gamers who wouldn't otherwise be
golfers.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   South Park Rally ($40; www.acclaim.com; for the PC) offers
nothing new to the pip-squeak, chortling-fathead, fantasy-racer
genre that Plumberboy built, save for the fact that it is
emphatically crass, rude, foul and dirty, punctuated by projectile
vomit and incessant wet-fart noises. Presented as an intentionally
simplistic game of low-grade cardboard-cut-out graphics, Rally
actually moves along crisply and cleanly. A sparse number of maps
are greatly augmented by numerous race &AMP; chase variants, from
simple check-pointed circuits to tag/capture-the-flag
free-for-alls. Overly indulgent, indiscriminate voiced-over curses
and toilet bowl comments from some 27 South Park characters round
out the charmingly foul experience. Also available on the PSX,
which is horrible, and the N64, which is good for a rental or
purchase by die-hard South Park fans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
