<HEADER>
A4399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-GEAR11-COX     04-12 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GEAR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sidewinder's a bit slippery
 &HT;    By Shaun Conlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Another entry in the battle to replace the mouse
and keyboard as the preferred interface device for First Person
Shooters (FPSs) while remaining a competent, general use
controller, the Sidewinder Dual Strike ($40; www.microsoft.com) is
an ambitious gamepad/mouse emulator hybrid. Held with both hands
and with hat switches, triggers and buttons for nearly every finger
and thumb, the innovative feature of the Dual Strike is its double
axis ball &AMP; socket rotator separating the two sides, which controls
the free look/aim function. The unit almost affords gamers a
second-skin, intuitive controller with great swivel and pivot
proffered by a limber wrist. Yet it manages to stymie that elusive
``instinctive feel,'' as a solid grip on the gizmo is impossible.
Held more like a sandwich being proffered to one's monitor, the
Dual Strike demands too much finesse while splaying the various
buttons just out of reach. A real handful, this Dual Strike
sandwich can be effective with a great deal of practice and
adaptation to its faults and unique attributes, but one has to
wonder, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   ADD SOME BITE TO YOUR GAMING
</P>
<P>
   Easily the best game pad you're going to find for your PC gaming
experience is InterAct's Hammerhead FX ($40; www.interact-acc.com).
Similar to the Dual Shock Analogue Controller of PlayStation
console fame, the Hammerhead's intelligent, ergonomic design offers
an exquisite second-skin feel. Symmetrical with two analogue thumb
sticks, four shoulder triggers, it also has a d-pad on the left and
six nicely splayed buttons on the right. A rock-solid device that's
perfectly functional with any gamepad-friendly game be it racer,
adventure, fighter or space marauder. More than that, the
Hammerhead FX does an adequate job with flight simulators, though
it can't, admittedly, better the multi-faceted, force feedback
functionality of a high-end joystick. It also does a moderately
fair job with First Person Shooters, but thumbstick free-look/aim
is too sluggish to really compete with a quick mouse. Nonetheless,
with stereo tactile (''rumble'') feedback and its overall hearty
design, this is a gamer's game pad doing everything a game pad
should do, perfectly. The search is over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 0804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
