<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 08:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-HOMEHELP11-COX     04-12 1845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-HOMEHELP11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speaker of the house
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jay and Marla Hiller sit next to each other on
chairs opposite the man who will help control the music they will
hear and the entertainment they will watch for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   On the table in front of them are blueprints of the dream home
they are building. It will be completed in November barring the
crises that such a large job always seems to entail. But months
before the Hillers and their two toddlers move in, Dale Johnson and
a team of workers from High Fidelity Inc. will go in and wire the
place, put speakers in unobtrusive places, install the new
high-definition TV set and put panels near the doors to control it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Their home will be automated, Internet-friendly, able to access
the family's CD collection from next to the pool or up in the media
room.
</P>
<P>
   It is an 8,600-square-foot dream home, but even dreamers wake up
to sticker shock.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Hiller leans forward, eyeing a comprehensive list with many
dollar signs assigned to a list of maybe hundreds of components,
wires, operating panels and remote controls. Johnson presents a
``not-to-exceed number,'' the high-end estimate of what the
equipment, installation, design and labor will cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many commas are in that not-to-exceed number?'' Jay asks.
</P>
<P>
   THE DREAMING HOME
</P>
<P>
   When Jay and Marla decided to build a house, they knew they
wanted to do it right. After spending time in Puerto Rico for Jay's
job as a consultant with Empowered Solutions Corp. of Georgia, they
were coming back to the place where they'd been born and bred. Both
University of Texas at Austin graduates, Marla (a retired high
school teacher) and Jay wanted a home free of complications, for
themselves and their kids.
</P>
<P>
   In the consultation with Johnson, who specializes in designing
and installing high-end audio and video systems in people's homes,
the couple says they want to rid themselves of the frustrations
they have in their current, temporary, home. Jay, a high-tech
junkie, has a system so convoluted that the in-laws have trouble
figuring out how to turn on the TV. It is this increasingly common
labyrinth of remote controls, wiring and set-top boxes that the
Hillers say they want to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't bother with it,'' Marla says. ``I want to be able to
push one button and have the music come on.''
</P>
<P>
   The system Johnson is designing will put controls for the home
in most of the rooms, allowing anyone in the house to access music,
movies or TV and satellite signals. It will also simplify their
home, bringing incredibly complex technologies down to the level
that a non-technophile can understand. Showing them a controller
that looks like an amazingly complicated keyboard, Johnson tells
the couple, ``This is the great simplifier.''
</P>
<P>
   They want to believe it will be. Like many, they put their faith
in gadgets, praying they will save time instead of creating
frustrations. They want to believe.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that Johnson, a manager at High Fidelity, has been
working with families on systems like this for 15 years and has the
easy, accessible friendliness _ not of a salesman, but of a guy who
loves to play with these toys, and who also has a wife who won't
abide the complications they add to life. He reassures the couple
that this system, installed by engineers and geeks who can tell the
difference in quality between an S-Video and a composite signal,
will be simple.
</P>
<P>
   After going through the list, crossing a few things out and
discussing some changes in the plan, the Hillers leave the small
office and go into the showroom, eyeing HDTV sets, one of which
will end up in their main living room. ``We never get to go to the
movies, so we might as well bring the theater to us,'' Marla says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard part,'' Jay adds, ``is writing the check.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of the job will decrease as they decide what they want
vs. what they really need. It won't really cost this much. But
right now, the estimate for the entire audio/video improvements to
their new dream home is $61,000.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW HI-FI
</P>
<P>
   The truth is this: These things are complicated. They require
special wiring, and sometimes holes are drilled into walls, and
even after all that work, ``Matlock'' may end up looking a little
fuzzy. But even though the Best Buy revolution has brought into the
home gadgets and equipment only dreamed about 10 years ago (the
digital receivers, the digital TV, the DVD players, the CD
recorders), there is still always the question: How does it all
work and who's going to set it up? Not so that it looks shabby, all
piled up on flat wooden boards in a rack system next to the TV like
some electronics mausoleum. How do you get it to look elegant, work
right and get rid of those godawful wires?
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, where high tech meets a particularly fierce love of
music and entertainment, local companies like Wizer Home Systems,
Audio by Design and Custom Systems Technologies Inc. are building
business on custom installations, multi-room systems and home
automation.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that used to focus on sales now place much more
emphasis on custom work and service as the demands of customers
have grown beyond the showroom. In the time Dale Johnson has been
at High Fidelity, the business has gone from being primarily a
consumer electronics store to a place that specializes in custom
installations. That can include everything from interfacing
computer equipment with the home entertainment system to installing
complex lighting systems that dim on command when the projection
screen comes down for a viewing of ``The Matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   Home audio and video has gone from vacuum tubes and speaker
grills to touch pads, Internet-enabled CD catalogs and a newfound
sense of style. The speakers can go in the walls now, unobtrusive
and practically invisible. The stereo components can go anywhere,
away from the inquisitive, jelly-stained hands of toddlers and into
a nook where only the remote controller will find it.
</P>
<P>
   But, we'll say it again. It's complicated getting all this stuff
to work, getting equipment pieces to talk to each other and signals
to travel the right way. That's why people who can afford it call
on someone like Johnson to do it for them. ``We do business with a
lot of people who don't have time to mess with this stuff, but they
want it done right,'' Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, even the high-tech elite need help installing
these systems, which can involve thousands of feet of wiring and
careful, computer-assisted planning and design. Customers,
especially techies, may know how to do some of this, but that
doesn't mean they want the grunt work. ``Someone like me has to be
really knowledgable. Especially in this town, you're faced with
people who know more than you do,'' Johnson says. ``You may have
somebody who designed the chip inside the component you're trying
to sell them.''
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE CALLS
</P>
<P>
   The Hillers said they were referred to Johnson by their builder,
and when they started asking around, they found lots of their
friends had worked with Johnson. ``Everybody knows Dale,'' Marla
says breezily.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who's worked with Michael Dell and the late Tom Landry
on home systems, drives around in a little red convertible,
checking the progress on this job or that, making house calls for
clients, in between bids and desk work. On a sunny Thursday, he
stops by Origin co-founder Richard Garriott's mini-castle to check
on a blown subwoofer and the installation of a flat-screen plasma
TV set Garriott received in exchange for frequent flyer miles.
</P>
<P>
   At Garriott's house, in a purple velvet-adorned entertainment
room, Johnson helps two installers who are struggling with a CD
catalog system and the reception on the flat screen TV. Amid ornate
crystal balls and mounted medieval weapons (and just upstairs from
the suit of armor gracing the entryway), they make calls on their
cell phones, ordering new equipment and calling in the converters
and wiring they need to finish a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard, this is Dale. I'm over at your house,'' Johnson says
into his cell phone. A few minutes later, Garriott has agreed to
ordering a new subwoofer and an S-Video VCR. ``We'll fix it for
you. Talk to you later.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the road, Johnson says Garriott is like a lot of
customers who care more about the end result of an installation
than the details of the work. ``He'll say to me, 'Dale, whatever I
need.' They trust us to take care of it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Garriott is entrusting Johnson to work on a future project,
helping to wire an enormous new castle that will take about three
years to build. That house will include voice automation and will
be one of the biggest projects Johnson has ever taken on.
</P>
<P>
   At any given time, High Fidelity has dozens or projects in the
pipeline at various stages of completion. The Hillers are at the
bid stage. Another client down the road is a former Dell executive
who wants automatic lighting controlled by specialized fixtures and
switches. That job is well under way. At another site, a Round Rock
family is adding a home theater room to their house, bringing in a
retractable movie screen, Italian speakers and other high-end
equipment. As it stands now, spools of wires sit in a wood frame,
waiting like empty arteries for a signal to transmit.
</P>
<P>
   THE FINAL PRODUCT
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson started, a stereo for many people meant two
speakers. Now, with consumers getting increasingly savvy about home
theater, DVD and surround sound, Johnson's job has become more
difficult. He and his staff go through near-constant training,
attending conferences and reading voraciously about the latest and
greatest, before their customers learn more than they do.
</P>
<P>
   They've had to become jacks-of-all-trades, understanding not
only TVs and stereos but also Internet devices, lighting and
Firewire, the technology many say will simplify home wiring by
putting all of a home's components on one interface and one kind of
wire. Johnson and the staff also use existing blueprints of a home
to overlay their own designs and plans for installation. It's not
just about good sound and video anymore; it's about incorporating
the technology into a family's lifestyle and the look of a house.
Many times, the company works alongside the builder, making sure
the final product is exactly what the family wants.
</P>
<P>
   High Fidelity, which has a waiting list of about four weeks
because of the 50 to 60 jobs it is currently handling, isn't
lacking customers. And they still do small jobs alongside the more
massive design work.
</P>
<P>
   It can be expensive, but the results, which Johnson said help to
incorporate music, entertainment and functionality into people's
homes and lives, are often just the thing the customers wanted, but
didn't know they needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We design a system to make someone really happy when they walk
into their house,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
