<HEADER>
A4402 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-KIDGEAR11-COX     04-12 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGEAR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putt-Putt puts the pedal to the metal
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ OK, so Pep the pup is no Jeff Gordon. Then
again, NASCAR legends don't get to navigate talking, purple cartoon
speedsters. The car in question is none other than Putt-Putt,
returning in another Humongous Entertainment adventure, Putt-Putt
Enters the Race ($30; Windows/Macintosh). Back from his previous
outing on the moon (try that, Dale Earnhardt!) Putt-Putt longs to
enter the Cartown 500 but Redline Rick, the sleek racecar who owns
the Cartown Raceway, sends our hero on a scavenger hunt first. To
enter the race, Putt-Putt needs to collect four items (including,
in a conscientious nod on Humongous' part, a safety helmet) hidden
in Cartown. Luckily for gamers, the items are hidden in different
locations and require different strategies to obtain with each
play. Characters encountered throughout the game help Putt-Putt and
Pep on their quest and all of the action is controlled with buttons
and switches on the car's dashboard. All this fun, and a race at
the end, too. Jeff Gordon never had it so good.
</P>
<P>
   PURR-FECTLY CHARMING
</P>
<P>
   Not sure if this game's appeal lies in its cute and cuddly
mascot character or the fact that game play is childishly simple.
Either way, Hello Kitty's Cube Frenzy ($30; www.newkidco.com)
offers a good reason to wrest the GameBoy Color from the older
sibling and give someone else a try. Basically a childish version
of Tetris, where rudimentary domino-flavored block shapes fall
agonizingly slowly from the sky hoping to snuggle up with similar
blocks. The only interaction offered by Hello Kitty herself is that
fact that she'll inadvertently get in the way as she meanders back
and forth across the bottom of the screen. Still, a good lesson in
strategy, foresight and motor skills for the wee one and a good way
to teach the older sibling about ``sharing'' the GBC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
