<HEADER>
A4416 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA0413-C     04-12 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA0413-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 0413: 'I was told to take pictures, and I did.'
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters.
Photos and a sig/locator map are available.)
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDERSONVILLE, Ga. _ Angelo Spinelli never shot a single German
soldier, but he was decorated for shooting many of his friends.
With a camera.
</P>
<P>
   The only U.S. prisoner of war known to have taken photographs
while in captivity, Spinelli, 83, has donated more than 400
negatives he shot in German stalags to the National Prisoner of War
Museum in Andersonville. He was honored this month when the museum
opened an exhibit of 92 of his little-seen pictures, taken in three
German POW camps between 1943 and 1945, each at the risk of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Sanchez, the museum's chief curator, maintains that
Spinelli deserves the Medal of Honor, because every time he took
one of 1,200 pictures, ``he was performing way beyond the call of
duty.'' Sanchez is spearheading a campaign by the National Park
Service to convince the Pentagon that Spinelli deserves the
nation's highest award for heroism and valor.
</P>
<P>
   The negatives were sought by museums around the country.
Spinelli says he decided ``Andersonville should get them because
it's the one place that honors all POWs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big coup for us,'' Sanchez says. ``It's
unbelievable.'' According to the museum, no other American prisoner
in any war has managed to take photographs inside a prison camp.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is timed to coincide with the second anniversary of
the POW museum, erected to honor all U.S. war prisoners. After
Memorial Day, the exhibit will be sent to the 8th Air Force Museum
near Savannah, then to the Fort Benning National Infantry Museum
and, next January, to the state Capitol in Atlanta. Museums across
the country already are lining up to get it after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told these negatives are priceless,'' says Spinelli,
who owned a jewelry store in New York before retiring to
Hallandale, Fla., in 1989. ``But money you could spend and forget
about it. I want the collection to be available to all Americans,
so they will know what POWs and all soldiers endure. I told my son,
`Money doesn't do nothing. Let's donate them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spinelli's pictures capture both the grim realities of POW life
_ a Russian prisoner shot dead reaching for a cigarette, Americans
sleeping outdoors to escape their lice-infested barracks _ and the
sometimes humorous ways the soldiers learned to cope _ GIs clowning
as women, playing baseball or just goofing around. One baseball
picture shows Mickey Grasso, who made the major leagues after the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Other images show the mundane side of camp life: men carrying
water, walking away from the latrine, dividing food parcels from
the International Red Cross, cooking over small stoves or standing
near dreary barracks in deep snow. One photo shows Spinelli himself
_ he'd handed his camera to a friend _ reading a letter from home
beside a Christmas tree loaded with homemade decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted into the Army in 1941, Spinelli was assigned to a combat
photography training unit because he had taken pictures in high
school and loved cameras. Rising to the rank of sergeant, he was
told to photograph whatever reflected GI life.
</P>
<P>
   After he landed in North Africa, for several months the only
action he saw was awards ceremonies. But on Valentine's Day 1943,
Spinelli and a dozen other men were assigned to take some German
POWs to the rear. They got lost, and ``all of a sudden we were
right in the middle of the Battle of Kasserine Pass,'' he says.
``In no time we were surrounded by Germans.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a prisoner of the men who had been his prisoners.
``Prior to being caught, I spoke with the Germans and gave them
cigarettes and chocolates,'' he says. ``That paid off. I thought
they were going to kill us, but they treated us fine. They took us
out of our locked room for breakfast, lunch and dinner at a place
overlooking the Mediterranean.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, he was put on a plane for Sicily, then to Naples,
Italy. There, he boarded a reeking boxcar to Stalag III-B, near
Furstenburg, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   About six months later, the prisoners in Spinelli's camp began
receiving Red Cross parcels, which contained cigarettes. Some GIs
traded cigarettes to German soldiers, so he approached an older man
who claimed not to be a Nazi.
</P>
<P>
   They struck up a kind of quasi-friendship, and Spinelli offered
the German cigarettes in exchange for a camera and film.
Surprisingly, the German agreed, and soon handed over a compact
Voightlander Besser 20mm folding bellows camera. (Spinelli is also
donating the camera to the Andersonville museum.)
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Spinelli was trading cigarettes regularly for film,
and even a tripod. The German even took the film to a nearby town
and had prints made, which Spinelli carefully hid.
</P>
<P>
   ``My orders were to take pictures of anything that would be of
interest to us, so I took the chance and took them,'' Spinelli
says. ``If they'd have caught me, I'd have been a dead man. Cameras
were strictly verboten.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told we were going to die anyway,'' he adds. ``At that
age, I didn't have any fear. If I'm gonna die later, so I die
sooner, and at least I have left evidence behind; they will know
how Americans lived in a POW camp.''
</P>
<P>
   To take the pictures, he attached a strap to the camera that
allowed it to hang down to waist level and concealed it in baggy
paratrooper pants. ``The guys would watch out for me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Spinelli kept taking pictures after he was moved to Stalag
III-A, just south of Berlin, in January 1945. Somehow, the guards
who searched the prisoners overlooked his camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``God was with me. If they'd have found it, I wouldn't be here
now.''
</P>
<P>
   By spring, Russian troops were closing in. One morning, all the
Germans were gone. Spinelli, who had lost 35 pounds to 115 during
his imprisonment, hitched a ride to the American lines. He arrived
in New York in June.
</P>
<P>
   He showed his pictures around, and got them published in a YMCA
pamphlet. But when he contacted Time-Life Books, he was turned
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The editor had them on his desk for four weeks,'' Spinelli
recalls. ``Being young, I got disgusted and said, `You don't want
to publish them, give 'em back.' I put them in my closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight years later, Time-Life editors stumbled onto the
YMCA pamphlet at the Library of Congress, contacted Spinelli and
published several of his photos in a book, ``Prisoners of World War
II.'' Later, in 1988, when President Reagan went to Moscow, CBS
News did a piece on Russian and American POWs, and Spinelli had a
few minutes of fame, along with several of his pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, only a few have been published. When he tried to strike a
deal with Yale University _ his negatives in return for tuition for
his three grandchildren _ he was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Now a widower bowed by a severe case of osteoporosis, Spinelli
remains feisty when recalling his years as a POW. ``I almost died
several times,'' he says. ``One time I got shot through the pants,
just below the groin, when I went over the warning fence for a
baseball. Two holes in there. Guess it's good I'm bowlegged.''
</P>
<P>
   He credits his faith for his survival, but also a determination
to do his duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told to take pictures,'' he says, ``and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
