<HEADER>
A4420 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LUXURY-BOATING-COX     04-12 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-BOATING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (Eds: with box material at end)
 &HT;    How Do You Spend $5 Million?: Whatever Floats Your Boat
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It cost nothing to think like a rich
man.
</P>
<P>
   So I had to ask yacht salesman Charles Amante the crucial
question:
</P>
<P>
   If a guy's got 5 million bucks to spend on a boat, where will he
and his Elizabeth Shue-look-alike be doing their nude sunbathing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right this way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled. At the high-end of a mega-boat show, it's all
about sex.
</P>
<P>
   And the 100-foot Tarrab, a drop-dead opulent yacht, is sexy. The
Tarrab was among 1,000 boats on display at the 15th annual Palm
Beach Boat Show this spring.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before the boat show began, or ``fluff and buff''
day, Amante took me to the ``sunpads'' atop the on-deck Jacuzzi _
the perfect spot for a tan. He showed off the handmade walnut
cabinets, the second Jacuzzi in the ``King's Cabin,'' twin Detroit
Diesel engines _ 1,450 horsepower each _ full-marble bath in the
No. 2 stateroom, cedar-lined walk-in closet, the eucalyptus wood
vanities, the black granite galley floor, the CD stereo system and
two Sub-zero freezers.
</P>
<P>
   For fish you'd catch?
</P>
<P>
   Amante offered a sympathetic you-poor-middle-class-fool smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, probably for caviar,'' he said. ``This yacht is built for
very opulent entertaining and long-distance cruising.''
</P>
<P>
   It took German and Italian craftsmen in Buenos Aires more than a
year to build the 25-foot-wide yacht, which is made with all U.S.
parts. Roughly the equivalent of a floating four-bedroom condo, it
has six sleeping rooms, seven bathrooms, a pilot house, main galley
and crew galley. There is also an outdoor wet bar and a salon at
the stern, which features couch, chairs and a wide-screen TV in a
remote control cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The yacht also has two of everything _ two freshwater pumps, two
generators, two engines _ just in case you break down in the middle
of your cruise to France.
</P>
<P>
   You and seven of your friends and family, plus crew, could
luxuriously cross the Atlantic to Europe in about 10 days. The
yacht can cruise at a comfortable 10 knots (12 mph), or a hurried
20 knots (25 mph).
</P>
<P>
   But that cruise will cost. For $40,000 to $50,000, a service
will deliver the yacht, or you can fill the 11 gas tanks with
diesel and sail yourself.
</P>
<P>
   A fill-up for the Tarrab costs about $4,000, and it burns about
20 gallons an hour. And don't forget maintenance. Upkeep will cost
you $150,000 to $200,000 a year, including your year- round
captain's salary ($60,000 to $80,000) and one mate ($20,000 to
$30,000).
</P>
<P>
   You could offset those costs by renting out the yacht for
$35,000 a week, but Amante says buyers at this level can afford to
not have strangers sleeping in their nautical bed.
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of buyers. New-boat sales, according to the
National Marine Manufacturers Association, jumped 20 percent over
1998 to $23 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Amante says his inventory is limited because yachts are
custom-made, but he sells four to six luxury jobs each year,
starting at $1.5 million. About 90 percent of his buyers pay cash _
``no stock market whizzes lately. It's been tried and true money.''
</P>
<P>
   Amante has no doubts the Tarrab will sell. A Philadelphia man
rich from the e-commerce biz flew down recently in his private jet
for a test cruise. He said he'd get back to Amante. And what if
someone walks up and buys it this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   ``You snooze, you lose,'' says the salesman, with his finest
ain't-this- a-great-country smile.
</P>
<P>
   THOSE 80-FOOT SUPERYACHTS ARE `IN'
</P>
<P>
   _ New boat buyers on average are 48 years old and earn $50,000
per household; 27 percent are women.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sale of superyachts _ 80 feet or longer _ has doubled the
past five years from 2,700 to more than 5,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ It costs $1 million a year to maintain a $10 million yacht.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 325-foot Christina O, where Grace Kelly and Prince Rainier
celebrated their wedding and Aristotle Onassis wooed Jackie, sleeps
36 and is available for charter. The price was $2.8 million for the
recent Millennium New Year's. The Talitha, owned by Paul Getty,
sleeps 12 and rents for $393,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Netscape-Silicon Graphics founder Jim Clark has placed an
order for the largest privately owned yacht, a 300-foot job that
will take four years to build in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Sunday Telegraph London, New York Times., National
Marine Manufacturers Association, Los Angeles Times
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
