<P>
   SMUGGLING-CHILDREN (Mexico City) _ Veronica Negrete Sanchez, 27,
is one of hundreds of mothers in Mexico who claim their children
were stolen or kidnapped, never to be seen again. They suspect
their children were sold for illegal adoptions, prostitution or
forced labor. At a time when the U.S. Congress has called for
better cooperation in tracking American children abducted during
custody fights to other countries, including Mexico, the issue of
missing Mexican children gets barely a mention. By SUSANA HAYWARD.
(For photo information, contact the San Antonio Express-News photo
department at 210-250-3297.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SMUGGLING-SISTERS (Piedras Negras, Mexico) _ The national
paranoia about Mexican children being taken to the United States
for black market adoptions, or worse, appeared confirmed after one
nationally publicized smuggling case. Although some impoverished
Mexican mothers gladly sell their children, ostensibly for a better
life on the other side, a great many more say their babies are
stolen or kidnapped. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   SMUGGLING-SEX (Washington) _ Amid startling testimony from
illegal immigrants who were pressed into service as sex slaves,
U.S. lawmakers are considering strengthening laws against
involuntary servitude and coercion. ``This is one of the cruelest
human rights abuses,'' says Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., warning
that the practice ``has increased dramatically over the last 10
years.'' By GARY MARTIN. (Also will be filed in the ``w''
category.)
