<HEADER>
A4454 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN13-COX     04-12 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arts foundation should take over monument to junk
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Today I'm starting the movement to save the
Cathedral of Junk.
</P>
<P>
   We need a wealthy yard art patron to step up with a large wad of
cash to preserve this significant South Austin work of art. Michael
Dell, where are you when we need you? I want to see a picture in
the newspaper showing a bunch of guys in suits holding up one of
those 3-by-5-foot cardboard checks. Let's start Friends of Junk.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Hannemann, 37, who rents a small house, created the
Cathedral of Junk in his Bubbaland back yard. It's three towers of
stacked junk wired together, the tallest tower standing 32 feet
tall. Vince carefully crafted each pile. ``It's all stuff one
person could pick up and find,'' he said. ``All you need is a
burrito and a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Vince is tired of dealing with it, so he's
taking it down piece by piece and selling it a chunk at a time.
Vince begs you to please not come by and visit the cathedral. ``I
feel like a dung beetle sometimes, rolling this big ball of
(provide your own noun here) around,'' Vince said. He began
disassembling the Cathedral of Junk a week ago Friday, and he hopes
to have it completely gone within a year.
</P>
<P>
   This monument to recycling should be maintained. It took Vince
11 years to build it. The work looks like what you'd get if you
picked up everything set on the curb in South Austin on bulky trash
day and piled it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have over 700 bikes and I have over 200 TVs in it, and
everybody underestimates those two things by a factor of 10,''
Vince said. Also in there, according to the text on Vince's
Cathedral of Junk T-shirt, are McDonald's Happy Meal toys, ``a few
G.I. Joes,'' rear-view mirrors, pinball machines, a plastic Jesus,
vacuum cleaners, crutches, urinals, coffee makers, Weedeaters,
blenders, shopping carts, typewriters, sewing machines and riding
mowers. As the pile grew, folks would come by and dump their junk
in Vince's driveway for him to use. So the cathedral was also a
public service, since it meant people didn't have to drive to the
dump.
</P>
<P>
   The artwork is so enormous that you can climb up to the top of
the tallest tower through a tunnel of junk on a series of stone
steps and stepladders. I struggled up there and sat on lawn
furniture at the top, and it seemed sturdy. ``There's no place for
anything to fall,'' said Vince, whose day job is doing stucco.
``The thing is like a Chinese puzzle. It's all interlocking.''
People will stand in line for two hours to climb the tower, Vince
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize I was building a tourist attraction when I
started this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the problem. Vince isn't much of a people person, and
he's fed up with dealing with the media and the public coming by to
see his masterpiece. (He doesn't charge admission, but he takes
donations.) The questions annoy him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me why,'' Vince said. ``Why ask? I was just having
fun. And now I'm through playing with my toys. I'm going to put
them up. It's rude to leave your toys lying around. So I'm going to
put them up and move someplace else. There's more toys where this
came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince said he wants to move to a small town and build an even
bigger pile of junk.
</P>
<P>
   I think we could talk Vince into letting us preserve the
Cathedral of Junk with the right amount of money, and if we made it
so he doesn't have to deal with the crowds. This is South Austin's
version of The Orange Show, a collection of discarded materials put
together by a Houston postman that now has its own arts foundation.
Shouldn't Vince's trash get the same recognition? Somebody with
some bucks needs to fund Vince's work before he takes it completely
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get an arts foundation together to give tours. Vince could
continue to live in the rent house out front, while little old
ladies in tennis shoes give tours of the junk and do the talking
for him.
</P>
<P>
   The work started out small before Vince started to add on. ``It
was just hubcaps along the fence, and it got carried away,'' he
said. Then the curiosity seekers started coming in droves. Vince
said his place is overrun by visitors Fridays through Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Vince has had enough of them. ``It's a huge headache for me, and
that's part of the reason I'm closing it down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Let's pay him for his work and save the cathedral before it's
too late.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
