r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN13-COX     04-12 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lies, mistakes will always be part of memories of Davidian
disaster
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ In a few days it will be a full seven years since
a startled nation watched in horror as a boiling fire consumed the
Branch Davidian compound that held scores of men, women and
children a few miles east of here.
</P>
<P>
   The April 19, 1993, fire appeared to start in an upwind corner
of the compound where a government tank had battered a hole in the
building while injecting massive quantities of disabling military
CS tear gas into the structure.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Mount Carmel building was on the point of collapse
due to a prolonged tank and gas assault on Davidian leader David
Koresh and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the government was through tormenting the Davidians
with psychological warfare tactics. There would be no more
negotiations. The 51-day siege of the religious sect was over.
</P>
<P>
   Every viewer of the live satellite feeds beamed from the scene
knew that the decision had been made to launch a final assault.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the nation approaches the seventh anniversary of the
fire, it is clear that the government failed to achieve the
finality it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   An example of this failure was how the event inflamed thousands
of Americans already distrustful of the government.
</P>
<P>
   One particularly dangerous anti-government malcontent exploded a
truck bomb outside a federal office building in Oklahoma City on
April 19, 1995, the second anniversary of the final assault. The
explosion killed 168 people.
</P>
<P>
   The government attempted to put the Mount Carmel incident to
rest by producing a three-volume, 1,000-page report filled with
self-praise and no blame. The Justice Department investigation of
itself and the FBI was an obvious whitewash despite Attorney
General Janet Reno's response to criticism of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should get blamed if they did something wrong,'' she
said. The idea that no one did anything wrong in an obviously
botched undertaking grated on the nerves of many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the recovery of 76 charred bodies, including 21
children, was a clear indication that a great deal went wrong in
the attempt to take Koresh and others into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had to be wrong when Reno and FBI tactical agents
decided to launch a final assault on the compound over the vigorous
objections of FBI behavioral experts and negotiators who warned
that the action could end in tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The whitewash report meant the government blew another chance to
close the books on Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was discovered that the FBI lied about its actions
during the final tragic assault on the Branch Davidian compound.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, FBI and Justice Department officials steadfastly
argued that agents did not fire pyrotechnic devices during the
final assault, right up to the discovery of evidence recovered from
the compound that contradicted government claims that agents did
not use incendiary devices during assault.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape was discovered with a soundtrack that contains
discussions among FBI Hostage Rescue Team members in which
permission was granted to fire incendiary tear gas cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the American people had been misled, and, once
again, any hope of putting closure to the tragedy was dashed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new investigation by a special counsel has run up a tab
exceeding $11 million as it attempts to find out who did what and
why seven years ago just east of here.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, some of the surviving Branch Davidians are
preparing to go to trial to settle their lawsuit against the
government over what happened seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The April 19 anniversary date will be remembered for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
