<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-FILE     04-12 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: For years I've heard Queen Elizabeth referred to as the
richest woman in the world. But a recent article said she was only
the eighth-richest British woman, worth $400 million. Can you
explain? If she isn't the world's richest woman, who is?
</P>
<P>
   A: Estimating the queen's wealth is difficult. For example, are
castles included? What about paintings and statuary?
</P>
<P>
   As the earlier article explained, Business Age magazine
published a report in 1995 saying that Queen Elizabeth's wealth
would amount to $3.4 billion if her art collection were added,
along with her properties, such as Buckingham Palace and Windsor
Castle. That figure, by the way, prompted a complaint by Buckingham
Palace to Britain's Press Complaints Commission, resulting in an
admission by the magazine that it might be legally difficult for
her to sell Buckingham.
</P>
<P>
   An even wealthier royal in Europe is Queen Beatrix of Holland,
with a net worth of $5.2 million, according to Guinness World
Records 2000. But even she isn't as well off as America's own Helen
and Alice Walton, widow and daughter of Wal-Mart founder Sam
Walton. Forbes estimates that each are worth $16 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the names of the lawyers and/or law firms
representing plaintiffs in the race discrimination case against
Coca-Cola? How may they be contacted?
</P>
<P>
   A: The plaintiffs' attorneys include Cyrus Mehri of Mehri,
Malkin &AMP; Ross (202-822-5100) and Lamar Mixson of Bondurant, Mixson
&AMP; Elmore (404-881-4100).
</P>
<P>
   Q: When approaching a city on any Interstate highway, we see
signs such as ``Atlanta 42 miles.'' Where is ground zero for the
cities?
</P>
<P>
   A: In large cities, the mileage is given to the center of the
city, if at all possible. In smaller cities in more rural areas,
where the Interstate highway passes near but not through the city
limits, and where there are many different routes going into the
city, the mileage given is the best estimate of the average
distance to the city center.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have seen several references saying the 13 stars on the
Confederate flag represent the 13 Confederate states. But every Web
site I go to for a list of the states shows only 11. Can you
explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's correct to say there were 11 Confederate states, but the
two additional stars can be explained. The 11: Texas, Louisiana,
Arkansas, Mississippi, Tennessee, Alabama, Georgia, Florida, South
Carolina, North Carolina and Virginia. Even though they stayed in
the Union, Kentucky and Missouri are the other two, because
secessionist groups in each set up separate state governments and
sent delegates to the Confederate Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the current salary for U.S. senators and
representatives? What fringe benefits, such as insurance, health
care, travel expense accounts, retirement, office and housing
expenses, do they receive?
</P>
<P>
   A: The salary is $141,200 a year, automatically rising with the
cost of living unless Congress specifically votes down the
cost-of-living increase.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Taxpayers Union, major fringe benefits
include allowances for such things as offices, staff salaries,
travel between Washington and home states, and communications with
constituents, which for House members averages $800,000-$1 million
a year, and for Senate members $2 million-$3 million a year; the
use, for a small fee, of the Capitol Hill Office of the Attending
Physician; a $3,000-a-year federal income tax deduction for the
necessity of maintaining two residences; and priority care at
Walter Reed Army Hospital and Bethesda Naval Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   They also are eligible to participate in a 401(k) retirement
plan with the government matching contributions dollar-for-dollar
up to 10 percent of their salary; and an inflation-protected
pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   Minor perks include free parking at Capitol Hill; reserved and
free parking at National and Dulles airports; free firewood
delivery if they have fireplace in their office; free plants and
reproduction prints from the National Gallery to decorate the
offices; and, for the Senate, a taxpayer-subsidized barber shop.
</P>
<P>
   The Taxpayers Union points out that some perks from previous
years have been eliminated, such as free car washes and daily
delivery of ice to their offices.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What determines the date thatEaster Sunday falls each year?
</P>
<P>
   A: The moon and mathematics determine the date of Easter each
year. Easter is the Sunday after the Paschal Full Moon, which
limits the dates it can occur from March 22 through April 25.
Orthodox Christians calculate differently, and Orthodox Easter can
occur as late as early May.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Council of Nicea in A.D. 325, Easter wasn't always
celebrated on a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The system that became the basis of the Gregorian calendar and
the table used to determine the date of Easter for most Christians
was formed in the 16th century. All algorithms used to date Easter
since then are based on these early tables.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many calendars written through the ages that set
the dates for Easter, but ``Carter's Algorithm,'' which settled the
dates from 1900 until 2099, used a simpler method.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was very surprised that the Methodist Church paid for one
of the lawyers for Elian Gonzalez's father, Juan Gonzalez, to go to
Cuba. Can you print the names of the Methodist officials who made
this decision?
</P>
<P>
   A: The decision was made by a denominational agency of the
United Methodist Church, the General Board of Church and Society,
in Washington. That group established a voluntary fund for
contributions to send Washington attorney Gregory B. Craig to Cuba
in early March.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thom White Wolf Fassett, top staff executive of the
Board of Church and Society, said no United Methodist Church
dollars are being used for the fund paying the lawyer, and that the
effort is supported only by outside contributions. Fassett said
Craig's visit included a three-hour meeting with Juan Gonzalez and
other family members.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett said the fund is not unusual, because the board has a
history of working in the area of child advocacy. He also said the
United Methodist Church is a leading advocate for abolishing the
U.S. embargo against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in Charleston Mayor Joseph Riley. He's been in
the news lately concerning the Confederate flag controversy. Where
was he born and raised?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Democratic mayor of Charleston, S.C., was born and raised
in Charleston. He is a 1964 graduate of The Citadel and received
his law degree from the University of South Carolina in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Riley organized a 120-mile march from Charleston to Columbia
that began April 2 to protest the flying of the Confederate flag
over the state Capital.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
