<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4460 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-FILE     04-12 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Rudy Ruettiger, the Notre Dame football
bench-warmer who inspired the movie ``Rudy''? He is married? Does
he have children?
</P>
<P>
   A: Daniel ``Rudy'' Ruettiger has written three books and is
semi-retired from the motivational talk and public speaking
circuit. Ruettiger, portrayed by Sean Astin in the 1993 film,
decided to devote more time to his wife and daughter. The family
moved from Chicago to Henderson, Nev., and since 1994 his talks
have been limited to occasional appearances before church groups.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I can't find any Massachusetts quarters. I hear they pulled
them because the anti-gun groups didn't like the Minute Man with a
musket in his hand. Are the coins out of circulation ?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Massachusetts quarters, over a billion of them, are in
circulation, says Michael White with the U.S. Mint. The first set
of the series of quarters for each state came out a year ago.
Citizen groups in each state, directed by each state's governor's
office, design the specialty quarters. White said there haven't
been any problems with the designs, and that and the Massachusetts
quarter will remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did Andres Galarraga get the nickname of ``the big cat''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Galarraga, 38, got the name early in his career because of
his quickness and cat-like reactions, says Atlanta Braves spokesman
Glen Serra. The first baseman signed with the Atlanta Braves from
the Colorado Rockies three years ago, but was out last season for
treatment of cancer in his back.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many different ways are there to qualify for the Masters
?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are 17 specific qualifications or lists of golf
tournaments that golfers must have won, or rankings they must have
achieved, to be invited to the Masters. But the committee also can
invite international players not otherwise qualified.
</P>
<P>
   The list of invitees includes U.S. Open champions, British Open
champions, the current U.S. Amateur champion, PGA champions, the
first 16 players in the previous year's Masters and the first eight
players in the previous years' U.S. Open Masters Tournament
champions are on the list, as are the three leaders on the current
year's official PGA Tour money list.
</P>
<P>
   Making it to the Masters is only the first hurdle. At the end of
36 holes of play, the field is reduced to the best 44 scores and
ties, plus those within 10 strokes of the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Millions of us watched Warren Beatty win the Irving Thalberg
Award during this year's Oscars ceremonies March 26. Who is
Thalberg, and why is the award presented in his name ?
</P>
<P>
   A: Warren Beatty was the 36th Hollywood producer to receive the
Irving Thalberg Award since 1937. The award for a body of work is
voted by the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences' Board of
Governors, and is not always given every year.
</P>
<P>
   Thalberg died at age 37 in 1936 of pneumonia after a short but
illustrious career. He became a producer at the Universal Film
Manufacturing Co. at 20, and three years later became vice
president and head of production for Louis B. Mayer. After Mayer's
studio became part of Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, Thalberg was vice
president and supervisor of production until his death eight years
later.
</P>
<P>
   The award is a solid bronze head of Thalberg on a black base. It
is 9 inches tall and weighs just over 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the president dies, is the first lady entitled to a
pension? Is there a widow's clause ? What if the they get divorced?
</P>
<P>
   A: A former first lady is entitled to $20,000 a year for the
rest of her life if her husband dies. According to the White House
press office, she isn't entitled to the pension if there is a
divorce. Presidents receive $151,000 a year after they leave
office.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard a report that 41,375 people were killed on U.S.
highways last year. How does that compare with gun deaths?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most recent statistics for deaths from firearms in the
United States lists 32,436 in 1997, according to the National
Center for Health Statistics. That includes all types of firearm
incidents. The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration lists
41,471 highway deaths in 1998. Preliminary figures for 1999 are
41,345.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was Elian Gonzalez brought back to shore by the fisherman who
discovered him or by the Coast Guard?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 6-year-old was rescued by two fishermen, Sam Ciancio and
his cousin Donato Dalrympler. They found him clinging to an inner
tube 3 miles off Fort Lauderdale, Fla., last Thanksgiving Day.
Elian's mother died along with 10 other Cubans when their boat
broke apart off the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend said a homeless man tried to sell him a blanket that
he said was given as an incentive for completing the census form.
Are the homeless filling out more than one form to get these
incentives?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lance Robertson with the U.S. Census Bureau said that they
are increasing efforts to get the homeless to fill out forms, but
they aren't giving out blankets or anything else. He said the only
thing census workers are allowed to give is advice. He also said
that in the past, the homeless population was undercounted, and
they are increasing efforts to get information and to prevent
duplication. Robertson said to call 1-800-471-9424 with any census
questions or concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the breakdown of oil imports from the OPEC nations,
and how does this compare with U.S. domestic oil production?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries produces
about 40 percent of the world's crude oil and 14 percent of its
natural gas. At the end of 1996 (the most recent figures
available), OPEC had 76.6 per cent of the world's total proven oil
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1996 report, the United States was the No. 3 oil
producer. Saudi Arabia was No. 1, producing 8.1 million barrels per
day. Countries of the former Soviet Union were No. 2, at 6.9
million bpd. The United States produced 6.5 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After reading about the production of oil, I am wondering:
How many gallons are there in a barrel of oil?
</P>
<P>
   A: A barrel contains 42 gallons of oil.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
