<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4463 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-CELEB-RECIPE13-COX     04-12 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEB-RECIPE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dine like your favorite celebrities: Now that's cooking
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Singer Sting and his wife, Trudie
Styler, live in the Lake House, a 16th-century country manor in
England. Styler and their chef, Joseph Sponzo, wrote ``The Lake
House Cookbook, which includes the recipe for sea bass with sauteed
wild mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   SEA BASS WITH SAUTEED WILD MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons grapeseed oil, plus extra for brushing
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh chanterelle mushrooms (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces fresh black trumpet mushrooms (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 sea bass (about 2 pound each, filleted)
</P>
<P>
   6 sprigs tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 lemon, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh peas
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs mint
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a medium frying pan over medium-high heat, heat 1 tablespoon
of the butter and 1 teaspoon of the oil. When the butter starts to
foam, add half the shallots and cook for 30 seconds before adding
the chanterelles. Cook for 1 1/4 to 2 1/2 minutes, stirring
frequently. Add a pinch of salt and pepper. Remove from heat,
transfer to a baking dish and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe the frying pan with a paper towel. Add another tablespoon
of butter and 1 teaspoon of oil and repeat the cooking process with
the remaining mushrooms. Transfer them to the baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to a very low setting (200 degrees). Place
mushrooms in oven to keep warm until ready to assemble the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large steamer pot with water and add tarragon and lemon
to the water. Bring to a boil. Season the sea bass on both sides
with salt and pepper. Brush the bottom of a bamboo steamer with
oil. Just before serving, place the steamer over the boiling water,
sit the bass in the steamer skin-side up, cover and steam for 4 to
5 minutes depending on the thickness of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a small saucepan, place the peas, 4 tablespoons of
water, 1/2 tablespoon of butter, the mint and some salt and pepper.
Heat gently until just warm then discard the mint.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place sea bass skin side up on plate. Arrange a
quarter of the chanterelles on each plate and scatter the black
trumpets on the other. Place a pile of peas next to each type of
mushroom.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   OPIE'S BUTTERSCOTCH PECAN PIE
</P>
<P>
   From ``Aunt Bee's Mealtime in Mayberry''
</P>
<P>
   FOR TWO PIES:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine, melted
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   2 8-inch unbaked pie crusts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pecans, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 package (6 ounces) butterscotch morsels
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat together margarine, eggs, sugar and syrup.
Pour equal amounts into both pie shells. Top both pies with equal
amounts of the nuts and morsels. Bake for 50 minutes in a 350
degrees oven.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 8-inch pies.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY'S YACHT CLUB GALLEY ONION CHEESE SOUP
</P>
<P>
   From ``Cooking with Mickey, Vol. II''
</P>
<P>
   3 large Spanish onions
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock or broth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon mace
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mild cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a 4-quart sauce pot on medium heat. Add onions
and saute until lightly browned. Add flour and cook an additional 5
minutes until butter and flour are well blended. Slowly add milk
and chicken stock, stirring constantly to prevent lumps. Season
with salt, pepper, and mace and continue to cook until soup
thickens. Whisk in egg yolk slowly and add grated cheese. Simmer
for another 5 to 10 minutes, stirring occasionally to prevent
burning. Remove from heat. Serve immediately. Makes 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   This was prepared for rock group Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   SEASONAL VEGETABLE PUFF PASTRY
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced white onions
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sun-dried tomatoes, poached and julienned
</P>
<P>
   4 cups julienned assorted vegetables (broccoli, asparagus,
cauliflower, carrots, etc.)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon herbs de Provence (or any herb mix)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cream cheese, chunked
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 8-inch squares puff pastry dough
</P>
<P>
   2 cups grated mozzarella cheese or Gruyere
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, whipped
</P>
<P>
   In a large saute pan, heat the olive oil and saute the garlic
and onions over medium heat for 2 to 3 minutes. Add the mushrooms
and saute an additional 2 to 3 minutes. Add the tomatoes and
vegetables and saute 5 to 6 minutes more. Add the herbs de Provence
and cream cheese chunks. Stir and continue to saute.
</P>
<P>
   As the cheese begins to melt and create a creamy sauce, add salt
and pepper to taste. Remove from the heat and set aside. Place the
pastry squares on a lightly floured pastry marble or cutting board.
Using half of the grated cheese, place equal amounts into the
center of each square.
</P>
<P>
   Place equal amounts of the vegetable cream cheese mixture over
the cheese. Use the remaining grated cheese to top the vegetables.
Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the edges of the pastry squares with the egg mixture. Fold
over a corner to meet the opposite corner, forming a triangle.
Press the outer edges together with the prongs of a fork and clean
up the edges with a pastry/pizza cutter if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Place the vegetable pockets on a nonstick baking sheet. Brush
with remaining egg mixture and bake for 12 to 15 minutes. Can be
served as a side dish with a Florentine sauce or as a vegetarian
entree.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Backstage Pass,'' by John D. Crisafulli, Sean Fisher,
and Teresa Villa, Cumberland House, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   GRANDMA VANASCO'S APPLE-AND-CHEDDAR STUFFED PORK CHOPS
</P>
<P>
   4 12-ounce center-cut pork chops, cut about 1-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 Golden Delicious apple, peeled, cored and cut into 12 slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Using a sharp knife, cut a deep pocket into the center of each
chop. Stuff each pocket with 3 apple slices and 2 tablespoons
cheese. Brush the chops with oil and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Build a charcoal fire in an outdoor grill, and let burn until
covered with white ask. In a gas grill grill, preheat to high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the coals heaped in a mound in the center of the grill. Do
not spread them out. Lightly oil the cooking grate. Place the chops
over the coals and cover. Grill, turning once, until seared on both
sides, about 5 minutes. Move the chops to the cooler, outside
perimeter of the grill. In a gas grill, grill on high until seared
on both sides, about 5 minutes, then adjust heat to medium.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook until an instant-read thermometer inserted into
the center of the meat of the pork chop reads 155 degrees, about 10
to 15 minutes. Serve immediately. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From Firefighter Thomas Vanasco, from ``The Firehouse Grilling
Book'' by Joseph T. Bonannno, Jr., Broadway Books, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED ZUCCHINI WITH VEAL OR CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   7 large zucchini (about 4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium onion, chopped ( 1/2 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground veal or chicken
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grated imported Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plain dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Trim ends of zucchini, then cut 6 of them into thirds. Using a
melon baller, scoop out and discard the centers of the zucchini
pieces. Set aside. Chop remaining zucchini and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat 1 tablespoon of the oil over
medium-high heat. Add the onion and cook for 2 minutes, stirring
frequently. Add chopped zucchini, garlic, and thyme and cook,
stirring frequently, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer mixture to a bowl and set aside. In the same pan, heat
the remaining oil over medium-high heat. Add the veal or chicken
and cook, stirring, until browned, about 5 minutes. Add the wine
and bring to a boil. Return the onion mixture to the pan, cover,
reduce heat and cook for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover the pan and continue to cook for 2 minutes to reduce the
liquid. Transfer the mixture to a food processor and pulse for
about 10 seconds, or until finely chopped. Add the cream and
Parmesan and process 5 seconds longer, just to blend. Season with
salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the inside of the zucchini pieces with salt and pepper.
Fill the zucchini pieces with the veal mixture, piling it about 1/2
inch over the top. Arrange the stuffed zucchini pieces in a baking
dish and sprinkle them with bread crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 25 minutes or until zucchini are tender.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From Colin Cowie's ``Effortless Elegance,'' HarperCollins,
1996.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
