<HEADER>
A4464 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CELEB-COOKBOOKS1     04-12 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CELEB-COOKBOOKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebs add spice to cookbooks
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Well, gawwwwly! Aunt Bee's gone and
written another cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   No, wait. It's Ken Beck and Jim Clark, authors of ``Aunt Bee's
Mealtime in Mayberry'' (Rutledge Hill Press, 1999) who've penned
the recipes in their second volume representing the doddering
sweetheart who fed Andy, Opie and the gang in the TV town of
Mayberry, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Their first book, ``Aunt Bee's Delightful Desserts,'' was
followed by another one cashing in on the name of another fictional
cook: Mary Ann, one of the castaways on Gilligan's Island (``Mary
Ann's Gilligan's Island Cookbook,'' out of print).
</P>
<P>
   Beck and Clark tapped all their friends for recipes to fill the
books _ they admit they're not cooks. The dishes represent foods
they say would have been served in the circumstances of the sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes are home-style and simplistic. The books focus on the TV
show dialogue, still shots from the shows and plot themes spelled
out for the fans; foods are secondary.
</P>
<P>
   But today, everyone's writing a cookbook. Celebrities, caterers
to celebs, and wannabes are publishing recipes with varying degrees
of sophistication and success.
</P>
<P>
   TV shows of the past have inspired a number of quasi-cookbooks.
``The Bewitched Cookbook, Magic in the Kitchen'' and ``Secrets of
the M.A.S.H. Mess: The Lost Recipes of Private Igor'' are examples.
Elinor Donahue of ``Father Knows Best'' added her recipes to ``In
the Kitchen with Elinor Donahue: Favorite Memories and Recipes from
a Life in Hollywood'' (1998, Cumberland Publishing).
</P>
<P>
   There's Suzanne Somers, whose weight-loss and fitness plans
often show up on infomercials. She wrote ``Get Skinny on Fabulous
Food'' (1999, Crown) with her dietitian, Diane Schwarzbein. It's a
low-carb, low-fat diet that Somers claims has kept her trim. The
recipes work, however; there's culinary backbone to support them.
</P>
<P>
   Another trio, John D. Crisafulli, Sean Fisher and Teresa Villa,
cook for the rock stars and their band members, and they've penned
``Backstage Pass,'' (Cumberland House Books, 1998). They dish
morsels of gossip about Billy Joel, Aerosmith and Elton John, among
others, while giving out the recipes for achiote chicken or Tuscan
pasta salad. Their catering recipes also are legit, and most sound
as though most of the aging stars are watching their diets.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Schwartz, a former Tequesta caterer, takes us to the
tables of movie stars in his book, ``Chef Harry and Friends:
Sharing the Joys of the Table,'' (Sourcebooks, 1997). He gives us a
glimpse of entertaining in celebrity settings, as does Colin Cowie
(``For the Bride: A Guide to Style and Gracious Living,'' Delacorte
Press, 2000), who has his own upscale entertaining show on the
Romance Network. Both have written comprehensive cookbooks with
tips on presenting beautiful foods at beautiful parties to the
beautiful people.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the beautiful people write their own cookbooks. Singer
Sting and his family moved into a huge country house and made it
into an organic farm on 60 acres. Sting's spouse, Trudie Styler,
got with her chef to write ``The Lake House Cookbook'' (Clarkson
Potter, 1999), a feast of recipes focusing on the organic produce
from their gardens. The recipes are articulate, and Styler's story
about restoration of the house and gardens, and her views on
organic foods are interesting reading on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's singer Jane Siberry's manager _ Bob Blumer. Food
Network TV fans will recognize him as the Surreal Gourmet. But he
started out as a guy who cooked for friends and family and who
decided to write a cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrities of their own making are entering the cookbook
market as well. There's Dr. Andrew Weil, who has earned a following
with his specials on PBS. The best-selling author now has a
cookbook to follow his health plan, ``Eating Well for Optimum
Health'' (Knopf, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   New York firefighter Joseph T. Bonanno Jr. is a celebrity among
his peers and has been featured on cooking shows as well. His
latest book, ``The Firehouse Grilling Cookbook'' (Broadway Books,
1998), gives the professional's take on cooking with fire. He
tapped firefighters from around the country to contribute recipes,
and the book is down to earth and doable for the backyard griller.
</P>
<P>
   And Florida's largest celeb, Mickey Mouse, has his own cookbook,
too (``Cooking With Mickey,'' Vol. II). Fortunately, he allowed the
chefs who work for him to contribute the recipes. Another of
Mickey's cookbooks, ``Mickey's Gourmet Cookbook: The Most Popular
Recipes from Walt Disney World and Disneyland,'' edited by Victoria
Stasio, has just been released in paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
