<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-CO     04-12 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Elian, Microsoft and flag-burning
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Three things either I'm too dumb to understand
or their proponents are too dumb to explain to me:
</P>
<P>
   Sending Elian back to Cuba:
</P>
<P>
   Suppose this same sort of incident had occurred at the height of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose it involved East and West Berlin instead of Havana and
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   A mother is fleeing East Berlin with her son. She dies trying,
but the boy survives. His family in West Berlin takes him into
their home.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine the child being sent back to East Berlin by the
West German government? I can't imagine sending any innocent
person, especially a child, back to a communist country, even if
it's to his father.
</P>
<P>
   What am I missing?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling against Microsoft:
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is good at what it does. What it does it does better
than anybody else. As a result the government is punishing
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of who succeeds in business is made by the buying
public. What is the court doing in this?
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood grocery stores put individual shops out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarkets put grocery stores out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Warehouse discount centers are putting all sorts of big stores
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping on the Internet may well put everybody else out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to the concept of free enterprise? What has
happened to the concept of competition in the market? What has
happened to the idea that success succeeds?
</P>
<P>
   What am I missing?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Opposing laws against burning the American flag:
</P>
<P>
   No one says they're in favor of burning the flag.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of folks are saying they're not in favor of laws
against flag burning.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of free speech, they say.
</P>
<P>
   An American burning the American flag is an obscenity.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, obscenities are protected by freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, obscenities aren't allowed in public places.
</P>
<P>
   I say burn the flag if you want to. But do it in the privacy of
your own home. Do it naked if you want to. I couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   But in a public place, it's a provocative act that has the
potential of starting a riot _ not unlike yelling ``Fire!'' in a
crowded theater.
</P>
<P>
   You want to make a speech about burning the flag? Make a speech.
I don't know what's stopping you.
</P>
<P>
   What am I missing?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Not that the above little speech is likely to make any
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions:
</P>
<P>
   Elian will go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, to some extent, will be broken up by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   No law will be passed against burning the flag.
</P>
<P>
   And a majority of Americans will never know what they've been
missing.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
