<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DESTINYS-CHILD13-COX     04-12 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESTINYS-CHILD13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Destiny's Child gone wild
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ All-female R&AMP;B quartet Destiny's Child,
currently riding near the top of the Billboard charts with its
jilted-lover single ``Say My Name,'' recently underwent a lineup
transplant two months ago that still has many fans confused.
</P>
<P>
   Original members LeToya Luckett and LaTavia Roberson were
themselves jilted _ or else they quit, depending on who you believe
_ and were hastily replaced by two members who fit the same
profile: 18 to 19 years old, African-American, shapely and
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the same characteristics of Beyonce Knowles and Kelly
Rowland, the other two founding members who remain in Destiny's
Child. Beyonce is the daughter of the group's manager, Mathew
Knowles, and Rowland is under Mathew's legal guardianship.
</P>
<P>
   Things turned especially sour last month when the two former
members filed a lawsuit against the manager and remaining two
members, alleging that they ``went on a rampage to destroy (our)
careers.'' The lawsuit, filed in Harris County District Court,
describes Mathew Knowles as greedy and domineering, a man who went
so far as to dictate the diets of the girls and demand they keep
their virginity. It also details how Luckett and Roberson were kept
in the dark about recent appearances at the Soul Train and Grammy
awards shows so the new members could perform there.
</P>
<P>
   A phone call to Luckett's home in Houston was not returned. A
man who answered said Luckett and Roberson had been advised by
lawyers not to talk to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, neither the lawsuit nor the quick switcheroo of
members appears to have hurt Destiny's Child, which formed in 1996
and debuted with a minor track on the ``Men in Black'' soundtrack
two years later. ``Say My Name,'' off the group's triple-platinum
second album ``The Writing's on the Wall,'' (released last year,
before the membership meltdown) is its biggest hit yet. It follows
such past singles such as ``Bills, Bills, Bills'' and ``No, No, No
(Part II).''
</P>
<P>
   ``Say My Name'' was released to radio immediately following the
group's two Grammy nominations. The video, with nary a sign of
Luckett or Roberson, was shot last-minute to include new members
Farrah Franklin and Michelle Williams. It's now in heavy rotation
on MTV and BET's music shows.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, one of the originals left in Destiny's Child, credited
the group's flourishing success amid all the controversy to ``the
grace of God'' and ``the strong family unit'' between her, Beyonce
and Mathew Knowles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my sister, and he is truly like a father to me, so it's
going to take a lot more than something like this to break that
up,'' Rowland said, calling from Houston last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been bad vibes brewing for a long time, a lot longer
than anyone knew about outside of the group. This new situation is
just full of good karma and positive energy, and we've been so
blessed. In a month our record sales have tripled, and the fans
have stood by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said she and Beyonce did about 85 percent of the singing
on the group's albums. Indisputably, too, the pair had always been
the primary singers in concert. Rowland said that all might change
with the addition of Franklin and Williams, ``because they're both
extremely gifted and have a lot to offer to the vocals.'' Franklin
had been a dancer in one of the group's previous videos, and
Williams was a back-up singer for Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lawsuit, Rowland couldn't go into specifics of
the split with Luckett and Roberson. Before the interview, Mathew
Knowles said ``it's a legal issue, but it's also a dead issue,''
emphasizing the group is already looking past the controversy to
its future.
</P>
<P>
   The next few months could be especially vital for Destiny's
Child. The group is planning American tour dates with 'N Sync and
Britney Spears, plus its own tour of Europe, where ``The Writing's
on the Wall'' is enjoying even greater success. England,
especially, has embraced Destiny's Child as the new Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was telling us `Say My Name' would be the big hit off
the record, which was why we waited to release it as the third
single,'' Rowland said. ``I think people like the fact that it's
such a true-to-life song. Everyone goes through their own
heartbreak now and then. Our fans like to know that we go through
the same things they do.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems especially true in recent months. Said Rowland,
``It's been hard, personally, going through this. But we've been
praying, and we've stuck together, and I think we're already past
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
