<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSBOYS-INFLATE13-CO     04-12 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSBOYS-INFLATE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsboys working out the bugs with bring-your-own arenas
 &HT;    By James Lloyd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The big hook. That is what characterizes a
Newsboys' live performance as well as the group's pop-rock sound.
We're not talking about an implement that comes out of stage right
and yanks an off-key singer out of sight. Rather, it is that live
image or recorded bit that stays in the mind long after the show or
song is over.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, that hook might have been a spaceship that
delivered the Christian pop-rock band on stage, a giant microphone
that descended from the ceiling or a rotating drum kit.
</P>
<P>
   Well, fasten your seatbelt. This time the big hook is the venue
itself, an inflatable arena that seats 2,500 people, with standing
room for another 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   It's been the talk of the Christian music tour scene this year,
because it's never been tried in the States. And bass player Phil
Joel admitted, ``We had a few `teething' problems at the beginning
(such as trying to set up in 60-mph winds in San Antonio, Texas),
but it makes sense. No one's ever done this before. We're making it
up as we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   The bugs should be worked out by tonight, when the tour with
Sonicflood and Beanbag hits Xenia, which is more than half-way
through the band's 65-city tour.
</P>
<P>
   Two arenas are used, with one being set up in the next city
while the other is used for a show. A crew of about 50 assembles
the dome, and the traveling entourage includes seven trucks, four
tour buses and trailers carrying merchandise, caterers and so
forth. One of the trucks contains 24 bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The ``blow-up air domes'' have their own generators for climate
control and power, according to tour information, and a
tractor-trailer is converted into a 40-by-40-foot, in-the-round
stage that is flanked by two video walls. A million watts of
lighting is available, as well as 150,000 watts of sound.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff, Joel says, is that no one is farther than about 70
feet from the stage, so ``you can have eye contact with just about
everyone in the venue, which is really nice.'' Being in the same
place every night also reduces the variables, such as sound
quality.
</P>
<P>
   The Newsboys' Joel said the interest in the show and the venue
has been worth the adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every man and his dog has turned out to see this crazy thing
...,'' he said. ``Obviously, all the bands in the Christian realm
have come to check it out, and a lot of different secular promoters
and management and booking agents have come to see it because this
thing, this whole concept of taking out your venue could change the
face of touring.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
