<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA 0413: 'I was told to take pictures, and I did.'
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters.
Photos and a sig/locator map are available.)
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSONVILLE, Ga. _ Angelo Spinelli never shot a single German
soldier, but he was decorated for shooting many of his friends.
With a camera. The only U.S. prisoner of war known to have taken
photographs while in captivity, Spinelli, now 83, has donated more
than 400 negatives he shot in German stalags to the National
Prisoner of War Museum in Andersonville. He'll be honored today
when the museum opens an exhibit of 92 of his little-seen pictures,
taken in three German POW camps between 1943 and 1945, each at the
risk of his life. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOME-PROJECTS _ Tips on inspecting your home before compiling
that list of summer projects. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 25.
WITH cover illustration and detail photos.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: CoxNet has packaged and moved two stories that sing the
praises of life on the water. The stories _ including photos _ make
great packages in sports or features sections. The stories have
moved in the Lifestyle (l) category.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEBOATS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Three months ago, Jeff Walker and
his cats, Razz and Tazz, traded in their 2-bedroom North Austin
apartment for a floating neighborhood _ a seaworthy subdivision.
Walker and his two felines now share a $250,000, four-bedroom
houseboat on Lake Travis, complete with a 450-gallon hot tub,
central air and heat and three stereo systems. Walker, who owns a
medical imaging business, originally bought the houseboat to
entertain clients. ``I found out it was so much fun that I just
decided to live out here,'' said Walker. ``And I have a much bigger
swimming pool now.'' With the robust economy, houseboat sales are
soaring _ from $25,000 entry-level used boats to high-end models in
the mid-six figures. ``The economy has a direct impact on the
houseboat industry,'' said Steve Smede, editor of Houseboat
Magazine, who has seen subscriptions to his publications double
during the past five years. ``People have money to spend and
they're buying nicer things.'' Sales at Harborside Boats and
Yachts, one of the largest brokers of houseboats in the Austin
area, have risen 10 percent to 15 percent a year for the past four
years, fueled largely by the high-tech boom. (Breyer, Austin
American-Statesman) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LUXURY-BOAT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It cost nothing to think
like a rich man. So I had to ask yacht salesman Charles Amante the
crucial question:
</P>
<P>
   If a guy's got 5 million bucks to spend on a boat, where will he
and his Elizabeth Shue-look-alike be doing their nude sunbathing?
``Right this way,'' he said. Don't be fooled. At the high-end of a
mega-boat show, it's all about sex. And the 100-foot Tarrab, a
drop-dead opulent yacht, is sexy. The Tarrab was among 1,000 boats
on display at the 15th annual Palm Beach Boat Show this spring. On
the day before the boat show began, or ``fluff and buff'' day,
Amante took me to the ``sunpads'' atop the on-deck Jacuzzi _ the
perfect spot for a tan. He showed off the handmade walnut cabinets,
the second Jacuzzi in the ``King's Cabin,'' twin Detroit Diesel
engines _ 1,450 horsepower each _ full-marble bath in the No. 2
stateroom, cedar-lined walk-in closet, the eucalyptus wood
vanities, the black granite galley floor, the CD stereo system and
two Sub-zero freezers. (Lomartire, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
