<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     04-12 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV30-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., APR. 30, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am installing a chair rail molding along the walls in my
dining room and a long adjoining hall.
</P>
<P>
   Since some walls are longer than any single length of available
molding, I will have to join some lengths end-to-end in several
places.
</P>
<P>
   However, this poses a problem for me because in the past, even
if I made a neat looking butt joint that was almost invisible at
first, after a time the molding shrank and a slight gap became
noticeable, even though the gap was filled with a crack filler of
some kind.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a better way to make such joints working with ordinary
hand tools?
</P>
<P>
   A: The simplest way to splice lengths of baseboard or chair rail
molding is to form a scarf joint where the lengths meet, rather
than a simple butt joint.
</P>
<P>
   Scarf joints are much less noticeable than butt joints and even
if the molding does shrink, they show little or no gap.
</P>
<P>
   To make a scarf joint you simply cut off the end of each piece
of molding at a 45-degree angle so that the two ends will overlap
when assembled (as shown in the illustration).
</P>
<P>
   Coat the beveled ends with a little glue before assembling and
secure the joint with one or two small finishing nails or brads.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had a new front door installed and it does not fit into its
frame properly.
</P>
<P>
   The top corner along the hinge edge rubs against the jamb or
frame when the door is opened or closed and the whole door seems
slightly canted, or tilted at a slight angle, when fully closed.
</P>
<P>
   There is a gap of almost a quarter inch at the bottom between
the door and its frame along the hinge edge, and another gap at the
top along the opposite edge of the door.
</P>
<P>
   How can this be corrected without removing the door?
</P>
<P>
   A: It sounds as though the door really needs to be taken off and
then re-hung properly.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the hinge edge where the door tends to stick or
rub, it is probably because the hinge leaf is set too deeply into
the edge of the door, or into the door jamb.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes simply shimming the hinge leaf out from the frame (or
the edge of the door) by inserting a piece of cardboard behind the
hinge leaf will do the trick, but there is also the possibility
that the hinge leaf at the bottom of the door was not set deep
enough into the wood.
</P>
<P>
   A carpenter should be able to straighten this out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The walls in our bedroom and hall were recently painted after
we had quite a bit of peeling.
</P>
<P>
   The peeling areas were scraped and sanded, then primed before
repainting, but now after only a year and a half the paint is
peeling again.
</P>
<P>
   Can you tell us what may be the likely cause of this peeling?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are so many different reasons why paint peels that it
would be impossible to list them all here _ and unfortunately there
is no answer that will hold true in every case.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely that in your case there was something on the walls
that caused the paint to peel in the first place and apparently it
is still there _ causing the new paint to peel.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that you bring some large samples of the peeling paint
to a local paint store that sells the brand you have been using and
ask them to send these in to the paint manufacturer for analyzing.
</P>
<P>
   If this is not possible your best bet would be to scrape all the
peeling paint off again, then prime with a stain-killing sealer
before applying a new coat of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In one of your books you wrote about a method for preventing
the growth of moss on roof shingles by installing a series of heavy
copper wires horizontally across the roof, spacing them from the
ridge down to the eaves.
</P>
<P>
   If I do this, will this make the house more susceptible to
lightning strikes?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. It is only a high vertical structure that will tend to
``attract'' lightning _ such as a tall tree, mast, chimney, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The wires are placed on the roof simply for their copper content
_ as they oxidize, the run-off discourages the growth of moss.
</P>
<P>
   You could also use strips of copper, or even copper tubing; it's
just that wires would be less noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``MOLDING JOINT'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Forming a scarf joint instead of a butt joint is the
neatest method of joining two lengths of molding end to end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
