<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-12 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CLINTON TO CUBA TO RENO TO RAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON: Recent polls show the president's wife pulling
ahead of Rudy Giuliani in New York's U.S. Senate race; the
pro-Clinton forces in the media are already tossing dirt onto
Rudy's political grave. As a friend of mine in Illinois used to
say: Wait once!
</P>
<P>
   Because Giuliani is mayor of New York City, he is constantly
being critiqued by voters, pundits and political activists of every
persuasion. It stands to reason that his popularity will rise and
fall in reaction to the city's good days and bad days.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, New Yorkers will surely decide that they'd
rather be represented in Washington by a controversial mayor with a
brilliant record of accomplishment than by a controversial first
lady whose major claim to fame is her association with one of the
least trusted presidents in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   RUDY GIULIANI: On the other hand, Giuliani desperately needs to
re-evaluate his penchant for saying exactly what's on his mind.
Hasn't this guy ever heard of the phrase ``No comment''?
</P>
<P>
   JANET RENO: The U.S. attorney general seems to be gearing up for
a resolution of the Elian Gonzalez mess. It's about time. Reno
should have demanded that the 6-year-old Cuban boy's Miami
relatives send him back to his father months ago.
</P>
<P>
   All this malarkey about little Elian bonding with these people
who arbitrarily took possession of him after his mother drowned and
he was fished out of the Atlantic Ocean in November could have been
avoided if Reno hadn't let the turmoil drag on and on. The kid
should have been sent back to Cuba before politicians and activists
in Cuba and the United States turned his plight into one of the
most breathtaking examples of child exploitation the world has ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: It was bad enough that the vice president changed his
position on the Elian controversy in a transparent attempt to
appease Cuban-American voters in Florida. But even worse than his
flip-flop _ from supporting Elian's return to Cuba to backing the
Elian-must-stay-in-America crowd _ was Gore's mind-boggling
insistence that he had not switched sides.
</P>
<P>
   Can there be any doubt that Gore studied the art of
prevarication at the right hand of the master? It must have made
Bill Clinton burst with pride to see his protege unleash such a
blatant falsehood without so much as a hint of embarrassment. Only
the great ones can lie with such aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN MCCAIN: Would somebody please inform the senator from
Arizona that he ``lost'' the Republican presidential race? McCain
doesn't seem to understand that the losers in such a contest are
supposed to offer the winner their unqualified and enthusiastic
support _ or, at the very least, ride off into the sunset and keep
their mouths shut until further notice.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's flash-in-the-pan success in GOP primaries was hailed by
an adoring media as the second coming of Ronald Reagan, but it was
nothing of the sort. The worshipful news coverage and McCain's
knack for passing himself off as more than he is combined to create
the illusion that his campaign was a big deal _ and McCain is doing
his best to perpetuate the scam.
</P>
<P>
   You can't help but feel sorry for him, though. Limelight
withdrawal can be an extremely painful ailment.
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT RAY: Robert who?
</P>
<P>
   You know _ Robert Ray, the guy who replaced Ken Starr as the
independent counsel responsible for investigating Clinton's sex
life, among other things. Even though Starr threw in the towel _
and even though the federal law providing for the appointment of
independent counsels has expired and is in no danger of being
revived _ Ray says he's thinking about indicting Clinton after the
president leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Will this never end? Can't we just let this crumb Clinton
slither back to Arkansas or New York or wherever he plans to go
when his seemingly interminable second term finally ends?
</P>
<P>
   Starr left because he grudgingly accepted reality: Clinton beat
the rap.
</P>
<P>
   Ray should let it go at that.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
