<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4562 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-INTERNET-STEALS-BUSIN     04-12 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-STEALS-BUSINESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'D EVERYBODY GO?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: To purchase this ``separate-buy'' article from
Smart Money magazine, please contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate representatives:  
 &HT;    --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' business news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JASON TANZ  
 North American rights only 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It's been a quiet morning at Aggieland Supertravel in College
Station, Texas. The phones aren't ringing, and there has been only
the slightest smattering of foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   To keep busy, the five travel agents on duty have been printing
backlogged airline tickets and making small talk.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Claudia Walker, 28, is with a customer, a middle-aged,
mustached man who has come to Aggieland Supertravel with hopes of
sending his son to New York City cheaply ... and the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see what I can do,'' the travel agent says doubtfully.
But when she finishes checking everything available in Worldspan,
the agency's computerized reservation system, her expression has
not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' Walker says. ``The best I can do is nearly
$2,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Her customer is shocked. ``Can't you go on Priceline and try to
get a better price?'' he demands.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pause as Walker considers his question. He's
suggesting that she log on to the Internet and bid for a ticket,
bypassing the agency entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do that,'' Walker finally answers. ``If you'd like to
go home and try out Priceline, you certainly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later he's gone. The agents roll their eyes and laugh. A
cheap ticket to New York, the day before the flight? Who's be
kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Yet their laughter masks a very real concern. For, however naive
that customer may have been, there's a good chance they just lost
his fare to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet Age unfolds, few of us can rest easy, knowing
that our professions will be secure throughout the millennium _ or
even throughout our own lifetime. Like the Industrial Revolution
before it, the Information Revolution promises drastic and dramatic
change.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, it is still too early to say for sure how our
own businesses will be affected and how we will react. But that's
not so for travel agents: Theirs is among the first businesses to
face the threat of obsolescence head-on.
</P>
<P>
   With airline tickets, hotel reservations and travel information
readily available over the Internet, it's getting harder and harder
for travel agents to justify their existence.
</P>
<P>
   Online travel sales reached $4.2 billion in 1999, a number
that's expected to quadruple in the next three years, according to
Jupiter Communications, a New York research firm. (How does that
compare with travel agencies? Smaller firms like Aggieland
Supertravel _ agencies that take in less than $1 million in revenue
a year _ collectively had $4.3 billion in revenue in '97, the last
year for which Calmers Travel Group has data.)
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with the reduced commissions agents now get from
airlines and it's no wonder many agencies are simply going out of
business. In 1995, there were 33,000 independent agencies in the
United States. Now there are 13 percent fewer, according to the
American Society of Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for travelers _ or at least for those who prefer
the personal touch of a real, live human. A great agent can be a
true lifesaver for the harried traveler, offering not only
expertise but advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   The news is much worse for agencies and their owners. Running a
travel agency was once a nice way to make a decent, if modest,
living. Plus there were great travel benefits. But that's all
changed _ and it's reflected in the value of travel agencies
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, the selling price of the average
small agency has dropped by 60 percent, to around $96,000, says Bob
Sweeney, president of Innovative Travel Acquisitions, a firm that
specializes in the sale of travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be fun,'' Sweeney says of the travel-agency
business. ``Now it's a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggieland Supertravel, a typical small-town agency, shows just
how mismatched the battle is. Operating from a storefront office in
a strip mall just a few yards up Texas Avenue from Texas A&AMP;M
University, the privately owned firm is going head-to-head with
some of the world's deepest pockets _ from American Express (whose
American Express Corporate Services is the dominant corporate
travel firm) to Microsoft (whose Expedia is one of the most popular
travel Web sites).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got over 500 customer-service agents, and we're open 24
hours a day every day of the year,'' boasts Terrell Jones,
president and CEO of the Web site Travelocity. ``Most of our
competitors in the physical world can't say that.''
</P>
<P>
   .....
</P>
<P>
   Agent Heather Blakey joined Aggieland Super travel three years
ago. Then a fresh-faced 21-year-old, she came straight from the
Southland Institute, a Houston-based travel school, and was looking
forward to the free travel, to the familiarization (or ``fam'')
trips, to the great discounts and to the steady income.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was glamorous,'' she remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Today the best Blakey can do is stare wistfully at the
Continental Vacations brochures on the agency's walls. The reduced
and free fares have stopped coming from most of the airlines and,
while Hayes will encourage the agents to go on the occasional fam
trip (Blakey once took Princess cruise), she remains deskbound.
</P>
<P>
   During slow hours, she checks her stock online or flips idly
through Travel &AMP; Leisure.
</P>
<P>
   As for that stable income? Well, she worries about it. Blakey
keeps a manila folder in her desk, where she scrawls down every
commission that she earns each week. Only a small portion of those
commissions will go to Blakey; the bulk goes to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   But she breathes a little easier when she finds that she has
earned that week's salary, that Aggieland Supertravel is not losing
money by continuing to employ her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten really depressing, '' she says. ``It is just so
slow. We just don't have the business that we used to.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than depressing for 57-year-old Linda Fisher, whose
salary is her only source of income. (The agents earn an average of
$18,000 to $20,000 annually, according to Hayes.) Her precarious
future in the travel-agency business is downright scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really try not to think about it,'' she says. ``Especially
at my age, I don't know who would hire me if I didn't work for the
travel agency anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to keep their clients out of the Internet's clutches, all
the Aggieland Supertravel agents are pushing themselves harder and
harder to ``go the extra mile'' for their customers. It's gotten to
the point that they'll do just about anything for them.
</P>
<P>
   Glenna Laffey recently heard from a favorite client who'd moved
to Nebraska but still calls Aggieland Supertravel to plan his
trips. This time he was coming to town for a business meeting and
then planned to meet up with a friend afterward.
</P>
<P>
   As he made his reservations, Laffey, 56, could hear the customer
talking to himself _ he'd have to hire a cab to get to the meeting,
and then again to get to his friend's house. That would be costly
and inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can pick you up!'' Laffey offered. She did more than that.
Laffey met her client at the airport, drove him downtown for his
meeting, waited in her Honda Accord for 20 minutes while he made
his presentation, then drove him to a department store where he
needed to pick up some supplies. Finally, she drove him to his
friend's house. It was, she insists, ``no biggie.'' Her colleagues
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a client, you have to treat them with kid
gloves,'' Connie Lara says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet travel agents' advantages are being constantly chipped away
by the airlines and online companies, which lately have begun to
offer special Internet fares, cheaper even than those a travel
agent gets.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Lara estimates that she receives 10 to 15 calls a week
from potential customers who have found a fare on the Internet and
wonder if the agents can beat the price. Lara says she can beat or
match the fare 70 or 80 percent of the time, but she finds it
frustrating to always be playing catch-up to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that the Internet is out to get us, and the airlines
are out to get us,'' Lara says. ``We're going to be without jobs.
That's what's going to happen, unless something miraculous happens.
It's scary.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jason Tanz is a staff writer for Smart Money magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
