 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Tapas-Style Dishes Are Tops at Zibibbo   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Few preparations of asparagus are as delicious as
this recipe from Zibibbo.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spears are sauteed with leeks and seasoned with thyme,
garlic and chiles. Then the vegetables are doused in dry sherry and
red wine vinegar, and the liquid is quickly reduced to form a
glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Jody Denton, who also is the mastermind behind LuLu and
Azie in San Francisco, suggests serving this dish with slices of
crusty bread.
</P>
<P>
   This is only one of the many tapas-style dishes that has become
the hallmark of this Mediterranean restaurant in Palo Alto. The
menu includes some excellent rotisserie specialties and some great
dishes, including whole fish and pizza out of the wood-burning
oven.
</P>
<P>
   The tapas offer the greatest variety with creations from
Morocco, Italy, Spain and other Mediterranean destinations.
</P>
<P>
   From the exterior, Zibibbo looks like a quaint Victorian, but
the interior, designed by Cass Calder Smith, has the open look of
an urban loft. In addition, there's an impressive patio that takes
advantage of the pleasant Peninsula weather.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Zibibbo, 430 Kipling St. (between University Avenue and Lytton &LR; 
 &LR; Street), Palo Alto; (650) 328-6722. Lunch and dinner daily. &LR; 
 &LR; Brunch Saturday and Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Adding the sherry and vinegar. &LR;  These elements not only add
flavor, but they ``pickle'' the asparagus, keeping the spears
slightly crisp.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Cooking the asparagus and oil together. &LR;  Letting the two
ingredients heat up together makes for an evenly tender spear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ASPARAGUS &AMP; LEEK ESCABECHE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches medium-size asparagus spears, trimmed to about 4
inches in length
</P>
<P>
   1 small leek (white part only), well washed and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons thinly sliced garlic (preferably spring garlic, if
available)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 whole small dried red chiles
</P>
<P>
   Leaves from 4 fresh thyme sprigs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil and asparagus in a large saute pan over low
heat, rolling the asparagus around as the pan heats up. Once the
asparagus begin to sizzle slightly, add the leek and garlic. Season
with salt and pepper. Continue to gently stir until the leek begins
to soften, about 3 to 5 minutes. Add the chiles and thyme and
increase the heat to high.
</P>
<P>
   When the pan is sizzling, add the sherry and vinegar and boil
until only a few tablespoons of liquid remain, about 5 to 7
minutes. Stir in the parsley and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 120 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 8 g carbohydrate,
7 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 9 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
