EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Kosher Catches Up to Premium Brands 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Gerald D. Boyd &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Leo Rosten, in his humorous and informative book
about language, ``The Joys of Yiddish,'' provides this definition
for kosher: ``As a Hebrew-Yiddish word, kosher generally means only
one thing: fit to eat, ritually clean according to the dietary
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosten goes on to explain that ``rabbis said that eating and
drinking are religious acts, for during them man partakes of God's
bounty.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the ``fit to eat'' requirement is as often applied to
drink, especially wine, as it is to food. And for many Jews and
others familiar with kosher wine, that means sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Many older observant Jews remember the days of sweet kosher
wines that tasted like Concord grape juice with alcohol. With the
'90s, the character and style of kosher wine began to change, as
Passover meals and celebrations of other Jewish holidays, called
for dry varietal wines with all the class and character of
nonkosher wines.
</P>
<P>
   The misconception is that kosher means inferior. Today's kosher
winemakers want you to know that is not true. So, what is a kosher
wine?
</P>
<P>
   Modern rules for making kosher wine include setting aside
equipment exclusively for the making of those wines. Further, only
certified kosher products, like yeasts and fining agents used in
winemaking, can be used in the production of kosher wines.
</P>
<P>
   An extra step used today with many popular kosher wines is
making the wine  &LR; yayin mevushal &LR; , or universally kosher. A mevushal
wine is where the grapes must be handled only by observant Jews.
The mevushal process is a flash pasteurization before fermentation,
which allows the wine to be handled by the general public and still
remain kosher. Kosher wine labels will carry the letter ``U''
circled to signify the wine was approved by the Union of Orthodox
Jewish Congregations and certified kosher for Passover with the
letter ``p'' on the label.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest suppliers of upscale kosher wines is the
Royal Wine Company, whose main brand is Baron Herzog, a line of
California varietal wines, such as Cabernet Sauvignon, Chardonnay,
Zinfandel and Sauvignon Blanc, in the $6 to $12 range. Herzog also
produces a super-premium line of three select varietal wines,
priced from $22 to $42.
</P>
<P>
   The other major California producer of kosher wines is Hagafen
of Napa Valley. Until 1996, Napa Valley's St. Supery made kosher
wines under the Mt. Maroma label, some of which might still be
available in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Wine Company also has a growing portfolio of imported
kosher wines, including Teal Lake, Australia; Alfasi, Chile;
Chateau Yon Figeac, Cotes du Rhone, France; Bartenura, Italy; and
the Gamla and Yarden wines of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Fortant de France, the popularly priced varietal wines from the
south of France, has three kosher varietal wines, priced at $10,
including Chardonnay, Merlot and Cabernet Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular producer of wines from the south of France is
Reserve St. Martin, produced by Les Vignerons du Val d'Orbieu. For
Passover, Reserve St. Martin has released 1999 kosher varietals
including Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot and Chardonnay, priced under
$10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; European Wine Treasures &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Christie's Los Angeles will be auctioning 1,400 lots of
Bordeaux, Burgundy, California and Italian wines from the private
collection of Henry E. Singleton, the founder and former CEO of
Teledyne, Inc. The two-day sale, April 14 and 15, will be held at
Christie's in Beverly Hills. A special presale wine tasting,
featuring 70 of the wines from the Singleton collection, will be
held on April 13, from 7-8 p.m. with a cost of $80 per person. For
more information, call Christie's Wine Department, at (310)
385-2603. To request a $30 catalog, call (800) 395-6300.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Q &AMP; A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ricardo Sander of Los Angeles was disappointed that Truchard
Vineyards was not mentioned in a recent Potpourri article on
Carneros Pinot Noir.
</P>
<P>
   The omission of Truchard certainly was not intentional... their
wines, especially Pinot Noir, Merlot and Syrah, are among my
favorites. But then, it's not possible to list or mention all of
the wineries that make good wine from Carneros grapes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gretchen Edgren, contributing editor, Playboy Magazine, is
interested in the piece that appeared on this page about Jim
Fetzer's biodynamic vineyard in Mendocino and was wondering how to
contact Fetzer.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fetzer, of the noted winemaking Fetzer family of Mendocino,
operates Ceago Vinegarden, on McNab Ranch Road in Ukiah. You can
contact Ceago at (707) 468-0377 or e-mail at  &LR; www.ceago.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
