<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: Far-Away Places Call the Adventurous Cook  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Depending on their ripeness, plantains can be as
filling and starchy as potatoes or as tender and sweet as bananas.
<P>
   I like them when they're somewhere in between green and
completely black. At this stage, they're tender enough to saute
quickly but not too sweet for dinner. Just be careful when sauteing
the plantain slices in this recipe, as the starchy fruit can burn
before you know it.
</P>
<P>
   The avocado cream is quite rich, a nice foil for the crisp-fried
plantains and spicy marinated fish. Add as much water as necessary
to get a desired saucy consistency, or replace the creme fraiche
with plain yogurt if you'd like a lighter dish.
</P>
<P>
   A note on swordfish: Although conscientious cooks tend to avoid
it because of dwindling stocks, the endangered fish are Atlantic
swordfish. If you are concerned about overfishing, make sure your
swordfish is from West Coast waters.
</P>
<P>
   For the 30-Minute Main Dish, we turned to Food Section intern
Noel Advincula for his Filipino Chicken Adobo recipe. The
combination of soy sauce and vinegar provides the traditional tangy
edge to the sauce, while coconut milk adds richness and complexity.
It's so good and easy you'll probably turn back to it again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   This week's weekend make-ahead recipe is based on the
meatloaf-and-potatoes of blue plate specials in days gone by. The
difference is that the potatoes go on top of the meat to form a
crust, sort of like a shepherd's pie, and they are spiked with
horseradish for extra flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Use a flat casserole dish instead of the standard loaf pan, or
each serving will get only a disappointingly dinky ration of
mashers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ROAST SWORDFISH WITH PLANTAINS &AMP; AVOCADO CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper + pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 to 2 pounds swordfish steaks
</P>
<P>
   3 ripe plantains
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe avocados
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon creme fraiche or sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Lime wedges
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the salt, pepper, cayenne, 1 tablespoon lime
juice and 2 tablespoons vegetable oil. Brush this mixture on both
sides of the fish. Place fish on a baking sheet lined with aluminum
foil.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the plantains and remove all tough fibers, using a paring
knife to make long slits through the skin if necessary. Cut
diagonally into 1/4-inch slices.
</P>
<P>
   Place the fish in the oven and roast until cooked through, about
10 to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place the remaining 2 tablespoons oil and the butter in a large
skillet over medium heat. (You may have to do this in batches.)
When the mixture foams, add the plantains and sprinkle with
cinnamon and a little salt. Saute until golden-brown on one side,
about 5 minutes, watching carefully so they don't burn. Flip the
slices, season with salt, drizzle with the honey and brown another
5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pit and peel the avocados, then mash to a pulp. Add 2
tablespoons lime juice, the creme fraiche and water to thin to a
smooth and saucelike consistency. Season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the plantains alongside the fish and spoon the sauce on
top. Garnish with lime wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 715 calories, &LR;   &LR; 37 g protein, 56 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 41 g fat (9 g saturated), 83 mg cholesterol, 1,276
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 15 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   NOEL'S CHICKEN ADOBO WITH COCONUT MILK
</P>
<P>
   This quick version of Philippine adobo was created by Food
Section intern Noel Advincula. Serve it with steamed rice.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot
</P>
<P>
   3 large skinless chicken half-breasts, bone-in
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons crushed black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop the garlic and shallot. Using a cleaver, cut each
chicken half-breast into 3 or 4 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the garlic, shallot, chicken, black pepper, bay leaf,
vinegar, chicken broth and soy sauce in a deep nonstick pan, cover
and simmer for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stem and derib the bell pepper, then cut into bite-size strips.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the adobo to a bowl, and remove the chicken from the
sauce. Wipe out the pan, add the oil and place over medium-high
heat. When the oil is hot, add the chicken and saute for about 11/2
minutes per side. Add the bell pepper and saute briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Return the adobo sauce to the pan, along with the coconut milk
and red pepper flakes. Simmer for 3 to 5 minutes, until the sauce
is heated through and flavors blend.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 290 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 10 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 19 g fat (11 g saturated), 51 mg cholesterol, 1,097
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   MEAT LOAF WITH HORSERADISH MASHED POTATO CRUST
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups panko breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions, cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   Leaves from 3 rosemary sprigs, minced
</P>
<P>
   21/4 pounds ground veal
</P>
<P>
   21/4 pounds ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 cup crushed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Horseradish Mashed Potato Crust
</P>
<P>
   9 russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly beat the eggs in a large bowl. Mix in the wine and
breadcrumbs; set aside to soften.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a skillet. Add the onions, garlic and
rosemary and saute until the flavors combine, about 4 minutes.
Transfer to a bowl and let cool briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Add the veal, beef, tomatoes, salt, pepper and Worcestershire to
the breadcrumb mixture and mix with your hands to combine. When the
onions are cool, stir them into the mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the meat mixture between two 3-quart baking pans or
casseroles. Cover with foil and bake for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the Horseradish Potato Crust:  &LR; Peel and quarter the
potatoes and place in a saucepan. Cover with water and bring to a
boil. Reduce to a simmer and cook until the potatoes are tender
when pierced with a knife, about 12 minutes. Drain and return to
the saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   While the potatoes cook, gently heat the cream with the butter
in a small saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   Mash the potatoes, then quickly stir in the cream mixture, the
horseradish and salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   After the meat loaf has finished cooking, increase the oven
temperature to broil. Discard some of the fat that has collected on
top of the loaves, and pour off some of the juices so the dish
doesn't overflow. Spread the mashed potatoes evenly over the top of
both meat loaves and broil for 5 to 10 minutes, until brown on top.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 735 calories, &LR;   &LR; 40 g protein, 30 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 49 g fat (23 g saturated), 301 mg cholesterol,
1,482 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
