<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-HAM-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Taste Panel Unwinds the Best Spiral-Cut Ham for 
 Your Holiday Table   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For some people, it's spring lambs, but for many,
Easter dinner is synonymous with ham.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spiral-sliced ham has become particularly popular at holiday
times because it makes the meal so easy on the cook. The meat not
only is fully-cooked, but presliced. It comes in sizes large enough
to serve family-size groups, usually with leftovers for sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   But you pay a premium for some brands _ almost $5 per pound in
some cases. That's as much as $40 for a half-ham, enough to serve
eight to 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted six brands of fully-cooked spiral-sliced
hams. In addition, four of our panelists shared some of their
favorite side dishes to go with ham to round out your Easter meal
(see recipes, this page).
</P>
<P>
   All of the hams were tasted as they are packaged. We did not use
any of the optional glazes that came with some brands. The hams
were tasted at cool-room temperature, not heated.
</P>
<P>
   The panel had two overwhelming favorites. The others came in
dramatically lower. In many cases, panelists felt the hams tasted
more of smoke or were too sweet. They also disliked the texture of
some hams.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors went to  &UR; Ashley &LR;   &UR; Farms &LR;  ($2.98 per pound, at
Safeway). Panelists commented on the good balance of salty and
sweet flavors, though one noted that it was saltier than some of
the other hams. Panelists also liked the texture. All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cook's &LR;  ($4.99 per pound at Andronico's) came in a close
second. Three panelists detected an artificial smoke flavor, but
two others thought it had the best ham flavor of all the hams.
Three would buy it; two might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Honeybaked &LR;  ($5.09 per pound at Honeybaked stores) came in
third. Panelists found the sweetness to be overwhelming, obscuring
the ham flavor. One panelist liked the smokiness, but another
thought the smoke tasted artificial. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dietz &AMP; Watson &LR;  ($4.99 per pound at Andronico's) came in
fourth. Panelists thought this ham was dry and bland. One found it
to be too salty. Others detected an artificial flavor. Some also
complained about the dry texture. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Draeger's and Safeway hams, but they
scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Main story followed by recipes in optional trim &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HERBED SWEET POTATO, BREAD &AMP; GOAT CHEESE CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Webber, chef-owner of Cafe Kati in San Francisco, loves the
combination of rich sweet potatoes with goat cheese in this crunchy
casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 celery stalks, cut into fine dice
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, cut into fine dice
</P>
<P>
   1 yam, peeled, cut into fine dice
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chicken stock or canned low-salt broth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   4 cups dried 1/2-inch bread cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, well beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup crumbled soft fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a heavy large skillet over medium-high heat.
Add the celery, green onions, onion, yam and garlic and saute until
soft but not brown. Add the wine and boil until the liquid
evaporates. Add the stock and raisins. Reduce the heat to low and
simmer 5 minutes. Transfer to a large bowl; let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Butter a shallow 11/2-quart
casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Add the bread cubes, eggs, rosemary and sage to the vegetable
mixture; stir to blend. Season with salt and pepper. Transfer to
the prepared casserole. Cover and bake 30 minutes. Uncover,
sprinkle with the goat cheese and bake until the top is golden
brown, about 15 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 270 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 31 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 12 g fat (7 g saturated), 93 mg cholesterol, 244 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POTATO, LEEK &AMP; CARROT CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Donna Katzl, chef-owner of Cafe for All Seasons in San
Francisco, serves this savory vegetable pancake to her family with
ham for Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 large leek, cleaned, thinly sliced (white and pale green parts
only)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound white potatoes, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a frying pan over medium heat. Add the leek
and saute until soft, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a food processor fitted with a large shredding disk, shred
the potatoes and carrot. Roll the potato-carrot mixture in several
layers of paper towels to remove as much moisture as possible.
Transfer to a large bowl. Add the sauteed leek. Season generously
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat,
tilting the pan so the oil covers the bottom evenly. Add the potato
mixture to the pan and pat down firmly and evenly. Cover and cook
until the bottom is golden brown, about 8 to 10 minutes. Uncover
and invert a large plate over the skillet. Carefully flip the
skillet over onto the plate, letting the cake fall onto the plate.
Slide the cake back into the skillet, browned side up. Cover and
cook until golden brown, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Slide the cake onto a platter. Cut into wedges. Sprinkle with
chives. Serve hot or warm.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 120 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 14 g carbohydrate,
6 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 8 mg cholesterol, 36 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ASPARAGUS &AMP; GNOCCHI CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Kim Severson dresses up store-bought
gnocchi for a wonderful side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 to 11/2 pounds asparagus, trimmed and cut into 1-inch lengths
(3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 (16- to 17-ounce) package gnocchi
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 small garlic clove, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese + additional cheese for
top, if desired
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Blanch the asparagus in a large
pot of boiling salted water for 1 minute. Using a slotted spoon,
transfer the asparagus to a colander. Cook the gnocchi in the same
pot of water for 3 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the cream, garlic, cheese and nutmeg. Lightly
butter a 9-inch square baking dish. Arrange the asparagus and
gnocchi in the dish. Pour the cream mixture over all. Sprinkle with
salt and pepper. Sprinkle additional cheese over the top, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until heated through and beginning to bubble, about 25 to
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 340 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 22 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 25 g fat (15 g saturated), 114 mg cholesterol, 154 mg sodium, 1 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; RED WINE APPLESAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author John Carroll has been a longtime member of The
Chronicle's tasting panel. He wasn't able to attend the ham
tasting, but he sent his favorite accompaniment recipe. He
frequently serves this instead of chutney, but notes that it has a
particular affinity for ham and barbecued pork.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds Golden Delicious apples (about 8 to 10), peeled, cored
and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (or more) dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the apples, wine, sugar, bay leaf and salt in a heavy
large saucepan. Bring to a boil. Cover and reduce the heat to
medium-low. Cook 20 minutes, stirring occasionally. As the apples
soften and become tender, mash them with a fork or potato masher,
leaving the sauce as smooth or lumpy as you like.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the raisins. Continue cooking, covered, for about 5
minutes. If the sauce seems too thick, add 2 to 4 more tablespoons
of wine and simmer for a minute or two. Remove the bay leaf. Serve
warm, at room temperature or chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 180 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 44 g carbohydrate,
1 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 15 mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Shelley Handler, consultant and food writer;
Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Julia
McClaskey, chef, Dine in San Francisco; Kim Severson, Chronicle
staff writer; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San
Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
