<HEADER>
A4575 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SOURCEOYSTER-SFCHRON &LR;      04-12 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCEOYSTER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 AT THE SOURCE: Pearls of Wisdom: Rich, pure water key to plump 
 Hog Island oysters   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  As animals go, oysters seem rather placid.
Actually, says Michael Watchorn, they are competitive creatures. If
if you don't separate the fast growers from the slow ones, the
little guys will be starved out by their voracious bigger brethren.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He should know. Watchorn has been growing oysters for nearly 20
years. He hadn't planned on that career, but right out of the
University of California at Berkeley, he found a job at an oyster
company in Monterey, and he got hooked on oysters.
</P>
<P>
   After a few years, he and fellow marine biologist John Finger
purchased a former general store built in the 1860s in West Marin,
obtained leases and set up the Hog Island Oyster Co., named for a
small island in the bay. The company, now co-owned by Terry Sawyer,
who previously worked at the Monterey Bay Aquarium, is the biggest
of five oyster farms on Tomales Bay and specializes in growing
oysters to be sold and consumed fresh. (Marin's biggest oyster
farm, the huge Johnson's Oyster Co., is located on Drakes Estero
and primarily raises oysters to be shucked and put up in jars.)
</P>
<P>
   Hog Island expects to sell about five million oysters this year,
all raised on wooden trestles anchored on 170 acres of the bay,
obtained from the California Department of Fish and Game under a
25-year renewable lease. Most of the acreage is on the north end of
the bay, within a quarter mile of the open sea. The water there is
richer in plankton, the oysters' food source, then it is further
south, and winter temperatures tend to hover around an ideal 40
degrees. Watchorn explains that even a few more degrees of warmth
can make the oysters grow fatter, which is not desirable: Plump is
good, fat is not.
</P>
<P>
   The Hog Island farmers employ the French growing method, first
putting the tiny seed oysters purchased from hatcheries in Maine
and on Puget Sound in nursery cages of extruded plastic mesh
anchored to the trestles. The constant movement of the tidal waters
keeps the small creatures rolling continuously, which produces a
deep cup and a plump oyster. Oysters that are raised in static
condition get long and ``snaky,'' Watchorn explains.
</P>
<P>
   Three times during the eight months the oysters spend in the
nursery, the cages get hoisted onto a barge and the fast growers
get sorted out to go into the second stage of their two-year
journey to the table, the grow-out period, during which they are
also housed in mesh cages, but in far smaller numbers than the
5,000 that go into the nursery cages.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Hog Island shipped the bulk of its production to
distributors. Now, almost half the crop is sold direct from the
farm in the small town of Marshall. There are also direct
deliveries to Buckeye Roadhouse in Mill Valley; Sam's Anchor Cafe
in Tiburon; and in the wine country, John Ash, Bistro Don Giovanni,
the Restaurant at Greystone and Gordon's in Yountville.
</P>
<P>
   Hog Island, rather than cultivating only one variety, gives its
customer four choices: the large, salty and slightly smoky
sweetwater (``which pays the bills,'' Watchorn says); the
button-small (seldom over two inches) sweet-tasting Kumamoto; the
medium-sized Atlantic, which displays assertive saltiness, and the
European flat or belon, which grows to about four inches and has a
slightly metallic, steely taste that ``people either love or
hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvesting at the right age is important. Age, not size,
determines taste and texture, Watchorn says. And, of course, purity
of water is essential. He and his partners have had to become
politically active, persuading responsible agencies to be more
vigilant in monitoring septic tanks on properties along the
shoreline and install more toilet facilities for kayakers and other
recreational users of the area. Being in a national marine
sanctuary helps, he says, but as filter feeders, oysters are so
sensitive to pollution that even one boater dumping sewage near
oyster beds can cause enormous damage.
</P>
<P>
   The oyster farmer puts his mouth where his money is: ``I love
oysters, clams and mussels (which they also grow) and abalone,'' he
declares, admitting that he sometimes forgets his wife, graphic
designer Marina Andriola's request to bring oysters home to
Sebastopol. When he does remember the oysters, they eat them raw on
the half shell, barbecued or fried.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite way of frying them is to coat them lightly in rice
flour seasoned with salt and cayenne, dip them in beaten egg, then
fry them quickly in peanut oil. For barbecuing, he prefers to shuck
the oysters, return them to a half shell, then top each one with a
teaspoon of sauce (garlic sauteed in olive oil, mixed with lemon
juice and a little butter for richness), then pop them on a covered
grill for a few minutes, adding chopped Italian parsley in the last
minute of cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   The Hog Island crew keeps a little sauce handy for eating
oysters at work _ a combination of rice wine vinegar, shallots,
lemon juice, a little pepper and cilantro. ``We call it hogwash,''
Watchorn says.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Hog Island Oyster Co., 20215 Highway 1, Marshall (about 10 &LR; 
 &LR; miles north of Point Reyes Station; (415) 663-9218. Open to the &LR; 
 &LR; public 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Wednesday to Sunday. Picnic area with &LR; 
 &LR; covered grills available; shucking knives, trays and gloves are &LR; 
 &LR; provided, but customers need to bring charcoal, beverages and &LR; 
 &LR; other supplies. Oysters are $7-$9 per dozen, depending on &LR; 
 &LR; variety. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Simple Preparations Let Bivalves Shine &QL;  &LR; 
Oysters are perishable, but they can be safely kept for a few days,
provided they are fresh when you purchase them and they are handled
correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The Hog Island Oyster Farm operators in Marshall recommend you
pack oysters cup-side down in a bowl and cover them completely with
a damp cloth or towel, making sure the cloth fits snugly against
the sides of the bowl and that it stays moist at all times.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure the oysters you buy in a store haven't been around too
long, you could ask to see the harvest tag, which is attached to
each shipment and lists all the facts _ place of origin, the
harvest date, etc.  &UR; This must be kept on file for 90 days by &LR; 
 &UR; restaurants and stores under state regulations, and while &LR; 
 &UR; retailers are not required to make this document available to &LR; 
 &UR; consumers, many will do so if asked. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A simple way to determine freshness is to check that no oysters
have opened. You also can pick up two oysters and knock them
against each other. They should sound almost like rocks. If the
sound produced is at all hollow, reject the oysters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
