<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4579 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      04-12 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED IT. Moving in
the ``E'' and ``L'' categories.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ``A MEMBER OF THE FAMILY'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Susan Merrell (HarperCollins, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This novel is built on a provocative idea but suffers in the
execution. Chris and Deborah Latham and their 3-year-old daughter
are the perfect family when they adopt an orphaned toddler from
Romania, but their dreams of a happy foursome are destroyed by
troubles from their new son's past. Because he was neglected as a
baby, Michael grows into a brutal boy _ his adoptive father calls
him ``amoral,'' incapable of love or socialization. By the time he
starts kindergarten, he is a danger to his classmates. Deborah's
efforts to help him and her determination to keep him in the family
even as he chips away a t her marriage are heart-rending.
Unfortunately, our sympathy for Michael is strained _ at times, he
is nothing less than demonic. Merrell also adds a distra cting
subplot about Chris Latham's past that culminates in a long scene
during which he and Deborah seem to forget that they've left
Michael at home, attacking his tutor. The book could do with less
plot and a defter touch with the lit tle boy at its heart.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``BEREFT'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Jane Bernstein (North Point, $24) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One evening in 1966, an Arizona State University student named
Laura Bernstein was stabbed six times as she was locking up her
bicycle behind the Casa Loma Hotel in Tempe. Later the same night,
17-year-old Jane Bernstein was in ed in her family's house in New
Jersey when she heard the telephone ring in her parents' bedroom.
Like a voyeur, she sneaked to their door and pressed her ear to it.
``Are you sure? Are you positive?'' she heard her mother say. Then
her mother hung up and said, ``Our baby is dead.'' In 1989, Jane
Bernstein came to Phoenix to see the place where her sister was
murdered for no reason, and for the next five years, she thought of
little else. This is her memoir, the story of a woman's troubled
life in the shadow of her sister's death, equal parts obsession and
avoidance. She writes of the murderer, a man named David Mumbaugh,
who died in prison in 1993. She was sad for him, she says _ ``not
sorry for him, but sad at the way this had turned out for all of
us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``FAIR BALL'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Bob Costas (Broadway, $21.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The oft-quoted Jacques Barzun line goes, ``Whoever wants to know
the heart and mind of America had better learn baseball.'' Bob
Costas is not convinced. ``All I can say, really, is that Jacques
Barzun scares me a little bit,'' he writes. Costas is not the
baseball romantic he's often made out to be. He's a Bull Durham guy
who never liked that other Kevin Costner movie about the gam e. And
he's here to remind you that on Opening Day 2000, the sport began
its seventh season as a dysfunctional operation, that fans were
``gamely hanging on out of loyalty, memory and sheer faith, long
after baseball itself had ceased to care much about any of that.''
He offers a cogent analysis of what went wrong and what might make
it right, and he hopes people have the will to read it. As he
points out, if Bobby Thomson's home run happened today, here's how
Russ Hodges would call it: ``The Giants win the pennant!! The
Giants win the pennant!! The Dodgers get the wild card!! The
Dodgers get the wild card!!''Isn't that exciting? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``AMERICAN POETRY: THE TWENTIETH CENTURY'' &QL; 
 &UR; (Library of America, $35 each) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is Dorothy Parker on Alfred Lord Tennyson: ``Should heaven
send me any son,/ I hope he's not like tennyson./ I'd rather have
him play a fiddle/ Than rise and bow and speak an idyll.'' We never
miss a chance to quote her, even when she's among more quotable
company. We also were happy to find Don Marquis here with archy and
mehitabel _ every collection of poetry needs a cockroach in it,
just to keep it honest. These are the first two volumes in a
four-volume set and include work written by poets born before 1914.
Organized by the poets' birth dates, there are multiple
contributions from the big guns _ Robert Frost, William Carlos
Williams, Carl Sandburg, Ezra Pound, e.e. cummings _ and surprise
showings by people such as Joe Hill, Ma Rainey, Cole Porter, Edith
Wharton, Bessie Smith and Tennessee Williams. They begin with Henry
Adams and end with May Swenson, and it's a long, pleasant journey
between.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
