<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4580 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEBS&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      04-12 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBS&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBS&AMP;MAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS.
STORY MOVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES) Here are Bill
Muller's reviews of a Website and current magazines: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEBSITE: www.dailynewspix.com
</P>
<P>
   The photo archive of the New York Daily News includes several
free features, including a gallery that showcases famous photos
taken over the years, many wit strong historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   From the main site, click on Photo Gallery, and you'll reach a
screen with `Greatest Hits'' and `New York Noir.'' The Greatest
Hits section includes a number of notable Daily News photos,
including the well-known Charles Hoff picture of the Hindenburg
zeppelin ablaze after exploding at Lakehurst, N.J., i 1937, plus
the obligatory duck-and-cover photo from a 1960s atomic bomb drill
and a portrait of John Lennon and Yoko Ono. There is also a Rosie
the Riveter photo from the World War II era, during which women
entered factories to replace men who were fighting overseas; a
photo of David Berkowitz, the Son of Sam killer, being led into
police headquarters; and poet Allen Ginsberg reading his work in
Washington Square Park.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Noir section is devoted to crime photos, including
the picture of Ruth Snyder being executed in the electric chair at
Sing Sing prison, the aftermath of the assassination of mobster
Albert Anastasia and several other graphic street crime photos.
</P>
<P>
   The site also features a portfolio work from Evy Mages, a Daily
News photographer who was named the New York Press Photographers
Association Photographer of the Year. There are several other
features, including a search engine for guests and members and a
link to the Daily News Web site (www.nydailynews.com). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MAGAZINES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ARCHAEOLOGY'S DIG'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to drag your kids away from those dreaded Pok mon cards?
Want to trick them into learning something? Then Dig, a bi-monthly
published by the Archaeological Institute of America, is for you.
It's archaeology for kids, chock full of interesting articles,
games, puzzles and cartoons, all based on ancient cultures and
discovery. Written in a straightforward, accessible style, the
magazine actually tries to make learning fun. Don't let the board
of education hear about this. Lead story, about the great pyramids
of Egypt, does a fine job explaining why the pyramids are such an
amazing feat of engineering (no slide rules, pocket protectors or
the Internet back in those days). Of course, it goes a little over
the top in quoting Napoleon, in the original French, remarking on
the pyramids. There is another good piece on how archaeologists
date artifacts, explaining how different items are found on
different levels of a dig, and how carbon-14 dating is used.
Another interesting piece trie s to determine whether Hercules
really lived, or is just a creation of Greek mythology and Michael
Eisner. Can you dig it?  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``BIOGRAPHY'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week's cover story profiles Paul Newman, salad dressing
entrepreneur and part-time actor. Naturally, the story is a fawning
piece of fluff, but the pictures are cool, stretching from Newman's
high school yearbook photo to studio shots of him in Cool Hand
Luke, The Sting, Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid and The Color
of Money, for which he won an Oscar. The story starts out talking
about how amusing Newman is, but none of the jokes he tells are
very funny. But he does, the author slyly notes, still have those
same blue eyes. Let's hope so. In the way of actual history, there
is a decent piece on John D. Rockefeller, founder of Standard Oil,
the mammoth monopoly that was broken up by a trust-busting Teddy
Roosevelt and turned into most of the gas stations you see on
corners today. The story also notes that Rockefeller turned
philanthropist in his later years, giving millions to education,
health care, churches and orphanages. Bully. In the Masters of the
Stunningly Obvious section, there's a story noting that movie star
Cameron Diaz is quite fetching. Bully, bully. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``DISCOVER'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lead story examines the hullabaloo around the Microwave
Anisotropy Probe (MAP for short), a NASA project that will catalog
microwave photons to answer the largest questions of the universe:
how old it is, how it will end, whether space is really infinite
and where exactly did I leave my car keys? The mission is a
follow-up to the Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE) that found the
faint afterglow of the Big Bang. If it survives its testing, and
launch, MAP will use its sophisticated equipment to recreate ``the
universe's baby picture.'' Another article notes that chimpanzees
speak in dialects, invent odd grooming styles and drum better than
most kids in marching bands, meaning they are closer to humans than
previously thought. And their TV shows are better than prime time,
too. In the category of Tediously Pointless Pursuits, a group of
climbers clambered up Mount Everest to stick a global positioning
device on top, to finally, once and for all, get its exact
elevation. And they got it. Plus or minus 7 feet. Doh!  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ROLLING STONE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cover story checks in on the Red Hot Chili Peppers, noting that
Flea and the boys are back on their game with the release of
``Californication,'' which the mag calls ``their finest sustained
work ever.'' Piece holds that the Chili Peppers have evolved from
half-naked out-of-control young turks to half-naked elder
statesmen, after 17 years and seven albums. Article's funniest line
points out that the Chili Peppers ``have had so many guitarists _
seven _ they could hold a reunion barbecue for them every summer.''
There is also a well-written piece on Levon Helm, drummer for The
Band (``The Night They Drove Old Dixie Down,'' ``Up On Cripple
Creek''), who is recovering from throat cancer and revisiting the
Delta blues and daughter Amy. In a Q&AMP;A, Latino heartthrob Marc
Anthony admits that he used to get sick to his stomach at the idea
of performing. Now he's engaged to a former Miss Universe. Go
figure. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-SMUGGLING-CHILDREN-2T     04-12 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLING-CHILDREN-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PARENTS OF MISSING CHILDREN FIND LITTLE SOLACE IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: For photo information, contact the San Antonio
Express-News photo department at 210-250-3297.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For nearly five years, Veronica Negrete Sanchez
has searched almost every corner of Mexico and parts of the United
States, looking for the baby stolen from her by two women dressed
as social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Negrete has even visited morgues and cradled dead babies,
including one she said was mutilated, searching softly with her
fingers for the distinctive mark that separates her child from
others.
</P>
<P>
   But she has never found that special spot on her baby's chest,
and DNA tests taken from her and the small bodies have confirmed
her doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Ivan Esquivel Negrete will be 5 years old May 26,
assuming he is alive. But the young mother with dark, sad eyes and
long black hair has not given up her search.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting tears, her chin quivering and mouth puckering, Negrete
whispers that it would be better to find out her baby, her
first-born, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray to God he will help me find out what happened. In the
best of circumstances, a good family has him, but I just don't
know,'' said Negrete, 27. ``I didn't stop crying until I got
pregnant again. The doctor said it was bad for my pregnancy. Before
that, I wanted to kill myself.''
</P>
<P>
   She is one of hundreds of mothers in Mexico who claim their
children were stolen or kidnapped from homes, schools, streets,
parks or malls, never to be seen again. They suspect their children
were sold for illegal adoptions, prostitution, child pornography,
forced labor and even for the trafficking of organs.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the U.S. Congress has called for better
cooperation in tracking American children abducted during custody
fights and taken to other countries, including Mexico, the issue of
missing Mexican children gets barely a mention.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where political and drug crimes get all the
publicity, where children are coddled and spoiled, it is Mexico's
dark secret: Babies, infants and teen-agers are disappearing. Some
accounts put the rate at one per day; others say it's much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Not much is being done about it, although legislation before the
Senate would increase jail time to a minimum of 60 years for a
kidnapper of a child under 12 years of age. The measure also calls
for the creation of a special agency, overseen by the federal
attorney general, to investigate crimes against children.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mexico has no national database with the names and
numbers of disappeared children and no single government agency
dedicated to finding them.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office oversees such cases, and since
1990 Mexico City's attorney general has operated the Center of
Support for Missing Persons, but it does not investigate
disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is among 28 countries that signed The Hague Convention on
Protection of Children and Cooperation in Respect of Inter Country
Adoption. Under the agreement, it is required to name authorities
responsible for controlling the trafficking of children.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion has been under way to create such a special agency,
but it has yet to develop. Mexican officials have been in contact
with the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children in
Alexandria, Va., to join forces. But it has yet happened.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are no official figures, there is no way to know
how many children run away, how many are taken in divorce or
separation disputes, how many are kidnapped for ransom, how many
are used in illegal adoptions or how many are used for prostitution
or child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   A special report published in 1998 by the United Nations Human
Rights Commission chastised Mexican officials for a ``hermetic and
defensive attitude still in a denial stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also lambasted Mexico's child legislation for not
being up to ``pertinent international standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common and visible sexual commercial exploitation of
minors in Mexico is prostitution,'' the report said. ``Children who
live in border states are more susceptible because these zones are
preferred in the production of child pornography for easy transport
to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a hidden crime known only to the affected: the mothers,
friends and relatives of a missing child.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people rob a bank, there are cameras. But if you steal a
child in circumstances no one sees, we are talking about an
invisible enemy,'' said Guillermo Gutierrez, who runs one of the
largest private organizations in Mexico dedicated to finding
missing children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a trace of anything,'' said Gutierrez, who heads
the National Foundation of Investigations of Stolen and Disappeared
Children and has been trying to establish links with the Center for
Missing and Exploited Children in Virginia. ``In the United States,
you have help from the government, from the FBI, from private
corporations. In Mexico we are on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez's organization is one of dozens of such private groups
throughout Mexico. In interviews in Mexico City with five
organizations, each reported to be working on an average of between
80 and 100 unresolved disappearances of children, many of them the
same cases.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
