<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-ORPHANS-AZR &LR;      04-12 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORPHANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIAN DETAILS UGLY CHAPTER OF RACISM AND INNOCENT YOUNG
VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: STORY MOIVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES.)
</P>
<P>
   Decades before political scandals cast a shadow over Arizona at
the end of the 20th century, a series of events in Clifton-Morenci
wrote an ugly chapter of state's history at the beginning of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chapter full of racism, anti-Catholic bigotry and
orphans dickered over like dry goods.
</P>
<P>
   While the 1980s and 1990s saw a governor deposed, a governor
indicted and stat legislators drawing up plans to secede from the
Union, no less shameful was the nasty tug of war that ensued over
40 homeless children sent west from New York in hopes of finding
new families.
</P>
<P>
   To officials of the New York Foundling Hospital, their plan
seemed simple: Place orphans with good Catholic families in the
wide-open spaces of the Arizon territory.
</P>
<P>
   How naive.
</P>
<P>
   Prejudice and politics proved insurmountable barriers between
the fair-skinned Irish foundlings and their would-be foster
parents, all of whom happened to be Mexican-American.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the territory's quest for statehood was
driving citizens to prove their American patriotism and resist
efforts to form one large state with the territory of New Mexico,
which had a higher percentage of Mexican immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   All of these factors converged in an episode that still causes
pain in the adjoining mining communities of Clifton and Morenci in
southeastern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   University of Wisconsin historian Linda Gordon has chronicled
these events in a her book, ``The Great Arizona Orphan Abduction''
(Harvard University Press, 1999), a work rich in detail about the
town and the scandal that pitted Anglo residents against their
Mexican-American neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Principal players were two nuns and a placement officer from the
New York orphanage, representatives of the local Catholic diocese,
Mexican families eage to adopt the orphans, White residents of
Clifton and Morenci bent on halting the adoptions and officials of
the Phelps Dodge Corp., whose economic caste system helped to
reinforce the notion that Mexican workers were inferior to Anglos.
</P>
<P>
   The story in ``Orphan Abduction'' is played out against the
backdrop of racial bia often tolerated in turn-of-the-century
America. Race meant not only Black and White, but also Irish,
German, Italian, Jew.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we call such divisions ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon opens her story on a night in October 1904 as a posse
arrives at the home of Margarita Chacon to demand the return of two
fair-haired orphans recently placed with Senora Chacon and her
husband, Cornelio.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several days, the Chacons would be only one of
many couples forced to surrender children promised to them by the
New York orphanage and their own parish priest, Constant Mandin.
</P>
<P>
   Father Mandin saw his Mexican parishioners as good Catholics
willing to take in foundlings. Anglos saw them as brown-skinned
kidnappers unfit to raise White children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AN EASTERN SOLUTION  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The children had come west on one of the celebrated orphan
trains operating in Eastern cities concerned with a growing
population of homeless children and street urchins.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, some children found loving new families. Some
found themselves valued only as unpaid farm labor.
</P>
<P>
   In Clifton-Morenci, a handful found homes, and a few were given
away as ``gifts,'' but the social climate prevented a generally
positive outcome. Most of the New York orphans reboarded their
train and were sent back for re-distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Beset by a strike and a devastating flood in 1905 _ events
coincidenta lly repeated in 1983 _ the residents of Clifton-Morenci
were left with wounds slow to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, whose academic specialty is women, families and labor
issues, discovered the orphan saga while reading histories of labor
disputes, in which the actions of Phelps Dodge are well-documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there were kids in this piqued my interest,''
Gordon said while vacationing in Portland., Ore., and on leave from
UW to teach at New York University. ``I came to understand the
story more and more as I went along ... I thought it was an amazing
story.''
</P>
<P>
   She also was intrigued by the racial aspect of a story that
involved not Blacks and Whites but ``Anglos,'' as she calls them in
the book, and ``Mexicans,'' as Mexican-Americans were known at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon began her research in 1994 and finished the book in 1998.
She made three trips to Clifton-Morenci during that time to
interview elderly residents and glean a sense of what the
communities were like 90 years before.
</P>
<P>
   Not all residents welcomed her inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Festering wounds had reopened during the strike of 1983, when
the communities once again split along ethnic lines.
</P>
<P>
   The strike destroyed once-thriving Clifton, Gordon said. Phelps
Dodge fired its protesters and replaced them with strike-breakers.
The town's young people moved away. Senior workers retired. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ANGRY COMMUNITY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, when Gordon arrived with pen in hand, some
residents refused to be interviewed. Even when she explained that
her interest was the 1905 orphan incident, conversations invariably
returned to the 1983 strike and the pain it had caused.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, some people opened up. One of Gordon's best sources was
the venerable Al Fernandez, a former mayor of Clifton and renowned
storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved to talk and had great stories,'' Gordon said of the
man who died in December at age 98.
</P>
<P>
   In Tucson, Catholic Church officials, eager to expose what they
believed had been an episode of anti-Catholic bigotry, made church
archives readily available.
</P>
<P>
   And in Phoenix, Gordon found a historian's pot of gold: complete
transcripts from a state Supreme Court trial whose verdict had
upheld taking the orphans from their Mexican foster parents.
</P>
<P>
   During that trial, even the attorneys for the Foundling Hospital
had ``concede'' that Mexican homes were inferior to those of Anglos
and probably unsuitable for White children.
</P>
<P>
   No Mexicans had been called as witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Bit by bit, Gordon pieced together the strange story. When the
train from New York pulled into the Clifton station on the evening
of Oct. 1, 1904, and unloaded its cargo of 40 weary children, Anglo
residents took notice.
</P>
<P>
   Where had these children come from, and where were they going?
</P>
<P>
   To their dismay, they discovered that the youngsters were
heading for their new homes. Mexican homes.
</P>
<P>
   Motivated both by prejudice and a sincere sense of concern for
motherless children, a group of Anglos, mostly women, began to
protest the placeme nt of the orphans. They and their husbands,
many armed with rifles, threatened Father Mandin, the sisters, the
placement officer, the bishop from Tucson and Mexican parents who
had the audacity to take the children into their homes and hearts.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HUMAN MERCHANDISE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anglos demanded that they be given the ``babies''as they fought
over the human merchandise like bargains at a rummage sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was upsetting to me,'' Gordon said of that chapter in her
research.
</P>
<P>
   With courts as high as the U.S. Supreme Court siding with the
vigilantes, the nuns eventually were forced to back down. One rainy
night, the Mexican families were ordered to turn over the children
to waiting Anglos. Fifteen of the orphans went to Anglo homes in
Clifton and Morenci. One child was sent to a Los Angeles family as
a ``gift'' from one of the law-enforcement officers. The rest were
returned to New York and found homes in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   No Mexican family was allowed to keep a child.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said she believes that Phelps Dodge helped foster the
prejudice that divided Mexicans from Anglos. Looking at blueprints
of company housing, she found that ``Americans'' had been assigned
homes with running water and flushing toilets, while the Mexicans'
accommodations were more primitive. The copper company rationalized
the disparity, she said, by asserting that Mexicans were used to
such conditions and aspired to nothing more. In truth, Mexicans
were upwardly mobile and sought parity with their Anglo neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Subjugating the Mexicans became a self-fulfilling prophecy as
poverty equated with inferiority and, in the case of the orphans,
immorality. Anglos hurled slurs at the foster parents, accusing
them of keeping dirty homes (untrue), being prostitutes (untrue)
and being prone to drink (Anglos ran the saloons).
</P>
<P>
   Although bigotry against minority laborers reared its head in
other pa rts of the country - Chinese workers often were vilified
on the West Coast - ``it became more deeply entrenched'' in
Clifton-Morenci, Gordon said.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MISGUIDED INTENTIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is not entirely unsympathetic to the Anglo women who took
back the orphans. Given the tenor of the times, they truly believed
that Anglo children belonged in Anglo homes and needed to be
``rescued '' from the clutches of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't always know their own motives,'' Gordon
speculates.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the officials of the New York Foundling Hospital
might not have fully understood the racial implications of their
proposal or exactly what the term ``Mexican'' meant. They knew the
Southwesterners as ``Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Gordon fault the nuns who buckled at the threat of
a well -aimed Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect them to be heroes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Great Arizona Orphan Abduction'' could be used in
high school and university history courses, its target audience is
a broad one, Gordon said. Anyone interested in history or in the
``true crime'' genre will find it absorbing.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said her book, already in its second printing, has
received good reviews from critics, and she finds that rewarding,
but she added that her favo rite reviews have come from former
residents of Clifton-Morenci.
</P>
<P>
   In their letters, she said, they tell her, ``You got it just
right.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at barbara.yost(at)arizonarepublic.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
