<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI COURT RULES THAT LEBANESE PRISONERS MUST BE RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG with CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Reversing a previous decision, the Israeli Supreme
Court ruled Wednesday that the government was not justified in
holding Lebanese detainees as ``bargaining chips'' for the release
of captured Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Following a hearing behind closed doors, the court ordered eight
of the 15 Lebanese being held in Israel released from prison
immediately. Seven others were in another group not included in the
petition considered by the court.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent of the seven are Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid, a
Shiite Muslim spiritual leader in the Hezbollah guerrilla movement,
who was abducted in 1989 from southern Lebanon, and Mustafa Dirani,
a leader of the Amal militia who was kidnapped in 1994 and also
transferred to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The two have been held by the Israeli army, apart from other
detainees, and their fate was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights lawyers said the court's ruling was broad and
should apply to all seven Lebanese whose release was not ordered
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for Israel's prisons excluded Dirani and Obeid
when she told Agence France-Press that ``all 13 Lebanese held by
the prisons authority will be released and returned to Lebanon as
soon as the technical arrangements have been finalized'' with the
International Committee of the Red Cross. She said the two detained
Lebanese leaders were not under the control of the prison
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting the sensitivity of the case, the supreme court
delayed releasing the 50-page decision so it could be reviewed for
classified information. Instead, the court issued a one-paragraph
summary of the 6-3 ruling by the panel of nine judges.
</P>
<P>
   The terse announcement left unclear whether the judges had
decided that the government does not have the right to hold
hostages in general, or whether their ruling applied only to
hostages who do not pose a clear and present danger to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision said that Israeli law on administrative
detention does not grant the Defense Ministry the right to hold
hostages. The decision was written by the court's chief judge,
Aaron Barak, who had written the earlier ruling in 1997 upholding
the detention of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The office of Prime Minister Ehud Barak released a statement
saying that he had been briefed on the high court's ruling and
respected the decision. ``Although the prime minister believes that
Israelis should continue to hold the detainees for a certain
period, he will act in accordance with the high court ruling,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has long faced international pressure to justify its
imprisonment of the Lebanese, some of whom have spent more than a
decade behind bars without charges against them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Lebanese were held to exchange for a missing Israeli air
force navigator, Ron Arad, who was captured after being shot down
in 1986 over southern Lebanon and has not been seen since. His
mother, Batia Arad, told Israeli Radio that ``the supreme court
abandoned Ron today.''
</P>
<P>
   Three other Israeli soldiers missing since a tank battle with
Syrian troops in 1982 are also thought to be prisoners-of-war,
though Syria has not acknowledged their captivity.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese hostages were seized inside their country by
Israeli commandos and Christian militiamen allied with the
Israeli-backed Southern Lebanese Army and held to trade for the
missing Israeli soldiers. The existence of the hostages in Israel
was kept secret for many years. The government did not admit
holding the hostages until 1998, six months after the court upheld
their detention in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A 16th Lebanese hostage, Ghassan Dirani, a former bank clerk,
was freed a week ago for reasons of mental health after more than
13 years in detention. Dirani had been abducted by a Christian
militia group in Beirut and turned over to Israel because he is
related to the Amal leader, Mustafa Dirani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
