<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-SMUGGLING-SEX-HNS &LR;      04-12 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLING-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOVERNMENT WEIGHS TOUGHENING LAWS AGAINST SEXUAL SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note nature; filed in ``i'' and ``w'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Maria's voice is a whisper, but her lurid tale of
being taken from Mexico and sold as a sex slave in Florida is a
damning indictment of the growing problem of the international
trafficking of women and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, at age 18, she was moved from one mobile home
to another in rural Florida, where she was forced to service up to
35 men per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weekends were worse,'' Maria said. ``Our bodies were utterly
sore and swollen.''
</P>
<P>
   She knew how many men she had been with from counting the
wrappers of condoms the migrant farm workers purchased for $25 _
``tickets'' that were exchanged for intimate time with the young
woman. ``I could not believe this was happening to me,'' Maria
said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who is now receiving counseling in the United States,
testified before a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee earlier
this month, describing her ordeal before a packed hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never ever have done this work. No one I know would
have done this work,'' she said through an interpreter, Virginia
Coto, a lawyer with the Florida Immigrant Advocacy Center.
</P>
<P>
   Coto said the sex trafficking ring that snared Maria also preyed
on Mexican girls as young as 14, like Rosa, a child from Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put it behind me. I still feel shame. I was a decent
girl in Mexico. I used to go to church with my family,'' Rosa said
in a statement submitted to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and other federal agencies estimate that
about 1 million women and children are held against their will,
raped, beaten and sold to the highest bidder each year worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   About 50,000 are brought to the United States from other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about slavery,'' said William Yeomans, chief of
staff for the Justice Department's Civil Rights Division. ``This is
as barbaric as the trade that brought African-Americans to this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has asked Congress to strengthen laws
against those who traffic in humans for sex, labor and other
purposes. The House and Senate are weighing separate bills to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, lawmakers are considering measures that include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing the penalty for involuntary servitude from 10 years
to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   _ Making it easier to prosecute acts of coercion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving victims of the crime permanent status in the United
States to receive medical care and to assist law enforcement
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the cruelest human rights abuses. Moreover,
it's a growing wave, which has increased dramatically over the last
10 years,'' said Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., the chairman of the
committee hearing the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Maria, the events began innocently enough.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a maroon dress, a scarf and sunglasses, she told
lawmakers that her illegal immigration into the United States
quickly plummeted into a living hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in fear for my life now more than ever,'' she told
lawmakers who listened intently to her story from the ornate,
fourth-floor room of the Dirksen Senate Office Building on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, she held a job in a general retail store and worked
as a domestic helper in Veracruz, Mexico. She was not married, but
she had a daughter and worked two jobs to feed and clothe her
family.
</P>
<P>
   An acquaintance approached her about jobs available in the
United States, in restaurants and bars that paid more money. Maria
jumped at the opportunity, and a ``coyote,'' or smuggler, took her
across the Rio Grande, near Matamoros, to Texas, where she was kept
in a safe house until she was smuggled to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   There, she testified, a man named Abel Cadena informed her that
she would be working at a brothel as a prostitute to work off her
$2,200 debt for being smuggled into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The woman testified that she was given ``tight clothes to wear''
and taken to a mobile home brothel to work with other girls in
similar straits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armed men were selling tickets to customers in the trailer.
Tickets were condoms,'' Maria said. ``At the end of the night, I
turned in the condom wrappers. Each wrapper represented a supposed
deduction to my smuggling fee. We tried to keep our own records,
but the bosses would destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never sure what we owed.''
</P>
<P>
   Each brothel had four girls and armed guards. The trailers were
located in rural and isolated areas. ``We were transported every 15
days to another trailer in a nearby city,'' she said. ``This was to
give customers a variety of girls, and so we never knew where we
were in case we tried to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Women who escaped and were caught were severely punished with
beatings and rape, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could do is stand there and watch,'' she said. ``I was
too afraid to try to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria's servitude ended in 1998 when federal and state law
enforcement officers broke up the prostitution ring that catered to
Hispanic migrant farm workers throughout central Florida. ``The
women and girls were forced to engage in sexual acts with as many
as 130 men a week. They were beaten and assaulted, and some were
forced to have abortions when they became pregnant,'' Yeomans said.
``We prosecuted the case and obtained seven guilty pleas.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, Mexican authorities arrested Abel Cadena Sosa in
Veracruz on a U.S. extradition warrant alleging he participated in
a prostitution ring using underage Mexican women.
</P>
<P>
   He is being held in Mexico City's Southern Penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   Coto, of the Florida Immigrant Advocacy Center, said other men
involved in the prostitution ring who were prosecuted in the United
States received as few as two years in jail. ``Eight defendants are
still at large,'' she told the senators, adding that ``these
survivors cannot return to the same neighborhoods where their
(former) captors live, and would surely retaliate against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities first detained the victims of the Cadena
ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not receive medical or psychological treatment. They
did not have adequate legal assistance,'' Coto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not understand what happened to them and what was
going to happen,'' she said. ``What they did know is that they were
terrified and needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, the Florida Immigrant Advocacy Center won their release
to Safespace, a battered women's shelter in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are illegal immigrants, they are not eligible for
public benefits in the United States. Community groups have
provided psychological counseling, medical care, food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Maria said the experience still haunts her. She is afraid of
people, and she suffers from ``flashbacks.'' Maria urged the
senators to help other young women ``so that they will not suffer
as we did in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were tricked into coming here,'' she said. ``Please help
me. Please help us. Please do not let this happen to anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gary Martin's e-mail address is gmartin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
