<P>
   BRAVE NEW MATH TESTS LIMITS OF ACCOUNTING
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-COMPANY-VALUATION-NYTSF _ When Internet companies swap
advertising space on each other's Web sites, they generally record
the value of their benefit from the barter as if it is a sale.
Interesting, indeed. To the dismay of many stock-market veterans,
valuing Internet companies has become a matter largely untethered
from reality, limited only by visions of distant triumph. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   YOU MAY BE YOUNG AND RICH, BUT MY LOBBYIST CAN BEAT UP YOURS
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-LOBBYING-COMMERCE-NYTSF _ E-commerce folks know more about
routers than riders, about margins than legislative markups. But as
they spend more time on Capitol Hill, they are learning one thing
fast: It takes a lot more than being this year's darling to get
what you want. When it comes to lobbying in Washington, the Old
Economy is still trouncing the New. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   NOW THAT THEY'VE COME, WHAT CAN WE SELL THEM?
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-MONETIZING-EYEBALLS-NYTSF _ Once upon a time, the Internet
was a place where people offered information freely. Personal home
pages, chat rooms and bulletin boards drew millions seeking advice,
news or companionship. Then, of course, came e-commerce. Now
alongside commerce sites are content sites, in which a publisher
provides news and information, and community sites, in which the
users help create the content. How do the latter make money? By
selling advertising _ and their constituencies aren't happy about
it. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE SMALL RETAILER, LIFE ON THE INTERNET IS ONE BIG BAZAAR
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-BAZAAR-NYTSF _ With a growing number of shopping platforms
from which small businesses can choose, a free-for-all is
developing in online retail. Portal shopping centers are offering
services like gift registries, price-comparison tools and reviews
to lure consumers while bolstering their base of merchants by
making it easy to set up and run an online store. A report on the
various shopping platforms available to new businesses. By Barbara
Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   DAY TRADING IS HERE TO STAY. NOW HOW TO GET A PIECE OF IT?
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-DAYTRADING-NYTSF _ After a day trader went on a murderous
rampage in suburban Atlanta last summer, big brokerage firms
distanced themselves from the risky, rapid-fire stock trading that
had cost the gunman, Mark O. Barton, nearly a half-million dollars.
Privately, many Wall Street executives voiced smug I-told-you-so's.
Less than a year later, day trading is still a dirty term to some
people on Wall Street, but euphemistically it is a hot topic of
conversation. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   IN ISRAEL, MAKING THE SHOVELS FOR THE INTERNET GOLD RUSH
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-ISRAEL-NYTSF (Jerusalem) _ Internet infrastructure, the
veins and muscles of the Web, has become Israel's entree to
e-commerce, a veritable back door to the global Internet market. By
Jessica Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   BLASTING YOUR WAY TO THE ELECTRONIC CHECKOUT COUNTER
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-GAME-MACHINES-NYTSF _ Fast forward to this time next year.
There's me, crashed on the sofa in front of the television, tapped
into a next-generation video-game console, playing another gamer
halfway around the world, then using the console to browse the Web
and also buy CDs and order pizza. I will eat that during my regular
Wednesday-night videoconference call over the console's high-speed
connection. After that, I will download a movie. In other words,
this is not your father's Game Boy; it is serious e-business. By
Joe Hutsko.
</P>
<P>
   THANKS TO THE WEB, CAMPUS RADIO IS CASTING A MUCH WIDER NET.
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-COLLEGE-RADIO-NYTSF _ On campuses across the country, a
radical change is taking place in college radio. Its image as a
noncommercial medium doomed by tiny transmitters and a minuscule
niche market is evolving into a global medium serving audiences
craving an alternative to commercial radio. The stations use
software like RealAudio or Windows Media Player to send video or
audio over the Internet. By Andrew H. Fixmer.
</P>
<P>
   E-TAIL SALES FOLLOW THIER OWN TIMETABLE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-ETAIL-SALES-NYTSF _ Sale time in the world of
brick-and-mortar retailing tends to mean holiday time _ Presidents'
Day, Labor Day and other times when people are off work and
physically out shopping. On the Web, retailing is also developing
its own sale rhythms, though they are less predictable and tied to
the times people are in cyberspace or visiting particular sites. By
J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE GLOBAL, FACELESS WEB, TRUST COUNTS FOR EVEN MORE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-TRUST-NYTSF _ In a Web-based world, where an electronic
embrace is replacing the personal encounter, business-to-business
entrepreneurs are rediscovering the might of the human touch _ and
trust. Some nouveau Net-setters are even pitching the Internet as
the ultimate ``people power'' tool. By Margot Slade.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET RID OF THOSE EXCESS FORKLIFTS
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-EXCESS-INVENTORY-NYTSF _ Like people who have used the
auction site eBay to turn the clutter in their garages into cash,
businesses are turning to the Internet marketplace to sell or swap
surplus goods, from diesel engines to fiber-optic cable. By Kate
Berry.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY SITES LET NICHE BRANDS PUT THEIR BEST FACE FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-BEAUTY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF _ Since last summer, there has been a
virtual explosion of online beauty retailers, which are estimated
to total about 300. The downside is that major players like Estee
Lauder, Lancome and Clinique _ which account for 70 percent of the
$4 billion high-end beauty market _ have not signed on with the new
sites, though some sites may sell these brands unauthorized. The
upside is that the start-ups have been a boon for niche brands. By
Donna Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEB ADDS EXOTIC COLORS, BUT AT THE GARDEN'S EDGE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-GARDENING-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF _ Gardeners in the United States,
who spend about $5 billion a year to watch things grow, can now
watch the emergence of gardening Web sites. Many electronic
seedlings are in place, but much pinching, pushing and pruning is
coming. By Neal Johnston.
</P>
</TEXT>
