<SLUG> BC-BEERNUT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUDE AWAKENING: TEXAS STOUT STANDS UP TO THE HEARTIEST GRUB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wildcatter Crude, made by Yellow Rose Brewery in San Antonio, is
a fine stout with a hoppiness that's reminiscent of Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   It lacks the fullness and the complexity of Guinness, but it's
an exceptional brew worthy of your consideration and the $2 per
bottle price at your favorite retailer of brewed, distilled and
fermented beverages.
</P>
<P>
   It goes down smooth, but is sturdy enough to accompany very
strong food. And it was just the thing as we sat down to a meal
prepared by my visiting Great Uncle Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Brother's stay was not exactly planned. He ran out of bus
fare in Dallas while en route to Vegas and decided to lay over
until his ``gub-ment'' check arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, he's not really my uncle or my brother. Growing up as
the sole male child with six sisters, he became known simply as
``Brother.'' Of course, to his sisters' children and grandchildren
he became known as Uncle Brother and then Great Uncle Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Brother is my mother's cousin, which makes him my
Second Cousin Great Uncle Brother, but then it really gets
complicated, since he also was briefly married to my father's
cousin's half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   He also smells a little peculiar.
</P>
<P>
   That might come from the mainstay in his diet. It's something he
calls ``Brother's Famous Sardine and Tater Tot Hash.'' The word
``famous'' was a recent addition designed to impress Lurine, a bar
hostess he is wooing at Red's Levee Lounge back home in Bunkie, La.
</P>
<P>
   So anyway, despite repeated protests that we had already eaten,
Brother insisted on whipping up a batch of hash.
</P>
<P>
   This sent us looking for a beverage, and we figured something
``Crude'' was just the thing to wash down Brother's hash.
</P>
<P>
   The hoppy aroma flooded my mouth just as Brother dumped two cans
of sardines and their oil into a cast-iron frying pan. He added a
chopped-up onion, a couple of handfuls of frozen tater tots and a
couple of jalapenos. You fry it 20 minutes and eat. Brother says it
tastes even better the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, food like this calls for an assertive brew, and
Wildcatter does the job.
</P>
<P>
   Brother, whose beer of choice is Schaeffers, said Wildcatter was
good, but he's afraid that at $2 a bottle he'd have little cash
left with which to woo Lurine.
</P>
<P>
   Brother gives it a 3. I give it a solid 4.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Rose Brewery also makes Bubba Dog Wheat, Cactus Queen
IPA, Honcho Grande brown ale, Vigilante Beer and Yellow Rose Pale
Ale.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1426EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
