r d BC-MATZO-RECIPES1-LADN &LR;      04-12 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATZO-RECIPES1-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: for use with Passover Main and Recipes2) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATZO BREI &QL; 
3 matzos &QL; 
Water &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
3 tablespoons butter &QL; 
Jam, sour cream, sugar OR cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Break matzos in half and then in half again. Soak in hot water 1
to 2 minutes. Remove and, with your hands, squeeze out as much
water as you can.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs lightly with salt in a mixing bowl. Add matzos and
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter in a heavy skillet and, when it starts to turn
brown, add eggs and matzos. Either leave mixture to set on bottom
and then turn as you would a pancake, or stir mixture with a wooden
spoon as you would scrambled eggs. By either method, matzo brei
will be done within 5 minutes, depending on how well-done you like
your eggs. Serve immediately with jam and/or sour cream, sugar or
cinnamon. Makes 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: To make souffle-like matzo brei, separate eggs. Beat yolks
until thick and pale in color. Add matzos to yolks. Beat whites
until stiff and gently fold into yolk-matzo mixture. Cook in butter
as for pancake variation.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)From ``The Passover Table,'' by Susan R. Friedland,
HarperPerennial.(END ITAL) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MATZO CHICKEN PIE
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)This delicious dish seems designed for the turkey or
chicken or capon leftover from the Seder or the chicken soup.(END
ITAL) &QL; 
6 to 7 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
2 cups chopped onions &QL; 
2 tablespoons minced garlic &QL; 
1 1/2 cups thinly sliced cultivated mushrooms (about 1/3 pound) &QL; 
3 cups bite-sized pieces cooked chicken (about 14 ounces) &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
Freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
1 cup chopped parsley &QL; 
5 eggs, lightly beaten &QL; 
5 to 6 matzos &QL; 
1 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Heat 5 tablespoons oil in a large skillet. Slowly sautee onions
and garlic until softened and translucent, about 10 minutes. Add
mushrooms and sautee until soft, an additional 5 minutes. Let cool.
Stir in chicken, salt, pepper, parsley and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil a shallow 6- to 8-cup baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Dip 2 matzos into stock until well moistened, but not falling
apart. Lay in baking dish, breaking pieces to fit. Spoon 1/2 of
chicken mixture on top and cover with 1 more moistened matzo,
remaining chicken and 2 remaining matzos. Pour 2 teaspoons oil over
top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 15 minutes. Sprinkle with
remaining oil and bake an additional 15 minutes or until top is a
rich, crisp brown. Let cool 10 minutes, then serve. Makes 6 to 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)From ``The Passover Table,'' by Susan R. Friedland,
HarperPerennial.(END ITAL) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SWEET MATZO AND &QL; 
COTTAGE CHEESE PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)This dairy bread pudding-like custard baked between
layers of matzo is delicious for brunch or dessert.(END ITAL) &QL; 
3 (6-inch-square) matzos &QL; 
Water &QL; 
1 pound cottage cheese &QL; 
3 large eggs &QL; 
7 tablespoons sugar &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped pecans &QL; 
1/3 cup raisins &QL; 
1/2 stick (1/4 cup) unsalted butter, melted &QL; 
Sour cream (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Soak matzos in cold water until slightly softened, 1 to 2
minutes. Drain on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together cottage cheese, eggs, 6 tablespoons sugar,
cinnamon, pecans and raisins.
</P>
<P>
   Coat bottom and sides of an 8-inch-square baking dish or pan
with 1/2 of butter. Put 1 matzo in dish and spread 1/2 of cottage
cheese mixture over it. Top with another matzo and remaining
cottage cheese mixture. Top with remaining matzo, brush with
remaining butter and sprinkle with remaining tablespoon sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in middle of a preheated 325-degree oven about 1 hour,
until golden, puffed and set. Cut into squares and serve warm.
Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)A recipe by Faye Levy that appeared in the April
issue of Gourmet magazine.(END ITAL) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOCK MACARONI AND CHEESE &QL; 
PASSOVER STYLE
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)Adults and children will love this dish.(END ITAL) &QL; 
3 large eggs &QL; 
6 whole matzos, broken into small pieces &QL; 
1 cup milk &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon ground white pepper &QL; 
8 ounces Cheddar cheese, cut into into 2-inch pieces &QL; 
1 pint sour cream &QL; 
4 ounces (1 stick) butter, cut into 16 pieces
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, lightly beat 2 eggs and mix in broken matzos.
</P>
<P>
   In a 4-cup measure or blender, beat remaining egg with milk,
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Grease or spray a 2-quart rectangular casserole. Place 1/2 of
matzo mixture and 1/2 of cheese in casserole. Add 1/2 of sour
cream, distributing in dollops evenly on surface, then 1/2 of
butter pieces. Make a second layer in same fashion. Pour milk
mixture on top.
</P>
<P>
   Cover casserole. Bake in preheated 350-degree 30 minutes.
Uncover and bake 10 to 15 minutes longer to brown the top. Cut into
squares and serve. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)From ``Let My People Eat! Passover Seders Made
Simple,'' by Zell Schulman, Macmillan.(END ITAL) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHIITAKE MUSHROOM-BELL PEPPER &QL; 
MATZO KUGEL &QL; 
(BEGIN ITAL)Shiitake mushrooms and red bell pepper give this
traditional kugel a new look and fabulous flavor. Your family and
Seder guests will love it.(END ITAL) &QL; 
1 tablespoon vegetable oil &QL; 
1 small onion, diced &QL; 
1 leek, white part only, sliced &QL; 
1 cup shiitake mushrooms, stems removed &QL; 
1 medium red bell pepper, seeded and diced &QL; 
2 cups crushed matzo &QL; 
1 1/2 cups low-fat chicken broth, warmed &QL; 
2 large eggs plus 2 large egg whites &QL; 
Freshly ground black pepper to taste &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Lightly grease a shallow 6-cup casserole.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium skillet, heat oil over medium-high heat. Add onion
and leek and cook until limp, about 10 minutes. Add mushrooms and
bell pepper and cook 5 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Place matzo in a small bowl and cover with chicken broth. Allow
to stand about 5 minutes. Empty into a strainer and press out as
much liquid as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, lightly beat whole eggs and egg whites
together. Add cooked vegetables, matzo, pepper and salt. Mix well.
Transfer kugel to prepared casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 35 to 40 minutes or until top
is brown and crisp and kugel is set. Serve immediately. Makes 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)From ``Let My People Eat! Passover Seders Made
Simple,'' by Zell Schulman, Macmillan.(END ITAL)
</P>
