<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     04-12 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS ARE LOVABLE LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They are members of baseball's longest-running comedy
series. It's been seven years of laughs for the Midwestern comedy
troupe known as the Minnesota Twins. In this, their eighth season,
not much has changed. Their show is just as bad now as it was in
1993, when they introduced fans to their strange, no-win humor.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins visited Fenway Park Tuesday for a 1 p.m. matinee. As
usual, they were awful. It's part of the act. They lost to the Red
Sox, 13-4. They will end this season with at least 91 losses, which
has been their average since '93 in nonstrike seasons. The only
pathetic goal they haven't reached since then is the magical
100-loss level. But there's always next year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're wondering how an outfit this bad can survive. I'll
tell you how: Quirks. The Twins and their entourage are loaded with
them. And as the Jerrys, Rickis, Judge Joe Browns, Judge Judys,
Larry Kings, and Vince McMahons can attest, America loves quirks.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins have the lowest payroll in baseball ($16.5 million)
but still have a chief financial officer. That's like being the
money manager for a peso account. You think sportswriting is easy?
I want (itals)that(unitals) guy's job.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of sportswriting, that's another interesting thing
about the state and its baseball team. If you are a baseball fan in
Boston, you are familiar with two people who work in Minnesota:
Brad Radke and LaVelle E. Neal III. Radke is the pitcher whom the
Sox should acquire. If they do that in exchange for minor league
talent, you won't have to worry about any Boston curses; the Sox
will win the World Series. And when that happens, the only
reference to lingering curses will be in Neal's briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   Neal is the Minneapolis Star-Tribune writer who left Pedro
Martinez off his 1999 MVP ballot. Shortly after this information
became public, Neal discovered that ``You've Got Mail'' is an
understatement. He received more than 400 e-mails, most of them
from Sox fans.
</P>
<P>
   One guy cursed Neal in Spanish and English, then requested a
phone call (he left his number) so he could tell the writer a few
more things. Another Sox fan at the University of Texas left an
e-mail with a subtle subject heading: ``You are a bastard.'' That
was the nice part. Another fan sent a six-page message that
contained one word. Loser. Except it was in block letters and
appeared like this: LOSERLOSERLOSERLOSER. For six pages.
</P>
<P>
   So, has Neal changed his mind about pitchers being eligible for
MVP?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, sifting through the weighty pile of mail.
Before doing that, Neal volunteered to compile the records of all
the teams he has covered. In six seasons, he has watched the Twins
and Kansas City Royals. The total record is 348 wins, 449 losses,
and a tie. Which means the man has watched a lot of bad baseball.
Neal hasn't spoken with Martinez yet, but says he will.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the strange Twins tale doesn't stop there. The team's
starter Tuesday was a kid named Joe Mays. It took him only 45
pitches to give up eight runs, five of them earned. He walked four
Sox, didn't strike out anyone and lasted 1 1/3 innings. It was a
classic early- to mid-1990s Twins performance.
</P>
<P>
   Awful.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Tom Kelly watched the game, retreated to his office, and
then said, ``We try to play baseball, and it wasn't a game today.''
He repeated his words and added, ``It was a terrible event. It
wasn't fun for anybody. It wasn't a game, and for that we
apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly has managed the Twins since 1986. He has won two World
Series titles. He is an interesting man, the kind of character that
you'd expect to leap off the page in a Kafka novel. (Perhaps ``The
Metamorphosis'' would be appropriate: He has seen a great team
become a non-team.)
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was asked if all this terrible, low-budget losing gets on
his nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't enjoy it, I wouldn't be here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly then shakes hands. Says it's nice to meet you. He walks
off and prepares for another day in which he will be asked to go to
a big league war armed with a collection of minor leaguers. You
think I'm saying that in a mean-spirited way? Meet Twins right
fielder Matt Lawton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of players better than myself stuck in Triple
A,'' Lawton said after going 2 for 5. ``The Yankees have a lot of
guys who could be in the big leagues. Maybe if I didn't play here,
I wouldn't be good enough to play on someone else's team.''
</P>
<P>
   There are double takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton is listed at 5 feet 10 inches, but he appears to be about
5-7. He also has a Martinez connection. That is, Pedro is not a fan
of his. Two years ago, Lawton tried to disrupt Martinez's rhythm by
continually stepping out of the batter's box when Martinez was
ready to deliver. So Pedro drilled him. Tuesday, Lawton extended
the rivalry by taking a swipe at Sox starter Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he was overpowering by any means,'' Lawton
said. ``I hope he stays in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another day, another odd Twins show. If Fenway had Dolby
Surround Sound speakers and cushioned seats, you'd swear that the
Twins were character actors in a laughably bad movie. But there's
something lovable about them. I'm sure the Sox and their fans will
agree with me on this: I wish the Twins could visit town more
often.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
