r d BC-MATZOS-RECIPES2-LADN &LR;      04-12 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATZOS-RECIPES2-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use with Matzos and Recipes1) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
SPINACH PIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   !ital!This Sephardic Passover spinach pie is good for a light
brunch or as an accompaniment to a roast &QL; 
6 tablespoons olive OR vegetable oil &QL; 
2 pounds fresh spinach OR 2 packages thawed, frozen spinach &QL; 
2 cups chopped green onions, including some green tops (about 12) &QL; 
1 cup matzo meal &QL; 
1 cup chopped fresh dill &QL; 
8 eggs &QL; 
4 tablespoons lemon juice &QL; 
Salt and pepper to taste &QL; 
2 whole matzos
</P>
<P>
   With 1 tablespoon oil, grease bottom and sides of a shallow
2-quart baking dish. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Clean fresh spinach, if using, removing thick stems; chop
coarsely (you will have about 8 cups).
</P>
<P>
   Heat remaining 5 tablespoons oil in a heavy skillet. Add green
onions and, after a couple of minutes, spinach. Stir until wilted
and well combined with oil. Stir in matzo meal and combine well,
using a wooden spoon. Add dill. Remove pan from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs with lemon juice until frothy, 4 to 5 minutes in an
electric mixer. Stir in spinach, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Break whole matzos and scatter pieces on bottom of oiled pan.
Pour spinach mixture into pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 30 to 45 minutes or until top
is nicely browned. Serve warm. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   !ital!From ``The Passover Table,'' by Susan R. Friedland,
HarperPerennial. &QL; 
MY TRADEMARK, MOST REQUESTED &QL; 
ABSOLUTELY MAGNIFICENT &QL; 
CARAMEL MATZO CRUNCH
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 unsalted matzos &QL; 
1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter OR unsalted Passover margarine &QL; 
1 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
3/4 cup coarsely chopped semisweet chocolate chips OR semisweet
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Line a large (or 2 smaller) cookie sheet(s) completely with
foil. Cover bottom of sheet with baking parchment _ on top of foil.
This is very important since mixture becomes sticky during backing.
</P>
<P>
   Line bottom of cookie sheet evenly with matzos, cutting extra
pieces, as required, to fit any spaces.
</P>
<P>
   In a 3-quart, heavy-bottomed saucepan, combine butter and brown
sugar. Cook over medium heat, stirring constantly, until mixture
comes to a boil, (about 2 to 4 minutes). Boil 3 minutes, stirring
constantly. Remove from heat and pour over matzos, covering
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Place cookie sheet in preheated 375-degree oven and immediately
reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees F. Bake 15 minutes, checking
every few minutes to make sure mixture is not burning (if it seems
to be browning too quickly, remove pan from oven from oven, reduce
temperature to 325 degrees F and replace pan).
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and sprinkle immediately with chocolate. Let
stand 5 minutes, then spread melted chocolate over matzos. While
still warm, break into squares or odd shapes. Chill, still in pan,
in freezer until set.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATION: You can also use coarsely chopped white chocolate (or
a combination of white and dark) and chopped or slivered toasted
almonds (sprinkled on top as chocolate sets). You can also omit
chocolate for a caramel-alone buttercrunch.
</P>
<P>
   !ital!From ``A Treasury of Jewish Holiday Baking,'' by Marcy
Goldman, Doubleday. &QL; 
DECADENT FUDGE BROWNIES &QL; 
WITH GLOSSY FUDGE FROSTING
</P>
<P>
   !ital!Just wonderful even when it is not Passover _ fudgy,
dense, delicious. &QL; 
BROWNIES: &QL; 
2 cups granulated OR brown sugar &QL; 
1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter OR unsalted Passover margarine,
melted and cooled &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
1 tablespoon brewed coffee &QL; 
3/4 cup unsweetened cocoa powder, sifted &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1 scant cup matzo cake meal &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped toasted walnuts (optional) &QL; 
GLOSSY FUDGE FROSTING: &QL; 
2/3 cup water OR brewed coffee &QL; 
7 ounces semisweet chocolate, coarsely chopped &QL; 
2 tablespoons unsalted butter OR Passover margarine, softened &QL; 
TOPPING: &QL; 
Finely chopped nuts (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Lightly grease a 7x10-inch rectangular baking pan, a 9-inch
square pan or an 8- or 9-inch springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   For Brownies, in a bowl, mix sugar into melted butter, then
eggs, coffee, cocoa, salt, cake meal and walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon batter into prepared pan. Bake in preheated 350-degree
oven about 25 minutes. Do not overbake. Brownies should be set and
seem dry to touch but there should not be a crust around sides.
Cool in pan.
</P>
<P>
   For Frosting, heat water in a small saucepan. As it comes to a
boil, reduce heat and stir in chocolate. Remove pan from heat and
stir until chocolate is thoroughly melted. Cool in refrigerator
about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk in softened butter and spread frosting on top of cooled
brownies. Decorate top by running tines of a fork through frosting
and sprinkle with additional chopped nuts, if desired. Cut into
squares or wedges (if baked in a round pan). Makes 30 squares.
</P>
<P>
   !ital!From ``A Treasury of Jewish Holiday Baking,'' by Marcy
Goldman, Doubleday.
</P>
</TEXT>
