<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      04-12 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTFOLIO'S NEAR-PERFECT, BUT BEEF UP ROTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I met with a financial planner but decided I want to take
control of my own financial situation. I would like your opinion on
my strategies on my 401(k), Roth IRA, Oracle stock, mutual fund
accounts, and mortgage payments. Should I change my 401(k)
allocation, which is 25 percent to each fund? Is Vanguard Index 500
the best IRA investment? Should I continue buying Oracle stock each
month? Do you like my choice of taxable funds? What should I buy
next? I'm considering Vanguard Small-Cap Index. Should I make extra
payments on the mortgage or continue to build the mutual fund
accounts? My overall goal, putting the Oracle holding aside, is a
total portfolio with 50 percent in large-cap stocks, 20 percent in
small-cap funds, and 10 percent each in mid-cap, international, and
health care funds.
</P>
<P>
   S.A., Beaverton, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. What can I say? By my lights, you have done it almost
perfectly. I like your target allocation, but I'd also move a few
things around.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you want the holding with the largest potential
gain in your Roth account, where all of it will eventually come to
you tax-free. For that reason, although it will bring you a tax
bill, I'd sell Vanguard Index 500 in the Roth IRA and buy Vanguard
Health Care for the Roth. Then I'd sell a like amount of Health
Care in the taxable account and buy Index 500. If you find the tax
consequences of that move too onerous, or if you are unwilling to
pay the redemption fee charged by the Heath Care fund, you could at
least target future contributions to the Roth IRA to Health Care,
and further contributions of the taxable account to Index 500.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if you are seeking another small-cap position, I'd
allocate some of the 401(k) contributions to Fidelity Low-Priced
Stock and Fidelity OTC rather than going with Vanguard Small-Cap
Index. Although I do frequently recommend Vanguard Small-Cap Index
fund, it's usually for people who want to stay within Vanguard or
who prefer index funds. Although the Vanguard fund tracks its peer
group nicely, my gut feeling is that the small-cap universe is a
place where index funds might be at a disadvantage, compared to
well-managed competitors.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Oracle stock, the position now represents about 39
percent of your portfolio, not counting the emergency savings
account. That's a fairly heady level, and I don't suggest that you
go much beyond that. But since you specify (in an edited part of
the letter) that you buy the shares at a 15 percent discount from
market price, I would continue buying new shares, selling older
positions as required to keep the position from exceeding 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Following the same reasoning as I suggested with the Roth IRA,
you would probably be better off, taxwise, to move some of your
401(k) money to more aggressive holdings and to balance that by
buying more cautious (and more tax-efficient) funds for your
taxable accounts. In this case, it's probably not worth making any
sales, but for future contributions, for example, you might buy
shares of Fidelity Equity Income fund in a taxable account instead
of buying additional shares of Strong Growth fund. You could then
buy a corresponding value of shares in Fidelity Growth company in
the 401(k), diverting the money for those purchases from the
Fidelity Equity-Income account there.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, your mortgage looks attractive at a 7.75 percent fixed
rate. Given your youth and the excellent long-term prospects of
your growing portfolio, I would favor continuing to build your
taxable fund accounts, rather than prepaying the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a small hardware store and am thinking of retiring. I
wonder if you can see ways to improve my investments. I have
written to Vanguard about its Capital Opportunities fund, which has
a $25,000 minimum. Is this priced too high? Is it too close to
Alliance Technology fund, which I hold in my taxable portfolio? Do
I have too much stock for safety? What would my projected income
be, the way you see it?
</P>
<P>
   L.R., Jasper, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. I calculate a whisker more than 57 percent of your
investments on the fixed-income side, which is perhaps a little
less than many would prefer, but on the other hand not particularly
drastic. I think the question of how _ or whether _ to change your
portfolio lies more with your needs than with the portfolio
breakdown. I estimate that you would have an income of nearly
$40,000 _ $39,963 to be precise _ if you made no changes.
</P>
<P>
   That estimate was based on an assumption of an average 6 percent
yield from your fixed-income holdings and annuities, and a 1.5
percent yield from your stock and fund accounts.
</P>
<P>
   My approach to the portfolio: start with the likely proceeds
from the sale of your business, and the put that amount to one side
in your mind. Then calculate what you would like to have as income
in retirement. Let's say the figure is $50,000 a year. You could
then calculate that you would need to have about $155,000 in a
fixed-income investment to provide a $10,000 annual income stream
(here using a 6.5 percent projected yield). You could then move
$155,000 of the money from the sale of the business, or both from
that pool and the equities portfolio, to a fixed-income investment
such as a good GNMA fund, and you'd have the desired income stream.
</P>
<P>
   The problem would come either if the proceeds from the sale of
your business were small or if your required income stream is very
large. You now have $293,844 in equities _ a handsome enough sum.
But if you were to move a very significant part of that amount to
the fixed-income side, you would be in danger of not providing
yourself with the overall portfolio growth that you will need to
protect yourself against inflation in the later years of your
retirement. I would see no problem if you moved $93,844 to
fixed-income investments, but I would be uncomfortable with the
overall situation if the equity side went below $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether to go for Vanguard Capital Opportunities fund,
that would in large part depend on how the previous questions were
answered. It's not exactly a duplication of your position in
Alliance Technology, since that fund focuses on technology stocks,
while Vanguard Capital Opportunity focuses most heavily on heath
care issues, followed by services, and then technology.
</P>
<P>
   Despite glowing recent numbers _ its 97.8 percent 1999 gain and
its 32.5 percent year-to-date advance, as this is written _ you
might look back to its early years to see that it hasn't always
been so. (Although you could also argue that those bad years came
under a different portfolio manager.)
</P>
<P>
   In any event, I would view it as one of Vanguard's riskier
funds. My suspicion is that this was the reason the fund family
bumped the minimum investment up to $25,000 _ probably seeking to
limit the fund's growth, but also to price out unsophisticated
investors.
</P>
<P>
   My view is that this might be a good long-term investment, but
at this stage of the market, I would tend to avoid it unless you
have a very large amount of cash left over after providing a
fixed-income portfolio that will provide for your needs _ and if
you are willing to hold the fund for a decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our annual income is just over $100,000; we have no debt. As
I grew older and looked at friends and relatives, I often wondered
how we stacked up financially. How are we doing? Can we be content
that we have handled our finances successfully?
</P>
<P>
   K.W., Sun City, Ariz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're doing just swell.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for statistics, a Web site run by the US
Department of Commerce Bureau of Economic Analysis lists per-capita
personal income for 1998 for each state, with Connecticut first, at
$37,598, and Mississippi last, at $18,958. The census currently
under way will probably yield more information, but not for a
couple of years. But any way you fry it, you're clearly doing very
well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
