<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NEWBALANCE-JUMP-ART-B     04-12 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBALANCE-JUMP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FASHIONS, BROADER BASE LEAD NEW BALANCE TO A RECORD PACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1990, at a spot on Heartbreak Hill near his home, Jim Davis
was watching the Boston Marathon. As chairman and chief executive
of New Balance Athletic Shoe Inc., he wasn't just enjoying the
race; he was also checking out the runners' footwear.
</P>
<P>
   Davis didn't like what he saw. Instead of New Balance shoes,
many runners were wearing other brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't getting the share we used to have,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, New Balance shoes could be spotted nearly everywhere,
on the feet pounding Heartbreak Hill as well as on trendy young
people who'd never dream of running a marathon. In 1999, running
shoes from niche brands such as New Balance, Saucony Inc., and
Asics Tiger Corp. seemed to be all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Long known as a company that makes quality sneakers for serious
runners, aging baby boomers, and folks with wide feet, New Balance
last year saw some of its new, flashier styles snapped up by
yunger, fashion-conscious consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For Boston-based New Balance, fashion was only part of the
story. Dismayed by the scarcity of New Balance-shod marathoners in
1990, Davis vowed then to broaden his customer base. Over the next
few years, he targeted women, children, and adults between 22 and
35 _ groups he hadn't always aggressively courted. All these
initiatives came together to produce a record year in 1999 as
worldwide sales rose 41 percent, to $890 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion trends gave a similar lift to Saucony. 1999 sales of the
Peabody, Mass. company rose 47 percent, to $154.06 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock groups have started wearing our shoes,'' marvels
Saucony's president and chief executive, John H. Fisher. Saucony's
core customer had previously tended to be age 30 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Those big gains are all the more impressive because the Sporting
Goods Manufacturers Association says overall US retail sales for
athletic footwear were flat in 1999 at $13.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to giants Nike Inc. and Stoughton-based Reebok
International Ltd.? In 1999, they may have lost some fashion cachet
to smaller brands.
</P>
<P>
   At Franklin Resource Group, a Boston sporting goods consulting
firm, president Marty Lillis calls it ``the Izod syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One year everybody's wearing your alligator; the next year
nobody is,'' he says. ``People don't want to wear what everyone
else is wearing. To be cool, you have to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   In a desire to be different, many fashion-conscious consumers
turned to New Balance, Saucony, and Asics last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, Reebok, and adidas AG all ``seemed to stumble at the same
time,'' Fisher says. And that created opportunities for smaller
brands to get more attention from retailers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, with Michael Jordan starring in splashy Nike ads,
basketball shoes dominated the athletic footwear industry. That
year, US consumers bought 345 million pairs of all kinds of
athletic footwear, the manufacturer's association says. But by the
time Jordan retired , the basketball-shoe fad seemed to have run
its course, and US sneaker sales had dropped to about 315 million
pairs.
</P>
<P>
   From $2.9 billion in 1996, retail sales of basketball shoes have
fallen by nearly a third, the SGMA says.
</P>
<P>
   That's been bad news for the likes of Converse Inc., of North
Reading, Mass., and Fila, whose brands are linked to basketball,
says Bob McGee, editor of Sporting Goods Intelligence, a trade
publication.
</P>
<P>
   As teens bought sandals, hiking boots, and other kinds of casual
shoes instead of basketball shoes, running shoes emerged as a
bright spot for the athletic footwear industry. According to the
SGMA, annual US retail sales of running shoes have grown to $2.6
billion from $1.7 billion over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   That's meant a big boost for companies with running heritages,
such as New Balance, Saucony, and Asics.
</P>
<P>
   At New Balance, Davis cautions against attributing too much of
his company's big 1999 to a shift in the fashion cycle.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the marathon in 1990 and seeing too few of his
shoes on runners' feet, Davis instituted a number of changes that
really gained momentum in the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   His first move was to diversify his shoe lines and broaden his
market beyond male baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, 20 percent of sales came from women; today that figure
is 45 percent, says Davis, who bought the privately held company in
1972. Once, New Balance aimed its mostly gray and blue shoes at
customers 35 and older. Now, it has added more colorful lines
designed to appeal to consumers ages 22 to 35.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sales of children's shoes, virtually nonexistent in
1996, now approach 15 percent of total company sales.
</P>
<P>
   Offering shoes in many widths, New Balance has also gone after
the estimated 15 percent of the market with big or small feet. Few
other athletic shoe companies pursue those customers.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of hiring sports celebrities such as Jordan to
promote its shoes, New Balance ads sometimes noted that many of its
shoes were made in the United States, something else that sets it
apart from rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But as sales grew, New Balance began to outstrip its capacity
for domestic manufacturing and it, too, had to look to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, 80 percent of New Balance shoes sold in the United
States were either made domestically or assembled here with some
overseas parts. By 1999, that number had dropped to about 50
percent, Davis says. New Balance operates five factories in
Massachusetts and Maine for the bulk of its US production.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, federal regulators took issue with some New
Balance ads that claimed its shoes were made in the United States.
The regulators contended the ads were misleading because some shoes
were made with imported parts.
</P>
<P>
   Now ads steer clear of such claims and instead urge consumers to
``Connect with yourself. Achieve New Balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a big 1999, Davis still takes an L.L. Bean approach to
fashion. It's an outlook that can be summed up this way: ``If
fashion comes our way, great. But we don't chase trends.''
</P>
<P>
   New Balance customers ``couldn't care less about purple shoes,''
says John J. Shanley, an analyst who covers the sporting goods
industry for First Security Van Kasper. ``What they care about is
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of the teen market, Nike and Reebok often flood the
market with new styles and colors. New Balance, in contrast, puts
out a style and sticks with it, tweaking it mostly with technical
upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   Because this year's line is so similar to last year's, Shanley
doesn't expect New Balance to see the stunning growth it
experienced in 1999. The fashion crowd could soon be looking
elsewhere for trendy casual footwear, he says.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK with Davis. Too much growth can strain a company.
Projected growth this year of 25 to 30 percent will be just fine,
Davis says. As New Balance prepares to move into larger Boston
quarters in October, sales should exceed $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion trends come and trends go. But one thing is almost sure.
When runners in the Boston Marathon struggle up Hearbreak Hill next
week, ``We'll see more New Balance shoes than we did 10 years
ago,'' Davis says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
