<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-MONETIZING-EYEBA     04-12 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-MONETIZING-EYEBALLS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW THAT THEY'VE COME, WHAT CAN WE SELL THEM? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By BOB TEDESCHI  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Before people realized they could make a million dollars on the
Web by putting an ``e'' in front of any word in the dictionary,
registering the new name and shaking down a venture capitalist for
seed money, the Internet was a much more communal place.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it was populated largely by academics and
technology geeks who either cared little about getting rich or
considered the idea so outlandish as to be irrelevant, the Internet
assumed a quaint identity as a place where people offered
information freely.
</P>
<P>
   Personal home pages, chat rooms, bulletin boards and Usenet
groups, which are open-discussion forums on various topics, drew
millions seeking advice, news or companionship. Those running the
sites frequently relied on surplus computer space from universities
or whatever network power they could scrape together with spare
money.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, came e-commerce, a phenomenon that prompted the
tripartite categorization of the Internet: Alongside commerce sites
are now content sites, in which a publisher provides news and
information, and community sites, in which the users create the
content.
</P>
<P>
   But the tremendous interest in making money from the large
number of people who frequent a site, or ``monetizing eyeballs'' in
industry parlance, also foretold profound changes for community
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Community sites began selling advertising to stay in business.
The sites incorporated and wrote business plans. Some, like
TheGlobe.com, went public. Others, such as the Internet Movie
Database (IMDb.com), were bought by bigger sites _ Amazon.com, in
this case. Still others, such as DejaNews.com, a buying guide in
which consumers rate products and give advice, assumed a new
identity (Deja.com) and charged headlong into the e-commerce fray.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the community sites angered their constituencies,
who accused them of selling out to commercial interests. In others,
the transitions were smooth. But whatever the story, analysts and
executives of community sites say the e-commerce revolution changed
the face of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Community sites have been wandering the desert in search of a
revenue stream,'' says Lisa Allen, an e-commerce analyst with
Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``Now they've latched onto
e-commerce, which is the fair-haired child of the Internet. The
only problem is, commerce isn't making any of them rich, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, commerce has alienated the users who helped create
the sites' content. Tom Phillips, the chief executive of Deja.com,
says that site angered ``a lot of people when we made the change.''
</P>
<P>
   The change Phillips referred to took place last year.
DejaNews.com, one of the few sites to provide easy access to and
retrieval of Usenet topics and information, became Deja.com, a site
devoted to users who wanted information about a range of products.
DejaNews.com had generated a loyal following and had made money by
selling advertising. But when Deja.com rolled out, it began posting
boxes on the site's pages, requesting opinions and ratings on
products.
</P>
<P>
   Those opinions were aggregated into a vast _ and anonymous _
database, the linchpin of the new Deja.com site. But as Phillips
says, ``we sort of force-fed people the ratings and reviews, and it
slowed the site down,'' leaving it less navigable.
</P>
<P>
   David Wilson, Deja's senior vice president, adds, ``The
complaints mostly talked about how Deja was, and is, the
standard-bearer of Usenet, and they were concerned we'd take our
eye off the Usenet ball and everyone would suffer for it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Phillips says, ``we lost a chunk of people _ but we
also gained some, so our traffic has been pretty flat.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Deja would drop the ratings boxes and that,
``given the viral nature of Usenet,'' he expected those who left
the site to return.
</P>
<P>
   But Deja is not dropping its e-commerce ambitions. rather, the
company's newest incarnation, released in March, expands its
offerings of purchase information and includes direct links to
merchants selling goods featured on the Deja site.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from community to commerce was much less bumpy
for the Internet Movie Database, a compendium of movie trivia built
largely by contributions from movie buffs around the world who
gathered on the IMDb.com site.
</P>
<P>
   According to Col Needham, who founded the database in 1990 in
Britain, the site received four complaints when it decided to start
selling advertisements in 1996, and no complaints when it was
bought by Amazon in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the people who used the database were thrilled. Some
felt that a friendly, comfortable online community had been
swallowed by a giant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Needham says, not only did the alliance with Amazon lead
to an increase in the number of contributors to the database, but
as it has grown the database has hired some of the people who had
previously contributed voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that, in the end, most people understand that when you
have e-commerce in a content site, you can fund the future growth
of the site, so users win both ways,'' he says. ``They can buy
things they're interested in, and they have better content.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo encountered trouble last year when it bought GeoCities, a
site that allows users to create free home pages. Soon after the
acquisition, Yahoo posted a notice on its GeoCities site
(http://geocities.yahoo.com), suggesting that Yahoo could take the
content from a person's GeoCities site and use it in a book, for
example, without compensating the home-page publisher.
</P>
<P>
   The event caused a stir among the GeoCities faithful, spawning a
boycott and inquiries from at least one consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand where the users were coming from,'' says Doug
Hirsch, a senior production director for Yahoo Communities. ``But
at the end of the story, we did change our terms of service.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, home-page publishers can rest assured that their
content is, in fact, their property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are very wary of what commerce sites are doing with
content they provide _ and they should be,'' Hirsch says.
</P>
<P>
   He argues, however, that GeoCities had become less commercial
since Yahoo bought it, notably containing less intrusive
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually proud that it hasn't lost its grassroots vibe,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Other community sites are heading into e-commerce, hoping to
make a similar claim in the future. Gamers.com, a site devoted to
video-game enthusiasts, is one such venture. Among other things, it
lets users rate video games and post notes on message boards about
anything related to games.
</P>
<P>
   According to the site's chief executive, Dennis Fong _ known in
professional computer-game circles as Thresh, the undefeated world
champion _ the company will soon introduce a service that allows
users to buy games on the site from retailers or buy from other
users in an auction format. In addition, he says, they will be able
to trade games.
</P>
<P>
   Fong says he expects no resistance from users, because the site
is committed to the open exchange of information about every game
on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the Switzerland of the games industry,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he adds, the transition should be done carefully,
lest it wave the e-commerce flag too proudly in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we want to be known as is a store,'' he says.
``It's very hard for a store to be cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4682 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-12 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SUBWAY   IS MASS NON-TRANSIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The subway here is perhaps unique in the world. It
is clean, and the trains run on time. It is, in effect, free; no
one checks if you have bought a ticket. The vast platforms are the
size of aircraft carrier flight decks; each one could accommodate
thousands of riders. When I was riding the system last week, there
were at most 15 or 20 people waiting for trains.
</P>
<P>
   That is the secret of the $5 billion subway's ``success'' _
hardly anyone rides it. For an Easterner, riding the Red Line (the
only line) is an out-of-subway experience. No accordion-wielding
buskers; no beer-breathed bums; no marauding schoolchildren. Sleek,
Italian-made cars full of comfortable, available seats. This is no
subway _ it's the Orient Express!
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has had a century-long love-hate affair with mass
transit; mostly hate. Cars rule. The transportationally
dispossessed ride buses. There are a few commuter rail lines
linking the center of the city with exurban destinations like San
Pedro or Long Beach. Twenty years ago, the city decided to build
what the Los Angeles Times now calls its ``cursed'' subway system.
The first few stations opened for business in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is smack in the middle of a horrific transportation
crisis. The storied freeways have been unreliable for almost a
decade. A routine trip could take 15 minutes, or an hour and 15
minutes. The state estimates lost work hours due to highway
congestion at 400,000 per day.
</P>
<P>
   So, with gasoline prices edging up to $2 a gallon, why not
embrace the subway? For starters, it really doesn't go anywhere.
You can't get to the airport. You can't get to Dodger Stadium. You
can't even get to the new Krispy Kreme doughnut stand in Van Nuys
that everyone is talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The existing line links downtown stations, like the Civic Center
and Union Station, with the businessy Wilshire Boulevard and the
still-sleazy-but-soon-to-be-tarted-up center of Hollywood. But the
people who work downtown or along Wilshire don't live in Hollywood.
The vast bedroom tracts of West Los Angeles (more affluent) and
East Los Angeles (less affluent) are untouched by the subway, and
will be forever.
</P>
<P>
   Cost overruns that make Jim Kerasiotes look like a management
whiz and an untimely gas explosion in the mid-1980s have soured
Angelenos on pouring new money down the subway hole. Eighteen
months ago, a local pol sponsored a successful ballot initiative
that halts new subway construction after this year. Just last week,
governor Gray Davis announced a $5.2 billion transportation plan
``to get California moving again.'' Although he staged the photo op
at a Los Angeles subway station, all of the allotted funds were
earmarked for freeway expansion, buses, and above-ground rail
lines.
</P>
<P>
   The subway has other drawbacks. Although Angelenos are not prey
to irrational earthquake fears, even the most stouthearted
straphanger wouldn't want to be caught in a subway tunnel during a
``seismic event.'' On a more visceral level, many residents just
plain don't like it. A ``New York solution for a Los Angeles
problem,'' is the phrase one hears.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this summer, the subway will reach a place where people
actually live: the San Fernando Valley, home to the world-famous
valley girls. The two new stops at the Universal City theme park
and in North Hollywood lie across the Cahuenga Pass, and could
theoretically relieve congestion on the traffic-choked Hollywood
Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the 11-mile-long system carries about 60,000 riders a
day, one-10th as many as Boston's vastly larger network. The
extension into the valley will add 6.3 miles of track and about
40,000 riders. At least that was the most recent estimate. When I
phoned a Metro Rail spokesman to check the numbers, he said the
subway isn't in the business of predicting ridership anymore. There
just hasn't been much good news to report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
