r a BC-ECOM-LOBBYING-COMMERC     04-12 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-LOBBYING-COMMERCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU MAY BE YOUNG AND RICH, BUT MY LOBBYIST CAN BEAT UP YOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By JERI CLAUSING  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   E-commerce folks know more about routers than riders, more about
margins than legislative markups. But as they spend more time on
Capitol Hill, they are learning one thing fast: It takes a lot more
than being this year's darling to get what you want.
</P>
<P>
   All those stodgy nondot-coms have not been paying all those
stodgy lobbyists all that money for nothing. And those
Gucci-loafered lobbying wizards love nothing better than
piggybacking their pet project onto somebody else's fast-track
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Take digital signatures _ e-commerce jargon for secure
electronic-identification codes. Many e-commerce transactions would
be simpler if such signatures were recognized as the legal
equivalent of their ink-and-paper counterparts, allowing
transactions to be completed online that now have to detour through
fax machines or the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Legal weight, of course, is conferred by laws, and a bill to
give electronic signatures that weight was a top Congressional
priority for Internet and high-technology groups last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huzzah!'' insurance and banking lobbyists cried, more or less.
``A complicated financial bill that's likely to pass! Allow us to
offer a few helpful suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates use the word ``hijacking'' to describe what
followed, as the bill magically sprouted amendments eliminating
some traditional paper record-keeping and consumer-notification
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting feud between Republican-backed financial interests
and the administration-supported consumer groups has largely left
the technology companies on the outside looking in, eager to
support whichever version of the bill has the best chance of
passage.
</P>
<P>
   And observers say the fight over digital signatures will pale in
comparison with some of the Internet battles that are looming. In
the process, alliances of all sorts are going to be stirred and
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   James Lucier, an Internet analyst at Prudential Securities, says
that right now Democrats on the Hill are losing e-commerce fights
because their traditional supporters, ``consumer groups, trial
lawyers, are persona non grata in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Republicans are going to get hit soon,'' he warns. ``Their
traditional interest groups _ insurance, realtors, broadcasters,
wholesalers _ are going to be coming into conflict one at a time
with Web-based businesses. It's not going to be pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   One way of looking at the conflicts is less in terms of partisan
politics than in terms of time frames or frames of mind. Influence
in Washington is based on everything the Internet is not: history,
both in relationships and campaign contributions, location, as in
the presence of insurance agents and restaurant owners in every
Congressional district, and mastery of legislative and regulatory
processes as arcane as, well, the legislative and regulatory
process.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol wholesalers showed how powerful such history can be on
Capitol Hill when, despite repeated calls by Democratic and
Republican Congressional leaders to keep the Internet generally
free of regulation, the House last year passed a bill that would
keep small wineries and breweries from selling alcohol over the
global network.
</P>
<P>
   Although that bill was initially proposed as a measure to ban
the sale of liquor to minors, wholesalers _ who often have virtual
statewide monopolies with complete control over what brands of
beer, wine and liquor are sold _ jumped on the bandwagon and got
the bill changed to prevent companies from selling alcohol online
unless they abide by varied and cumbersome state distribution and
tax laws that are too complex for small companies to follow.
</P>
<P>
   And Internet businesses face another threat, the kind that comes
with success. So far, e-commerce and high-technology interests have
stood together to oppose bills that threatened the freewheeling
nature of the Internet. But as interests shift, that solidarity
could dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the recent decision by eBay, the online auction
company, to quietly switch sides in a brewing dispute over how far
copyright protection should extend to online databases.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Realtors, along with Lexis-Nexis,
the New York Stock Exchange and other compilers of traditionally
proprietary databases, are pushing for a bill introduced by Rep.
Howard Coble (R.-N.C.), chairman of the House Judiciary Committee's
intellectual-property subcommittee. His bill would give broad
copyright protections to both databases and many of the individual
facts they are built on, prohibiting most people from using
information contained in those compilations.
</P>
<P>
   Because much of the Internet has been developed by start-ups
experimenting with variations on traditional businesses, it is not
surprising that Internet interests are backing a narrower bill by
Rep. Thomas Bliley (R.-Va.), chairman of the House Commerce
Committee. The bill introduced by Bliley would protect the
compilations, but not the facts within them.
</P>
<P>
   EBay, however, has moved from Internet start-up to Internet
giant. As it sees more competitors using its listings, its
representatives have begun independently visiting Congressional
offices, making subtle noises about changing sides. To help make
its case, it recently opened a Washington office, hiring a lobbyist
from one of the most influential groups in town _ the Motion
Picture Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, the eBay folks will be buying Gucci loafers
for themselves, and steak-and-martini lunches for lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
