r a BC-ECOM-COMPANY-VALUATIO     04-12 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-COMPANY-VALUATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVE NEW MATH TESTS LIMITS OF ACCOUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR. 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When Priceline.com arranges deals in which consumers name their
own prices for, say, airline tickets, it reports the money that the
passenger pays for the seat as its own revenue, even though it
neither owns nor flies any airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   And when Internet companies swap advertising space on each
other's Web sites, which has become routine, they generally record
the value of their benefit from the barter as if it is a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitable issues arising from the new world of business in
cyberspace? No doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Are they important only as grist for discussion among
accountants? Not on your Lifeminders.com.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of many stock-market veterans, valuing Internet
companies has become a matter largely untethered from reality,
limited only by visions of distant triumph. Indeed, most of these
companies have yet to turn a profit, much less pay the skimpiest of
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of traditional benchmarks, analysts and investors
focus on less-substantial gauges such as how much investment
capital has been poured into the business, how many eyeballs are
being attracted to a Web site and, probably most important, how
much money is coming in _ without regard to how the income relates
to the expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies tend to be valued on the basis of their
revenue,'' says Robert Willens, a tax-and-accounting analyst at
Lehman Brothers. ``For Internet companies, it's particularly
crucial to show top-line revenue growth.''
</P>
<P>
   And since fledgling companies need booming stocks to raise
capital at low cost and to attract and hold scarce
stock-option-minded talent, they have considerable incentive to
build revenue however they can.
</P>
<P>
   Some professional investors, mainly those who specialize in
betting on which stocks will fall, complain that various companies
are overstating results.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of a New York hedge fund, for example, questions
whether Internet companies should be allowed, in effect, to use the
capital markets to create revenue by buying smaller competitors and
then collecting fees from them for Web space.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have refrained from saying that there has been any
significant abuse, but they are becoming concerned about aspects of
Internet accounting.
</P>
<P>
   The concern was reflected in a list of 20 issues that Lynn E.
Turner, the chief accountant for the Securities and Exchange
Commission, identified in October as warranting consideration by
the Financial Accounting Standards Board, the profession's chief
rule-making body.
</P>
<P>
   Urging attention by the Board's Emerging Issues Task Force,
Turner says that these items are either not yet addressed in
accounting rules, are being treated differently by different
auditors or are subject to what he called ``inappropriate''
developing practices.
</P>
<P>
   One chief issue is whether an Internet company should report its
transactions ``gross'' or ``net'' _ that is, should it regard as
revenue the entire value of what it sells, such as an airline
ticket, or only its profit from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Another accounting issue is fulfillment costs, such as shipping,
handling and warehouse expenses, which are a significant cost of
doing business for many e-tailers. Some companies show these
charges as marketing expenses rather than as a component of gross
profits, which would shrink this major gauge of performance.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the SEC, which is reportedly scrutinizing
Amazon.com and eToys on this point, says such differing treatment
should be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A transaction should be accounted for the same, whether it's
an e-business or a brick-and-mortar business,'' says Scott Taub, an
aide to Turner.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting-standards board's panel put as its first order of
business the treatment of barter deals, in which Internet companies
exchange Web advertisements, which are recorded as both revenue and
offsetting expense. The panel decided in January that the practice
is legitimate only when the participants can show a history of
collecting cash payments for ``similar advertising'' within the
last six months.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet-accounting questions include whether to write off
the cost of developing Web sites as it is incurred or to spread the
deduction over several years. How to value stock options is also up
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   It is a knotty set of decisions, not easily unraveled, and some
of them are bound to become visibly contentious soon. But Taub
expressed optimism that accountants and their clients will find
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope,'' he says, ``is that the bulk of these issues can be
resolved this year.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robert D. Hershey Jr. is a writer at the Washington bureau of
The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
