<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-EXCESS-INVENTORY     04-12 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-EXCESS-INVENTORY-784-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET RID OF THOSE EXCESS FORKLIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KATE BERRY 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Kate Berry is a reporter for The Orange County (Calif.)
Register.
</P>
<P>
   Like people who have used the auction site eBay to turn the
clutter in their garages into cash, businesses are turning to a new
Internet marketplace to sell or swap surplus goods, from diesel
engines to fiber-optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   Online exchanges hope to attract a wide range of businesses that
want to unload excess inventory through an electronic forum where
companies can accept bids from potential buyers. The concept is
sometimes linked to barter, which is flourishing on the Internet
among companies that swap advertising space. But online exchanges
deal primarily in cash and have a bigger market in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a business out there that doesn't have excess
inventory or idle assets,'' said George Samenuk, the president and
chief executive of TradeOut.com, an online exchange. TradeOut, in
Ardsley, N.Y., focuses on Fortune 1,000 companies that want to
unload excess inventory. The average transaction on TradeOut.com is
$20,000, compared with just $40 on eBay, which happens to be a big
investor in TradeOut.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most misunderstood and hidden areas of
business,'' Mr. Samenuk said. ``Not many people want to publish how
much excess inventory they have.'' That dissuades some potential
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   TradeOut.com is typical of most online exchanges, charging
sellers a $10 fee to list an item and a 5 percent commission once a
transaction is complete. Bids are sealed, as opposed to a
traditional auction, when each bidder knows what the others have
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts think live Internet auctions, broadcast from
factory floors, will supplant traditional liquidators and
auctioneers as more businesses make deals online. Electronic
business-to-business auctions and exchanges are expected to grow to
more than $700 billion in 2004, up from $29.4 billion this year,
according to Forrester Research. At stake are surplus goods or
assets valued at $300 billion to $500 billion worldwide, experts
say, though they will probably be sold at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   Online exchanges are already jockeying for position. As with
other big Internet businesses, the key to growth is the ability to
get businesses to list goods on their sites. And as with other big
Web sites, the bigger the audience, the more valuable the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But business buyers have caught on slowly. TradeOut.com has sold
just 5 percent of the $450 million in inventory available on its
Web site, which was started in June.
</P>
<P>
   The business-to-business auction companies say their Web sites
are efficient for sellers seeking a wide variety of buyers, which
can result in higher prices. Excess goods that might have gone out
the back door for 30 cents on the dollar often command 70 cents on
the dollar online.
</P>
<P>
   A few sites have decided not to identify the seller. Being
anonymous is an incentive for companies that do not want to risk
the ire of their distributors or manufacturers or do not want to
reveal their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies can't send merchandise back to the vendor
and are tempted to e-auction it,'' said Tom Petters, the chief
executive of Redtagoutlet.com, in Minneapolis, which operates
Redtagbiz.com, an exchange that caters to manufacturers selling
mostly surplus consumer goods. The anonymity is appealing to
sellers because ``no one wants to show other people what didn't
sell.''
</P>
<P>
   BigVine.com, in Redwood Shores, Calif., straddles the wall
between an online exchange and a barter operation. Bippy Siegal,
the company's chief executive, thinks small businesses, which can
carry as much as 15 percent to 20 percent extra inventory, are
interested in swapping goods not for cash, but to use as barter.
His site allows sellers to set the price of an item, which is
listed in so-called trade dollars. These can be used to buy other
goods or services on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very interested in barter and in trading,'' Siegal
said. BigVine is backed by American Express, which invested $10
million for a 10 percent stake, giving American Express a chance to
market a variety of services to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Serra, a senior vice president for interactive service at
American Express, said small companies were strapped for cash but
had plenty of excess inventory or services to give away. She sees a
huge market because only 500,000 of the 25 million small businesses
in the United States barter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What barter does is give a new distribution channel to small
companies,'' Serra said.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
