<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4686 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-TRUST-1199-NYTSF     04-12 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-TRUST-1199-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE GLOBAL, FACELESS WEB, TRUST COUNTS FOR EVEN MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARGOT SLADE 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In a Web-based world, where an electronic embrace is replacing
the personal encounter, business-to-business entrepreneurs are
rediscovering the might of the human touch. Some nouveau
Net-setters are even pitching the Internet as the ultimate ``people
power'' tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``In business-to-business _ as against business-to-consumer _
Web transactions, human beings generally represent value added,''
said Anna Copeland Wheatley, the editor-in-chief of ``AlleyCat
News,'' a business magazine that covers the Internet and technology
in the New York region.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers do not need much handholding when buying simple
commodities, like books and tapes, or even standard office
supplies, Wheatley explained. But in most of the
business-to-business market, transactions involve complex
purchasing decisions, a host of variables, lots of money and
manufactured items bought and sold among a comparatively small but
educated audience. That means that relationships with suppliers can
be more important than the lowest price; companies have gone
bankrupt saving money on the wrong product.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this universe, you often need more than textual
information,'' Wheatley added. ``You need to bond a bit with the
people you're dealing with; you need an element of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Developing trust means going beyond e-mail exchanges; research
shows, and experience confirms, that we are face-to-face animals.
We gauge character through signals, like body language. And bonding
requires someone responsive to bond with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business customers come back, I suspect, because of the
stickiness of the seller, not the site,'' Wheatley said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, interviews with business consultants, scholars and
executives confirm that from venture capitalists to sales
representatives and product distributors, the business-to-business
supply chain is relationship-rich _ stubbornly so for entrepreneurs
determined to connect buyers and sellers by electronics alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always disturbed by these tattooed, ponytailed
netrapreneurs saying they'll revolutionize industries by
eliminating the middlemen and their human inefficiencies,'' said
Mark Walsh, the president and chief executive of VerticalNet Inc.,
which runs 56 industry-specific Web sites. ``So they launch Web
sites that declare war on all the supply chain participants who
existed before the Internet came on the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Guiding their attacks is the notion that the Internet is so rich
with information that it creates an omniscient buyer who knows the
cost and the price of everything. But business types with Internet
expertise and brick-and-mortar experience note that many
netrapreneurs, enamored of technology and highly skilled in it, are
short on real-world business experience. They haven't cut deals
themselves. Or as Walsh said, ``They haven't lived with the lies
they've told in business, nor with the humiliation of being lied
to.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they do not understand that businesses are not
purely price-driven, that business executives believe in margins
and a degree of loyalty to vendors. They love it when vendors
remember what they bought last; they want the best that works.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Walsh thinks there will be a backlash in which people
who participate in the new marketplace say the Internet is
primarily a relationship enhancer. The vanguard may have already
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Derek Bromley, who joined Greg Ahnert in 1997 and
founded BevAccess.com, an online exchange where beverage-alcohol
producers, distributors and buyers research, buy and sell wine,
spirits and beer. ``We don't want to cut industry sales forces, but
to help them work smarter _ to shorten sales cycles and reduce the
time spent in transit and on paperwork so as to improve
relationships and contacts with existing and new accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Coes, the president and chief executive of eSprocket, a
Boston start-up trying to create a marketplace in the $400 billion
worldwide, used-industrial-equipment industry, is a relationship
convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like our competitors, we were going to cut out the brokers and
dealers by launching an auction site,'' Coes said. ``We now think
that was wrong. Dealers and brokers are essential in a business
where the typical buyer is a career person at a small or midsize
company making an occasional purchase, the typical seller is a
Fortune 1,000 making an occasional sale and the average transaction
is between $35,000 and $60,000.''
</P>
<P>
   What these new businesses seem to be discovering, consultants
and scholars say, is the importance of human interactions in
business relationships and the need to understand how those
relationships work in particular industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auctions, for example, create a false sense of urgency by
leaving no time for discussion,'' said John R. Coleman, a founding
partner and president of VIA Inc., in Portland, Me. The firm
specializes in marketing and Internet strategies for eSprocket,
among others. ``But in something like used capital equipment, you
need a site that allows initial contacts to happen and negotiations
to take place _ and not just through the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman has discovered empirically what Kathleen L. Valley, an
associate professor at Harvard Business School, has shown
experimentally. ``We found that e-mail transactions and
negotiations are most successful when the parties have a
pre-existing relationship,'' Valley said. Even then, Internet
communication has limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the volume of exchanges these days, she said, e-mail
puts a premium on saving time and money by keeping messages short
and succinct ``with no social greasing of verbal interactions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But our research also found that the norm in e-mail exchanges,
anyway, is to not share information,'' she said. ``It seems that
there is very little trust.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. ``Whatever information is shared
electronically is much more likely to be altered in some way,''
Valley said. ``People tend to shade and misrepresent more readily,
even though e-mail is a written record.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor are Web sites and e-mail exchanges the best avenues for
negotiated deals, even among parties who enjoy long-standing
relationships. Valley has found that when people meet face to face,
the impetus is to come to a mutually beneficial agreement.
Telephone conversations resulted most often in lopsided deals.
``Surprisingly,'' she said, ``callers tended to assume that
listeners could not detect a lie, while listeners assumed that they
were hearing truths.''
</P>
<P>
   But e-mail exchanges most often resulted in impasse, and often
with increased anger leading to a cutoff of communications, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Valley's advice to business executives? ``Appreciate electronic
exchanges for allowing you to stay in touch: you can communicate
any time with anyone, inexpensively and efficiently. But spend time
sharing with customers and business partners the kind of social
information that develops trust. And when it comes to the clinch,
meet with the other person, or pick up the phone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
