<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-ETAIL-NYTSF &LR;      04-12 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-ETAIL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-TAIL SALES FOLLOW THEIR OWN TIMETABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Sale time in the world of brick-and-mortar retailing tends to
mean holiday time _ Presidents' Day, Labor Day and other times when
people are off work and physically out shopping.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web, retailing is also developing its own sale rhythms,
though they are less predictable and tied to the times people are
in cyberspace or visiting particular sites.
</P>
<P>
   Many e-commerce sites already discount merchandise and therefore
do not follow traditional sales schedules. The exceptions are the
big shopping holidays _ Christmas, Valentine's Day, Mother's Day
and Father's Day _ according to statistics from BizRate.com, a site
that tracks online shopping habits.
</P>
<P>
   Sites that specialize in gift-giving help spread online shopping
activity past the holidays. Flooz.com, which sells gift currency
that users can redeem in online stores, is seeing the sales of its
retail partners, which include Tower Records and Godiva chocolates,
increase at off-peak times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love that we can take advantage of the holidays by
getting people to send and receive Flooz, and then drive the
recipients into the stores right after the holidays,'' said Robert
Levitan, the company's cofounder and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Reel.com, a film-related site that combines content with the
sale of movies on videocassette and DVD, offers sales and
promotions tied to news events and trends rather than calendar
holidays, said Dave Rochlin, the chief operating officer. The site
has made its own annual sales tradition centered on the Academy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously know the Oscars are huge for movie watchers,''
Rochlin said. He added that Reel.com has in the past brought in
many customers for its content, which included Oscar-prediction
games and film retrospectives, and ended by selling them movies.
</P>
<P>
   Even sites that are spun off from traditional establishments are
adapting their sales practices to the habits of online shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're catering to different customers with different time
considerations,'' said Gene Domecus, the vice president for
Internet merchandising at Macys.com. ``When consumers come to your
Web site looking for a product, they are ready to buy it now. `On
sale tomorrow' or `Come back three days from now' doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Macys.com went online in 1996 offering only bridal registry
services. The site was revamped in 1998 to include many of the
items found in Macy's retail stores, from women's suits to
toasters.
</P>
<P>
   But though the merchandise may be the same, the sale practices
are not. The purchasing habits of online shoppers differ: ``I do
most of my business between noon and 3,'' Domecus said. ``People
really shop online at lunchtime and then after 10 at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales online are a different animal, too; the borderless
dimensions of Macys.com enable the site to reflect a special sale
at the Macy's West or Macy's East division.
</P>
<P>
   But the convenience of online shopping in general may also
diminish the need for significant discounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the stores are closed and we're still open and doing
business,'' Domecus said, ``the sale calendar also starts to not
make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (J.D. Biersdorfer is a staff writer for The New York Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
