<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4688 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-GAME-MACHINES-NY     04-12 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-GAME-MACHINES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLASTING YOUR WAY TO THE ELECTRONIC CHECKOUT COUNTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JOE HUTSKO  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Fast forward to this time next year. There's me, crashed on the
sofa in front of the television, tapped into a next-generation
video-game console, playing another gamer halfway around the world,
then using the console to browse the Web and also buy CDs and order
pizza. I will eat that during my regular Wednesday-night
videoconference call over the console's high-speed connection.
After that, I will download a movie.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is not your father's Game Boy; it is
serious e-business.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of promises of gadgets to link your PC and your
TV, it turns out that games are the thing that will make this a
marriage made in couch-potato heaven. And the biggest thing about
these monster game machines, which will cost less than $500, is the
possibilities they pose beyond games.
</P>
<P>
   All the usual console-game heavyweights are here: Sony, Nintendo
and, back from the near dead, Sega. Oh, and one new contender,
Microsoft, which may wind up in a league all its own (one it knows
well): domination.
</P>
<P>
   While the other players are modifying video-game machines to act
more like PCs, Microsoft is doing the opposite. Its product is
called X-Box, and guess what? It is really just a Windows PC tuned
for gaming _ like the one I already own with a Pentium III
processor, a big hard disk and a high-end video card _ crammed into
a small box that plugs into the TV.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows better than Microsoft where people want to go _
and spend money _ on the Web? It already has the browser, e-mail
and, more important, e-commerce security goodies for making its
video-game way to the Web a palatable proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Plug-in ports will make it possible to attach devices like
keyboards, mice and joysticks, turning the X-Box into the sort of
device that Microsoft has struggled to make work as WebTV for so
long, without all the trade-offs, like dumbed-down Web browsing and
e-mail. Microsoft says that the X-box will be available in the fall
of 2001, practically a millennium away in gamer years.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Big Three of video games are not down for
the count, not by a long shot. Each thinks its strategy will win
the hearts, minds and wallets of both game players and Net
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Sega's Dreamcast, a $200 video-game console introduced last
year, which is far more advanced than the current Sony PlayStation
and Nintendo 64 consoles, is the taste of the near future. It is
the first video-game machine with a built-in modem. To register for
Internet service by using the Dreamcast requires only a credit card
and a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Those few minutes are difficult, though. While the Dreamcast
controller earns praise for landing kicks and punches in fighting
games, it is not a great mouse for tapping information onto the
on-screen keyboard. An optional $25 keyboard plugs in to make Web
browsing and e-mailing simpler.
</P>
<P>
   But Sega is not betting the farm on browsing and e-mailing.
Community and multiplayer gaming are where the company intends to
earn a prizefighter position. Its current bag of Net tricks,
however, is not exactly making hard-core game players palpitate.
</P>
<P>
   There's Chu Chu Rocket, a cutesy (and addictive) cat-and-mouse
puzzle game that can be played solo or against other players
nationwide. Sega also offers small diversions like up- and
downloadable enhancements for Sonic Adventure, and posting high
scores from Sega's Web site to see who is the speediest ``Star
Wars'' Racer.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall, Sega plans to offer an add-on digital camera called
Dreameye, which can e-mail snapshots or make videophone calls _
activities familiar to desktop PC users.
</P>
<P>
   Also due for Christmas is a snap-in module that will link many
players in different places and give the Dreamcast the high-speed
Net performance that serious PC multiplayer fans demand. That means
your game console will be able to handle any high-speed connection
your cable TV or telephone company can provide. Thus, no stammering
slowdown when blasting an enemy, and filling your online shopping
cart faster.
</P>
<P>
   Online shopping is a major e-commerce component that Sony plans
to let buyers tap into by using its PlayStation 2 console, which
will go on sale in the United States in the fall. (When PlayStation
2 went on sale in Japan early this month, the company sold nearly a
million units in three days.)
</P>
<P>
   The device, which should cost about $400, also plays DVD movies,
creating two consumer products in one. PlayStation 2 offers a fast
network connection and an optional hard drive that has lots of
space for downloading games, videos, movies and music.
</P>
<P>
   What is unclear is whether Sony's own record and entertainment
labels _ already playing on CD, DVD and VHS as well as Cineplex
screens around the world _ will get top billing among the products
accessible via PlayStation 2.
</P>
<P>
   Taking its cue from the cable TV business, Sony might offer
pay-for-play gaming events, similar to pay-per-view championship
boxing matches. The difference is that you will be in the ring,
taking virtual punches instead of just watching.
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least in the battle of the consoles is Nintendo,
whose early-2001 next-generation entry, code-named Dolphin, is
still under wraps. Count on Nintendo to also offer high-speed Net
access along the lines of what Sony and Sega are promising, as well
as ports that should make it possible to connect devices like disk
drives, keyboards, mice and cameras, probably at about the same
price as its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   If all these forward-thinking video-game systems sound like PC's
in disguise, that is because they are. It takes the enormous
capacity of a hard disk to store all that entertaining information,
along with the bits of data, like credit-card numbers and buying
preferences, that matter most to the companies on the other side of
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   So don't just zap an opponent in Half-Life. Ready, aim, spend!
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Joe Hutsko writes about technology and games for Wired
magazine and The Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
