<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-COLLEGE-RADIO-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO THE WEB, CAMPUS RADIO IS CASTING A MUCH WIDER NET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW H. FIXMER  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   With both transmitters out of commission, little money and more
than $40,000 in repairs needed to keep Boston University's student
radio station, WBTU, on the air, Bill Rigby was getting desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things never looked bleaker,'' said Rigby, a Boston University
senior and the station's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it dawned on him that one important aspect of campus life
might work in the station's favor: 70 percent of his audience,
students living in dorms, had high-speed Internet access in their
rooms. So, in an all-or-nothing gamble, he abandoned the airwaves
for the Internet, investing the last of the station's money in
equipment for broadcasting over the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   For the last quarter of 1999, the station could afford only to
Webcast its programming. Yet during that time, WBTU received high
participation rates from listeners and built its highest ratings in
years on sports, which Rigby, 22, attributed to more alumni
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   By New Year's Day, the station could afford enough repairs to
get back on the air; staff morale was high; and student
applications for on-air, online and production jobs were pouring
in, Rigby said.
</P>
<P>
   And the very nature of the station changed. It began investing
its increasing revenues not just to fix its broadcast equipment but
also to expand its Internet features.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if this was working so well, why not push it further
with chat rooms and a Web cam showing the D.J. on the air,'' Rigby
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Laksin, a Boston University freshman and frequent listener
to WBTU, liked the Webcasting. ``Why would I turn on my radio when
I can get interactive radio online?'' Laksin said.
</P>
<P>
   On campuses from the University of Maine to San Jose State
University, a radical change is under way in college radio. Its
image as a noncommercial medium doomed by tiny transmitters to low
ratings and a miniscule niche market is evolving into a global
medium serving audiences craving an alternative to the slickly
marketed, predictable fare offered by commercial radio.
</P>
<P>
   The new potential for global reach has also enabled alumni to
keep in touch with campus events. Sports coverage is also proving
popular, often testing the limits of the stations' Web servers.
</P>
<P>
   The stations use software like RealAudio or Windows Media Player
to ``stream'' music _ in streaming, the audio or the video that is
transmitted over the Internet begins to play when only partly
downloaded, reducing waiting time. The cost for most college
stations to start Webcasting with RealAudio is a couple of thousand
dollars, which is cheap by radio standards.
</P>
<P>
   Depending upon the size of the bandwidth of the radio station's
server and the number of listeners logged on, the sound can range
from scratchy mono to crystalline stereo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality is good enough that it reaches the same quality
level of FM radio that people are used to hearing,'' said Jay
Wampold, a spokesman for RealNetworks, the maker of RealAudio.
</P>
<P>
   At Seton Hall University in South Orange, N.J., WQHS has enjoyed
a cult following of its heavy-metal and hard-rock music, producing
unheard-of ratings for college radio stations. Nevertheless, the
station's general manager, Lenny Sprecht, agreed that Webcasting
has allowed the station to reach listeners who had not had access
to the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get at least a hundred e-mail messages a month
congratulating us on our show from as far away as Austria,''
Sprecht, a senior, said.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of Webcasting is the increased fees charged by
Ascap and BMI, the recording industry's major royalty-collection
agencies, for permission to play music by artists they represent.
These fees are determined by the size of the audience that the
radio signals reach.
</P>
<P>
   Royalties paid by the station at Ithaca College in Ithaca, N.Y.,
have increased nearly fivefold, said Chris Wheatley, the manager of
radio operations.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Ithaca College's station is adding tracking
software to record the amount of traffic on the server, which
Wheatley hopes will enable the station to charge advertisers higher
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the software and technology is not in place,
the potential for e-commerce is staggering. Before, college radio
stations were limited to Class C, nonprofit educational broadcast
licenses that, under Federal Communications Commission rules, left
them few means of raising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Now, broadcasting through a virtually unregulated Internet,
stations with these licenses can charge higher advertising rates
and sell college and station merchandise and hard-to-find CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Rigby credits Webcasting for allowing WBTU to ``rise up from
nothing to a pretty bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew H. Fixmer is a senior at Rutgers University in New
Brunswick, N.J.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
