<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-ISRAEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ISRAEL, MAKING THE SHOVELS FOR THE INTERNET GOLD RUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JESSICA STEINBERG 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Internet infrastructure, the veins and muscles of
the World Wide Web, has become Israel's entree to e-commerce, a
veritable back door to the global Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   Established and start-up companies are providing software and
microchip technologies that allow people to search, find and buy
products relatively easily, and with some measure of security, on
the World Wide Web. Indeed, of the 91 Israeli companies trading on
the Nasdaq, almost a quarter are involved in Internet
infrastructure technology.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity was almost irresistable: The Internet's quick
growth often overwhelmed businesses' e-commerce systems, clogging
the bandwidths and security arrangements with a flood of
information that needed to be routed, and sometimes rerouted.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Israeli entrepreneurs created thousands of
companies that strove to quickly relieve Internet traffic jams,
devise security checks and verify information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israeli companies anticipate the problems and provide the
quick fix,'' said Noam Ohring, an Israeli venture capitalist who
specializes in Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a commerce haven here, but you'll always find
behind-the-scenes kinds of companies.''
</P>
<P>
   What these companies have formed is a world of fire walls and
digital packets, load-balancing equipment and ``push'' technology,
customized information tailored to specific needs. Where they have
excelled is in not just patching up problems, but in turning their
solutions into the industry's standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli entrepreneurial knack is, to a great extent, a
result of the country's four-year mandatory military service for
men at the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers learn to improvise and be responsible for
others at a relatively young age. In addition, many of the
entrepreneurs served in elite technical units, gaining skills that
they use now in software start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   BackWeb Technologies is one such example. As a start-up, it has
quickly become the ``FedEx of the Internet.'' This Nasdaq-traded
company acts as a bulldozer behind dozens of e-commerce companies,
customer-relations management firms and supply sources.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, BackWeb's stock went up 142 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of people doing what they're doing,'' said
Elan Zivotofsky, a Goldman, Sachs technology analyst.
</P>
<P>
   One Israeli entrepreneur, a nuclear physicist named Nahum
Sharfman, founded two companies, first CommTouch Software Ltd.,
then DealTime, both of which cater to the supply and maintenance
end of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies are as close as Israeli companies get to
providing pure e-commerce content.
</P>
<P>
   CommTouch develops consumer e-mail applications by outsourcing
services to companies and organizations, with surfers receiving an
e-mail box bearing the company's or organization's logo. CommTouch,
whose president is Isabel Maxwell, the daughter of the late British
media magnate Robert Maxwell, also offers various value-added
services, such as translating mail into 15 languages, including
Hebrew, and transmitting e-mail messages to telephones, fax
machines and beepers.
</P>
<P>
   Dealtime, Sharfman's second start-up, is a shopping service that
rates products and merchandise, everything a consumer might need to
know about anything from computers to books.
</P>
<P>
   DealTime and CommTouch, however, are not typical Israeli
infrastructure companies because their technology is ``in the
basement,'' as Sharfman likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   DealTime, for example, thrives on service, trying to find the
best deals on the Internet for its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's managers are in New York, where they search for
products and services, while the programmers are in Netanya, a
resort north of Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis are out-of-the-box thinkers,'' said Nir Barkat, one
of four managing directors of the BRM Group, a Jerusalem investment
firm that acts as an incubator for local high-tech companies.
``They're far from the market, so they play with ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   One of BRM's first successful companies was Check Point Software
Technologies Ltd., a Nasdaq-traded security software provider used
by many Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking ahead has been a prime part of the company's success.
It came out with its first fire wall product in the 1990s, long
before anyone was thinking about the Internet and security. Now its
products form the core of the fire-wall market.
</P>
<P>
   BRM calls itself a ``vincubator,'' developing companies from the
``womb to I.P.O. tomb'' by providing capital and management skills
to create as many Internet infrastructure companies as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli companies always seem to do better when there is a
technology element to their trade, though this is not surprising
considering the legions of Israeli army-trained engineers and
managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leverage yourself when you focus on a subsegment of the
Internet market,'' Barkat said. ``You have to have the goal of
being a guerrilla in a place where you can be significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jessica Steinberg is a free-lance business writer based in
Jerusalem.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
