<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-DAYTRADING-NYTSF     04-12 1591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-DAYTRADING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY TRADING IS HERE TO STAY. NOW HOW TO GET A PIECE OF IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   After a day trader went on a murderous rampage in suburban
Atlanta last summer, big brokerage firms distanced themselves from
the risky, rapid-fire stock trading that had cost the gunman, Mark
O. Barton, nearly a half-million dollars. Privately, many Wall
Street executives voiced smug I-told-you-so's.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year later, day trading is still a dirty term to
some people on Wall Street, but euphemistically it is a hot topic
of conversation. Firms represented by such sober spokesmen as
Charles Schwab and Peter Lynch, the former manager of Fidelity
Investments' Magellan fund, are recommending their firms' services
for ``active'' traders and offering those investors lower
commissions than other customers pay.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders try to make money by buying and selling stocks
quickly via low-fee Internet trades _ often using money borrowed
from brokerage firms _ to capture small price movements. They are
called day traders because they generally close out their positions
every day rather than hold stocks overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Charles Schwab Corp., whose founder and co-chairman has
preached the virtues of long-term investing for many years, took
the biggest plunge earlier this year when it agreed to pay $488
million for Cybercorp.com, a company that develops technology for
what it calls ``the professional, experienced online trader.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say it is inevitable that big Wall Street
brokerages, such as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Citigroup, will follow
Schwab's lead in courting the most active traders.
</P>
<P>
   What these firms have discovered is that although frequent
trading may not be a sure way for investors to make money, it is
certainly lucrative for the brokerage firms. They collect a fee of
$8 to $20 each time a customer buys or sells shares. The problem
the big brokers face is how to embrace day trading without
alienating the customers who were attracted by pronouncements about
the importance of making a long-term financial plan and sticking to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really fine line,'' said Steve Galbraith, an analyst at
Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., ``to try and preach this investment
mantra of `buy and hold' out of one side of the mouth and at the
same time court the day traders.''
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith, who analyzes investment firms, expressed amazement
that highly respected firms would risk, from his point of view,
sullying themselves to cash in on a frenzy of speculative trading
that he thinks may be a fad.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite its poor image, day trading is as alluring to
some brokerage firms as it is to some individuals. David Pottruck,
who shares the titles of chairman and chief executive with Charles
Schwab, said that his company, which is in San Francisco,
considered acquiring one or more of the firms that operate
casinolike day trading rooms, where customers try their luck at
shifting money in and out of stocks for hours on end.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck said he thought most of those day-trading rooms posed
issues of compliance with securities-trading regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that it was a reputational risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even thinking about operating day-trading rooms like the ones
that Barton attacked is a stretch for a firm headed by Schwab, who
has been a pied piper for small investors. In his 1998 book,
``Charles Schwab's Guide to Financial Independence,'' he advised:
``Hold on. Investing is not an overnight phenomenon. It's a
financial commitment of at least seven years. Longer is even
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Schwab appears in television advertisements for his firm's
high-speed trading service, Velocity.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch has also published books recommending that investors do
research on companies before buying their stocks, and is well known
for his buy-what-you-know approach. But, at the same time that
Fidelity is using Lynch to promote its mutual funds, the Boston
company is marketing its PowerStreet Pro online trading service to
active traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can make the generalization that one message
necessarily conflicts with another,'' said Tracey Curvey, the
executive vice president of Fidelity Online Brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Where does Fidelity stand on the growing number of people trying
to make a living by trading full time online?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not discouraging it, but we don't encourage it,
either,'' Curvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck sees the shift as evolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed,'' he said. ``A few years ago, it was our
belief that the extremely active trader never made money.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that individual traders can gather much of the market
information that was formerly available only to Wall Street pros,
Pottruck said, Schwab thinks many very active traders are quite
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to the conclusion that it was in fact a good
business,'' Pottruck said. ``We don't want to concede any end of
the market. We want to be successful in all ends of the trading
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainstreaming active trading is likely to lead day trading out
of the kind of offices that attracted Barton, analysts say.
Thousands of people will be spending most of their time trading
stocks electronically, analysts predict, but virtually all will do
so from home, using technology provided by big brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Most traditional Wall Street brokerage firms were slow to offer
online trading to customers, fearful of alienating their armies of
well-paid brokers. But last year, some of the biggest brokerages,
including Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.,
introduced low-commission electronic trading services. Having taken
that plunge, these firms are exploring ways to broaden their appeal
to serious online traders.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Keene, who analyzes the stocks of electronic-brokerage
firms at Putnam, Lovell, deGuardiola &AMP; Thornton, recently visited
several small firms that have developed stock-trading systems for
day traders. Company executives were buzzing about the prospect of
selling to big brokerages, as CyBerCorp did with Schwab. The buyout
fever is running so high that a firm in Richardson, Texas,
1800daytrade.com, is considering changing its name, Keene said, to
make it a more palatable takeover target to a firm worried about
its image.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; SIDEBAR: MUTUAL FUNDS ARE MOVING TO INTERNET TIME, BUT VERY SLOWLY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It is Friday morning, and you are watching a professional
investor being interviewed on CNBC. Struck with an urge to buy into
the mutual fund he manages, you call up the fund's Web site within
seconds, only to find it will take a week to own any shares.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of instant gratification, most mutual-fund companies
and even some brokerage firms are still denying investors the
ability to buy now. Despite their claims of technological savvy,
these firms insist that investors fill out and sign an application,
attach a check and mail it to open a new account.
</P>
<P>
   The hang-up has been the one thing most investors cannot supply
electronically: a signature. Most mutual-fund companies think they
must have a signed application before they can sell shares to
investors, even though securities regulations do not seem to
require one.
</P>
<P>
   While other companies wait for digital signatures to be given
the definitive force of law, John Pauley is setting an example by
plunging ahead. Pauley, 30, is the vice president for electronic
commerce at Invesco Funds Group, a mutual-fund company in Denver
that has been opening accounts directly over the Internet
(www.invesco.com) since late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Invesco has landed 22,000 new accounts from people who logged on
to the site, filled out an application and authorized Invesco to
withdraw as much as $25,000 from their bank accounts. Those
customers received a quick confirmation that Invesco would sell
them shares after that day's stock market closing.
</P>
<P>
   The site pays off for Invesco, whose funds are sold mostly
through the fund supermarkets run by Charles Schwab Corp. and
Fidelity Investments. When people buy the company's funds through
brokerage firms, Invesco does not know who they are or how to
contact them. But people who buy online become Invesco's customers.
</P>
<P>
   Other fund companies are coming around to Pauley's view. Marsico
Capital Management, a fund company in Denver, recently started
opening accounts online (www.marsicofunds.com). Several bigger fund
companies plan to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Internet adds value is when someone does business
with you and says, `I had no idea it could be this easy,''' Pauley
said. ``Once this industry embraces the technology, that's when
you'll see the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Patrick McGeehan is a New York Times staff writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
