<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-BAZAAR-NYTSF &LR;      04-12 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-BAZAAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE SMALL RETAILER, LIFE ON THE INTERNET IS ONE BIG BAZAAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BARBARA WHITAKER 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   GeniusBabies.com, a fledgling business owned by Michelle
Donahue-Arpas, joined the giant online mall Yahoo Stores in April
1999. One month later, its sales doubled; by November, sales had
reached $20,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Though Yahoo has served Donahue-Arpas well _ with a 95 percent
customer approval rating, she is a featured merchant _ she knows
she should expand her horizons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo giveth, and Yahoo can taketh away,'' she said, referring
to the ``featured merchant'' designation, which raises the profile
of her business, a seller of educational and developmental toys for
babies and toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   As a small fish swimming in a very big pond, Donahue-Arpas, like
other small retailers, must make careful decisions about how to
expand her company. In such a world, it would be easy to be
overwhelmed, overshadowed or swallowed up if she is not careful.
</P>
<P>
   With a growing number of shopping platforms from which small
businesses can choose, a free-for-all is developing in online
retailing. Portal shopping centers are offering an increasing
number of services, such as gift registries, price-comparison tools
and reviews, to lure consumers while bolstering their base of
merchants by making it easy to set up and run an online store.
Amazon.com has opened an Internet bazaar it calls zShops, and a
growing number of companies known as e-business service providers
are offering retailers free tools to establish and maintain online
stores with them.
</P>
<P>
   Each alternative has advantages and disadvantages for merchants,
and no clear answers have emerged about the best way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most retailers are still unclear on how to do it and, more
importantly, who to do it with,'' said Kneko Burney, director of
markets and computing at Cahners In-Stat Group, a research group in
Scottsdale, Ariz. ``The big hurdle for them is building a Web
presence that makes sense and making it known.''
</P>
<P>
   In-Stat estimates that 60 percent of the small companies in the
United States have Web sites and about 80 percent use the Internet,
but few do an effective job of selling products or services online.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of platforms that offer a quick fix for big
bucks,'' said Sue Schwartz, who developed YarnXpress.com, which
sells specialty yarns, with the help of an e-business service
provider called Freemerchant.com. ``It's really `Let the buyers
beware,''' she said, referring to the merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if caution is in order, analysts think there is also
opportunity. Seema Williams of Forrester Research, which analyzes
e-commerce, observed, ``A bit of a free-for-all is actually a good
thing,'' opening up options for small retailers. It is important to
remember where interests lie.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she noted, Amazon.com is foremost a store, and its
interests will come first. Shopping portals such as Yahoo, which is
not a retailer, will always have more allegiance to their big-name
merchants, who pay more money to be on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that small merchants must look out for
themselves, getting their names out in any way possible and using
resources as long as they are cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, of YarnXpress, could not agree more. She said she was
pleased with the set-up features offered by Freemerchant.com but
played down the links it provided to search engines as a way of
generating business. More valuable, she said, was the link to eBay,
which led to the sales on which she built her business. Rather than
pay to put her business on established sites, she has used other
strategies, including starting an online group for knitters and
advertising in a knitting magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Freemerchant sees itself as giving small businesses ``a techno
grub stake,'' offering free site construction, free hosting and
back-office support like inventory control and sales-tax
calculation. But it stops short of being a shopping destination.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, online malls and portal shopping centers have the
benefit of traffic and built-in name recognition that can give an
instant lift to a merchant. While the cost of aligning with some of
these sites remains prohibitively high, other sites are lowering
monthly fees and offering business-related services.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista, for example, is adding a variety of direct-marketing
capabilities to its Shopping.com service while plugging more stores
_ large and small _ into the search and product listings areas.
</P>
<P>
   But such a relationship costs a few thousand dollars a month,
more than what many small retailers can afford. In addition,
analysts said, the big shopping sites' focus on comparison
shopping, particularly regarding price, is not often advantageous
for small retailers, who will be undercut by larger merchandisers.
</P>
<P>
   At Yahoo, whose goal is to be the leading shopping site on the
Web, Jennifer Dulski, a brand manager for Yahoo Shopping, which
includes Yahoo Stores, said services were geared to buyers as well
as sellers. Yahoo Shopping, which includes 9,500 stores and an
auction, offers tools to merchants to help them establish and
manage Web sites. The cost is about $100 a month to post 50 items,
but it rises from there.
</P>
<P>
   In late September, Amazon.com introduced zShops, which offers
merchants the chance to list their stores for $9.99 a month. Amazon
can process credit-card orders for an additional 2.25 percent of
the total sale. Merchants can also take advantage of Amazon's
one-click shopping feature, which allows consumers to store their
shipping and credit-card information in a database.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a senior analyst with Forrester Research, said that
while Amazon would provide a retailer with traffic for a while,
``the worry is, you're going to lose your category if Amazon
decides to offer your product.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, linking with a site that has a customer base of 17
million people is enticing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the people who have the financial resources to
advertise their Web site or latch on to those who can advertise for
them are the ones that are going to be successful,'' said John
Arnold, a customer-service manager with the Pacific Cookie Co. in
Santa Cruz, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Cookie has established a Web presence mainly through
partnerships in which it provides goods to sites wholesale but pays
nothing up front. It began with sites like Greatfood.com and then
established relationships with entities like Givechocolate.com, a
gift site.
</P>
<P>
   When approached by Amazon about joining zShops, Pacific Cookie
readily agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen a lot of orders from them,'' Arnold said,
``but just to be on a site like Amazon we thought was worth the
cost we were putting forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Cookie will not stop there. By this summer, Arnold said,
the company will be listed on about 10 shopping platforms, most of
which cost the company nothing.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bryan Matthews, who sells antique books in Los
Angeles, has stuck mostly to putting his books on databases.
Although he said he was approached daily by online virtual malls to
join their sites, he has gone with zShops because of his
longstanding relationship with Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews is also investing his time and energy in developing the
first online cooperative of booksellers, which he thinks will
protect his business interests in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will let people know there are all these independent
booksellers and turn them away from the brands and the big
platforms,'' he said. ``We want to let buyers know they are better
off dealing with personalities. We're the ones that have the
books.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Barbara Whitaker is a New York Times staff writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
