<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-GARDENING-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEB ADDS EXOTIC COLORS, BUT AT THE GARDEN'S EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Neal Johnston is a lawyer who gardens in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENERS in the United States, who spend about $5 billion a
year to watch things grow, can now watch the emergence of gardening
Web sites. Many electronic seedlings are in place, but much
pinching, pushing and pruning is coming.
</P>
<P>
   So far, growth has been slow, and it is almost entirely native.
All American mail-order gardening companies are now online, from
niche nurseries to the giant ones that fill a gardener's mailbox
and fulfill fantasies in January and February _ like Park Seed
(www.parkseed.com), Stokes Seeds (www.stokeseeds.com) and Burpee
Seeds and Plants (www .burpee.com). And all are struggling to
exploit the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Many gardeners are sure to switch to electronic ordering. Not
having to find a stamp or add up all those .95's at the end of
every price is an argument-winning convenience. Selection, as
opposed to ordering, is a different matter. The industry consensus
is that so far, the bulk of the e-commerce gardening business
involves new gardeners. The old hands still spread the catalogs
over the coffee table and spend half the winter gazing at the
midsummer marvels that always look best in February.
</P>
<P>
   But the move onto the Internet is inevitable. Those beautiful
catalogs are not cheap.
</P>
<P>
   For example, three years ago, White Flower Farm, a classic among
East Coast mail-order garden companies, bought Daffodil Mart, a
well-respected source of virtually every jonquil, tazetta and
cyclamineus daffodil ever named. It would be ridiculous excess for
White Flower to incorporate 600 different daffodil bulbs into its
fall catalog; it would be no less a waste to reduce the serious
specialists' choices to one-tenth of the number traditionally
listed by Daffodil Mart.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, White Flower Farm will post all the old Daffodil
Mart options on its Web site and continue to sell the four or five
dozen standard bulbs through its catalog.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce seems most likely to affect the garden's exotica: it
is a natural for the novice and the specialist. For the vast
middle, accustomed to ordering King Alfred daffodils by mail and
stopping by the garden center to eye a flat of white impatiens, its
utility will be restricted to ordering the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Only one company has its sights set on serving the entire
dirty-fingernail set: Garden.com, which was created in 1995 in
Austin, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   The company has contracted with about 70 nurseries nationwide,
each shipping directly to the buyer. The scattered inventory has
about 20,000 items, from seeds, plants and cut flowers to books and
garden gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Its Web site, at www.garden.com, is thoughtful, and its sales
last quarter tripled to $3.6 million from $1.2 million in the same
period the year before. But in the best e-commerce tradition, its
losses were even more impressive, rising to $7.2 million last
quarter from $2.1 million for the same period a year ago. The
company says it expects to turn a profit at the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Garden.com is a wonder world for the novice, and it is the
novice it has reached so far. The company says 90 percent of its
customers do not order through the mail, which creates
head-scratching by the experienced gardener who finds the site. For
instance, at the end of the season, Garden.com was offering
amaryllis buffs more than five dozen kinds of bulbs (at half price,
no less), and at the same time was offering four different types of
morning glory seedlings for $4.25 each. The only thing more certain
to grow than a morning glory seed is a child's foot, so only
gardeners with a profound mistrust of the post office would think
of ordering a morning glory seedling in late winter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the unsure, the options have been enormously
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I disagree about most things, including almost
everything in the garden. So she gets the backyard and I get the
top-floor deck. She likes tall, delicate, spiky things. I prefer
loud, vulgar splashy things. One such vulgarity is the caladium, a
flowerless low-lying leafy thing that resembles leftover Christmas
wrappings.
</P>
<P>
   The standard catalogs generally offer a half-dozen varieties of
caladium, which should satisfy most tastes. But two minutes with a
search engine leads straight to the handful of commercial caladium
growers around Lake Placid, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   These farms supply the mail-order houses, and in this case, if
home gardeners are willing to buy in lots of 25 bulbs where 5 would
normally do, they can quickly find twice as many choices at half
the regular price.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, a gasp of discovery and despair resonated
through the gardening world when yellow clivias were suddenly
available, at several hundred dollars for a flowering plant. The
clivia takes five years from germination to flower, but what
results is a wondrous foot-high stalk bearing a globe of red-orange
florets that last almost as long as an orchid and leave a rattle of
attractive seeds that glide from green to red to deep maroon over
12 months. It is a splendid way to thumb one's nose at mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that price was too steep even for the strangest of
colors. Two years later, the catalogs offered yellow clivia seeds.
I ordered two, for $40, with the near promise that five years later
at least one would turn into a yellow plant. After the indignity of
being put on a waiting list, I got my two seeds, and in three more
years may have something to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   My law partner, who can't tell a rhizome from a res ipsa
loquitor, went to the Web and tracked down the South African
hybridizer. At www.clivia.co.za, he ordered three seeds for a mere
$20.
</P>
<P>
   But as international as the Web may be, seeds and plants are a
focus of every country's border police, and retail commerce in
greenery is wrapped in red tape. Each order of yellow clivia seed
requires a $15 ''phytosanitary'' certificate.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dutch with their tulips and the Brazilians with their
passionflowers and the South Africans with their gesneriads put
their wares online, the American gardener may be exceedingly
frustrated by all the material that is not quite available at the
click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Author bio ... .) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
