<SLUG> BC-ECOM-BEAUTY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY SITES LET NICHE BRANDS PUT THEIR BEST FACE FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   By DONNA WILKINSON
</P>
<P>
   WHEN Kate Shoup Welsh wants to buy hip beauty products, she does
not head to a mall. ''I live in Indiana, and though we have some
nice stores here, you can't find a lot of high-end boutique
brands,'' said Ms. Welsh, the author of ''Bargain Shopping
Online.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, her fingers do the walking on the Web: ''I've shopped
at beautyscene.com, beautymax.com, beautybuys.com, eve.com,
beauty.com _ you name it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, there has been a virtual explosion of online
beauty retailers, which are estimated to total about 300. The
downside is that major players like Estee Lauder, Lancome and
Clinique _ which account for 70 percent of the $4 billion high-end
beauty market _ have not signed on with the new sites, though some
sites may sell these brands unauthorized. Major brands often set up
their own sites, instead.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the online slice of the beauty pie has been small. The
NPD Group, a research and consulting company in Port Washington,
N.Y., reported that in 1999, fewer than 1 percent of all beauty
products were sold online. However, Jupiter Communications, an
Internet research company based in New York, projects that by 2004,
5 percent of all beauty products will be sold online.
</P>
<P>
   The upside is that the start-ups have been a boon for niche
brands, which get limited shelf space in department or specialty
stores. ''A lot of these brands, even known ones, may not advertise
all over the country,'' Ms. Welsh said. ''I didn't even know
Versace made cosmetics until I saw them on beauty.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Lord, the vice president for content at ibeauty.com,
said, ''We're giving niche players a chance that they never would
have had in retail.'' Boutique beauty companies like Philosophy,
Bloom, Joey New York, Tony &AMP; Tina, Jaqua Girls (or Tom Girls),
Benefit, Urban Decay, Hard Candy, Nars, Tocca, Lorac, Vincent Longo
and Lolita Lempicka may not have the presence of a Lauder, but Web
exposure is helping to build their recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Philosophy, which is based in Phoenix and sells
250 beauty products with tongue-in-chic names like Hope in a Jar
and The Miracle Worker, was introduced in Barneys New York,
followed by Nordstrom, Saks Fifth Avenue and Sephora. ''People like
Oprah Winfrey talked about our line on her show, yet when people
went out to the stores, they could never find it,'' said Cristina
Carlino, the chief executive of Philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Internet companies started calling. Philosophy
signed up with eve.com, then ibeauty.com, gloss.com, beauty.com and
sephora.com. ''All of a sudden, e-commerce gave us a very broad
distribution,'' Ms. Carlino said. ''It's still limited to people
who are on the Internet. But for a small company like Philosophy,
it's been a good thing.'' It also boosted business at the counter.
''People who'd never heard of us were going into stores asking,
'Where's Philosophy?' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Internet's immediacy, the beauty business is
changing. ''There's a revolution going on in cosmetics right now,''
said Mariam Naficy, a founder of eve.com. ''Previously, it was
difficult to gain nationwide distribution. Department stores are a
very expensive proposition for any manufacturer _ you have to pay
for fixtures, the staff behind the counter and so on. On a Web
site, there is virtually nothing in costs, no fixed fee. It's
extremely profitable and it's a way to display the brand with
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey New York, which carries a 25-product skin-care line that
includes hot products like Super Duper Lips and Botox in a Bottle,
began eight years ago by selling through salons, spas and catalogs.
The company expanded to stores like Henri Bendel, Bergdorf Goodman
and Sephora. Now, Joey New York products are available at major
beauty sites _ beauty.com, beautyjungle.com, eve.com, ibeauty.com
and sephora.com.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our brand-name recognition has grown tremendously,'' said Joey
Roer, the company's founder and chief executive. ''In New York or
California, it's easy to get products like ours because there are a
lot of specialty stores, but for consumers who aren't aware of our
line, the sites have been great.''
</P>
<P>
   The sites have also helped Joey New York's bottom line. Ms. Roer
said, ''The beauty sites account for about 15 percent of our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, however, niche products cannot live by the Web alone.
''The real question will be the rate of growth,'' said Varsha Rao,
Ms. Naficy's partner at eve.com. ''Can they grow fast enough on the
Net? It remains to be seen. They may need multiple points of
distribution. It could be a store, a catalog or their own site.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Carlino said: ''I don't believe you can exist just in the
virtual world. I think people need to see these lines in very
traditional places.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that when it comes to beauty, real-world retail
still reigns. The sensory component _ packaging, texture, color,
scent _ plays a critical role in selling cosmetics. Most consumers
want to touch before they buy, which is the weak point of online
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts agree. ''The sites can't duplicate the
department-store experience,'' said Mike May, a digital commerce
analyst with Jupiter Communications. ''Sampling is going to have to
be a huge initiative for all these sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Karyn Schoenbart, a group president for tracking at the NPD
Group, said: ''When you go into a store like Saks and buy an
expensive product, there's a whole ambience that goes along with
that experience. I don't believe that beauty or apparel products
online are ever going to be as big as other types of online
products.''
</P>
<P>
   There certainly are few bargains. Online prices for niche beauty
products are usually the same as retail. ''It's hard to find
discounted high-end cosmetics online,'' said Ms. Welsh, the beauty
author. ''It's the convenience factor, and that counts for a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger question remains: How will all these beauty sites
with similar names and products survive? ''Without question, many
of the sites, even the well-capitalized ones, are going to fall by
the wayside or be rolled into another operation,'' Mr. May said.
Ms. Schoenbart agreed, saying, ''I feel confident saying there's
going to be tremendous consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is happening already. In recent months, jasmin.com, a
fragrance site, was bought by Ashford.com, a luxury goods site, and
beauty.com was recently purchased by drugstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   The online winners, Mr. May said, may be those sites with a
retail link. ''This is where Sephora has an advantage,'' he said.
''It can drive sampling and first-time purchases at its
brick-and-mortar stores. And then they can move customers to the
Internet for speedy replenishment purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   For niche brands, getting their message out is most important,
and the Web is an effective tool, Ms. Schoenbart said. ''There are
a lot of ways to build brand equity, and the Web is certainly one
of them,'' she added
</P>
<P>
   But being the next Estee Lauder may not be every beauty maker's
intention. Small is beautiful, too. ''We're very happy about where
we are today,'' said Ms. Carlino, of Philosophy. ''I don't think we
need to be anywhere else. We're just not prepared to handle any
more distribution. We just aren't there yet. It will take another
three or four years to think about getting bigger. We can only
handle where we are today.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital Style Guide For Beauty Sites
</P>
<P>
   With the crush of cyberbeauty retailers out there, it can be
hard to tell them apart. Here is what some popular sites offer:
</P>
<P>
   IBEAUTY.COM Features: Fashion show reports; expert advice on
skin care, fitness, nutrition and beauty; guide to services in
major cities. Policies: 30-day return; free shipping in the United
States; free gift-wrapping.
</P>
<P>
   EVE.COM Features: Advice from Charla Krupp, a former beauty
director of Glamour magazine; step-by-step videos by Vincent Longo,
a makeup artist; ''Beauty Oscars,'' like best mascara to Winona
Ryder in ''Girl, Interrupted.'' Policies: 30-day return; free
shipping in the United States with an order more than $40;
gift-wrapping, $3 per order; samples with purchase.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY.COM Features: Live chats with beauty advisers;
step-by-step makeovers from Kevyn Aucoin, a celebrity makeup
artist; ''It Girl'' profiles of hip young women. Policies: 30-day
return; free shipping in the United States; free gift-wrapping;
samples with purchase.
</P>
<P>
   SEPHORA.COM Features: Interactive celebrity makeup lessons
(Catherine Zeta-Jones's party face, for example); Q. and A. makeup
advice; step-by-step makeovers. Policies: 60-day return; free
shipping in the United States; free gift-wrapping; samples with
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTYJUNGLE.COM Features: ''Eye of the Beholder'' essays on
beauty; magazine- product-review database; ''Talk of Tinseltown''
describes how to get the stars' looks. Policies: 30-day return;
free shipping in the United States; gift-wrapping, $2.95.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTYSCENE.COM Features: Live chats with experts in plastic
surgery and hair care; articles on fashion, makeup, hair, fitness
and nutrition. Policies: 30-day return; free shipping in the United
States; free gift- wrapping; samples with purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
