<SLUG> BC-ADMISSIONS-CRUNCH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE ADMISSIONS RACE TIGHTENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL AND DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A crush of high school graduates, a flush economy, and changes
in the admissions process have made 2000 the most competitive year
ever for top students trying to gain entry to the college of their
choice, a survey of universities indicates.
</P>
<P>
   With many Ivy League colleges reporting record numbers of
applications, students from abroad and around the country
increasingly applying to colleges on the Internet, and more money
available for scholarships, the nation's top universities are
having to reject some of the best and brightest applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, for example, accepted its lowest percentage of applying
students this year. With a record 18,691 applications for 2,035
slots, the university turned down about 1,000 valedictorians, as
well as hundreds of students with perfect Scholastic Assessment
Test scores. Just since 1998, the percentage of applicants accepted
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology has fallen from 23
percent to 15 percent. And even Boston University, which has cut
recruiting to reduce the size of incoming freshman classes,
continues to get record numbers of applications.
</P>
<P>
   Admissions officials at schools including Brown, Yale,
Dartmouth, Princeton, Cornell, Tufts, Williams, Stanford, and
Amherst also report being swamped with applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real story isn't just in the numbers,'' said Marlyn
McGrath Lewis, director of admissions at Harvard College. ``From
where we sit, for several years running, the strength and quality
of the pool of applicants is much higher, and we can really feel
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Top grades and high SAT scores still land applicants in the A
pile for consideration, but as schools receive a glut of such
statistically promising students, other more subjective factors are
used to determine the cream of the crop.
</P>
<P>
   As well known as it is that applicants are judged on more than
SATs and grade point averages, the nation's top high school seniors
need more than a position on the student council or a
resume-building weekend volunteering at a local soup kitchen to
edge out their competition, admissions directors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make our decisions solely on objective information,''
said Maria Laskaris, admissions director at Dartmouth. ``We look at
love of learning, curiosity, a willingness to question and debate,
depth of analysis, and recommendations that tell us more than a
student is bright and hard-working. That distinguishes successful
applications.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, changing demographics have been the
most obvious explanation for the increased competition at top-tier
colleges. An ``echo baby boom,'' as some call it, is creating
increasingly larger numbers of 18-year-olds, and more of them are
applying to colleges every year.
</P>
<P>
   Of the approximately 2.8 million students who graduated from
high schools in the spring of 1997, a record 67 percent attended
college in the fall of 1998, according to federal figures.
</P>
<P>
   And those numbers are expected to increase through the next
decade. By the year 2012, according to the College Board, the
number of high school graduates will grow by 31 percent in the
West, 23 percent in the South, 17 percent in the Northeast, and 10
percent in the north-central states.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, however, the rise in the number of high school
graduates is supposed to peak sometime between 2004 and 2008,
according to the New England Board of Higher Education. And the
region is still recovering from a 15-year downturn in the number of
18-year-olds, which ended in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But since the rebound in population began _ New England public
and private colleges received more than 500,000 freshman
applications in 1999, a 7 percent increase from the previous year _
the competition only has gotten more intense, educators say. Last
year, 64 percent of the 217 undergraduate campuses in the region
saw an increase in freshman applications, according to the New
England Board of Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enrollment in New England is down compared to the rest of the
country because we have had the nation's slowest-growing
population,'' said John Harney, executive editor of the board's
Connection magazine. ``Students can now study at less expensive
institutions elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasing mobility, virtual tours of universities via the
Internet, and the ease of applying electronically have erased
previous boundaries for bright high school seniors who might have
chosen to attend a college closer to home otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Though hard data are lacking, admissions officials say
competition has been boosted by the number of applications filed
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a huge reason for higher numbers of
applications,'' said Michael Goldberger, director of admissions at
Brown University in Providence. ``Kids today are doing a better job
investigating, and the colleges are a lot more accessible to them
this way. It's easier for them to apply to multiple institutions,
and the schools don't seem quite as far away.''
</P>
<P>
   The stiffening competition to get into Brown, which had a record
16,803 applicants this year for 2,541 places in the freshman class,
is also attributable to changes in the university's admissions
process, Goldberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, like Harvard, MIT, and Boston College, has dropped
restrictions that prevented students seeking early admission from
applying to other colleges. In the past, students could only apply
to such schools for an early December decision if they didn't seek
such early acceptance elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the difference almost immediately,'' Goldberger said.
``Our regular applications stayed the same, while our early action
candidates increased by 65 percent from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The booming economy has also played a role in attracting more
applications to top schools that otherwise may have been
off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   The surging stock market, for example, has helped raise
endowments at Harvard to nearly $15 billion, $7 billion at Yale, $5
billion at Princeton, and $4.5 billion at Stanford. The more money
the universities have, the more they can give in scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, nearly 50 percent of undergraduates this year will
receive some form of financial support from university resources, a
record for the school. The average grant will cover almost
two-thirds of the $33,100 it costs to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Some educators also say rising SAT scores, aided by a growing
industry of test-prep services, have increased the number of
seniors who can consider applying to the top colleges.
</P>
<P>
   in Massachusetts, for example, high school students taking the
college-entry exam last year scored on average six points higher
than the previous year, and the scores have been improving steadily
since 1994. The average was 511 on both the math and verbal
sections of the SATs, with 78 percent of all high school students
in the state taking the test.
</P>
<P>
   But all the competition has hurt many hard-working high school
seniors and has put pressure on admissions committees and directors
to explain why top-tier candidates are rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The calls come in now every few hours, sometimes more
frequently, and it's often up to Lewis to explain to the angry
parent on the line why the student in question, maybe a
valedictorian with perfect SAT scores, didn't get into Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Laskaris at Dartmouth said she can hear it in the tone of
their voices. Sometimes it's the students who call, confused,
disappointed, and looking for answers. And as much as she tries to
explain the process, how a knack for fencing or leadership on the
student council might make the difference, she said it will never
be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not believe this, but it's painful turning away so
many promising candidates,'' Lewis said. ``All we can do is try to
tell people the truth: There was not any flaw in their son or
daughter's application; it's just other people were chosen instead.
Of course, that's a very unsatisfactory message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
