<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     04-12 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES HURT WHEN NEW, OLD ECONOMIES COLLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it wasn't the ideal moment to tell the world you were
gung-ho on electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   No one will compare the Staples Inc. stock slide of the last six
weeks to the kind of plunges suffered by investors in scores of
Internet companies, but there is little doubting a connection
between them.
</P>
<P>
   The Staples slump since March 1, which has cut the company's
stock price by 29.5 percent, also shows just how difficult it can
be to mix conventional business with new economy ventures and keep
shareholders happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many investors who own retail stocks are not the same people
who buy Internet stocks,'' said Staples chief executive Tom
Stemberg. ``In effect, a retailer actively pursuing e-commerce is
selling apples to orange buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing black and white about the recent Staples slide.
Continued interest rate hikes by the Federal Reserve could hurt
business, though many retail stocks have climbed recently.
</P>
<P>
   Worries over how weaker competitors could hurt Staples's office
supply market persist. Some people wonder if the company's overhead
cost containment, which helped results in the most recent quarter,
can be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no getting around the impact of comments by Staples
on March 2 about business at its Staples.com, which is expected to
sell as much as $250 million in tracking stock to the public,
probably later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Wall Street was starting to punish e-commerce companies
that spent relentlessly to bring business through the virtual door,
Staples announced it would accelerate online investments and
planned to lose $150 million on its Internet venture this year,
twice as much as previously forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was awful,'' said Rary Delaney, an analyst at Fleet
Investment Advisors, which owns Staples stock.
</P>
<P>
   Staples.com was knocking the cover off the ball in its fiscal
fourth quarter with sales that increased 80 percent from the
previous three months and 450 percent compared to the same period a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to capitalize on this is now,'' Staples.com president
Jeanne Lewis said in a statement at the time. The goal was
explicit: strike while the iron was hot and spend to win market
share by acquiring new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the reason for upping the spending was to be put in
the category of a very aggressive dot-com company with a land-grab
mentality,'' said Eileen Leary, an analyst at State Street Research
and Management, another big Staples investor.
</P>
<P>
   That led Aram Rubinson of PaineWebber to downgrade Staples to a
``neutral'' recommendation shortly after the announcement, though
he appeared to be the only brokerage analyst to cut his rating. ``I
think it's probably the biggest issue at the moment, whether the
existing shareholder base is willing to tolerate as aggressive
(Internet) spending as they are with a pure play,'' said Rubinson.
</P>
<P>
   Stemberg is not one to pin all of Staples's stock problems on
the company's more aggressive Internet expansion, but he agrees it
is a ``contributing factor.''
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with Staples executives, Stemberg says, ``I
discussed a number of factors that have contributed to the stock
decline, including that investors are not excited about our
aggressive spending decisions, decisions to take a leadership
position in the small business arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage analysts and institutional investors generally like
Staples's chances in the online world. It already has lots of
advantages start-up e-retailers spend a fortune to create: a valued
brand name, sophisticated order fullfillment operations and volume
that commands the best prices from suppliers. They have helped
generate online gross profit margins north of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Staples.com also brought in a blue-chip group of Internet
investors and venture capitalists for an early stake and seats on
an advisory board that also includes eBay Inc. chief Meg Whitman
and William Sahlman of the Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   But the type of large institutional shareholder who owns Staples
stock isn't necessarily thrilled about fast-spending Internet
ventures and Web investors aren't interested in conventional retail
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   When Staples.com goes public, it may help by creating stocks for
both categories. But Staples still will own the lion's share of its
online venture and therefore investors in the parent company will,
too. Who will stay and what will they demand?
</P>
<P>
   These are no easy questions and will be posed in many different
industries coping with the Internet for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retail business is like an aircraft carrier _ investors
are looking for steadiness, healthy growth,'' Stemberg said.
``Internet businesses are more like cigarette boats that fly over
the waves and you are willing to take the bumps. The game is about
revenue growth. When you try to mix the two together, what you end
up with is something that is not entirely appealing to either
category,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
