<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-BIRD-BOS &LR;      04-12 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BIRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS SHARE BIRD'S VISION: A FAREWELL CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The game is over, and the W is in the books. The
coach strides into the interview room, looks down at a local
scribe, and without being asked a question, starts talking about
``36 percent on contests'' (as in accent on the second syllable).
</P>
<P>
   So who is this? Hubie Brown, coming out of retirement? Larry
Brown? Rick Pitino? No, it's Larry Bird, indulging in some serious
coachspeak.
</P>
<P>
   He really is a coach, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he is, and he's kind of amused with the transformation
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 26 or 27,'' he said with a laugh, ``the only thing
I'd be thinking about after a game was going home and drinking some
beer in my garage.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, deep into his third season as head coach of the Indiana
Pacers, he walks like a coach, talks like a coach, thinks like a
coach, and, most of all, agonizes like a coach.
</P>
<P>
   `You know,'' he said, ``when I played, if we were up 5 with two
minutes to go, I figured you could chalk it up. We're at Toronto
last Sunday, and there's just a couple of minutes left. Sam Perkins
hits a three to put us up 21. I said, `All right, maybe this is
over.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So what's with this ``contest'' business?
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy put a hand up on me, it never bothered me much,'' he
explained. ``But it really makes a difference. We keep track. I was
talking about this with (Indianapolis Star beat man) Mark Montieth
Tuesday, and I was just telling him that they shot 36 percent when
contested and 54 percent when uncontested.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   A coach never runs out of worries, but Bird will tell you this
for sure: He won't be worried about coaching matters much longer.
Catch him now, because he swears that when the Pacers' season is
over, no one will ever find him on the sidelines again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe him,'' said the Pacers' Jalen Rose. ``He's said from
Day 1 that he'll coach out this contract, and that's it. We've got
to make sure it ends with cigars and champagne. Hopefully, we're on
course for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are good, but no one believes they are that good.
They are an old, fragile team, with some obvious strengths and some
appalling weaknesses. They may have peaked in a seven-game series
with Chicago two years ago. It would be a significant achievement
for the Pacers to outmaneuver Miami and New York, not to mention
Philadelphia and Charlotte, and somehow win the Eastern Conference
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to come out of the East,'' Bird said, ``and it
could be us. If Shaq goes down, anything could happen. That's why I
stress, `Get there, and let's roll the dice.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But win or lose, he is outta here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three years have gone by pretty fast; I'll tell you
that,'' he said. ``But I believe that three years are enough for
any coach, other than Pat Riley. And Jerry Sloan gets away with it.
It's all according to the kind of players you have. But, for me,
three years will be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Some slight interpretation is needed. What Larry said in
parenthesis is that three years in one place is about right for the
average guy in any average situation. As for Bird, the Pacers were
the only team he ever would have coached, and three is enough for
him. He has always pretty much thought that the coaching sun rose
and set on Riley, and he thinks that the Jazz are a realm unto
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   People in the organization are willing to accept it, but they
don't really understand it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so few players who come in and really get it, right
away,'' said general manager David Kahn. ``Larry did. And he's just
gotten better and better as a coach. It is very frustrating to see
him walk away when he is starting to master his craft.''
</P>
<P>
   If the mucky-mucks are sad about Bird's imminent departure, how
do you think the players feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe him,'' said Austin Croshere, Bird's first draft
choice. ``I wish it weren't true. He's a lot more hands-on this
year. He's taken more control in practice. He's more open
personally with the players. I think he's having a good time. He
coached in the summer league last year, and I sensed he really
liked being around the young kids who were just running up and down
the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the funny part. Bird does like coaching. He just thinks
it's ``time.''
</P>
<P>
   He's satisfying his competitive urges. He's tapping into some
old feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to love winning on the road,'' he said. ``There was
nothing better. There still isn't. When we win a good one on the
road, I like to just sit in the office a little longer after the
game and soak it up. Of course, you know there's a love fest going
on out there on the floor, and I hate that. I don't want to see
that. It's a different league now. So I'll sit inside and enjoy
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He recognizes that it's all different with him than with most
other guys. He's got all the money he and several generations of
Birds will ever need. He's coaching because he wants to coach, not
because he has to. He took the Indiana job because it was the right
time, with the right franchise, with the right immediate boss
(Donnie Walsh), with the right owners (Herb and Melvin Simon), and
with a team that could win. Subtract any of these ingredients, and
he would not have taken the job, not that he needed a job. He
cannot imagine how gut-wrenching this life would be if he had to
coach generic Team X in order to put food on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand how guys are lifers at this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What no one can figure out is what Bird will do next. He
discovered just how quickly the golfing and fishing thing can get
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year I probably played five times a week,'' he said.
``At the end I was probably out there once a week _ if that.''
</P>
<P>
   When he took the Pacers job, he said it was, in part, because
coaching was the closest thing he could find to replicate the
competition he had relished during a 25-year playing career. So he
won't have that kick any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' he said, ``I'd love that. There just aren't too
many people out there you'd want to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   General managing or player personnel stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's left to do that really intrigues me,'' he
said, ``is to be able to put a team together. That would be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing cooking on any of these fronts. So what is
he going to do once he retires from coaching? A lot of people who
are interested in him from afar, not to mention many people who
really do know him, are concerned. What could possibly make Larry
Bird happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Professionally?'' he said. ``Look, I've only been really happy
professionalwise for three weeks in my life _ the week after each
of the championships. Believe me, other than that, I've never been
happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy around my kids, and I'm happy doing stuff with
(wife) Dinah. But professionally, it's always just grinding and
grinding and never remembering enough about the good games.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of kids, how would you like to be coach of a youth team
and see Larry Bird sitting in the stands? It happens. Connor Bird
is growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Connor's playing now,'' said Bird. ``The other day we
came home after a game and I thought of something Red used to say.
I told him, `Connor, you're out there in the living room, and the
action's in the kitchen.' I always liked that. But Connor's my
little M.L. Carr. When the other kids are out of the game, they're
waving to the crowd. But Connor is really watching the game, and
he's cheering for the other kids. Yup, he's my little M.L.''
</P>
<P>
   The best guess is that Bird will return to Naples and take at
least a year off. Let everyone else worry about what he's going to
do. Bird isn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, Larry. One year from today, you have no idea what you
might be doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' he said with a shake of his head. ``Absolutely no
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got antsy last time, he took the Pacers job. When he
gets antsy this time, he'll do something else. It's about that
simple.
</P>
<P>
   For the final time, would Larry Bird ever coach again, at any
level?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never do it again,'' he said. ``And not because I didn't
like it. It's been a ride. It's been competitive. It's been fun.''
</P>
<P>
   John Updike said, aropos of Ted Williams, that ``Gods don't
answer letters.'' They don't always have the same thought process
as we mortals, either. Larry Bird simply feels it's time for him to
go, and so nothing else matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
