<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ELIAN _ MIAMI _ The latest developments in the case of
6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez. (MWilliams, Cox News
Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RALLY _ WASHINGTON _ The AFL-CIO leads a massive rally to
reject permanent ``normal trade relations'' with China. Congress is
expected to take up the issue in earnest and vote on it next month.
While corporate interets have pushed hard for it, unions and human
rights groups are steadfastly against it. The organizers expect
more than 10,000 ``working families'' to descend upon Capitol Hill.
Developing. (A.Schultz, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LIPSTADT _ LONDON _ A profile of Dr. Deborah Lipstadt, Emory
University scholar. Who is she? We get her thoughts in the
aftermath of the Holocaust trial verdict. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, saying that , Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas was engaged in ``political malpractice,''
urged newspaper editors Wednesday to take a close look at health
care reforms proposed by his Republican rival. (Glass, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAXES _ WASHINGTON _ Senate Commerce Committee Chairman
John McCain, R-Ariz., said Wednesday that because of growing
pressure from state officials and traditional retailers, he will
delay trying to extend an Internet tax moratorium.. (Geewax, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   PIPELINE-SAFETY _ WASHINGTON _ The Transportation Department
holds a round-table discussion Wednesday to respond to Vice
President Al Gore's proposal to improve oil and gas pipelines,
which critics say pose environmental and safety hazards. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Wis., one of the
most liberal members of Congress, joined Wednesday with a staunch
conservative, Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., to introduce legislation
to crack down on the growing problem of tafficking in sexual
slavery. A recent CIA report says that 50,000 women and children
are brought into the United States annually for forced
prostitution. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CDC-PROBE _ WASHINGTON _ A congressional investigation of
Atlanta's Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has expanded
to another controversy, this one over a planned public education
program to identify people who might have had transfusions of blood
tainted by hepatitis C. Investigators for the House Commerce
Committee have asked for documentation for $13.7 million budgeted
for hepetitis C. At the same time, the House panel has been
obtaining stacks of agency documents, including travel and
personnel records, for Dr. Brian Mahy, the former Viral Division
chief. The committee is examining whether the CDC has misled
Congress in how the Viral Division spent its funding. (Malone, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS _ DENVER - President Clinton travels to Denver to
tout his gun control plans. (Grand Junction Daily Sentinel). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDWARDS _ BATON ROUGE, La._Former Gov. Edwin Edwards continues
testifying under cross-examination in his racketeering trial.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG _ COLUMBIA _ So far, the battle over South Carolina's
flying the Confederate battle flag atop the Statehouse has been
fought in public rallies, newspapers and broadcasts. Wednesday, the
skirmish moves to a body that has a real say in the debate: the
state Senate. Senators will try to hammer out a compromise that
will move the Civil War emblem to a spot on the Statehouse grounds
and off the penny-colored dome. It's widely thought that state Sen.
Glenn McConnell holds the key to compromise. The Charleston
Republican, who owns a Civil War memorabilia shop, has been
steadfast in his support of the flag. Moderates, though, are
hopeful he'll be the one to offer a compromise deal that ultimately
will be sent to the state House. Another pro-flag senator said
Wednesday will be ``Armageddon'' in the already fiery debate. South
Carolina is the only state that flies the battle flag from its
Capitol dome, though Mississippi and Georgia have incorporated the
design into their state flags. Debate starts at 11 a.m. Wednesday
and could drag into the weekend if needed. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-PRISONS _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla., _ With a state prison
crowding problem more than five years behind them, lawmakers are
contemplating what will happen if private prison companies start
importing murderers, drug dealers and other criminals from out of
state. Prison companies insist they have no plans to host the rest
of the country's inmate population in Florida, though they do own
vacant land. Since the state has no laws on this issue, corrections
officials say that leaves the door open to private companies could
building new prisons for out-of-state inmates, tomorrow with
virtually no state regulation. ``It's ridiculous,'' said Sen. Tom
Rossin, D-West Palm Beach. ``Why do we want to bring (inmates) from
out of state into the state? We have enough of our own problems.''
(Bierman, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
