<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4711 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-HOVAN-BOS &LR;      04-12 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-HOVAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOVAN ALL SET TO TACKLE THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Chris Hovan will gather up his belongings Wednesday,
load them in his new Ford Expedition, point himself in the general
direction of the Midwest, and begin the solitary drive back home to
Cleveland. He'll groove to a few tunes along the way. Nothing too
metallic. Or too boring. Maybe even some country music. Perhaps
Willie Nelson crooning ``On the Road Again'' would be appropriate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just some easy listening,'' he said with a laugh. ``I don't
want to get too hyped up before Saturday because I know that's how
I am. That's me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovan will be alone with his thoughts on the way home to
Cleveland, where his football career began as a standout defensive
lineman at St. Ignatius High. ``He started out as a linebacker in
the fifth- and sixth-grade recreational league,'' recalled Hovan's
father, Dennis. ``But he just kept moving up and up as he kept
getting better and better. By the time he got to the seventh- and
eighth-grade parochial school league, they started flopping him
over and playing him on both sides of the line. He never came out
of the game except for halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, that career will come full circle when the
All-American defensive tackle from Boston College is selected in
the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Hovan made certain of his future employment with an eye-opening
performance in the NFL scouting combine in February in
Indianapolis, where the 6-foot-2 1/2-inch, 305-pounder had several
scouts doing double-takes. He ran a 4.8 in the 40-yard dash, pumped
out 32 repetitions in the 225-pound bench press, clocked a 4.16 in
the short shuttle run, and recorded a 30-inch vertical leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest knock on me going to the combine was my
athleticism,'' said Hovan, who devoted a considerable amount of
time after his stellar senior season working with BC's assistant
strength and conditioning coach, John Whitesides. ``I knew what I
could do and I knew what I had to do to prove these people wrong.
So we worked on the 40, we worked on the short shuttle, the bench,
the vertical, the three-cone drill . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``People were really, really happy, and I turned a lot of
people's heads. I went through the line drills really fluidly, and
I was able to open the eyes of some GMs and coaches, so that was
the main focus.''
</P>
<P>
   The only questions that remain for draft day are: What round?
And which team?
</P>
<P>
   Will it be the first round, as predicted in The Sporting News,
which ranked Hovan second behind Florida State's Corey Simon among
a strong class of defensive tackles?
</P>
<P>
   And will it be the Packers who select him? The Giants? Jets?
Steelers? Eagles? Colts? Seahawks? Or Raiders? All have expressed
an interest.
</P>
<P>
   What questions could NFL scouts possibly have about Hovan now?
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been that many,'' said BC coach Tom O'Brien.
``Everybody calls and basically asks the same thing. Nowadays,
character seems to be a much more important question. Will he
practice? Will he play hurt? Those kind of things are what they
generally ask about everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hovan's case, that was never the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably the one kid who improved, both on the field and
off, every single year in my three years here so far,'' O'Brien
said.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year starter at BC, Hovan was regarded as a tireless
worker in the weight room and the strongest player on the team for
the last three seasons. Noted for the eye-black he smears on his
face, Hovan gained more notoriety when he wrapped up his senior
year by making 75 tackles (47 unassisted, 20 for losses, including
11 sacks). He became the first BC player to be named All-Big East
first team three consecutive years, and he was a first-team
selection to the Burger King/AFCA All-America team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a player like him,'' said BC defensive line
coach Mike London, ``you try to put him in as advantageous position
as possible, so we moved him around a lot and tried to put him in
match-up situations where we could best utilize his abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Hovan plans to utilize those abilities in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Ask any draft hopeful where he would prefer to play, and
invariably the answer will be: ``Anywhere.'' But ask Hovan, and
he'll tell you, straight up, it would be for his hometown Browns.
</P>
<P>
   But he knows it is not likely, given Cleveland's pole position
in the draft order and the expectation Penn State defensive end
Courtney Brown will be the first player taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when you're a kid you always love your hometown
team,'' he said. ``I've got to the point in my life where I love
football so much that I just want to play anywhere where I can play
right now. I just can't wait to play in the NFL right now. If a
team wants me more than another team, then that's where my heart
and soul is going to be _ with that team. So, really, you start up
with the team that wants you and, hopefully, you end up that way,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one player he targeted during his workouts at the
combine: Simon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courtney Brown will probably be the No. 1 pick,'' Hovan said.
``He's a very good player and he's a great pass rusher and he's a
talent that hasn't come around for a long, long time. Hopefully,
for myself, I'm neck-and-neck with Corey Simon. That was the main
goal. If it wasn't to jump ahead, then to make people think twice
about us. I wanted to make people think, `Chris Hovan's got a lot
to offer, and Corey Simon's a great player, too. This is a tough
choice.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, by the style I play, they'll choose me ahead of
him. That was the main focus, to go down there and jump out to No.
1 tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all up to the GMs and coaches now. It's their decision
now. Certain coaches have talked to me and interviewed me, and it's
going to be the team's preference, so we'll just see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the player London described as ``a guy who has a great
motor'' will crank it up one more time, hit the road, and head for
home, where he plans to spend draft day surrounded by family and
friends to get the phone call for which he's waited his entire
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited,'' he said. ``It's something that I've been
dreaming about since I was a little kid. Now the opportunity has
arisen and I'm just getting ready and excited, and I just can't
wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
