<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-TAX-RUSH-ART-BOS &LR;      04-12 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-RUSH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR TAX-PREPARATION PROS, DAYS ARE IN LONG FORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HINGHAM, Mass. _ Poor John Danehy. The only time he's been able
to find to fertilize his evergreens is at 6:30 in the morning. He's
temporarily given up jogging, he's cut his tennis time in half, and
he hasn't given skiing a moment's thought all winter. Even worse,
his baseball pals went to Opening Day at Fenway Park Tuesday
without him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Danehy is spending about 80 hours hunkered down inside
his carpeted office here. Just as he did last week. And the week
before that. His tie is loosened only slightly (he's a certified
public accountant, after all), but he's besieged on all sides by
the tools of the season. His files bulge. His computer purrs. His
telephone jangles. And visions of itemized deductions dance in his
head.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Danehy is no undertaker, but if death is indeed
one of life's only two certainties, he represents the other: taxes.
He's an income tax preparer, one of the uncounted tens of thousands
of paid professionals assisting roughly half of the country's 126
million individual taxpayers with their 1999 returns. Normally the
tax season runs from approximately February 1 to precisely April
15, but this year, because of the upcoming holiday weekend, it will
last three days longer for those of us _ meaning the residents of
the six New England states and upstate New York _ who file at the
Andover IRS Center. That means that Danehy, a ``sole practitioner''
with one full-time employee, has until Tuesday to labor over
returns for the 220 or so of his 320 individual clients who aren't
taking a four-month filing extension.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why the folks who pay him $250 and up (and whose
incomes range from modest five figures to low seven figures) have
this year been in no particular hurry to bring him their requisite
data. For his part, Danehy is puzzled by their tardiness. ``I
thought the good weather would bring 'em in, because usually even a
snowflake causes them to cancel appointments,'' he says. ``So now
my theory is that people are doing so well in this economy that
most of them owe the government money. And since they knew they
weren't getting refunds, they were reluctant to come in early.''
</P>
<P>
   He sighs. ``In February, I was sitting here twiddling my
thumbs,'' he laments.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it is not only self-employed accountants who are
experiencing the annual tensions of tax season. A mixed bag
consisting of lawyers, IRS-certified ``enrolled agents,'' and
just-plain kitchen-table types also plies the tax-prep trade.
There's Mary Lou Wilson, an H&AMP;R Block employee who is one of the
company's nearly 50,000 tax preparers and who will personally turn
out about 600 returns by Tuesday. There's Richard Eckstein of the
accounting firm of Walter &AMP; Shuffain PC, who takes his clients'
data home at night, cranks up his PC, and works ``until I can't do
it anymore.'' There's Lynne McLaren, an enrolled agent who labors
alone in a second-floor walk-up, a well-heated office where a copy
of the original Form 1040, vintage 1913, hangs on the wall. There's
Eric Weinstein, a second-generation tax preparer who works in
storefront and sells cars when he's not crunching numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But while tax preparers differ, their high season does not, and
Danehy's is typical: He simply hits the pause button on his
nonprofessional life. ``Between February 1 and the middle of April,
I don't pick up a paintbrush or a snow shovel unless it's an
absolute emergency,'' he muses. (When Tax Season '78 turned into
the Blizzard of '78, Danehy went to work anyway and, after his car
was hit by a snowplow, was stranded on Route 128 while police
evacuated his pregnant wife from their heatless home.)
</P>
<P>
   Capital gains? Income from estates and trusts? IRA
distributions? Danehy wrestles with such gremlins until long after
sundown, whereupon, having skipped lunch yet again, he hauls
himself home to eat a late dinner before invariably falling asleep
on the sofa in front of the family television set.
</P>
<P>
   He concedes that more than 25 tax seasons have robbed him of
considerable time with his three daughters, now grown, but there
was at least one instance of payback along the way: Several years
ago, after their father dozed off in front of the TV, the trio
placed bows in his hair, put lipstick on his mouth, and painted his
nails. ``The next morning, he showered and went to work,'' says his
youngest daughter, Liz Danehy. ``While he was meeting with a client
he noticed that his pinky nail was still painted red. Needless to
say, he wasn't happy with us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for him at this time of year,'' says Danehy's wife,
Mary, whom he wed 27 years ago. (``Notice I got married after tax
season ended,'' John Danehy points out.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just dragging when he comes home,'' Mary says. ``He's not
physically tired. He's mentally exhausted. I don't know how he
thinks straight.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of most days, Danehy admits, he doesn't. ``I know
it's time to go home when I start making mental errors and snapping
at people,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Danehy will do his best to limit his appointments over the next
few days, leaving time not only for last-minute details but also
for the type of client who showed up on his doorstep one April 14:
a clinical psychologist who in the previous year had married twice,
had divorced once, had worked in two states, had lived in a third,
and had worked two jobs. ``It took three days just to figure out
what his marital status was,'' Danehy says. ``Needless to say, I
filed an extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Danehy's clients include four senior military officers, three
authors, a restaurateur who gains income in both Massachusetts and
Florida, a United Nations employee in Mozambique, and a US
physician with Canadian income. He prepares about 40 out-of-state
returns. Like most tax prepararers, he is extremely grateful for
the commercial diagnostic software _ for which he says he pays
about $3,000 a year _ that helps him wind his way through the
growing complexities of US tax law. ``I do not,'' he says, ``wear a
green visor or a pocket protector.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the returns that Danehy prepares are for
working couples, but something has clearly changed in the world of
family finance. ``With the over-50 types, it's the guy who watches
the money,'' the accountant explains. ``Among younger couples, it's
often the wife who's the more financially savvy about personal
financial matters. That's true even if she's a stay-at-home wife. I
have big-income guys who can't do their taxes without calling their
wives.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, John Danehy will go out for a celebratory dinner
with the five other accountants who rent space in the same office
condominium. Sometime thereafter, he and his wife will leave for
their annual post-tax-season vacation to a yet-to-be-determined
destination. Then he'll come back to his office to face the 100 or
so 1999 tax returns for which he has filed an extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Including,'' he points out wearily, ``my own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
