<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARAMEL OR PECANS _ THE SLICE IS RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kathryn Moore of Bedford, Texas, sent in the requested recipe
for caramel pie. She writes, ``My grandmother, Bertha Reese White,
and my mother-in-law, Opal Lathrup Moore, and her mother, Tommie
Lathrup, made wonderful homemade caramel cream pies. I am sending
two lists of ingredients, and the directions are the same for both.
I hope this is exactly the taste that the reader is looking for. I
must admit that I never took the trouble to make this pie, but it
makes my mouth water just thinking about the caramel smell and
taste in my grandmother's kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda B. Dickson of Arlington, Texas, sent the cake recipe. She
writes that this recipe was originally on the back of an Imperial
Brown Sugar box, probably in the early 1970s, and is named harvest
pecan cake. ``The first time I made it,'' she writes, ``there was
an immediate addition to my `favorite' list. The rich, dark color
and the wonderful taste of pecans made it a winner that I serve at
special occasions and just because.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CARAMEL PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups scalded milk
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Butter (size of an egg)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Deep-dish pastry pie shell, baked
</P>
<P>
   My family used an iron skillet to caramelize or brown the sugar.
Cook on low heat. Watch carefully, or it will scorch. When brown,
add milk. In a bowl, mix flour, melted butter and vanilla, blending
well. Add egg yolks to flour mixture. Mix until smooth and creamy.
Add this to the milk mixture. Cook until thick, stirring almost
constantly. Some people use a double boiler so it will not stick or
burn. Add salt.
</P>
<P>
   Make meringue with egg whites. Pour filling into baked pie
shell. Top with meringue and bake until meringue is brown.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 549 calories, 16 grams fat, 95
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 126 milligrams cholesterol,
259 milligrams sodium, 27 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   HARVEST PECAN CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 16-20
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 cups butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dark-brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons instant coffee granules dissolved in 3 tablespoons
hot water 4 cups chopped pecans, see Note
</P>
<P>
   Note: Do not skimp on the pecans. It will not be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Grease bottom of a 10-inch tube pan. Preheat oven to 325
degrees. Separate eggs and beat yolks well. Cream butter and sugar
in large mixing bowl. Sift flour with baking powder and salt.
Combine milk, vanilla and coffee. Mix together, alternating wet
with dry ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg whites until stiff but not dry. Fold pecans and egg
whites into batter mixture. Pour into prepared tube pan and bake
for 1 1/2 hours, or until cake tests done.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 518 calories, 35 grams fat, 47
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 65 milligrams cholesterol,
341 milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
