<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-JACOBS-BOS &LR;      04-12 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-JACOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANE JACOBS'S NEW YORK STATE OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jane Jacobs doesn't look much like a folk hero. She
seems more like a figure from a Roz Chast cartoon in The New Yorker
_ the frumpy lady with white bangs, beaked nose, big glasses, and a
jolly smile that makes her face beam.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, though: Jacobs once terrified the powers of
this city. She led protest brigades, saved whole neighborhoods from
the wrecking ball, inspired generations of community activists, and
changed the way urban planners, scholars, and ordinary citizens
think about cities.
</P>
<P>
   She left New York for Toronto 32 years ago and carried on there,
stopping an expressway that threatened to cut through the middle of
the city practically the moment she arrived. She has rarely come
back to her old hometown in the decades since. But when she visited
late last month, to speak at the Public Library and promote her new
book, ``The Nature of Economies'' (Modern Library), hundreds packed
the hall to cheer her return.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, sitting in her hotel room on the Upper East Side,
Jacobs said she has no regrets about leaving all those years ago,
but she retains her love for New York _ ``it has so much vitality,
so much pizazz.'' And while she despairs at its many problems, she
is pleased with how much the place has improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``One good thing about getting old,'' said Jacobs, who is now
84, ``is you get to see how things turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, New York has improved to the degree that it has
followed Jane Jacobs' advice, and it has serious shortcomings to
the degree that it has ignored her.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, Jacobs wrote ``The Death and Life of Great American
Cities,'' and if she had never written another word or committed
another act, her place in history would be secure. An audacious and
clear-headed tome, written by a mother in her mid-40s who never
went to college, it famously began:
</P>
<P>
   ``This book is an attack on current city planning and
rebuilding. It is also, and mostly, an attempt to introduce new
principles of city planning and rebuilding, different and even
opposite from those now taught in everything from schools of
architecture and planning to the Sunday supplements and women's
magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the high priests of urban planning touted the
bulldozing of disorderly neighborhoods for massive expressways and
sterile towers (and called it ``urban renewal''), Jacobs celebrated
the hubbub of unplanned diversity and the spontaneity of the
sidewalk, which she viewed as ``the art form of the city'' and its
true source of vitality and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Back then she lived on Hudson Street, in the West Village, the
area of Manhattan that most matched her ideal _ short, winding
blocks, with a mix of old and new buildings, residential and
commercial, and lots of people out on the street, for lots of
different reasons, at all hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, when urban planners tried to declare her
neighborhood a ``slum'' and raze it for high-rises, Jacobs led the
opposition and won the battle. She even designed an alternative
plan for a big middle-income apartment complex that could be built
in the area without tearing down anything (the West Village Houses,
still the happy home of hundreds).
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, when the city planned to build an expressway
to connect the Holland Tunnel with the Manhattan and Williamsburg
bridges _ essentially wiping SoHo off the map _ she jumped into
action again, this time dealing Robert Moses, the most powerful
builder-destroyer in New York's history, his first major defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Berman, the cultural historian, saw her victory as a
turning point, a decisive acceptance of the idea ``that the street
and the neighborhood were the very heart of city life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of her victory, Jacobs _ disgusted by the US
government's involvement in the Vietnam War, and feeling alienated
by its harsh suppression of the antiwar protests _ moved to Toronto
in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The deterioration of New York City in the early 1970s deepened
her mood. ``When I'd come back and visit,'' she recalled, ``I would
realize how sad I had been getting with the way things were getting
continually worse _ and how happy I was with the way things in
Toronto were getting wonderfully better, how this improved the
spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, she went all the way and became a Canadian citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much more civil society than America,'' she said of her
adopted homeland. ``I like that civility. But it does have its
drawbacks. It's hard to know really what people are thinking, and
it's considered impolite to ask. In New York, people don't mind
telling you, `What you said was stupid!' In Canada, it's a little
like talking to a pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs's new book is written in the form of a spirited
conversation among four friends. ``I was going to set it in
Toronto, but I couldn't get my characters to argue with each
other,'' she said with a cackle of a laugh. ``I was at my wits' end
with writer's block. So I put them in New York _ wow, that was
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   The five books she has written since moving have taken on the
same themes as ``Death and Life of Great American Cities.'' ``The
Economy of Cities'' (1969) analyzed how cities spur the economic
rise and fall of regions and nations. ``Cities and the Wealth of
Nations'' (1984) cast cities as the driving force behind global
development.
</P>
<P>
   Her new book posits the idea that cities, and economic systems
in general, work according to the same principles as the ecosystems
in nature. ``I've been getting broader and broader,'' she said,
again with a laugh. ``First cities, then the world, now the
universe.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an idea that she began pondering 30 years ago. ``I didn't
know I was thinking about a particular book,'' she said. ``I was
just noticing things that were adding up.''
</P>
<P>
   Failed foreign-aid projects, the downfall of Detroit, the
ruination of farmland in Uzbekistan, deserts that never bloom _ all
had a similar cause: a lack of diversity, which, as she had found
in her earliest studies of cities, was essential to refueling and
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to understand how innovation occurs
successfully and how diversity grows successfully,'' she said,
``because we can do better whenever we introduce new methods, new
products _ and that requires economies that can develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream economists have long viewed specialization as the
best avenue for growth, especially for poor regions or Third World
countries. Jacobs sees it as the surest road to failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada used to try to help its poor regions with these big
projects,'' she recalled. ``They'd put a big factory out in the
middle of nowhere to make heavy water for a nuclear power plant. Or
they put a great big cucumber project in Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is,'' she went on, ``they didn't realize
development doesn't happen in isolation. You need other things to
sustain life in a community, and these other things never
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   This is precisely the widespread fear about New York City: that
its latest economic boom is so dependent on Wall Street, if the
stock market collapses, the city will, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs doesn't accept this line entirely. ``Compared with any
other city, New York is amazingly diversified,'' she said. But she
too considers it more vulnerable than it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem, not only in New York but throughout
America,'' she noted, ``is there is so little manufacturing. A lot
of manufacturing has been lost for good reasons: the products have
become so obsolete or it's become more economical to produce
somewhere else. But why is this the case? It comes down to
innovation. The design and improvement of computers _ we've become
very good at that. But manufacturing computers is not done at all
in America. Taiwan can outdo America. It's not just low wages _
wages have been rising in Taiwan. It has to do with our methods of
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York used to take the lead in solving common problems _
problems of health, transportation, social problems. It hasn't been
so good at this lately. It hasn't been in the forefront of the
waste-and-garbage problem and how you recycle.''
</P>
<P>
   New York has also been trapped in the rut of subsidizing what
Jacobs calls ``vicious circles.'' For example, rent controls have
dampened incentives to build new housing. But if controls were
lifted, housing might not be stimulated anyway, unless other things
changed at the same time _ for instance, lower construction costs,
which are part of the reason for controls to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like someone who's a drug addict because his life is
miserable,'' she said. ``You can't take care of one without the
other. This sort of dynamic can reach a point of no return, where
the vicious circle gets so gridlocked, you can't do anything about
it.'' What happens then? She shrugged and replied, ``You die.''
</P>
<P>
   There are ways out of the circle. She points to the conversion
of moribund factory buildings to residential lofts, and how that
revitalized lower Manhattan. She traces the origins of the
canned-fruit business in early-20th-century San Francisco and how
it spawned a rich complex of enterprises _ in agriculture,
glassware, tin, and ironworks _ that kept the city from
deteriorating after the collapse of the Gold Rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that dynamic systems can stay alive is constant
self-renewal,'' she said. ``That goes for a person, a city, a
species, a biomass, whatever.'' By that measure, Jane Jacobs should
be around for quite a while longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
