<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4716 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-12 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR HAPLESS HITS BOTTOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Opening Day for the Red Sox was Closing Day for public
confidence in the Cellucci administration. Far from the madding
crowd at Fenway, the governor skulked in Washington, proffering his
figurative knuckles for a stern rap-rap-rap from the federal
officials who have shoveled billions in US taxpayer cash into the
bottomless pit known as the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   Catching the spear for the most incompetent state administration
in living memory is James Kerasiotes, the outgoing Turnpike czar
whose management, competence, and veracity have been called into
question by a lengthening train of auditors, accountants,
administrators, and accusers. Cellucci can't fire himself; more's
the pity. The hapless successor to William Weld, elected by a
margin of 3 percent two years ago on promising ``the Big Dig is on
time and on budget,'' is drowning in bad news, red ink, redder
faces, and bleak prospects for any immediate turnaround in his
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Having bragged to The Wall Street Journal months ago that
Cellucci was afraid to fire him, Kerasiotes ran out of excuses and
friends in high places at just about the same time. Having insulted
the governor's top two aides as ``a reptile'' and ``a moron'' in
that same interview, Jimmy the K saw his fate debated Tuesday in
Cellucci's inner sanctum by the fraidy cat, the reptile, and the
moron. Did anybody say what goes around comes around?
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, like a tenderfoot out on a wilderness trek who is
about to lose his guide, looks skyward for help. If I fire Jim, he
murmurs, who do I get to take the job? What if Kerasiotes decides
to get even with me by spilling more beans? How much more grief can
I take? With his lieutenant governor hung up between dubious
helicopter flights to family meals and smarting aides drafted to
baby-sitting duties, with a string of appointees crashing and
burning in the wake of various behavioral lapses, with a business
community concluding he is not a go-through guy, and with a largely
hostile media crowd convinced he is a dope, Cellucci has to face
the music.
</P>
<P>
   His tendencies over the three years he has been running the shop
betray a simple pattern: provoke a fight, blame the other guy,
throw large dollops of tax-cut promises, capital punishment vows,
and other raw meat items at the media, and pray that economic boom
times will let everything blow over.
</P>
<P>
   He still blames Mike Dukakis for anything that went wrong. He
blames the Legislature for ``lunacy'' when they point out, ahem,
er, Guv, your tax cut won't fly with a $2 billion overrun. He
blamed the Massachusetts congressional delegation, all Democrats,
for failing to loot the federal treasury of even more reimbursement
money than has already been filched.
</P>
<P>
   But all those mythical fall guys evaporated as the Big Dig
hemorrhaged cash. Every time a shovel dipped further into the muck,
more problems appeared. At $1.7 billion per mile, it is the
priciest roadway on the planet. The moon could be paved over for
what this will cost.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci's political aspirations fed off Big Dig money.
Contractors and insurers and all manner of pie-slicers and
pork-choppers forked over dump truck loads of campaign
contributions. Unions that could be suborned by shadowy promises
broke ranks with Democratic rival Scott Harshbarger. Hundreds of
new pickup trucks, thousands of new mortgages, countless fancy
meals and trips to the Cape and beyond, were financed by Big Dig
cash flow. Dozens of cops make more than $100,000 a year, thanks to
Big Dig details.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't we hear anything about the lies and deceit of the
overruns? ``Because everybody was getting their money,'' explained
a veteran criminal investigator appraising the debacle. ``No one
spoke up because the money kept coming. It's when the money stops
that stuff starts to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about this simple question: How come barely one person in
a thousand knows the name of the big cheeses involved in the Big
Dig? Because they never raised a ruckus. Why no ruckus? They got
just about everything they wanted from Mr. Big. Kerasiotes
extracted signed promises from staff not to reveal financial
secrets. He bullied underlings. He threatened outsiders with
ostracism or political retribution from the Cellucci machine.
</P>
<P>
   The whole scheme was stitched together with cash _ most of it
from Washington, until the federal government got wind of the
debacle. Now the state will be penalized. The Massachusetts
taxpayer will have to dig deeper. Cellucci's income tax cut
referendum on the November ballot is a huge hoax. Bridge and
highway projects around the state will expire, throttled in the
cradle, because the Big Dig cannot be left uncompleted.
</P>
<P>
   But Uncle Sam holds the purse strings now. Kerasiotes's chief of
staff mocked the feds' investigation as ``silly season.'' But who's
laughing now? The congressmen Cellucci had his henchmen denounce
are all that stands between the Massachusetts taxpayers and a
vengeful federal establishment. Grandstanding at home by promising
a big income tax cut while pleading poverty in D.C. does not cut
it. Somebody has to explain that simple fact to Cellucci. The
newspapers tried. The legislative chiefs tried. The Massachusetts
Taxpayers Foundation tried. But he's the governor who doesn't get
it. Which is why Kerasiotes will have to get it. Because governors,
no matter how incompetent, can't fire themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
