<HEADLINE>
POLITICIAN'S BEST FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their feelings are easily hurt and their self-esteem is shaky.
When an opponent mentions voting records, they holler ``Negative
campaigning!'' If rivals cast doubt on their abilities, they
scream, ``Personal attack!'' Today's candidates whine and whimper
like nap-deprived children. Instead of complaining, they should
each get a dog.
</P>
<P>
   One small terrier, Fala, figured in the most satisfying response
to criticism in the history of presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, running for a fourth term, Franklin Delano Roosevelt
looked every one of his 62 years. His opponent, Thomas E. Dewey, a
Republican racket-buster before becoming governor of New York, was
42. He charged that FDR's administration had become ``old and tired
and quarrelsome in office.'' Dewey did not oppose New Deal
programs, which caused Republicans to grouse about ``me-tooism,''
but which also made him a formidable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt had more to worry about than Dewey. In July, a month
after the successful Allied invasion of Normandy, he traveled to
Hawaii to meet with Admiral Chester W. Nimitz and General Douglas
MacArthur about the conduct of World War II, then toured Pacific
military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Roosevelt Republicans in Congress had targeted his wife,
Eleanor, and his sons, who were serving in the military. Then,
Representative Harold Knutson of Michigan charged that a Navy ship
had traveled 1,000 miles to fetch Fala, forgotten in Alaska. The
House majority leader, John W. McCormack of Massachusetts, called
the Navy to determine the facts, and said, ``The dog was never
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   In speeches at Bremerton, Wash., and San Diego, FDR looked as
old and tired as Dewey had alleged. As the war and homefront
rationing dragged on, he abandoned his nonpolitical strategy and
spoke on Sept. 23 to a friendly audience, the Teamsters Union, and
to voters via radio. The familiar grin reappeared as he warned that
in election years, Republicans ``suddenly discover that they really
love labor . . . Can the Old Guard pass itself as the New Deal? I
think not.''
</P>
<P>
   With the hotel audience and the nation securely in his grip, his
baritone slowed into mock mournfulness. ``These Republican leaders
have not been content with attacks on me or my wife or my sons. No,
not content with that, they now include my little dog Fala,'' FDR
said, igniting laughter and allowing him to slow down even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, of course, I don't resent attacks, and my family doesn't
resent attacks, but Fala does resent them,'' the president said, to
more laughter. ``You know, Fala is Scotch, and being a Scottie, as
soon as he learned that the Republican fiction writers, in Congress
and out, had concocted a story that I had left him behind on the
Aleutian Islands and had sent a destroyer back to find him _ at a
cost to the taxpayers of two or three or eight or twenty million
dollars _ his Scotch soul was furious. He has not been the same dog
since.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooting and hollering, banging the tables, the Teamsters wanted
more, as did millions at home. FDR complied, with patrician
earnestness: ``I am accustomed to hearing malicious falsehoods
about myself, such as the old worm-eaten chestnut that I have
represented myself as indispensable. But I think I have a right to
resent, to object to libelous statements about my dog!''
</P>
<P>
   In response to what a Reader's Digest feature called ``the
perfect squelch,'' Dewey said, ``Mr. Roosevelt designed that speech
to make me angry, and he has. The result is that I will now
campaign all the harder.'' Yeah, right. Roosevelt won 432 electoral
votes. Dewey won 99.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs do not guarantee presidential serenity. Richard Nixon, who
owned Checkers, complained about a left-wing conspiracy. The wife
of Bill Clinton, who has Buddy, alleged a right-wing conspiracy.
But a fragile ego can benefit from canine companionship, especially
if it's a dog like Fala, who was, at one crucial moment in 1944,
one man's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
