<SLUG> BC-RELIGIION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS SONGWRITER EXPLAINS HIS JOURNEY TO ISLAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON AND DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a young boy named Steven Demetre Georgiou, his religious
identity was muddled _ his father was Greek Orthodox from Cyprus,
his mother a Baptist from Sweden, and his teachers were nuns at a
Catholic school in London.
</P>
<P>
   As a young pop singer named Cat Stevens, he flirted with
Buddhism, astrology, and even Pythagorean numerology on what he now
describes as a quest for truth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as an adult who has taken the name Yusuf Islam, he is a
devout Muslim who is trying to use his fame to spread the word of
his adopted religion.
</P>
<P>
   The songwriter has only recently begun to reenter the world of
music _ he won't play the guitar but he has resumed singing and
songwriting _ and he is now on a speaking tour in the United States
to promote two albums and to explain, in his words, ``why this rock
star who seemed to have everything going for him would hang up his
guitar and say goodbye to that kind of world.''
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance at Harvard University this week, Islam said
becoming a Muslim at age 28 came after years on a spiritual quest
triggered by a harrowing bout with tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wrote the song `Peace Train,' where was the peace train
going? I didn't know, but I felt I was on it, on this kind of holy
journey to the station of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his introduction to Islam came when his brother, knowing
he was on a spiritual quest, gave him a copy of the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found my place and my identity,'' Islam said, adding that
every question he had was answered in the Koran, the sacred book of
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   But he complained that since his conversion, his words about
Islam have been ignored or sensationalized in the media. He was
particularly critical of news coverage of his remarks a decade ago
about author Salman Rushdie, although he did not recant from or
apologize for his position that Islamic law would allow capital
punishment for what Islam described as the author's unrepentant
blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Islam complained that the very question posed to him
about Rushdie was ``cunning,'' an effort to hurt his image.
</P>
<P>
   Islam sold his guitars when he became a Muslim, and says he is
not willing to play the guitar any longer because the music might
be offensive to some orthodox Muslims. But he said he has resumed
singing, starting in 1995, recording a few new songs, reissuing old
songs, and recording spoken-word albums about Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Islam now has two new albums on the market, ``The Very Best of
Cat Stevens,'' a greatest hits album featuring a previously
unreleased recording, and ``A is for Allah,'' a children's album
about Islam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Question of the Week
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is mortal sin?
</P>
<P>
   Mortal sin is the most serious level of sin in Christianity and
is a term generally applied to violent actions such as murder and
to extreme heretical actions such as the denial of God, also called
apostasy.
</P>
<P>
   Most Christian traditions hold that people who commit mortal
sins are not eligible for salvation unless they are absolved of
their sins by a clergyman. Catholics consider abortion, as the
taking of a human life, to be a mortal sin.
</P>
<P>
   Although mortal sin is one of the oldest concepts in
Christianity, theologians today are reshaping the language they use
to talk about mortal sin and the importance of mortal sin in
society. The theologians talk of punishment for mortal sin not as
hell, but as life without God.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of mortal sin is understood not so much in terms of
an action we do, but in terms of breaking our relationship with
God,'' said the Rev. Robert M. Friday of the Catholic University of
America. Contemporary theologians _ unlike their medieval
predecessors _ also increasingly view mortal sin as rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time, particularly from the 15th to 17th
centuries, when the assumption was that people were sinning
frequently, and in some old manuals almost anything that had to do
with sexuality was considered a grave matter, so that an adolescent
boy daydreaming was almost as malicious as the dreadful violent
rape,'' said Boston College theologian Thomas Groome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contemporary Catholic theology would say that an ordinary,
everyday struggling human being never sins mortally. A mortal sin
is not the incidental haphazard lapse. Very few ordinary struggling
people commit mortal sins.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holiday of the Week
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April 12 is Ramnavami, a Hindu holiday honoring the birth of
Rama. Rama is a popular Hindu deity, thought to be one of the two
most important incarnations of Vishnu, the god who preserves the
cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   Rama is revered as a paragon of moral virtue _ at a time of
polygamy, he only had one wife and was loyal to her. And he was
said to be an accomplished warrior _ he was a king and military
leader who vanquished demonic opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rama has become very important in the modern Hindu
imagination,'' said Arvind Sharma, a professor of comparative
religion at McGill University. ``He is very upright and martial,
and he symbolizes the persistence of the Hindu hope for some kind
of restoration of his power.''
</P>
<P>
   The central feature of celebrations of Ramnavami is the ritual
recitation of the Ramayana, which is an epic narrative describing
Rama's life. The Hindi version is embellished with homilies and
narratives, and accomplished speakers can expound on the text for
hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
