<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-NATSIOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOSS'S WAYS SEEN AS BANE, BENEFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When he takes control of the largest public works
project in the nation, Andrew S. Natsios will come with a fierce
belief in mininalist government and a stubborn streak that often
tries even his closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   At the State House, where Natsios has served as Governor Paul
Cellucci's chief fiscal operative for the last year, visitors to
his office seeking state assistance are routinely ushered to a
conference table dominated by a sign engraved with a single word:
``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say Natsios's renowned tight-fisted ways, and his
experience going nose to nose with local officials demanding more
state aid, make him ideally suited to impose fiscal order on the
financially troubled Big Dig project.
</P>
<P>
   They also say his record as manager of international famine
relief programs under President George Bush, and the respect he
commands as one of the brightest officials in the Cellucci
administraion, are certain to help him restore federal confidence
in the administration's management ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy is a superb choice to head the Big Dig project,'' said
Paul Guzzi, president of the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce.
``He's had extensive state financial experience, and he's had
extensive federal management experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But other business leaders privately worry about Natsios's
tendency to adopt principled stands without considering their
practicality _ a trait some say led to the downfall of outgoing Big
Dig manager James J. Kerasiotes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Natsios, 50, insisted that Cellucci veto
$94 million in additional state aid for local education _ only to
suffer a unanimous override in which Cellucci was abandoned by
every Republican in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios freely admits to a certain hard-headedness that has
characterized his career since he served as a gadfly in the state
Legislature. He was a Republican representative from Holliston in
the 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a streak in me that's stubborn and absolutely
hard-headed,'' he said in a Globe interviewTuesday, adding that in
a job as demanding as running the Big Dig, stubbornness ``is almost
a prerequisite.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, business leaders and elected officials alike
are questioning whether Natsios has the ability to match
Kerasiotes's record of completing more than half of the technically
complex project safely and without significant disruptions of
downtown traffic or commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to all the revelations of Big Dig cost overruns, I would
have given Kerasiotes about the highest marks of anybody in the
administration,'' Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham said.
</P>
<P>
   But Natsios said he believes that, with most of the engineering
work done, the principle challenges in managing the Big Dig are
restoring public confidence in Cellucci administration officials
and controlling costs.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said his first order of business on taking the helm of
the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority and the Central Artery/Tunnel
project Wednesday will be to establish ``a culture of openness'' to
encourage staffers to keep him apprised of any bad news.
</P>
<P>
   In a list of 16 management priorities he will distribute to Big
Dig staff, Natsios says: ``I will not shoot the messenger of bad
news. Keep me informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said it may take a couple of months before a review of
the Big Dig by the accounting firm of Deloitte &AMP; Touche will allow
him to inform federal officials and the public about the full
extent of the Big Dig cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he's confident that the $2 billion estimate cited
by federal auditors is the last word on the subject, Natsios simply
said, ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1449EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
