<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4724 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-12 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRO-HUNGARIAN CUISINE COMES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cab driver can't locate Danube, one of the most talked-about
restaurants in New York City, on a dimly lit block of Hudson Street
in Tribeca, so we tell him to pull over and we get out. It's half a
block back, the entrance so understated that I have to peer at the
little sign on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it's like falling into a plush, decorated egg. Gorgeous
blue and yellow tiles cover the walls; heavy draperies in a burnt
orange with delicate cream undercurtains cover the windows. Pretty
chairs are deep enough to sink into; table linens are so starched
they crackle as I brush past; waltz music wafts in the air. At 6:30
p.m., the room is full of well-dressed, abundantly jeweled diners
and waiters stiffly at attendance.
</P>
<P>
   In the same measured beat that a waltz is played, the
Austro-Hungarian empire has swirled back onto the stage. Danube is
the newest restaurant of David Bouley, whose contemporary
interpretations of French cuisine ruled the New York and US food
worlds for almost a decade, until he closed shop in 1996. Now, in a
land awash in Mediterranean and French-influenced cuisine, he's
betting that we've all missed those pots of sour cream and
dumplings, the pickled vegetables and apple strudel. For that style
of cooking _ whether in Austrian, Hungarian, or German restaurants
_ flourished in an earlier America and still does in parts of the
Midwest. It harks back to a time when going out to dinner meant
either a steakhouse or a formal restaurant where the menu ran to
Wiener schnitzel and oodles of schlag over apple strudel. The heavy
sauces, the sour cream, the goulash sound exotic now. And none too
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Not to fear, however, that Bouley and his chef, Mario Lohninger,
will smother the eater in sour cream. Danube's interpretation leans
resolutely toward the delicate. From the first offering _ an
amuse-gueule that is tiny tastes of a sardine on a wisp of a potato
chip, a thimbleful of squash soup, a postage stamp-size cut of mahi
on red cabbage, a cocktail duck sausage _ the dishes tiptoe around
the theme. The classic Austro-Hungarian ingredients are sprinkled
up and down the appetizers and entrees but with utmost discretion.
And quark, which sounds Mr. Spock-y but is actually a type of soft
farmer's cheese, seems to be Bouley's answer to sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   Potatoes abound, but what potatoes. A little potato dumpling is
stuffed with salty caviar, the two tastes heavenly together. Potato
ravioli, really an ethereal gnocchi, wrap around a heady veal
filling. Austrian potato salads with several entrees only vaguely
resemble the German potato salad I grew up with. Thin shavings of
potatoes in a sprightly vinegary dressing glisten on the tongue _
it's as though the lowly potato had just stepped out of
Cinderella's pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Lest all this sound too modern and light, Bouley pours richness
into plenty of his dishes. One amazingly long-winded appetizer _
Carinthia ``Schlutzkrapfen'' high-altitude Austrian cheese ravioli
with harvest corn and smoked Canadian chanterelles _ is
heart-stopping in its intensity, the cheese lingering at the back
of the palate as the heady mushrooms hit the front of the tongue.
And the Wiener schnitzel, though light, tasted pretty much like
schnitzel.
</P>
<P>
   Desserts pull out all the stops _ while not heavy, they
certainly aren't spa. A vanilla savarin shimmers on the plate and
the tongue; mousse-like chestnut cake melts into one's
consciousness at the same moment as the surprise of licorice ice
cream. Chocolate sacher is definitely an up-to-date version,
intense but svelte, and the apple strudel has a flaky, buttery
crust.
</P>
<P>
   Fiddling with this cuisine doesn't do disservice to history. The
Austro-Hungarian empire was never homogeneous in cuisine. German
sausage spilled over into Austrian dumplings and became seasoned by
the Hungarian fondness for paprika over several centuries, until
the 19th-century nationalism pulled the empire apart.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no Danubes in Boston _ at least not yet _
there are a few chefs who evoke some of the same romance. The
grande dame of this cuisine here is Cafe Budapest, a place whose
history and that of its owners has kept it unchanged in almost four
decades. Here the courtly maitre d's seem frozen to their positions
as they preside over sparsely populated dining rooms. When I met a
friend at the bar before dinner recently, our talk was accompanied
by a violinist and a pianist playing for us alone, as the bartender
audibly stood by sighing. The food, served quickly and very
solemnly by tuxedo-clad waiters, was from an earlier era, too. The
breading of the Wiener schnitzel predominated; a pork chop
smothered in a gulyas of onions was tough; a dobos torte was sweet
but a little dry. The Sleeping Beauty feel of the place reminded
one that even cuisine must change to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rosen of Salts in Cambridge takes another tack in his
interpretations of Eastern and Middle European dishes, drawing on
strains of family ancestry _ his family's Russian and Romanian
roots and his wife Lisa's Polish ones. As with Bouley, the flavors,
the memories of grandmothers' dishes, the romance illuminate the
food, never overwhelming or dating the cuisine. A delicious red
lentil soup is spiked liberally with smoked paprika and bears a few
feathery white lentil-and-garlic dumplings, a wonderful contrast to
the soup. Venison gets an almost medieval tinge from its
accompaniment of black currant jam; poppy-seed spaetzle soaks up
the meat juices.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen says he's always looking for a slightly lighter tone to
the food, while respecting the tradition. For summer, he plans a
very thinly rolled-out pierogi dough stuffed with sweet corn to
serve over a lobster ragout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get in the scene where it's too far out,''
says Rosen, who enjoys reading food history for inspiration. ``I
want it to have a more solid footing. I'm looking for a little bit
of refinement,'' without making unrecognizable combinations.
</P>
<P>
   So the Austro-Hungarian empire waltzes into a new century,
wearing a lighter, more elegant gown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
