<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS TO GIVE INSTRUCTIONS ON HANDOVER OF CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to end the series of delays that have kept Elian Gonzalez
from his father, Justice Department officials said they would send
instructions Wednesday to the boy's Miami relatives telling them
how to hand over Elian to the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides in the international custody battle agreed Tuesday
night to reunite father and son in Washington Wednesday. But the
Miami relatives who have cared for Elian for four months canceled
the meeting late Tuesday after a flurry of last-minute
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still encouraging the meeting, but we will be going
through with the letter,'' said Carole Florman, a Justice
Department spokeswoman. ``It's a transfer order. It gives them
instructions.''
</P>
<P>
   Florman said the letter with the instructions would likely be
sent by facsimile to lawyers representing the Miami relatives. She
refused to give details of the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, had
agreed to fly with the boy to Washington to meet Wednesday with
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the father who came from Cuba last week to
claim his son. But shortly before midnight, the great-uncle told
journalists and anti-Castro protesters outside his Miami home that
Elian did not want to go through with the meeting. Federal
officials were never notified, said Maria Cardona, a spokeswoman
for the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had not heard officially at that point that the meeting was
completely off,'' Cardona said. ``At that point, we were involved
in discussions about the meeting. We are still focusing on our
efforts to try and get the families to meet and talk. If they do
that, we believe it will be possible for this to be quickly and
peacefully resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, representatives from the Cuban American National
Foundation said Wednesday morning that they were trying to broker a
meeting in Washington. The talks might take place at the Vatican
mission because both sides would feel comfortable meeting under the
auspices of the Catholic Church, said Jorge Mas Santos, an official
with the group, which opposes Cuban President Fidel Castro's
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have done is to support the family's efforts to make
this meeting happen,'' Santos said at a Washington news conference.
``It's important that there are no conditions placed with the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department confirmed Wednesday that the Vatican's
diplomatic mission in Washington was being discussed as a possible
meeting place.
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton's support, Attorney General Janet Reno
has said that the government would reunite Elian with his father
before the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the father, has said he does not want to
meet with the Miami relatives unless they give him his son. But
Elian's great-uncle has refused to turn over the boy without first
determining whether the father is acting under durress from Castro.
Juan Miguel Gonzalez said last week that Castro had been like a
``brother'' to him through this ordeal. He, his current wife and
their 6-month-old son are staying in a Cuban diplomat's home in the
Washington suburb of Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The father left the residence Wednesday morning to meet with his
lawyer, Gregory Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was given temporary residency status and placed in the
care of his great-uncle after fishermen discovered him floating in
an inner-tube off the Florida coast on Nov. 25. The boy was one of
three survivors of a capsized refugee boat. His mother, who was
divorced from the boy's father, and 10 other Cubans drowned.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like thousands of Cuban Americans who oppose Castro's
government, Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, is reluctant to
see the boy returned to Cuba. He is asking the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta to compel the INS to grant the boy an
asylum hearing. The court is scheduled to hear oral arguments the
week of May 8.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 Cuban Americans who want Elian to remain in this
country have maintained a round-the-clock watch at the Miami home,
waving Cuban flags and staging candelight vigils. They have
practiced locking arms in a human chain to prevent federal
officials from forcibly removing Elian. Signs outside the home read
``Loco Castro'' and ``Let Elian Stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, as a heavy downpour drenched Miami streets,
Lazaro Gonzalez took Elian to Mercy Hospital, where the two met
with the boy's cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez. She had been one of
Elian's primary caretakers but was hospitalized over the weekend
for exhaustion. Afterward, Elian and his great-uncle went to the
Miami Beach home of Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, who has acted as a
mediator in the custody dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez suggested Tuesday that O'Laughlin's home be used
as a neutral site for a family meeting. The nun hosted a meeting in
late January between Elian and his Cuban grandmothers, who had
flown to the United States in an unsuccessful attempt to bring the
boy back to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The great-uncle has said he would not hand Elian back to his
father unless he gets a guarantee that Juan Miguel Gonzalez would
not try to return to Cuba with his son before the Atlanta court
reaches a decision. But Elian's father has not promised to stay in
the country, although federal officials have said he would likely
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez said last week that if he stays through the
appeals process, he would like to be accompanied by an entourage of
Elian's teachers, classmates and close relatives, as well as
doctors and a high-ranking official. He pleaded last week with the
State Department to grant visas to such a delegation, which had
been assembled by Castro. The State Department granted six visas to
the group last week and said it is considering 21 others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
