<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FUNDS-ROLLERCOASTER-A     04-12 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-ROLLERCOASTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 INVESTORS RUE TECH'S TUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even the staunchest believers in technology stocks have had
their faith tested in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   For mutual fund investors, it's meant hanging on while
tech-heavy portfolios were pummeled _ and seeing that a euphoric
ride up can be grim on the way back down.
</P>
<P>
   Though last week was dramatic, with two violent days for the
Nasdaq Composite index, technology stocks have in fact been under
pressure since March 10, their recent high point. They've tumbled
nearly 12 percent since then, more than halving their gains since
the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very active quarter because the changes in the
market have been so drastic,'' said Gary Craven, manager of
Evergreen's successful Small Company Growth fund, who has been
standing up to the pressure admirably.
</P>
<P>
   Craven's $1.5 billion fund gained 18 percent in first-quarter
2000, while his peers tracked by Lipper Inc. in the
mid-capitalization growth group were up 17 percent, on average.
Year-to-date through Thursday, he was still up 13.6 percent,
outperforming the average 11.9 percent for the group.
</P>
<P>
   While tech stocks and biotechnology were the only place to be at
the end of 1999 and early this year, by late February, Craven
explained, those sectors had moved ``too far, too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the slump in the second half of March, aggressive
growth fund investors had little to complain about in the first
quarter. Mid-cap growth funds surged 17 percent, according to
Lipper; small-cap growth funds charged ahead 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret which sectors fared best. Science and technology
funds jumped nearly 18 percent in the quarter, while investors in
health and biotechnology funds enjoyed an 18.2 percent rise.
Telecommunications funds gained 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last week's gyrations, the small and the tech-oriented
funds have easily outpaced large stock funds this year. Craven
thinks that's where the best bets still lie as he looks ahead
through year-end. ``It's still the most attractive part of the
domestic market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's picky. He trimmed back his biotech holdings after
prices soared; some are again attractive, he suggests. He likes
technology, but avoids frivolous Internet plays. He's interested in
wireless companies and Web infrastructure. Those with no plans for
profitability need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-coms, both B2C and B2B, are really getting to the
point where they have to deliver,'' Craven said, ``and make it
clear how they're going to grow and ultimately make money.''
</P>
<P>
   The awakening to the risks of the market's Internet darlings
could push gains in other parts of the market, experts contend.
Large companies are having to become more serious about doing
business online, and those in the lagging ``value'' category, such
as construction, steel, and financial services, are trying to
remake themselves to compete with start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Goodman, chief economist at Putnam Investments in Boston,
calls this phenomenon the rise of the new old-economy companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the next six months, a new theme is going to develop on
Wall Street,'' Goodman predicted. The cyclical companies, he said,
are ``taking on growth-like characteristics and therefore should be
accorded growth valuations.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a big shift in thinking. Value funds have posted
lackluster returns this year, not exceeding 5.8 percent on average.
Not since a brief period last April has value outpaced growth as a
category.
</P>
<P>
   One week is hardly enough to build a crystal ball around. But
last week, as tech funds were slumping 3.7 percent, large-cap value
funds rose 1.7 percent. Small- and mid-cap value funds gained more
than a percent each, as well.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, value funds are ahead of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index _ the large-cap growth benchmark _ which gained 0.9 percent
last week and is up a modest 2.3 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rosenbaum, research director at Lipper, called the recent
value gains ``further indication of a change of leadership in the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   But he warns against having too many eggs in any basket. ``This
market has been giving investors a wake-up call since March,'' he
said. ``Please examine your assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   The best idea, of course, is to be exposed to all sectors.
Putnam's Goodman does not suggest shifting out of growth funds, but
adding new money to value funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tech area is alive and well,'' he said, and the bull
market is still chugging along. The trouble, he said, is that some
people have lost track of the level of risk they've taken on.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it's because their aggressive funds have reaped such
strong returns that they now make up a larger part of their
portfolio than was intended. Others, Goodman said, ``think they can
just get on a computer and buy stocks they know nothing about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund companies clearly believe there will be a continuing
appetite for technology-focused funds. Some are jumping on the
bandwagon late, having missed last year's dot-com frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer Mutual Funds of Boston just kicked off a Science and
Technology fund, citing a ``dynamic and rewarding investment
sector.'' Boston-based MFS Funds is rolling out a technology fund
this month, despite its stance that profitless Internet stocks
don't meet its investment standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are big technology investors,'' MFS spokesman John Reilly
said. ``We also pay close attention to valuations. We're going to
use the same research discipline we use in everything we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly admits the timing could be better: ``Sometimes the knees
are a little weak after a sell-off,'' he said. ``We think it's
still an area of great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not only on US soil that small growth funds have fared best
so far in 2000. International small-cap funds climbed 13.1 percent
in the first quarter. Other strong areas included China region
funds, which surged 14.8 percent _ making it the strongest gaining
foreign sector of the past 12 months. Canadian funds followed, up
10.9 percent. European funds notched a 5.9 percent return.
</P>
<P>
   Japan funds slumped 3 percent in the quarter, after their vast
rise of last year. Latin American funds rose 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, everybody's expecting volatile markets in the
months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Said Craven, ``We've had it pretty easy for the past year.''
Look for a strong year, he said, but ``the second quarter should
prove to be challenging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
