<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTLEY-FOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JOBS, LIKE INVESTING, REQUIRES RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The cornerstone of career and financial success
might well be a very old and very lame joke: How do you eat an
elephant? One bite at a time.
</P>
<P>
   When you tackle overwhelming projects, you break them into a
series of smaller tasks, then gobble them up one at a time. If you
want to be the chief executive of a corporation, you have to
navigate each step on the corporate ladder. Smart workers know all
that. But even smart workers can feel overwhelmed by the whole idea
of personal finance, especially investing in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding personal finance is a crucial and often overlooked
career skill. Using your money wisely can give you enough of a
financial cushion to quit an unsatisfactory job, cut back to
part-time work or start your own business. Those things are scary
or downright impossible for people living from paycheck to
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite Web sites is the Motley Fool (www.fool.com),
because it approaches personal finance the same way workers should
approach their jobs. Here are a few Foolish lessons, for your money
and your life:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't automatically assume something is too complicated for
you.
</P>
<P>
   The Motley Fool is the best site I've seen for explaining what
you need to know about investing in stocks and how you can
determine whether any particular stock would be a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial planners tell clients that the stock market is so
complicated that individual investors stand a good chance of losing
their money. Depending on the planner and the investor, that can
either be good advice or incredibly self-serving advice. This site
does a good job of explaining the basics and getting rid of the
intimidation, giving you a better opportunity to decide whether you
have the smarts and temperament to invest on your own.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happens with careers, particularly in high-tech.
People get so intimidated by all the jargon or frustrated by a
couple of bad experiences that they automatically reject high-tech
as a career field. If they had better teachers or more patience,
they might have found that the field wasn't so intimidating after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly a lot of people won't be suited for high-tech careers
_ or investing in individual stocks. But try to struggle past the
jargon in both cases; the potential rewards could be well worth it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Separate the substance from the hot air.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets are filled with breathless pundits who talk
about what stocks will do in a week or a month or a minute, but
that's closer to legalized gambling than investing. The Motley Fool
talks about investing in good companies for the long term and
generally ignoring short-term comments from analysts. When you do
that, the stock market isn't so risky after all.
</P>
<P>
   Careers can be like that, too. We get so caught up in day-to-day
politicking and overwhelming projects that we lose sight of what's
really important: long-term growth. At least once or twice a year,
set aside some time alone or with your family to discuss your goals
and how you're trying to accomplish them.
</P>
<P>
   Are there assignments your boss could be giving you that he's
not? Have you earned the right to those assignments? Have you been
adding people to your network? What makes you a more attractive
worker or job applicant now than you were a year ago?
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand the importance of framing.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund companies do this all the time. If they had a great
year, they compare their year's results with the S&AMP;P 500. If they
had a lousy year, maybe they'll do a five-year or 10-year
comparison instead. Or they'll compare their fund with similar
