<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4743 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SAYING-NO-HNS &LR;      04-12 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAYING-NO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOMETIMES AT WORK, THE BEST ANSWER IS PLAIN `NO' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's a two-letter word that can get you into
four-letter trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to just say no in the workplace. Bosses demand long
hours, clients push for constant service, colleagues beg for help.
And if you give in to all their requests, your spouse just might
head for the door.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you turn a no-win situation into a no-with-a-win
situation? Three of the keys are perspective, preparation and
prevention, says Patti Breitman, the coauthor of ``How to Say No
Without Feeling Guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, written with Connie Hatch, covers how to say no in all
sorts of situations without sounding like a naysayer, including a
large chapter on work. In a recent interview, Breitman said many
people don't re-examine their career goals often enough to make
sure they still fit in with the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us achieve success and don't realize it,'' she said.
``Most of us are too busy to even think about whether we're
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Breitman said bosses can be demanding, but many times workers
perform an extra task because they assume it's expected of them,
when really it isn't. ``Sometimes we're our own worst slave
drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when things are expected of you, often you can avoid
trouble. ``The best way to do it is to practice prevention,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a family outing planned for the last weekend of the
month, for example, let people at work know early that you won't be
available then. If you know you'll have a big project that will
leave your department scrambling, let others know in advance that
you won't be able to help with routine items during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more warning, the better,'' Breitman said. ``We recommend
honoring plans with yourself and your family as much as you honor
plans with everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that it's often best to tell people simply that you
have a commitment. If you explain precisely what you're doing, you
create the possibility of an argument if your priorities for
balancing work and life don't happen to suit theirs.
</P>
<P>
   What should you tell a boss who asks for an explanation?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long-standing family commitment I cannot break,''
Breitman said. ``I'm the kind of person who likes to keep my
commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   She said an answer like that is hard for bosses to argue with
because they know that you'll also keep your commitments to them in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   One key principal behind saying no without guilt is to have a
clear understanding of what is important in your life, not only to
you, but to your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and your partner should have an ongoing negotiation and
compromise,'' Breitman said. ``If you focus on what you're saying
yes to, it's easier to say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Breitman said she is not encouraging people to say no to the
boss all the time, but just to be clear on what role work plays in
their lives. Some people who are trying for a promotion or working
for an Internet start-up might have to make major personal
sacrifices, and they need to make sure their family members
understand what long-term benefits could occur because of those
sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   When a boss insists that you do something you don't want to do,
Breitman suggests you make sure you understand the boss's real
goal. Maybe you're told that you have to work on Saturday, for
example, but the real goal is to make sure you have a report
finished by 9 a.m. Monday. By working Friday night or early Monday,
you might meet the boss' real goal without sacrificing the
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes saying you have a policy can help, such as if your
family has a policy of having dinner together. ``It sounds more
authoritative,'' Breitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often not the boss who is pressuring you, but your
colleagues,'' she added. ``You never say, `That's not my job,'
because then you're not perceived as a team player.''
</P>
<P>
   Breitman suggests three steps when faced with a request you
don't want to fulfill:
</P>
<P>
   _ Express your desire to be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly make it clear that you can't perform the task
requested.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suggest a person or resource that might help.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes colleagues make other requests, such as asking for
charity sponsors or donations for a party. Breitman said it's often
best to pick a couple of charities worthy of your donations; by
saying yes to those charities, it will be easier to say no to the
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know in your heart that you give generously to other
causes, you won't feel guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't contribute money for office parties because you
have other financial priorities, the author suggests offering your
services in some other way, such as picking up the cake or shopping
for a present. ``There can be all kinds of resentments if you don't
participate somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosses also have to say no, of course. For them, too,
preparation is key. If they can't give a good employee a raise
because the budget is tight, they should consider whether there are
other alternatives that would be attractive, such as better fringe
benefits, extra time off or allowing the worker to telecommute.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a good boss, you're probably giving praise whenever
it's due,'' Breitman said. ``When you do need to say no, it's in
the context of someone who's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
