<HEADER>
A4747 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ANTI-SEMITIC-HNS &LR;      04-12 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-SEMITIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ADL REPORTS RISE IN ATTACKS ON JEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VENISE WAGNER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The number of anti-Semitic incidents in
California increased last year while the number nationwide
declined, according to an annual audit released by the
Anti-Defamation League (ADL).
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine states and the District of Columbia reported 1,547
anti-Semitic incidents to the ADL in 1999, a 4 percent decrease
from 1998 when 1,611 were reported. Of those incidents, 868 were
harassment and 679 were acts of vandalism. Eighty-five percent of
the harassment cases were against individuals rather than Jewish
institutions and synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   In California, 275 incidents were reported in 1999, a 23 percent
increase from 1998 when 223 incidents were reported. California
ranked second among states with the highest number of anti-Semitic
incidents reported. New York led the nation with 352 incidents
reported. After California, came New Jersey with 226, Massachusetts
with 111 and Florida with 88.
</P>
<P>
   The ADL said the five states have the largest Jewish populations
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Bernstein, director of central Pacific region of the
ADL, said the high profile firebombings of synagogues in Sacramento
and the community center shooting in Los Angeles prompted copycat
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, those anti-Semitic acts heightened
awareness, making people more inclined to report incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are becoming tolerant of people different than
themselves,'' he said. ``We've made some significant inroads.
Still, we have a long way to go. At the same time . . . there are
those people who are hard-core haters, who are being pushed to the
extremes because they are no longer accepted in political (and
social) circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidents tend to be more bold, in-your-face attacks
rather than vandalism,'' Bernstein said. ``That's a disturbing
trend we have to keep an eye on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
