<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BO     04-12 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with FUNDS-ROLLERCOASTER, TAX-RUSH and
NEWBALANCE-JUMP, and a graphic with ADMISSIONS-CRUNCH are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ADMISSIONS-CRUNCH (Undated) _ This may be the most competitive
year ever to win admission to the college of your choice.
Demographics, the raging economy and rising SAT scores have
conspired against many members of the high school class of 2000 to
deny them entrance to their first college pick. By David Abel and
Doreen Iudica Vigue. 1500 words. GRAPHIC: 22 picas x 7 inches,
``Stiff competition.''
</P>
<P>
   BIGDIG-NATSIOS (Boston) _ As he moves to take control of the
largest public works project in the nation, Andrew S. Natsios
carries a reputation as an ascerbic penny-pincher with a fierce
belief in mininalist government and a zeal for confrontation. By
Michael Rezendes. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   ROTARY-POLIO (Marblehead, Mass.) _ Fifteen years after Rotary
International made polio eradication its No. 1 worldwide goal,
thousands of volunteers have helped reduce polio cases from 350,000
in 1988 to 5,000 today. Health and children's rights advocates say
it's a remarkable example of how ordinary citizens can help change
the world. By John Donnelly. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- Governor Hapless hits bottom. By David
Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- A famous songwriter explains his
journey to Islam. By Michael Paulson and Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ One small terrier, Fala, figured in the
most satisfying response to criticism in the history of
presidential politics. By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Derrick Jackson is writing on a local topic today; his
column will not move.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TAX-RUSH (Hingham, Mass.) _ Poor John Danehy. He's spending
about 80 hours a week inside his office. He's an income tax
preparer, one of thousands assisting half of the country's 126
million individual taxpayers. By Nathan Cobb. 1240 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Los Angeles) -- For an Easterner, riding the Red
Line (the only line) here is an out-of-subway experience. By Alex
Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-JACOBS (New York) _ Jane Jacobs, 84, has led protest
brigades, saved whole neighborhoods from the wrecking ball,
inspired generations of community activists, and changed the way
urban planners, scholars, and ordinary citizens think about cities.
By Fred Kaplan. 1670 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD (d) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-COLUMN (Undated) -- The Austro-Hungarian empire waltzes
into a new century, wearing a lighter, more elegant gown. By Alison
Arnett. 1070 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEWBALANCE-JUMP (Undated) _ Long known as a company for aging
baby boomers and folks with wide feet, New Balance Athletic Shoe
got a bonus last year when younger consumers snapped up New Balance
footgear in flashier colors. The result? A 41-percent sales jump.
By Chris Reidy. 1100 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS-ROLLERCOASTER (Undated) _ Even the staunchest believers in
technology stocks have had their faith tested in the past month.
For mutual fund investors, it's meant hanging on while tech-heavy
portfolios were pummeled. By Beth Healy. PHOTO 1170 words.
</P>
<P>
   ONJOBS-COLUMN (Undated) -- Job-changing, for some the fastest
and surest route to monetary and career advancement, is a critical
problem for employers confronted with low unemployment and, as a
result, a labor shortage. By Diane E. Lewis. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Don't bother looking at any
Internet stocks if you want to see how adverse the market has
become to dot-com empire building. Look at Staples, which is
preparing to launch its own Internet tracking stock and watching
its own shares get clobbered in the process. By Steven Syre and
Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER (Undated) _ Financial planner has good ideas, but
investor wants to take control of his own destiny. By Kenneth
Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DRAFT-HOVAN (Undated) _ Chris Hovan made certain of his
future employment with an eye-opening performance in the NFL
scouting combine in February, where the 6-foot-3-inch, 305-pounder
had several scouts doing double-takes. By Michael Vega. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BIRD (Indianapolis) _ Deep into his third season as head
coach of the Indiana Pacers, Larry Bird walks like a coach, talks
like a coach, thinks like a coach, and, most of all, agonizes like
a coach. By Bob Ryan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-MARA-RAINSBERGER (Boston) _ Former winner Lisa
Larsen-Weidenbach-Rainsberger has turned coach. By Barbara Huebner.
1330 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN (Boston) -- It's been seven years of laughs
for the Midwestern comedy troupe known as the Minnesota Twins. In
this, their eighth season, not much has changed. By Michael Holley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
