</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline to kum) _ Developments. Attorney General
Reno is expected to send letter setting out time and place for
transfer of Elian, who was taken to the home of a Catholic nun who
had brought his grandmothers to meet him last month. With reporting
by Rick Bragg in Miami and David Johnston in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-PROTESTS (Great Barrington, Mass.) _ From the Berkshires to
Cambridge, brushfires of civil disobedience flared in classrooms
across Massachusetts on Wednesday, as hundreds of high school
sophomores, and dozens of fourth- and eighth-graders, boycotted the
first of nine days of statewide standardized testing. In a sign of
rising student and parent discontent with politicians' reliance on
such tests, the protests followed _ and exceeded _ similar
rebellions in recent months in Illinois, Ohio, Louisiana, Wisconsin
and Florida. Though most of the students in Massachusetts reported
to class as scheduled, they chose to write essays about their
opposition to testing rather than answer the questions posed. Some
of the students face disciplinary actions ranging from suspension
to having a failing test grade incorporated into their third
quarter marks. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Denver) _ President Clinton talks about guns. By
Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL-HISPANICS (Los Angeles) _ Border Patrol agents may
not consider a driver's Hispanic appearance when deciding whether
to stop someone for suspected smuggling or illegal entry, a federal
appeals court has ruled. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-SCHOOLS (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles school district,
under fire for low student test scores and poor management, will be
broken into 11 mini-districts By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER-BEN&AMP;JERRYS (Undated) _ Unilever, which has been
shedding brands, makes two high-profile acquisitions in the United
States. As expected, it seems to have brought an end to the
skirmish for control of Ben &AMP; Jerry's by agreeing to pay $43.60 a
share, a total of $326 million. And, at the other end of the
calorie spectrum, it will buy SlimFast Foods for $2.3 billion,
adding the top producer of weight-loss products to its growing
nutrition business. In connection with the Ben &AMP; Jerry's purchase,
it will establish a formal structure for achieving socially
conscious goals. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   JDN-REALTY (Atlanta) _ JDN Realty, an Atlanta real estate
investment trust and a major Wal-Mart partner, has uncovered
``discrepancies in cost and other information'' in leases and sales
with both Wal-Mart and Lowe's, its other big tenant. The company's
stock is down 25 percent on Wednesday _ on top of a huge drop that
came when JDN acknowledged in February that two of its executives
had received millions in unreported salary in the last five years.
Management experts criticize the company's board, which is packed
with friends and associates of top officers, for failing to react
to the original bad news. The continuing travails make JDN an
excellent case study of the conflicts between the interests of
shareholders and executives at small companies. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TELECOMS (London) _ The auction for five licenses for
Britain's ``third generation'' mobile telephone systems is shaping
up as a windfall beyond the government's wildest dreams. The bids,
which have been rising day after day, now approach $25 billion,
twice the government's budget surplus. For the companies still
alive in the bidding, the prices are not out of line with
expectations of great demand when the dazzling new
telecommunications gear becomes available in two or three years. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2:30 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 108 points, while the Nasdaq index was down 154
points, as a prominent analyst reduced his revenue projections for
Motorola. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   AMD-EARINGS (San Francisco) _ Advanced Micro Devices will report
earnings after the stock market closes. The Forecast is for
earnings of 51 cents a share; the whisper numbers appear to be as
high as 63 cents. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-GROWTH (Washington) _ The world economy will expand 4.2
percent in 2000, the International Monetary Fund says in its latest
world economic outlook report. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-INTERNET (Beijing) _ A look at Sina.com, the most visited
Chinese Web site in the world and the first of the China Internet
companies to sell shares on Nasdaq. The initial public offering is
to be priced Wednesday. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   HKONG-AUSTRALIA-TELECOM (Hong Kong) _ Pacific Century CyberWorks
Ltd., which is acquiring Hong Kong's local telephone company, plans
to sell 40 percent of the mobile-phone business of Cable and
Wireless HKT to Telstra, the state-controlled phone company of
Australia, for $1.5 billion. Telstra will also invest $1.5 billion
in Pacific Century to create an alliance that aims to be Asia's
leading provider of Internet, data, wireless and broadband
communications services. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TELECOM (Tokyo) _ Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, Japan's
monolithic telecommunications company, announced further plans to
improve profitability and prepare for the explosion in demand for
Internet-related telecommunications services. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column. By Jeff
Madrick.
</P>
