<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-12 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANGLERS GEAR UP FOR THE START OF SALMON SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The opening of salmon season out the Golden Gate
is always a mystery. What anglers are praying for, however, is that
the mystery not be turned into doubt.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of both for this Saturday's opener, along with an
undercurrent of pent-up excitement from the latest opening day for
salmon in history.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery? Where are the fish? Right, now nobody knows, although
there are plenty of guesses, including the Deep Reef, the Weather
Buoy, B Buoy and the Farallon Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Doubt? Will bad weather tank the day?
</P>
<P>
   Excitement? According to the California Department of Fish and
Game, the ocean is full of salmon, and many are already big, 8 to
10 pounds, and will be growing a pound and an inch per month as the
season progresses _ with the ocean plugged with feed from roughly
the 50-fathom line on out another 10 miles.
</P>
<P>
   What is for sure is that thousands of fishermen on hundreds of
boats are planning to head out from Bay Area ports at dawn Saturday
in one of the few big-time annual traditions remaining in the
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks tremendous, with fish up and down the coast,'' said
Roger Thomas, captain of the Salty Lady from Sausalito. ``The Bay
Area boats will probably head to deeper water, where the amount of
feed is just fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is so excited just to go out there and fish for
those salmon,'' said Jacky Douglas of the boat Wacky Jacky out of
San Francisco. ``We can hardly wait to fire those engines up and
head out the Golden Gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Stone of Emeryville Sportfishing said his fleet of boats
has been booked for the opener for months and that many owners of
private boats have been trying to inveigle a few secrets from the
pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to know where we'll be fishing, but this year
the decision won't be made until Saturday morning when all the
boats are heading out,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   The only consensus is that the fish are not inshore and that the
Golden Gate Fleet will break up and search across the Gulf of the
Farallones, starting at the 50-fathom line, where whale watching
has been outstanding in the past two weeks because of such high
amounts of feed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll fan out and start prospecting,'' Thomas said. ``The
radio will get lively as soon as somebody catches one.''
</P>
<P>
   An insider's note is that private boaters should tune in to VHF
Channel 67, where most skippers will be trading information.
</P>
<P>
   The opener is the latest ever, with two more weeks cut off from
the beginning of the season (for years, the opener was set for Feb.
15). However, Thomas, who represents the Golden Gate Fleet on the
Pacific Fisheries Management Council, was able to help negotiate
adding another week to the end of the season, enhanced further by
attractive size limits.
</P>
<P>
   The season is now set to run through Nov. 5, with a 24-inch size
limit through May, then a 20-inch size limit starting June 1,
approved last Thursday by the Council.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, circle hooks will again be required for mooching,
but J hooks are acceptable for trollers, rules which result in a
fish being hooked in the jaw and high-survival rates for undersize
fish that are released.
</P>
<P>
   When circle hooks were first introduced, many fish were lost by
experienced fishermen trying to set the hook and instead simply
pulling the hook out of the salmon's mouth. With a circle hook, you
do not set the hook, but instead allow the fish to turn their heads
and swim away with the bait, and at that point, you just reel, and
bingo, you're on, with the hook solid in the jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas predicted that for the opener, the fleet will be split
50-50 between trolling and mooching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
