<P>
   SCI-ONEILL-DEATH (Undated) _ Eugene O'Neill, playwright of souls
in search of forgiveness, is given an absolution of sorts himself
today, in the pages of a medical journal. Contrary to Mr. O'Neill's
own suspicion that heavy drinking in his youth caused the brain
disease that crippled him later in life, a new report says alcohol
was not to blame. Far more likely, the progressive deterioration of
O'Neill's brain was due to a rare genetic disorder, said Dr. Bruce
H. Price, chairman of the neurology department at McLean Hospital
in Boston, and coauthor of an article in the New England Journal of
Medicine that is based on a new analysis of his medical records and
autopsy, and describes in detail the illness that kept him from
writing during the last 12 years of his life. By Denise Grady. (900
words)
</P>
