<P>
   OPEN-CURTAINS (New York) _ Gina Tarantino has sheer curtains,
but she and her husband never draw them. Neither do their
neighbors, who roll out of bed naked each morning, as unashamed as
Adam and Eve before the consumption of the apple. The 38-year-old
product designer, maintains that despite the view from her East
Side living room into the neighbors' bedroom, there remains a real
sense of anonymity.In fact, the curtainless situation has become a
challenge of wills. ``It has almost become a war,'' Ms. Tarantino
added. ``We're both just waiting to see who's going to draw their
curtains first. Our parents tell us all the time that it's just
like `Rear Window.''' Trend watchers, take note: It's curtains for
drapes. Farewell to billowing swathes of fabric. By Kimberly
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-FURNITURE-ARTWORK (Milan, Italy) _ Fearing that the latest
sleek samples of minimal elegance and technological wizardry might
not sufficiently wow the crowds at the annual furniture fair here,
organizers asked 14 international artists to create installations
within the splendid Rotonda della Besana in the middle of the city.
Robert Wilson, Yoko Ono, Peter Greenaway and other artists
interpreted the theme of ``rooms and their secrets.'' By Julie V.
Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-QNA (Undated) _ Gardening questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVORS-HAGGADAH (Undated) _ Every Seder table needs its
user's manual; it's called the Haggadah _ Hebrew for ``telling.''
But one long forgotten Haggadah stands out as starkly, darkly
different from all others. Called ``A Survivors' Haggadah,'' it was
created by and for displaced Jews in Munich, Germany, for their
first Passover after the end of the Third Reich. By Peter Hellman.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-BOOKS (Undated) _ Bookstore shelves are groaning under
the weight of ever more design titles. And whether they're
coffee-table fluff, scholarly analyses or plain-spoken how-to
books, they find buyers. A look at interesting new releases in the
field, whether triumphs or ambitious failures. By Eve Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-FURNISHINGS (High Point, N.C.) _ The ladies who lunch made
a surprise reappearance at the International Home Furnishings
Market, which opened here last Thursday and finishes tomorrow. Just
as Minimalism and Modernism are entrenched in the mainstream, the
upper end of the market took a swerve toward the traditional,
glamorous looks of the 1930s and '40s, offering a champagne
complement to the dry martini Deco modern that ushered out the
1990s. By Liz Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
