<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE MOST FROM CIRCULAR SAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most popular power tool for professionals and
do-it-yourselfers, after the portable electric drill, is the
circular saw. It can make most of the cuts done by table or
radial-arm saws, and it has the added advantage that it can be
carried to the job site. Fitted with the right blade, a portable
circular saw can cut through almost any material, and obviously,
faster than a hand saw.
</P>
<P>
   Most portable circular saws have similar design features. The
motor is enclosed in a housing mounted on a baseplate, or shoe. The
cutting part of the saw blade projects through a slot in the
baseplate. There are two handles mounted on the motor housing: the
main handle and the front handle. The main handle has the trigger
switch, which is a ''dead man's switch'' _ when finger pressure is
relaxed the switch opens and the motor is turned off. The front
handle is a knob that affords a two-hand grip and gives the user
greater control over the tool.
</P>
<P>
   For safety reasons, the blade is enclosed in two guards. The
upper blade guard is attached to the motor housing and remains
fixed in place. The lower blade guard is movable and retracts as
the saw cuts. It is spring-loaded so it snaps back to cover the
blade after the cut is made.
</P>
<P>
   All circular saws feature two blade adjustments. The depth of
cut adjustment moves the motor up or down on the baseplate so more
or less of the blade projects through the cutting slot. The angle
adjustment tilts the motor and blade so the saw can make miter
cuts. Most saws have a protractor gauge on the angle adjustment so
the blade can be set for a variety of angles.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the saw is determined by the diameter of the blade,
and blades are available in diameters from 4 3/8 inches to 8 1/4
inches. The most popular and practical size saw for the
professional and do-it-yourselfer is the 7 1/4 -inch model fitted
with a one-horsepower motor. (Many professional choose this size
saw with a heavier, two-horsepower motor.)
</P>
<P>
   Different blades are available to cut a variety of materials,
including wood. Wood-cutting blades are available with
carbide-tipped teeth. These blades are more expensive than ordinary
steel blades, but they stay sharp longer and make smoother cuts.
Generally, the more teeth per inch a blade has, the finer the cut.
For routine wood cutting jobs, buy a general-purpose, combination
blade with 20 to 24 teeth. This will allow you to rip or crosscut
lumber and composition board. A fine-cutting blade with 36 to 40
teeth is useful for cutting plywood and veneered stock. Other handy
wood-cutting blades are the hollow-ground planner blade and the
flooring blade.
</P>
<P>
   The hollow-ground planner blade is designed to produce a fine
finish on both surfaces when making either crosscuts or miter cuts.
The blade is thinner than the standard combination blade so the cut
is narrower. This blade cuts more slowly than the other
wood-cutting blades, but it makes a smooth cut.
</P>
<P>
   The flooring blade has tough carbide-tipped teeth and is
designed to cut through rough lumber, secondhand boards and
flooring. This is the ideal blade to use when cutting through wood
materials that have a high glue content, like particleboard.
</P>
<P>
   There are special blades for hard materials. The most useful is
the abrasive disk. Abrasive disks are not made of metal but are
molded from tough, abrasive materials like silicon carbide. There
are abrasive disks for metal and others for masonry andconcrete.
When cutting thick masonry or metal, it is best to start with a
shallow cut, then make several passes, increasing the depth of the
cut each time.
</P>
<P>
   Another type of metal-cutting blade is the friction blade. It is
made of steel and has square, not pointed, teeth. It is designed to
slice through corrugated steel and sheet metal. The biggest danger
when using a portable circular saw is called kickback. It occurs
when the blade binds in the stock, and the powerful torque
generated by the motor propels the saw back toward the user. There
are a number of ways to minimize the danger of kickback. Always cut
with a blade that is sharp and clean. Support the work adequately
so the kerf does not close in on the blade. Do not attempt to saw
through wet wood, and be especially careful when cutting wood that
is warped or knotty.
</P>
<P>
   When using a circular saw or any power tool, wear all the
necessary protective equipment like goggles and earplugs. You
should also wear a dust mask when cutting pressure-treated lumber.
</P>
</TEXT>
