<P>
   CUBA-BOY (Miami, Fla.) _ Elian Gonzalez has been transferred
from the home of his Miami relatives to the care of a nun as an
interim step in the anticipated transfer of the 6-year-old Cuban
boy to his father. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Denver) _ President Clinton urges people in Colorado to
take their own steps for gun control. He also will join a town hall
meeting on guns. The trip is part of the president's effort to
encourage states to enact gun-control laws rather than wait for
Washington to do so. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BANK-IMF (Washington) _ Already the target of hundreds of
demonstrators in the nation's capital, the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank come under more fire in Congress as members
of both parties chastise the organizations, calling them
ineffective and too secretive. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-FUNDING (Washington) _ A key Senate panel approves a plan
that would preserve San Francisco's current $35 million in federal
AIDS dollars, dealing a blow to efforts to redistribute much of the
city's funding to other places where the epidemic is growing. By
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   ORGRAN-TRANSPLANTS (Washington) _ Senate and administration
negotiators have reached agreement on legislation to overhaul the
nation's organ transplant system, a deal that could end a bitter,
two-year fight over transplant policy. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Lawmakers criticize the management
of NASA's Mars program but stop short of calling for changes in the
space agency's brass in the wake of two failed missions to the Red
Planet. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HEALTH (St. Louis, Mo.) _ George W. Bush unveils another
plank in his health care platform, proposing that the federal
government spend $3.6 billion over the next five years to create
1,200 new community and migrant health centers for low-income and
uninsured Americans. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BUSH (Washington)_ Vice President Al Gore derides
Republican George W. Bush's long-awaited health care proposal,
calling the Texan's plan ``political malpractice'' and another
attempt to gloss over his record as governor. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN-TEAMSTERS-CHINA (Washington) _ Patrick Buchanan, the
likely Reform Party presidential nominee, joins Teamsters Union
officials in denouncing a proposal to put freer trade with China on
a permanent basis. He and Teamsters President James Hoffa Jr. tell
a large crowd at a Capitol Hill rally that the plan would cost
American jobs. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
