<HEADER>
A4791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-LIPSTADT-HOLOCAUST-$A     04-12 1645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSTADT-HOLOCAUST-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE HER COURT VICTORY, LIPSTADT SEES MORE HOLOCAUST BATTLES
AHEAD
 &HT;    With Photos 
 &HT;    Advance for April 15 
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON, Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ About 20 years ago, a student interrupted Deborah
Lipstadt during a history lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Then a young college professor in California, Lipstadt was
telling her students that the U.S. government in the 1930s and
1940s had received reports about Nazi atrocities against Jews. It
stands to reason, she told
</P>
<P>
   them, that American newspapers carried stories reflecting these
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe you,'' a student blurted out. ``I don't
believe that people like my parents could have known about it and
done nothing and then said that they didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt was taken aback by the student's distress. She decided
to take the students to the library to see for themselves what
American newspapers had reported.
</P>
<P>
   What she found was both disturbing and enlightening. When she
expected to see a major story on the front page, she would find
something relegated inside the paper. When she expected to see at
least a mention of
</P>
<P>
   some event, she would find nothing.
</P>
<P>
   She came to the realization that American newspapers may have
severely underplayed the story of the Holocaust story. This
launched her five-year odyssey through aging newspaper clippings
that produced her
</P>
<P>
   first book: ``Beyond Belief: The American Press and the Coming
of the Holocaust 1933-45.''
</P>
<P>
   She argued in the book that if the press had been more
aggressive in its coverage of the worsening situation for Jews in
Germany and eventually much of the rest of Europe, then public
opinion might have also been stirred. This might have prompted the
U.S. government to do more.
</P>
<P>
   Now nearly two decades later, Lipstadt, a 53-year-old professor
at Atlanta's Emory University, finds herself concerned about how
the story of the Holocaust is told.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, she is not fighting over how the story was
reported in the past but how it is being told in the present and,
perhaps more importantly, how it will be told in the future.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she won a decisive triumph over English historical
writer David Irving, who had sued Lipstadt and her British
publisher Penguin Books over her portrayal of him in her book
``Denying the Holocaust: The
</P>
<P>
   Growing Assault on Truth and Memory.'' It was published in the
United States in 1993 and in Britain in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A British judge found that three months of testimony and
documents supported Lipstadt's portrait of Irving as a bigoted
would-be historian who had intentionally distorted historical facts
to support his extremist political views.
</P>
<P>
   Irving, who has made a handsome career out of trashing the
accepted understanding of what happened to European Jews during the
World War II era, was humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   At a packed news conference at the London Waldorf hotel Tuesday
afternoon, Lipstadt, who had been silent during the three-month
trial, confidently unleashed her flat, New York accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked many times if I had it to do over again, would
I write this book again,'' she said. ``The answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience gasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have written a tougher one,'' she said, sounding more like
a jubilant New York Yankee in a post-World Series news conference
than a scholar who had prevailed in an cerebral contest.
</P>
<P>
   Over coffee the day before the verdict, Lipstadt _ described
Wednesday by the Times of London as a ``striking redhead'' _ was
supercharged in a way people often are when they find themselves in
a favored limelight. In Britain as in the United States, she has
been widely portrayed as the defender of good against David
Irving's bumbling prince of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   In the sitting room at her elegant London hotel _ Lipstadt's
home away from home during the trial _ a waitress brought her a
small porcelain coffee pot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you nervous?'' the waitress asked politely as she set the
pot and cup on the table before Lipstadt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adrenaline. Adrenaline,'' said Lipstadt, who apparently
decided that was all the stimulant she needed and asked for decaf.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning during the trial the uniformed doorman wished
Lipstadt good luck as she headed off to court. When she returned at
night, he asked her how it went.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concierge told me to be optimistic because there is plenty
of time to be pessimistic afterwards,'' she said, clearly proud of
the quasi-family she has acquired at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   She will miss the hotel life. ``I'll really miss the magic
bed,'' she said. ``You know, every morning I leave and it's a mess
and when I come back it's made.''
</P>
<P>
   Her journey to this fine hotel in London began in New York City,
where she was the child of two devout Jews who instilled in her a
deep respect for the faith and intellect.
</P>
<P>
   He late father, Erwin Lipstadt, owned a cemetery stone business
in New York. He left Germany in 1928 during the Great Depression.
``He treasured, treasured America because of the opportunities it
provided him
</P>
<P>
   and his family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Miriam, came to the United States from Canada as a
baby. She is a former newspaper columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt knows of no relative who died in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Her interest in Jewish history blossomed her junior year at
Hebrew University in Jerusalem. In the course of her studies, she
once said she noticed that ``everything I was doing was on American
Jewish history. And I said somebody is telling me something here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt earned a Ph.D. in American Jewish history at Brandeis
University in Massachusetts. She helped start the Jewish studies
program at the University of Washington in Seattle in the 1970s.
After five years in
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, she left for UCLA in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to LA's Occidental College before being lured by
Atlanta's Emory University in 1993 during the early years of the
school's campaign to recruit first class faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very excited to come to Emory because of Emory's
reputation _ it's a really fine university,'' she said. ``And also
I was attracted by Atlanta's reputation as a city. I have been
wooed by other universities _ good universities _ but they weren't
in metropolitan areas that I wanted to be part of.''
</P>
<P>
   A little over a year ago, she was appointed to the chair of the
newly-created Institute of Jewish Studies at Emory, the first such
program of its kind in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt also was recently re-appointed by the White House to
the executive committee of the Holocaust Memorial Council, which
administers the Holocaust Museum in Washington. She has also just
completed a term as Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's adviser
on religious discrimination abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The Irving verdict almost certainly will cast her more into the
fray over Holocaust deniers, perhaps elevating her to the position
of their prime nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt, who said she often found the trial ``deeply
energizing,'' seems up to the fight, and believes the cause is
worth the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   She worries that revisionists such as Irving are working their
way into mainstream thinking, slowly eroding the shared memory of
the Holocaust. ``I don't see deniers as a clear and present danger,
I see them as a clear and future danger,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors are the greatest protectors of the Holocaust's legacy,
but their ranks are dwindling, she said. ``Soon there won't be
people to tell the story in the first person singular.''
</P>
<P>
   She rejected an invitation to settle out of court because she
feared it would be seen as a victory for Irving and his cause. ``I
was sued. If I hadn't fought it, he would have won by default,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she has always avoided debates with deniers because she
feared this could give them unwarranted authority. ``It would be
the equivalent of asking astronomers to debate whether the Earth is
flat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has had substantial help in her battle.
</P>
<P>
   Penguin, which is owned by the British media giant Pearson,
stood resolutely by her. (Pearson is headed by Marjorie Scardino, a
Texan who made a name by winning a Pulitzer Prize with her husband
Albert Scardino at a Savannah, Ga., weekly newspaper.)
</P>
<P>
   Her legal team, headed by two noted lawyers, was from the
British powerhouse firm Mishcon de Reya. (CQ) Richard Rampton is
one of the country's foremost libel lawyers, while Anthony Julius
is famous for representing Princess Diana during her divorce from
Prince Charles.
</P>
<P>
   While she was impressed with the decorum of the British
courtroom, Lipstadt frankly doesn't know what to compare it to.
``This is my first law case, period,'' she said. ``I was a complete
novice when it comes to the law courts.''
</P>
<P>
   She offered particular praise for Emory University, which along
with Penguin Books picked up most of her costs for transportation
and lodging in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emory as an institution has been outstanding,'' she said.
``You would hope a university would do that when one of their own
came under fire, but they don't all do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got e-mails not just from the president, the provost, the
dean of the college. I got e-mails and messages from secretaries
and custodians there wishing me support and everybody in between,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Next for her is a return to Atlanta, where she will redouble her
efforts with the fledgling institute.
</P>
<P>
   She also plans to write a book about the Irving trial.
</P>
<P>
   She says she has no illusions that winning the case means the
end of her fight. ``The nightmare is not over,'' she said hours
after the verdict was rendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no end to the battle against racism, anti-Semitism,
and fascism.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton can be reached by e-mail at:
bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
