<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Problems With PDFs And Noisy Zip Drives
</P>
<P>
   Q. I downloaded a PDF file from the Internet, and there was
nothing in it but blank pages. Is it the file or my PC that's
having the problem?
</P>
<P>
   A. The attraction of PDF, the Portable Document Format created
by Adobe Systems, is that computer users on a variety of platforms
can see and print documents as they were originally designed
without having the fonts and graphics loaded on their machines. To
view PDF files, you need to have a small program called Acrobat
Reader.
</P>
<P>
   You might try to download a PDF file from a different site and
see if you can view it. If you can open other PDF files, the
problem may lie with the document in question. There have been
several versions of Acrobat Reader released in the past few years,
so you may be trying to look at a PDF file that was created in a
later version of the program and isn't compatible with the older
version of Acrobat Reader you have on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   You can go to Adobe's Web site to download the latest version of
Acrobat Reader that is available for your operating system. There
is a link to the downloading page for Acrobat Reader on Adobe's
main page (www.adobe.com).
</P>
<P>
   If you've never seen a PDF file, you might want to look on
Adobe's Web site at several literary works that have been converted
to that format. You can download them free if you register in the
ePaper part of the site (www.adobe.com/epaper/main.html). The
titles include ``Hamlet'' and ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland.''
For those with more modern tastes in fiction, there is also a link
to download a PDF file of Stephen King's new novella, ``Riding the
Bullet,'' which was recently published in electronic book format.
</P>
<P>
   PDF files may even help you save gasoline. The federal
government has posted many common forms on its sites that you can
download and print out. If you're the type who hasn't yet started
filling out your tax forms, you can even download PDF versions of
the proper forms at www.irs.gov/forms(underscore)pubs/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My Zip drive sometimes makes a lot of clicking sounds when I
use it. Is that normal behavior for this type of device?
</P>
<P>
   A. It is normal to hear a quick clicking sound when you first
put a Zip disk into a Zip drive. That is the sound of the drive's
heads finding the disk. Iomega, the manufacturer, warns that
constant clicking sounds coming from the drive might be a problem
and that disks that click constantly should not be used.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is sometimes called the ``click of death'' among Zip
users because it is often the mournful cry of a Zip drive getting
ready to malfunction for good. If your drive is perpetually
clicking, the company advises that you notify it on the Web at
www.iomega.com/support/nav(underscore)contact.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I use a Macintosh and Microsoft Word 98 as my writing tools
of choice, and I hate having to press multiple keys to get the
proper quotation marks. Is there a way to make this easier?
</P>
<P>
   A. Turning on Word's AutoCorrect feature (found under the Tools
menu) will automatically put in the proper quotation marks when you
press the apostrophe key, or the shift of that key. You can also
assign keyboard shortcuts to typographic characters that you use
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, go to the Insert menu and select Symbol from the
list. You will see a box with two tabs pop up on your screen. One
tab contains accented letters, symbols and dingbats, and the other
has a selection of special punctuation characters like quotation
marks and dashes. Click on the symbol or character you want and
then on the Shortcut Key button. A new box will pop up that will
allow you to assign the symbol to a single key on the keyboard.
Pick the key or key combination you want and click Assign. The
program may not let you override regular letters, but you can
assign shortcuts to the row of F keys along the top of your
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
