</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DORA GALITSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frozen Oleander
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a beautiful oleander, grown from a little cutting 20
years ago. In the winter it lives in the garage, where it gets
plenty of light and where the temperature is never below freezing.
This winter, however, someone left the garage door open one night,
and it was exposed to the bitter cold for about 12 hours. My
husband said we should throw it out since its leaves all looked
dead, but I am still watering it in the hope that it may revive.
Could it? It has great sentimental value to me. Is a freezing cold
night always fatal?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not necessarily. Thomas Silva, who teaches plant physiology
at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y., said that when a plant
freezes, death comes as a result of cells bursting. That can happen
if the liquid in the cell freezes, expands as it forms ice
crystals, and breaks the walls. Or if water in the vascular system
surrounding the cell freezes first. That draws water out of the
cell, causing its walls to shrink. When the ice thaws, the water
rushes back into the shrunken cell, bursting it like an overfilled
balloon. If enough cells die, so does the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The tricky part is figuring out how far below freezing the
temperature has to go, and for how long, before damage is fatal.
Leaves are out there in the cold air, so they freeze first. A plant
can stand losing its leaves and a few branches as long as its roots
survive. Since they are insulated by soil, it takes colder
temperatures or a longer time for them to freeze.
</P>
<P>
   How much soil was in the pot and how wet it was are important
factors. Moist soil is a better insulator for the roots than is dry
soil because the water has to freeze first.
</P>
<P>
   Some or all of your oleander has obviously been damaged, but I
would keep caring for it until it is very clear that reports of its
death have not been exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Privet Hedge Control
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have 8-foot-high privet hedges that line my driveway and
act as a beautiful natural fence. Because of their height, they are
now unmanageable. I would like to cut them back to 5 or 6 feet. To
do so, I would be cutting established branches 1/4 to 1/2 an inch
thick. What is the best time of the year to cut privet hedges back
so drastically?
</P>
<P>
   A. Today. Right now. Don't even go to work. Ideally, major
privet renovations should be done just before new growth begins in
the spring in order to give the plants the best opportunity to heal
their wounds.
</P>
<P>
   While cutting back 2 or 3 feet may sound drastic, it isn't.
Privet hedges can be cut back to 18 inches above the ground and
will do just fine if they are cared for afterward _ fertilized,
mulched and watered during summer dry spells.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of total renovation may be necessary if improper
pruning, or no pruning, has resulted in a hedge with foliage at the
top but sparse foliage at the base. To let light in to the whole
shrub, promoting foliage growth all the way down, be sure to prune
with a taper so the top is slightly narrower than the bottom. That
will prevent the upper section from shading the lower parts.
</P>
<P>
   When you do your maintenance pruning in the spring, including
this shortening, shear off half of last year's growth on the sides
as well as the top to continue promoting a dense wall all the way
down without bare areas. Go over the hedge lightly in mid-July just
to keep it neat. And smile while you prune. With a 5-foot hedge,
you will have a different relationship with your neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd
St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(at)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
