<HEADER>
A4803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SURVIVORS-HAGGADAH-AR     04-12 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVORS-HAGGADAH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUNICH, 1946: WORDS FROM A SEDER UNLIKE ANY OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of one of the woodcuts is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER HELLMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every Seder table needs its user's manual; it's called the
Haggadah _ Hebrew for ``telling.'' As Passover begins next
Wednesday evening, our family's choice will be the old standby
distributed since 1934 by Maxwell House coffee (40 million copies
in print), augmented by direct readings from Exodus. The Passover
story, with its ever timely theme of liberation from bondage, has
begotten thousands of Haggadot, including specialized versions for
feminists, vegetarians, hippies, gays, lesbians, Christians and
ecumenicals.
</P>
<P>
   This year even brings a children's pop-up Haggadah based on the
famed Bird's Head Haggadah from Germany (circa 1300), in which
humans do indeed have slightly macabre birds' heads. At West Side
Judaica in New York, I counted 70 Haggadot for sale. Cody's Books
in Berkeley, Calif., claims to stock 200.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, just as Seder night is different from all other nights, one
long forgotten Haggadah stands out as starkly, darkly different
from all others. Called ``A Survivors' Haggadah,'' it was created
by and for displaced Jews in Munich, Germany, for their first
Passover after the end of the Third Reich. These stateless souls
were called in Hebrew she'erith haptelah, the remnant that escaped.
</P>
<P>
   The Seders were held in the Deutsches Theater restaurant on
April 15 and 16, 1946. The unlikely publisher was the occupying
American Third Army. Two years ago, the American Jewish Historical
Society published 500 copies of a richly annotated collector's
edition, priced at $360. Now comes a commercial edition from the
Jewish Publication Society, at $50.
</P>
<P>
   The DPs, or ``displaced persons,'' who sat down to Seder in
Munich in 1946 were no longer in bondage to Hitler, yet neither
were they free. They could not or would not go home to the wreckage
of their former lives. Those who fervently wished to go to
Palestine faced the British blockade. America was then closed to
them. And, of course, their families had been murdered. How were
they to ``celebrate'' Passover?
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Haggadot praise God for the miracle of deliverance
from bondage into freedom. But the pages of ``A Survivors'
Haggadah'' resonate with bitter sarcasm toward the God who was a
spectator to the Holocaust. Consider its twist on the normally
joyful Seder song ``Dayenu,'' which means ``It would have been
enough.'' Instead of reciting God's wondrous acts and adding that
refrain, this version ticks off the atrocities permitted by God:
``Had he given us Hitler but not ghettos, dayenu. Had he given us
ghettos but no gas chambers and crematories, dayenu. Had he given
us gas chambers and crematories but our wives and children had not
been tortured, dayenu.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven spectral woodcuts invoke the Jews' bondage to Hitler. Most
are accompanied by traditional text. A biblical passage, for
example, accompanies ``Selection,'' which shows a hard-faced Nazi
officer separating a boy from his mother as masses of Jews trudge
off toward smokestacks: ``While Pharaoh decreed death only for male
children, Laban sought to uproot all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Haggadah's final woodcut, smoke is seen curling up from
tall chimneys, becoming the disembodied heads of an old couple and
a child. The four-word caption, ``We are bound to ...,'' will be
cryptic to those unfamiliar with the traditional Haggadah, where
these words, taken from the psalmic verses of praise called hallel,
continue, ``... thank, laud, praise, glorify and exalt him who
performed all these miracles for our forefathers and us.'' ``A
Survivors' Haggadah'' chooses silence, not praise, for the God who
performed no Holocaust miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its singular power, ``A Survivors' Haggadah'' was
quickly forgotten. Then, three years ago, Saul Tauster, a retired
professor of law and social policy at Brandeis University, was
sifting through four generations' worth of family papers when a
copy of ``A Survivors' Haggadah'' fell out of a box of his late
father's papers. On its cover was a white letter A in a red and
blue bull's-eye, the emblem of the Third Army.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, Tauster set out to learn all he could about this
curious Haggadah, even though he was proficient in neither Hebrew
nor Yiddish. A little dabbling quickly became an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   The text was credited to Yosef Sheinson, a Hebrew teacher from
Lithuania who had survived the war as a slave laborer before
arriving in Munich as a DP. Sheinson also created the Haggadah's
line-drawn borders, mixing pharaonic, Nazi and Zionist motifs. And
those accomplished woodcuts? They were signed only Ben Benyamin
(``Son of the Son of the Right Hand''). It took two years of
digging before Tauster identified the artist as Miklos Adler, a
survivor from Hungary. At the end of the war, Adler had returned to
Debrecen, his hometown, and had gone to work on a portfolio of 16
woodcuts. In a preface, Adler wrote: ``My means, I know, are modest
and old-fashioned; my style, I know, is poor. And yet I feel that
I, too, must tell what follows in these pages. Oh, my murdered
brothers and sisters, you who sanctified God's name! I will mourn
you until I die.''
</P>
<P>
   He died in 1965, and Tauster suspects, based on interviews with
several relatives, that the artist never knew that seven of his
woodcuts had found their way into ``A Survivors' Haggadah.''
</P>
<P>
   The Haggadah's preamble, written by Abraham Klausner, an
American Army chaplain assigned to the DPs, invokes the name of
Gen. Lucian K. Truscott, commander of the occupation army. But it
ignores his predecessor, Gen. George S. Patton, who had been fired
by Eisenhower. While Patton had only scorn for the plight of the
DPs (his diary attacks those who ``believe the displaced person is
a human being, which he is not, and this applies particularly to
the Jews, who are lower than animals''), Truscott had only empathy.
His grandson, the writer Lucian K. Truscott IV, told Tauster that
his grandfather had ``indelibly marked the Holocaust on his
family's conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tauster's Seder next week, the traditional Haggadah will be
supplemented by readings from ``A Survivors' Haggadah.''
</P>
<P>
   Satisfying a yen to hold in my own hands a 1946 original, I
visited the rare book room (frigid to preserve delicate pages, pens
prohibited lest they leave errant marks) in the library of the
Jewish Theological Seminary in New York. Two copies are in the
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have something of related interest,'' volunteered David
Wachtel, a library associate. He handed me another small Haggadah
in a slipcase of multiple pastel hues, this one published for
Passover in 1945, nearly two months before the Nazi surrender, by
the advancing 42nd Infantry Division, known as the Rainbow
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the Rainbow Haggadah was an accompanying letter from
Eli Bohnen, a Jewish chaplain with the division, dated April 16,
1945, exactly one year before ``A Survivors' Haggadah'' was used at
the Deutsches Theater. ``I am confident,'' he wrote, ``that it is
the first Hebrew religious work printed in Germany since the advent
of Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter recounts, too, that the Haggadah was printed on a
captured offset press. The press was dirty, and ``the only rags
available were some Nazi flags.''
</P>
<P>
   For once, the chaplain concluded, Nazi flags ``served a useful
purpose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
