 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, April 13. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECT (Lima, Peru) _ Tension mounts as people still await
final election results, which government said would come by noon
Wednesday. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-PROTEST (Washington) _ Reciting a litany of negatives about
trade, thousands of steelworkers, truck drivers, auto workers and
other union members rallied on Capitol Hill and swept through the
halls of Congress in a show of muscle intended to block a trade
agreement with China. Their message, conveyed both by union leaders
and rank and file members who traveled here from as far away as
Michigan and Nebraska, was that trade was working for American
corporations but not for American workers. It served to kick off a
series of demonstrations planned by a diverse coalition of activist
groups for the next five days around meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,4.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PRISONERS (Jerusalem) _ Reversing itself, the Supreme
Court of Israel ruled Wednesday that Israel is not justified in
holding Lebanese detainees as ``bargaining chips`` for missing
Israeli soldiers. The court ordered that eight of 15 Lebanese
detainees who have been imprisoned without charges for more than a
decade be released immediately. In the closed-door hearing, the
court said the men did not ``pose a danger to state security'' and
that, ``absent any other reason for their arrest,'' their long
detention was illegal. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-25YEARS (Ho Chi Minh City) _ Special Report: An overview
of the situation in Vietnam 25 years after the war ended. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is the first story in an occasional series marking
the quarter century since the end of the war in Vietnam.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline to kum) _ Developments. With resolution of
his fate drawing nearer, Elian Gonzalez today moved to a
sympathetic nun's house as Attorney General Janet Reno traveled to
Miami to try to settle the custody dispute over the young Cuban
refugee. Reno left Washington in the afternoon to meet with the
Miami relatives who have cared for Elian since he was found
floating in the Atlantic off Florida at Thanksgiving. Reporting by
Rick Bragg in Miami and David Johnston in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-PROTESTS (Great Barrington, Mass.) _ From the Berkshires to
Cambridge, brushfires of civil disobedience flared in classrooms
across Massachusetts on Wednesday, as hundreds of high school
sophomores, and dozens of fourth- and eighth-graders, boycotted the
first of nine days of statewide standardized testing. In a sign of
rising student and parent discontent with politicians' reliance on
such tests, the protests followed _ and exceeded _ similar
rebellions in recent months in Illinois, Ohio, Louisiana, Wisconsin
and Florida. Though most of the students in Massachusetts reported
to class as scheduled, they chose to write essays about their
opposition to testing rather than answer the questions posed. Some
of the students face disciplinary actions ranging from suspension
to having a failing test grade incorporated into their third
quarter marks. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
