<P>
   NAZI-ART-MUSEUMS (New York) _ After nearly two years of scouring
their collections for artworks that might once have been stolen by
the Nazis, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Museum of Modern Art
and a few other major American museums are finally starting to
reveal their findings. But they are taking different tacks, and
some are clearly closer to the full disclosure they promised than
others. Some of the works could conceivably now be claimed by heirs
to those who owned them half a century ago. At 9 a.m. Wednesday,
the Met posted on its website (www.metmuseum.org) a list of 393
paintings, drawn from the 2,700 European paintings in its
collection, whose ownership histories have a gap between 1933 and
1945 _ even if it is only a month. By Judith Dobrzynski.
