<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-ZINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES CLAMOR FOR TEEN-AGERS' ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By ERIC V. COPAGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do teen-agers want? That question _ which once would have
elicited a ``who cares?'' _ has become a $150 billion mantra among
advertisers tripping over one another as they clamor for their
attention. The burgeoning population of adolescents is predicted to
grow to 34 million from its current 29 million by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Although the answer to the question remains a mystery, a clue
may be found in the technology with which the teen-agers of
Generation Y have grown up. Susan Chaggaris, director of a panel on
teen-agers for North Castle Partners Advertising, which specializes
in the teen-age market, said adolescents use the Internet mostly to
make new friends and keep in touch with older ones and to research
homework.
</P>
<P>
   But teen-agers also put information about themselves on the
Internet. What do their home pages and e-zines reveal about them as
a group?
</P>
<P>
   Surfing the Web to discover what teen-agers are posting about
themselves can be problematic. Typing anything containing ``teen''
into some search engines is as likely as not to return a multitude
of variations on ``Lolita Does Dallas.'' And the sheer exertion and
expertise needed to start and maintain a Web site may account for
why so many prospective sites return the message ``URL cannot be
found'' or ``site under construction.''
</P>
<P>
   The sites that do exist are often, not surprisingly, about their
creators. ``There is usually an `about me' thing,'' said Esther
Drill, executive director and co-founder of gURL.com, which posts
home pages by teen-age girls. ``What's fun is that they have rants,
which are mini-essays about what they feel passionately about.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerl.org, an elegant, spare site created by a 19-year-old, is a
case in point. It includes questions and answers detailing a few of
her favorite things (smell? banana nut bread; brand of gum?
``something sugarless'') and links to friends' sites with names
like Insanitarium, One More Addiction and Colourless World. The
Gerl site mixes the bathos of the cartoon heroine Daria with 1970s
Joni Mitchell-like fragility.
</P>
<P>
   Bolt.com, a site for teen-agers and young adults, offers
earthier fare on a section of the site that every week offers
temporary lodging for 13 home pages created by teen-agers. Recent
highlights included a delightfully surrealistic haze of a page
called Dreaming Realm, created by a 19-year-old. His dense site
includes his meditation on men and women. (He writes that when
girls ask, ``Do I look fat in this dress?'' it means, ``We haven't
fought in a while.'') There is also Real Audio video of several
versions of the Lambada (The Forbidden Dance) and a selection of
the teen-ager's artwork and poetry, and the poetry of visitors to
his realm.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Bolt.com is a 15-year-old girl's colorful and elaborate
homage to ``Sailor Moon,'' an animated Japanese story about a
14-year-old girl who is given magical powers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes teen-agers are happy to simply document the lives of
their favorite television, movie and musical stars.
</P>
<P>
   The more outward-looking Web sites even take on established
presences on the Internet. Steven Drypolcher, 16, who created the
game site www.game-guru.net, said: ``I couldn't relate to other
game sites because they had no teen angle. Older guys will describe
things in technical terms that are way over the head of teens.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is possible that Drypolcher was speaking with some
self-promotional exaggeration _ certainly top gaming sites run by
adults speak ``teen'' flawlessly _ his Game-Guru is a clean,
well-organized and attractive site, done in cool robin's egg blue
and drawing a staff from his school computer club. He said his ``as
for now'' nonprofit site gets an impressive 10,000 hits a day.
``Every time I put in an article, I send it to a gaming news site,
such as Blue's News or Voodoo Extreme, and they will post it,'' he
said. ``From there, people see it and follow the page.''
</P>
<P>
   But the days of the renegade teen-age Webmaster may be coming to
an end as Mother, Father and Big Brother see the dollar signs and
catch teen-ager fever. The phrase ``by teens, for teens'' seems to
have become a kind of drumbeat to market a site to adolescents.
Even the likes of the MXGonline.com megasite (run in part with
support from USA Networks) bills itself as ``built by girls for
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Edelman, the 41-year-old president of the Student Center, a
network of a dozen Web sites for college students and teen-agers,
contemplated the changes in teen-agers' presence on the Internet
over the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays it would be very hard to start because there has been
such an explosion,'' Edelman said. ``Just two or three years ago,
it was far easier to get links to your site because there was less
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelman's company has bought two sites from teen-agers,
including Technoteen.com and Teens-online.com, which attract more
girls than boys. Another site Edelman owns, Teenadvice.net, says in
its About Us section, ``If we want to talk about music, we'd rather
talk with our peers than with the frustrated 40-somethings reliving
their Woodstock years.'' All of Edelman's sites are run by
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   So, according to the Internet, what do teen-agers want? They
want to make money. And they want to be celebrities, or at least
meet some celebrities. And most of all, it seems, they want to
explore and interacting with the world in a way that can be can be
summed up with lyrics from those Paleolithic Woodstock years: ``See
me. Feel me. Touch me. Heal me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0203 </DOCNO>
