<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES IN CHINESE-OWNED INTERNET BUSINESS SET TO GO PUBLIC IN
U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The first of China's leading Internet companies is set
to go public in the United States on Thursday _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   The initial public offering, from Sina.com, is the first of what
are expected to be many such Nasdaq listings in the months ahead.
But investors who buy the stock will not actually own a stake in
China's most popular Internet portal. Instead, they will own a
piece of the Sina.com's offshore Web sites _ a fraction of its core
business.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are buying a stake in the company's marginal Hong
Kong, Taiwan and North American portals. Sina.com, incorporated in
the Cayman Islands, holds various licensing agreements with a
Chinese company that owns the Chinese portal.
</P>
<P>
   People in China's Internet industry are closely watching the
offering, somewhat aghast that American investors may be willing to
accept a company gutted of content. Sina.com's performance will
determine whether other Chinese Internet companies take the plunge
or choose to wait until China's ever-shifting regulations change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it will fly,'' a Chinese Internet entrepreneur
said Wednesday at an industry party in Beijing called ``The Bubble
Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sina.com, founded by a 32-year-old Beijing University graduate,
became the hottest Web site in China last year after it posted
reports of the NATO bombing of China's embassy in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, within minutes of the official press.
</P>
<P>
   And it provided more information than any other mainland source,
relying heavily on foreign news reports.
</P>
<P>
   The company's main Chinese portal is linked to nine different
``channels,'' Web sites that offer everything from news to online
shopping for cellular phones, flowers, even food. The company's
free and fast e-mail accounts and timely news updates have made it
the most popular portal in China for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the IPO, however, will own none of that, thanks to
regulations intended to allow Chinese Internet companies to raise
capital on overseas stock markets while adhering to China's
longstanding ban on foreign investment in the telecommunications
and media industries. Those rules are supposed to change when China
joins the World Trade Organization. And the country has welcomed
private foreign investment in the Internet. Venture capitalists
estimate that as much as $1 billion has flowed into Chinese
Internet start-ups in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   But the country remains fearful of allowing ownership of its new
e-businesses slip overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Sina.com quickly grew from a handful of people to more than 500
Wednesday in Zhongguancun, Beijing's answer to Silicon Valley.
Investment bankers were soon offering the company bundles of cash,
and it subsequently raised nearly $100 million, giving it an
estimated market capitalization of close to $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's boldness won it fans, but not among China's
conservative officials, who made it clear that Sina.com would not
be given approval to list abroad unless the company toed Beijing's
line. With its access to venture capital nearly exhausted, the
company was eager to improve relations with the regulators, said
people close to the company. To win their favor, the company
dropped news from all sources other than the state-run press and
removed links on its site that led users to foreign media sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0205 </DOCNO>
