<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SNOWMOBILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNING A CLEANER, QUIETER SNOWMOBILE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Wyo.)   (Circuits)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clean snowmobile'' may sound like a contradiction in terms.
Snowmobiles produce both noise and exhaust emissions, and the
machines have numerous foes who want them banned from national
parks and other locations.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of engineering students at the State University of
New York in Buffalo may lead the way toward rehabilitating these
vehicles. The students won a design contest by retrofitting a used
snowmobile to eliminate virtually 100 percent of its unburned
hydrocarbon emissions and a great deal of its noise.
</P>
<P>
   The retooled machine won first place in a contest for improved
snowmobile design sponsored by the Society for Automotive
Engineers, which announced the winner in Jackson Hole, Wyo., on
April 4. Seven colleges competed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of a technical solution to a huge
problem,'' said Dr. Lori Fussell of Wilson, Wyo., an environmental
engineer who dreamed up the competition with a colleague two years
ago and has been working on the project ever since. ``People on the
extremes of the issue want either unrestricted use or complete
prohibition,'' Fussell said. ``This way we can deal with it not as
a political issue, but as a research one, finding ways to reduce
pollution and noise at reasonable cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitors worked with two-year-old snowmobiles, former rentals
from Yellowstone National Park. ``National parks are extremely
interested in a technological solution to this controversy,''
Fussell said.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong series of tests at Jackson Hole evaluated the
snowmobiles for fuel economy, performance, design, noise and
emissions. At the end, trophies were awarded, and the Buffalo team
got $17,000 in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo group, which won in all categories except
performance (a combination of acceleration, hill climbing and
handling) designed a four-stroke engine that reduced unburned
hydrocarbons to undetectable levels when compared with controls.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up, the University of Waterloo in Ontario, reduced
the amount of unburned hydrocarbons by 95 percent with a two-stroke
engine.
</P>
<P>
   Interested in joining the competition next year and improving
the reputation of the snowmobile? Check the Society of Automotive
Engineer's Web site (www.sae.org).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
