<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TAXI-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD THE SEAT BELTS AND STEP ON THE GAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By JEFFREY R. YOUNG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When taking the wheel of Crazy Taxi, you can forget about seat
belts, traffic lights and anything you may have learned about
defensive driving. In this game, the more near-collisions,
spin-outs and drawbridge leaps you manage, the bigger the tips from
your virtual passengers, who praise your speed and daring. It's
enough to confirm your worst fears about how taxi drivers view the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy Taxi, an irreverent arcade hit, is now available for
Sega's Dreamcast. When the cab is empty, nothing matters but
picking up passengers. And when there is a fare on board, nothing
matters but getting to the destination as quickly as possible (an
arrow hovering in the sky shows the way).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike adrenaline-fueled racing games like Sega Rally, Crazy
Taxi has no predetermined routes, so players can drive nearly
anywhere, including through shopping malls or even into the ocean.
Because the goal of Crazy Taxi isn't just reaching a finish line
but also pleasing passengers, the riders do their share of
back-seat driving and are quick to leap out of the cab without
paying if they think the trip is taking too long.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is a fictional metropolis that blends the hills and
trolleys of San Francisco with features from other cities. The
passengers' destinations, however, are real product placements;
they include Pizza Hut, KFC and Tower Records.
</P>
<P>
   The game is intuitive enough that players can start their own
crazy taxi services immediately. But to gain anything more than
mediocre tips, it is necessary to memorize the layout of the city.
After all, cutting through an alley can shave valuable seconds off
many a trip.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps to master the advanced driving maneuvers taught in
the manual, like the ``crazy drift'' _ shifting the cab into
reverse while slamming the wheel to the left or right to make
sharper high-speed turns.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy Taxi falls into a tradition of arcade classics that place
gamers in seemingly mundane jobs, but with a twist. Perhaps the
best example is Paperboy, where players run a paper route but score
points for breaking windows of houses belonging to nonpaying
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples are Burgertime, where players take the role of a
chef who builds giant hamburgers while running from evil walking
eggs, pickles and hot dogs, and Tapper, where players must sling
beers to an endless stream of misfit drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast version of Crazy Taxi is a nearly perfect copy of
the arcade game, with rich graphics and fast-paced action that
shows off what Sega's 128-bit game console can do. The home version
also offers an extra city to explore and a training section to help
players hone their skills.
</P>
<P>
   To reinforce the game's theme that only a wild misfit would want
a license to drive a taxi, players must choose to play one of four
antisocial drivers. Each has a different attitude and a different
type of cab.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a half-hearted attempt to give personalities and
backgrounds to the passengers. These aren't exactly Taxicab
Confessions: the game manual says some of the many passengers
you'll encounter are the flower-toting Pierre, ``who spends all of
his time and money chasing women'' and a graduate student named
Dan, who is doing his thesis on ``the impact of the fashion
industry on world markets.'' But it's hard to deduce these
backgrounds from the lines passengers mumble as they enter and
leave the cabs.
</P>
<P>
   The soundtrack, with neo-punk tunes by Offspring and Bad
Religion, matches the game's frenetic pace. But unfortunately,
Crazy Taxi has just a few songs. A few trips around the block lead
to the painful sensation of being stuck in a car tuned to a grating
radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest allure of Crazy Taxi is that it gives players the
satisfaction of speeding through city streets that in real life
would doom drivers to gridlock. That puts it in a category with
recent games like Midway's San Francisco Rush and Microsoft's
Midtown Madness, where players can race through virtual renderings
of well-known cities.
</P>
<P>
   The incredible level of detail in the games also points to how
far driving games have come from the low-resolution days of Pole
Position. In Crazy Taxi, it's easy to keep the speedometer at or
above 80 miles per hour, and there are no police officers to
interfere.
</P>
<P>
   When a lane of traffic backs up, just use the sidewalk and plow
through phone booths, hot dog carts and other obstacles. You can
adjust the density of traffic in the game by using the options
settings, but even the thickest traffic level leaves plenty of room
to weave an uninterrupted path of cab exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Those cab rides through Times Square might seem tame in
comparison. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crazy Taxi, by Sega; for Dreamcast; $49.99; for teen-agers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
