<SLUG> BC-HKONG-AUSTRALIA-TELECOM-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC CENTURY CYBERWORKS AND AUSTRALIA'S TELSTRA PLAN 2 MAJOR
DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Pacific Century CyberWorks Ltd. does not even own
Hong Kong's local telephone company yet. But the upstart is already
selling off chunks of it.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century said Wednesday it would sell 40 percent of the
mobile-phone business of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT to Telstra Corp., the
state-controlled phone company of Australia, for $1.5 billion.
Telstra will also invest $1.5 billion in Pacific Century to create
an alliance that its partners said would be Asia's leading provider
of Internet, data, wireless, and broadband communications services.
</P>
<P>
   Both transactions depend on Pacific Century's completion of its
huge acquisition of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT. That deal, which was
announced in late February and has been called into question by
Pacific Century's eroding share price, must be approved by HKT's
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Li, the 33-year-old who started Pacific Century
CyberWorks less than a year ago and has turned it into one of the
brightest stars in Asia's cyberspace, exuded confidence Wednesday.
``We have not been sitting around waiting for technical issues to
be settled in the merger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Li's chief lieutenant, Francis Yuen, predicted that Pacific
Century would gain the approval of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT's
shareholders without much trouble. And analysts in Hong Kong agreed
that shareholders would regard Telstra's investment as a vote of
confidence in the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacific Century is getting $3 billion from Telstra, which
should reassure Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT's shareholders that the deal
will go through,'' said Greg Feldberg, the head of Internet and
telecommunications research at Indosuez W.I. Carr Securities in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century, which owns a portfolio of investments in
Internet start-ups and is developing a satellite-delivered Internet
and television programming service, offered to buy HKT in a stock
deal initially worth more than $38 billion. But the company's
shares have been dragged down in the global sell-off of technology
stocks, and the offer is now valued at barely $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century's shares were suspended Wednesday before the
announcement of Telstra's investment. Some analysts predicted that
they would soar Thursday, since the shares of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT,
which now trade in tandem with Pacific Century, jumped 14 percent
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Telstra's planned investment has eased one big worry: That
Pacific Century would be swamped by $11.3 billion in debt after it
took over Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT. Li estimated that Telstra's $3
billion _ plus $2 billion already on the balance sheet of HKT and
another $2 billion on his company's balance sheet _ would enable
Pacific Century to whittle down the merged company's debt to $5
billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite its many financial benefits, Li preferred to focus on
the strategic implications of the alliance. He said Telstra and
Pacific Century would create two joint companies: a regional
mobile-telephone carrier and a wholesale carrier of voice, data,
and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Li said the carrier would immediately compete with international
players like Global Crossing and Level 3. And he said the partners
would take it public. The regional mobile-phone service, which will
be 60 percent-owned by Pacific Century, will include HKT's 900,000
subscribers. In addition to cash, Telstra will contribute an
undisclosed number of its cellular customers outside Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lofty multiples of recent cellular deals like
Vodaphone's acquisition of Mannesmann, some analysts said they were
not impressed by Pacific Century's deal. ``Hong Kong has a very
competitive mobile market, so perhaps the customers aren't worth as
much,'' said David Webb, a former investment banker who edits
Webb-site.com, an Internet service that tracks deals.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important than cash, Telstra will offer Pacific
Century another distribution channel for its ambitious Internet and
entertainment service. The service, dubbed Network of the World, is
to be introduced in India and China in July. Skeptics have
questioned whether Li will be able to attract an audience large
enough to justify his enormous investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacific Century has gone around the world looking for partners
who will expand the audience for Network of the World,'' Feldberg
said. ``It looks like Telstra will be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Telstra said it wanted to break out of its home
market and ally itself with a company that was perceived as being
on the leading edge of the information revolution. Telstra is still
51 percent-owned by the Australian government. But the government
sold off shares in mid-1998 and late 1999, and says it intends to
sell the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are unifying two large, capable companies who stand apart
from their competitors in being progressive,'' said Ziggy
Switkowksi, the chief executive of Telstra.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
