<SLUG> BC-UNILEVER-BEN&AMP;JERRYS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN &AMP; JERRY'S AGREES TO BE ACQUIRED BY UNILEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's, the quirky Vermont-based ice cream company that
made advancing socially responsible policies a crucial part of its
business strategy, agreed early Wednesday to be acquired by
Unilever PLC, a $50 billion global giant that already owns the
Breyer's and Good Humor ice cream brands.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever is paying $43.60 a share for Ben &AMP; Jerry's, making the
all-cash deal worth about $265.75 million, a significant premium on
Ben &AMP; Jerry's earlier share price, which by early afternoon jumped
$8.125, to $43.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever also said Wednesday that it was paying $2.6 billion for
Slim-Fast, the diet shake company based in West Palm Beach, Fla.
Slim-Fast controls 45 percent of the $1.3 billion nutritional
supplement and weight management market.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the deal for Ben &AMP; Jerry's appear to preserve the
unusual aspects of a company that has created a loyal following
over the years, creating a fund to help disadvantaged businesses,
contributing the same 7.5 percent of profits to an existing
foundation that works on causes like preserving the environment,
and keeping the company's operations in South Burlington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge win-win for all the constituents involved,'' said
Perry Odak, Ben &AMP; Jerry's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Antony Burgmans, the chairman of Unilever, said in an interview
that he pursued Ben &AMP; Jerry's to fill gaps in his company's product
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a situation where Unilever has the largest ice cream
manufacturing presence in the world, but no strategic presence in
the super-premium category,'' Burgmans said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIOBAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief issues facing Ben &AMP; Jerry's is its distribution
system in the United States, where it sells most of its flavors
like Cherry Garcia and Wavy Gravy. Until 1998, most of Ben &AMP;
Jerry's ice cream was distributed by Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream, an
Oakland, Calif.-based company that has a large share of the market.
Ben &AMP; Jerry's broke off the arrangement, which began in 1987, and
replaced it with one that relied on Haagen-Dazs, another big
competitor, as well as Dreyer's and some company-owned
distributors. Many analysts saw this arrangement as a
less-than-ideal solution.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly not a negative for Unilever,'' said Jeffrey
G. Kanter, a food stocks analyst for Prudential Securities on
Tuesday. ``Whether or not it becomes a home run remains to be seen.
Unilever is obviously looking at this for the long term. It's a
fair price for an asset with strong brand equity.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's, which had received takeover offers in the past,
issued an unusual statement in early December in which it said it
had received ``indications of interest'' and would be evaluating
them. The stock has risen since then from about $17 a share, and
people involved with the company, including several owners of
franchised ice-cream shops, said Ben &AMP; Jerry's appeared to be
taking the offers more seriously than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A big concern of the franchise owners has been whether a new
owner would preserve Ben &AMP; Jerry's commitment to social causes like
helping the homeless and conserving the environment. Unilever
maintains on its Web site that it is working to preserve clean
water resources and is involved with other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer's made an offer of $31 a share in February, according to
a copy of documents submitted with the offer. Two days later,
Meadowbrook Lane Capital submitted an offer of $32 a share. Both
were lower than the $40 a share that Unilever bid around the same
time, said a person familiar with the negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
