<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HDTV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HDTV IMAGES ARE THE BEST, BUT BE PREPARED FOR THE WORST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By ERIC A. TAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few people would fail to notice the extraordinary picture
quality created by high-definition television. Images from
standard-definition DVDs sparkle, while programs transmitted in
true high-definition format are as sharp and clear as if you were
looking through a window.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing new owners of these expensive digital TVs are
learning is that weak analog television signals, whether broadcast
over the air or transmitted by cable or satellite, may look even
worse on a $5,000 HDTV set than on an old $400 set.
</P>
<P>
   To make standard broadcasts approximate the quality of
high-definition transmissions, manufacturers of HDTV sets have used
line-doubling technology that fills in the blanks on the picture,
erasing the horizontal lines of a regular television image that are
so noticeable on very large screens. (HDTV broadcasts, with more
than twice the number of scanning lines for each frame, do not have
visible lines.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the technology not only doubles the lines but
also doubles picture ``noise'' like snow and wavy lines. If the
original transmission looks bad on a regular TV, the line-doubled
version will look even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely a true phenomenon,'' said Yves Faroudja,
whose company, Faroudja Laboratories, sells $6,000 line-doubling
equipment for sophisticated video installations. ``Line doubling
without precautions will give you a fuzzier picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Line-doubling systems work by comparing one line of the video
image with the line immediately below it, and then approximating
the picture information that should be in a line added between the
two.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's Digital Reality Creation technology compares each line
with a database of tens of thousands of digital video patterns and
picks one to approximate a high-definition image. Philips
Electronics, which will introduce several new picture tube HDTV
models this year, has the Digital Natural Motion system, which
analyzes the movement of each picture element and tries to
compensate for signal noise.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba's technology compares successive video lines but also
looks at the lines from the preceding video frame before deciding
which information to use to fill in the missing picture elements.
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of these systems is perfect. Before spending $2,500
or more for a digital or digital-ready television, it makes sense
to judge the quality of a regular broadcast, cable or satellite
signal on the high-definition set, not just a high-definition
transmission or a DVD movie.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to turn off line doubling would seem to make sense,
but manufacturers say the additional circuitry needed to disable
the doubling technology would add to the cost of an already
expensive piece of equipment. ``The question is, is line structure
more objectionable than a softer picture,'' said Foy Wilkey, a
product manager for Thomson Multimedia, the French company that
manufactures RCA and Proscan TVs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could only receive noisy television pictures, I'd think
twice before buying a digital television,'' said Linda Schumann,
director of television product planning for Philips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0210 </DOCNO>
