<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER13-COX     04-12 1589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: For log cabin Republicans, maybe next time
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush and the Log Cabin Republicans, a gay group, have
forged a truce as Bush prepares to meet with other gay Republicans
today. Bush excluded Log Cabin leaders from the meeting because
they supported John McCain in the primaries. But Richard Tafel, the
group's executive director, said Bush aides have assured him of
likely inclusion in future sessions. Bush spokesman Scott McClellan
, however, would say only that ``there have been discussions.''
Among those invited today are Carl Schmid, an alternate GOP
convention delegate from Washington, D.C.; former Rep. Steve
Gunderson (R-Wis.); Plattsburgh, N.Y., Mayor Dan Stewart; and D.C.
Councilman David Catania. Said Schmid: ``I think the important
thing is what is talked about, and not exactly which people are in
the room.''
</P>
<P>
   BEG YOUR PARDON?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, asked by newspaper editors Wednesday about a pardon for
President Clinton stemming from the Whitewater and Monica Lewinsky
investigation, said Clinton has effectively eliminated the
possibility that he would pardon himself or accept one. ``He said
publicly some time ago that he would neither request nor accept a
pardon. That is the answer to that question,'' Gore said. Laura
Quinn, Gore's communications director, said afterward that Gore
believes Clinton ``has taken (the pardon option) off the table'' by
saying he would refuse to accept one.
</P>
<P>
   I USED TO BE A NEWSPAPER MAN MYSELF
</P>
<P>
   A day after George W. Bush proposed tax credits to help working
people buy health insurance, Al Gore accused his rival of
``political malpractice'' Wednesday at the annual conference of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors in Washington. He prodded the
editors to give Bush's proposals a close examination. ``I worked in
journalism long enough (''The Tennessean'' in Nashville) to know
that some claims demand serious scrutiny,'' Gore said. Bush ``wants
us to believe he's committed to issues like education, health care
and the environment. Let's face it, the Bush approach on these
issues is a headline without a story.''
</P>
<P>
   BILLIONS FOR HEALTH IN REMOTE AREAS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush followed up his $42 billion ``New Prosperity
Initiative'' Wednesday with a five-year, $4.3 billion proposal to
expand health care in underserved and remote areas. The cornerstone
is a $3.6 billion proposal to add 1,200 community and migrant
health centers across the country, raising the total to 4,200. Bush
also wants to overhaul the National Health Services Corps to better
place health care providers in areas of shortage. The newest
proposal, called ``Strengthening the Health Care Safety Net,''
would provide $500 million in grants over five years for
communities to establish pilot health care programs.
</P>
<P>
   FOOT-IN-MOUTH DISEASE ?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was working hard to walk away from remarks made
by Texas Health Commissioner William R. Archer III, a Bush-approved
appointee who was quoted as suggesting Hispanics are primarily
responsible for the state's high teen birthrate. Archer issued an
apologetic press release, which read in part: ``I deeply regret
that I have created an erroneous impression about Hispanics and
teen pregnancy.'' Previously, though, he said that teen pregnancy
was hard to limit among Hispanics because they didn't believe
``that getting pregnant is a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   JESSE WILL EAT, BUT WON'T ENDORSE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is getting together with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura at
a private dinner Wednesday night at home in Washington. Aides to
both said their meeting would be as much a social opportunity for
them and their wives as a chance to talk issues. But a coveted
endorsement by Ventura, the nation's best-known independent
officeholder, was not in the works for today: ``It just won't
happen,'' said Ventura spokesman John Wodele. After dinner, Gore
heads for Charlotte, N.C., to make good on the rain check he gave a
middle school when he canceled a visit there last week to stay in
Washington and be with a sick friend.
</P>
<P>
   CASH AS THE APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was stimulating his appetite before dinner with Jesse
Ventura by raking in some cash. He was joining fund-raising pro
Terry McAuliffe at an intimate meeting Wednesday to rally other
prominent Democrats to raise money for the party's Aug. 14-17
national convention in Los Angeles. He also was holding forth at a
small, $500,000 luncheon at the Washington home of former New York
Rep. Tom Downey, now a government consultant whose clients include
Microsoft. On Saturday, he and President Clinton are to campaign
together for the first time this year to court big-money
contributors assembled by Hollywood moguls David Geffen and Steven
Spielberg in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   AND CASH FOR DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore kicked off his week of multimillion-dollar fund-raising
for the Democratic National Committee with a dinner last night at
the Mayflower Hotel in Washington. Andrew Tobias, the financial
writer who is treasurer of the committee, was the host of the
dinner, where 50 people paid $20,000 each, raising $1 million for
the party.
</P>
<P>
   HARD POSITION ON SOFT MONEY
</P>
<P>
   John McCain vowed to boycott a record Republican fund-raiser and
salute for George W. Bush. McCain, a leading voice for campaign
finance reform, said he'll stay away from the April 26 gala in
Washington because much of the $15 million raised will be
unregulated ``soft money.'' ``I won't have anything to do with soft
money,'' McCain said. Bush is to be the featured speaker at the
fund-raiser, expected to draw more than 1,000 people, including
many members of Congress and governors. Even though he isn't going,
McCain said he remains a loyal party member committed to reducing
the influence of money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN HAS ROLE FOR HOFFA
</P>
<P>
   Sharing a stage with unlikely allies, the Reform Party's Pat
Buchanan promised protesting Teamsters Wednesday that he would
appoint union President James Hoffa to his Cabinet and oppose
normal U.S. trade relations with China. Approving such status for
China, which President Clinton wants, would hand American jobs and
money to a nation with a poor human rights record, Buchanan told
several thousand Teamsters gathered in the Capitol's shadow.
``There's something that unites us all. It's the belief that
citizens of the United States are citizens first before they're
consumers and there are values higher than money,'' Buchanan said.
``This battle's about the American family.''
</P>
<P>
   FINALISTS SET IN TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   A retired military lawyer, Gene Kelly, won the Democratic
nomination to run against Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison in
November. In runoff elections, Kelly beat ex-state Rep. Charles
Gandy, and state Rep. John Culberson defeated businessman Peter
Wareing in a bitterly fought Republican runoff for the seat of GOP
Rep. Bill Archer, who is retiring. Hutchison is an odds-on
favorite, and Democrat Jeff Sells, who won outright last month, is
expected to provide Kelly only token opposition in the
predominantly Republican district in November.
</P>
<P>
   PARENTAL DISCRETION, _ AND NOT JUST FOR TV
</P>
<P>
   Mothers and fathers could become a critical swing vote if Al
Gore can't close what might be called a ``parent gap'' between
himself and George W. Bush. Interviewed by The Associated Press at
shopping centers, schoolyards and diners across the Midwest and
into New Jersey, parents have been saying that Clinton
administration scandals have dimmed their view of Gore. Many
parents said promises by Bush to improve schools and the
environment have made it easier for them to reject Gore _ at least
for now. One typical example: Phoebe Cairo, a 40-year-old single
mother in suburban Cleveland who normally votes Democratic, said
there is a ``strong possibility'' she'll back Bush.
</P>
<P>
   PRODDING TO TAKE A STAND
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton asserted that Rudy Giuliani was avoiding
discussion of how he would vote in the Senate, and said it is not
enough to ask voters to judge him based solely on his record as
mayor of New York, as Giuliani has suggested. ``I am running a
campaign that will tell you what I will do,'' Clinton said in a
hall packed with municipal workers in Albany. Giuliani has
discussed these issues, but only in a limited way and only in
response to questions. He has yet to give a major policy speech in
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   GRAMS AGAINST THE LAWYERS
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Sen. Rod Grams, a Republican facing a tough
re-election battle, also has had to contend with tough TV
advertising. Issue ads sponsored in part by the Association of
Trial Lawyers of America attacked Grams for supporting legislation
that would make it harder for victims of asbestos-related illnesses
to sue asbestos companies. Grams accused the lawyers of attempted
blackmail and bribery, saying a lobbyist left a taped telephone
message suggesting the ads wouldn't run if Grams dropped his
sponsorship of the bill. Grams' office says the Justice Department
will investigate. The lawyers' group dismissed Grams' charge as
``not only absurd, but libelous on its face.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
