<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DEAFNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING IMPLANT WITH A GENTLE TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By DANIEL SORID   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A novel variation of an implantable device that has brought
hearing to tens of thousands of deaf people could soon make speech
more understandable for people who are hard of hearing, who
sometimes get little help from today's hearing aids.
</P>
<P>
   The new device, a type of cochlear implant, goes beyond the
basic sound amplification achieved through traditional hearing aids
to help people with partial hearing loss, and it seems to work
while protecting the patient's natural hearing. But its value has
yet to be proved because at this stage of the research, it has been
used by only a few people.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who lose their hearing _ often from aging, disease
or overexposure to noise _ first lose the ability to hear
high-frequency sounds, like the sound of the consonants ``s'' and
``d.'' That can make understanding conversation almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The broad amplification of analog hearing aids serves little
purpose for patients who have trouble hearing high-frequency
sounds, although many of them may be helped by digital hearing aids
that amplify only the high-frequency sounds. And people with
partial hearing loss who have standard cochlear implants can find
that their remaining natural hearing is endangered.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers at the University of Iowa are experimenting with
a cochlear device that may be able to restore only high-frequency
sounds without destroying the patient's ability to hear other
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   In normal hearing, sound is processed in the cochlea, a tube
that is curled in a spiral like a nautilus shell and contains the
organs of hearing. Sound wave vibrations are conducted to the
cochlea, where they lead to movements of the fluid, hair cells and
membranes inside. Then hair cells send nerve signals to the brain.
Hair cells in deeper areas of the cochlea respond to low-frequency
sounds, while cells in the area closer to the opening process
high-frequency sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Most cochlear implants include an electrode array that occupies
most of the cochlea's spiral and, behind the ear, a microphone. A
box where the signals are processed is worn on a belt or behind the
ear. The device designed at the University of Iowa uses a shorter
array of electrodes that occupies only part of the cochlea and is
intended to augment only the areas that are involved in processing
high-frequency sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Iowa device is designed to restore
high-frequency hearing without destroying the natural hearing
ability. The shorter electrode array does not need to be threaded
through the entire cochlea, which minimizes damage.
</P>
<P>
   When a longer electrode array is inserted in a regular implant,
that can injure delicate membranes, destroying the ear's ability to
process sounds naturally. And the shorter electrode component also
reduces the risk that the array will push against parts of the
cochlea that need to vibrate freely to work.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Iowa device was designed by Dr. Bruce Gantz,
head of the university's department of otolaryngology. In three
implants completed as part of a feasibility study, he said, the
natural hearing of low-frequency sounds was maintained while the
patients' ability to recognize consonants was improved.
</P>
<P>
   After the implant, one patient reported hearing someone say
``sh,'' Gantz recalled. ``This person said, `I haven't heard that
for years,''' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if we'll be able to integrate that into helping
them understand words,'' Gantz said. ``If it will, it would be a
major advancement for people with moderate to severe hearing loss
that have very poor word understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people that have progressive hearing loss from
aging or noise exposure always start with high-frequency loss. We
say that there are 28 million people that have hearing loss in this
country. That means there's a whole host of people that have
high-range hearing loss that causes communication problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who are most likely to develop high-frequency hearing
loss include farmers, factory workers and musicians, who are all
exposed to loud noises. That kind of hearing problem can also be
caused by illnesses and often affects the aging.
</P>
<P>
   The definition of which patients can benefit from cochlear
implants is expanding as the Cochlear Corp., which built the
short-electrode-array implants for the University of Iowa, and the
several other developers of cochlear implants make more innovative
and efficient cochlear devices, even though cochlear implants with
standard electrode arrays put a patient's natural hearing at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criteria for implantation have been relaxed,'' said Dr.
Chris van den Honert, director of research at the Cochlear Corp. in
Englewood, Colo., part of Cochlear Ltd., based in Australia. ``It's
really an acknowledgment of a trend in the entire industry toward
implantation of people with less and less hearing loss. Ten or 15
years ago, someone had to be completely deaf to qualify as a
candidate for a cochlear implant.''
</P>
<P>
   The short-electrode-array implant is a good thing, said Dr. Peg
Williams, executive director of the Cochlear Implant Association, a
nonprofit group for implant recipients, their families and
researchers. ``It stands to help a whole new generation of people
that have not had help before by the use of cochlear implants,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Research on the device is still preliminary; even if the device
continues to show promise, clinical trials will probably not begin
for another year or two. But one sign of hope is that the brain
seems able to handle auditory stimulation from both natural and
artificial processes in interpreting speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought it would be difficult for the brain to
integrate acoustic and electrical processing because electrical
processing is much more rapid to the nerve,'' Gantz said. ``These
people don't seem to have a problem with that. There doesn't seem
to be any delay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
