<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4825 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-STADIUMS(2TAKES)-     04-12 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STADIUMS(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GAME IN TOWN: DATABASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The national pastime has fallen prey to the national obsession _
technology. While the game itself is relatively unchanged since the
19th century, computers have changed nearly everything else about
baseball. And teams from the majors to the minors are going digital
to lure fans to technically sophisticated new ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are most apparent at the three new major-league
parks that have opened in the past week: Enron Field in Houston
(Astros), Comerica Park in Detroit (Tigers) and Pacific Bell Park
in San Francisco (Giants). These parks are designed to evoke the
cozy feeling of old-time stadiums, with lots of brick and exposed
steel beams. But inside, the stadiums practically hum with
technology. Fiber optic networks handle torrents of data flowing
from voice and data links, concession stands, scoreboards, security
cameras, sound systems, interactive kiosks and video production
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Many clubs now have information managers, and the teams are
collecting so much data about fans _ not to mention players _ that
the game is almost becoming a new sport, databaseball. From various
places in the new ballparks, a fan can call up statistics on a
player, a player can call up video archives of an opponent, and the
owner can call up statistics on the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Even older parks are swinging for the fences with technology,
preparing giant LED (light-emitting diodes) video scoreboards for
the arrival of high-definition television, wiring suites and
premium seats for Internet access and offering Internet-based
services to fans.
</P>
<P>
   These new technologies add millions of dollars to the cost of
the stadiums. But the technologies are also designed to squeeze
more money out of fans and sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   All the major-league teams have Web sites where fans can check
the schedule, order tickets, buy team merchandise, listen to the
game over Internet radio, chat with other fans, get the latest team
news and information, subscribe to electronic mailing lists,
download pictures of their favorite players and even get a job (the
New York Yankees are looking for a stadium watchman).
</P>
<P>
   Internet access is a standard feature in the luxury suites that
are now built into every new stadium. And many baseball parks are
also considering adding Internet-access kiosks throughout the
stadium for fans in the cheaper sections.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next few years, with the Internet becoming an integral
part of fans' lives, Internet and e-mail access will be seen as a
necessity rather than as a luxury at sports stadiums,'' said
Matthew Freedman, editor of Team Marketing Report.
</P>
<P>
   SMART SEATS
</P>
<P>
   Tropicana Field in St. Petersburg, Fla., the domed stadium that
is the home of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, may take the prize for
electronic distractions. Mounted on swivel arms on the expensive
seats behind home plate are liquid crystal displays that deliver an
interactive software service called ChoiceSeat.
</P>
<P>
   The service lets fans call up photos, scouting reports and
statistics for any player; to see a graphical representation of the
position, type and speed of every pitch; to view replays from
different camera angles; to follow scores of other games; and even
to watch the regular live TV broadcast of the game in front of them
_ just like at home.
</P>
<P>
   If they choose, fans in the smart seats can shop for official
team merchandise, vote for All-Star selections and play a trivia
game or bingo. Of all the services available, including statistics
and game scores, bingo is the most popular, a team spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   (Technology and baseball do not always mix at Tropicana. Last
year a radio-controlled video blimp went haywire on its maiden
flight and nearly crashed into the pitcher's mound.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps surprisingly, there are no smart seats at the three new
ballparks. The Giants held focus groups and polled their fans, many
of whom work for Silicon Valley high-tech companies, and the fans
balked at smart seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said part of the reason they come to the park is to
concentrate on the game and leave the computer at the office,''
said Sandy Eeds, vice president and project manager for HOK Sports
of Kansas City, Mo., which designed all three parks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other teams building new stadiums, the Giants chose not
to wire the seats. ``Why invest in conduit when we can go wireless
later?'' Eeds said. With Pacific Bell as a sponsor, wireless data
access may be in the ballpark's future. Concession workers who send
hot dog and beer orders from the premium seats to the concession
stands already use it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FAN LOYALTY PROGRAMS
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of baseball stadiums now have database-driven fan loyalty
programs that reward frequent ballpark visitors for attending games
and buying refreshments and merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   They work like this: Fans sign up for the team's program either
on the Internet or at any of the interactive kiosks at the ballpark
and receive a plastic identification card that has a magnetic
stripe capable of storing information. Fans accrue points by
swiping the card at a kiosk each time they attend a game or buy a
hot dog. The points can be redeemed for items like free or
discounted game tickets or team jackets. At certain thresholds, the
points earn the fan the opportunity to attend autograph sessions
with the players, do a half inning of play-by-play announcing on
the radio broadcast of the game and even play catch or take batting
practice with the team before the game. The rewards tend to be more
extravagant at minor-league ballparks, which traditionally are more
aggressive in their promotions. AIM Technologies of Austin, Texas,
created the FanCard loyalty kiosks used by more than 40
professional baseball teams.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The use of fan-loyalty cards, the Internet and bar-coded tickets
allows team owners to know more about the fans than ever before.
And it is not just what games the fans attend, when and where they
arrive at the stadium and how many hot dogs they buy. Web sites
connect the teams to the fans in ways never possible before. As a
condition for gaining FanCard points and receiving discount coupons
at the stadium, the fans have to answer questions on a touch-screen
display, including questions that the team will use to plan things
like future promotions, concession sales and staffing.
</P>
<P>
   TICKET TURNSTILES
</P>
<P>
   At Pacific Bell Park, the technology begins at the gate, where
electronic turnstiles include bar code readers. Each ticket is
printed with a unique bar code stripe that not only helps to
control counterfeit tickets (Giants tickets are in such high demand
that all but a few of the 81 home games are already sold out) but
also sends valuable information to a central attendance server
computer.
</P>
<P>
   By tracking the bar codes as the turnstiles read them, the club
gets precise, instant counts on attendance and traffic patterns,
which in turn enables the redeployment of ushers, concession
workers, kegs of beer and even extra mobile turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   Lost or stolen tickets can be ``turned off,'' or invalidated, by
the computer, and new tickets can be issued.
</P>
<P>
   By midseason, said Bill Schlough, a Giants vice president and
chief information officer, the club hopes to be able to allow
season-ticket holders who cannot attend a game to call or e-mail
the box office, turn off their tickets and let the club resell the
seats (splitting the money, no doubt). Doing so will not be as
lucrative for the ticket holder as scalping the tickets outside the
stadium or selling them on eBay, but it will certainly be more
convenient.
</P>
<P>
   If a season-ticket holder misses several games, the club can get
in touch with that person to find out why, all in the interest of
providing improved customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are talking with Ticketmaster and other high-tech
companies about a plan to enable fans to buy tickets over the
Internet and print their tickets on a home printer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ultimate vision is that you shouldn't need to have a
ticket at all,'' Schlough said. ``The technology is moving to a
stored-value card.'' A stored-value card, he explained, could be
encoded with the digital equivalents of game tickets and cash. It
would be swiped at the turnstile, at a concession stand or at a
souvenir stand.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCOREBOARDS
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has come a long way from the mechanical scoreboards
still being used at Chicago's historic Wrigley Field, home of the
Cubs (and, in a nice touch of tradition, at Pacific Bell). Modern
video scoreboards are huge. The one at Comerica in Detroit is 204
feet wide, the same size as a 10-story building across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Older video displays were made up of collections of cathode ray
tubes, like regular television sets. The newer ones have switched
to light-emitting diodes, or LEDs, which yield better-quality
video, use less electricity and last longer.
</P>
<P>
   The giant video screen in Houston will be capable of receiving
high-definition television signals when that emerging technology is
ready, said Ron Baker, senior associate at Wrightson Johnson Haddon
Williams, a Dallas design company. In Detroit, the scoreboards are
controlled from a video production room where more than a dozen
technicians work during the game.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboards are also revenue machines. Using a variety of
recent technologies that allow advertisements to be cycled
throughout the game, an electronic billboard can have more than a
dozen sponsors. In Detroit, the $10 million scoreboard system has
the potential to generate $2 million a year in advertising revenue,
said Michael Delano, the team owner's representative.
</P>
<P>
   SOUND SYSTEMS
</P>
<P>
   Most stadiums have replaced their old, echo-producing speakers
with modern sound systems. At Enron Field in Houston, more than 400
speakers are distributed throughout the stadium, backed by more
than 100 power amplifiers that can make between-innings music
really rock.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing the speakers closer to the fans has made announcements
clearer, and the sound is synchronized with the scoreboard video
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stadium sound systems are as good as the stereo
systems in the fans' homes,'' said Robert D. Wyatt, a vice
president of the Barton Malow Co., which helped develop parks
including Enron Field, Camden Yards in Baltimore and Coors Field in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Enron has radio headsets that amplify sound for hearing-impaired
fans and a full-time stenographer to transcribe announcements for a
closed-caption display system. During breaks in the action, the
same board can be used to display scrolling stock quotes (a feature
appreciated by the millionaire players as well as the fans, no
doubt). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   Fans are not the only ones enjoying the technology. At the park
in San Francisco, bouquets of satellite dishes pull down video
feeds from other games and store videos of opponents in a 750-disc
DVD jukebox. Remote-control video cameras record every pitch and
at-bat from multiple angles, to help players dissect and refine
their games. Computer-based simulators and exercise equipment keep
players in top shape. Some managers say that technology alone could
add a few extra victories per season.
</P>
<P>
   And that would be good for the fans _ the ones that pay
attention to the game, that is. In Houston, young fans can
entertain themselves playing Sega video games or watching a genuine
steam locomotive that appears to pull the retractable roof open and
shut. Boys of a more distant summer can try the video batting cages
or clock their fastballs with a radar gun. Detroit has a Ferris
wheel, a carousel and ``liquid fireworks'' _ a computer-controlled
water fountain that sends choreographed jets of colored water 120
feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   To help pay for all of that technology, clubs are raising ticket
prices sharply this year. In Detroit, a family of four can expect
to pay about $165 for an afternoon at the ballpark (four
average-price tickets, four small sodas, two beers, four hot dogs,
two programs and two caps _ carousel rides and Internet access not
included) .
</P>
<P>
   No wonder most parks have added cash machines, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
