<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-TAXES13-COX     04-12 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCAIN DELAYS BILL ON INTERNET TAXES
 &HT;    550&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yielding to pressure from state officials and
traditional retailers, Senate Commerce Committee Chairman John
McCain, R-Ariz., Wednesday postponed a vote on his bill to extend
the federal moratorium on new Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advocates of increasing the tax burden on the public have
prevailed in having (the bill) removed'' from the committee's
agenda, McCain said. He promised to renew his fight later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's debate among committee members showed just how
tough that battle may be, as several fellow Republicans argued in
favor of allowing states to require online retailers to collect
taxes, just as traditional retailers do now.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas took an especially hard line,
warning that unless states continue to get large flows of revenue
from sales taxes, they will look to income taxes to fund schools,
police and other basic services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spilled some blood in my state to avoid having a state
income tax,'' she said. If consumers are allowed to avoid paying
sales taxes by shopping on line, ``I can see a drumbeat beginning
for a state income tax, which I am going to fight to the death,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   A ban on Internet sales taxes not only could harm states, but
would also undermine traditional merchants who collect and remit
sales taxes, she argued. ``A retailer paying taxes that support the
community should not have an unfair competitive disadvantage,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, McCain wanted Congress to permanently bar states
from requiring Internet-based retailers to collect taxes on
purchases, regardless of whether customers lived out of state. But
in recent months, he has faced stiffening opposition from state
leaders and traditional retailers who want their online and
mail-order counterparts to bear an equal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, McCain has backed off from a permanent ban,
pushing instead for a five-year extension of a tax moratorium now
set to expire in October 2001. Until recently, such an extension
seemed likely to speed through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Leavitt, the Republican governor of Utah and
chairman of the National Governors' Association, has coordinated a
campaign to get state, county and city officials to oppose a
lengthy moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony to the Commerce Committee on Wednesday, Leavitt
submitted a letter signed by 36 governors calling on Congress to
refrain from prohibiting states from imposing tax collection duties
on online companies, saying that would be unfair to Main Street
merchants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would put the federal government in the position of both
picking winners and losers,'' the governors said in their letter.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt's efforts have been bolstered by the lobbying muscle of
many traditional retailers, such as Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. and J.C.
Penney Inc.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, argued that ``if each state and local
jurisdiction attempts to impose its own business regulations and
taxes to it, the opportunities presented by this new economic
engine (the Internet) will be destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt agreed the current patchwork of sales taxes ``is a
mess,'' but said states should be given a year or two to radically
simplify their tax rates and rules.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While McCain's committee was meeting, the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce was formally presenting its report to the
Republican leaders of Congress. Gov. James Gilmore, the Republican
governor of Virginia and the panel's chairman, handed over his
report to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and House Speaker
Dennis Hastert on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was charged by Congress with making
recommendations on Internet sales tax policy. When it failed to
reach the prescribed two-thirds votes to make a recommendation,
Lott told Gilmore he would accept a ``report'' based on a simple
majority.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 11-8, the panel approved a plan to extend the tax
moratorium until 2006, repeal a 3 percent telecommunications excise
tax and provide tax exemptions for certain Internet-based
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, the leader of the majority voting bloc, said sales
taxes on online purchases are unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states and localities are awash with cash,'' he said.
``There is more money that is being raised in terms of revenue in
taxation, more money that is being spent than has ever been before
in the history of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert praised the report and said he hopes to move bills
implementing its provisions ``early this year.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.e-fairness.org.
www.ecommercecommission.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
