<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     04-12 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF AN ONLINE APPLESAUCE THIEF
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  NEW YORK _ I had been cheating Priceline's online grocery service
for months, and worse, no one seemed to care.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, it was just applesauce. A few months ago, with all but
one item on my list already in my shopping cart (along with my
2-year-old), I still needed applesauce. To get my prearranged
discount from Priceline, I had agreed to buy Musselman's. I scanned
the shelves. No Musselman's.
</P>
<P>
   As a Priceline veteran, I knew the rules: no Musselman's, no
discount. But instead I reached out, fingered the labels on the
applesauce, took a jar of Mott's and, coupon in hand, made my way
to the checkout register.
</P>
<P>
   I will not try to make excuses. It does not matter, for
instance, that I was planning to make potato pancakes for supper
and desperately needed that applesauce or that my daughter was
biting into an apple that had not yet been paid for and yelling,
``Get-me-Tic-Tacs-now-now-now,'' at a volume more typically heard
at a rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   My heart was pounding as I checked out. No one stopped me or
seemed to notice the difference. But I knew my violation struck at
the very heart of Priceline's business model, which is to pit
competitive manufacturers against each other by giving discounts to
shoppers who don't care what brand they buy. And I knew switching
brands meant that Musselman's was giving me a discount for buying
Mott's.
</P>
<P>
   I became a repeat offender a short time later when I took an
unauthorized can of Bumblebee tuna instead of the Starkist that I
had promised to buy. Then I substituted Glad sandwich bags for
Ziploc. Ruffles instead of Tostitos.
</P>
<P>
   The more I did it, the more guilty I felt. Then one night last
week, after consuming a large number of Ruffles, I found myself
unable to sleep. Was it guilt or the grease from the chips? I
cannot say. I only knew, the next morning, that I needed
absolution. So I phoned Kevin Goldman, a spokesman for
Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise, he told me that Priceline was aware of my
behavior. The company keeps transaction logs to track the items
shoppers take home. After checking the logs for my purchases,
Goldman pointed out that I had failed to mention the time I took
Progresso soup after promising to buy Campbell's. (I had forgotten
that one.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't care?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do care,'' he said. ``At this time, it's not worth our
resources to spend the time to have the computer system go back and
flag every single person who takes the wrong soup and send them
e-mail about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is hard to know exactly whom I am cheating.
Priceline's discounts are subsidized in three ways: by
manufacturers, of course, but also by sponsors who offer half-price
tokens to shoppers who fill out marketing surveys and by Priceline
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline has not disclosed exactly how much of the money it is
spending to attract customers. But Goldman said the company hoped
to recoup much of the cost after it started to charge the
advertised $3 monthly service fee (which is being waived for now).
</P>
<P>
   Then Goldman asked me to please not do it again: ``Ninety-nine
percent of consumers obey our rules.'' He paused. ``You know,
Michelle, most people are honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, I needed help. So I phoned some medical professionals,
the sort of people who specialize in analyzing the behavior of
(let's not mince words) liars, sneaks and cheats.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing I learned was that my behavior is not as deviant
as I had feared. ``Many people are clearly and easily willing to
act out some minor kind of deception when the risk of getting
caught is not large,'' said David Nyberg, a professor of education
and medicine at the State University of New York at Buffalo and the
author of ``The Varnished Truth: Truth Telling and Deceiving in
Ordinary Life'' (University of Chicago Press, 1993). ``One-third to
one-half of all Americans in all subcategories admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   But I wouldn't cheat a live merchant. Why would I cheat
Priceline?
</P>
<P>
   ``The anonymity makes it easier to cheat,'' said Charles Ford, a
professor of psychiatry at the University of Alabama at Birmingham
and the author of ``Lies! Lies!! Lies!!!: The Psychology of
Deceit'' (American Psychiatric Press, 1996). ``When you cheat
Priceline, who are you cheating? The degree to which people will
tell the truth is to a large extent determined by the personal bond
they have to the individual they are dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   The real issue, apparently, was that I clearly resented
Priceline and that I was acting out in the supermarket. But why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they make you feel cheap?'' Dr. Ford asked gently.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he mentioned it, I did resent that I had to draw
attention to myself by separating my Priceline purchases, slowing
the checkout line. And come to think of it, I had a few quibbles
with how arbitrary the service seemed. Some days, for example, it
would grant me discounts on peanut butter and jelly, but the next
time I would get only the jelly.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of thinking led me to wonder if I could beat the
system. I phoned Goldman again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot beat the system,'' he said. (I think he was getting
a little sick of me.) ``When you say you want to buy an item, there
are these companies who make brands who want your business, and the
question is how much business do they want at this price at that
moment in time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One more thing,'' I said meekly. ``You know what makes me
angry? The way my ability to buy certain products, like fruits and
vegetables, is restricted. I can only buy those things on Priceline
if I agree to use half-price tokens, but I don't want to fill out
the surveys it takes to get the tokens.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said many distributors of produce did not compete by
brand so there were no manufacturers to give me discounts. ``But
you still want the apples, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   He knew I did. He had, after all, pulled my transaction logs and
knew that my family ate 10 or more apples a week. He probably even
knew that my daughter bit into at least one of those apples before
it was paid for.
</P>
<P>
   But what he might not have known (or was too polite to mention)
was that I also had misused Priceline tokens. A few weeks ago, I
had a token to buy Valencia oranges for 15 cents apiece. But
instead of taking the Valencia oranges, I picked up five of the
more luscious _ and, at 99 cents each, more expensive _ blood
oranges. The cashier didn't bat an eye.
</P>
<P>
   There, I feel much better. This confession stuff really works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
