<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS13-COX     04-12 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE REPUBLICANS PROPOSE MEDICARE DRUG BENEFIT
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans offered their own version of a
Medicare drug plan Wednesday that relies on private insurance with
federal subsidies for the poor. The Clinton administration said the
plan doesn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP proposal is an alternative to a plan Clinton put forward
during his State of the Union message in January and heightens the
possibility a prescription drug benefit under Medicare will be
enacted this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, the federal health program for 40 million elderly and
disabled Americans, does not cover prescription drugs, which are
covered by most major private health insurance plans.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing the high stakes both sides have attached to a
prescription drug benefit, the GOP proposal was unveiled by House
Speaker Dennis Hastert along with key Republican members of the
Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a balanced and responsible prescription drug plan
which permits market forces _ not regulations and price controls _
to offer Medicare beneficiaries more choices and lower drug
prices,'' said Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan, like the Clinton plan, would be open and voluntary
to all Medicare beneficiaries. It differs in two major ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Clinton plan, once it is fully implemented in 2009, would
cover half of all drug costs up to $5,000 for all beneficiaries.
The GOP plan would cover all drug costs that exceed a yet-to-be
determined amount.
</P>
<P>
   _ Under the Clinton plan, prescription drugs would be covered
directly by Medicare, similar to doctor and hospital coverage.
Under the GOP proposal, the federal government would pay the
private insurance premiums of elderly patients with incomes 150
percent of less than the poverty level _ now $12,600 for an
individual and $17,000 for a couple.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan envisions that Medicare beneficiaries would pay
lower prescription drug costs because the insurance plans would be
able to make deals for reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
   A study released this week by the Clinton administration
indicated that Medicare patients pay 15 percent more for drugs than
those covered by private insurers who have negotiated better
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would pump $300 billion of the projected federal
surplus over the next 10 years into the Medicare program, including
$160 billion for the drug benefit. In addition, Clinton would spend
$35 billion to offer a catastrophic drug benefit, which would cover
all costs above an undecided amount.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan would earmark $40 billion over five years
for the drug benefit and to help shore up the Medicare program,
which federal actuaries say will remain financially healthy until
2023.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton health policy adviser Chris Jennings said the
administration was ``disappointed that (the Republican plan's)
provisions don't match up with the rhetoric of how it's being
described.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said there were substantial questions about whether
insurers would offer prescription drug coverage and, if so, how
much the premiums would cost and how much of a benefit they would
provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it should be available and affordable to all. They
can't assure that anyone will have access to any benefit, let along
an affordable one,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   Horace B. Deets, executive director of AARP, the nation's
largest organization of Americans aged 50 and over, said the GOP
plan ``has merit and should be explored carefully and fully.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
