<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DEAD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-12 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEING DEAD': THE LIFE AFTER DEATH OF A PAIR NOT YET GONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Celice and Joseph, middle-aged zoologists, revisit the desolate
beach dunes where they first made love 30 years earlier and attempt
an anniversary reprise. A drifter shadows them, bludgeons them to
death with a rock and takes off with the few possessions they'd
brought along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bodies were discovered straight away,'' the next chapter
unremarkably begins. Immediately come the whiplash words: ``A
beetle first,'' followed by this initial discoverer's struggle to
crawl out from under Celice and Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Other discoverers arrive: a gull pecking at Celice's shoes,
flies ``lined up like fishermen along the banks of the bodies' open
wounds,'' and crabs ``already laboring through their exaggerated
countrysides toward the corpses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being Dead'' records the viewpoints of beetle, gull, crabs and
flies. It notes briefly the thoughts of the killer, of whom we hear
no more. Mainly it speaks of and for Celice and Joseph at the time
they met, through the years of their marriage, and on their last
day alive.
</P>
<P>
   It voices as well, weirdly, the point of view of their gradually
decomposing bodies during the six days before they are discovered
by the police. It speaks for the beach grass, the sand, the wind;
and pretty much for life, death and the universe at large.
</P>
<P>
   Restrain a natural impulse to dismiss this as mystic
pantheistics addled with goriness. Though not widely known in the
United States, Crace is one of Britain's most remarkable writers,
and has been for the past couple of decades. He is unique, as well.
Two inflated adjectives, but what they denote in tandem is that
Crace is a novelist able to precipitate large and cloudy themes
into slashes of a particular, revivifying rain.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Gift of Stones'' he brought close up the distant light
and melancholy sunset of a Stone Age people faced with the advent
of artificers in bronze. In ``Quarantine'' _ winner of Britain's
Whitbread Prize and a Booker finalist _ he wrote of a variegated
collection of desert refugees who spend 40 days as neighbors to an
annoying, seemingly hysterical young man: Jesus, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Prehistory, religion: Crace's allegories make disconcerting and
tangible fictions of impalpable realms. His humans set in
strangeness are not us; we might be them, though, if bent and made
strange.
</P>
<P>
   The realm of Crace's new novel is the strangest of all. It is
death, or more exactly, it is the life in death and the death in
life. For the former there are the flies' and crabs' assorted meals
_ for a moment we seem conjured into a sort of restaurant review _
and the minute day-by-day charting of the changes in the two bodies
on the beach. Not the bodies that were, but the bodies that still
are Celice and Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   What ought to be grisly is strangely not. Reverent, if anything,
and thanks to Crace's ability to set up human habitation in taboo
territory, almost beautiful. The Latin saying ``Nothing human is
alien to me,'' he extends to ``Nothing human is dead to me, not
even death.''
</P>
<P>
   While Crace is imparting life, even jaunty life, to dissolution
he is introducing death repeatedly into the knottily individual
lives of Celice, Joseph and those they know. Celice tells her
students that whereas single-celled organisms, dividing again and
again, are essentially immortal, ``death is the price we pay for
being multi-celled.'' She ends her slide lecture holding a
rectangle of white light on the screen and announcing: ``You're
dying now. Get used to it!''
</P>
<P>
   Crace, though, is not really after the stoic note of Thomas
Nashe's poem, ``I am sick, I must die,'' or William Dunbar's
catalog of death in ``Lament for the Makers.'' His novel,
alternating brief chapters about Celice and Joseph alive and their
dead bodies on the beach, is a series of variations that circle and
circle and ultimately hold both states in a kind of balance.
</P>
<P>
   The couple meet at a seaside cabin _ the country is never
specified but suggests, perhaps, a scruffy Australia in some near
future _ along with four other zoology students who are there for a
mix of study and carousing. Celice is gawky, but a recent seduction
has quickened her instincts: she is both sexually avid and sexy.
After casting about she fixes her sights on Joseph, quiet and
hard-working, his only flair a shiveringly powerful singing voice.
</P>
<P>
   While they are making love in the dunes, a badly placed lantern
or possibly a cigarette or maybe a stove not shut off (the weighing
of possibilities has the same peculiar ambling fascination as the
gait of the beach crabs) sets the cabin on fire, killing a student.
Love on the beach, death not far off.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later it will be the same intermingling. Love will
persist: Joseph's dying gesture is to clasp his dead wife's ankle.
Death will persist, as hand and ankle decay.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult, anyone could think, reading an account of Crace's
novels, particularly this one; and lofted at so strained an
altitude that oxygen must surely be lacking. But this overlooks the
paradoxes of his art.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he is an insidious storyteller. The encounter of
Celice and Joseph, their first lovemaking, the mix of
incompatibilities and attachments in their 30 years together, the
search reluctantly conducted by their estranged daughter _ her
repressed sorrow surges when she sees bone hand around bone ankle _
and even the progressive decay of dead flesh and organs: all these
things display an unlikely narrative springiness and zest.
</P>
<P>
   If the characters in Crace novels are ostensibly on high-flown
literary missions (dying, inhabiting prehistory, being God), their
flights swoop so near ground level, in fact, that they whip up
gravel, grass, gestures of startlement, and the smoke of human
cooking fires.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BEING DEAD'
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Crace
</P>
<P>
   196 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $21.
</P>
</TEXT>
