fought in public rallies, newspapers and broadcasts. Wednesday, the
skirmish moves to a body that has a real say in the debate: the
state Senate. Senators will try to hammer out a compromise that
will move the Civil War emblem to a spot on the Statehouse grounds
and off the penny-colored dome. It's widely thought that state Sen.
Glenn McConnell holds the key to compromise. The Charleston
Republican, who owns a Civil War memorabilia shop, has been
steadfast in his support of the flag. Moderates, though, are
hopeful he'll be the one to offer a compromise deal that ultimately
will be sent to the state House. Another pro-flag senator said
Wednesday will be ``Armageddon'' in the already fiery debate. South
Carolina is the only state that flies the battle flag from its
Capitol dome, though Mississippi and Georgia have incorporated the
design into their state flags. Debate starts at 11 a.m. Wednesday
and could drag into the weekend if needed. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
