<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-AIDS-FUNDING-HNS &LR;      04-12 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATE PANEL VOTES TO FREEZE SAN FRANCISCO AIDS FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate panel approved an update of the Ryan White
care program Wednesday that would preserve San Francisco's $35
million annual share of federal AIDS dollars, defeating a move to
redistribute one-quarter of the city's funding to other places
where the epidemic is growing.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Health, Labor, Education and Pensions Committee
unanimously approved a new $1.6 billion Ryan White program that
would freeze San Francisco's share of the money at within 2 percent
of the current $35.3 million for each of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan White program, begun in 1991, empowers the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services to pay for care and
medication for people with HIV and AIDS who aren't poor or sick
enough to receive Medicaid, but who don't have private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., predicted the full Senate would
approve the committee's bill, including the provision that protects
San Francisco's share of federal AIDS dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., had predicted that San Francisco
would lose about $8 million in funding from the Ryan White program
unless Congress continues to provide the city with an exception to
the funding formula. Officials in Los Angeles are lobbying Congress
to end the exception, saying San Francisco is getting an unfair
share of federal AIDS dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Congress decided in 1996 to maintain funding levels for San
Francisco even as the lawmakers adopted a new funding formula that
would otherwise have cut the city's share.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Ryan White formula was no longer based on a city's
cumulative number of AIDS cases over the years and on the density
of AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Congress declared that funds should be distributed
based on the total number of people living with AIDS in the city.
Under that formula, cities like San Francisco where the disease had
spread earlier in the epidemic would have received less money.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would provide a new stream of money for rural
areas and mid-sized cities where the disease is spreading
_especially among women and minorities and would direct more money
for drug therapy and prevention. Local providers would retain
flexibility in deciding how the dollars should be spent.
</P>
<P>
   The reauthorization bill is a blueprint for how the money should
be spent. Congressional appropriations panels will determine later
how much money to actually earmark for the Ryan White program.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jim M. Jeffords, R-Vt., said the bill reflects how the
epidemic has spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a recognition that the problem of AIDS and HIV is
expanding out of urban and poor areas,'' Jeffords said. ``Now it's
widespread throughout the population. Therefore, it's important to
expand the accessibility of coverage to rural areas as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., also a member of the panel, said
she was disappointed that the new version of the legislation
eliminates a requirement to enroll a significant number of women
and children in clinical trials. The provision was dropped after
AIDS researchers at the Department of Defense and the National
Institutes of Health expressed concern that some mothers with AIDS
were being coerced to join clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still do not believe it is a wise move,'' she said. ``We do
have to reach out to women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan White program is named after the hemophiliac teenager
from Kokomo, Ind., who contracted the disease through tainted blood
and died in 1990 at age 19. The program serves about a half million
people each year and, since 1991, has distributed $6.4 billion to
states and local governments for local use.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ryan White program began in 1991, the focus was on
end-of-life care, such as paying hospital bills, providing meals on
wheels and paying for drugs like morphine and antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   When it was reauthorized in 1996, the Ryan White program was
refocused to provide new drug therapies that stall the onset of
AIDS. It also began enrolling women and children with HIV and AIDS
in clinical trials and focused on early diagnosis and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address Judy &LR; hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
