<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LOUVRE-WORLD-NYT     04-12 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUVRE-WORLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICKING AND MOANING, THE LOUVRE GOES PRIMITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Stephane cq in 7th graf.) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Even in matters of artistic taste, it seems, French
presidents enjoy enviable power. Five years ago President Jacques
Chirac expressed the view that what was long called primitive art
should have a permanent place in the Louvre Museum. The Louvre
protested heatedly that it was not a universal museum, that
specialist collections should be housed elsewhere. On Thursday,
Chirac will open four newly renovated galleries of the Louvre
dedicated exclusively to art from Africa, Asia, Oceania and the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of disdain is over,'' noted Jacques Kerchache, a
renowned French collector of African art who is a close friend of
the French president. ```Primitive art' has finally entered the
Louvre.''
</P>
<P>
   Situated in the southern arm of the U-shaped museum, the new
galleries on the first floor of the Pavillon des Sessions are not
exactly in the heart of the Louvre. But they are accessible from
anywhere in the museum. And the idea is that, from now on, the 112
works of African, Asian, Oceanic and American art on display there
should be treated as the aesthetic equals of, say, the Egyptian,
Greek or Renaissance art elsewhere in the vast building.
</P>
<P>
   ``These galleries have been conceived for visitors to the
Louvre,'' Chirac wrote in an introduction to the catalog of the
collection. ``Literally `overexposed' to masterpieces of the most
varied styles and materials in other departments, upon entering
this beautiful installation, they will discover, I am certain,
works that can be compared to the purest treasures of the Louvre.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the Louvre has lost this battle, it is not ready to sue
for peace. Chirac's other dream was to create an entire museum
dedicated to the art of early civilizations. And this too should
come true. Late last year, a design by Jean Nouvel was chosen for a
new museum to be built at a cost of some $190 million along the
Seine on the Quai Branly beside the Eiffel Tower. That museum,
which will absorb the collections of the existing Museum of African
and Oceanic Art and the Ethnology section of the Museum of Man, is
to open in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent, says the Louvre's president, Pierre Rosenberg. So
what better moment, he suggests, for moving his unwanted lodgers in
the Louvre to a new home? ``No one would understand why visitors to
the Quai Branly Museum should be deprived of the major works on
display here,'' he wrote recently in the Louvre's magazine, adding
that the Louvre ``does not have a vocation for presenting the art
of all human civilizations.''
</P>
<P>
   So the issue may be reopened in 2004, even though by then
Rosenberg will have retired and Chirac may no longer be president
(though he is widely expected to seek re-election in 2002).
``Permanent is not necessarily eternal,'' said Stephane Martin, the
director general of the future Quai Branly Museum. ``What we have
in the Louvre is a political statement. Perhaps after the opening
of the Quai Branly Museum, the message will be clear and the Louvre
will not be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   For a good many unhappy curators at the Louvre, however, the
message in question is simply one of political correctness. For
them, the Louvre exists to present Western art from the Middle Ages
to 1840, plus the ancient civilizations that are at the origins of
Western art. They also note that, in contrast to the encyclopedic
approach of, say, the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York, the
French tradition is to maintain a galaxy of museums with focused
collections, not least the Musee d'Orsay and the Georges Pompidou
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the new Louvre galleries, on the other hand, argue
that the incursion of ``primitive art'' is not the result of
political whim but rather of a campaign that began in the early
years of this century when the likes of Picasso and Brancusi found
inspiration in African art. In 1909, for instance, the poet
Guillaume Apollinaire said the Louvre should present ``certain
exotic masterpieces.'' He was later seconded by Andre Malraux and
Claude Levi-Strauss, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac has long admired African and Asian art. And in Kerchache,
he has a strong advocate not only for the new presentation in the
Louvre but also for the new Quai Branly Museum. Kerchache, who has
the post of scientific adviser to the new museum, personally
selected the works in the Pavillon des Sessions, selecting from the
existing collections in Paris, borrowing from some French regional
museums and foreign museums and acquiring a score of new works.
</P>
<P>
   The display opens with 46 African sculptures, starting with an
Egyptian stone figure dating from around the fifth century B.C.
that, Martin said, serves as a bridge from the Louvre's own
exceptional Egyptian collection. This section includes ivory pieces
from Sierra Leone, 13th-to-15th-century wooden figures from Mali,
two Benin bronzes and a remarkable multiheaded terra cotta Nok
sculpture from Nigeria that is at least 1,500 years old. Unlike
most of the African works, a wooden and metal sculpture dedicated
to the god Gou in Benin in 1858 can be attributed to a specific
artist, Akati Ekplekendo.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian section contains just six works because the Quai
Branly Museum does not plan to duplicate the Asian collection at
the Musee Guimet. Rather, it is focusing only on those regions not
influenced by the ancient Asian religions, like Indonesia, the
Philippines and Taiwan. One of the most surprising pieces is a
10-foot-high sculptured wooden figure from a village in Taiwan that
Kerchache saw many years ago and was able to borrow.
</P>
<P>
   The Oceanic works in the Louvre, which number 28, are mostly
from former French possessions in the South Pacific. A wooden
figure from Hawaii and a stone head from Easter Island are also on
display. From the Americas, along with pre-Columbian ceramic and
clay figures, mainly Aztec and Mayan, from Mexico, the 32 works
include Taino objects from the Caribbean and Inuit heads from
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   What is noteworthy is that in these galleries, designed by
Jean-Michel Wilmotte, the objects are presented as art and not
ethnography. In contrast, the Quai Branly Museum _ it has been
given this name to forestall arguments about ``primitive art'' _
will aim at a more comprehensive interpretation of the role and
context of the pieces on display and, in that sense, satisfy those
who believe in a distinction between art created as art and objects
made for, say, a religious use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Quai Branly Museum's public will be different,'' Martin
explained. ``People visit the Louvre as they might a temple, so the
idea here is to pay homage to the artists of four continents. Now
people can see Egyptian and Greek and pre-Columbian art in one day
in one place. But we're not trying to create a mini-museum here.
That's why we wanted Jacques Kerchache to pick the pieces. It is
his personal point of view that gives unity to the presentation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
