<HEADER>
A4855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-PARDON13-COX     04-12 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PARDON13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE: CLINTON DOESN'T WANT A PARDON
 &HT;    With GORE. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore told newspaper editors
Wednesday that there won't be any stories about presidential
pardons if he moves into the White House when Bill Clinton moves
out next January.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton is way ahead of you on this,'' the
Democratic presidential nominee-in-waiting informed the American
Society of Newspaper Editors at their annual meeting here. ``He
said publicly some time ago that he would neither request nor
accept a pardon, so that's the answer to that question.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gore campaign spokeswoman in Nashville said the no-pardon
pledge came during impeachment hearings before the House Judiciary
Committee on Dec. 9, 1998. It was issued on Clinton's behalf by
then-White House counsel Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, asked Ruff whether he could assure
the panel that Clinton would neither grant himself a pardon nor
accept one from his successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Ruff replied.
</P>
<P>
   While the president later prevailed in an impeachment trial
before the Senate, the question posed to Gore has recently assumed
an added dimension.
</P>
<P>
   That is because Robert Ray, who succeeded Kenneth Starr as the
independent counsel investigating White House matters, is
considering an indictment of Clinton after he leaves office in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process has to be vindicated,'' Ray has told reporters.
``No person is above the law, even the president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray's remarks led to a spate of questions for presidential
spokesman Joe Lockhart at Tuesday's(cq) White House briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe, given the fact that the president paid the $90,000 fine
and did not appeal (U.S. District Court) Judge (Susan) Wright's
finding that he gave ``false, misleading and evasive answers''
under oath, and given Mr. Ray's statement ... can you assure us the
president will not pardon himself on or before January the 20th?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Another reporter asked whether Clinton ``had any discussion with
the vice
</P>
<P>
   president about a potential pardon situation, that you're aware
of?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not that I'm aware of,'' Lockhart responded.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart quipped that he was ``a little too young'' to recall
when Gerald Ford succeeded Richard Nixon after Nixon resigned as
president in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Ford issued Nixon a prospective pardon for his role
in the Watergate scandal _ but not before he told the House
Judiciary Committee that ``the American people would never stand''
for such an act.
</P>
<P>
   Article II of the Constitution states that the president ``shall
have power to grant reprieves and pardons for offenses against the
United States, except in cases of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Constitution remains silent as to whether a president
may use his pardon authority to protect himself from prosecution
after he leaves office, whether by removal, resignation or the
conclusion of his elected term.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
