<SLUG> BC-SEX-TRADE13-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEGISLATION FILED TO COMBAT SEXUAL SLAVERY
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects Wellstone's state to Minnesota in graf 2.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two senators who agree on little else introduced
almost identical bills Wednesday to crack down on the growing
worldwide problem of trafficking women and girls for forced
prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Most people ``don't believe this could actually be happening
today, in the year 2000,'' said Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., one
of the most liberal members of Congress, who has formed an alliance
with staunch conservative Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the Central Intelligence Agency estimates
that at least 700,000 women are tricked or kidnapped and taken to a
foreign country for forced prostitution each year. The CIA reports
that 50,000 women and girls are brought into the United States
annually for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Among other provisions, the bills would double the maximum
penalties for ``enticement into slavery and sale into involuntary
servitude'' to 20 years and adds the possibility of a life sentence
in cases involving death, rape or abuse of children.
</P>
<P>
   Victims, who are now often jailed or deported, would be eligible
for temporary visas, legal aid, and crisis treatment. To aid in
prevention, the United States would sponsor a public information
campaign abroad to warn women not to trust offers of lucrative jobs
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The two senators differed on only one issue, U.S. sanctions
against countries that refuse to fight this crime. Brownback wants
to mandate specific sanctions, and Wellstone would give the
president more leeway.
</P>
<P>
   However, the two senators agreed to back whichever version
emerges from the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. Brownback said
he was hopeful that the panel would move soon, although no action
is scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   A companion bipartisan bill is moving through the House.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists have said that no country has laws that
are tough enough to stop this modern sexual slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutions are rare, even in the United States, where some
traffickers in Florida last year were given only a two-year
sentence for holding a group of Mexican women, including a
14-year-old girl, under armed guard and forcing them to service
migrant workers in trailers converted to brothels.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: To read the CIA report on sexual slavery,
see www.cia.gov and click on ``Center for the Study of
Intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
