<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-EARNINGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Higher fuel costs cut into AirTran's profit
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sharply higher fuel costs pushed AirTran Airways'
profit down 5 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But executives at Atlanta's second-largest carrier called the
results solid, adding they expect to begin a significant expansion
this year following two years of nominal growth as the company
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the company on a good operational and financial footing
it's our intention to start ramping growth up,'' Chief Executive
Joe Leonard told analysts during a Wednesday conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect 15 percent (seat capacity) growth starting in the
second half of the year for as far out as we can see,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said AirTran will probably add two new destinations from
Atlanta this year. He said it will continue to focus on Atlanta as
its primary hub and local market, although it has also added a few
non-Atlanta routes such as Philadelphia-Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, AirTran had a profit of $2.9 million, or 4
cents a share, down from $3.1 million, or 5 cents a share, for the
same period of 1999. Revenue rose 10 percent to $132.4 million, as
ridership gained 5.5 percent and yield, or average fare per mile,
grew 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth consecutive quarterly profit for AirTran, which
grew out of the former ValuJet and struggled to survive in 1997 and
1998. Leonard took the helm in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran's average cost of jet fuel zoomed to 90.4 cents per
gallon from 42 cents a year earlier, a 115 percent increase. That
pushed unit costs up 8.6 percent, although they declined almost 6
percent excluding the higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said Y2K concerns and ice storms also dragged down
first-quarter profits. He said the airline has experienced some
shakedown glitches with its new Boeing 717s, which are gradually
replacing AirTran's aging DC-9s, but added he remains happy with
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended the quarter with a lot of momentum,'' Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
