<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FURNITURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MILAN, MINIMUM FURNITURE, MAXIMUM FUSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan, Britain)   By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ A wallop of sugar was added this week to the
frothy zabaglione that is the annual Italian furniture fair, where
hundreds of editors and thousands of buyers, manufacturers and
designers descend each year to test, compare, cheer and dismiss new
products and retreads of old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that the latest sleek samples of minimal elegance and
technological wizardry might not sufficiently wow the crowds, fair
organizers asked 14 international artists to provide a supplemental
jolt of novelty.
</P>
<P>
   So on Monday, the eve of the fair's official opening,
installations by Robert Wilson, Yoko Ono and Peter Greenaway, among
others, were presented within the splendid 19th-century Rotonda
Della Besana in the middle of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Each artist interpreted the theme of ``rooms and their secrets''
before an audience of 2,000 _ mostly Milanese hungry for
contemporary art. Luisa Agliatta, a design student from Zimbabwe
studying here, said she didn't mind waiting for an hour to get
inside. ``I'm willing to see anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty to ponder. In one corner of Wilson's
installation, a woman dressed like a character from Chekhov
staggered around a darkened space where columns had been
transformed into tree trunks. She reacted sometimes violently,
sometimes disconsolately, to a voice apparently from her past
speaking German.
</P>
<P>
   Greenaway, the film director, flooded his space with water,
overflowing from about 10 bathtubs. Open suitcases also overflowed
with the stuff of everyday life: bottles, appliances, tennis balls.
A naked man sat in one tub while the room filled with steam.
</P>
<P>
   The smolderingly handsome Bosnian filmmaker, Emir Kusturica, was
there, too, re-creating an underground bunker from his 1995 film,
``Underground,'' the story of two friends who go into hiding for a
very long time only to find upon emerging that their homeland,
Yugoslavia, has disappeared, along with one man's wife. The
director imported truckloads of Serbian dirt, cabbages and onions
to his re-created bunker. ``There's no place left for secrets;
there's only the underground as a place to hide your agenda,'' he
said, when asked to explain its significance.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, Kusturica also performed with a rock band
(formed by his son) that provided the musical entertainment. One
observer quipped that it sounded like ``a bar mitzvah band.''
</P>
<P>
   Many viewers felt the entire installation, which runs through
May 7, was overegging the zabaglione.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's useless,'' said Achille Castiglioni, the legendary
designer who in his 80s remains a vital presence on the scene, as
he emerged with a shrug, unimpressed by a video installation
projecting images of two naked bodies struggling to fit into a
small cube.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's trying to be experimental but it makes no real point that
I can see,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The sideshow hardly seemed necessary, what with the Italian
furniture business thriving with roughly $101 million in sales to
the United States alone for 1999, an increase of about 6 percent
over 1998. About 2,300 exhibitors, all but 200 of them from Italy,
were expected to show new wares at this year's fair. Many were
groaning about sensory overload before the fair even opened
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the artists may have won hands-down when it came to
metaphor, the furniture designers were busy grappling with how to
make technology more human, and if not poetic then at least
practical.
</P>
<P>
   At the Milan fairgrounds, the Italian furniture company Edra was
once again in the forefront, presenting furniture upholstered in
hybrid materials: their shimmery waterproof linen, in fashion
colors, had a rain-slicker look. Other pieces were covered in a
wool injected with synthetic fiber that gave the fabric an almost
Naugahyde sheen.
</P>
<P>
   The shapes this year were appealing to the inner lounge lizard
in everyone. One sprawling sofa at Edra, called Flap, designed by
Francesco Binfare, recalled a squashed baseball mitt with fingers
that could be raised or lowered as back and leg rests.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was this sofa, or any one of the many
low-to-the-ground samples in evidence everywhere, that prompted the
architect Adam Tihany to complain that Italians have no
understanding of the American body. ``Don't they know that we all
have bad backs?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edra was not the only company that had a stake in technological
derring-do. Kartell, the plastics giant, was also on hand with a
love seat called Bubble Club by Philippe Starck. While pointedly
old-fashioned in look, with traditional rolled arms, the sofa took
advantage of the latest techniques in molding plastic. It required
a special rotational device to make a piece of plastic that large,
with a bit of comfy give in the seat. (No spindly aluminum legs
like they always have on plastic seating units in airports.) The
piece will cost $400 to $500 when it arrives in the United States
later this year, according to Kartell.
</P>
<P>
   Starck, wearing glasses with a Fendi tag still pasted to the
lens, noted that to be able to make a piece of ``such size and
durability for so little is a revolution; you can put it in your
salon or forget it for 100 years in your garden.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's kind of no style, coming from the collective
unconscious. I like that it's not `designed' by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Understated minimalism, championed by designers since the
mid-90s, is selling too well to dismiss. There was plenty of
minimal furniture on show, with only the slightest deviation from
years past: a little extra nub on the politely textured wool
upholstery at B&AMP;B Italia, for example, but bring your magnifying
glass to discern it. The company's sales are up more than 35
percent in the United States and so there were plenty of new pieces
by Antonio Citterio, the maestro of low-key elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of messing with the success of clean lines, many
manufacturers opted for saturated late-'60s colors borrowed
straight from Barbra Streisand's wardrobe in ``Funny Girl'' or
perhaps from Andy Warhol's silk-screen portraits.
</P>
<P>
   To assuage some apparent restlessness or perhaps just to attract
a younger crowd, B&AMP;B also reissued a newly hip '60s classic:
Gaetano Pesce's bright Up furniture collection, with its famous
bulbous high-back chair, resembling a Botero mother. The ottoman is
a round ball tethered by a bungee cord. The chair will be about
$1,729 in the United States. At the Satellite, a pavilion for
aspiring designers, it was a great hit with young talents trying to
catch some shut-eye between events.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cappellini tapped two young talents, Erwan and Ronan Bouroullec
from Brittany, who reinterpreted a native cloistered bed. The piece
also invoked Australian shuttered architecture, including
fire-watching towers, in its elevated ``treehouse'' style, with
framing in steel and paneling in lacquered birch plywood.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a few architects were invited to punch up the
streamlined shapes. The company Driade asked David Chipperfield,
one of the master minimalists of London, and Kazuyo Sejima, known
among cognoscenti as the Rem Koolhaas of Japan, to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Sejima stretched farther than Chipperfield, who designed a
collection of regulation mahogany and aluminum home office
furniture. She created a five-piece sitting room with multipurpose
pieces that range from a black, tatami-inspired foam platform that
barely hovered above the ground, to a zany inflatable lime-green
slipcover for side chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, everyone has these very hard chairs to sit on,''
Sejima said. ``I wanted to find a cheap way to make them more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Although still in prototype form (it emitted a few embarrassing
whoopee-cushion sounds when tested) the slipcover promised to be
poetic and inspiring. Artists, please take note.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
