<HEADER>
A4866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-IRVING-BOS &LR;      04-12 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-IRVING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VERDICT FOR HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The verdict of a British judge on the libel suit filed by
Holocaust denier David Irving against Emory University professor
Deborah Lipstadt was a powerful denunciation of Irving's
distortions of history and his neo-Nazi attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Upholding the truth of what Lipstadt had written about Irving in
her book, ``Denying the Holocaust: The Growing Assault on Truth and
Memory,'' High Court Justice Charles Gray said: ``I have come to
the conclusion that the criticisms advanced by the defendants are
almost invariably well-founded. Irving has significantly
misrepresented what the evidence, objectively examined, reveals.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's ruling does justice to the memory of the millions
murdered under Adolf Hitler's Nazi regime. It makes a lucid
distinction between truth and falsification. And in ruling that
Lipstadt's book did not libel Irving, Gray was moved to say not
only that Irving's misrepresentations of the Nazi genocide were
deliberate, but also that Irving is an anti-Semite, racist against
people of color, and a Nazi sympathizer.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has pondered the meaning of the Holocaust will
breathe a sigh of relief at Irving's failure to win his libel suit
in a British court, where the burden of proof is placed on the
defendants _ in this case the author and her publisher, Penguin
Books _ to prove they did not libel the plaintiff. Irving's defeat
may not vanquish the forces of revisionism or neo-Nazism, but, had
he won his case, the myth-makers who wish to efface the Third
Reich's crimes would have had a monstrous victory.
</P>
<P>
   That said, if the great treasure of open inquiry is to be
preserved, no court should have to decide a quarrel among
historians. Gray may be correct in ruling that ``Irving has for his
own ideological reasons persistently and deliberately
misrepresented and manipulated historical evidence.'' But when a
judge must judge a debate among historians, relying on testimony
from other historians, something of scholarly free inquiry is lost.
In this case, it was Irving himself who brought the debate to
court, but more honest historians should avoid repeating his error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
