<HEADER>
A4868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS &LR;      04-12 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY LOOPHOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This nation's landmark 1968 gun-control law prohibits both
felons and persons who have been involuntarily hospitalized for
mental illness from buying handguns. The 1993 Brady law, which
requires a waiting period before gun purchases to screen out those
who are not eligible, did not address a major loophole in the 1968
law: Because of privacy concerns, police often have little, if any,
information about involuntary confinements of the mentally ill,
with the result that many deeply disturbed people have no trouble
buying guns. Closing that loophole should be a top priority in both
Congress and the state capitals.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of this problem was made clear in a New York Times
series this week on rampage killers _ people who suddenly start
shooting others in a school, workplace, commuter train, or other
public site. The series looked at 100 such incidents and found that
half the killers had a history of serious mental illness, with at
least eight having been involuntarily committed. Repeatedly, the
Times found such people could buy guns easily because little
information is exchanged between mental health officials and
law-enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, police send names of gun-permit applicants to
the state Department of Mental Health, which checks the records of
only public mental-health institutions near the applicant's home.
State Senator Cheryl Jacques, a member of the Public Safety
Committee, says this is inadequate. But, she notes, ``these are not
criminals we are talking about.'' She expects to confer with
advocates for the mentally ill to make sure any new legislation
protects privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts does have another line of defense against severely
disturbed people buying handguns _ the discretion that local police
chiefs have to deny permits to applicants they consider dangerous.
But this too is far from foolproof. Ideally, Congress should close
the loophole while protecting privacy. This can be done with a
tightly controlled national registry of the involuntarily committed
that would respond only to police requests for matches against gun
applications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
