<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4870 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS13-COX     04-12 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich and Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  SHOW TUNES
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnelli on Minnelli''
</P>
<P>
   Liza Minnelli. Angel. 24 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   A full orchestra, heavy on strings. A fading star. A comeback
concert that honors a dead daddy. ``Minnelli on Minnelli'' has all
the elements of great drama, and there is great drama on this disc,
recorded live at New York's Palace Theater in December. Some of
that drama comes from the material _ great songs from ``Gigi,''
``Meet Me in St. Louis'' and ``The Band Wagon.'' Some of it comes
from wondering whether Liza Minnelli, a hard-living 53, has
anything left in her bag of tricks. She does, and it's mostly the
tricks: the overly emotive phrasing; the sloshy vibrato; the
girlish giggles that flirt with hyperventilation. Still, with a
manly sextet providing serious support, she sells it. She even
turns the tables with a quippy ``I'm Glad I'm Not Young Anymore''
verse that skewers the gossips and critics, and her ``Trolley
Song'' is insistently hummable. Love Liza with a Z or hate her, you
gotta admit the girl's still here.
</P>
<P>
   _Kathy Janich
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: More on Liza Minnelli: pages.prodigy.com
</P>
<P>
   /liza.minnelli/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FOLK-BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying Saucer Blues''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Case. Vanguard. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Lonesome losers and acoustic blues go hand in hand. And few
songwriters know both as well as Peter Case. One-time leader of
'80s new wavers the Plimsouls _ lone hit: ``A Million Miles Away''
_ Case has spent the last 15 years exploring the gritty side of
America's barrooms, bedrooms and boulevards. On his seventh solo,
the folk troubadour delivers more autobiographical tales of
drifters, misfits and boozers than you'd expect from a 40-something
upstate New York native. But it's a familiar cast for Case, whose
most recent albums play like a grim soundtrack for the luckless.
What keeps Case's warts-and-all storytelling from becoming maudlin
is the lyrical wit at the core of his spare Dylanesque tales. It's
what cuts through his boyish vocals and Delta blues fretwork,
whether he's lamenting lost chances (``Coulda Shoulda Woulda''),
childhood innocence (``Black Dirt &AMP; Clay'') or Y2K angst
(``Paradise Etc.''). Overall, ``Blues'' is not as rich as 1998's
stellar ``Full Service.'' Similar pacing and structure handcuff
many of the songs here, and melody too often takes a backseat to
the lyrics. But for fans of road-ripe blues, these are merely bumps
along the way in a trip worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Case plays the Blind Willie McTell Blues Festival in
Thompson, Ga., on May 13. For details: 706-597-1000, or on the Web
at www.blindwillie.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: More on Peter Case, Vanguard Records:
www.buzznet.com/petercase
</P>
<P>
   /vanguard.html
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Janich and Nick Tate write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
