<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4871 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOME-PROJECTS-COX     04-12 2083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for things to do
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time to go out looking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A house is thousands and thousands of individual parts that work
together to keep you comfortable and safe, and there's a good
chance dozens of those parts need maintenance, repair, replacement
or general sprucing up right now.
</P>
<P>
   Your job, now that it's warm enough to spend a few hours
outside, is to take a close look around the house to figure out
what needs attention and how badly. Once you've done a thorough
inspection trip, you can prioritize and give yourself a good to-do
list.
</P>
<P>
   Today we'll list some of the important things you should check
and give you some tips on how to check them. We'll save tips on
correcting most of the problems you might find for another day.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn and lawn tools
</P>
<P>
   While walking across the lawn, notice the feel of the ground.
Freezing and thawing sometimes creates spongy soil. You also may
notice mole trails that appear as raised lines of grass.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawn care experts suggest running a roller over a spongy or
mole-damaged lawn. Others prefer an aerator that takes plugs out of
the soil to improve water and fertilizer penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Go with aeration if the lawn has a thatch layer more than 1/2
-inch thick. Thatch is the tightly intermingled layer of living and
dead stems and other plant parts that develops between the grass
and the soil surface.
</P>
<P>
   To measure the thatch layer, cut a plug of the lawn a few inches
deep with a shovel. You'll see how thick the thatch is by looking
at the plug from the side.
</P>
<P>
   You also may run across a few insect larvae buried near the
surface. You won't be able to do much about the grubs now, but make
note to deal with them in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   If you have small bare spots scattered around the lawn that were
green last summer, you may have a crabgrass problem. Larger bare
spots usually indicate bigger problems.
</P>
<P>
   Now's a good time to spread a pre-emergent crabgrass agent over
the lawn. It will kill the young crabgrass plants before they take
root firmly.
</P>
<P>
   Check your garden hoses for leaks and cuts. Attach a sprayer to
the end of the hoses, but leave the sprayer closed when you turn on
the water.
</P>
<P>
   Leaks at connections can usually be fixed by replacing hose
washers, but hoses with splits or breaks should be replaced to
avoid wasting water. Save the damaged hoses; you'll find lots of
uses for lengths of rubber tubing cut from an old hose.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a sprinkler system, turn it on and see if it's
working properly. If it has a timer, set the clock to trigger the
system to be sure it turns on and off when it's supposed to. An
elaborate professionally installed sprinkler system may need
attention from your irrigation contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Check your lawn mower if you haven't used it yet. Use a paint
scraper to clear any clipping residue stuck inside the mower
housing. Then scrape the inside of the housing with a wire brush.
</P>
<P>
   While cleaning, examine and tighten all the screws and bolts and
make sure all the switches, levers, pulleys and other control
devices are moving properly.
</P>
<P>
   Before you use your lawn mower, sharpen the blade, change the
oil, replace the spark plug, clean or replace the air filter and do
other maintenance tasks the owner's manual suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Also fire up your other lawn equipment _ weed trimmers, hedge
trimmers, power saws, etc. You may still be able to beat the worst
of the spring rush at repair shops if you find a problem soon.
</P>
<P>
   Decks, walks and drives, lighting
</P>
<P>
   Examine wooden decks and fences. You probably will wait for
spring rains to pass before cleaning and resealing your outdoor
wood, but structural repairs can be handled earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Check all joints and fasteners on the deck; they should be
secure and free of rust. Look for deck nails that are working
loose. You might want to replace them with screws. Are the posts
that support the deck showing any signs of decay?
</P>
<P>
   To see if your deck will need to be resealed this year, toss a
bucket of water on the deck when it is dry (no rain in about three
days). If the water beads, you're in good shape for this year. If
it soaks in, you'll need to apply a sealer.
</P>
<P>
   On your wooden fences, look for loose boards, popped nails,
``weep'' lines under nails, discoloration and rotting wood.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete walks and driveways and asphalt driveways naturally
develop cracks. Large cracks will have to be repaired to keep large
holes from developing, but whether you deal with hairline cracks is
up to you. Some people ignore them, although others insist that no
crack is a good crack.
</P>
<P>
   Look for a smooth, even black surface on an asphalt driveway. If
the surface is discolored or if pebbles clearly show, you probably
need to apply an asphalt sealer.
</P>
<P>
   On walkways, look for evidence that tree roots are lifting the
pavement. Roots can create dangerous breaks that will trip
unsuspecting walkers. Breaks are especially dangerous in winter
when they're difficult to keep free of snow and they're difficult
for pedestrians to see.
</P>
<P>
   Check any landscape lights you have running along the walks and
driveways. Turning the lights on for a daytime inspection may mean
resetting a timer or disabling a light sensor.
</P>
<P>
   Check the course of the wires leading to landscape light
fixtures. Are the wires in danger of being unearthed and exposed to
lawn mower blades?
</P>
<P>
   Check your porch lights and security lights. Turn them on and
look for burned-out bulbs or flickering fluorescent light tubes.
</P>
<P>
   After dark, check such things as motion sensors. Do the lights
come on as expected as you approach?
</P>
<P>
   Siding
</P>
<P>
   Paint on wooden siding deteriorates over time and must be
periodically replenished. Examine painted siding for peeling,
flaking, bubbling and powdering. Also look for rusting nails and
gaps around seams and openings or rotting and damaged boards.
</P>
<P>
   If your paint job has gone bad less than five years after the
last painting, seek advice from a seasoned professional before
repainting. You may need to correct some underlying problem to make
your next paint job last.
</P>
<P>
   Look for dark blotches or spots on the walls. If the spots fade
when wiped with bleach, you have a mildew problem.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum siding also deteriorates over time, although not as
quickly as paint. If your siding is more than 15 years old, look
for fading and chalking. If the original color layer has failed,
exposing unprotected metal, you need to act quickly to repaint it.
</P>
<P>
   Brick, like other sidings, can develop a salty white coating.
The white residue is caused by moisture passing through the brick,
so you must find and fix any leaks or sources of condensation that
may be causing moisture to make its way into the masonry.
</P>
<P>
   Windows, doors and air conditioners
</P>
<P>
   The points at which the frames of your doors and windows meet
the siding should be caulked to keep air from passing through
cracks around the frame. Caulk can harden and crack over time, so
check all the frames for problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also check the putty that holds the glass part of the window in
its wooden frame. Dry, hard, cracking window putty should be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The window frames themselves usually show stress at the joints
first, and all hardware and home-improvement stores sell metal
corner plates to shore up loose frames.
</P>
<P>
   While checking the airtightness of frames on your doors and
windows, don't forget the door of your attached garage. Keeping
some of the cold air out of your garage reduces the heat loss
through walls adjacent to the garage in winter and help. Sealing
the garage in summer reduces the cost of air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Check that exterior doors are equipped with sweeps, which seal
the area where the bottom of the door meets the threshold. Replace
broken or brittle sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully examine all locks and tighten any loose screws. Assess
whether additional locks are needed; good deadbolt locks should
protect all entry doors.
</P>
<P>
   Inspect all screens for holes. If you have the kind of screens
that are removed and replaced with storm windows in the winter,
check the screen frames to see if they need repair or painting.
</P>
<P>
   If you have central air conditioning, also inspect the outside
condenser unit. Leaves and other debris should be cleared before
the first use. Also trim shrubs or plants that crowd around the
condenser.
</P>
<P>
   The system should be inspected professionally once a year in
most cases. Check your owner's manual for tips on how often your
unit should be serviced.
</P>
<P>
   When you install window air conditioners, be sure they fit
snugly in the windows. If you find gaps around the unit or between
window sashes uses weatherstripping materials to seal them.
</P>
<P>
   Most units have a removable front filter. Check the filter
before turning on the unit, and clean it if necessary. If the
filter is frayed or otherwise deteriorated, replace it. Clean the
filter at least once a month this summer, or more often if your
owner's manual says so.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure your clothes dryer is set to vent outdoors, and be
sure the vent cover is working properly. Clean accumulated lint
from the lint exhaust system.
</P>
<P>
   Roof and gutters
</P>
<P>
   The top is as good a place to start as any, so we'll start at
the chimney and work down.
</P>
<P>
   After a hard rain, go up to the attic to examine the underside
of the roof deck using a flashlight to check unlighted areas. Poke
with a knife or screwdriver to locate wet, darkened or
deteriorating wood on the ceiling beams or rafters. If you find
any, trace the moisture path back to its origin. This may be
difficult; the steeper the roof's pitch, the farther the moisture
can travel from its entry point to where it has collected.
</P>
<P>
   Next, turn off the lights and look for pinholes or cracks of
daylight in the roof surface. When you find the leak, measure its
location in relation to a reference point such as a chimney or vent
stack. This will help in locating it from the top of the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the chimney if it passes through the attic. It
should be sound without deteriorating plaster or bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, start in the yard with a pair of binoculars on a strap
around your neck. Look with your bare eyes for problem areas, then
use the binoculars for a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   When looking at your chimney, check for cracks, missing bricks,
deteriorating plaster or signs of water damage. If you have a
chimney that runs up the side of the house, check its entire
length.
</P>
<P>
   Is the top of the chimney equipped to keep out birds or other
animals or is there evidence animals have entered?
</P>
<P>
   Check the fireplace damper and close it if you're through using
the fireplace for the season.
</P>
<P>
   On the roof, worn shingles may have dark spots where the
granules on their surface have washed off. Another sign of roof
problems are shingles that have curled at the edges.
</P>
<P>
   If your house has wooden shingles or shakes, check for curled,
warped and split shingles. Also look for stains from rusted nails
or shingles that have become loose. On slate or tile roofs, look
for breaks or loose roofing material.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing is the metal plating around chimneys, skylights, vents
and other holes through the roof. It should be flat and rust-free,
and the sealing material around its edges should be smooth and
intact.
</P>
<P>
   After looking up from the ground, position your ladder for a
closer look at the roof and the gutters.
</P>
<P>
   Check the gutters and look for evidence of leaks, rust and
depressions where water might collect. Also check for loose
connections between gutters and downspouts and for loose nails or
brackets.
</P>
<P>
   If you wish, you can clean debris out of your gutters now or you
can wait until the trees near your house have shed their blooms and
seed pods later in the spring. Remember that even if your gutters
are screened, small plant debris will still get in, and you have to
occasionally remove the screens to clean the gutters.
</P>
<P>
   Spray the roof with a garden hose and make sure water coming out
of the downspouts is carried two feet or more from the house and
that the lawn slopes away from the house at least a little where
the water is released.
</P>
<P>
   Finally check out the hammock or patio lounger. By this time you
deserve an inspection that can be done from a prone position.
</P>
<P>
   Contact James Cummings at jamescummings(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
