<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-INSIDER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video pick: `Insider' offers plenty to Crowe about
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More smoke than fire here, but Russell Crowe, the hunky,
hot-tempered cop in ``L.A. Confidential,'' gives an astonishing
Oscar-worthy performance. (Too bad he lost to ``American Beauty's''
Kevin Spacey).
</P>
<P>
   Crowe plays Jeffrey Wigand, the real-life cigarette industry
consultant who blew the lid off the tobacco industry. Al Pacino
plays the ``60 Minutes'' producer dogging the story. The film
received seven Oscar nominations. It didn't win any.
</P>
<P>
   `The Insider'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Tumbleweeds'' (PG-13) _ Definitely give this one a tumble.
Janet McTeer and Kimberly J. Brown give sensational performances in
this funny, heartfelt film. McTeer, who earned an Oscar nomination,
is a sassy vibrant Southerner with a talent for finding _ and
leaving _ the wrong men. Brown is her savvy adolescent daughter who
knows her mom's hit-and-run tactics all too well. It sounds like
``Anywhere But Here,'' but it's a far more real, more affecting
work. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Three Kings'' (R) _ George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and Ice
Cube play three U.S. soldiers in the Gulf War who go after Saddam
Hussein's stolen Kuwaiti gold. Their consciences are tested when
they see anti-Saddam civilians rounded up by Iraqi soldiers. While
the film's script cynically bashes George Bush's political stance,
its visuals pop with energy. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Happy, Texas'' (PG-13) _ A one-joke movie, and it's not a
good joke. Jeremy Northam and Steve Zahn play escaped convicts who
hide out in a small town, posing as a gay couple who stage beauty
pageants. What follows is a tepid romance between Northam and a
local beauty (who of course thinks he's ``harmless''), and some
funny shots of Zahn teaching toddlers to pose and dance. But it
wears out its welcome fast. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Minus Man'' (R) _ Not many pluses. An affable drifter
(Owen Wilson) moves to a small town and insinuates himself into the
lives of the residents. Trouble is, he's also a serial killer. The
idea of a compulsive killer as a freaky cipher who, if anything,
seems too normal is intriguing, but the film is as flat and
affectless as Wilson's performance. After a point, you kind of hope
Wilson will kill again, just to pick things up. Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Superstar'' (PG-13) _ Whaddya know _ a ``Saturday Night
Live'' big-screen transfer that doesn't bite. As the ebullient
Catholic schoolgirl Mary Katherine Gallagher, Molly Shannon
delivers a memorable mix of adolescent brazenness and
self-mortification. It's clear the actress loves this character,
but she's never afraid to push the envelope of outrageousness,
whether talking baby-talk to her own breasts, or fantasizing that a
tree (or a handy stop sign) is her fantasy lover. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
