<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Much to `Like' (but women get no respect)
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Water for Chocolate''
</P>
<P>
   Common. MCA. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The fourth album by Chicago-based rapper Common is probably the
first hip-hop album to come out this year that's really worth
buying. But there's an asterisk at the end of that statement.
Musically, ``Like Water for Chocolate'' is not unlike R&AMP;B singer
D'Angelo's atmospheric and involving current CD, ``Voodoo.'' Which
shouldn't be surprising considering D'Angelo and much of his
``Voodoo'' accompaniment _ Roy Hargrove on trumpet, ?uestlove on
drums _ appear throughout this similarly strong effort. Lyrically,
though, ``Like'' could take you back a beat or two. Particularly if
you remember the even-toned Common who joined rapper/singer Lauryn
Hill to craft the incredibly thoughtful take on abortion, ``I Used
To Love H.E.R.'' Here, there are occasional references to women
(``The Heat,'' ``A Film Called Pimp'') that are so offensive, even
the well-written and seemingly genuine paean to the fairer sex,
``The Light,'' doesn't smooth away those stings. Not completely,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: More on Common:
</P>
<P>
   www.com-mon.com
</P>
