<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4875 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-SATURN13-COX     04-12 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-SATURN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trademark sound on a roll
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Doubt vocalist Gwen Stefani was the ``it'' girl several years
ago. She and her band made a big splash with 1995's
multi-million-selling ``Tragic Kingdom,'' the quartet's third
album. Anticipation is high for this much-delayed follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   These Southern Californians got together in the late 1980s, and
their chronological roots show. The ska and new wave influences are
still as pervasive as they were on ``Tragic Kingdom.'' The grunge
hangover of the mid-'90s left audiences ready for No Doubt's
sprightly sound, and the band doesn't mess with success.
</P>
<P>
   From the punky chug of lead track ``Ex-Girlfriend'' to the
squiggly synthesizer unpinning ``Six Feet Under,'' No Doubt drags
new wave into the new millennium. If '80s nostalgia were all they
had, though, they'd never have bothered the charts at all. Tom
Dumont tosses off understated, inventive guitar riffs, the melodies
flow effortlessly and the rhythm section keeps everything moving
forward with abandon. Like Blondie before them, the boys in the
band rarely get the credit they deserve. Debbie Harry and Stefani
attract all the attention, but both were blessed with powerhouse
bands.
</P>
<P>
   Stefani gets plenty of attention for her lyrics, too. Her
honesty borders on too much information, but her unpretentious
soul-baring is one of her more endearing qualities. Still, do we
really need to hear, as she sings in ``Bathwater,'' ``I still love
to wash in your old bathwater''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Return of Saturn'' finds No Doubt more mature and worldly, but
surprisingly unperturbed by success. It's the sound of a band
that's just getting better at what it does.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Return of Saturn''
</P>
<P>
   No Doubt / Interscope / 14 tracks / Our critic's Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: More on No Doubt: www.nodoubt.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
