<HEADER>
A4876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FRIED-EGGS13-COX     04-12 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIED-EGGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fried eggs
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was in culinary school, I learned the cheffy French
method of scrambling eggs: whisk them with cream in a metal mixing
bowl and then plate the bowl over a pot of simmering water,
whisking constantly until you end up
</P>
<P>
   with eggs so creamy, they're just this side of a custard. Hmm.
They are fancy, but to my American palate, eating these eggs is
like sitting down to a bowl of whole-milk ricotta when you really
want some 4 percent cottage cheese. Large curd, natch.
</P>
<P>
   I love scrambled eggs with large, loose, wavy curds. You get
these by pushing the eggs in the pan rather than whisking. Also,
water works far better than cream at giving the eggs the light,
soft consistency I crave.
</P>
<P>
   My Favorite Scrambled Eggs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Beat the eggs with the water, salt and pepper until fully
blended and no clumps of white remain. Heat the butter in the
bottom of a 12-inch preferably nonstick skillet until foaming but
not brown. Swirl to cover the bottom of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the eggs over the surface and immediately push along the
bottom of the pan with a sturdy rubber spatula or a flat-bottomed
wooden spatula. Reduce heat to medium.
</P>
<P>
   Continue pushing the eggs, tilting the pan and lifting the eggs
to allow the runny portion to slide underneath. Break up any very
large clumps. When the eggs are just a little but too runny, remove
them from the heat source and continue pushing, tilting and lifting
until the eggs are just set. Do not
</P>
<P>
   allow them to form a flat surface on the bottom, like an
omelette.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: x199calories, 13grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 71), 1 grams carbohydrates, 440
milligrams cholesterol, 127 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
