<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4877 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MUSIC-TREND13-COX     04-12 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TREND13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McDonald doing music on his own via the Internet
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to poke fun at one-time Doobie Brother Michael
McDonald. His throaty vocals on hits such as ``On My Own'' helped
'70s rock artists (such as Sting) evolve into the kingpins of
today's jazz-influenced, adult-contemporary music.
</P>
<P>
   It was this sound that prompted Trey Parker, creator of the
irreverent animated television series ``South Park,'' to recruit
McDonald as perhaps the most unlikely participant in the bawdy film
``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut.'' In a moment of self-parody,
the singer/songwriter planted tongue firmly in cheek to record the
movie's closing tune, ``Through the Eyes of a Child,'' a gushy
ballad meant to skewer every closing credit anthem ever written.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little reluctant to do it, but when they told me it
was a spoof on artists like myself, it sounded kind of funny,''
McDonald says, calling from his car phone, somewhere on the road
between Nashville and his home in a rural suburb. ``My kids are
still not letting me live that one down _ but I don't even let them
watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridge to a new audience
</P>
<P>
   The ``South Park'' cameo was just the beginning of an unlikely
midlife resurgence for the 48-year-old McDonald, who is playing
Atlanta's Roxy tonight. After seven years without an album _ and at
a time when many acts his age are content cashing royalty checks _
the gray-haired singer has decided to try to shake up the music
business a bit.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald and actor Jeff Bridges have decided to start their own
label, Ramp Records. The company's first two releases: a
left-of-center album from Bridges (``Be Here Soon'') and a new CD
of R&AMP;B tunes from McDonald (``Blue Obsession'').
</P>
<P>
   ``We get these dark periods where everything sounds alike, very
formulated,'' McDonald says. ``Then a wild card pops up, such as FM
radio or Internet access, and the audience eats it up. Think about
the artists we grew up with. Who would have heard of Country Joe &AMP;
the Fish or Buffalo Springfield if not for FM radio? The Internet
will serve the same purpose. It's going to make young people privy
to a lot more artists.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era dominated by rap and hip-hop, McDonald has created a
sizzling R&AMP;B album in the tradition of Marvin Gaye and Stevie
Wonder. Fueled by the hot hum of a B3 organ, sassy horns and backup
singers who sound like the Sweet Inspirations, the album is
definitely out of step with today's radio playlists. But McDonald
hopes that Ramp Records, through an Internet presence
(www.ramprecords
</P>
<P>
   .com), can reach audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges' album, which McDonald helped produce, is certainly an
example of the kind of musical experimentation that rarely reaches
the mainstream. On the nine tracks (six he wrote himself), the
actor's voice wobbles from John Belushi sendup soul to artsy chants
borrowed from David Byrne. The lyrics also dwell on noncommercial
themes, from Bill Clinton's sexuality to self-doubt. But it was
Bridges' quirky approach that enticed McDonald to return to the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff, as a songwriter, impressed me greatly. I play on a lot
of records, and this doesn't sound a whole lot like anything else.
His songs have humor and intelligence. He brings a certain
unconventional taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Can two graying baby boomers change the music business?
</P>
<P>
   McDonald says he just hopes for one thing _ ``That the public
gets a chance to decide for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McDonald
</P>
<P>
   8:30 tonight, $26, The Roxy, 3110 Roswell Road N.W., Atlanta,
</P>
<P>
   404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
