<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL13-COX     04-12 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Excitement awaits in caper flicks
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good caper movie is hard to find. Hard to make, too. That's
probably why pictures like ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' or this
week's new Paul Newman film, ``Where The Money Is,'' usually find
an appreciative audience. Here are a few more clever flicks about
clever folks whose only real fault is a weakness for taking things
that don't belong to them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Topkapi'': Long before Tom Cruise dangled from the ceiling
in ``Mission: Impossible,'' this classic heist film pulled off the
same heart-stopping stunt. An international cast, led by Melina
Mercouri, Maximilian Schell and Peter Ustinov, teams up to steal a
priceless jewel-encrusted dagger from a well-protected Turkish
museum (the title comes from the name of the museum). Another bit
of larceny: Ustinov took the best supporting actor Oscar away from
favorites Stanley Holloway (``My Fair Lady'') and John Gielgud
(``Becket'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``How to Steal a Million'': Audrey Hepburn and Peter O'Toole,
two of the most talented and beautiful people ever to grace a movie
screen, dabble in a little art thievery. The top-notch supporting
cast includes Hugh Griffith, Eli Wallach and Charles Boyer.
Director William Wyler, whose credits range from ``Wuthering
Heights'' to ``Ben-Hur,'' pretty much summed up the film when,
before shooting began, he noted, ``We may not have the best script
in the world, but we're going first class.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gambit'': Shirley MacLaine had been given carte blanche to
choose her leading man for this glossy bit of fluff about a cat
burglar and a dancer who steal a statue from a reclusive
billionaire. Having just seen ``The Ipcress File,'' she chose
Michael Caine and thus was responsible for bringing him to
Hollywood. In her memoir, ``My Lucky Stars,'' she wrote that Caine
was, for all his partying, one of the hardest-working actors she'd
ever met. She also noted that, as he cut a swath through
Hollywood's female population, his major complaint was pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sneakers'': A surprising fizzle in theaters, this is just
the sort of neat-o movie that deserves a second life on video. A
ragtag team of techno-whizzes, who specialize in foiling security
systems, is sent on a government-mandated mission to steal a
mysterious black box. Robert Redford is the gang's smooth-operator
leader, with Sidney Poitier as his right-hand man, a former CIA
agent. Dan Aykroyd is appropriately dorky as a conspiracy geek;
David Straithairn is a blind audio genius; and the late River
Phoenix, playing a teenage hacker, shows some of what made him so
special. The director, Phil Alden Robinson (``Field of Dreams''),
fills the movie with countercultural humor and some
state-of-the-art fake-outs. In many ways, this is a better
``Mission: Impossible'' than the Cruise version.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Big Deal on Madonna Street'': Not all caper flicks are airy,
debonair affairs. Take, for example, this broadly comic Italian
picture, which focuses on a stunningly inept gang of burglars who
bumble their way through a store robbery. In a sense, the movie,
which nabbed a best foreign language film nomination, is a sendup
of the caper genre. But it works on more than just a satirical
level, in that it makes us care for its misbegotten would-be
thieves. Marcello Mastroianni, who plays one of the gang's leaders,
signed on mostly as a favor to his former theatrical colleague
Vittorio Gassman. The filmmakers figured that Mastroianni's star
power would give the film some needed box office insurance. Decades
later, Bob Fosse tried to remake it as a Broadway musical, but the
result was a resounding flop.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
