<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-EGGS-RECIPES13-C     04-12 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EGGS-RECIPES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eggs make a comeback
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beat egg whites until stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you've mastered this technique, you've got the foundation
for some of the world's most impressive dishes, from souffles, to
roulades, to meringues, to mousses, to angel food cakes.
</P>
<P>
   You needn't be intimidated. It's just a matter of timing.
Whether you use an electric mixer or _ if you've got the muscles
for it _ a hand whisk, what you are looking for is soft white peaks
with a satiny sheen that stand up when you lift the beater. If you
go overboard and whisk in too much air, the foam bubbles will burst
and the whites will have a lumpy, curdled appearance.
</P>
<P>
   A few other tips from ``The Good Egg'':
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use room-temperature eggs for greater volume.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When separating eggs, make sure no yolk gets into the white;
yolks contain fat, which can inhibit the foaming of beaten egg
whites. For the same reason, make sure the mixing bowl and beaters
are free of any grease.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Add a pinch of cream of tartar to help stabilize the whites so
they won't lose their volume and smooth texture if slightly
overbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   _Staff writers
</P>
<P>
   SOUFFLES AND MORE
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Classic Cheddar Cheese Souffle
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 30
to 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Beginners, start here. This recipe is simple and delicious. It's
sure to make you a souffle fan. We served it with roasted asparagus
and a beet salad; it would be great with any number of veggie
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Fine dry bread crumbs for the souffle dish
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, separated, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups grated cheddar cheese (about 5 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg white, at room
</P>
<P>
   temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   Position a rack in the center of the oven and preheat the oven
to 400 degrees. Generously butter a 6-cup souffle dish. Sprinkle
lightly with bread crumbs, shaking the dish to coat evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a small saucepan over low heat. Add the flour
and cook, stirring constantly, for 3 minutes. Gradually whisk in
the milk and bring to a boil, stirring constantly. Cook, stirring
constantly, for 3 minutes more. Stir in the mustard, salt and
pepper to taste. Remove from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk the egg yolks until blended. Whisk in a
little of the white sauce to temper the eggs, then add the
remaining sauce, whisking until blended. Stir in the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Place the egg whites in a large bowl, add the cream of tartar
and beat slowly with an electric mixer until soft peaks form.
Increase the speed to high and beat until the peaks are stiff and
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Using a rubber spatula, transfer about one-third of the egg
whites to the cheese mixture and gently fold in until blended. Add
the remaining whites to the cheese mixture and gently fold until
blended. Pour into the prepared dish.
</P>
<P>
   Put the souffle in the oven and reduce the oven temperature to
375 degrees. Bake until puffed and golden, 30 to 35 minutes. If you
like your souffle firm in the center, bake it for 5 minutes more.
Serve at once. _ From ``The Good Egg'' by Marie Simmons
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 367 calories, 20 grams protein, 28 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 69), 8 grams carbohydrates, 307
milligrams cholesterol, 610 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reagan Walker
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Spinach Roulade
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 main-dish servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking
time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Roulades are like savory jellyrolls; souffle batter is spread in
a shallow pan and baked. It's then spread with a filling, rolled
and sliced. This version, good hot or cold, makes a pretty and
tasty first course or brunch dish.
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces chopped spinach
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup ( 1/4 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons shredded cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   6 scallions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces peeled shrimp, cooked and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Wilt the spinach in butter for 3
minutes. Remove from heat. Add the seasoning, cheddar cheese and
egg yolks; mix. Whisk the egg whites until stiff, then fold them
into the mixture. Pour the mixture into a parchment-lined jellyroll
pan and bake for 10 minutes until set.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the roulade out of the pan and onto a serving plate. Gently
remove parchment. In a large bowl, blend the remaining ingredients;
spread evenly over the roulade. Roll up like a jellyroll and serve
immediately. _ From ``Essentials: Egg'' by Jane Donovan
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 406 calories, 22 grams protein, 33 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 73), 6 grams carbohydrates, 360
milligrams cholesterol, 419 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Orange Meringue Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 35
minutes Cooling time: 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Egg yolks are used for the curd filling and egg whites for the
meringue in this twist on the classic lemon meringue pie. The
updated meringue technique is based on the American Egg Board's
recommendation for safe handling of egg whites. Look for the
premade crust in the baking aisle of your local grocery store, or
prepare as directed on a package of chocolate cookie crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4 cups freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1 prepared 9-inch chocolate-cookie or regular crust
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 1 teaspoon water
</P>
<P>
   Combine 1 cup of the sugar with cornstarch and salt in 4-quart
saucepan. Whisk in 1 1/2 cups of the orange juice and the lemon
juice. Cook over medium heat, stirring constantly, until mixture
thickens and sugar is completely dissolved, 10 minutes. Remove from
heat; whisk in butter. Stir in egg yolks and remaining orange
juice. Return to heat; simmer, continuing to whisk constantly,
until mixture is very thick, about 5 minutes. Pour into prepared
shell; cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Combine egg whites, remaining 1/2 cup
sugar, cream of tartar and water in top of double boiler. Cook over
simmering water, beating with portable mixer on medium speed, until
whites reach a temperature of 160 degrees, about 10 minutes. Pour
into large bowl; beat on high speed until whites stand in soft
peaks, about 2 minutes. Spread meringue on top of cooled filling,
covering filling completely.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 8-10 minutes, until meringue is golden. Chill until set,
about 3 hours. _From the Chicago Tribune
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 560 calories, 7 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 33), 90 grams carbohydrates, 155
milligrams cholesterol, 490 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
