<HEADER>
A4882 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-EGGS13-COX     04-12 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EGGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protein source regains its spot at mealtime
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend, who's trying to lose weight and get her blood sugar
back in whack, came back from an appointment with her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to eat more eggs,'' she said matter of factly. ``At
least three times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's the kind of irony that hits you like a pie in the
face: doctors prescribing eggs. How are you supposed to take them:
with a vodka chaser, a chaw of Skoal and a quick spritz of Agent
Orange?
</P>
<P>
   Aren't eggs _ high in cholesterol and teeming with bacteria _
considered by health professionals the worst of the worst?
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Recent studies have shown eggs aren't nearly as hard
on the arteries as once believed. In ``Eating Well for Optimum
Health'' (Knopf), Dr. Andrew Weil writes that the inclusion of eggs
in the diet actually ``makes an insignificant contribution to serum
cholesterol'' but provides ``an important source of the scarce
essential fatty acids.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the bacterial threat, better inspection programs have
resulted in fewer cases of illnesses related to salmonella in eggs.
And pasteurized eggs will be test marketed on the East Coast this
spring, making raw eggs once again safe to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have been quick to make amends. Thanks in part to
high-protein diets like my friend's, egg sales are the highest
they've been in 15 years. There are even several new cookbooks
solely devoted to egg recipes, such as ``The Good Egg: More Than
200 Fresh Approaches From Soup to Dessert'' by Marie Simmons
(Houghton Mifflin). Imagine that. Stylish, guilt-free eggs for
dinner. Spaghetti with tomato sauce, fried eggs and prosciutto.
Life is good.
</P>
<P>
   To fully appreciate the myriad eggy virtues, we need to master a
few basic techniques. As anyone who cooks for a family knows, a
million things can happen to an egg once you crack it into a hot
pan, and everyone has a personal preference. For one of my kids I
poach eggs. For another daughter I have a proprietary system for
``frambling'' eggs _ starting them as fried eggs, then breaking the
yolks and tossing them into a gooey strata of yellow and white. The
third will eat any egg cooked any way in bubbling butter.
</P>
<P>
   Even the basic fried egg is protean. Cooked over a gentle flame
and never allowed to brown, it becomes the ideal candidate for over
easy _ the white soft and slippery, the yolk pale and gushy.
</P>
<P>
   Now turn up the heat and the white gets tough, its albumin
congealing quickly and unpleasantly, pocked with bubbles. But turn
up the heat full force, and the white browns, becoming the crisp,
lacy basket for an avatar of sunny-side-up perfection.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just a simple fried egg for breakfast. Eggs leaven
cakes and souffles. Eggs emulsify oils in sauce. Eggs are so
versatile the word ``versatile'' barely begins to do them justice.
Let's take a look.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
