</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Egg whites make this cake a lightweight
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Josephine Debnar of Roswel, Ga., fondly recalls
chiffon cakes popular in the 1960s and '70s, and asked for a
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to angel food and sponge cakes, chiffon cakes rely on
eggs for lightness and air. But they are the richest of the three
because they include oil, which is incorporated into the batter,
and then added to beaten egg whites carefully so the air whipped
into the whites is not lost.
</P>
<P>
   This basic cake is from the 11th edition of ``Better Homes and
Gardens New Cookbook'' and has been published here before.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chiffon Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 70 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups sifted cake flour or 2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   7 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely shredded
</P>
<P>
   orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely shredded
</P>
<P>
   lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Mix flour, sugar, baking powder and salt in a large mixing bowl.
Make a well in the center of the dry mixture. Add oil, egg yolks,
orange peel, lemon peel, vanilla and water. Beat with an electric
mixer on low speed until combined. Beat on high speed 5 minutes
more or until satin-smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly wash and dry the beaters. In a separate, extra-large
mixing bowl, beat egg whites and cream of tartar on medium speed
until stiff peaks form. Pour flour batter in a thin stream over
beaten egg whites; fold in gently. Pour into an ungreased 10-inch
tube pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 65 to 70 minutes or until top springs back when lightly
touched. Immediately invert cake, leaving it in pan. Cool
thoroughly. Loosen sides of cake from pan; remove cake.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 291 calories, 5 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 40 grams carbohydrates, 124
milligrams cholesterol, 173 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   Gean Terrell of south Fulton County lost a magazine recipe from
about 10 years ago for main-dish Chinese New Year's Rice. She
remembers it as simple, tasty and including cubed chicken. Sound
familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Quittis Taylor of Ellenwood, Ga., would like a copy of a recipe
from more than 30 years ago called either Glorious Rice or Heavenly
Rice _ a dessert with Minute Rice, pineapple and whipping cream,
but no coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Published recipes
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of a recipe previously published in the newspaper,
call the Stacks at 404-526-5668.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
