<HEADER>
A4884 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-SCRAMBLED-EGGS13-COX     04-12 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCRAMBLED-EGGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scrambled eggs
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Egg-in-a-Hole
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, my brother, Wayne, wouldn't lift a finger in the
kitchen, though as I recall he ate well and quite a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcia, make me an egg-in-a-hole,'' I still hear him pleading.
</P>
<P>
   But that was more years ago than either of us cares to remember,
supplanted only recently by a delightful discovery. Wayne now cooks
eggs-in-a-hole at his Roswell, Ga., home about once a week when
he's not on the road, but he also holds forth at the stove managing
a couple of hot skillets for a 36-egg-in-a-hole brunch in
Charleston with a dozen tennis-playing buddies every spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``My secret is that I use more butter than anybody in the
world,'' he claims, a fact to which his wife, Mary, attests. ``I
put lots in the pan, then butter one side of the bread, then tear a
hole the size of a yolk in the bread.''
</P>
<P>
   The round-top squishy white bread goes buttered-side-up into the
skillet full of hot melted butter. Then he cracks an egg into the
hole and fries that side. When it's good and crispy, he flips it,
adds a few shakes of Tabasco sauce and salt and pepper, then pokes
a couple of holes in the yolk so it will cook through, and fries
until that side is crispy. ``Because I'm cooking so many, I cook
them the way I like them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot with Bloody Marys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get much better than that,'' Wayne says, noting
that his cooking secrets are the only secrets that he will divulge
about the tennis-week gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Fried egg sandwich
</P>
<P>
   Our grandmother was the first to make eggs-in-a-hole for us, but
Wayne was the one who appreciated the concept.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I am not a particularly particular eater, but to me eggs
are simple: They should be white and yellow and never, ever brown.
An egg left to brown turns into a completely different animal to my
taste. It's like burning the toast. And since eggs are just about
as cheap as toast, you just have to give them to the dog or the
brother and start over.
</P>
<P>
   But a fried egg that stays white and yellow, now that is a work
of art. Many's the night I've feasted on my all-time favorite
sandwich, perfected after I learned how to fry a brownless egg:
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1 teaspoon butter in a nonstick skillet over medium-low
heat. Crack an egg into the pan and reduce heat to low. Sprinkle
with black pepper. Cook slowly until all the white is set and
bright white. Flip egg, then poke the yolk to break so it will cook
through. Top with a slice of Swiss cheese. Sprinkle with a teaspoon
of cold water, cover with a lid that leaves room for steam to
escape and cook 3 to 4 minutes or until yellow is cooked through,
cheese is melted and nothing is brown. Put egg on one slice of
white bread. Spread second slice of bread with 1/2 tablespoon
Miracle Whip salad dressing, swirl on about 1 teaspoon ketchup, add
a leaf of dark green lettuce, close sandwich and open mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
