<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Bluffton, S.C.
 &HT;    Palmetto State town booming, but charm remains
 &HT;    By Susan Soper
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUFFTON, S.C. _ Gone are the days when you could blow through
Bluffton en route to Hilton Head beaches and barely slow down. It's
no longer just a drive-through speed trap with quaint curb appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are discovering what we always knew we had _ and tried
to hide,'' says Babbie Guscio, a lifelong Blufftonian sometimes
called the mother of Bluffton (as well as social director, event
planner and owner of the Store). ``Bluffton is like what the gold
rush in California must have been like: `There's gold in them thar
hills!'''
</P>
<P>
   In the past couple of years, growth and development have gone
what some call ``berserk,'' and that means commerce can't be far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's all relative. S.C. 46, also known as May River Road,
which leads into the one-square-mile town (population 800) can't
compare with U.S. 41 heading north into Marietta, Ga. But Bluffton,
settled in 1825 as a summer resort on the banks of the lush May
River, is booming. (The town has recently annexed 22,000 acres of
undeveloped property, making it the fifth-largest and least
populated town in South Carolina.)
</P>
<P>
   There wouldn't be Wall Street Journal boxes in the grocery store
parking lot if there weren't bags of money nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The construction of the Talmadge Bridge from Savannah in 1926
was the first development to have a major impact on Bluffton _
ending trade by water in the riverside town and turning it into a
summer getaway. The nearby retirement community Sun City Hilton
Head has also had a big impact: It has brought to the area more
than 1,300 households of the 8,000 planned.
</P>
<P>
   While on one hand Blufftonians may groan that their peaceful
place is unalterably changing, their other hands are out to welcome
new settlers and visitors and accept their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get people coming from all over the world, timing their
arrival and departure so as not to get in the mess surrounding
Hilton Head,'' says potter Jacob Preston. ``People who want to see
what actual South Carolina is like. And they're usually pleasantly
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   While strolling through Bluffton we discovered ...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Store has been in continuous use for almost 100 years,
over 20 of them as ``a stylish state of mind'' run by Babbie
Guscio. Find reproduction weathervanes like the red enameled goat
($140), objets d'art, costume jewelry, china, lamps. April through
September, fresh produce and homemade baked goods are sold in the
front yard. 56 Calhoun St. 843-757-3855
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eggs 'n Tricities is sometimes called ``the Bloomingdale's of
Bluffton.'' Items include a wooden bench ($750) _ a perfect perch
from which to watch the comings and goings at ``Eggs,'' a former
gas station filled with doodads (a cherry-painted lunch box, $31);
clothes (Flax, Bluefish, Marteeni); folk art (a carved wood
chicken, left, $40); and jewelry. 71 Calhoun St. 843-757-3446. &QR;  Red
Stripe Gallery is really an outdoor collection of motorcycles
serendipitously assembled from odds and ends by
builder-welder-artist Bill Sease. 11 a.m.-4 p.m. Saturdays. 59
Calhoun St. 843-837-2318. &QR;  Crossroads Fine Art &AMP; Framing.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much development and new houses mean empty walls,'' says
Jon Nelson, assistant manager of Crossroads Fine Art &AMP; Framing.
``More and more people are finding us on their way to Hilton
Head.'' Original art, prints, gifts. ``Canopy II'' by Jon Nelson
($625). 107 Towne Center, Mellichamp Road. 843-757-5551. &QR;  Jacob
Preston Gallery, the former Bluffton Tabernacle, is now home,
studio and gallery to the Lowcountry's premier potter. If you stop
by for a soup tureen, bowl or platter and he's not around, don't
miss the note he leaves: ``Hello, I had to leave. Please help
yourself. Leave check or note. Thanks, Jacob.'' Semi-glazed and
oxided high-fire stoneware jar ($350). 10 Church St. 843-757-3084. &QR; 
Stock Farm Antiques Center houses several antiques vendors
including May River Designs (hand-painted red folk art lamp, $315),
with rugs, huntboards, rockers, porcelains, planters and art.
1263-B May River Road. 843-757-8046.If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From Atlanta, take I-75 south to I-16 east at
Macon to I-95. Go north on I-95 to Exit 8, U.S. 278, and follow
that to S.C. 46, Bluffton Road. The intersection of 46 and Calhoun
is the commercial and historic heart of Bluffton.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Generally, shops are open 10 a.m.-6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are on one level, with few if
any steps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: A few stores have parking lots; otherwise, park on
the street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Area restaurants, filling stations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Heyward House, 52 Boundary St. 843-757-6293.Where
to stay
</P>
<P>
   There aren't any overnight accommodations in the one-square-mile
town yet, but chances are you will be heading for Savannah
(Convention and Visitors Bureau, 1-877-728-2662) or Hilton Head
Island (Visitor and Convention Bureau, 1-800-523-3373). Beaufort
and Charleston are also close enough for a day trip to Bluffton.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   As you pass through town, Squat 'n Gobble practically jumps into
the road at you, but if you're looking for more than Silver
Skillet-type fare, there are other spots to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Squat 'n Gobble may be the second-most-photographed spot
in Bluffton _ after Church of the Cross. American food, burgers,
barbecue and pizza. 11 a.m.-9 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; 7 a.m.-9 p.m.
Saturdays; 8 a.m.-2 p.m. Sundays. 1231 May River Road.
843-757-4242.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sigler's Rotisserie and Seafood: Though this isn't technically
within the town limits, locals claim it as ``the best kept secret
of Bluffton,'' an intimate spot featuring fresh local seafood (as
well as lobsters flown in from Maine), rotisserie chicken, grilled
vegetable plate, grilled romaine salad with tomato dressing and a
good wine selection. Check out the chef's counter/wine bar, where
you can watch award-winning chef Michael Sigler in action.
4:30-9:30 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays. 12 Sheridan Park Circle (off U.S.
278 to Hilton Head Island). 843-815-5030.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Copper Kitchen. This good stop for breakfast and lunch
recently changed hands but is worth a try when you are looking for
something fast and casual. Closed Sundays. 5 Godfrey Place (outside
town). 843-815-4555.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pepper's Porch. Lowcountry seafood and culture, open for lunch
(11:30 a.m.-2:30 p.m.) and dinner Tuesdays through Sundays. 1255
May River Road. 843-757-2295.Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Heyward House, home to the Bluffton Historical Preservation
Society, is the starting point for a walking tour of antebellum and
post-Civil War homes and churches. Pick up a map of ``A Walk
Through Time'' and maybe catch some of the planned activities:
basket making, canoe making and local artists plying their crafts.
$3 adults. 10 a.m.-3 p.m. Wednesdays-Saturdays. 52 Boundary St.
843-757-6293.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Church of the Cross was designed by Edward Blake White and
constructed in 1854 on the banks of the May River for $5,000. It
was one of the few buildings to survive a Federal gunboat
bombardment in 1863 but was damaged during a storm in 1893. The
Episcopal church is on the National Register of Historic Places and
is the most photographed building in Bluffton. The church is not
officially open to the public but is planning to begin a docent
program soon to accommodate visitors. In the meantime, just knock
on the office door and someone will let you in to visit. 110
Calhoun St. 843-757-2661.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bluffton Oyster Co.: Until May 14, when oyster season ends,
the Bluffton Oyster Co. is worth a stop to watch the boats unload,
the women shuck and the soft shell crabs shed. It's one of the few
oyster factories still in operation on the eastern seaboard and
open to the public for retail. Larry Toomer, a third-generation
seafood worker, proudly says, ``nothing arrives or leaves here by
truck.'' 8:30 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; 10 a.m.-4 p.m.
Saturdays. 63 Wharf St. 843-757-4010.Annual events
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Through Sunday: MCI Classic _ The Heritage of Golf on Hilton
Head Island. 1-800-234-1107.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monday through April 23: Family Circle Cup Women's
Championship Tennis Tournament on Hilton Head. 1-800-677-2293.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 5-31: Bluffton Images Art Show, a juried exhibition on
view at Heyward House. 843-757-3855.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 13: Mayfest (always the Saturday before Mother's Day) is a
social street party up and down Calhoun Street. Church of the Cross
is famous for shrimp salad sandwiches (gone by 11 a.m.). Also,
vendors galore; and potter Jacob Preston will be at his wheel.
843-757-3855.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 2: Christmas Parade featuring the Ladies Drill (as in
Black &AMP; Decker) Team, the Daddies Baby Buggie Brigade, the Branager
Bluff Bubba Ballet (in camouflage and pink tutus) as well as an
oyster roast and bazaar. 843-757-3855.
</P>
<P>
   Shop talk
</P>
<P>
   Antiques/furniture
</P>
<P>
   Antiques and the Garden, S.C. 46
</P>
<P>
   Bluffton Antiques and Gifts, S.C. 46 (next to Pepper's Porch)
</P>
<P>
   Calibogue House Furniture, S.C. 46
</P>
<P>
   Art galleries
</P>
<P>
   Crossroads Fine Art &AMP; Framing, Mellichamp Road
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Preston Gallery, Church Street
</P>
<P>
   Red Stripe Gallery, Calhoun Street
</P>
<P>
   Gifts
</P>
<P>
   Eggs 'n Tricities, Calhoun Street
</P>
<P>
   Fine Jewelry of Bluffton, S.C. 46
</P>
<P>
   The Store, Calhoun Street
</P>
<P>
   Children's apparel
</P>
<P>
   Big Yellow Dog, Calhoun Street
</P>
<P>
   Miscellaneous
</P>
<P>
   Bluffton Package Shop, S.C. 46
</P>
<P>
   Nearly New, S.C. 46
</P>
<P>
   May River Orchids (greenhouses), Confederate Avenue
</P>
<P>
   Susan Soper is A.M.E. for the Features Department at the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
