<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking the breast cancer message to African-Americans
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Karen Jackson was diagnosed and treated for breast cancer
seven years ago, she emerged from the ordeal with not only a good
prognosis but a commitment to changing the future for other
African-American women. She realized that much more needed to be
done to decrease breast cancer mortality rates of African-American
women. While whites develop breast cancer at higher rates than
blacks, the death rate for African-American women is 22 percent
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, of Houston, founded Sisters Network Inc., a nonprofit
organization with 1,000 members (all breast cancer survivors) and
25 chapters across the country. Its national conference is in
Atlanta Friday through Sunday. Staff writer Patricia Guthrie spoke
with Jackson as she prepared for ``The Journey to Healing and
Wholeness'' conference.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Lack of early detection of the cancer is one of the main
reasons given for the mortality disparity between black and white
women. But there are numerous educational campaigns about the
importance of getting mammograms and doing breast self-exams. Why
does early detection remain such a problem among African- American
women?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because as much as people think there is a lot of information
out there, it's not really getting to the people most in need.
There are numerous reasons for the disparity, such as not as much
access to what's available. Also, things are in place
institutionally that don't work for us. We know African-American
women are dying from breast cancer at an earlier age, yet the
recommended age for having the first mammogram is age 40. So, if
you're under 40, and you're African-American, and you feel a lump,
you will be told you're too young for tests.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What more could be done?
</P>
<P>
   A: Making people aware. As a breast cancer survivor, and being
with an African-American group, African-American women do stop and
listen. They do hear the message as: `This could be you.' Early
detection does work, also, and we need to do more to help dispel
the fear that when you go in and find out about cancer, you die.
</P>
<P>
   The Sisters Network Inc. conference at the Renaissance Concourse
Hotel features workshops and panel discussions, Friday through
Sunday. $150 for three days or $100 for Saturday; includes
breakfast, lunch and banquet; register at the door. Information on
Sisters Network: 1-713-781-0255; Atlanta chapter, 770-469-0343, or
www.sistersnetworkinc.org.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : Join a 24-hour telephone support network for
breast cancer survivors: www.accessatlanta.com
</P>
<P>
   /community/groups/breastfriends/
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
