r l BC-SPAS-TRENDS13-COX     04-12 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAS-TRENDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day Spas: The Inside Story
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ That collective ``ahhh'' you hear is from a team of 10
intrepid journalists who eagerly loaned our bodies to science _ the
science of relaxation. We fanned out from Kennesaw, Ga., to
Peachtree City, Ga., Atlanta to Lawrencub and a chair with
three-way massage feature, which feels great but is rather loud.
The treatment includes a paraffin wax dip, which is designed to
maximize the skin's ability to lock in moisture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: After an hour and 15 minutes of soaking,
sloughing, oiling and massaging in the capable hands of a young
woman named Susanne, my little piggies _ sporting Confucius Says
Coral from O.P.I.'s Far East Collection _ went ``oui, oui, oui''
all the way home. My peds felt downright silky, and my usually dry
heels felt soft as a baby's bottom.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: Totally relaxing and satisfactory. I
l). Pregnancy massage ($65). A dozen facials including Aromatherapy
($70) and Sea Toning ($70). Sea Salt Glow ($45). Seaweed body wrap
($80). Spa manicure ($20). Sea spa foot treatment ($50).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE PRODUCTS: Skin care, cosmetic and aromatherapy products
used in treatments and sold here are generally formulated with pure
fruit, flower and herb essences. The Natural Body Spa Basics Face &AMP;
Body Care line is available. Other brands used and sold include
Aveda, the Thymes and Jurlique. There's a nice selection of Burt's
Bees products, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE AMBIENCE: Natural Body is known for its serene, New Age-y,
slightly funky atmosphere that is totally unpretentious. Lighting
is low; temperature just right; linens pristine. There's a peaceful
hush _ only the slightest hint of music in the background _
throughout the shop/waiting area and the treatment rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: I tried the signature aromatherapy facial,
which included general cleansing, a hydrating masque and massage of
the face, head, neck and shoulders. Be aware that the one-hour
facial also includes ``extraction,'' shorthand for removal of the
gunk clogging up your pores. This can be slightly painful and is
controversial among some aestheticians because it can cause broken
capillaries, breakouts and scarring if done incorrectly. My
facialist asked lots of questions first, then used gloves and was
very gentle _ obviously well-trained.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: Floating for days afterward. My skin was left
soft, hydrated and with a pretty glow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: A return trip is in order. Personnel
here are friendly in a quiet, gentle sort of way. Even though
Natural Body is also a store, there is no hard-sell when you leave
(despite the checklist of what you should be doing to your skin
each day). And the facial was unimpeachable.
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Sabulis,
</P>
<P>
   for the Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   SPA SYDELL
</P>
<P>
   10593 Old Alabama Road Connector,
</P>
<P>
   Alpharetta ( at Mansell Point). 770-552-1880.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS: 9 a.m.-9 p.m. Monday-Saturday; 11 a.m.-7 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SELECTED SERVICES : Hot stone massage ($85). Body massage ($65
for 60 minutes). Thermomineral mask facial ($89), pumpkin peel
($89). Seaweed wrap ($55), hydromassage tub (soak and massage
$57.50). French manicure ($21.50). Pedicure ($38). Body paraffin
($65). Reflexology ($50).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  PRODUCTS: The spa has its own line of products for the face
and body. They also offer a variety of other lines as well as
candles and bath products.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AMBIENCE: Contemporary with muted colors and subdued lighting.
A fountain flows in the lobby, where there is a check-in counter
and products displayed. The seats are comfortable and there is soft
music playing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: Greeted promptly at my appointment time, I was
led to the cozy massage room. The stones _ actually lava that has
been tumbled perfectly smooth _ are kept in hot water. I was told
that this would be different from a more traditional Swedish or
sports massage in that it was more for relaxation than comfort for
sore muscles _ not as deep a massage as I was used to. First, I lay
face down and the massage therapist rubbed oil over my body to
allow the stones to move freely. Then he placed one stone, about 4
or 5 inches wide, at the base of my back and left it there to allow
the warmth to soak in. The stones varied in size from small pebbles
used on the face to about 5 or 6 inches across. After placing the
stone on my lower back, he proceeded to take a stone in each hand
and rub then across my back.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: The sensation of the warm, smooth stone gliding
across the oiled skin was wonderful and very relaxing. Some of the
stones were left in different places on my back while he smoothed
others along my neck and arms and legs. After I turned over onto my
back, he place one small, very cool pebble on each cheek and one
each on my chin and forehead. The small cool stones were very
soothing _ a nice contrast to the warm ones. For some reason, I was
very thirsty when it was over. No problem. I was greeted with a
cold glass of water on my way out.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE BOTTOM LINE: At just about an hour, I felt like the
treatment was just a warmup. Unfortunately, he spent very little
time on my feet and none on my hands. More time spent rubbing the
warm, smooth stones over my feet would have greatly added to the
experience. Overall though, the treatment was very relaxing _
almost meditative.
</P>
<P>
   _Jean Shifrin
</P>
<P>
   DASS _ DON &AMP; SYLVIA SHAW SPA
</P>
<P>
   Park Place, 4505 Ashford-Dunwoody Road. 770-393-8303,
www.donshaw.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS: 10 a.m.-7 p.m. Tuesdays-Fridays; 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SELECTED SERVICES: Spa Glow ($35). Seaweed Scrub with Vichy
Shower ($70). Seaweed Wrap with Hydro Tub ($70). Mud Wrap with
Hydro Tub ($70). Herbal Wrap ($35). Hydrotherapy Tub ($35).
Cellulite Treatment ($90). Aromatheraphy Steam Shower ($15). Single
Massage, one hour ($60).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE PRODUCTS: The spa has its own line of products for the
body and face. Mud is imported from Austria, seaweed from France.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE AMBIENCE: A sleek, functional spa, perhaps like one in
Sweden, done in wood and chrome. When I arrived, I was immediately
led to a tiny room to completely undress (save for a paper string
bikini bottom) and handed a short white terry robe and plastic
chartreuse shower slides.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: Mud wrap with hydro tub. The combo of mud, heat
and wrap is designed to help break down toxic deposits and make it
easier for the body to flush them away. (Some people think wraps
help them lose weight and inches as well, but this is subject to
debate.) First, aesthetician Sheryl Kedziora slathered black,
mineral-rich Moor mud all over my body. Next, with my arms at my
side, she wrapped me tightly, like a mummy, in a plastic sheet,
then a solar wrap (cellophane with a rubber back) and finally a
blanket heated to about 60 degrees. After applying a moistened
towel to my forehead, she lowered the lights, put on music from New
Ager Ottmar Liebert and left me to relax and sweat for 20 minutes.
By the end, I was feeling a bit claustrophobic.
</P>
<P>
   After the allotted time, Kedziora peeled off the layers and led
me to a ``wet'' room. The warm hydrotheraphy tub uses massage
therapy to relax your body. I was handed a pair of gloves and soap
to wipe off the mud and left alone for 25 minutes. The finishing
touches? Avocado lotion for my body, a glass of icy mineral water
and a cup of energy mix.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: I felt quite relaxed after my treatment. And my
skin was soothed and softened. But I didn't lose inches or pounds
and frankly, I don't know if any nasty toxins were pulled out of my
body or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: I would not do the mud wrap again. I
just didn't see or feel any benefits. But I would go to the spa for
a water massage, an aromatheraphy steam shower or for an hour
massage.
</P>
<P>
   _Marylin Johnson
</P>
