<P>
   ATLANTA: for an hour massage.
</P>
<P>
   _Marylin Johnson
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH MICHAEL SALON &AMP; DAY SPA
</P>
<P>
   2000 Riverside Parkway, Suite 101 (downstairs) Lawrenceville.
770-682-3706.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS: 10 a.m.-8 p.m. Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday; 10
a.m.-6 p.m. Friday; 9 a.m.-3 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SELECTED SERVICES: Manicure ($18), whirlpool footspa pedicure
($40); aromatherapy European facial ($65); back cleansing facial
($60); peppermint sea twist body treatment ($60); European seaweed
body treatment ($60); honey body polish ($60).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE PRODUCTS: For face and body the spa uses MD Formulations,
YonKa and O.P.I. nail products.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE AMBIENCE: Traditional styling with touches of Southern
flair_ emerald greens, lace and magnolias. Greeted right on time by
Theresa for my 10 a.m. Wednesday appointment, I am led to the body
treatment room. Shell-like wall sconces glow with an amber hue,
new-age music plays softly in the background, and two aromatherapy
candles burn with a heavenly scent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: I chose a European Seaweed Body Treatment
designed to tone muscles and remove toxins. Fearing that my
sensitive skin might make me look like lobster girl, I came by the
day before for a test patch _ which Theresa was more than willing
to do. At that time she thoroughly explained the procedure and
assured my modest self that although undressed, I would be covered
the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   She left me to settle in and returned with a knock. Undraping
only a small part of the body at a time, she slathered on warm
green seaweed. Then she wrapped a towel and mylar sheet around me
and tucked me in. She said to shout if felt at all claustrophobic,
which strangely I didn't. While in my makeshift papoose, Theresa
began massaging my face, neck and head pressure points. Slowly
pulling me up, she wrapped me in more towels and led me to the
shower across the empty hallway. I returned to a glass of water,
and fresh sheets on the table. I climbed in and after a knock, she
came in and smoothed lotion all over me.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: Relaxed? Beyond relaxed, I was mush. I couldn't
really feel the toxins taking mass exodus, but my skin did feel
smoother for a few days and I felt oh so pampered.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: A spa neophyte, I was pleasantly
surprised with the whole spa experience. I have already made
another appointment _ this time for a massage.
</P>
<P>
   _Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   KEN ARTHUR
</P>
<P>
   SALON &AMP; SPA
</P>
<P>
   1217 Canton Street in Roswell's historic district. 770-643-6737;
www.kenarthur.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS: 10 a.m.-7 p.m. Monday, Wednesday and Friday; 10:00
a.m.-8 p.m. Thursday; 9:00 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SELECTED SERVICES: Men's fitness facial ($55). Swedish massage
($35). Aromatherapy salt glo ($45). Seaweed botanical wrap ($75).
Manicure ($15, add $10 for paraffin wax dip). Aromatherapy scalp
treatment (from $25).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE PRODUCTS: Pevonia Botanica used exclusively for spa
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE AMBIENCE: This place makes the case for never judging a
spa by its cover. From the street it looks like a tiny house that
might serve as a spa only for Liliputians. However, the interior is
deceptively spacious and lush, the staff as down to earth as one
could hope.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: First, I indulged in a manicure capped by a
paraffin wax dip. Once my cuticles were snipped and nail technician
Nhan Vu massaged my hands and forearms with a brisk exfoliating
scrub, I was ushered past a small, plush waiting alcove to a
treatment room for the wax mixture. The bottle green melted wax was
scented with fragrant oils and I was surprised at how good it felt
as I plunged my hands into the warm, liquid wax. After three quick
dips, my hands were immediately placed in plastic bags and Vu
whisked me back to her manicure table where she stuffed my hands
into hot mitts. After about 10 minutes, she slipped the wax off as
easily as if she were peeling off a pair of gloves. The wax, which
acts as a lavish moisturizer, made my hands feel postiively dewy.
For my second treatment, I had an aromatherapy scalp massage.
Massage therapist and foot reflexologist Sue Ann Schlesinger dimmed
the lights and left me in the room with the soft glow from a
perfumed candle and low music in the background. She'd instructed
me to undress from the waist up and slip under the covers of the
massage table. Oil scented with extracts including lavander was
massaged onto my neck and shoulders, then the therapist worked her
way to my head, slowly massaging my temples and scalp. After about
40 minutes of this coddling, I was left alone to dress, then
offered a glass of cold water.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: Wonderful. I felt as limp as a boneless cat as I
was led to a shampoo bowl where someone washed and blow dried my
hair.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: As Arnold said, ``I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   _Sabine Morrow
</P>
<P>
   QUINTESSENCE
</P>
<P>
   3220 Peachtree Road N.E. Buckhead. 404-364-0474,
www.jurlique.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS: 10 a.m.-8 p.m. Monday-Friday; 10 a.m.-7 p.m. Saturday;
Sunday reserved for group bookings of six or more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SELECTED SERVICES: ``Lavender Relax'' mineral oil exfoliation
and massage ($35). ``Simple Elegance'' aromatherapy facial ($70).
Aromatherapy enhanced manicure ($30). Massage therapy (30 minutes,
$40). ``Back facial'' exfoliation ($45). Waxing ($15-$60).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE PRODUCTS: Jurlique line of cosmetics, cleansing lotions,
skin conditioners, aromatherapy oils, face masks and hydrating
sprays. Plant-based, not tested on animals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE AMBIENCE: Outside: Well-kept two-story colonial house.
Inside: Sleek hardwood floors, oriental rugs, soft amber lighting
and a pastel color scheme create a luxurious first impression.
Ornate, green wrought-iron tables give the consultation parlor the
look of a tea room.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: The Sanctorum sound and aroma therapy, one hour
for $45. I am led into a large, forest green room upstairs and
seated in a gray leather chair that resembles an oversize,
ergonomically curved shoe insole. The spa director, Brooke
Robertson, hands me a pair of headphones, places a few drops of
``Tranquility Blend'' oil into an aromatherapy evaporator and pops
a CD into the player. As she leaves the room, I am enveloped in the
sounds of rain and thunder, and in the smells of lemon and
lavendar. Suddenly, I feel the thunder in my legs _ a series of
woofers within the chair is sending rhythmic vibrations directly
into parts of my body. Native American-style drums erupt, and I
feel their pulse in my neck and lower back. The visceral soundtrack
prods me with upbeat, insistent percussion, then later bathes me in
tranquil New Age keyboard washes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: Nirvana. (The state of mind, not the band.) The
vibrations warmed and soothed my neck, legs, back and other
stressed-out body points. The dramatic music focused my mind away
from work and traffic and I entered a floating, dreamlike state.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: Anyone who has ever put on a CD to
relax after a hard day at the office will love this: It's like
being inside the music. Guest can arrange to bring their own CD,
but the spa recommends their own carefully orchestrated treatment.
So do I. This is one musical experience that will leave your body
and mind in complete harmony.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   BODY IMAGING _ THE DAY SPA
</P>
<P>
   2615 George Busbee Parkway, Kennesaw 770-422-9000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS: 10 a.m.-8 p.m. Monday, Wednesday-Friday; 9 a.m.-7 p.m.
Saturday; noon-6 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SELECTED SERVICES: Facials: regular ($55); anti-aging ($70);
acne ($65); teens ($40); peels ($25-$55). Spa massage ($60).
Hydrating steam mudwrap with massage ($100). Pregnancy massage
($65). Manicure ($15). Pedicure ($35). Add $5 for paraffin
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE PRODUCTS: Essentiel Elements for body and aromatherapy
products; PeterThomas Roth for skin care; Matrix for makeup.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AMBIENCE: The decorating style is no-frills modern in white,
black and blue. The lighting in the main waiting area is rather
bright because of the light that streams in from the large
storefront windows. Black leather sofas are positioned opposite
product display cases along the front wall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: I chose the sugar glow bath and massage package
called the spa retreat. The mixture (sugar, oil and bath gel)
exfoliates the skin, leaving it softened and moisturized. First, I
was led to a massage room where I put on a robe and slippers. Then
Melissa took me to the Vichy Shower Room where I stretched out on
an elevated table underneath a series of five shower heads. I
started out lying on my back and Melissa rubbed the mixture over
most of my body, rinsing it off with a strong stream of warm
water.Then she used the shower nozzles for a final head-to-toe
rinsing. Next, I flipped over to repeat the process. The scent of
rosemary was very pleasant and the roughness of the sugar granules
was invigorating on my skin. When she applied the mixture, the
massage techniques were so relaxing that her steady hand was a
welcome help when I had to get off the table.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 minutes later we went back to the massage room. I was
treated to a 60-minute massage as the sound of rain falling in a
thunderstorm played on a CD player.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: I was completely relaxed. I liked the tingly,
clean feeling I had after the bath and my skin felt soft from the
oils and lotions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: The staff was very friendly and
helpful. The receptionist who answered my initial inquiry spent a
good deal of time with me on the phone, helping me decide what
service I'd enjoy the most. I would return for the same treatment,
something my sun-damaged skin would appreciate on a bimonthly
basis.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Candice Hannigan, for the Atlanta-Journal Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LIME PIE
</P>
<P>
   806 N. Highland Ave. , Atlanta. 404-873-6512.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS: 10 a.m.-5:30 p.m., Tuesdays; 11 a.m.-6:30 p.m.,
Wednesdays; 9 a.m.-7:30 p.m. Thursdays and Fridays; 9 a.m.-4:30
p.m., Saturdays; 10 a.m.-5:30 p.m., Sundays. Closed Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SELECTED SERVICES: Aquatherapy body polish ($85); aquatherapy
aroma body wrap ($85); essential back treatment ($60); deluxe
whirlpool pedicure treatment ($40); pure full body massage with two
massage therapists (starting at $120).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE PRODUCTS: Aveda for everything from skin to hair; O.P.I.
for nails.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE AMBIENCE: You wouldn't know the spa is right next to Key
Lime Pie's bustling retail store, it's so quiet, with walls draped
in heavy, neutral fabrics, dim lights, hot tea brewing and pastries
on the coffee table. New Age-style music is everpresent _
unfortunately, it was so loud in my treatment room I could barely
hear the therapist ask which aromatherapy scents I wanted blended
in my massage oil. My treatment room had exposed brick walls and
small windows open to let in the light. Would be a nice touch if
the spa were on a Tuscan hillside; unfortunately in this case, the
room overlooked (and I could overhear) a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE TREATMENT: A one-hour massage. Unlike many other spas, Key
Lime Pie doesn't outline a variety of treatments _ just a ``pure
full body massage.'' When asked why, the receptionist said ``you
just discuss it with your therapist.'' My therapist, however,
didn't offer me options (Swedish, deep tissue, etc.) but simply
asked why I had come in. I told him that basically I wanted a
massage, that my neck and upper back were tight. He said okay and
went to work, asking me if the pressure was alright. Because I've
had a lot of massages, I knew what I wanted, but had I been a
novice, I may have wanted more information up front.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE RESULTS: The massage was very good _ he had worked pretty
hard through some tight spots, but I felt relaxed,
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE OVERALL EXPERIENCE: Good. Lots of pampering _ from people
bringing you water or tea to personalizing your own massage oil to
offers of the steam room and shower (complete with Aveda products)
after your session.
</P>
<P>
   _Robbyn Footlick
</P>
