<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CHINA-RALLY-0413-COX     04-12 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RALLY-0413-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LABOR ACTIVISTS RALLY AGAINST CHINA TRADE PACT
 &HT;    By ALEC SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Capitol Hill echoed with shouts of ``No Blank Check
for China!'' as thousands of union activists Wednesday urged
Congress to oppose a landmark trade agreement with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Commerce Secretary William Daley released a report
asserting that the measure, if approved, would benefit every state.
</P>
<P>
   The union demonstrators included members of the AFL-CIO, the
United Auto Workers, the United Steelworkers and the Teamsters.
Crowd estimates ranged from 5,000 to 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   They are targeting the agreement, championed by President
Clinton, that would grant permanent normal trade relations to
China, whose trade status is currently subject to annual
congressional review. Clinton says the agreement, if approved by
Congress, would expand U.S. trade with China and pave the way for
its entry into the Geneva-based World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions counter that the deal would benefit only corporate
interests and that hundreds of thousands of U.S. jobs would be lost
to low-paid Chinese workers.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives is scheduled to vote on the
legislation the week of May 22, and the unions are determined to
round up enough votes _ mostly from undecided Democrats _ to defeat
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have enough votes to defeat it,'' said Teamsters
President James Hoffa, but he acknowledged that it will be a tough
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions oppose the trade bill because they believe that
China violates worker and human rights, shackles religious freedom,
pollutes the environment, and prohibits freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our workers are forced to compete with prison labor and
sweatshop workers making as little as 13 cents an hour. And while
we are losing hundreds of thousands of jobs, China is setting new
records for violations of human rights and polluting the
environment,'' AFL-CIO President John Sweeney told demonstrators at
a noontime rally on the grounds of the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared its approval when Sweeney added: ``Until there
is freedom of speech and freedom of association in China, until
there is freedom of religion and freedom to join unions in China,
there can be no permanent free trade agreement with China.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders spent the day lobbying members of Congress to vote
against the trade bill, focusing in particular on the undecided
House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., spoke at the rally
and promised to carry organized labor's fight to his colleagues in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior is leading the effort in Congress to defeat the trade
bill. ``We're for an America that doesn't give the back of its hand
to people who work with their hands. With this agreement, some
people will get ahead. But the bottom line is that most of us stand
to get left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   He also asserted that China's current government does not
protect worker rights and personal freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rewarding a Chinese government that thumbs its nose at those
values would be the wrong choice for America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called the trade bill ``a 100% win for America.''
</P>
<P>
   In a White House statement released Tuesday, Clinton said
congressional rejection of the trade agreement ``would have
extremely harmful consequences for our national security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese will see rejection as a strategic decision by the
United States to turn from cooperation to confrontation, to deal
with China as an adversary,'' the president continued. He also said
rejection would embolden hard-liners in China's leadership. He
described them as ``the same forces most threatened by our
alliances with Japan and Korea, the same forces that want the
Chinese military to sell dangerous technologies and the same forces
that would pursue confrontation with Taiwan rather than dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the union leaders and several members of Congress said
Wednesday they believe that even if the deal passes, China will
renege on its share of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney noted that the United States has negotiated four trade
agreements with China, but he said ``China has repeatedly violated
all four agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior reiterated that theme as he asked the assembled crowd:
``Is it a 100% win for America when the Chinese government treats
the agreements they've already signed as if they're not worth the
paper they're written on?''
</P>
<P>
   The union activists are part of a coalition of group who will
stage anti-globalization protests in Washington through the weekend
as the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank hold their
spring meetings. They are hoping to repeat the success of
protestors who disrupted World Trade Organizations meetings last
year in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this report)
</P>
<P>
   (Alec Schultz can be reached by e-mail at: alecs(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
