<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE13-COX     04-12 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH CARE TAKES CENTER STAGE IN PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    With GORE-PARDON. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What to do about the 44 million Americans who lack
health insurance emerged Wednesday as the latest battleground in
the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the American Society of Newspaper Editors, Vice
President Al Gore accused Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his
presumed Republican rival for the White House, of ``political
malpractice'' for proposing a tax credit of up to $2,000 a family
to help working people buy health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, finally Governor Bush said he wants to do something
about health care,'' Gore told the editors. He urged them to
carefully scrutinize the plan, which would cost the U.S. Treasury
about $40 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome him to the debate,'' Gore added. ``I hope he will
start by trying to enroll some of the hundreds of thousands of
uninsured children and families in his own state of Texas who have
no health insurance (and) who are legally eligible for it, but do
not have it because of the political malpractice of the Bush
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we believe what he says he would do nationally, when
we see what he has done as governor?'' Gore asked.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush made his second health care proposal in as many
days by announcing at a St. Louis campaign stop a $4.3 billion plan
to tighten the ``safety net'' for needy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's latest five-year proposal is aimed at helping uninsured
people in medically underserved and remote areas, such as
inner-city neighborhoods and rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult places to build a quality health care
facility are the very areas where the need is greatest and where
patients have the least ability to pay,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore remained mightily unimpressed, calling on the editors
to ``look closely at what Governor Bush proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been estimated that his plan costs about the same as
mine. Yet it covers about one-third as many people _ and only
one-tenth of the Americans who are uninsured.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked in St. Louis if he wanted to respond to Gore's attack,
Bush said: ``Not right now, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer brushed off the vice
president's comments, maintaining that the expected Republican
challenger has made progress in health care and the environment in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worse Al Gore is doing in the polls, the more he attacks
and misrepresents the governor's record,'' said Fleischer, buoyed
by new national surveys that show Bush once again taking the lead
against the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon Al Gore will say he invented health care,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on a broader plane, Gore, the presumptive Democratic
nominee told the editors that Bush ``wants us to believe he's
committed to issues like education, health care and the
environment. Let's face it. The Bush approach on these issues is a
headline without a story.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also said he would accept a
presidential-debate invitation from any newspaper editor attending
the convention. Tom Koenninger, the editor of the Columbian, a
small-circulation newspaper in Vancouver, Wash., promptly invited
him to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept,'' Gore said. ``But it's your job, not mine, to see
to it that Governor Bush shows up too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has challenged Bush to debate him twice a week, said,
``If he thinks it's a bluff, all he has do to is call it.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, Fleischer said: ``We are looking forward to the debate
with Al Gore (later this year) on education, health care, taxes and
honesty and integrity in government.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.algore2000.com, www.georgebush.com,
www.asne.org.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
