<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4894 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-BROWN-ANIMATION-A     04-12 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BROWN-ANIMATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL JUST ONE JAMES BROWN, BUT AN AVATAR COULD RAISE DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Calif. _ In a single-story, wooden building about the
size of a mobile home, crammed ceiling to floor with wildly
expensive and exotic computer hardware and software, sits a group
of artists, animators and technicians trying hard to conjure up the
spirit of James Brown, the Godfather of Soul, circa 1963.
</P>
<P>
   For the last seven months the computer wizards of Digital
Domain, a company in Venice, Calif., that has made special effects
for films like ``Apollo 13,'' ``True Lies'' and ``Titanic,'' have
been trying to create a convincing, animated double of the
self-proclaimed Hardest-Working Man in Show Business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to make it definitively James Brown,'' said
Caleb Owens, computer generation supervisor of the project, as the
synthetic soul singer sprang to life on several nearby computer
monitors. ``It cannot just look like James Brown. It's got to have
the attitude, it's got to have the soul, got to have the truth that
is this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   While computer animation has become a mainstay of popular films,
television shows and commercials, the dizzyingly complex
application of refined, computer-generated imagery is pushing the
boundaries of what has been done before, Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have done computer-generated people before,'' said
Andre Bustanoby, the project's visual effects supervisor. ``We've
done it on Titanic. But this is taking it to the bleeding edge of
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   If the computer-generated rendering is finished on schedule, the
digital James Brown, complete with authentic yelps, grunts and
grimaces, will be installed in a interactive popular-music museum
that is set to open in Seattle on June 23. The 140,000-square-foot
museum, called the Experience Music Project, was founded by Paul G.
Allen, co-founder of Microsoft and now a major investor in new
media, and his sister, Jody Allen Patton.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the museum, which was designed by the architect Frank
Gehry, is being filled with exhibitions and artifacts that tell the
story of rock 'n' roll from its roots through its permutations _
rhythm and blues, jazz, grunge, soul, funk and hip-hop music. Key
among 1,200 artifacts on display, the museum's curators said, will
be 55 vintage guitars, including the white Fender Stratocaster
played by Jimi Hendrix at Woodstock in the summer of 1969, and
pages of handwritten lyrics by musicians like Hendrix and Kurt
Cobain.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual James Brown, an homage to one of the most celebrated
and innovative forces in soul, rhythm and blues, and funk music,
will reside in a section of the museum that will be called the
Artists' Journey. It will be a combination walking tour and motion
ride. Brown will appear to leap from a two-story billboard set to
look like part of a vacant corner of a New York streetscape. He is
then supposed to beckon visitors to follow him in something called
``Funk Blast'' as he belts out songs like ``Sex Machine'' and
dances as he did when he was 30.
</P>
<P>
   (The exact year Brown was 30 is in dispute. Brown himself has
said he was born in 1933, making him 30 in 1963, the year his album
``Live at the Apollo'' was released. But many other sources give
his year of birth as 1928. Digital Domain has accepted Brown's
statement.)
</P>
<P>
   The digital performer will take audiences to the throbbing heart
of funk music as he spins, jumps and does splits on a large
wraparound screen.
</P>
<P>
   To make the virtual James Brown believable, a crew from Digital
Domain flew to Augusta, Ga., Brown's adopted hometown, to take a
true measure of the man. While Brown performed with his band for
the Digital Domain artists and technicians, he was filmed from
multiple angles. Later, the minute details of his face were
captured with a handheld laser scanner, then reduced to the precise
computer language of ones and zeros.
</P>
<P>
   To capture the fancy footwork that was the trademark of vintage
James Brown performances, a dancer was used as a stand-in for
Brown's body.
</P>
<P>
   To replicate the precise mechanics of Brown's face, tiny balls
were affixed to his face at key points, like his jaw line, the tops
of his cheeks and the skin at the corners of his eyes for a common
special effects technique called motion capture, which recorded the
balls' movements. Once the information was digitized and plugged
into a 3-D map of Brown's face, Digital Domain had a working yet
still crude model of how his face actually moves.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also allowed Digital Domain to make a plaster cast of his
entire head, from which a highly detailed plastic bust was made. A
texture artist added levels of details a scanner cannot see, like
Brown's coloration and individual pores and fine lines in the skin.
Lifelike eyes and teeth and a pompadour were also fashioned and
added to the head. It sits, disembodied, in the wooden building,
now dubbed the Funk Bunker, on the Digital Domain complex in
Venice. The head is frequently used as a reference for the digital
James Brown face.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the artists and technicians laughed when they recalled
how Brown had said during one of the many scannings of his face:
``Ah, I know what you are trying to do. You're trying to clone
me.''
</P>
<P>
   To give the face lifelike qualities, the artists and technicians
in the Funk Bunker used highly sophisticated software that had been
meticulously programmed to mimic the movements of skin and the
muscle beneath the skin as the flesh moved over and around
substructures like bone.
</P>
<P>
   By studying old photographs and film of Brown's face in
performance, animators were able to adjust the data they received
from an older James Brown to create a more youthful one. For every
movement _ the furrow of a brow, the curl of a lip _ animators can
choose how much of that movement will be a direct translation of
Brown's real-life movements and how much will be extrapolated from
archival footage.
</P>
<P>
   The work is painstakingly done frame by frame, like the cells of
an old cartoon. But instead of drawing tables and pens and ink,
there are banks of Silicon Graphics workstations capable of
crunching several terabytes of data.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the bunker an artist was animating Brown's
tongue, which floated free from its face on a computer screen.
Nearby, someone else checked the dependency graph, a complex branch
of lines and tags that track the various relationships that parts
of the face have to other parts when a single element, like an eye,
is moved. Someone else worked on the merger of Brown's face with
the dancer's body, while others worked out the virtual camera
angles and lighting schemes to make it all work without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, said Joshua Kolden, the computer generation sequence
supervisor for the project, the digital James Brown's performance
has to be just as electrifying as the flesh-and-blood one _ all
without letting on that the museum version is actually powered by
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to wow people with the technology,'' Kolden
said. ``That's not the point. We want James Brown to be James
Brown, not an effect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
