<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-OIL-VS-NATURE-ALASKA-     04-12 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-VS-NATURE-ALASKA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S FRAGILE ARCTIC WILDERNESS THREATENED BY BP AMOCO  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska)   (This excellent 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MICHAEL MCCARTHY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The area is known as America's Serengeti _ a vast Alaskan
wilderness providing a wildlife spectacle paralleled only in the
legendary national park in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   But BP Amoco, the giant British oil company that unceasingly
proclaims its environmental responsibility, is backing efforts to
have it opened up as an oil field.
</P>
<P>
   The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge bordering the Arctic Ocean
on Alaska's northern shore is perhaps the most pristine wilderness
area in the United States, and home to a spectacular range of
Arctic wildlife, from polar bears to musk oxen.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, it is noted for the 130,000-strong Porcupine
River caribou herd, which every summer migrates in its entirety 400
miles towards the sea. It is the greatest wildlife display on the
American continent, comparable only to the Serengeti's vast herds
of wildebeest on the move.
</P>
<P>
   However, for 20 years oil companies have been keenly eyeing the
1.5-million acre coastal plain, the biological heart of the refuge
_ the caribou give birth to their calves there _ and an underground
continuation of Alaska's North Slope oil field to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 800-mile trans-Alaska pipeline was built in 1976, to
carry oil to year-round ice-free ports on Alaska's southern coast,
the north-coast oil field concentrated on Prudhoe Bay has continued
to expand.
</P>
<P>
   It now provides 20 percent of home-produced oil in the U.S. The
adjacent coastal plain of the wildlife refuge, with its known oil
reserves, is seen by oilmen as a natural extension.
</P>
<P>
   Three efforts to have the coastal plain opened for development
have been defeated in Congress since 1980 and, with oil prices at
their highest for years, a fourth is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Its development is being supported by BP Amoco, which on its own
Web site describes Alaska as ``a place of unmatched wilderness and
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has lobbied for the development in Washington, and
is openly supporting Arctic Power, a lobby company based in
Anchorage whose sole purpose is to have the refuge developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worried about fuel prices?'' Arctic Power's publicity tells
Americans. ``ANWR (the refuge) equals 30 years of Saudi Oil.''
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco Alaska's vice-president for external affairs, James
Palmer, sits on Arctic Power's board, and the company agrees that
``we have supported the state of Alaska in its efforts to have the
status of ANWR changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says it does so because it believes the coastal
plain can be developed ``without detriment to the environment,''
but its claim is angrily rejected by a coalition of American and
Canadian environmental and socially conscious investment groups.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a serious concern for native peoples, in particular
the 7,000-strong Gwich'in people who have lived off the Porcupine
River caribou herd for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Those opposing the oil plans have put down a resolution for BP
Amoco, calling for it to reject the idea of the refuge as an oil
field. The resolution is also supported by another influential
Washington group, the Sierra Club, and by Greenpeace and the World
Wide Fund for Nature from the U.K.
</P>
<P>
   The million-member U.S. Public Interest Research Group and
Trillium Asset Management, which claims to be the biggest fund
manager in the U.S. specializing in socially responsible
investment, are also key supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are particularly concerned about the Arctic
because climate change is proceeding there more rapidly than
anywhere else in the world, with the summer sea ice now retreating
to a greater extent than witnessed previously.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife such as walruses are already suffering because the sea
ice on which they have their pups is now on the surface of water
that is too deep for the walruses to catch shellfish that live on
the sea bed, on which they feed.
</P>
<P>
   Sir John Browne, the chief executive of BP Amoco, has repeatedly
said the company accepts the reality of climate change and global
warming, and as a result has gained a reputation in recent years as
the most environmentally responsible oil company.
</P>
<P>
   But its position on the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is
likely to dent that reputation considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Sullivan, the director of programs for the United
Kingdom branch of the World Wide Fund for Nature, said: ``BP Amoco
refuses to acknowledge publicly the damage that even exploratory
drilling would do in the refuge, let alone the impact of
large-scale oil extraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan added: ``It all comes down to this: multinational oil
companies already have access to 95 percent of Alaska's oil-rich
coastal plain. Can't this last 5 percent be left undisturbed?'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
