<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a chilly dawn in the Northeast on Thursday, ample sunshine
will increase readings close to seasonal levels. Winds will be
light, and the air will be dry. A wedge of cool air over the
Piedmont will provide an ideal dome to lift mild, moist air flowing
inland across the Southeast. Damp conditions are likely from the
western Carolinas to the Mississippi Delta.
</P>
<P>
   A few strong thunderstorms will soak sections of Florida,
bringing relief from the recent spate of brush fires. Abundant low
clouds will linger in the wake of low pressure over the Gulf
states. Warm weather will return to the Plains on breezes from the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary with polar air over Canada will be active from the
Great Lakes to Montana. Mixed showers will dampen the border
region. A large disturbance from the Pacific will move inland with
showers from Central California to Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WATERSPOUTS
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, mariners around the southern and eastern coasts of
Florida were alerted to the potential for waterspouts. Between 3
yards and 100 yards in diameter, these short-lived whirlwinds
usually have winds less than 50 mph. Nevertheless, they pose a
serious threat to small craft. Unlike tornadoes, which are spawned
by severe thunderstorms, fair-weather waterspouts typically form
beneath ordinary cumulus clouds. Tornadic waterspouts, which occur
when tornadoes form over land and move over water, are much more
dangerous. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
