<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NAZI-ART-MUSEUMS-ART-     04-12 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-ART-MUSEUMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUMS IDENTIFY ART WITH WARTIME PASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After nearly two years of scouring their collections
for artworks that might have been stolen by the Nazis, the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Museum of Modern Art and other
major U.S. museums are starting to reveal their findings. They are
taking different tacks, and some are closer to the full disclosure
they have promised than others.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the works could now more easily be claimed by heirs to
those who owned them before Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany
in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Met posted on its Web site (www.metmuseum.org)
a list of 393 paintings, drawn from the 2,700 European paintings in
its collection, whose ownership histories have any gap between 1933
and 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The list, which includes paintings by Matisse, Gauguin, Ingres,
Manet and dozens of others and can be cross-referenced with the
2,200 images of paintings already on the Web site, is an invitation
for people to come forward with information filling in the blanks
or with claims. As that happens and as the Met continues its
research, the museum will delete artworks that were not taken
illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a very conscious decision to give as broad a list as
possible because we did not want to inflect the list with any
arbitrary criteria,'' said Philippe de Montebello, the museum's
director, testifying at a hearing on Wednesday in Manhattan called
by the Presidential Advisory Commission on Holocaust Assets in the
United States. ``We decided that a gap is a gap.''
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art, meanwhile, is providing more
information about fewer works. Calling its effort a work in
progress, it issued a list of 15 paintings drawn from about 500
European works that were acquired by the museum after 1933.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have included them because we do not yet know where they
were during all or part of the Nazi period,'' said the museum's
director, Glenn D. Lowry. The museum plans to post the list, which
includes such major works as Braque's ``Road Near L'Estaque'' and
Leger's ``Contrast of Forms,'' and the known provenance of the
listed works on its Web site (www.moma.org) by Thursday night. It
hopes to have digitized images of the paintings available on the
site by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry said the museum may expand the list as it does more
research on its holdings, and added that eventually it will post
its entire collection.
</P>
<P>
   Both men stressed that the lists were not rosters of suspect
pictures, but rather paintings about which crucial information was
lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Two other museums also have gone pubilc with results of their
provenance research. On Monday, the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston
said that it had found more than 200 paintings in its collection
with gaps in provenance between 1933 and 1945. But the museum
posted on its Web site (www.mfa.org) only seven works that are ``of
most concern'' because of their association with people implicated
in World War II-era looting or because of dubious transactions in
their history.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials said that they may add to the list and that
they plan to post information about all 1,500 European paintings in
the collection by December.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Art Institute of Chicago posted on its Web
site (www.artic.edu) a list of 548 works for which links in the
chain of ownership between 1933 and 1945 are either unclear or not
fully documented. The works are illustrated in color where
possible, but the Art Institute provides no details about
provenance except its acquisition dates.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the National Gallery of Art in Washington announced
that it had checked its 1,600 prewar European paintings and found
only one, ``Still Life with Fruit and Game'' by Frans Snyders, that
might have been looted by the Nazis. It placed information about
the painting on the Web (www.nga.gov).
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, after several highly publicized ownership claims
raised suspicions that many U.S. museums might own Nazi-tainted
works, members of the Association of Art Museum Directors pledged
to search collections for works taken illegally during the Nazi era
and never returned. Until recently, none of the association's 175
members, representing the largest art museums in North America, had
produced any results. Some critics of the museums had begun to
complain.
</P>
<P>
   But at Wednesday's hearing, which no doubt prompted the flurry
of action, William S. Singer, a Chicago lawyer who is the chairman
of the presidential commission's Committee on Art and Cultural
Property, praised the ``major movement'' made by museums since
1998. ``The ground has shifted from `we are examining our
collections' to full disclosure,'' he said. Now, he added, the
burden shifts to the claimants.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the postings being so new _ and with only a handful of
museums producing them _ no one in the United States has claimed
anything in the listings. Still, at the hearing, Lawrence J.
Wheeler, the director of the North Carolina Museum of Art in
Raleigh, said that a painting by Lucas Cranach, a German
Renaissance artist, was stolen by the Nazis and recently returned
by his museum to two sisters in Austria had been discovered on the
museum's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   And Malcolm Rogers, the director of the Museum of Fine Arts in
Boston said that since its postings went up on Monday some people
had volunteered some information, ``though I can't say any that has
been useful.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, where British museums jointly published a list of 350
paintings with gaps in their wartime provenance, and where the
German government has a Web site (www.LostArt.de) listing more than
2,200 looted artworks, some claims have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning, each museum director at the hearing promised
to keep searching for missing details on the provenance of art in
their collections. They also asked the commission to recommend the
appropriation of federal money for the task, which can entail
research in foreign archives. Smaller museums, which have tiny
curatorial staffs and few researchers, especially need aid, they
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
