<HEADER>
A4911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OSCILLATE-$ADV16-COX     04-12 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCILLATE-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OCEAN TEMPERATURE SHIFTING TOWARD STRONGER HURRICANES?
 &HT;    With OSCILLATE-DATA. For release Sunday, April 16.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year's Atlantic hurricane season, already
predicted to be more severe than normal, might be even worse than
expected because of a little-known Pacific climate condition,
scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists believe that while the huge Pacific Ocean
weather-making machine is going through its cycles known as La Nina
and El Nino every five to seven years, a slower set of changes
called the Northern Pacific Oscillation (NPO) also takes place.
</P>
<P>
   And if their observations are correct, whatever the NPO lacks in
colorful Spanish nicknames, it more than makes up for in the bad
weather it causes.
</P>
<P>
   Climatologist Anthony Lupo of the University of
Missouri-Columbia says an analysis of hurricane records since 1938
indicates that worse-than-average hurricane seasons during La Nina
years _ like this year _ are even worse when La Ninas correspond to
NPO conditions that seem to be developing now.
</P>
<P>
   It's a complicated analysis, comparing three different sets of
weather data _ the NPO patterns between warmer and colder surface
waters, the similar shifts between El Ninos and La Ninas in
equatorial latitudes, and annual hurricane records.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is the North Pacific's lazy shifts between states
called NPO-1 and NPO-2, phases that can last 30 years or more.
Nobody knows what drives the NPO changes. Some scientists think
massive ocean currents may push warm water around in a way that
causes a ponderous, ocean-wide slosh of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   Others think atmospheric conditions may be driving the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NPO is like a giant, long-lived El Nino,'' Lupo said.
``The first phase, NPO-1, is characterized by warmer surface
temperatures in the eastern Pacific (along the coast of North
America) and lower surface temperatures in the western Pacific.''
</P>
<P>
   During the other phase, NPO-2, the reverse is true. Scientists
say that from about 1945 until the mid-1970s, the Pacific was in an
NPO-2 phase. Beginning in the 1970s, it shifted to NPO-1, and now
appears to have at least started to change back to NPO-2 again.
</P>
<P>
   Lupo and a student assistant, Grant Johnston, will publish their
analysis of NPO-La Nina-El Nino-hurricanes in an upcoming issue of
the National Weather Digest, a scientific journal.
</P>
<P>
   They found that when colder La Nina conditions in the tropical
Pacific coincide with NPO-2 conditions in the north Pacific,
Atlantic hurricane seasons seem to be about one major hurricane
worse than average.
</P>
<P>
   During the 62 years covered by their analysis, La Nina episodes
in the Pacific corresponded to an average of 2.7 hurricanes that
qualified as category 3, 4 or 5 storms, from those with sustained
winds of 111 miles per hour to those with winds of more than 155
miles per hour, Lupo said.
</P>
<P>
   When La Nina episodes occurred during NPO-2 years, the average
number of major storms was 2.9. However, La Nina hurricane seasons
during the NPO-1 phase typically produced only 2.0 major storms.
</P>
<P>
   The tendency of El Ninos to suppress powerful hurricane activity
also seems to be enhanced by the NPO phases, according to Lupo's
data.
</P>
<P>
   Other atmospheric scientists reacted to the findings with
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pacific Ocean has a troubling tendency to be joined
together,'' said Eugene Rasmusson, a climate specialist at the
University of Maryland who has studied the El Nino phenomenon for
years. ``I'm not sure that the North Pacific Oscillations and the
El Nino patterns are totally independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, he said, a statistical significance test would have to
be applied to Lupo's data to determine whether he has spotted an
actually significant link or a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
typhoon.atmos.colostate.edu/forecasts/2000/april2000/
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
