<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d BC-FOOD-CRAWFISH-COX     04-12 2383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CRAWFISH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's boil up them crawfish
 &HT;    By Jana Collier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's only one way to eat a crawfish _ at a party.
</P>
<P>
   And this Saturday, the folks at Waco Custom Meats &AMP; Seafood Inc.
will boil 600 pounds of the juicy mudbugs for Central Texans to
enjoy at the fourth annual Crawfish and Folk Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Though they do have more legs than something you'd normally try
to eat, crawfish are easy to cook and make a great focus for any
outdoor party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the whole fun of the thing _ the atmosphere and
everything,'' said Mike Mayfield, who owns the seafood division of
Waco Custom Meats &AMP; Seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Broadfoot of Houston, a veteran crawfish boiler, agrees.
``You have to have a party for crawfish,'' he said. ``It's just so
much fun that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark and my brother-in-law, Chip Saegert, recently held a big
crawfish boil at Chip's Houston home. They boiled 160 pounds of
crawfish, along with corn, potatoes and mushrooms, for about 50 of
their friends and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of having a crawfish boil at your house,
here's a guide from Mark and Chip and the folks at Waco Custom
Meats &AMP; Seafood.
</P>
<P>
   The crawfish
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish season runs from January to June, but the prime time
for the crustaceans is April and May. That's when the supply is
greatest and the crawfish are biggest.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the crawfish supply nationwide is significantly down,
primarily due to a poor yield in Louisiana. However, Waco Custom
Meats gets most of its crawfish from Texas farms, and those farms
are currently producing well, Mike said. How long those farms
continue to produce will depend on the heat and rain, he said,
noting that the price is up this year because of the low supply.
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish must be cooked live, so storing them properly is
crucial to a successful boil.
</P>
<P>
   At Waco Custom Meats &AMP; Seafood, which supplies crawfish to many
Central Texas restaurants, a special cooler was built just for
crawfish. The mudbugs should be kept at a temperature of 38 to 40
degrees _ cold enough to stay fresh, but not cold enough to freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Mark and Chip bought their crawfish at a Houston grocery store a
few hours before their boil and stored them in ice chests until
time for cooking.
</P>
<P>
   To tell if a crawfish is alive or dead, pick it up before it's
cooked and look at the tail: If its tail droops when handled, it's
dead; if the tail curls under its body, its still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Some crawfish must be ``purged'' or cleaned before cooking, but
it isn't always necessary. Mike said most Texas farmers clean their
crawfish in aerated, fresh water tanks before shipping, so they do
not need to be purged. Crawfish that have not been cleaned, though,
will need to be purged to remove mud sediment, fish bait and other
impurities.
</P>
<P>
   To purge the crawfish, Mark said he rinses them first with clean
water and then sprinkles salt over them while still in the ice
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Most people boil their crawfish in propane-fired pots, which can
be bought at area hardware stores such as Lowe's and Home Depot.
For smaller amounts of crawfish, you can use a large stockpot on
the stove.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the pot, fill it about a half to three-fourths full
of water and add plenty of spices. At Waco Custom Meats, they use
Chef Geoffrey Michael's Cajun Red seasoning and the ultra-hot Swamp
Fire seasoning, both of which are sold at the store.
</P>
<P>
   Mark said he uses a large bottle of Zatarain's liquid shrimp and
crab boil and half of a large bottle of powdered shrimp and crab
boil for each pot he boils. He also adds one to two sticks of
butter, which he says makes the crawfish easier to peel, and about
5 lemons, halved.
</P>
<P>
   Many people cook corn and potatoes with their crawfish. Mark
also adds mushrooms, and Sondra Waits of Waco Custom Meats &AMP;
Seafood said she's seen people add whole garlic cloves. Some people
also add onions.
</P>
<P>
   Sausage and shrimp can be cooked with the crawfish, which is
nice for those who don't care for crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   Mark said he puts his vegetables in a mesh lingerie bag. This
keeps the vegetables from floating up to the top where they can
sometimes get too spicy. Depending on the size of the potato
pieces, you might want to add those first to give them a little
extra time to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Once the water in the pot is boiling and the spices are added,
throw in the crawfish and vegetables. The crawfish should cook
about 15 minutes. After they've cooked, Mark turns off the heat to
let them soak for another 15 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   The place
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish should be eaten outdoors _ they're way too messy for
inside.
</P>
<P>
   At Waco Custom Meats' festival on Saturday, they'll have tables
set up outside for those who want to eat the crawfish there.
</P>
<P>
   My brother-in-law Chip actually built two large tables to set up
on his deck. He made them taller than most tables, so people could
stand and eat their crawfish as they were poured out on a
tablecloth of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The eating area should be well-stocked with paper towels and
napkins and extra seasonings for those who like their crawfish very
spicy.
</P>
<P>
   Having tables set up outside makes cleanup easy. Once the
party's over, just remove the leftover food and newspapers and hose
down the tables and ground.
</P>
<P>
   The munchies
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone likes crawfish, and, in particular, children are
often turned off by the idea of eating something that looks like
the star of last night's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   My 7-year-old Claire and 4-year-old Rachel finally tasted some
crawfish tails, but they certainly didn't eat enough to constitute
a meal.
</P>
<P>
   That's why many people add sausage or shrimp to the crawfish
pots. Chip and Mark also fried a turkey, which was a nice addition
to the party. Waco Custom Meats will have shrimp at Saturday's
festival, although it will be cooked in a separate pot.
</P>
<P>
   My sister, Shannon Saegert, assembled a large table of crackers,
vegetable trays and dips, along with praline bars and
crawfish-shaped cutout cookies, iced with red icing and decorated
with silver dragees for eyes. In addition, Shannon's friend, Betty
Broadfoot (Mark's wife), baked a batch of crawfish bread that
turned out to be the biggest hit of the party.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a basic recipe for boiled crawfish from the Texas Marine
Advisory Service and the Texas A&AMP;M University Sea Grant College
Program.
</P>
<P>
   BOILED CRAWFISH
</P>
<P>
   12 to 15 pounds of live crawfish
</P>
<P>
   1 package (3 ounces) crab and shrimp boil mix
</P>
<P>
   1 cup salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-gallon stew pot, bring water, crab boil, salt and pepper
to a boil. Add crawfish and boil for 10 minutes. Remove from heat
and let crawfish soak for 10 minutes. Soaking allows the meat to
absorb flavors, so don't shorten the soaking time. Drain and serve
immediately. Makes 4-5 servings.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe for crawfish bread was the hit of my sister and
brother-in-law's party. Betty Broadfoot made it, following a recipe
from chef Emeril's cookbook Every Day's a Party. Crawfish bread is
a popular food at New Orleans' annual Jazz Fest, and those who had
been to Jazz Fest proclaimed this recipe exactly like that served
at the festival. You can buy packages of frozen crawfish tails for
about $6 a pound at Waco Custom Meats &AMP; Seafood.
</P>
<P>
   CRAWFISH BREAD
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plus 1 teaspoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups warm water (about 110 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups bleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped yellow bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds peeled crawfish tails
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pound sharp cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Monterey Jack Cheese with jalapenos, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine yeast, sugar and 2 tablespoons vegetable oil in the bowl
of a stand mixer fitted with a dough hook. Add the warm water. With
the mixer on low speed, beat the mixture for about 1 minute to
dissolve the yeast. If the yeast mixture doesn't begin to foam
after a few minutes, it means it's not active and you will have to
start over with fresher yeast.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine the flour and 1 teaspoon of the
salt. Add it 1/4 cup at a time to the yeast mixture, mixing on low
speed until the dough lightly comes together. Increase the speed to
medium and beat until the dough pulls away from the sides of the
bowl, forms a ball and starts to climb up the dough hook.
</P>
<P>
   Coat a large bowl with the remaining 1 teaspoon vegetable oil.
Put the dough in the bowl and turn it to oil all sides. Cover the
bowl with plastic wrap, set aside in a warm, draft-free place and
let rise until doubled in size, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a large skillet, melt the butter over medium heat.
Add the onion, bell pepper, the remaining 1 1/2 teaspoons salt and
the cayenne. Cook, stirring for 4 minutes. Add the crawfish and
cook, stirring, for 5 minutes until they are soft. Remove from the
heat, drain off any excess liquid from the pan and set aside to
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the dough from the bowl and turn it onto a lightly
floured work surface. Push it down, then using your hands, pat it
out to flatten it. Pick it up, dust the work surface with flour and
return the dough to the work surface. Roll it out to a
20-by-15-inch rectangle, about 1/4 inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cheese in a medium-size mixing bowl. Sprinkle half
of the cheese over the upper half of the rectangle of dough,
leaving a 1/2-inch border. Spoon the crawfish mixture evenly over
the cheese. Top with the remaining cheese. Fold the other half of
the dough up over the filling, forming a half-moon shape, and pinch
the edges tightly to seal completely. Fold the edges over, seal
securely, and then crimp. Carefully transfer the dough to a baking
sheet lined with parchment paper. With a sharp pointed knife, make
three slits on top, about 6 inches apart. Brush the surface of the
dough with the beaten egg and sprinkle with the kosher salt and
black pepper. Cover with plastic wrap and set aside in a warm,
draft-free place until doubled in size, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the plastic wrap and bake the bread until golden brown,
30 to 35 minutes. Let cool slightly. Cut crosswise into 12 equal
portions and serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a great recipe for leftover crawfish tails from my
sister, Shannon Saegert. If you don't have leftovers, you can buy
packages of frozen crawfish tails.
</P>
<P>
   CRAWFISH FETTUCINE
</P>
<P>
   2 onions
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 stalks celery
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 sticks butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds crawfish tails
</P>
<P>
   1 jar picante sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Velveeta
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half and half
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces Fettucine
</P>
<P>
   Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Pepper and cayenne to taste
</P>
<P>
   Saute vegetables until soft. Add flour, parsley, crawfish and
spices. Cook 15 minutes. Add picante, Velveeta and half and half.
Cook fettucine separately and add to crawfish mixture. Top with
Parmesan cheese. Bake at 350 degrees for 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This is another way to use leftover crawfish tails. If you don't
have leftovers, you can buy frozen bags.
</P>
<P>
   CRAWFISH CARDINAL
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons scallions
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   Salt, white pepper and red pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds crawfish tails
</P>
<P>
   Oven toasted and buttered French bread
</P>
<P>
   In large skillet, blend butter and flour, stirring two minutes.
Add scallions, milk and wine. Bring to a simmer. Stir in tomato
paste and seasonings. Add crawfish and simmer 10 minutes. Serve
over toasted, buttered French bread slices.
</P>
<P>
   From The Food of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, my sister served cookies cut into the shapes of
crabs and crawfish along with Southern Praline Bars. The crawfish
cookie cutter was really a lobster shape, but it worked perfectly
as a crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   CUTOUT COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon milk or cream
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter. Beat in sugar. Beat in egg, milk and vanilla. Stir
in flour. Chill in freezer. Roll on slightly floured board to
1/8-inch thickness. Cut into shapes and place cookies on ungreased
cookie sheet. Bake 8 minutes at 360 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ICING
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/8- 1/4 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Shake of salt
</P>
<P>
   Red food coloring
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk, or more
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup powdered sugar, or more
</P>
<P>
   Silver dragees for decorating
</P>
<P>
   Put margarine, vanilla, salt and food coloring in mixing bowl.
Add milk and powdered sugar. Beat on high with electric mixer until
creamy. Keep adding additional milk and powdered sugar until icing
is of a good spreading consistency. Spread on cooled cookies. Place
two silver dragees as eyes on each crab or crawfish shape. Allow to
dry before stacking.
</P>
<P>
   These Southern Praline Bars were delicious and easy to make. I
found the recipe in Talk About Good II, A Toast to Cajun Food, a
cookbook by the Junior League of Lafeyette, La.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN PRALINE BARS
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups flour, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, salt and baking powder. Melt shortening
in large sauce pan, then put remaining ingredients in and stir
well. Spread in 13-by-9-inch greased and floured pan. Bake at 350
degrees for 30 minutes. Cool slightly in pan, then cover with
Praline Frosting.
</P>
<P>
   PRALINE FROSTING
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners sugar
</P>
<P>
   chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter and brown sugar; add cream. While over heat, stir in
confectioners sugar and beat until smooth. Pour over warm cake and
top with chopped pecans. Cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
