<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-FURNISHINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HIGH POINT, PUTTING ON WHITE GLOVES AND PEARLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ SEYMOUR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ The ladies who lunch made a surprise
reappearance at the International Home Furnishings Market, which
opened here last Thursday and closes tomorrow. Just as Minimalism
and Modernism are entrenched in the mainstream, the upper end of
the market took a swerve toward the traditional, glamorous looks of
the 1930s and '40s, offering a champagne complement to the dry
martini Deco modern that ushered out the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the world these days is beige and gray _ it's a
uniform,'' said Carleton Varney, a New York decorator, sitting in
the Kindel showroom, painted in his signature baby blue and azalea
pink. The inheritor of the 1940s decorator Dorothy Draper's grande
dame style, Varney was making his debut in High Point with a
22-piece collection of wood and upholstered furniture, along with
lamps, throws and pillows.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Buatta invoked the spirits of Syrie Maugham and Elsie de
Wolfe with eight new pieces in his collection for John Widdicomb.
``Glamour is back,'' he said. ``The '80s was a bit more lush, but
this is a sparer '30s kind of thing that looks very new for the
21st century.'' The Buatta collection included a sexy button-tufted
sofa, a chinoiserie coffee table and an ottoman dressed in a
hulalike skirt of deep, bouillon fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the manufacturers believed their surging business in
classic traditional was being driven by newly wealthy
under-40-year-olds. ``We saw an e-commerce study the other day that
said that 50 percent of the furniture bought by young millionaires
is in traditional styles,'' Chris Plasman, president of Baker,
said. ``To them it's new.'' Baker, which has worked with modern
designers like Barbara Barry and Michael Vanderbyl, went
traditional all the way, with additions to its Stately Homes
Collection of British furniture and a new French Collection.
</P>
<P>
   The word livable replaced casual as many showrooms
metaphorically put on their white gloves and pearls. Even pretty _
a word all but banished from the fashion-oriented end of the market
in recent years _ returned in a cloud of marquetry inlays and silk
or silklike fabrics. At Mitchell Gold, a new bed was offered with
organdy slipcovers that were unabashedly pretty; at Baker a new
chest of drawers in the Stately Homes Collection was inlaid with
classical urns and floral scrolls; new tables at Harden's Forbes
collection were covered with marquetry balloons and playing cards;
Hickory Chair showed some of its new upholstery in a cheerful color
it called National Geographic yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The brighter, lighter colors matched the buoyant mood of an
industry that is experiencing a record run. ``It doesn't get any
better than this,'' said Jerry Epperson, a furniture business
analyst for Mann, Armistead &AMP; Epperson in Richmond, Va. ``There's a
level of euphoria that I haven't seen in a long time.'' In 1999,
the industry had its best year ever, with $61 billion in retail
sales; those figures are expected to grow by 3 to 4 percent in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of space dedicated to selling furniture here at the
International Home Furnishings Market is growing apace. Bagpipes
and a parade accompanied the opening of the 350,000-square-foot
Suites at Market Square showroom space at what is already the
world's largest wholesale market of home furnishings. With the
addition of the Suites, the market now has more than eight million
square feet of showroom space, and is to grow another 2.5 million
square feet by fall 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong business, most manufacturers are playing it
safe with designs that are at best variations of their own (or
competitors') proven winners. French styles _ translated into a
kind of Franglais for the American market _ were everywhere,
spanning the timeline from French Provincial to French modern. (One
of the nicest Francophone collections was at Lane, whose Boulevard
group brought the dark-wood-and-silver-hardware styles by Barbara
Barry at Baker and Thomas O'Brien at Hickory Chair to a mid-market
price level.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most startling French collection was Hemingway's
Paris, an addition to Thomasville's hugely successful _ $100
million in sales its first year _ Ernest Hemingway Collection.
Loosely inspired by Hemingway's penurious Paris years, the
collection featured a most un-Hemingway-like carved armoire, a
hand-painted bar cabinet and a cast metal bed with scrollwork
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   American and English 18th-century design, heavy on the carving
and hardware, were also back, often in overscale proportions
suitable for equally overscale new suburban homes. Stickley, which
built its reputation reviving its own Arts and Crafts designs,
allied itself with Colonial Williamsburg to bring out 35 pieces of
18th-century reproductions, including a huge bombe chest on chest
and a massive serpentine front chest of drawers. The architect
William Poole, known for his mini-mansion designs, weighed in with
his own collection for Hickory Chair. ``People have trouble finding
furniture to fit my houses,'' he said. His solution: king-size beds
and an 88-inch-tall pedimented bookcase.
</P>
<P>
   But sleek and modern furniture can still be found: two of the
market's handsomest collections were by Ralph Lauren and Michael
Vanderbyl. Lauren's furniture, made by Henredon, was the glossy
mahogany, chrome and leather Mercer Collection. Vanderbyl, whose
Archetype collection has been a hit for Baker, brought out a sleek
set of outdoor furniture in teak, aluminum and cloth webbing for
McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   For many manufacturers, however, style was not the biggest
talking point. That honor went to services like delivery times and
speed of manufacturing. The customer, once all but forgotten, was
talking back to manufacturers through focus groups, consumer
surveys, advisory boards and e-mail. New licensing programs, in
particular, were being touted as ways to reach customers more
directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers these days hold the power in this business,'' said
Bob Stec, president of Lexington Home Brands, which used to be
called Lexington Furniture. ``As consumers have more choices, and
less time, they're looking for a shorthand way to make a decision,
and that's what a recognizable name gives them.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so: licensed home furnishings, one of the fastest
growing categories in the licensing business, accounted for $4.7
billion in retail sales in 1999. The tables have even turned.
Thomasville not only licensed the Hemingway line of furniture but
allowed its own name to be licensed; Home Depot is presenting a
Thomasville line of kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the more promising licensed collections were allied with
HGTV veterans. Joe Ruggiero created a clean, livable collection for
Norwalk, and Chris Madden introduced a well-priced collection of
soccer-mom style furniture in comfortable washed-out green, rust
and gold. Tellingly, Bassett began test selling its Chris Madden
Collection directly to consumers in February, two months before it
was shown to retailers _ an almost unprecedented move in the
industry. (Things seen at this market normally take six months to
reach consumers.)
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and the growing number of dot-com sites have helped
to cut the distance between manufacturers and consumers, but
whether they produce furniture sales is still up for debate.
``We've seen four competitors get out of selling home furnishings
to consumers just this calendar year,'' said Doug Mack, chief
executive of Goodhome.com.
</P>
<P>
   But one Internet introduction was an immediate market hit. At
the back of the La-Z-Boy showroom, weary buyers stood three deep
for their turn in the Microsoft WebTV Plus Recliner, a plush
collaboration from La-Z-Boy and Microsoft. With a built-in tray and
keyboard in one arm and a drinks holder and storage compartment in
the other, the $1,049 recliner comes with a two-month subscription
to WebTV Plus, which allows people to watch television and surf the
Internet simultaneously on their television screens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
