<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOCCER NOTES: Clubs dealing with fans' deaths
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A week remains before the second leg of the UEFA Cup
semifinals. But it might not be enough time for the heated verbal
volleys from the chairmen of Leeds and Turkey's Galatasaray to cool
down. Both clubs still are dealing with the stabbing deaths of two
English fans in Istanbul last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   UEFA, the European soccer governing body, has delayed until
Friday a decision on admitting Galatasaray fans into Leeds' Elland
Road ground for next Thursday's return match. Five Turks have been
arrested in connection with the murders of two Leeds supporters
outside an Istanbul night club on the eve of the first leg.
Galatasaray, which won 2-0, has petitioned for a neutral site if
Leeds is granted its wish of barring visiting fans.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds Chairman Peter Ridsdale excoriated Galatasaray management
and threatened to pull his club out of the competition if it cannot
play at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been trying to find any means possible to get
through to the final without kicking a football,'' Ridsdale said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue should not be turned into a blood feud,''
Galatasaray chairman Faruk Suren responded.
</P>
<P>
   It might be too late already.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND: NEWCASTLE RUN ENDS
</P>
<P>
   Two goals Sunday by Gustavo Poyet, including the winner with 18
minutes to play, put Chelsea in the FA Cup final for the second
time in the last four seasons. Chelsea won 2-1 over Newcastle in
the semifinals. Alan Shearer set up Robert Lee for the equalizer on
a header in the 67th minute for Newcastle, which has lost in the
finals each of the last three years. Chelsea, which won the title
in 1997, plays Aston Villa for the cup May 20 in Wembley Stadium.
... Manchester United got four goals in the second half to edge
Middlesbrough 4-3 on Monday to go 11 points ahead of second-place
Liverpool in the Premier League.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: DORTMUND PLUNGES DEEPER
</P>
<P>
   Only three years after winning the European Cup, Borussia
Dortmund is facing relegation from the Bundesliga after a 3-1 loss
to unheralded Unterhaching on Tuesday. Dortmund, losers of six in a
row, has not won before the Christmas break and is only three
points out of the relegation zone. ... Mehmet Scholl converted a
penalty kick with three minutes remaining Wednesday, and Bayern
Munich beat Freiburg 2-1 to regain the Bundesliga lead on goal
difference over Bayer Leverkusen. The latter drew 1-1 with Hansa
Rostock.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: FEARS PROMPT TIME CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Fiorentina-Lazio match in Florence has been moved up
from the evening to the afternoon because of security concerns from
last season's match there. A Fiorentina fan was stabbed, about 20
people were injured, and Lazio fans set a train on fire as they
made their way to Tuscany. ... Juventus stayed three points ahead
of Lazio in Serie A play with a 2-0 win at Bologna on Sunday. Darko
Kovacevic came off the bench to score in the 88th minute, and
Massimo Paganin added an insurance goal in stoppage time. ... Inter
Milan's skid continued in a 3-0 loss at Udinese; Carlos Sosa
registered a hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: UNEASE IN BARCA
</P>
<P>
   Tensions are mounting between Barcelona players and unpopular
manager Louis van Gaal after a horrible week that included a 3-1
loss to Chelsea in the Champions League and a 3-0 humiliation by
Mallorca in the Nou Camp in the Primera. Cameroonian Samuel Etoo
had two goals and an assist for Mallorca, which got a scare when
defender Miguel Angel Hadal suffered a collapsed lung during the
match. He was moved from intensive care on Monday. Barca stars
Rivaldo and Patrick Kluivert, egged on by the Spanish media, turned
up their criticism of van Gaal. ... Roy Makaay scored a hat trick
for Primera leaders Deportivo La Coruna in a 4-1 win over Atletico
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLAND: PSV'S LEAD IS 12
</P>
<P>
   A hat trick by Luc Nilis pushed PSV Eindoven to a 12-point
advantage in the Honor Division in a 4-0 win over Fortuna Sittard.
Nilis is bound for England's Aston Villa next year. ... Defending
champion Feyenoord is 16 points back in fifth place after a 2-1
loss to lowly Utrecht. The defeat prompted the immediate
resignation of coach Leo Beenhakker, who was set to step down at
the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TOLUCA QUALIFIES
</P>
<P>
   Goals by Jose Cardozo and Carlos Morales paced Toluca to a 2-0
win over Atlante on Saturday, and the club became the first to
advance to the Torneo Verano playoffs. ... Mexican national-team
legend Luis Hernandez, the subject of transfer rumors to the Los
Angeles Galaxy of Major League Soccer, had both goals Sunday when
Tigres blanked UNAM.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
