u s BC-DIMAGGIO-NYTR &LR;      04-12 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMAGGIO-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY: THOU SHALT NOT USE THE DIMAGGIO NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB PADECKY    
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In sports, an industry that spawns compliments as if they were
so many salmon swimming upstream, rarely is a pat on the back
refused. In fact, in many places it is demanded as a rite of
passage. It would be like gaining entrance, say, into a trendy
nightclub owned by Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the secret password?'' the bouncer asks the guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, Dennis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good. You may come in.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was with great interest that a very nice compliment was
refused last week in San Francisco. The Board of Supervisors voted
to name the city park where Joe DiMaggio learned the game of
baseball after the Yankee Clipper. The park is in the Italian
section of San Francisco, is heavily trafficked and, especially,
offers the imagination a marvelous daydream of young Joe running
across its sod. The honor would get a lot of action. It made sense.
</P>
<P>
   Not to Morris Engelberg, DiMaggio's attorney. Morris told the
supervisors that if they went through with their ridiculous idea,
he'd sue. He saw their pat on the back as a slap to Joe's face. No
one treats Joe this way, Morris said in so many words. Joe deserves
better. This would be demeaning. As a modest suggestion, Morris
thought either the San Francisco Airport or the Bay Bridge should
be renamed after the Yankees center fielder who passed away 13
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The supes refused, confused. No one could quite figure out what
a bridge had to do with DiMaggio, other than the fact he traveled
over it. Or what SFO had to do with DiMaggio, other than the fact
he traveled through it. Plus, the murmurs went, who in their right
mind would want their name associated with THAT airport? It's bad
enough anyone has to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Why not rename the new Giants ballpark? It could be Joe DiMaggio
With Permission From Morris Engelberg Park.
</P>
<P>
   As you might have gathered by now, Morris guards the use of
Joe's name as if it were gold bullion. No one just walks away with
it.
</P>
<P>
   I might be even risking a lawsuit right now, just by using Joe's
name in this column without Morris' permission.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the heck with it ... Joe DiMaggio. Joe DiMaggio. Joe
DiMaggio. Joe DiMaggio. Joe DiMaggio. Joe DiMaggio. Joe DiMaggio.
Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   We certainly can all agree that Joe's name should not be
cheapened. Joe is an American icon so his name on lamp posts and
park benches and coat racks would soil his shine. There is a
certain standard, and we can all agree that it would be violated if
Denny's were serving Joe DiMaggio's Grand Slam Breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Joe was the last guy to call attention to
himself. Yes, he wanted to be introduced at banquets as ``the
greatest living baseball player,'' but that was hardly ego. That
was just the truth. From his baseball retirement in 1951 to his
death in 1999, Joe's longest recorded sentence was, ``Hey, how ya
doin'?''
</P>
<P>
   Greta Garbo never asked for an airport to be named after her.
Neither did Joe DiMaggio. Joe wanted to be left alone. We left him
alone. Nowhere is it recorded that on his deathbed did Joe turn to
Morris and say, ``Make sure they name the Pacific Ocean after me.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not Joe's style. He didn't care if a large piece of
architecture had his name on it. He wanted to be remembered as a
guy who played the game well. You can just bet Joe wouldn't have
threatened a lawsuit because San Francisco wanted to name his
boyhood park after him. He would have nodded, said ``Thanks,'' then
walked away, pulling the bill of his fedora over his eyes. He was
undercover more than some of the guys at the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Morris should remember the words he spoke at the time of
Joe's death from lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fought his illness as hard as he played the game of
baseball, with the same dignity, style and grace in which he lived
his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dignity, style and grace, that's how we should be remembering
Joe DiMaggio today, not worrying that one day we'll be on the Joe
DiMaggio Bridge at 4:30 p.m., where there is anything but dignity,
style and grace on it.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
