A4921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CDC-PROBE13-COX     04-12 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDC-PROBE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS EXPANDS CDC PROBE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional panel is expanding a probe of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention to examine the handling
of funds to seek out 4 million people thought to be infected by
hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee Chairman Thomas Bliley, R-Va., sent a
letter last week to Surgeon General David Satcher seeking
documentation on how the Atlanta-based CDC is spending $13 million
allocated for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley said his panel ``is examining the apparent failure of
CDC'' to launch general education programs to alert people who were
transfused with tainted blood before testing could detect hepatitis
C in the blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   CDC officials responded Wednesday that the agency was conducting
a major effort to find and notify the infected individuals through
tracing records on blood transfusions. That ``look back'' is 90
percent complete, said Virginia Bales, deputy director for program
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are funding and implementing a fully comprehensive
strategy'' to combat hepatitis C, she said. She added that the
program is complicated and said, ``It's perfectly understandable
that we're not at a level of full understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Bales is leading the CDC efforts to respond to audits and
investigations that have followed controversies over evidence that
the federal agency misled Congress when it diverted funds budgeted
for chronic fatigue syndrome and the Hantavirus to other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley's latest letter indicated continuing skepticism about
CDC's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be a diversion of funds and, on the surface,
that seems to be a pattern at CDC,'' said Pete Sheffield, a
spokesman for Bliley.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee has already received several boxes filled
with records on management of CDC, particularly the operations at
the Viral Division, whose director, Dr. Brian Mahy, was forced to
step down in the earlier controversies over spending. He is now a
senior biological research scientist, working ``exclusively'' on
writing for scientific publications, Bales said.
</P>
<P>
   The records collected so far indicate that Mahy and other top
officials at CDC spent a considerable portion of their time, as
much as 100 days a year, traveling. Travel for scientific meetings
has long been part of the agency's operations, but the requests for
documentation appear to be aimed at discovering whether there has
been abuse of the custom.
</P>
<P>
   Bales said that such extensive travel is necessary for top
scientists at the agency. ``Our scientists are in great demand
worldwide,'' she said. ``I'm out of town every week myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is also looking into the potential of
conflicts of interest involving private companies and the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In previous requests, Bliley's panel has sought Mahy's calendars
and notebooks going back to 1990 and records of communications
between Mahy and private companies since 1996. Last week, the House
investigators sought information on total spending for travel for
CDC since 1996 and a list of grants to pharmaceutical companies
since that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken some hits,'' Bales said, but the CDC is continuing
its top-to-bottom review. ``I see it as restoring trust in CDC,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:www.cdc.gov, or click ``issues'' at
www.house.gov/commerce
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
