<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-ONEILL-DEATH-NYT     04-12 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ONEILL-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUGENE O'NEILL'S SUSPICIONS WERE WRONG, REPORT SAYS: DRINK DIDN'T
KILL HIM 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass.)   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eugene O'Neill, playwright of souls in search of forgiveness, is
given an absolution of sorts himself, in the pages of a medical
journal.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to O'Neill's own suspicion that heavy drinking in his
youth caused the brain disease that crippled him later in life, a
new report Wednesday confirms that he died of a rare brain disease,
but says that alcohol was not to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The progressive deterioration of O'Neill's brain was due to a
rare genetic disorder, said Dr. Bruce H. Price, chairman of the
neurology department at McLean Hospital in Boston, and co-author of
an article in the New England Journal of Medicine. He said the
pattern of O'Neill's illness did not follow a typical path of
alcoholic brain disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad luck of the genetic draw that took him,'' Price
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The article, coming 47 years after O'Neill's death at the age of
65, is based on a new analysis of his medical records and autopsy,
and describes in detail the illness that stopped him from writing
during the last 10 years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill had long had a tremor in his hands, but it worsened
markedly in 1939, when he was 51. By 1941 he was having trouble
controlling a pencil, and his handwriting became shaky and so
cramped that a magnifying glass was needed to read it. Doctors
mistakenly diagnosed Parkinson's disease. In 1943, he finished the
play, ``Moon for the Misbegotten,'' and soon gave up writing,
abandoning his hope of completing a cycle of 11 plays.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, he began to have difficulty walking, feeding himself
and speaking. He choked on food and his own secretions, and became
prone to respiratory infections. During his last few months, he was
mostly bedridden. But his mind remained clear to the end.
</P>
<P>
   He died in 1953, of pneumonia, in a hotel room in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Carlotta, requested an autopsy, because, she told one
of his biographers, ``I wanted to know what in the name of God was
the matter with this man.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the New England Journal article suggests that O'Neill's
autopsy results had never been released before, his wife gave the
full autopsy report to other biographers, Arthur and Barbara Gelb,
in 1960. The Gelbs summarized the findings in their 1962 book,
``O'Neill.'' Gelb, a former managing editor of the New York Times,
now oversees the scholarship program of the New York Times
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy showed that O'Neill never had Parkinson's disease.
Rather, he had a degenerative disorder, ``perhaps familial,'' the
report stated, that had progressively destroyed his cerebellum, the
part of the brain responsible for muscle control and coordination.
</P>
<P>
   The original autopsy report did not blame alcohol. But Gelb said
in an interview that O'Neill himself had always blamed his
``alcohol-ravished youth'' for his later illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sincerely believed it, and all his doctors at the time
believed it,'' Gelb said. He added that although he had read the
new report, he still found it hard to believe that O'Neill's
alcoholism had not contributed to his illness. ``That man, to his
own accounts, lived a life of dereliction,'' Gelb said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill had drunk so heavily as a young man that he had suffered
blackouts and delirium tremens, a severe form of alcohol
withdrawal. But by his 40s, O'Neill drank just occasionally, and
not heavily, and during his last eight years he did not drink at
all. He stopped, Gelb said, because a doctor had warned him that
alcohol would damage his brain, and he feared that he would become
unable to write.
</P>
<P>
   Price said he had always been drawn to O'Neill's plays, and
became curious about his long illness in 1988. He contacted Dr. E.
P. Richardson, a professor emeritus of neuropathology at the
Harvard Medical School, who had supervised O'Neill's autopsy, and
suggested that they re-examine O'Neill's records and slides, in the
light of more recent knowledge about brain diseases. Richardson
agreed; he died in 1998, after the work was done but before the
article was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Price obtained permission to reopen O'Neill's records from his
granddaughter, the actress Geraldine Chaplin, one of eight children
born to O'Neill's daughter, Oona, and the actor Charlie Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   Examining the slides of O'Neill's brain, the doctors confirmed
the original diagnosis, ``late-onset cerebellar cortical atrophy.''
They described the condition as ``idiopathic,'' meaning its cause
was unknown. And they also said the condition was completely
unrelated to the mild hand tremor that O'Neill had early in life,
which they attributed to a familial condition known as essential
tremor.
</P>
<P>
   Price said that the cerebellar damage on the slides was
identical to that found in two different conditions: a genetic
disease, or brain atrophy due to alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that O'Neill's medical history did not match the
typical pattern of cerebellar degeneration found in alcoholics,
because that condition usually develops in those who continue to
drink heavily. It is not known to occur as a delayed reaction in
people like O'Neill, who had quit drinking years or decades before
the symptoms developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way we think alcohol works on the central
nervous system,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Richardson thought it more likely that O'Neill had a
genetic disorder. Several genetic conditions affecting the
cerebellum have been identified during the past decade. But they
could not prove that O'Neill's condition was genetic because there
was not enough tissue left for DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was no evidence that others in the family had the
condition, the doctors said it might have been due to a spontaneous
mutation that affected only O'Neill. They did not know whether he
passed it on. His daughter, Oona, had no symptoms, but whether his
two sons might have developed them is not known, because they did
not live long enough: Both committed suicide at relatively young
ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-OPEN-CURTAINS-ART-2TA     04-12 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEN-CURTAINS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAINS FOR DRAPERIES AS CONSUMERS LET THE SUN SHINE IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By KIMBERLY STEVENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gina Tarantino has sheer curtains, but she and her
husband never draw them.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do their neighbors, who roll out of bed naked each
morning, as unashamed as Adam and Eve. ``My husband tells me not to
put on my glasses,'' she said. Still, Tarantino, a 38-year-old
product designer, maintains that despite the view into the
neighbors' bedroom, there remains a real sense of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never run into each other on the street,'' she said. ``I
don't even know if I'd recognize them with their clothes on.'' In
fact, the curtainless situation has become a challenge of wills,
``It has almost become almost a war,'' Tarantino added. ``We're
both just waiting to see who's going to draw their curtains first.
Our parents tell us all the time that it's just like `Rear
Window.'''
</P>
<P>
   Trend watchers, note: It's curtains for draperies. Farewell to
billowing swathes of fabric. Goodbye to traditional decorating
moneymakers like valances, box pleats and chintz balloon curtains.
Industry experts confirm that consumers are balking at such heavy,
detailed window treatments _ not to mention their prices _ and
letting the light shine in.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As they do, they're giving the neighbors a peek. Just look out
of any high-rise apartment building in Manhattan. From the
businessman in Hell's Kitchen whose neighbors have been treated to
nighttime views of him and his bed mates (male and female) to a
couple on Fifth Avenue and 16th Street whose lovemaking is a
midmorning feature for workers in a nearby building, the modest
tradition of the drawing of the drapes is waning.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jayne, a New York decorator, attributes it to an
evolutionary shift in what is and is not considered private.
``There was a time when closing the curtains every evening was a
routine, almost a ritual,'' he said. ``It indicated private time
and a sense of closing down for the evening. People aren't as
private as they used to be. They eat in the street and they talk on
their cell phones at any time, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, it was in vogue to jam operatically scaled curtains
into small rooms to bolster architecture that was undernourished.
Today, however, a clean minimal aesthetic reigns. Jayne pointed out
that the textiles people are using are very telling: voile, unlined
silk, open-weave cottons _ all an exhibitionist's delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become joyful scopophiliacs,'' said Charles Melcher,
the editor of ``Voyeur'' (Harper Collins, 1999), a book that shows
the furtive side of famous photographers. Today, cameras monitor
restaurant diners, pedestrians, even people undergoing plastic
surgery. Cinema-verite television shows like ``Blind Date'' capture
real life on camera. ``We are amongst a society filled with very
sophisticated voyeurs or lookers,'' Melcher said. ``With the
explosion of explicit images on TV and on the web, our eyes have
been trained in a way that didn't exist 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the trend toward sheer decor, as Melcher opines,
``allows us to see, and be seen, at a very safe distance'' or
merely reflects a new casualness in the way we live and entertain,
there is a visible lightening up in the generally heavyweight world
of window treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of sheer curtains have been growing steadily at about 5
percent a year, said Andrea Lillo, a product editor at Home
Textiles Today, a trade newspaper. ``People don't want anything
fussy or formal _ they want something airy and minimalist,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Foley, the president of CHF Industries in New York, one of
the world's largest ready-made curtain companies, estimates that
sheer and semisheer fabrics comprise 90 percent of the wholesale
market today, up from 50 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Products like the semisheer louvers called window shadings have
doubled in sales since they were introduced in the early 1990s;
purchases of once-trendy shutters, known as ``hard products,'' and
ready-made formal curtains are on the decline, Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at ABC Carpet and Home, Saundra Smith, a customer,
grimaced as she flipped through swatches of chintz. ``The only
curtain I'll have in my home is one for the shower,'' she said. A
stay-at-home mother, Smith, 37, recently moved to a loft in Chelsea
where she installed only sheer shades, which she rarely closes. ``I
notice that all the lofts around us have no curtains in the windows
either,'' she said. ``And I just got the windows cleaned, so it
makes it even better.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sorkin, an architect and teacher, has no curtains in his
Greenwich Village apartment. ``I'm constantly flashing the
neighbors,'' he admitted. ``It's a way of making contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtainless living does create one problem. ``It's a struggle if
you want to sleep past dawn,'' he said. ``I have bags of those
masks that they give you on the airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The New York designer Laura Bohn says of her clients, ``They'll
give up privacy any day before they'll give up a light airy
space.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Design magazines like Wallpaper rarely show windows swathed in
curtains. They are also getting harder to find in more traditional
shelter magazines. ``I think people are afraid of draperies because
when they're bad, they're very, very bad,'' said Dominique
Browning, editor of House &AMP; Garden. But, she added, ``When they are
good, they are beautiful.'' Her advice: only trust a master.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Hadley, the legendary New York decorator, after reviewing
the differences between curtains and draperies _ he never says
``drapes'' _ said that he prefers a simple window, often one with
no curtains at all.
</P>
<P>
   The English designer John Stefanidis took a similar tack in a
historic house in Providence, R.I., that is featured in the April
issue of Architectural Digest: curtainless windows _ all the
better, he explained, to showcase the bold neo-Classical details.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're still set on the couture look and want to find it on a
budget, get thee to Target or Pottery Barn. The velvet curtains at
Target are $39 a panel; Pottery Barn's sell for $99.
</P>
<P>
   Celia Tejada, vice president of product design for Pottery Barn,
said that the chain's velvet line is still selling well _ but that
sales of sheer curtains are ``exploding.'' A 44-inch panel of
polycotton sheer is $15.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand drapes anymore,'' Gary Paul, an New
York architect, lamented. ``A drape is made to last, and there is
care involved in maintaining them. The idea of hanging something
that is made to last is competing with a society that is taught to
throw everything away.''
</P>
<P>
   But he too has opted for a fresher approach these days. He
recently designed a pied-a-terre for Derick and Suzanne Steinmann
that he referred to as ``pared down Park Avenue.'' In the formal
dining room are translucent Rogers &AMP; Goffignon linen sheers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Many homeowners would simply rather spend their money elsewhere.
Leah Epstein, a stay-at-home mother living in Larchmont, N.Y.,
recently spent weeks looking at expensive window treatments
``because I started to feel like my life was a movie set,'' she
said, referring to a large picture window at her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I started to look at all the heavy chintz with the
box pleats, I started to panic,'' she added. ``My husband and I
would rather spend the thousands of dollars on a rug or an
antique.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Jones, a co-owner of La Regence on West 29th Street, one
of the few remaining workrooms in the city that make custom
draperies, said many of the younger clients don't plan to stay put
for for long enough to invest in permanent decor. ``I think they'd
rather spend that amount of money on something they can take with
them,'' she said, noting, however, that many of the sheer panels
she makes could cost just as much as heavy drapery or balloon
shapes: $600 to $800 for one window, prices she attributes in part
to labor costs. Gauzy Asian fabrics require hand finishing. Jones
employs eight finishers, compared with three just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Park Slope, Brooklyn, Nancy Polstein, 38, says old-fashioned
draperies ``feel stuffy and nasty.'' She's replacing the midnight
blue velvet ones with sari-inspired panels trimmed in gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main concern is that they are low maintenance,'' said
Polstein, an accountant who moonlights as a rock 'n' roll drummer.
``I'm really too busy to even care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
