<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-KILLINGS-0413-     04-12 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-KILLINGS-0413-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THREE MEXICAN AGENTS PROBING DRUG CARTEL WITH AMERICAN HELP
FOUND DEAD
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican authorities on Wednesday found the
battered bodies of three federal agents who were working with U.S.
law enforcement agencies to investigate a powerful drug cartel
along the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   The agents were found dead in their car off a steep cliff along
a remote highway between the Baja California cities of Tijuana and
Mexicali.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths could be the latest in a long string of drug-related
killings of police and others investigating drug smuggling along
the border, especially in Tijuana, which is near San Diego, Calif.,
and Matamoros, which is near Brownsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The agents' bodies showed no signs of gunshots and authorities
still don't know how they died, said a visibly upset Mariano Herran
Salvatti, Mexico's chief of federal anti-drug operations.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference here Wednesday Herran said he couldn't be
sure yet if the agents' deaths were a message of intimidation. But
showing photos of bodies with massive head wounds, he praised the
agents' ``sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be stopped because of events like this,'' he said.
``We are going to redouble our efforts against drug traffickers.''
</P>
<P>
   The agents were investigating the powerful Arellano Felix
cartel, an organized crime group that smuggles cocaine and other
drugs into the United States through the Tijuana area.
</P>
<P>
   The agents had been missing since Monday when they failed to
show up for an appointment in the border community of Otay Mesa,
Mexico, which is far from the area where their bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   One of the agents, Jose Patino Moreno, had requested more than
60 search warrants in the Tijuana area and other parts of northern
Mexico before he died, Herran said.
</P>
<P>
   The probe into the Arellano Felix organization was advancing
daily, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Its most recent lines of investigation stemmed from the March 11
arrest of Jesus Labra Aviles, the alleged ``financial brain'' of
the Arellano Felix cartel, and the subsequent gangland-style
killing of Labra's lawyer, Gustavo Galvez Reyes, in Mexico City on
March 15.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the agents, Patino Moreno, was living in San
Diego for his personal safety while he worked on his investigation.
He was also living in San Diego because he was working closely with
agents from the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration and the FBI
who are also investigating the Arellano Felix group, Herran said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the start of our investigation and search for our
comrades we had the collaboration and support of the DEA and the
FBI,'' Herran added.
</P>
<P>
   The agents' deaths follow an execution-style killing Sunday of a
newspaper reporter on the opposite side the U.S.-Mexico border.
Pablo Pineda, who specialized in police corruption and drug
smuggling for the Matamoros newspaper La Opinion, was shot in the
head and dumped on the Texas side of the border. U.S. Border Patrol
agents found his body.
</P>
<P>
   The Tijuana area is notorious for scores of killings of federal,
state and local police who were targeted either because they were
honest and were investigating smugglers or because they were
corrupt and had crossed traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, Tijuana has been plagued by almost daily violent
killings.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 27 Tijuana police chief Alfredo de la Torre Marquez was
machine-gunned to death while driving on a Tijuana avenue in broad
daylight.
</P>
<P>
   The killing occurred just days after President Ernesto Zedillo
visited the neighboring city of Mexicali and pledged to crack down
on organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Herran said state _ not federal _ authorities are investigating
the police chief's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Sanchez of Tijuana's College of the Northern Border, who
has studied public security in Baja California, said the state is
vulnerable to organized crime because of police corruption and a
lack of coordination between federal and state authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Baja California is governed by the National Action Party, or
PAN, while the federal government is controlled by the dominant
Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``They mutually accuse each other of responsibility (for
violence),'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss can be reached by e-mail at:
susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
