<SLUG> BC-UNIONS-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONISTS PROTEST EASING OF TRADE RELATIONS WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 10,000 labor activists gathered at the US
Capitol Wednesday to protest the Clinton administration's proposal
to normalize trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 environmenalists arrived wearing bright-green sea
turtle costumes, in an expression of a belief that the World Trade
Organization is devastating the natural world. But for the most
part, the labor participants were focused exclusively on US China
policy, in contrast to the sweeping complaints of protesters
outside the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund across
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money,'' said Joe Teixeira, 42, a fork lift
operator from the Duro Finishing plant in Fall River, Mass. ``They
don't care about the little guys. Why would they want to deal with
a communist country? We're supposed to be the leader of the free
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton proposal would normalize trade relations with China
for the foreseeable future, rather than require Congress to vote on
the trade status on a yearly basis, as it does now.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the measure argue that it would simply force China
to open its markets, saying the only US concession is the offering
of a constant, regulated trade accord.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the pact would undercut a labor force already
suffering from previous trade deals such as the North American Free
Trade Agreement. They also oppose the next step that the accord
would allow: China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting Congress on notice that the Teamsters Union is
100 percent opposed'' to the China pact, said the Teamsters general
president, James P. Hoffa said. ``We will do whatever it takes to
protect American workers and win this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration does not expect many, if any, of the
Massachusetts legislators to vote in favor of the measure. Both
Senator Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry have strongly favored
free-trade agreements, although neither has taken a position on
this measure yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
