A4941 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CLINTON-GUNS-BOS &LR;      04-12 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BACKS COLORADO GUN-CONTROL MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ President Clinton brought his gun-control campaign to
Ground Zero in the national debate over the issue, throwing his
support behind a statewide ballot effort that was prompted by the
worst school shooting in US history.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing here a week before the first anniversary of the
Columbine High School shooting, Clinton promoted a petition drive
to get an initiative on the November ballot that would require
background checks for firearm sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you're not alone; and second, America is listening. All
across America, people like you are speaking up,'' Clinton said at
a rally at the Colorado Convention Center that he estimated
attracted 3,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, several family members and friends of the victims
of the Columbine shooting in the Denver suburb of Littleton looked
on. The incident last April 20 in which two Columbine students
killed 12 young people and a teacher before turning the guns on
themselves shocked the nation and brought a sense of urgency in
some quarters of America for stiffer gun-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to Columbine and other school shootings that have taken
place under his watch, Clinton said, ``I don't want any future
president to have to go to Columbine, or to Springfield, Ore., or
to Jonesboro, Ark., or to all the other places I have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough enough to comfort the families of our servicemen
and women who die in the line of duty,'' he said. ``Children have
no duties, except to their studies and their families. Our duty is
to protect their lives, and give them futures.''
</P>
<P>
   While applauding the effort in Colorado and in states like
Massachusetts, which recently instituted enforcing consumer product
safety rules for guns by banning so-called junk guns, requiring
child trigger locks and other devices to prevent children from
firing guns, Clinton argued that national legislation was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child in America deserves these protections,'' he said.
``You deserve a national government that follows your lead, and
Congress is the only body that can provide the kind of national
approach we need to protect all the children in every state,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit here came just a day after he joined
Maryland Governor Parris Glendening as he signed a gun-safety law
requiring external trigger locks on new handguns sold in the state
beginning in October and built-in safety locks on new handguns sold
after 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's trip seemed to have more in common with the
struggle in Colorado than in Maryland's success.
</P>
<P>
   The group sponsoring the petition drive was founded after the
Colorado legislature defeated a bill that would have required
mandatory background checks on all firearm sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The group, called SAFE Colorado, which stands for Sane
Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic, was founded after the
Columbine shooting. Clinton has been highlighting efforts being
undertaken by the state to tighten gun control laws while being
frustrated over his own inability to get Congress to move on his
gun-control proposals. The group must collect at least 62,000
signatures by August to get on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been stalled since last May on a bill that would
promote child safety locks on guns, ban the importation of
high-capacity ammunition clips, bar juveniles from possessing
assault weapons, and prohibit youths with criminal records from
possessing handguns. It has deadlocked over the issue of background
checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, a
Republican of Illinois, and Representative John Conyers of
Michigan, the committee's top Democrat, took steps to try to break
the logjam. They sent a letter to Senate Judiciary Committee
Chairman Orrin Hatch, a Republican from Utah, urging him to
schedule a meeting to work out the House and Senate differences on
the gun provision. Clinton wants congressional leaders to act on
the legislation before they recess at the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gun-show loophole is now a serious problem,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, an estimated 5 million attend more than 4,400 gun
shows across the country, according to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, Clinton was interrupted by a heckler concerned
about Iraq. Outside the convention center, a few demonstrators
protested Clinton's appearance and carried signs such as ``Gun
rights are human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Clinton said, ``It is true that even in Washington, not
every Democrat is for this legislation and not every Republican is
against it. This is largely a matter of political organization and
power among the opponents of this legislation...and a matter of
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later took part in town-hall meeting televised
nationally on MSNBC called ``Up in Arms: What Should Americans
Do?'' moderated by Tom Brokaw at Denver University.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw described Colorado as a state where the tension of the
old west meets the pressures of modern American. Clinton's
appearance in the state was rebuffed by the Repubican governor, who
refused to appear with the president at the rally or town-hall
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those tensions and the potency of the issue of gun
control, Clinton was optimistic. ``The fact that it's an election
year might help us to pass it,'' he said on the television program.
Clinton said all he wants is for America to be ``the safest big
country in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
