u i BC-ISRAEL-CHINA-(TRIMS)-     04-12 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CHINA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE PRESIDENT VISITS ISRAEL AS U.S. PROTESTS AIRCRAFT DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Jiang Zemin of China flew into Israel and
a storm of controversy Wednesday as U.S. opposition to a planned
Israeli arms deal with his country overshadowed the first official
visit by a Chinese leader here.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, arriving at Ben-Gurion International Airport several
hundred yards from a rusting hangar that is home to an advanced
aircraft at the center of the controversy. For a year, technicians
from Israel Aircraft Industries have been outfitting a
Chinese-owned Ilyushin-76 with its advanced Phalcon airborne early
warning system. Crowned with an AWACS-style radar pod and crammed
with espionage gear, the droop-winged jet can monitor the movement
and communications of planes, ships and ground troops across 250
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang is to hold talks Thursday with Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
who is flying home from a meeting at the White House, where
President Clinton reiterated Washington's objections to the sale.
In a suggested compromise that promises to satisfy neither
Washington nor Beijing, Barak is said to have told the Americans
that Israel would provide the Chinese with just one of the advanced
plane, although it had agreed to give them an option to purchase at
least three more.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. congressional leaders have threatened to cut military aid
to Israel in retaliation for the sale, which Pentagon officials say
could endanger United States forces in case of a Chinese
confrontation with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have adopted an almost defiant stance,
pointing to legal and ethical commitment to contracts. They also
noted that Washington did not object when Israel formally notified
it of the pending sale four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be put in a situation whereby we cannot act
without authorization from every country,'' Foreign Minister David
Levy said Wednesday morning on Israel Radio. ``Clearly we will not
do something that harms the United States. But at the same time,
the United States must understand that we are a country like every
other country and we are also working to further our interests,
just as it does _ even with China.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official stressed that Washington was
concerned not just by the Phalcon transaction, but also by the
entire ``developing defense relationship'' between Israel and
China. U.S. officials cite China's new J-10 jet fighter, which
defense experts say is based on an Israeli prototype developed with
U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis continue to argue that a closer relationship with
the Chinese military can help Israel dissuade Beijing from
supplying sophisticated weaponry to Iraq and Iran, despite
persistent reports that some Israeli-assisted Chinese arms
technology may have already indirectly found its way to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The experts also dispute a contention that Israel would be
supplying China an airborne surveillance system that it could not
obtain elsewhere. When Israel was negotiating for the contract, the
experts said, at least one European company, now part of a giant
British military contractor, BAE Systems, was also bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Israel cancels the deal today, with all that implies in
terms of our future interests, would other countries, especially
European countries, not fill this niche?'' Levy asked. ``There
should be no delusions here.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's visit is planned as the culmination of a long courtship,
intended to open China to Israeli commerce and pry Beijing from its
once-staunch support for Israel's adversaries in the Arab world. In
a weeklong stay interrupted by day trips to Egypt and
Palestinian-governed Bethlehem, Jiang will visit Yad Vashem, the
Holocaust memorial, and the Western Wall in the Old City of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At his request, he will also tour software centers in Tel Aviv,
where China is seen as a prime market. But with the AWACS
controversy unexpectedly clouding the visit, Israeli officials are
scaling back economic expectations for the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Even one Phalcon plane, at a reported $250 million, would
represent more than a doubling of annual Israeli sales to China.
Last year, two-way trade between Israel and China reached $520
million, with Israel exporting $190 million.
</P>
<P>
   Four Phalcon-equipped planes _ the price would come down to $230
million each, industry executives have said _ would together
represent one of the largest foreign contracts ever for Israel
Aircraft Industries. With 14,000 workers and $1.5 billion in
foreign sales last year, the state-owned company is the single
biggest employer and export earner in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not do anything which could upset or damage our
relations with the United States,'' Levy said. ``On the other hand,
we cannot tell the Chinese that our promises are not promises and
our oaths are not oaths or our signature is not a signature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
