u f BC-GRASSROOTS-LEAGUE-BOS     04-12 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRASSROOTS-LEAGUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES PROTEST GRASSROOTS.COM, LWV DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A deal between a Web company and the League of Women Voters is
being criticized by a conservative lobbying group, which wants the
government to launch a broad review of online political activities.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Grassroots.com, runs one of a new group of sites
that aim to draw in users with material about candidates and local
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sites &UR;  &LR;  earn revenue by charging candidates to
publish their literature or to forward e-mail to certain voters.
</P>
<P>
   Grassroots offers similar services, and in February it struck a
deal with the League of Women Voters to publish information on
local and national elections and to make use of the League's large
network of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the League received an ownership stake in Grassroots,
a for-profit company based in San Bruno, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The league said the deal was needed to obtain more money to
promote its online efforts, which also include a nonprofit known as
DNet. Other Grassroots backers including Knight Ridder Inc., the
big newspaper publisher.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrangement with Grassroots has drawn objections within
the League and from other activists, who felt it could compromise
the League's independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, they're auctioning off control of the public
agenda,'' said Scott Reents, president of the rival
democracyproject.org site in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives also groused at the league's arrangement. In a
complaint filed with the Federal Election Commission this week, the
National Legal and Policy Center alleges Grassroots' service
amounts to a ``commercial venture providing highly valuable goods
and services without charge to candidates,'' in violation of
elections laws.
</P>
<P>
   The center has been a frequent critic of Democrats such as
Hillary Clinton and the Teamsters Union. Now it wants the elections
commission to review an advisory opinion issued last October
approving the league's DNet activities. It said the approval
shouldn't apply to the league's for-profit ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Flaherty, the center's president, called the league's
actions ``a bait-and-switch'' and said he will seek fines and other
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the league and Grassroots denied there was
subterfuge and noted that the FEC last fall approved the actions of
a for-profit political Web site as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This complaint raises questions that have already been
answered by the FEC'' in the company's favor, said Craig Johnson,
the Grassroots' interim chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   So long as the sites are nonpartisan and offer equal access to
all candidates, he said, prohibitions on their corporate activities
shouldn't apply.
</P>
<P>
   Grassroots has raised about $35 million in venture capital from
investors including Knight Ridder. A Knight Ridder spokeswoman
didn't return calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
