<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-NYT     04-12 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE, BUCKING THE HOUSE, PROPOSES SHARING ORGAN TRANSPLANTS
NATIONALLY
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md., Pa., Neb., Va., Fla., Tenn., Mass.)  By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With support from the Clinton administration, the
Senate Wednesday took a bipartisan crack at breaking the political
deadlock over organ transplants, but the House of Representatives
remains committed to an entirely different approach.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are whether donated organs should be distributed
locally or nationally when they become available and whether
decisions about these scarce resources should be made primarily by
the private sector or the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate health committee Wednesday unanimously approved a
bill that would make it the national policy to reduce the
geographical disparities in the availability of organs for
transplant. The bill would establish a mediation system to resolve
disputes over organ allocation between the Department of Health and
Human Services and the private organization that runs the
distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the legislation were worked out by Sen. Bill
Frist, R-Tenn.; Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; and Donna E.
Shalala, the secretary of health and human services.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been arguing for years that organs should
be shared broadly throughout the country, with the sickest patients
generally given priority. The Senate bill would make that possible.
</P>
<P>
   Under the existing system, authority for organ distribution
rests with a private nonprofit organization, the United Network for
Organ Sharing. The country is divided into 62 localities. When an
organ becomes available, it is offered locally first. The waiting
period varies considerably by town and region.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, by a margin of nearly 2-to-1, the House passed a bill
that would have the effect of maintaining this system and
preventing national distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The main advocates of the House bill, Reps. Thomas J. Bliley Jr.
of Virginia, chairman of the Commerce Committee, and Michael
Bilirakis of Florida, chairman of the health subcommittee, both
Republicans, would not comment Wednesday on the Senate bill. But a
House staff assistant who has been following the legislation
closely said, ``We are still on opposite sides of the Grand Canyon
on this.''
</P>
<P>
   A Senate staff expert conceded, ``We have a long, long way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences are parochial and not partisan. In the House,
politicians from Virginia voted one way and those from Maryland the
other, regardless of party. The same was true with representatives
from Kansas and Nebraska and those from New Jersey and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The determining factor is that large transplant centers like
Johns Hopkins in Baltimore, the Lied Transplant Center in Omaha and
the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center believe they would have
better access to needed organs from a national system. Smaller
transplant centers are afraid they will be put out of business by
the giants.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Health and Human Services, 278
hospitals in the nation perform organ transplants, and most of them
are relatively small. That has considerable influence on members of
the House, many of whom have small hospitals that perform
transplants in their districts or in adjacent ones.
</P>
<P>
   A political counterbalance to this could be the authority
exercised by Frist, who was a transplant surgeon before he was
elected to the Senate in 1994 and who founded a small transplant
center at Vanderbilt University in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since there are too few organs to go around, how we distribute
the organs that are available decides who will live and who will
die,'' Frist said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The chief factors, he said, should be ``scientific data, medical
principles and equity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
