<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4955 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NE-OIL-RESERVE-BOS &LR;      04-12 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NE-OIL-RESERVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OK'S HEATING OIL RESERVE FOR NORTHEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Aiming to stop the heating oil price spikes that
afflicted New England homeowners this winter, the House of
Representatives Wednesday voted to create a government-controlled
reserve of heating oil in the Northeast that could be released
during ``severe'' price hikes or supply shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, drafted by Representative Edward J. Markey,
Democrat of Massachusetts, has the support of President Clinton,
but its Senate prospects are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Home heating oil prices nearly tripled within a few weeks this
year, thanks to a slowdown in OPEC production and because a mild
winter turned suddenly colder, creating strong demand at a time of
low inventories. Iced-in harbors also made it hard for tankers to
make deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The price hikes hit hardest in the Northeast, as the region
relies heavily on heating oil to heat homes.
</P>
<P>
   The new, 2 million barrel heating oil reserve would be in
addition to the nation's Strategic Petroleum Reserve, which
contains about 570 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The national reserve is intended to keep the nation running
during severe energy supply disruptions, generally interpreted to
mean wartime or a cutoff by foreign producers. Presidents have been
reluctant to release oil to manipulate market prices and give
consumers relief.
</P>
<P>
   Looser rules would guide the release of heating oil from the new
Northeast reserve. The president could sell oil from the reserve
into the market when there are ``severe'' price increases or other
emergencies affecting supplies in the region. Under the bill, this
winter's price spikes and low supplies ``would be a prime
candidate'' for triggering a release from the reserves, one
congressional aide said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute, a trade group, said the
reserve would ``do more harm than good,'' encouraging wholesalers
and distributors to keep stocks at low levels, so that the total
volume of heating oil on hand would not change. Moreover, ``the
high cost of operating the reserve would fall upon taxpayers and
consumers,'' the trade group said in a recent policy statement.
</P>
<P>
   The reserve would be managed by the US Department of Energy,
which would likely lease storage space in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the measure in a lopsided 416-8 vote, largely
because Texas lawmakers won a provision that requires the
government to buy oil from certain producers when prices plummet.
</P>
<P>
   As heating oil prices rose this winter, a variety of Northeast
lawmakers called on President Clinton to sell oil from the national
reserve, but he resisted. He took several other actions, such as
releasing emergency aid for low-income people to buy heating oil.
He also called on Congress to create a Northeast reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the idea in the Senate is uncertain. Senator Edward
M. Kennedy of Massachusetts has introduced a bill requiring
wholesalers to keep heating oil reserves at a certain level as a
cushion against shortages and price runups. Senators from New York
and Maine have proposed changing the mission of the national
reserves so that the president could release oil more easily. But
it is unknown whether Northeast senators can win votes from other
regions of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
