<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS-COX     04-12 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Consider the Braves exposed.
</P>
<P>
   In the cold of Wrigley Field, the NL Central bottom-dwelling
Cubs have found the worst in the Braves and pounced on it.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of three-run home runs by Shane Andrews cut to the core
of the Braves' pitching problems. Andrews' first homer beat Kerry
Ligtenberg on Monday. His second, in his next at-bat, helped beat
former Cub Terry Mulholland 11-4 on Wednesday. The Cubs won two
games in a row for the first time this season, and the Braves lost
two in a row for the first time. The Braves, who will lose their
first series of the season, are now 1-9 in their last 10 games at
Wrigley Field, with one more game to play today.
</P>
<P>
   In a repeat of his last outing against the Giants, Mulholland
gave up three more home runs and reeled in another loss. He also
compounded the doubts about keeping a 37-year-old journeyman in the
rotation. He is 0-2 with a 12.96 ERA and has yet to make it out of
the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stunk. I flat-out stunk,'' Mulholland said. ``I'm
embarrassed to be out there throwing the ball like I'm throwing it
right now. It's not fair to the other guys on this club to put up
that kind of performance while they're busting their butts to try
to get back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   His outing overshadowed a big day from Chipper Jones. The third
baseman homered twice to give him three in the two-game series and
drove in all four Braves runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned the corner, I think, but it certainly takes some of
the luster out of it, not playing well as a team,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   After two trips through the rotation, the Braves still have some
pitching decisions to make. Their Band-Aid approach to the loss of
John Smoltz has resulted in 13 runs given up and two loses, and
they haven't had to worry about a fifth starter yet.
</P>
<P>
   The same possibilities they have for a fifth starter _ Bruce
Chen, John Burkett, Luis Rivera and, eventually, Steve Avery _
would seem logical for the fourth, if they don't look outside the
organization first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when we've had problems, we've fixed them,'' Jones
said. ``I'm sure it'll come internally. . . . It's weird, because I
feel like everybody is still getting used to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland said he had no business pitching the Cubs inside the
way he did in the first inning, when he surrendered a double to
Eric Young, a walk to Sammy Sosa, a single to Glenallen Hill and
the homer to Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   But that inning wasn't as tough to take as the fifth, when he
gave up four more runs, three on a three-run homer to Hill on an
inside fastball, after the Braves had cut the lead to 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   His six home runs allowed is one more than Mulholland gave up in
16 outings for the Braves last season after arriving in the July 31
trade with the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
