<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-DECIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6-YEAR-OLD CAN'T MAKE CRITICAL DECISIONS, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taken at their word, Elian Gonzalez' relatives in
Miami canceled a long-awaited meeting with Elian's father in
Washington Wednesday _ which presumably would have hastened the
conclusion of an emotional international custody battle _ because a
6-year-old boy didn't want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in child development and psychology, however, agree that
no one as young as Elian is capable of understanding abstract
notions such as death, freedom, or permanence, much less the
complex concepts involved in life-altering decisions such as where
to live for the rest of his life or with whom.
</P>
<P>
   They warn that elevating a child's sense of self-importance to
such a high level, as often happens during divorces and other
custody disputes, can result in a psychic ``crash'' that leaves
lingering scars when a boy or girl inevitably realizes how little
power he or she really has. And that is only one aspect of
childhood development that specialists say the Gonzalez family in
Miami apparently either hasn't fully considered or doesn't
understand.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Catherine Snow heard that Elian's great
uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, had cited the boy's desire as the reason
for canceling the meeting with his father, she believed Elian
probably had expressed reluctance. She thought, however, that he
had reflected the sentiments instilled by the adults around him and
not necessarily his real feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Weiner found Lazaro Gonzalez's explanation ``bizarre'' and
``incredible'' because ``nobody with any proper knowledge or
appreciation of childhood would allow a child that young to make
such a critical decision.'' Mainly, he wondered if Elian's
purported veto was just a handy excuse for an adult looking for
one.
</P>
<P>
   Snow is a childhood-development specialist at the Harvard
Graduate School of Education, and Weiner, a psychiatrist, is one of
three prominent mental-health experts advising the federal
government on Elian's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cuban-Americans in Miami, along with Elian's family there
and their lawyers, have repeatedly urged federal officials to
consider the boy's desires when deciding his fate.
</P>
<P>
   Without discussing the politics of the case or offering opinions
about the eventual outcome, many of those interviewed Wednesday
suggested Elian's current guardians are behaving irresponsibly if
they believe a 6-year-old should have a say in either the custody
battle _ unless he provides evidence of abuse or some other extreme
behavior _ or the logistics of a meeting with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might ask them what they want in order to understand what
they're thinking, what their fears are and to determine how best to
help,'' said Aaron Lazar, a psychiatrist and chancellor of the
University of Massachusetts Medical School in Worcester. ``But it's
not the basis for any adult making any decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazar, who also is executive director of the Center for Adoption
Research at his school, said it was ``disingenuous'' for Elian's
great uncle to place responsibility for the canceled meeting on the
boy. ``It's an inappropriate way to treat a 6-year-old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those interviewed Wednesday used similar analogies:
Every parent has experienced a child insisting he wants to stay
home from school, wanting only doughnuts for breakfast or making
some similar demand. And nearly every parent has simply said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might let your kids decide whether to brush their teeth
now or later, but it's the parent's responsibility to make the
serious decisions and set the boundaries,'' said Ellen
Pinderhughes, a professor at Vanderbilt University who studies
family socialization processes and has acted as a consultant in
custody cases.
</P>
<P>
   Pinderhughes said adults who have physical possession of a child
are sometimes advised by their lawyers to retain hold as long as
possible so their bonding increases, while the child's alienation
from the parent seeking custody grows. As a result, a child may not
to want to see his father, which could influence a judge or other
officials making a custody decision.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, judges involved in custody cases know that a
6-year-old's testimony has limitations and generally appoint a
guardian to advocate for the child's interests; the guardian
interviews the child, as well as others, before making a
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   A judge might interview a child as young as 9, but that is not
common. ``It's highly unlikely a judge would interview a 6-year-old
child directly,'' said Gerry Koocher, chief psychologist at
Children's Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Gordetsky, a child psychologist who has been involved in
many custody cases, said so much of what a 6-year-old says is
influenced by the emotions of his immediate situation, and a child
that age can detect in subtle ways what is expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children at that age are very sensitive to what the adults
around him want them to say and feel,'' she said. That is
especially true of children who have experienced trauma and loss,
who frequently try to please the adults around them partly out of
fear that they will be abandoned yet again.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans in Miami seem less certain than the
psychiatrists and behavioral specialists, however.
</P>
<P>
   At La Carreta, a popular Cuban restaurant on Calle Ocho, Little
Havana's best-known street until Elian arrived, many lunch-time
patrons had trouble Wednesday comparing the boy with other
6-year-olds or their own children.
</P>
<P>
   No child, the diners said, should make important decisions.
That's up to the parents or family. Yes, they inevitably added,
Elian should have a say in his future, if not the entire say.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Alzafe, an engineering firm executive and mother of a
16-year-old daughter, stressed that Elian's relatives must listen
to his fears, especially if they include fears of his father and
life in Cuba. Like many other diners, she said she did not believe
Elian's relatives have planted thoughts in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child is saying, `I don't want to go,' and you can see
it's traumatic for him,'' Alzafe said. ``You should listen to what
he's saying. You have to hear him out. If he's reacting in terror,
he's sending out a message. ... We all know this is a special
case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff writers Patricia Wen in Boston and Lynda Gorov in Miami
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
