u a BC-MA-ANTISEMITISM-BOS &LR;      04-12 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ANTISEMITISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTISEMITISM UP IN BAY STATE, ADL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In contrast to a national trend, the number of
anti-Semitic incidents in Massachusetts rose slightly last year,
according to a study by the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   But the escalating intensity of such incidents _ including
shootings in Los Angeles and Chicago _ and the virulent tone of
Internet messages has raised concern beyond the raw statistics, ADL
officials said at a news conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone is getting more vulgar and more frightening,'' said
Andrew Tarsy of the ADL.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Massachusetts recorded 112 incidents, five more than
in 1998 and the fourth-highest total nationwide, according to the
study. Only California, New York, and New Jersey recorded more
incidents. While the state figure rose slightly, incidents declined
slightly nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The expressions of anti-Jewish bias included an incident in
September, in which an Agawam woman's car was covered with
swastikas and firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   Swastikas were painted on or burned into several public places
as well. An Andover teen burned one into a high school athletic
field; in Groton, someone scorched a swastika on the surface of a
public tennis court; and in North Attleborough, a swastika was
burned into the ground of a little league baseball field.
</P>
<P>
   Organized hate groups were found to be operating in the Bay
State, including the World Church of the Creator, which dropped
anti-Jewish literature in at least five towns, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Smith, a movement leader whose teachings include a
rejection of the Holocaust, targeted college newspapers in New
England and got an advertisement published at Fitchburg State
College, Emerson College, the University of Massachusetts at
Lowell, and UMass-Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't pranks and it's not just vandalism,'' said
Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly ``It's purposeful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4970 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN-TEAMSTERS-CH     04-12 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-TEAMSTERS-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUCHANAN URGES CONGRESS TO OPPOSE INCREASED CHINA TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Patrick Buchanan, the likely Reform Party
presidential nominee, charged Wednesday that granting China normal
trading relations permanently would threaten American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that over the last two decades trade deals,
including those with China, have led to ``plants, factories, jobs
sent overseas. That means us borrowing. That means us selling out
our country.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined Teamsters President James Hoffa and five members of
Congress in a union rally on Capitol Hill aimed at persuading
Congress to vote against freer trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, referring to the strong lobbying by business
executives for more China trade, argued that ``the jobs of American
workers, the economic security of American families and the
economic independence of the American nation come ahead of the
stock options of the Fortune 500.'' The audience of several
thousand people cheered loudly.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative commentator also said the U.S. government
should not grant China permanent trade status until Beijing allows
its people more freedom and ceases to produce weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were there in the White House I'd tell (Chinese leaders),
`You stop persecuting Christians, you stop threatening my country
or you guys have sold your last pair of chopsticks in any mall in
the United States of America,''' Buchanan declared.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-free-trade candidate, who ran for president in 1992 and
1996, has joined with many AFL-CIO unions to fight the trade
measure proposed by President Clinton to give China permanently the
same low tariffs that the United States grants most other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979 Congress has reviewed China's trading status
annually, and each year, often after fierce debates, it has granted
the normal status to Beijing. Thus, Clinton's proposal would end
what has long been an annual rite of spring.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa urged Congress to retain the annual review so it can
continue to threaten China with the loss of exports to this country
if it doesn't improve its labor and human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters leader, referring to Beijing's imprisonment of
labor activists and political dissidents, said, ``Let's keep China
on probation.''
</P>
<P>
   The China bill is expected to pass in the Senate, but its
chances in the House, which will vote first on it in late May, are
too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has argued that increasing trade with China would create
American jobs instead of losing them.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Roeder, spokeswoman for Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., a
strong supporter of the China bill, noted that ``22 percent of the
world's consumers are in China. The opportunities for (America's)
small businesses and medium-sized firms (to sell to the Chinese)
are astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents also say that if permanent trade status is not
granted, American business will lose out to nations that do grant
it to China. Beijing has said it will lower tariffs for the nations
that accept permanent trade relations with it.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. David Bonior, D-Mich., Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., Joe Baca,
D-Calif., Christopher Smith, R-N.J., and Bernard Sanders, I-Vt.,
also spoke at the rally against permanently lowering barriers to
China.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said large corporations are spending huge amounts of
money to lobby for more China trade. He warned the union members
who were preparing to lobby their own lawmakers that when they
approach the Capitol they should ``duck because there's money
flying all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)Hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
