<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WORLD-BANK-IMF-HNS &LR;      04-12 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BANK-IMF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESS JOINS CHORUS OF PROTESTERS, DENOUNCES LENDING
AGENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress on Wednesday denounced the International
Monetary Fund and World Bank as ineffective and secretive, echoing
the chorus of demonstrators converging on the nation's capital in
criticizing the lending organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care whether you're talking about a local government
in New Jersey or the IMF . . . the doors of government should be
open to the public that pays its bills,'' Rep. Jim Saxton, R-N.J.,
told a congressional hearing on the IMF and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton, chairman of the Joint Economic Committee of the House
and Senate, said Republicans and Democrats in Congress want more
transparency in the two organization's decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our own representative to the IMF couldn't even tell us
exactly how decisions are made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Capitol, hundreds of people demonstrated against IMF
and World Bank policies toward poor nations. The lending
institutions' leaders are meeting in Washington this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank, known formally as the International Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, provides long-term loans for
economic development projects in poor countries. The IMF arranges
short-term loans directly to countries in sudden economic crisis,
often imposing austerity measures on them in return for the aid.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the disappearance of millions of dollars in IMF loans to
the Russia, Saxton said the IMF and World Bank also need to improve
their ability to keep track of the money they loan to countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Russia last year, and it was obvious to anyone with
eyes that the IMF had done nothing to look after the money it
loaned to Russia's Central Bank,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fortney ``Pete'' Stark, D-Calif., accused the IMF and World
Bank of failing in their missions.
</P>
<P>
   By forcing many East Asian countries to cut back on social
spending and benefits to the poor, the IMF caused those nations'
financial crises of the late 1990s to ``last longer and hurt
more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF takes advantage of countries when they are most in
need, coercing them to adopt policies which will benefit the rich
at the expense of the poor,'' Stark said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stark, World Bank polices also resulted in lower
living standards. In addition, he said the bank's loans have caused
``massive'' environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Bank is focused on economic growth at any cost,''
Stark said. ``The fact that the wealth created goes to only a few
individuals while the vast majority of workers are forced to live
on less and less doesn't seem to matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark said poor countries, in attempting to meet IMF and World
Bank criteria, lower labor standards and discard environmental
protections. ``The flip side of the race for profits is the `race
to the bottom' in terms of workers' rights and the degradation of
our planet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stark called on the two institutions to incorporate labor
standards and environmental protections in evaluating when to give
loans.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank spokeswoman Merrell Tuck said in an interview that
her organization and the IMF already have revamped their operations
to increase openness and financial accountability. She added that
the IMF and World Bank work with countries to ensure reasonable
labor conditions and environmental protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of our organizations are committed to improving living
standards and helping the economies of poor countries develop,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank and IMF are specialized agencies of the United
Nations and are primarily funded by developed countries.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hundred yards away from the hearing room, hundreds of
demonstrators demanded similar changes in the IMF and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two organizations are wreaking havoc on workers and
environments around the world,'' said Michael Jones, a demonstrator
from Paterson, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, one of a number of protesters dressed as a sea turtle,
was joined by several members of the ``radical cheerleaders.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest activities are being coordinated by a coalition
called the Mobilization for Global Justice, comprised of many of
the same groups that disrupted meetings last December of the World
Trade Organization in Seattle, forcing authorities to declare a
state of emergency and call out the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   The protest groups are hoping to use human chains and other
tactics employed in Seattle to block intersections on Sunday and
keep finance ministers from attending a joint meeting of the IMF
and World Bank, which are two blocks from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The police here have studied tapes of the Seattle demonstrations
and hope to avoid the melees that occurred there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
