<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     04-12 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MISSING FROM THE CAMPAIGN: SPEECHES THAT STIR AMERICA'S SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 16)  &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By November we should know just about all we need
to know about the positions of Al Gore and George W. Bush on the
major issues that will help shape America's destiny in this new
century.
</P>
<P>
   We also should know much more than we do today about the
character, temperament and integrity of the two presidential
contestants. From their speeches, their debates and their reaction
to adversity, we will begin to see what our candidates are made of
and how they will react under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from all that, we should learn what their aspirations
are for themselves and our country. Where and how would each
candidate like to lead America during the next four or eight years?
Does he have a positive vision of America's future akin to those of
the greatest of our past presidents?
</P>
<P>
   Speech writers can provide a candidate or a president with
lyrical passages and messages of hope. Even Warren G. Harding, whom
most historians rate as our worst president, delivered an inaugural
speech in 1921 that was filled with flowery phrases and inspiring
prose.
</P>
<P>
   A speech writer cannot, however, set an administration's course
in time of crisis or infuse a president's backbone with steel or
his heart with kindness. Those attributes must emanate from the man
himself.
</P>
<P>
   In the current campaign, we have watched Gore barnstorm the
country like an old-time evangelist on the sawdust trail, shouting
his promise of a new birth of well-being for all who follow him. We
know from his performance thus far that he has a tendency to
exaggerate his past accomplishments and lay claim to some, such as
playing a key role in inventing the Internet, that were created and
perfected by others.
</P>
<P>
   We have watched Bush move swiftly from village to town to city,
claiming, with a self-satisfied smirk, a peerless record of
achievement as governor of Texas. But his claim, especially as it
pertains to education and the environment, is disputed by many
Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Although it seems that the presidential campaign already has
been under way for years rather than months, it may be too early to
discern which candidate _ by virtue of experience, knowledge,
veracity and a vision of the future _ is better equipped to become
the republic's 43rd president.
</P>
<P>
   Watching New York's then-Gov. Mario Cuomo from afar, Richard
Nixon noted a few years before his death that Cuomo understood the
``poetry of politics.'' He was right. Cuomo can soar on a rainbow
of eloquence as he contrasts the hope and the reality of the
American dream.
</P>
<P>
   He proved that when he keynoted the 1984 Democratic National
Convention and when he placed Bill Clinton's name in nomination at
the 1992 convention.
</P>
<P>
   Not many politicians, including presidential aspirants, possess
the innate ability to project what former President George Bush
dismissed as the ``vision thing'' and make it sound sincere. But
history will remember Bush as the man who was president when the
Berlin Wall tumbled down, when the Soviet Union disintegrated and
when Operation Desert Storm liberated Kuwait from the military
invasion of Iraq's Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   It also may remember Bush as a president who urged Americans in
all walks of life to sacrifice time and effort helping other
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may recall his words, composed by speech writer
Peggy Noonan, in his Inaugural address: ``I have spoken of a
thousand points of light, of all the community organizations that
are spead like stars throughout the nation, doing good The old
ideas are new again because they are not old, they are timeless:
duty, sacrifice, commitment and a patriotism that finds its
expression in taking part and pitching in.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither Gore nor George W. Bush has demonstrated an
ability to define the American experience and the American dream
with the eloquence of Cuomo, John Kennedy or Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, who learned on the Warner Brothers sound stages how to
project conviction and hope, was a master communicator who
described America as ``the shining city on a hill,'' a special
place chosen by the Almighty as a land of unfettered promise and
goodness.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan understood the need for oratory that lifted the human
soul above of the doldrums of everyday survival.
</P>
<P>
   And what words of Kennedy's have reverberated across the
decades? Those of his Inaugural address in 1961 when he declared,
``Ask not what your country can do for you; ask what you can do for
your country.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Woodrow Wilson, Kennedy left a legacy to generations that
followed him _ he reawakened in the soul of Americans everywhere
the hope and conviction that government is good and that politics
need not be practiced in a negative manner.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II it was said that Winston Churchill had
marshaled the English language as a mighty weapon to instill
courage and resolve into the people whose homes and places of work
and worship were being destroyed each night by German air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   One of Franklin D. Roosevelt's great talents was his ability to
use his radio fireside chats to restore hope to millions of
Americans who had lost their homes and their livelihoods in the
Great Depression of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   America is not now standing with its back to a wall, fighting a
cruel enemy. But it is a country whose soul needs uplifting. That
should be a basic element of the presidential campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
