<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-12 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HERE COME THE BIG PARADES 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's capital is bracing for the springtime
Invasion of the Demonstrators. The corner outside my office is
patrolled by helmeted cops ordered to smile at marchers while
snarling traffic; barricades channel the flow of picketing,
chanting paraders; windows are being boarded up by nervous
restaurateurs.
</P>
<P>
   I love it. No dissident Chinese is allowed to protest in
Tiananmen Square, and no apathetic Russian can be moved to hold up
a sign in Red Square, but the streets around the White House are
filled with Americans espousing their causes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the banner of ``Mobilization for Global Justice,'' here
come anarchists allied with tree-huggers, prayer vigilantes,
foreign-debt cancelers, Luddite globophobes and gutsy human rights
activists. They seek to relive the battle of Seattle by disrupting
next week's sessions of the IMF and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   And look _ there are the 10,000 members of the AFL-CIO,
arm-in-arm in solidarity with 5,000 Teamsters, headed up toward
Capitol Hill to stiffen the sinews of Democrats who may be wavering
in their opposition to President Clinton's plan to reward
anti-union China with entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   That's only the beginning of the season's big parades. Next week
comes the Earth Day rally and celebration on the Mall, hosted by
the ABC newshawk Leonardo DiCaprio, possibly featuring Al Gore in
his latest earth-tone outfit, which would give George W. Bush the
opportunity to participate the week after in the gays' ``Millennium
March for Equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Militant matriarchs come next. The ``Million Mom March,'' with
Rosie O'Donnell at the anchor desk, will turn Mother's Day into a
rally for stringent gun-control laws. (Will the NRA counter with
its own parade of ``pistol-packin' mamas''?)
</P>
<P>
   My favorite demo, scheduled for May 7 _ between the Sundays
chosen by the gay Millennium Marchers and the Million Moms _ is the
``Million Mutt March.'' This is advertised (on metropets.org/mmm)
as the local part of ``a nationwide effort to promote adoption of
mixed-breed, older, and special-needs dogs, and help eliminate
canine discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Derrico, its organizer, informs me that 20 local animal
shelters will join with lovers of companion animals to help end the
stigma of cross-breeding. She never calls them mongrels (``dogs of
blended heritage'' is preferred) and does not expect a million to
show up, any more than Rosie expects a million moms. Maybe a
hundred or two sniffing around; it's just the alliteration every
march now needs.
</P>
<P>
   But one of my Bernese mountain dogs, Emily, is heartbroken.
Berners are purebred, said to be descendants of the breed that led
the Carthaginian general Hannibal's elephants across the Alps.
Emily was chairbitch of last year's Bark Ball, a black-tie
fund-raising event of the Humane Society, but because of her
pedigree feels unwelcome at the Million Mutt March. (I may bring
her to watch the marchers near the Capitol steps, if she will learn
to ``sit-stay.'')
</P>
<P>
   Is today's series of mobilizations different from the angry
``new mobe'' that sought to paralyze the government three decades
ago?
</P>
<P>
   In those days of Vietnam, troops in fighting gear patrolled our
streets. Bumper-to-bumper buses ringed the White House to form an
impenetrable barrier. A shrewd park service director denied the use
of Lafayette Park to the protesters by fencing it off, ostensibly
to repave the walkways with brick, a project the Nixon staff
managed to string out for years.
</P>
<P>
   No mood like that exists today. Some jerks will befoul the
demonstrations by breaking windows or taunting patient cops into
arrests, but the level of anger and resentment is of a different
order of magnitude. These cell-phoned crowds are activist but not
militant; today's ``mobe'' is no mob.
</P>
<P>
   So bring on the signs and graffiti that provide gainful
employment for camera crews. Make Loans Not War; Gay Bankers
Forgive Debts; Put That Pistol Down, Ma; Adopt a Mutt, Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you agree or not, or watch on TV or from the middle of a
traffic jam, take pride in Washington's peaceful parade of parades.
Be a playgoer at the thrilling street theater of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at curbside, Emily and I will urge on the outdoor
activists as they exercise their legs, lungs and rights. (Sit!
Stay.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
