<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4976 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CLINTON-GUNS-COX     04-12 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton: Country's `duty' is to keep kids safe
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The battle to pass ``sensible'' gun legislation will be
a long and laborious challenge, President Clinton said here
Wednesday, but Colorado and other states need to set an example for
Congress in the ultimate goal of keeping the nation safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve a nation that follows your lead,'' Clinton told
about 2,500 people at a downtown rally for a proposed ballot
initiative to close the so-called gun-show loophole in Colorado
that would require background checks for all firearms sales at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Currently only federally licensed gun dealers are required to do
background checks on buyers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the initiative a necessary measure of prevention, not an
effort to remove guns from society, Clinton said it was up to
adults to take the lead in increased efforts to keep guns out of
the hands of people who shouldn't have them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children have no duties but their studies and their
families,'' Clinton said. ``Our duty is to protect their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   According to SAFE Colorado, the gun legislation advocacy group
that introduced the initiative after the Legislature failed to pass
a similar bill this session, more than 80 percent of Coloradans
would support the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said such a background check should be of no concern to
law-abiding gun owners and dealers, adding that more than 95
percent of criminal background checks can be completed in an hour.
The checks that take longer than that have a rejection rate 20
times higher, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's worth a little bit of inconvenience to save a few
thousand lives over the next few years,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mauser, father of Columbine High School shooting victim
Daniel Mauser and the political affairs director for Sane
Alternatives to the Firearm Epidemic, said the people have sent a
message to the Colorado Legislature already.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Legislature's failure to pass (the gun
legislation) really ticked off a lot of Coloradans,'' Mauser said
to resounding applause. ``Those feelings are going to provide us
with a lot of momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado House Speaker Russell George, R-Rifle, said the bill
would not work because it put the burden on the citizen to get
approval before being allowed to take a gun home. He also said the
state could not afford the program.
</P>
<P>
   George said the initiative does not address those issues, but if
it passes, it will be up to the Legislature to figure out how to
make it work.
</P>
<P>
   The president spent about an hour at the Colorado Convention
Center and the SAFE rally before heading about five miles south to
the University of Denver where he taped a live town hall meeting
with NBC's Tom Brokaw before about 350 invited students and
dignitaries for the MSNBC cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined at the rally by Denver Mayor Wellington Webb
and state and national lawmakers, including U.S. House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from both events was Gov. Bill Owens, who supports the
gun-show legislation but had said he believed Clinton's politicking
fell too close to the one-year anniversary of the Columbine High
School shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Owens had plans to attend a similar panel discussion at the
university later Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember an issue that has been as volatile, as
emotional and hits as close to home as this one does,'' Brokaw told
the audience at Sturm Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech at the convention center was interrupted by a
protester who held a sign that read, ``Guns Do Kill Children.'' He
was quickly escorted out of the ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Outside both venues, gun-rights advocates protested Clinton's
visit and the ballot initiative, saying it is just another move in
a long-line of government infringements on the Second Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the insane movement to pass more
ineffective gun legislation,'' said Darryl Watson of Aurora as he
wrote on a posterboard outside the convention center. ``We have a
vast movement in our country to avoid personal responsibility and
it's time for that to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley Brown, executive director of Rocky Mountain Gun Owners,
the largest gun-rights organization in Colorado, said the
president's timing and ``him using (the Columbine shootings) to
pass a form of gun control is vampiric.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown helped organize the protest outside the convention center
that included a diverse group of gun-rights advocates including war
veterans, senior citizens and children.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve-year-old Jon Widdifield missed a day of school in
Johnstown to be at the protest with his father and brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with what (Clinton) is trying to do with more
gun control,'' Widdifield said as he held a sign that read: ``A gun
with a lock is like a car with no gas: Useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the convention center, the invitation-only crowd cheered
wildly and gave thumbs up to Clinton as he arrived, just about on
schedule shortly after 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Weaver, 71, of Denver, said she wasn't a member of any
sort of firearms club or organization, but said she probably would
join the list of 3,000 members of SAFE after the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking them to take away any guns,'' Weaver said as
she awaited the president's arrival. ``We have no intention of
taking away guns, we just want people to be more careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Cole of Denver agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this infringes on their rights to own guns at
all,'' Cole said. ``It's merely an attempt to get a few more guns
out of the hands of people who shouldn't have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Denver came a day after Maryland became the
first state in the nation to require built-in locks on guns.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, the U.S. House approved a bill that would send
financial incentives to states that impose tough mandatory
sentences on criminals who carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Taylor can be reached via e-mail at ttaylor(at)gjds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
