<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FREAKNIK-NOSHOW13-COX     04-12 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-NOSHOW13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freaknik arriving, but how can you tell?
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the downtown sidewalk vendors aren't hawking
Freaknik T-shirts by now, then it's likely the annual weekend
dominated by traffic jams, loud music and black college spring
breakers will be nothing to waste film over, Atlanta police and
city vendors said.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed nothing heralded the arrival of the event Wednesday.
In years past, multi-colored T-shirts with Freaknik themes of all
persuasions swayed in the wind from vendors' carts along Peachtree,
Marietta and Alabama streets.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, you wouldn't even know Freaknik was coming unless
the media told you so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year will be worse than last year,'' said vendor I.B.
Ciss, who sells T-shirts, watches, sunglasses and other items from
a small cart downtown. ``Last year I bought 200 Freaknik T-shirts
and I sold two. That's not going to happen to me again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably be a Freaknik of some kind, but I don't
think we'll even notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown hoteliers echoed vendors' sentiments. Most said college
students had not made weekend reservations as in years past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is gonna be a flop,'' said Julie Napier, the
guest services manager at the Super 8 Hotel. ``Last year was bad
and this is nothing like last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Napier said the hotel, with 231 rooms, was at 20 percent
capacity: ``In the past we've had at least 100 rooms taken by
now.''
</P>
<P>
   While Courtyards by Marriott manager Michelle Vann said a lot of
her hotel's business included spring breakers walking in at the
last minute, she did not foresee that happening this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we would have seen them by now or by Thursday
morning,'' Vann said. ``But we haven't seen anyone and we haven't
gotten any reservations. ``
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for a possible onslaught of pedestrians, MARTA
will re-route downtown buses in order not to interrupt Freaknik
foot traffic along Peachtree and other side streets. Trains will
run on the regular schedule, said MARTA spokeswoman Dee Baker. The
MARTA plan also could change if Freaknik fizzles.
</P>
<P>
   At least one competing event _ Kappa Fest 2000 in Galveston,
Texas _ will be held during what has traditionally been the weekend
Freaknik reigned.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently driving the partygoers away has been Atlanta's
clampdown in recent years on the cruising, lewd behavior and public
drunkenness that is Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   But if the city is suddenly inundated by scantily-dressed
college students dancing atop shiny SUVs, Atlanta police and MARTA
officials are ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the T-shirt vendors are a good barometer,'' said
Atlanta Deputy Chief Wesley Derrick. ``But we have our plans in
place and we can always scale back if we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Those plans include 12-hour shifts for officers starting Friday
and strict enforcement of the illegal parking, blocking
intersections, noise and hanging out of cars ordinances. Towing
will be the practice of the day, Derrick said, with at least 50
wreckers on stand-by for police in case things get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   All uniform officers will be on duty and more than 100
detectives will be in uniform, as well, Derrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
