<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN BLAMES NASA MISMANAGEMENT FOR MARS FAILURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House's chief overseer of NASA on Wednesday
blamed mismanagement for two failed Mars missions but stopped short
of calling for changes in the space agency's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   An independent review of the missions, which both failed in
1999, concluded last month that they failed because of inadequate
testing, inexperienced staff, poor communication and insufficient
funds. But Rep. James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wis., said those
problems could have been avoided had management paid more attention
to tests, employee training and budget management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear: It is not our job, or our intent, to try to
run NASA from Capitol Hill,'' said Sensenbrenner, who chairs the
House Science Committee. ``But after reading these reports, I am
left to wonder: Who was managing them?''
</P>
<P>
   NASA Administrator Dan Goldin, who is to appear before the
committee next month, has accepted responsibility for the failure
of the Mars missions, which cost $372 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner delivered his comments as he and fellow committee
members questioned Thomas Young, who led the independent panel of
18 experts who investigated the missions of the Mars Climate
Orbiter and its companion craft, the Mars Polar Lander.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the lawmakers focused on Goldin's previously announced
pledge that his agency would work ``faster, better, cheaper'' to
accommodate Congress' desire to reduce federal spending. Although
they endorsed his goal of streamlining the space program, many
lawmakers said Goldin might have been too hasty in launching the
Mars missions.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner, a proponent of Goldin's stated approach, said the
administrator might have lost his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faster, better, cheaper was supposed to be a way of pushing
the technological and scientific envelope in order to make the
entire space program more responsive and more robust,'' he said.
``It must never become a cover for mediocre engineering, haphazard
testing and insufficient project management.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Texas, the committee's top Democrat, said
that faster, better, cheaper ``gives me a lot of concern'' in light
of Young's finding that workers on the Mars missions might have
bypassed necessary tests in an effort to keep expenses down.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eddie Bernice Johnson, D-Texas, also expressed misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us believe in faster, better, cheaper, but is it
risking other problems?'' she asked ``Are we cutting too much?''
</P>
<P>
   NASA chief Goldin has conceded the lawmakers might be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warning bells are sounding,'' Goldin told workers last
month at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. ``The
trend is very, very sobering and one we can't ignore. It says we
pushed too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigator Young, a retired aerospace company executive, told
the committee that NASA did ``cut too much'' in the areas of
oversight and testing before launching the Mars missions.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Climate Orbiter, which was to collect weather data, was
lost in September as it attempted to maneuver into orbit around the
planet. Young's panel, the Mars Program Independent Assessment
Team, attributed the failure to navigational errors caused by an
embarrassing mix-up between NASA and its contractor, Lockheed
Martin Astronautics, over whether they were using metric or English
measurements.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Mars Polar Lander lost communication with NASA
before descending toward Mars' surface. The assessment team
concluded that the lander most likely shattered on the frozen
terrain when a computer software flaw caused the probe's descent
rockets to shut down while it was still 130 feet above the surface.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
