<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-DESIGN-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      04-12 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT DESIGN, FROM LASSO TO GATED COMMUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of each review.)  (ART
ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EVE KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Book store shelves are groaning under the weight of ever more
design titles. Whether they're coffee-table fluff, scholarly
analyses or plain-spoken how-tos, they find buyers. Here are some
interesting new releases in the field, whether triumphs or
ambitious failures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marc Raeder, a German photographer, became fascinated and
repelled by America's outbreak of gated communities while he was
traveling in California during the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   His book consists almost entirely of his portraits of these
well-protected sites, all examples from outside either San
Francisco or Los Angeles. Many of the images are panoramas in which
fenced-off complexes back unsociably onto each other across
hillside after hillside.
</P>
<P>
   In Raeder's close-ups, the individual houses do seem a little
friendly, with their porches and balconies encouraging neighborly
interaction, but the lawn signs warn of armed-response alarm
systems, and what appear to be street lamps overhead are actually
surveillance cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of the photographs is somehow distorted, so that
everything looks like a toy railroad accessory _ clearly Raeder is
criticizing these developments as small-minded and cheesy.
</P>
<P>
   Condemning sprawl is not a new idea, and this slim visual attack
won't convert anyone who doesn't mind a manned guardhouse down the
block.
</P>
<P>
   The book is an ideal gift for disaffected souls like teen-agers
who are (temporarily) stuck behind those walls.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SCANSCAPE'
</P>
<P>
   By Marc Raeder
</P>
<P>
   Actar/Distributed Art Publishers, 96 pp., 52 illustrations,
$29.95
</P>
<P>
   A visual encyclopedia on Frank Lloyd Wright sounds like an
enticing prospect, especially given his ever-shifting styles and
technological adventurousness over a seven-decade career _ not to
mention his complicated love life. One would have imagined this
book's spreads filled with anything from detailed drawings of
Prairie-style cantilevers to portraits of his many former wives.
</P>
<P>
   What Iain Thomson has assembled instead is a sometimes
amateurish collection of biographical notes and project
descriptions. He does mention hundreds of built or proposed
designs, as well as virtually every person important or tangential
to Wright's life, down to ex-brothers-in-law. But the text can be
skimpy _ a structure can receive as little analysis as ``an I-plan
house of rectangular interlocking spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   The photos, however, nearly make the book worth its relatively
low cover price. The interior shots don't seem to have been styled;
they show how owners of Wright houses really live with their
unyielding houses, furnishing them with lace-trimmed coverlets and
French provincial armchairs that would have irritated the purist
master. Equally informative are the exterior shots, mostly aerial
views, which give rare glimpses of what these forms must have
looked like when they were still little models on some awed
apprentice's desk.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FRANK LLOYD WRIGHT: A VISUAL ENCYCLOPEDIA'
</P>
<P>
   By Iain Thomson
</P>
<P>
   Thunder Bay Press, 416 pp., 1,000 illustrations, $24.98 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy following Dimitris Philippides into his deep
scholarly analysis of a few aspects of Greek decorative arts. He
focuses on how residential wall and ceiling ornaments evolved from
the 1700s to just before World War II, with an emphasis on how
Greece rediscovered and reinterpreted its design legacies after
winning liberation from the Ottomans in 1827.
</P>
<P>
   The text leaps from primitive to folk to high styles: from stone
hut facades carved with reliefs of fertility goddesses, to sea
captains' parlors lined with riotously colorful painted panels, to
the Athens, Greece, town house of the archaeologist Heinrich
Schliemann, where the murals appropriately show cupids excavating
ancient statuary.
</P>
<P>
   The assortment is appealingly quirky, and the illustrations of
little-known aesthetic traditions are handsome. Philippides'
speculations on why certain popular motifs evolved are among the
book's liveliest passages; were murals of knives slashing into
watermelons meant to suggest sexuality, which had been a taboo
subject under the repressive Ottomans, or did they just indicate
``a particular dietary weakness on the part of the owner''?
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the text will put off newcomers to the field,
however. It includes words like apotropaic and transhumant. Oddly,
Abrams is marketing the book as a coffee table survey of Greek
design that will ``provide ideas for incorporating that style into
today's homes.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GREEK DESIGN AND DECORATION'
</P>
<P>
   Three Centuries of Architectural Style
</P>
<P>
   By Dimitris Philippides
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, 285 pp., 468 illustrations, $65 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a lovingly written tribute to working ranches and their
simulacra from the 1840s to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hess tells of 31 sites with equal enthusiasm, be they stone
bunkhouses for actual cowboys or Will Rogers' mansion equipped with
Indian blankets and riding tack but located just off Sunset
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The prose is evocative and accessible, rich with anecdotes about
original owners who hung their wagon-wheel chandeliers with old
spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the cavelike ranch house, with glass enclosing the gap
between two boulders, he writes, ``The encircling balcony is where,
in the movies, a fistfight would send one combatant head over heels
onto a poker table while the ladies of the bordello upstairs draped
themselves over the railing to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   A quibble: why are there no interior shots for eight of the
featured projects, including some of the most intriguing cases,
built by celebrities like William Randolph Hearst, Jack London and
Joel McCrea? Were the spaces inaccessible, or just not photogenic?
</P>
<P>
   Another quibble: The photographer didn't always focus on
features that appealed to Hess. We are told but never shown, for
example, that in a 1930s dude ranch, ``tin cutouts of broncos and
saguaros ornament the knotty-pine wet bar at the pool house.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from these lapses, the book is a purely pleasurable ride
into them thar hills.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RANCHO DELUXE'
</P>
<P>
   Rustic Dreams and Real Western Living
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Hess, photographs by Alan Weintraub
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Books, 208 pp., 240 illustrations, $40 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William L. Price died suddenly of a stroke in 1916, just as his
Philadelphia-based architectural practice was hitting its stride.
He was 54, and his innovative work ended up largely forgotten. At
first, the firm specialized in residences, mostly in a Tudor or
Gothic vein. In his 40s and 50s, Price began winning prominent
commercial commissions like railroad stations and resort hotels. On
those jobs he tried out the era's new structural materials, like
reinforced concrete, and he developed a design repertory of
setbacks, buttresses and domed turrets that clearly prefigured Art
Deco.
</P>
<P>
   Price was also something of an affordable-housing dreamer; he
founded a short-lived utopian colony outside Philadelphia, where
residents as young as 5 could vote on decisions and a furniture
workshop helped pay the bills. By the 30s, dogmatic Modernists had
written Price out of the history books, and by the 70s his late
masterpieces like the Traymore and Blenheim hotels in Atlantic City
had been demolished.
</P>
<P>
   George E. Thomas is bringing Price's achievements back to light
with a rather plodding prose style and a trove of photographs from
the firm's archives (which the author purchased at auction in the
late 1960s). Repetitions mar the text somewhat: Thomas keeps
jousting with the long-dead dogmatic Modernists and defending
seemingly sleepy Philadelphia as the birthplace of ``the first
consumer culture.''
</P>
<P>
   More annoying, the essays that make up the book's first half
don't give page numbers for the plates that take up the second
half, so you have to keep flipping from index to plate to text.
Another sign that the volume was perhaps finished in a hurry is
that Thomas doesn't always mention whether a project still exists,
and if so in what condition. Price has almost, but not quite, been
as well served as he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WILLIAM L. PRICE'
</P>
<P>
   Arts and Crafts to Modern Design
</P>
<P>
   By George E. Thomas
</P>
<P>
   Princeton Architectural Press, 362 pp., 299 illustrations, $60
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
