u a BC-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      04-12 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES GUN CONTROL ADVOCATES TO TAKE ISSUE TO VOTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A week before the first anniversary of the Columbine
massacre, President Clinton urged gun control advocates Wednesday
to override lawmakers' qualms about imposing limits on firearms and
take the issue directly to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't quit until you win,'' Clinton told about 3,000
supporters of a drive to get a measure on Colorado's November
ballot that would require buyers at gun shows to undergo the same
background checks that face firearms purchasers at licensed
dealers. ``In spite of all the attempts to put roadblocks in your
way, you must not be deterred.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the initiative movement was justified ``because the
Legislature wouldn't do it for you.'' Additionally, the president
said, success of the initiative movement in Colorado would be a
goad to Congress, where gun-control measures are stymied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other states will follow your lead,'' Clinton said. ``I hope
and pray Congress will follow your lead as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton belittled the contention of gun advocates, about a
hundred of whom demonstrated outside the Colorado Convention
Center, that requiring background checks at gun shows would be too
burdensome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about you, but I think it's worth a little
inconvenience to save a few thousand lives a year,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun shows, long a target of control advocates, are an emotional
issue in Colorado because some of the weapons used by the two
teen-age shooters at Columbine High School were given to them by an
acquaintance who bought the weapons at guns shows.
</P>
<P>
   The young gunmen shot dead 12 fellow students and a teacher at
the suburban Denver school last April 20 before killing themselves
in what was the deadliest school shooting in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was introduced by Tom Mauser, a leader of the initiative
fight and the father of one of the students killed at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movement is not about our tragedy,'' Mauser said. ``We
lose 12 kids a day to gunshots in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said 70 percent of background checks at gun shows could
be completed in minutes and 95 percent within a day. The remaining
5 percent ``should still be done,'' Clinton said, because the
difficult clearances were 20 times more likely to be rejected
because of a criminal record or other reason to deny the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited a federal study in which one-third of a sample of
weapons sold at gun shows were later used in serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also appeared on a live MSNBC special broadcast on gun
violence from the University of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   During the program, state House Majority Leader Doug Dean
pointed out that the young woman who bought the guns later given to
Columbine shooters Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold would have passed
the background check that would be required by the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton countered that the young woman said she would not have
bought the guns if she knew she would have been subject to a
background check, but Dean said he did not ``buy her claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Thomas, the district attorney in the Columbine incident,
voiced support for closing the gun-show loophole.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, Clinton spoke to supporters of SAFE (for Sane
Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic) Colorado. When legal hurdles
are cleared, the group needs 62,000 signatures to get the gun-show
initiative on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ought to be able to get 62,000 signatures in two hours if
everybody who is for this will sign up and go get the signatures,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Initial polls show strong voter support for such a measure,
despite Republican legislators' opposition and Colorado's
reputation as a pro-gun state.
</P>
<P>
   The measure rejected by the Republican-controlled Legislature
had the backing of Republican Gov. Bill Owens. He supports the
initiative but did not attend the rally and said of Clinton's
visit: ``I do hope that he doesn't politicize a Colorado issue and
get involved in something that ought to be up to Coloradans to vote
and agree on.
</P>
<P>
   Other local Republicans criticized Clinton's trip because of its
timing near the Columbine anniversary and the president's
willingness to inject himself into what they view as a state issue.
</P>
<P>
   When the president's visit was announced, state Senate Majority
Leader Tom Blickensderfer, who represents the Columbine area, said
that because Clinton ``is not real popular in the state'' he could
hurt the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won Colorado in 1992 but lost the state in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Tom Tancredo, a Republican who represents the area
near the high school, said the timing of Clinton's visit was
``insensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal juvenile justice bill, with a provision to require gun
show background checks in 72 hours, passed the Senate last May,
just after the Columbine shootings. A similar House-passed bill
would give only 24 hours for the checks to be run. It is just one
of several differing points that have frustrated attempts to
convene a House-Senate conference committee to work out a single
version of the competing bills.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton flew to Colorado, the White House distributed copies
of a letter that House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and
the panel's senior Democrat, Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, sent to
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, asking for
a conference committee to be convened as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The House members conceded ``there is not complete agreement''
on the outstanding issues, but ``we also recognize the need for
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Wednesday he almost certainly would sign a bill
supported by both Conyers and Hyde but wanted to make certain there
was a provision to keep guns from the small percentage of potential
buyers who do not pass background checks within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that we can't work this out,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
