u a BC-OBITUARY-VORENBERG-BO     04-12 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-VORENBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES S. VORENBERG, 73; LAW SPECIALIST, WATERGATE PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS AND JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James S. Vorenberg, the former Harvard Law School dean, longtime
law professor, and associate Watergate prosecutor who helped
organize the legal team that took on the Nixon Administration, died
Wednesday, 48 hours after suffering a massive heart attack. He was
73, and lived in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   An over-achiever even in circles filled with such people, Prof.
Vorenberg was a tall, lean criminal law expert whose occasionally
unconventional views drew praise even if they raised eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   But whether advocating legalized prostitution, as he did in a
1976 article, or creating a new holistic vision of the justice
system, as he did while director of President Lyndon Johnson's
Commission on Law Enforcement and the Administration of Justice,
Prof. Vorenberg's weaving of the theoretical and practical usually
astonished his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was good at everything he did,'' Archibald Cox, the former
Watergate special prosecutor, said of Vorenberg Wednesday. ``He was
a combination of a thinker with a strong grasp of reality and an
ability to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his work under Cox, in the summer of 1973, for which
Prof. Vorenberg is perhaps best remembered, and the work he
remembered most fondly, said his wife, Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Under Cox, who had known Prof. Vorenburg since he served as
president of the Harvard Law Review, Prof. Vorenburg was
responsible for pulling together lawyers from across the country to
conduct the Watergate case. He also did nearly all of the work to
create the vast organization such a legal effort entailed, Cox
said.
</P>
<P>
   While that was not the most glamorous task, Cox said, it was
some of the most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the nuts and bolts, but it takes imagination,
responsibility, and judgment to put an organization like that
together,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his affiliation with the Watergate case, from 1965 to
1967, Prof. Vorenburg headed the Commission on Law Enforcement,
which concluded with a 10-volume, 2 million-word report in 1967
that even today serves as a model of research.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Katzenbach, the former U.S. Attorney General for whom
Prof. Vorenberg worked as a special assistant, said Wednesday that
the report Prof. Vorenburg produced stands out as a notable
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a truly extraordinary piece of work,''
Katzenbach said. ``If you read that report today, it would hold up,
and that's remarkable, 35, 36 years after the fact. There's very
little he or I would have changed today.''
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Vorenberg was born in Boston on January 10, 1928, the son
of Frank Vorenberg, a Boston merchant, and Ida (Muhlfelder)
Vorenberg. He was a graduate of Phillips Exeter Academy and Harvard
College, magna cum laude, in 1948, and of Harvard Law School, magna
cum laude, in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   After law school, he spent two years in the Air Force legal
department. He was one of a team of attorneys that successfully
negotiated for Air Force bases in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   From 1953-1954, Prof. Vorenburg was a law clerk to Supreme Court
Justice Felix Frankfurter before joining the Boston law firm of
Ropes &AMP; Gray. He became a partner in 1960. While practicing law, he
became a part-time instructor at Boston University Law School. In
1962 he took a full-time professorship at Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist in criminal and corporate law, Prof. Vorenberg was
appointed by Attorney General Robert Kennedy in 1964 as the first
director of the Office of Criminal Justice in the Department of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Such work was good training for the future. In 1981, while
serving as chairman of the Massachusetts Ethics Commission, he
became dean of Harvard Law School during a time of great tumult.
</P>
<P>
   Under his stewardship of the school, Prof. Vorenberg sat at the
middle of a furious crossfire between adherents and opponents of
the controversial Critical Legal Studies movement, which held that
the traditional approach to law preserved the status quo at the
expense of social justice. These ideological differences erupted
into bitter political battles over tenure votes in 1985, 1986 and
1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved it all,'' his wife said of his deanship. ``He is a
great politician and he really liked threading his way through the
factions. He loved being dean.''
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Vorenburg resigned as dean in 1989 to resume teaching,
which he continued until his death. He did so despite suffering
from Parkinson's Disease, diagnosed in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Vorenberg is survived by his wife, Elizabeth Vorenberg, of
Cambridge; three daughters, Jill Alberts of New York, Amy Vorenberg
of Concord, N.H., and Eliza Vorenberg of Los Angeles; two
stepchildren, Amy Troubh of Newton, Mass. and John Troubh of New
York; and ten grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Edgar Driscoll, formerly of the Globe staff, contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
