<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-PLUNGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ LEADS FREEFALL IN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite Index Wednesday continued its dramatic
plunge from a record high a month ago, falling 286.27 points as
nervous investors were again reminded how treacherous technology
stocks have become.
</P>
<P>
   The tech-laden Nasdaq, which closed Wednesday at 3769.63, down 7
percent, has shed a quarter of its value since March 10 when it
stood at 5,048. Wednesday's tumble was Nasdaq's second-biggest
point decline. It was set off by a report that Microsoft Corp.'s
revenues may soften due to declining sales of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   While Nasdaq has been taken a beating amid concerns that tech
stocks are overvalued, the laggard Dow has begun to gain ground in
recent weeks. But the Dow was unable to resist technology's
downward pull Wednesday, dropping 161.95 points, or 1.43 percent,
to close at 11,125.13.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dow is still down 3 percent this year, its losses
amount to less than half of those suffered by Nasdaq, which has now
given back more than 7 percent of its value this year.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nasdaq has become an extremely risky bet for mutual
funds and individual investors who have stuck with tech stocks as
they have deflated this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning that every time Nasdaq goes down, it doesn't
just as quickly go back up in this round,'' said Heydon Traub, an
investment strategist for State Street Global Advisers. Just as
worrisome, Nasdaq's swings have steadily widened as the index is
experiencing ``probably the most volatility we've ever seen'' in a
US stock market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traub said the average daily swings in Nasdaq _ up or down _ are
2.3 percent, three times the volatility seen in the early and
mid-1990s. The Dow's volatility has risen in tandem, to about 1.17
percent a day.
</P>
<P>
   And investors are feeling every move.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Syron, former president of the American Stock Exchange,
said tech-stock investors are beginning to see the inevitable
fallout of an industry that must suffer numerous losers in the
process of ascertaining which companies have the winning
technologies that will prevail in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the dot-coms. Some will do terrifically, and most of
them will go out of business,'' said Syron, chief executive of
Thermo Electron Corp. ``On average, investors will do fine but
they're going to lose their shirts on some'' companies.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers predicted more down days in the future for
technology stocks, many of which are still trading at levels not
justified by their current revenues or profits.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is virtually impossible to predict the future
direction of the stock market, Robert Mellman, senior economist for
J.P. Morgan in New York, said the growing uncertainty in financial
markets is certainly not good for an economy that is being
propelled by high demand from consumers who spending some of their
stock gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates uncertainty,'' Mellman said. ``People thought we
had a solid economy.'' But ``with the Nasdaq off very sharply over
the past couple weeks _ and I'd guess it'll go lower _ people
aren't so sure about the outlook for the second half of the year,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq's fourth consecutive decline Wednesday pushed the index
far below the watershed 4,000 mark achieved with such jubilation
last Christmas on the way toward unprecedented gains for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Efron, co-manager of USAA Aggressive Growth, a $1.9 billion
mutual fund that is nearly half invested in tech companies,
speculated that institutional investors wary of sky-high stock
prices started the selloff and that individual investors have
followed. Others said selling has continued as fund managers have
had to raise cash to meet redemptions and individuals have had to
close out positions due to margin calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks were momentum stocks on the way up, and they're
also momentum stocks on the way down. It's brutal,'' Efron said.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio-based USAA has been careful to warn investors that,
though tech stocks may pay off in the long-term, they are not for
the feint of heart. ``You're going to see gut-wrenching moves both
up and down, and you better be prepared for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, those unprepared investors are apparently bailing out of
big-name tech companies as well as vulnerable start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   What was unusual in Wednesday's drop was that the nation's
biggest technology companies all declined. Microsoft led the tech
giants' slide, losing $4.50 a share to $79.375. An analyst for
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., citing a slowdown in sales of PCs to
businesses, sheared $100 million from his estimate of revenues
expected in the fourth quarter for the world's biggest software
maker.
</P>
<P>
   Once Microsoft's fall began, none were spared: Cisco Systems
Inc. was down $5 a share; Intel Corp., down $8.875; Sun
Microsystems, down $7.875; Hewlett-Packard Co., down $10.8125; IBM
Corp., down $6.375; and, Dell Computer Corp., down $4.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last week, investors looking for safe harbors for their
money bypassed US Treasury bonds, which tumbled Wednesday for a
second straight day and instead snapped up higher-yielding bonds of
corporations or quasi-government agencies such as Fannie Mae. The
yield on 30-year US Treasury bonds rose from 5.75 percent to 5.82
percent, while their prices declined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
