<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEETING WITH BUSH EXPOSES RIFT AMONG GAY REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also BUSH-HEALTH) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Thursday morning Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
will meet with a handful of representatives from what may be the
tiniest sliver of his party's electorate: gay Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   While the votes of gays will not likely tilt the election, the
gathering, at Bush's campaign headquarters in Austin, is shaping up
as one of the more remarkable events of the campaign. That is in
part because many gay leaders have repudiated Bush's political
agenda and, from the other direction, many of the governor's
conservative allies have accused gays of promoting a lifestyle that
the conservatives condemn as an assault on family values.
</P>
<P>
   But what at first glance seems like an unlikely decision by Bush
to meet with about a dozen gay supporters _ this is the first time
a Republican nominee has convened such a session _ the event
underscores new realities about Republican politics and about the
maturation of gays as a force in that party.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they conceded that they expected to draw little support
from gays in November, strategists for Bush said that they
considered building relations with gays an important way to appeal
to moderate voters, much as Bush did with his recent criticism of
the National Rifle Association. A national survey of
self-identified gay voters in the 1998 election _ who made up 4
percent of the electorate _ found that 56 percent were Democrats,
20 percent Republicans and 24 percent independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this election is going to be decided by the gay
vote _ it's not going to be that close,'' said Fred Steeper, a
pollster for Bush. ``But by meeting with groups like gay
Republicans you appeal to those voters who highly value diversity
and toleration. The trade-off is there are others who would say you
are promoting the wrong type of lifestyle. It will help with some
voters and hurt with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Bush camp is ambivalent about how aggressively to
court gay support. Fearful, perhaps, of incurring the wrath of
conservatives, Bush campaign officials this week contacted
prominent conservatives to assure them that Bush was not about to
cave in to the agenda of his visitors on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they felt they needed to do it,'' Michael Ferris, a
leading conservative home school advocate, said of his call from a
Bush campaign official. ``I've been assured that there would be no
change in policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he expressed some concern about the meeting, saying:
``Someone demanding a right at the table because of their
homosexuality _ that's what bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   While some gay Republicans applaud Bush's entreaties, the
closed-door gathering has intensified a roiling fight in their
ranks over political strategy in general and, specifically, over
how much they should cozy up to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Log Cabin Republicans, a national organization of
gay Republicans that says it has 11,000 members, have taken a
combative approach: For months, the group criticized Bush's stands
on issues of consequence to homosexuals. During the primaries, the
group helped Bush's opponent, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who had
met with the Log Cabin group but whose positions on issues
important to the organization were similar to Bush's _ and
unacceptable to many of the group's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But other prominent gay Republicans, including members of some
local Log Cabin branches, have pressed for a more pragmatic, and
conciliatory, strategy of working on the inside by backing Bush and
trying in a nonthreatening manner to persuade him to embrace their
positions. They accused the Log Cabin group of thriving on
publicity at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   By criticizing Bush, the Log Cabin leaders have found their
influence in the Bush campaign diminished. The meeting on Thursday
includes gay Republicans who are committed to supporting the
governor; national Log Cabin leaders were not invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are Republicans first; others are gay first,''
said former Rep. Steve Gunderson, R-Wis., who is gay. ``Some people
believe that a seat at the table is always progress no matter where
a candidate stands. Others believe that for the interest of
integrity you have to have some kind of gesture from a candidate
before you can be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson said he would attend the meeting because it was a good
first step, but ``no candidate ought to expect support from gays
and lesbians just from recognizing our existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of the national Log Cabin group, Rich
Tafel, who has criticized Bush and who was excluded from Thursday's
meeting, warned that the participants should not be ``boosters of
the candidate irregardless of specific policy issues.'' He
questioned whether the participants would press the governor on
matters such as his position on discrimination in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tempting when the governor says, `Come to the mansion,
you're a supporter.' That's exciting,'' Tafel said. ``Some of these
people are thrilled at the idea of being power brokers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tafel said that he was concerned about Bush's mixed signals on
whether he would appoint openly gay people to his administration.
And he said that he had expected Bush to repudiate efforts by his
supporters to attack homosexuals when his campaign was seeking
support from conservatives during the South Carolina primary.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding at times supportive and at other times dismissive about
the session in Austin, Tafel said: ``They'll try to lay the ground
work to get a real meeting set up'' that would include Log Cabin
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Schmid, a former president of the Log Cabin club in
Washington who will attend the meeting, said it was a mistake for
Tafel and others to publicly criticize Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot attack one day and expect to be invited the next
day to meet with the candidate,'' Schmid said. ``The way you act
determines how you make progress. Do you want to do it through the
headlines or do it through hard work and positive, constructive
dialogue and patience?''
</P>
<P>
   Scott E. Huch, a vice president of the Log Cabin Club of
Northern Virginia, who will take part in the meeting, also preached
patience among those who are critical of Bush. ``We expect Bush to
be an expert on public policy issues that affect gay and lesbian
people,'' he said. ``But Bush is probably right about where you'd
expect somebody to be if there were an ordinary person who never
had to deal with this issue on a personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Campaign, a gay political organization that has
endorsed Vice President Al Gore, said the meeting was critical.
``It's disingenuous to marginalize the meeting,'' said David Smith,
the group's spokesman. ``There is room for Bush to move to the
center. And if this group can make it happen, more power to them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the disputes among gay Republicans might reflect their
growing influence, several of them said the strains were troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gay political movement has matured in this country,''
Gunderson said. ``But we're not very good at practicing the same
tolerance and respect that we preach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
