<SLUG> BC-LESSIG-STANFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD LAW'S LESSIG TO TAKE POST AT STANFORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawrence Lessig, the hot cyber-law specialist at Harvard Law
School, has told colleagues he plans to leave for Stanford
University this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The departure comes just as Lessig has become perhaps the
nation's most prominent commentator on law and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor cited one of his
articles in a decision overturning an online antipornography law in
1997. More recently, Lessig was drawn into an even more prominent
case: the Microsoft Corp. antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, US District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson asked
Lessig to provide advice on how antitrust law applies to some of
the government's central charges against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The move was highly unusual and a sign of Lessig's prominence in
the field, analysts said. ``Courts will sometimes bring in experts
on isolated technical issues _ for example, how a chemical
composition works in a patent case,'' said Thane Scott, an
antitrust specialist at Palmer &AMP; Dodge in Boston. ``But judges
usually think of themselves as capable of resolving complex
questions of the law and social policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessig's recent book ``Code and other Laws of Cyberspace'' was
widely reviewed and well received. It warns that free speech,
privacy and other civil liberties on the Internet might be eroded
by the demands of electronic commerce. The Harvard professor also
writes a monthly column for The Industry Standard, a magazine that
covers electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Currently on sabbatical in Berlin, Lessig notified colleagues by
e-mail this week that he will head to Stanford, said Michael
Chmura, news director for Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig, 38, has been at Harvard since 1998. He is the Berkman
professor of law and member of the law school's Berkman Center for
Internet &AMP; Society, a research center that studies the development
and regulation of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   His departure leaves the center with several other prominent
members, including faculty members Jonathan Zittrain, Charles
Nesson, Arthur Miller and Charles Ogletree. ``I think we'll be able
to take care of the gap'' left by Lessig, said Chmura. ``I'm
optimistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
