<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNILEVER-BEN&AMP;JERRYS-1     04-12 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNILEVER-BEN&AMP;JERRYS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN &AMP; JERRY'S AGREES TO BE ACQUIRED BY UNILEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to rewrite and expand, refines lede; story grows by about 450
words; art note added)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did Ben &AMP; Jerry's sell out, or is the Ben &AMP; Jerry's culture
invading the corporate world? A scoop of each, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Ending a four-month process that had some twists and turns, Ben
&AMP; Jerry's Homemade, the quirky ice cream company that made social
consciousness central to its strategy, said Wednesday that it had
agreed to be acquired by Unilever, the global giant that owns the
Breyer's and Good Humor brands, for about $326 million in cash, or
$43.60 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The deal seems to pave the way for Ben &AMP; Jerry's to continue its
maverick ways. The company will be a wholly owned subsidiary of
Unilever, with a separate board that will include Ben Cohen and
Jerry Greenfield, the founders of Ben &AMP; Jerry's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholders will be rewarded,'' said Ben &AMP; Jerry's in a
statement. ``Ben &AMP; Jerry's employees will be protected; the current
social mission of Ben &AMP; Jerry's will be encouraged and well-funded,
which will lead to improved performance in this area, and an
opportunity has been offered for Ben &AMP; Jerry's to contribute to
Unilever's social practices worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the deal, which the board approved at 2 a.m., both
companies said that Ben &AMP; Jerry's would continue as it always had
and that Unilever, which is based in the Netherlands, would commit
7.5 percent of Ben &AMP; Jerry's profits to a foundation and agree not
to reduce jobs or alter the way the ice cream is made. Unilever
will also contribute $5 million to the foundation, create a $5
million fund to help minority-owned businesses and others in poor
neighborhoods and distribute $5 million to employees in six months,
said Perry D. Odak, chief executive of Ben &AMP; Jerry's.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cohen will work on evaluating Unilever's
involvement in activities like protecting the environment. A bit of
Ben &AMP; Jerry's attitude, in short, is being transferred to a $45
billion company, affirming the principles that Cohen and Greenfield
have advocated since they started their company in a Vermont gas
station in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I would have preferred for Ben &AMP; Jerry's to remain
independent, I'm excited about this next chapter,'' said Cohen in a
statement, which included lyrics from the Grateful Dead song
``Scarlet Begonias'': ``Once in a while you get shown the light in
the strangest of places if you look at it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen will also work on developing products that will bear the
Ben &AMP; Jerry's name. Such branching out was proposed by several
possible buyers of Ben &AMP; Jerry's, which is known for high-fat ice
cream in flavors like Chubby Hubby and Cherry Garcia. On Dec. 2,
the company said it had received ``indications of interest'' and
would be weighing them.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Greenfield, both 49 and friends since seventh grade,
spent the early years railing at ice-cream giants like Pillsbury,
which has since been acquired by Diageo and manufactures
Haagen-Dazs. Both Haagen-Dazs and Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream
distribute Ben &AMP; Jerry's, although the three are rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's went public in 1984 and, from a fiscal point of
view, had been a disappointment to investors. Until December, the
stock had hovered around $17. Wednesday, it gained $8.125 a share
to close at $43.0625.
</P>
<P>
   The deal replaces one in which Cohen, together with Unilever and
a venture-capital group called Meadowbrook Lane Capital, would have
taken Ben &AMP; Jerry's private for $38 a share. The board agreed to
that plan on March 23, but the deal was derailed by an all-stock
offer, also at $38 a share, from Dreyer's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, we won big-time,'' said Terry Mollner, a
Meadowbrook principal and a founder of the Calvert group of
socially responsible mutual funds. ``Unilever has agreed to
something called the social mission process.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this process, Antony Burgmans, a co-chairman of
Unilever, said his company discovered early in its negotiations
that it and Ben &AMP; Jerry's had a similar vision. ``Unilever prides
itself on the way it does business worldwide,'' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Burgmans, who also announced Wednesday that Unilever would buy
Slim-Fast Foods Co., the diet-plan maker, in a deal worth $2.3
billion, said the company had paid ``full price'' for both
Slim-Fast and Ben &AMP; Jerry's. ``These two brands fit into trends,''
he said. ``One is about vitality, and the other is about enjoyment
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Burgmans said he did not
expect a return on the investment in Ben &AMP; Jerry's for three years,
said Jeffrey G. Kanter, an analyst at Prudential Securities. ``For
two years, there will be no layoffs,'' Kanter said.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of Ben &AMP; Jerry's shops around the country, who had
watched the process anxiously, said they hoped their businesses
would remain intact. ``I wish the company could have stayed
independent,'' said Rosanne Haggerty, executive director of Common
Ground Community, which operates a Ben &AMP; Jerry's in Manhattan and
plans to open three more. ``But I'm cheered that they have created
a mechanism to not just preserve the values that have made Ben &AMP;
Jerry's special, but to expand them. In a strange way, this could
be a validation of all those quirky values.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan to take Ben &AMP; Jerry's private came apart when Dreyer's
offered $38 a share in a stock swap. ``The board felt they had no
choice but to let all three groups put their best offers on the
table yesterday,'' Mollner said, adding, ``We think it's horrible
that a company has no choice but to sell to the highest bidder or
get sued.''
</P>
<P>
   Odak described Niall Fitzgerald, the other Unilever co-chairman,
as arriving for a meeting with a knapsack on his back, an
appearance that seemed to play well with Ben &AMP; Jerry's management.
``He talked for three hours about all the sustainable-agriculture
programs they have,'' Odak said. ``We were very, very impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the negotiations, Richard Goldstein, head of Unilever's
North American operations, made a move to convince Cohen of the
role he could play at Unilever. ``He said, `Ben, do you realize the
opportunity you have here to help this company grow in its social
commitment?''' Mollner recalled. ``Ben looked back at him and
realized, This man is sincere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
