<HEADLINE>
COURT GIVES RUIZ CHANCE AT HEAVYWEIGHT TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than the date of his meeting with Evander Holyfield changed
for John Ruiz Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling that surely stunned undisputed heavyweight champion
Lennox Lewis's handlers, Judge Lewis Kaplan ordered the champion to
either vacate the World Boxing Association portion of the title or
fight Ruiz prior to his previously scheduled April 29 bout with
Michael Grant at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   When Holyfield and Lewis met in their rematch earlier this year,
both sides agreed that the winner's next opponent would be the
WBA's No. 1 contender or its highest-rated available fighter. Lewis
had no interest in a second fight with then-No. 1 challenger Henry
Akinwande, however, and when the WBA subsequently removed Akinwande
from the No. 1 spot for inactivity and inserted Ruiz, Lewis
continued to ignore the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Lewis signed to face Grant in a fight that is being
widely anticipated because Grant is considered by most to be the
best of the crop of young heavyweights. Lewis's people tried to
convince Ruiz to step aside until July before meeting Lewis in
London but promoter Don King chose to press his claim on an
immediate shot at the WBA belt and put together a better than $1
million payday for Ruiz to meet Holyfield in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   At the time it was unclear if the Ruiz-Holyfield fight would be
for a world title or merely be considered an elimination bout to
name a new No. 1 WBA contender. That is until the organization
itself announced it would not strip Lewis if he agreed to fight the
Holyfield-Ruiz winner immediately following the Grant bout.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis agreed but also sued King claiming he had been defrauded
into signing a contract that forced him to fight the WBA's No. 1
contender first. King countersued claiming breach of contract.
Wednesday Kaplan ruled Lewis was free to fight who he wanted but if
it was not Ruiz first, Lewis had to vacate that portion of the
title. That effectively turned the Ruiz-Holyfield fight into a WBA
title bout because they are the No. 1- and No. 2-rated heavyweights
in that organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz's handlers declined to step aside as asked because they did
not believe the promised July fight would ever come off and King
continued to press the issue in court until he got himself a
victory that could make Ruiz, who is from Chelsea, Mass., the first
New England heavyweight to fight for a world title since Tom
McNeeley was stopped by Floyd Patterson more than three decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the biggest blunder in boxing history,'' crowed
Norman Stone, Ruiz's manager. ``Lewis is the one who took Johnny to
court originally and now the court ruled in our favor. This is
unbelievable. It's something you wait your whole life for _ the
opportunity to fight for the heavyweight title.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz was vacationing with his family in Florida when his cell
phone rang and he heard Stone screaming on the other end. At first
it was difficult to be sure what the news was but when it became
clear, Ruiz took it in his usual understated fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road so I'm glad it all came out well,'' said
Ruiz, who would become the first Hispanic heavyweight champion in
boxing history if he can defeat the 37-year-old Holyfield. ``The
thing is I definitely want to fight Holyfield. If it's for a title,
all the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the judge went with us but I'm still looking at it
just as a fight with Holyfield. That alone would be a tough fight
and a big thing. If it's a title fight, all the better. That's been
my dream ever since this started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
