<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BIGDIG-CHANGES-BOS &LR;      04-12 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-CHANGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOSS DIGS RIGHT INTO CONTROVERSIAL HIGHWAY JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New Big Dig chief Andrew Natsios plans to review the
performance of the project's lead contractor in coming weeks, as he
moves to restore confidence in Massachusetts' management of the
highway construction.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a sharp contrast with James J. Kerasiotes, his ousted
predecessor, Natsios also pledged Wednesday to flood the media and
public with information about the giant highway project, which is
expected to cost close to $14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be bored by the amount of information'' Natsios said
after a meeting with business leaders. ``They're going to have more
information than they're going to want to print.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said he will await a report by consultants
O'Brien/Kreitzberg before deciding whether to end or alter the
state's long relationship with Bechtel/Parsons Brinckerhoff, the
$150-million-a-year management consultants on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is premature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bechtel came under attack from Federal Highway Administrator
Kenneth R. Wykle Tuesday, who suggested that the firm deserves
greater scrutiny for failing to reveal a $1.4 billion cost hike in
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios may face pressure to impose new oversight on Bechtel.
Some have called for a project management organization to be hired
by the state to oversee the contractor. According to a former Big
Dig employee, O'Brien/Kreitzberg has been seeking the work for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios also announced he has assembled a team of state
specialists in personnel, accounting and construction would help
him quickly take over its management.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios was appointed Massachusetts Turnpike Chairman Tuesday by
Governor Paul Cellucci, who fired Kerasiotes for intentionally
concealing cost overruns. The Big Dig has been managed by the
Turnpike since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Several Kerasiotes aides will follow him out the door. Two of
Kerasiotes' closest aides, Jodi d'Urso and James McGrail, will
leave this week, a source said. Project director Patrick J.
Moynihan, a Kerasiotes loyalist, is expected to leave within
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios had been serving as Administration and Finance
secretary, but increasingly tackling Big Dig fiscal problems
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios first learned he might be put in charge of the nation's
largest public works project Friday, when he attended a regularly
scheduled meeting with Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, already distancing himself from Kerasiotes in
public, laid out how he might deal with the situation if Federal
Highway Administration called for Big Dig management heads to roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little taken aback by some of the options he
presented,'' Natsios said. One was, essentially: ``Grab your hard
hat, Andy, you're in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said he eventually hopes to meet with Kerasiotes, but,
``Tensions are kind of high right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios Wednesday delivered a speech on the state's economic
condition, which he had written before Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But before and after his speech, he accommodated the horde of
reporters hungry for indications of how Natsios plans to take
control of a project whose managers the Federal Highway audit said
had engaged in an ``unconscionable'' effort to conceal the growing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Bechtel/Parsons Brinckerhoff could be too large
and experienced for him to control, Natsios seemed confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my seventh management job,'' he said. ``In a number of
jobs, people told me the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said his priority will be people. He said he will ``hire
better people than me'' and tell them to take responsibility for
their actions and ``keep me informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether employees will be fired, he said, ``That is one of
the first thing I will look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said he had dealt with several Big Dig managers in his
role as secretary of Administration and Finance. Though they were
``adversaries,'' he said, ``I was very impressed with their
diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would know more when the full O'Brien/Kreitzberg
analysis comes back, in about three weeks. ``It's a very political
situation now on all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he may bring some management or accounting practices
employed by state government _ but not by authorities like the
Turnpike _ into use. He was not specific.
</P>
<P>
   He also said cities and towns looking for highway and bridge
money will not suffer further because of the Big Dig's $1.4 billion
cost increase. ``There's a five-year capital plan for the state. It
has not changed,'' Natsios said.
</P>
<P>
   He is seeking a meeting on Friday with US Department of
Transportation officials to go over the audit in more detail,
including clarification of a suggestion that the project might be
better managed by the Massachusetts Highway Department.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the last word has been heard on Big Dig cost,
Natsios said no. ``We don't know how much this thing is going to
cost exactly,'' he said. But the official state estimate of $13.1
billion is as good any, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Kerasiotes, who usually arrived at engagements with a
bevy of aides, Natsios walked to the front of the room alone.
</P>
<P>
   He said the water heater at his home broke Tuesday, so he got
his second cold shower in two days. The first, of course, came when
Cellucci called to tell him he was now in charge of the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep much last night,'' Natsios said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
