<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDITORS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE QUESTIONS BUSH'S CREDENTIALS AS REFORMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT1 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his harshest and most comprehensive critique of
his Republican rival to date, Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday
questioned Gov. George W. Bush's self-annointment as a ``reformer
with results'' and said that if Texas was Bush's model for what he
would do as president, he had no credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps saying he's a reformer with results,'' Gore said in a
speech to the American Society of Newspaper Editors. ``Where are
the results? They're not in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a series of policy speeches in which Bush had
ventured into traditionally Democratic issues, Gore said that Bush
was pretending to care about issues like health care, education and
the environment but that his record in Texas showed he had done
little on these fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we believe what he says he would do nationally when we
see what he actually has done as governor?'' Gore asked. ``This is
about something more than public policy. It is about credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech seemed to betray some concerns in the Gore campaign
about Bush's potential to make inroads with traditional Democratic
voters as well as suburban swing voters with his proposals on
health care, education and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   And they come on the heels of a couple of recent polls that show
Bush with leads of 5 to 9 points over Gore, a point that Bush's
aides made in responding to the criticism. ``The worse Al Gore does
in the polls, the more he attacks and misrepresents Governor Bush's
record in Texas,'' said Ari Fleischer, Bush's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's recent policy initiatives have prompted the Gore campaign
to intensify its critique of Bush's record, painting Texas as a
near-Third World backwater where children are poorly educated and
go without health insurance, and where chemical polluters control
environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also cast himself as the one who would ``take on the
special interests'' as he renewed his call for overhauling the
campaign finance system. Describing his plan for an endowment
financed by corporate and individual donors and distributed to
congressional candidates without regard to party, Gore told the
audience: ``The views of the donors will have absolutely no
influence on the views of the recipient. In this way, we can break
the connection between the giving of money and the gaining of
influence in these election contests.''
</P>
<P>
   But in discussions later in the day with contributors, Gore was
quick to offer reassurance that at least until the system is
changed, their money will not go unwanted _ or unspent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight fire with fire,'' the vice president promised 25
people, each of whom gave $25,000, at a Democratic National
Committee luncheon at the home of Tom Downey, the former
congressman from New York and now a lobbyist who is one of Gore's
closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon was Gore's second of the day. At the first, held at
the Westin Fairfax Hotel, the same Embassy Row building here where
Gore grew up as the son of a senator, Gore was the drawing card for
about 30 people whom the Democratic National Committee hopes will
contribute to a May 24 gala for the party.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel luncheon was hosted by Terry McAuliffe, President
Clinton's top fund-raiser, who is organizing the gala as a tribute
to the president, although the vice president will be the chief
beneficiary. McAuliffe said he hoped the gala would raise $7
million, which is about half of what the Republican National
Committee has said it would raise at its own gala on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   In an unlikely pitch to his well-heeled listeners, McAuliffe
vowed: ``The Republicans are going to have a beautiful, black-tie
event with candelabras and wine and champagne. Ours is going to be
a barbeque from Tennessee and Arkansas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
