<SLUG> BC-MONEY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL NEWMAN, ALL CHARM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Where the Money Is,'' though undemanding and not very
ambitious, is a pleasing enough entry in the caper comedy
sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   It's got Paul Newman in the tried-and-true, scamp-with-a-heart
mode we've always enjoyed, from ``The Hustler'' to ``Cool Hand
Luke'' to ``Butch Cassidy'' and ``The Sting.'' It's got Linda
Fiorentino sending up her ``Last Seduction'' femme fatale image
with uncharacteristically adorable warmth.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have a whole lot else going for it; but then, this
modest little charmer doesn't really need more.
</P>
<P>
   Newman is legendary bank robber Henry Manning. Fiorentino is
nursing home attendant Carol Ann McKay. They meet when he fakes a
stroke to get out of prison and is put in her care.
</P>
<P>
   She rightly suspects that the catatonic codger is pulling a fast
one. But he's good; no matter how hard she tries to get a rise out
of him, Henry remains impassive in his wheelchair. Unmoved by loud
noises and lap dances, Henry is finally forced to come to when
Carol dumps him in a river. Now they can get down to business.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Carol is frustrated by her dead-end job and
marriage to her high school sweetheart, a working stiff named Wayne
(Dermot Mulroney). She thinks Henry _ who was only ever caught
because of a freak power failure that trapped him in a bank vault _
can help them pull off a robbery that will change their boring
lives. The old pro, of course, has no intention of hooking up with
these amateurs. But when his own escape/retirement plans head
south, he seriously reconsiders the eager nurse's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, her marriage isn't the greatest, she's impressed by
him, and despite Henry's awesome self-control, he !ital!is played
by Paul Newman...
</P>
<P>
   The movie's only really noteworthy element is Newman's
concentrated stillness in the early scenes; he's virtually playing
dead, or at the very least comatose, and he's still the most
charismatic guy in the room. When Henry wakes up, Newman
essentially falls back on the understated gruffness he's been
working so well in his old age. And in those parts, he's
!ital!still the most charismatic guy in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorentino craftily earns her share of attention, too. She
invests Carol's larcenous determination with a becoming innocence.
The woman doesn't have a mean bone in her body, she'd just like a
little more, well, something out of life. Fiorentino understands
that Carol is, first and foremost, a kook, and pitches her attempts
at manipulation accordingly. And by keeping her sincere, the
actress makes the character funny without turning her into a fool.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Marek Kanievska, a Brit who was evidently so
traumatized by studio interference with his last feature film,
``Less Than Zero,'' that he's stuck to TV and commercials for the
last 13 years. Consequently, every moment of ``Where the Money Is''
has a lovingly handmade feeling to it. Though it's hardly the most
clever heist story, that quality does make it one of the sweetest _
which may not mean money in the bank, but it's worth something. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Where the Money Is'' (PG-13; adult situations, mild
violence). &QL; 
The stars: Paul Newman, Linda Fiorentino, Dermot Mulroney. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Marek Kanievska. Written by E. Max
Frye, Topper Lilien and Carroll Cartwright. Produced by Ridley
Scott, Charles Weinstock, Chris Zarpas and Christopher Dorr.
Released by USA Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 29 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
