<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DRAFT-RISKYPICKS13-CO     04-12 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAFT-RISKYPICKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Risky business: The drafting of bad boys
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was, in the opinion of former
Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson, one of the most thorough pre-draft
investigations in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins didn't just look at tape of Cecil Collins playing
football or examine a pile of his workout statistics. They spent a
week in his hometown. They talked to high school teachers. They
scoured court records. They learned all about the failed drug
tests, the break-ins at women's apartments, the expulsions from two
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   And then they drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, with Collins sitting in Broward County Jail as
merely a footnote to the NFL's recent off-the-field problems _ two
others players, Ray Lewis and Rae Carruth, are charged with murder
_ the league is looking for ways to prevent its nearly 2,000
players from producing such headline-making incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Among the suggestions: If you don't want bad apples, don't pick
them. Not in the first round. Not in the fifth round. Not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Bowlen, owner of the Denver Broncos, believes league action
such as punishment for off-the-field conduct can only go so far.
The true solution, he says, rests with teams _ the owners, coaches
and general managers who often are willing to overlook warning
signs and give the players jobs in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think as an organization, you've got to pay more
attention to players' conduct and reputations before you bring them
in,'' Bowlen said. ``I think more often than not, when you take a
chance on a player of questionable character, you're making the
wrong decision.''
</P>
<P>
   During the NFL's annual meeting last month in Palm Beach, the
owners and head coaches held a two-hour discussion of how to combat
the off-the-field problems. At one point, Bowlen stood up and gave
his recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to stop taking these guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Will Bowlen's peers listen to him? For that matter, will he
listen to himself? Or will a eye-popping time in the 40-yard dash
continue to leave teams blind to other problems?
</P>
<P>
   The first test will come this weekend. The 65th annual NFL
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a Lawrence Phillips in this draft,'' analyst Joel
Buchsbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a long list of college football players who
were arrested during the past year and charged with an assortment
of offenses _ domestic violence, assault, bribery, phone scams, an
infamous shopping spree and, in the case of a 260-pound Kansas
defensive end, an attempt to climb through the drive-through window
of a Taco Bell to get a chalupa.
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams, if they are serious in their attempt to weed out
potential problem players, must decide how heavily to weigh each
incident. And many observers believe when the teams are faced with
the moment of decision _ the clock ticking as NFL Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue stands at the podium, ready to announce their pick _
on-the-field potential will count for more than potential
off-the-field problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone will always give the superior athlete with rare
ability chance after chance,'' Buchsbaum said. ``That won't
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But New York Giants coach Jim Fassell insists it has.
During an ESPN ``Outside the Lines'' special, Fassell said:
``Sometimes the guy is such a great player and stuff, you know, you
might turn your back a little bit to it. But I think people are
starting to realize you can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps their most interesting test of whether Fassell is right
will come in the form of three former Florida State players:
receivers Peter Warrick and Laveranues Coles and kicker Sebastian
Janikowski.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski, dubbed the Polish Cannon because his thick thighs
can help launch a football 70 yards, has earned a reputation for
being a loose cannon when the sun sets. He is banned from two
Tallahassee nightclubs. He missed curfew during Sugar Bowl week in
New Orleans. And after the season, when a roommate was arrested
outside a nightclub in Tallahassee, Janikowski allegedly dropped a
couple $100 bills in the lap of police officer _ a move that earned
him a felony charge of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   His draft fate: The Super Bowl champion St. Louis Rams are
considering taking him with the 31st pick, which would make him the
first kicker selected in the opening round since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's stock has dropped in recent months. He once was
expected to be the top pick in the draft. Now there is talk that he
won't be one of the top three picks. The reason isn't a sudden
concern about off-the-field incidents _ from paying $10.70 for
$244.38 of clothing at Dillard's to an arrest after a confrontation
with police in a McDonald's parking lot in Tampa _ but rather
questions about his size and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for pure speed, you don't take him,'' one
NFL scout said. ``You take Coles.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to perhaps the biggest character question in the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone calls him ``Trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least they used to. His mother gave him the nickname when
four days of labor ended and the doctor told her, ``This boy is
gonna be trouble.'' But these days, Coles is asking friends and
family to drop the nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just call me L.C.,'' he said. ``I want to put that behind
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles, reached at his mother's house in Jacksonville this week,
said that for most of his life he didn't live up to his nickname;
that he carried a 3.0 grade-point average in high school; that he
is a good person; that he just made some bad decisions while at
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   When he was kicked off the team after the Dillard's incident,
FSU officials cited prior problems _ misdemeanor battery for
hitting his father's ex-wife; violating team curfew before the Duke
game; threatening a woman at a bowling alley and accepting a plane
ticket from an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Coles denies some of the problems happened _ the bowling alley
incident, the violation of curfew and the plane ticket. He says
that when he ``mushed'' his father's ex-wife's face against a car
window, he was defending his mother. And as for the Dillard's
incident, he calls that ``a stupid mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like everything that has happened I brought upon
myself,'' he said. ``There's nobody to blame but myself. But
whoever takes me will get a good player _ and a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   This much is indisputable: Whoever takes him will get a fast
person.
</P>
<P>
   He is the fastest player in FSU history. Faster than Deion
Sanders. Much faster than Warrick. Coles was timed at 4.16 in the
40 during his FSU career. In March, on the slippery floor of a
gymnasium, he ran a 4.35 _ shortly before Warrick ran a 4.63.
</P>
<P>
   It was these kind of numbers that Dr. Lauren Langman, a
professor of sociology at Loyola University in Chicago, had in mind
when he predicted that the NFL owners, despite what was said in
Palm Beach, won't slam the door shut on players with off-the-field
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be like the day when Vince McMahon announces that the
WWF no longer is going to fix matches,'' he said. ``If the people
who gathered there did that, they wouldn't get the best players.
Are the owners thinking about doing something good for society or
are they concerned with making money?''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are looking for a fast receiver. But, following
their owner's character-counts edict, the team reportedly crossed
at least 10 players off their list of possible draft picks. It is
unclear whether Coles was among the rejects. It is clear he won't
be going to Tampa Bay. The Buccaneers refused to even meet with
Coles at the Indianapolis scouting combine _ a move that adds to
Bucs coach Tony Dungy's reputation for doing more than talk about
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone can play for me,'' Dungy said.
</P>
<P>
   Coles says that when he is playing for someone else, he plans to
make Dungy and the Bucs pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to light them up for three scores someday,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He would love to end up staying in Florida. And although the
Jacksonville Jaguars have a history of steering away from players
with problems, he says they have shown interest. So have the
Oakland Raiders, the franchise that has embraced bad behavior. And
then there is that other team in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like him,'' Dolphins director of college scouting Tom
Braatz said.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation is that Coles will drop into the second round.
Would the Dolphins, who don't have a first-round pick, dare use the
53rd overall selection to take him? What if he falls further?
</P>
<P>
   Last year they decided that despite all they knew about Collins,
the cost of adding him _ a fifth-round pick and a relatively small
salary _ made it worth the risk. And although new coach Dave
Wannstedt refuses to comment on Coles, he seems to leave the door
open to another controversial draft day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no surprises when we picked a couple guys late _
and I emphasize the word late _ with character issues,'' Wannstedt
said. ``Now, is that what we want to do? Obviously you never want
to draft a guy who is going to be a problem for your football team,
the organization and the community. But to stand up here and say,
'We're never going to draft a guy who's had a problem in the past'
... I can't say that. I can just tell you that it's not something
we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
