<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH UNVEILS LATEST PART OF HEALTH PLAN; GORE ATTACKS PREVIOUS
PROPOSAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore heaped scorn on Republican
George W. Bush's long-awaited health care plan Wednesday, calling
the Texan's proposal ``political malpractice'' and another attempt
to gloss over his record as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's attack came as Bush unveiled another piece of his health
care plan in St. Louis, proposing that the federal government
expand community and migrant health centers for low-income and
uninsured Americans and to assure that doctors are sent to
communities short on medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier in Cleveland, the Texas governor waded into the
health care debate by outlining a $39.6 billion package that is
built largely on providing tax credits to help America's working
poor buy health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush announced his health care proposals a week after flying to
Pennsylvania to outline his plan for cleaning up the environment.
Both issues, long considered the home turf of Democrats, have been
at the center of Gore's campaign for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington early Wednesday, Gore told a meeting of newspaper
editors that Bush has failed to push initiatives that could change
Texas' first-place ranking among the 50 states in air pollution and
49th in the percentage of children with health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   About one in four Texas children are not covered by health
insurance, Gore said, ``because of the political malpractice of the
Bush administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said Bush calls himself ``a reformer with
results'' but has little to show. ``Where are the results?'' Gore
said. ``They're not in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``wants us to believe he's committed to issues like
education, health care and the environment,'' Gore told the
American Society of Newspaper Editors. ``Let's face it. The Bush
approach on these issues is a headline without a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday in St. Louis for a response to Gore's new
criticism, Bush said: ``Not right now, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer defended the governor's record,
saying Texas health care has improved during his tenure. ``The
worse Al Gore is doing in the polls, the more he attacks and
misrepresents the governor's record,'' said Fleischer. ``Pretty
soon, Al Gore will say he invented health care.''
</P>
<P>
   After vetoing a patients' protection act in 1995, Bush two years
later signed several bills that included patients' rights, but not
a provision allowing patients to choose their own doctors. In
addition, a measure allowing patients to sue their insurance
companies became law without his signature.
</P>
<P>
   Bush fought in 1999 to limit the number of Texans allowed to
participate in the Children's Health Insurance Program, then
yielded to state lawmakers' demands that it be made available to
children from families whose incomes are twice the poverty level.
More than 400,000 children are eligible to participate in the $179
million program, but no one knows how many will enroll.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who has made health care a centerpiece of
his campaign for the White House, has proposed spending $146
billion over the next decade in an effort to provide health
insurance coverage for all children.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, Bush proposed Wednesday that the federal
government spend $3.6 billion over the next five years to create
1,200 new community and migrant health centers, which would bring
the total number to 4,200 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult places to build a quality health facility
are the very areas where the need is greatest _ and where patients
have the least ability to pay,'' the Texas governor said. ``For
these Americans, community health centers are the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the community centers, which were used by more than 11
million people last year, save about $6 billion a year in
emergency-room visits, hospital stays and other medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the end what counts is not just saving money. What
counts is saving lives,'' he said during a visit to St. Louis'
Grace Hill Family Health Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also called for changes in the National Health Service
Corps to assure that doctors are sent to the areas most in need.
And he proposed the establishment of a ``Healthy Communities
Innovation Fund'' to provide $500 million in grants to pay for
local pilot projects targeting specific community health needs.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost of Bush's new proposals would be about $4.4
billion over the next five years. That would be in addition to a
$39.6 billion health-related package he laid out on Tuesday in
Cleveland. The centerpiece of the earlier package would provide
$34.7 billion in tax credits to help America's working poor buy
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   This week marks the first time that Bush has made health care a
central focus of the presidential campaign that he officially
launched last June.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
