<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-GROWTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF PAINTS ROSY ECONOMIC PICTURE BUT WITH CAVEATS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TRADE-PROTESTS) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The final strains of the financial virus that
toppled emerging market economies have dissipated, allowing the
world economy to regain its health and to grow at its fastest pace
in more than a decade, the International Monetary Fund said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In its twice-yearly World Economic Outlook, the monetary fund
forecast that the global economy, led by the persistently robust
growth in the United States, would expand at a rate of 4.2 percent
in 2000, its fastest pace since 1988. IMF economists estimated that
growth would taper off slightly in 2001 to 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the fund, based in Washington, warned that several things
cloud that rosy outlook, including lopsided growth among countries,
currencies that appear to be out of whack with one another and high
stock prices in some countries, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The fund said that the United States needs to engineer a soft
landing for its economy, that Europe must not kill faster economic
growth with rising interest rates and that Japan needs to put some
zest in its ``fragile'' recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence of a strong rebound in the global economy has
continued to accumulate in recent months and the momentum of the
recovery from the 1997-98 slowdown has proven much stronger than
anticipated,'' IMF said. ``At the same time, considerable
uncertainty remains about the sustainability of the expansion in
some countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which monitors the world's macro economy and makes
loans to poor and middle-income countries, sounded a strong note of
caution about the United States. Though the fund estimated that the
United States will grow at a faster-than-average rate of 4.4
percent this year and 3 percent next year, it cited signs of
financial excess that could derail the expansion and wallop the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Overvalued stock markets, the widespread use of credit, record
low savings rates and a giant gap between the amount the United
States spends on goods abroad and the much smaller amount that
foreigners spend on U.S. goods create worrying ``imbalances'' that
could make any economic downturn in this country sharper than it
would otherwise be, it said.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely scenario for the U.S. economy is a soft landing
in which the expansion slows before picking up again, IMF said. But
it also cited a less likely set of events in which an increase in
inflation, a 25 percent drop in stock prices and a 20 percent dive
in the value of the dollar combine to bring U.S. growth to a sudden
halt _ a hard landing. In that case, worldwide economic growth
would be a full percentage point lower, the fund estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very high valuations, particularly in the technology and
bio-tech sectors, continue to pose the risk of a large market
correction and a sharper economic slowdown'' in the United States,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the fund's economic outlook came just before the
formal beginning of the annual spring meetings at the fund and its
sister agency, the World Bank. Financial ministers from around the
world will arrive in Washington this weekend to review the
performance of the fund and the bank, which together seek to
maintain economic stability and alleviate poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings have attracted a much larger than usual response
from groups wary of globalization, especially some nongovernment
organizations that support environmental, religious and third-world
development causes. Protesters said they will attempt to shut down
the meetings because they accuse the two agencies of supporting
corporations over poor nations and rampant free-market capitalism
over sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
   From the IMF's perspective, the meetings are in some respects
less stressful than they have been in the past. Many nations that
receive IMF aid, including long-slumping Russia, are performing
better than expected, meaning that the fund is in the position of
raise its growth estimates rather than lowering them as it has had
to do in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5025 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-PSYCHO-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      04-12 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHO-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSYCHO SATIRE SURPRISES EVERYBODY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They said it couldn't be done. They said it shouldn't be done.
</P>
<P>
   But they've done it: made a movie out of ``American Psycho,''
Bret Easton Ellis' 1991 novel about young Wall Street money mover
Patrick Bateman, whose contempt for all things inexpensive is
mirrored by his evolution into an insane serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' says the Sherman Oaks-bred provocateur Ellis himself.
``I never thought that a movie would be made of 'American Psycho.'
And I never thought it would be made by a woman, and a feminist,
and someone who's about to have a baby. If you'd told me that 10
years ago, I would've said, 'You're lying, you're teasing me, stop
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although the novel was basically a satire of the 1980s greed
culture, early excerpts of ``Psycho's'' clinically deadpan
descriptions of detached sadism and brutal torture proved so
shocking that the book's original publisher, Simon &AMP; Schuster,
declined to release it. When it did come out as a Vintage
Contemporary (which has since gone through 33 more printings),
``Psycho'' was excoriated throughout the media, by women's groups
and in all places where gentlefolk put forth opinion, usually by
people who hadn't read it.
</P>
<P>
   But some did read it, and even got the joke. Among these were
filmmakers Mary Harron, the director of ``I Shot Andy Warhol,'' and
Guinevere Turner, an actress who wrote and produced the lesbian
dating comedy ``Go Fish.'' Both women with impeccable feminist
credentials, they wanted to make this supposed misogynist
monstrosity into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   And they did. But as you might imagine, it was not easy in any
way, shape or form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't want to make another serial killer story,
but I did want to make a social satire about the late '80s,'' says
Harron, a former music journalist whose baby girl is due in two
weeks. ``I thought 'American Psycho' caught the mad obsessiveness
of the period very well. It had always seemed, to me, a time when
people went crazy over restaurants, clothes, buying things ... What
the book did that I thought was clever was to take this madman and
have him sort of represent the psychosis of the age.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But regardless of whether you found it comic or
repulsive, adapting such a bloodthirsty work from the printed page
to the more immediate medium of cinema required a certain, ah,
surgical precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially when you're looking at a book that was surrounded
by so much controversy when it came out, we had to really think
about how to get away from that,'' notes Turner, who co-wrote the
film's screenplay with director Harron and plays one of Bateman's
victims in the movie. ``I think the book was unnecessarily
criticized when it came out, but that was because people were
blinded by all the violence. It's just that Bret took it too far,
and I'm sure that, since my and Mary's careers have been all about
feminist work, it was very strategic for the producers to have us
on the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Until it wasn't, but more on that in a moment. Indeed, the two
women were determined to tone down the novel's more
stomach-churning violence (a good example: a nail gun is only seen
in the movie, not used). They also finessed Bateman's brutal sexism
into more generalized, gender-neutral misanthropy, while all the
time maintaining the piece's scathing critique of the money
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts were a revelation to Christian Bale (``Velvet
Goldmine,'' Steven Spielberg's ``Empire of the Sun''), the young
British actor whom Harron was convinced early on would be her
perfect Bateman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't read the novel when it first came out, but, like most
people, I knew about the controversy but had only been informed
about the extreme violence of it and nothing of the satire,'' Bale
explains. ``So the screenplay was a complete surprise to me because
it just wasn't what I was expecting of 'American Psycho' in the
slightest.''
</P>
<P>
   Enthused, Bale threw himself into capturing Bateman's deranged
mindset and pumping up his body into the appearance-conscious
monster's idea of the perfect physical specimen.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how hard he worked it, the handsome Brit was no
Leo. Shortly before the planned start of ``American Psycho's''
production, word leaked out of the Cannes Film Festival that
Leonardo DiCaprio, then hotter than any other actor in the
universe, was interested in Bateman as his ``Titanic'' follow-up
role.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally enough, Lions Gate, the small Canadian company that
was backing the $10 million project, was eager to pony up $21
million for the superstar. Harron, however, was not similarly
smitten. She refused to helm the project she'd been nurturing so
carefully without Bale. Other directors, most notably ``Wall
Street'' sensationalist Oliver Stone, were soon circling the
production, while Harron's team was left out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was snatched away for, like, six months, and Mary and I
read about it in the papers like almost everybody else,'' Bale
recalls. ``All I know was that it was our movie, and suddenly there
was the idea to make it a massive-budget movie. Mary said no, so
she was kicked off it as well, but we just stubbornly kept talking
as if we were going to still make it anyway. It was infuriating,
but I still don't know to this day what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, DiCaprio opted to make ``The Beach''
instead, in which he played a role that, ironically, was in many
ways as off-putting as Patrick Bateman. But infinitely dumber.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of rumors why (DiCaprio) didn't do it,''
Turner notes with a snarky smile. ``One such rumor is that Gloria
Steinem met with him and asked him, for the good of all 13-year-old
girls in this country, not to make this film.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what we got from it, aside from lunatics approaching me
and asking me if I could get their scripts to Leo, was just a lot
of publicity and a lot of hype,'' Turner happily adds. ``And Mary
got to make the exact movie that she wanted to make.''
</P>
<P>
   All, apparently, was forgiven between Lions Gate and the Harron
camp by the time ``Psycho'' filming got under way in Toronto last
year. But that was not the case between the production and Canadian
critics of the book. It seems one of the nation's actual serial
killers, Paul Bernardo, had read ``American Psycho,'' and even
though protests against the film took a characteristically polite
tack _ letters to newspapers as opposed to bullhorn-wielding
throngs _ many contracted locations balked at letting the film
company onto their sites.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it took the good old U.S. film rating authority,
the MPAA, to dependably place the final hurdle in ``Psycho's'' path
to a theater near you. They gave Harron's initial cut a
commercially deadly NC-17 rating. Perversely, though, It wasn't
anything about the chainsaw chase or poleax sequence that upset the
American censors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but think that the ratings board felt that they
had to do something, had to some way put a stamp on this movie
because of the controversy surrounding it,'' Bale says. ``So it was
just a matter of which scene would they pick. How typically
American that it was a sex scene.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve a more commercially viable R rating, Harron had to
trim 17 seconds and half a two-syllable expletive out of a
menage-a-trois scenario that Bateman orchestrates with a pair of
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm offended, personally, because I'm also acting in the film
and I get killed in a three-way sex scene,'' Turner cracks with
mock indignation. ``They didn't want to edit that at all!''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of offensive: Now Lions Gate is offering actual shares
in the movie that can be bought through the online Hollywood Stock
Exchange (HSX.com). That's a new marketing wrinkle, and a pretty
ironic one to be connected with a picture that comments on today's
overwrought investment culture by making fun of one recently past.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of that, the principles are pleased with the result
of the long, bloody struggle to bring ``American Psycho'' to the
screen. Understandably, though, they're still a little nervous
about how the film will be received _ though not necessarily for
the reasons you might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, some fans of the book have complained that the
movie's not violent enough,'' Bale notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it might still be too much for some people, although I
hope it's not,'' Turner adds. ``But I'm also afraid that, since
it's called 'American Psycho,' people are going to walk away
saying, 'Well, it wasn't that scary,' and they're going to miss the
fact that it's supposed to be a satire.''
</P>
<P>
   But the man who first unleashed Patrick Bateman on an
unsuspecting world is sanguine _ in the non-sanguinary meaning of
the word _ about the way the movie has turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a totally faithful adaptation would have been
ruinous for this movie,'' author Ellis acknowledges. ``There are a
lot of things in that book that I don't particularly want to see or
hear or have to sit in a theater and deal with. Reading a book and
going to a movie are two completely different things. I don't
really want to see some of the violence in that book re-created for
the screen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
