<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAITH' HAS TOO FEW REWARDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Keeping the Faith'' is a movie about a priest and a rabbi and
a corporate executive. The priest and the rabbi are never on a
rowboat, although they do tread water on numerous occasions. Edward
Norton plays the priest and also makes his directorial debut here.
And while the film has all the marks of an actor's vanity project _
it's too long and is often weighted down by too much talk _
``Keeping the Faith'' has much to recommend it, starting with the
pleasure of watching Norton the actor at work.
</P>
<P>
   Norton plays Brian Finn and Ben Stiller is his childhood friend,
Rabbi Jake Schram. The two energetic young men stride through
Manhattan's Upper West Side wearing black leather jackets and
acting as if they have the keys to the kingdom. (Father Finn does
say that if God had hired him, He would have had the world made by
Thursday.) Their messages from the pulpit come off as stand-up
homilies, full of wacky references to pop culture. (``God is a lot
like Blanche DuBois ...'')
</P>
<P>
   For Father Finn, celibacy is part of the job description, but
Jake must deal with the ``Kosher Nostra,'' temple mothers anxious
for their daughters to wed a handsome rabbi who wears expensive
tailored suits with his yarmulke. Jake is not a particularly good
dater. His ease in front of his congregation evaporates when he's
alone with a woman. (Stiller makes for perfect casting here.)
</P>
<P>
   Enter (or re-enter, as it were) Anna Reily (Jenna Elfman). Anna,
Jake and Brian were childhood chums who did everything together
before Anna's family moved to California when she was 13. Anna now
works as a corporate fixer (``I talked McDonald's out of the
McOyster'') and she's temporarily in New York to work her magic.
Her spell extends to the boys_ who still consider Anna the coolest
woman they've ever known, even though they haven't seen her in some
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   This sets up the classic romantic comedy love triangle, but
``Keeping the Faith'' is smarter than most films in the genre.
Written by playwright Stuart Blumberg, a Yale buddy of Norton's,
the film is particularly adept at examining the ways faith and love
intersect. Spirituality has rarely been treated so seriously in a
film this light, as the three main characters confront their own
personal crises of faith. (Brian: ``I was really starting to think
I had a few things worked out there.'')
</P>
<P>
   Factor in engaging turns from Norton, Stiller and Elfman (sort
of playing the anti-Dharma here) and you have the makings of a
sweet, warm-hearted movie. Two things, though, sour the
appreciation a bit. Blumberg, a playwright, has an ear for good
dialogue, but that's about it. The film is dull visually, a product
of a couple of first-timers who don't have ideas about what to do
with a scene that doesn't spotlight people talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping the Faith'' is also a good 20 minutes too long, its
characters taking forever to act on the things they (and the
audience) long ago figured out. When Ben Stiller looks into the
camera as Jake and says, ``This could take a while,'' it's not a
plot point. It's a warning. Any movie that has a karaoke finale
where everyone sings Barry Manilow's ``I'm Ready to Take a Chance
Again'' and !ital!stilldoesn't end has a problem. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Keeping the Faith'' (PG-13; some language, adult
situations). &QL; 
The stars: Ben Stiller, Edward Norton, Jenna Elfman. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Edward Norton. Screenplay by Stuart
Blumberg. Released by Touchstone Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, eight minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
