<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING FOCUS ON HEALTH CARE, BUSH MAKES ANOTHER BILLION-DOLLAR
PROPOSAL
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story, eliminated earlier, is now restored; see also
BUSH-GAYS) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ For the second day in a row, Gov. George W. Bush on
Wednesday kept his campaign focused on health care, touring a
community clinic and proposing to spend an additional $4.3 billion
over five years to expand health care services to the needy in the
inner cities and remote rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican visited the Grace Hill Neighborhood Health
Center, located in a traditionally Democratic area of Missouri. He
then announced his proposal flanked by doctors and nurses, black
and white, creating another campaign tableau showing him with
members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society resolved long ago to provide a safety net for
those in the most desperate circumstances _ a safety net that
includes income support, housing assistance and health services,''
Bush said, a day after he proposed that $41.6 billion be spent
across five years in tax credits, tax incentives and vouchers to
help lower income Americans buy health insurance and their own
homes.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the governor added a few more proposals, for a $3.6
billion increase over five years in federal aid to create 1,200 new
community and migrant health centers to serve inner city and rural
residents without health insurance. He also proposed a $500 million
fund to make grants for pilot programs that try to address
particular health problems, like diabetes. And he called for some
changes in the operation of a federal scholarship program that
places physicians in areas short of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, Bush had largely been silent on health care
issues. But the latest proposals are part of a sustained drive by
the presumptive Republican presidential nominee to try to eat into
the traditional Democratic advantage on issues like education and
health care, which have moved to the forefront of public concern in
a time of peace and economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   With experts questioning whether Bush's centerpiece initiative
for the uninsured _ tax credits of up to $2,000 _ would be
sufficient to help low- and moderate-income families buy health
insurance, Vice President Al Gore went on the offensive against
Bush, asserting that hundreds of thousands of Texans lack health
insurance ``because of the political malpractice of the Bush
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose campaign has been pointing to Texas' grim statistics
on public health issues and its high number of residents without
health insurance, accused Bush of posturing on issues of public
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants us to believe he's committed to issues like
education, health care and the environment,'' Gore said in an
appearance in Washington before newspaper editors. He added, ``We
need the nation's reporters and editors to challenge every
assumption and question every proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked as he was shaking hands with members of his audience
whether he had any response to Gore, the Texas governor refused to
be drawn into the fray, telling a reporter, ``Not right now, thank
you.'' Though he plans to hold a news conference Thursday, Bush has
not taken questions in two days in an effort to keep attention from
being diverted from his health care announcements.
</P>
<P>
   It was left to his spokesman, Ari Fleischer, to reply. ``The
worse Al Gore is in the polls, the more he attacks and
misrepresents Governor Bush's record,'' he said. ``Pretty soon Al
Gore will say he invented health care,'' he said, alluding to
Gore's remark last year, in which the vice president took credit
for developing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said they were delighted to see Gore having to
fight back on issues on which the Democrats have traditionally
dominated, and they were heartened by the governor's slight rise
ahead of Gore in several recent national polls, although in each
case his lead was within the margin of sampling error. Fleischer
said Bush would continue making policy speeches throughout the
spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
