<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKS KEEP THEIR CORE TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In that murky never-never land, somewhere between New
Jersey and Long Island, the New York Jets were sending away their
very best football player. Like most teams in most towns, the Jets
were officially starting over.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the Bronx, the only thing that seems to change is the
height of Andrew Giuliani as he soars upward, toward the Yankee cap
on his father's head.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't pay attention to the subtleties, it could still be
the 20th Century, with the bunting flapping in the breeze for the
home opener, Joe Torre feigning serenity, and the sun and wind
playing havoc with the visiting left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   And when it really mattered, there was good old Paulie and good
old Bernie and good old Tino whacking the ball, and good old
Mariano inflicting another demoralization on the Texas Rangers,
8-6.
</P>
<P>
   It's been happening so long that it could get to be boring,
except that sports fans tend to admire excellence, and so do the
players who perform it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get tired of winning,'' said good old Derek Jeter,
who precedes the aforementioned good-olds in the lineup. ``There's
a lot of tradition here, a lot of memories.''
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing is that a good chunk of tradition and memories
are still going around in a Yankee uniform. Nobody has dealt Bernie
Williams for a bunch of callow youths out of Florida State. Nobody
is cutting David Cone or Paul O'Neill to fit a salary cap, or
justify a youth movement. Nobody has underestimated Tino Martinez,
not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is a throwback, and that's important to fans,'' said
Brian Cashman, the 33-year-old general manager. ``I can trust
people's track record. I don't believe players just suddenly turn
old at 37.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bad old days, Yankee domination should have been the
subject of a congressional anti-monopoly hearing. Now, stability
seems almost refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the alternative. Jets' fans got used to seeing Keyshawn
Johnson catch the ball over the middle, with a linebacker about to
clobber him on the spinal column. Then the Jets' new owner lets
Johnson get away to save money and accumulate draft choices, some
of whom might even turn out to be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman does not claim to understand the economics or the mind
set of football, but he has heard the Dallas Cowboys geared up for
another championship era by trading Herschel Walker for bodies and
draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to make a change,'' Cashman said. ``Look at
the great trade Doug Melvin made for the Rangers. He couldn't keep
Juan Gonzalez, so he got some good new players. That happens in
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Football is driven by shared network television money that
allows a Tampa Bay to sign a Keyshawn while baseball is rendered
inequitable by local television money. Plus, Cashman said, the
Yankees' longevity is a tribute to five straight leaps in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the king in his counting house has not made a grievous
error in a very long time, although the Yankees do practice
attrition. Letting John Wetteland walk after 1996 did not hurt
because Mariano Rivera was ready. They already miss Joe Girardi and
Luis Sojo, considered expendable after last year. But in Yankee
Stadium, the center continues to hold, and it feels all right
because there is not a certified jerk among them.
</P>
<P>
   The players appreciate their own continuity, but they also
understand mobility, particularly if it makes them rich, or
enhances their own home-town team. Martinez, with his roots in the
Ybor City section of Tampa, had his own take on the enrichment of
Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was great,'' Martinez said after the game. ``I'm a
Buccaneer fan. I loved it. I'm sorry, but he's a big-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could not admire a man signing for millions? But the Yankees
manage to get rich and stay put. This will be the eighth season in
the Bronx for O'Neill, the eighth full season for Williams and the
fifth for Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all professional hitters,'' said Jeter. ``They know
they don't have to hit a home run. They are content to hit
singles.''
</P>
<P>
   It must be fun to be a Yankee fan. There was Bob Sheppard,
managing to sound dignified on his 50th opening day despite the
witless sound effects blasting from the loudspeaker. There was good
old Zim, his fertile noggin secure behind a brand-new fence in
front of the dugout. And there was the mayor, stiffing potential
voters and donators upstate in order to sit with his kid in the
cold for the long game, and watch his guys win on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose in November, Giuliani won't be mayor much longer.
His team does not have term limits, and does not appear to be going
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BEN-JERRY-BOS &LR;      04-12 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN-JERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNILEVER SCOOPS UP BEN &AMP; JERRY'S FOR $326 MILLION IN CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ben will still be around, and so will Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   So will the plaque that marks where the two boyhood chums
started the ice cream company that quickly became as much a symbol
of Vermont as the Green Mountains themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But their company, Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade Inc., long a purveyor
of counterculture capitalism along with such flavors as Chunky
Monkey and Cherry Garcia, will now be part of the world's largest
consumer products conglomerate. Wednesday, Unilever said it was
buying Ben &AMP; Jerry's for $326 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   That left Ben &AMP; Jerry's fans in Vermont and beyond asking
whether the quirky company's commitment to social causes _ perhaps
its most important brand asset _ would survive.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of promises accompanying the deal, Unilever said it
would.
</P>
<P>
   The global giant that boasted $45 billion in sales last year of
brands that range from Lipton tea to Dove soaps, promised to keep
Ben &AMP; Jerry's operations and offices in Vermont, to maintain
employment at present levels for at leat two years, and to keep
employee benefits at current levels for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever also agreed to contribute at least $1.1 million a year
from pretax profits on Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice cream sales to a
foundation that supports causes selected by founders Ben Cohen and
Jerry Greenfield, from literacy to world peace.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, currently the company chairman, and Greenfield, who
retired from active involvement several years ago, also will retain
management roles, Unilever said. Neither founder was available for
comment. Friends said Cohen had taken the day off for meditation.
</P>
<P>
   A Massachusetts-based socially conscious investment group that
earlier worked with Cohen and Unilever to take Ben &AMP; Jerry's
private rather than sell to another bidder, Dreyer's Grand Ice
Cream Co., said it played a key role in winning these commitments
and applauded Unilever's willingness to sign them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to understand not only the marketing purposes of the
Ben &AMP; Jerry's social mission but the purposes of the mission
itself,'' said Terry Mollner, chief negotiator for Meadowbrook Lane
Capital, the group that included founders and board members of Body
Shop, Rhino Records and Calvert Group Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   In what some saw as the most unusual of the list of promises,
Unilever agreed to form an independent 11-member board to monitor
how well these conditions are being met.
</P>
<P>
   Eight members of this oversight panel are to be named by
existing Ben &AMP; Jerry's management, one by Unilever, and two by
Meadowbrook Lane Capital. A Ben &AMP; Jerry's spokeswoman said the
agreement gives the two Meadowbrook Lane members the right to sue
Unilever if other conditions aren't met.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Ben &AMP; Jerry's plant in Waterbury, Vt., where the
company offers factory tours, some visitors Wednesday received news
of the takeover with dismay. ``Being owned by a big corporation
takes all the thrill out of eating their ice cream,'' said Doug
Darrow, of Worcester, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to see how it all sugars off,'' said Tim Shea,
at the Lake Champlain Chamber of Commerce in Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, an Anglo-Dutch company whose brands also include
Gorton's fish filets and Wisk detergent, agreed to pay $43.60 a
share for Ben &AMP; Jerry's after rival Dreyer's, based in Oakland,
Calif., boosted its bid to $38 a share to counter the venture that
Cohen, Meadowbrook Lane and Unilever formed in March.
</P>
<P>
   With only $300 million in capital behind them, Mollner said, the
Meadowbrook Lane group backed out after the Dreyer's move. ``We
felt we couldn't win a bidding war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately _ and by coincidence, a spokesman said _ Unilever
also announced Wednesday an acquisition on the other end of the
calorie scale. It said it was buying SlimFast Foods Co. for $2.3
billion, also in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Florida-based SlimSoft, which with sales of $611 million last
year held 45 percent of the US market for weight-loss drinks, was
the bigger catch. But the Ben &AMP; Jerry's sale grabbed far more
public interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of this company's success has been this community
responsiblity, this rural Vermont flavor they bring to the
business,'' Unilever spokesman John T. Gould Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by Cohen and Greenfield from the day they opened their
first shop in May 1978 in an abandoned gas station on Church Street
in Burlington, this mission ``has become an important part of the
brand, the heritage,'' Gould said.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street welcomed the deal, bidding up Ben &AMP; Jerry's shares
$8.125 to close at $43.0625. Unilever PLC shares traded on the New
York Stock Exchange closed at $28.75, up 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever got ``a powerhouse'' in Ben &AMP; Jerry's, said analyst
Jeffrey Kanter of Prudential Securities in New York. Kanter said
the acquisition would allow the European-based conglomerate to
enter the US premium ice cream market on sound ground. Unilever's
US ice cream brands now include Breyer's, Good Humor and Sealtest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This helps Unilever fill in a part of the category where they
weren't contributing,'' said Eric Katzman, analyst for Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
