u w BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-HNS     04-12 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL OKS COMPROMISE 
ON ORGAN TRANSPLANT REGULATION &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration Wednesday signed off on
a Senate bill calling for broader sharing of the country's scarce
supply of organs for transplant while allowing medical
professionals to write transplant policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people deserve consensus in a highly charged
field where we have not done as well as we might have in the
past,'' said Sen. Bill Frist, a former heart and lung transplant
surgeon who brokered the compromise he hopes will end a two-year
power struggle over who should decide who gets a transplant and who
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of negotiations, Frist, R-Tenn., finally reached
agreement with Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and U.S. Health and
Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala at 2:30 a.m. Wednesday.
Hours later, the Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions
Committee passed his bill unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   The bill clarifies the roles that the federal government and its
private contractor, the United Network for Organ Sharing, should
play in running the country's transplant system, and sets up an
outside committee of transplant experts to settle any disputes
between them.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala will appoint all 21 members of the committee. Seven of
her choices will represent Health and Human Services; seven will
come from 12 recommendations submitted by the United Network for
Organ Sharing; and seven will come from 12 recommendations by the
Institute of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   While stopping short of demanding that organs be shared
nationally, the bill requires that the transplant system ``seek to
reduce disparities'' in who gets a transplant based on where they
live or which hospital they choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will be the most important public health bill
we'll pass this year,'' Kennedy said after the 18-0 vote. ``Organs
are really a national treasure, and in our society of equity and
fairness, we have an enormous responsibility'' to ensure an equal
chance of getting a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 69,000 patients are waiting for transplants of a heart,
liver, kidney or other organs. This year, only 20,000 organs are
expected to be donated. About 5,000 will die waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, organs are first offered to patients
in the geographical area where they are collected, even though a
sicker patient may be just a few miles outside that boundary. The
Frist-Kennedy bill encourages broader sharing by eliminating
geography as a serious barrier to transplant, along with
socioeconomic status, race and ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   If passed by the full Senate, the bill would proceed to a
conference committee to be reconciled with a House bill passed last
week. President Clinton has threatened to veto that bill, which
would give sole authority over transplant policy to the United
Network with little government oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said the Senate bill is ``a day-and-night improvement''
over the House bill and would ``provide a sound foundation for
moving toward a better, fairer organ transplant system for
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Network for Organ Sharing, which last week applauded
the House bill, said Wednesday that it hopes the Senate will pass
the Frist-Kennedy bill so the debate can move to the conference
committee and a quick resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see this thing over,'' said Mark Rosenker, managing
director of the network's Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenker said too much time has been spent in the two-year fight
between Health and Human Services and his group, taking attention
away from the more important question of how to increase organ
donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that same effort were focused in organ donation awareness,
and in advancing the science of transplantation, perhaps this
incredible gap of supply and demand would be much closer,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
