<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-TELECOM-NIPPON-     04-12 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TELECOM-NIPPON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIPPON TELEGRAPH AND TELEPHONE RESTRUCTURES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, the Japanese
telecommunications monolith that has restructured over the last
year to become more adaptable and profitable, announced further
plans to better position itself for an explosion in demand for
Internet-related services.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new three-year strategy, the company said on Wednesday
that it intended to post consolidated profits of 1 trillion yen, or
roughly $9.43 billion, in the fiscal year that will end on March
31, 2003. That is about 43 percent more than its earnings for the
fiscal year that just ended, and it includes NTT's affiliates, the
mobile phone provider NTT DoCoMo Inc. and the NTT Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan was long on vision and short on details, which the
company acknowledged. ``There is nothing of substance here written
in this report,'' said Junichiro Miyazu, president of NTT. ``But it
shows we must start thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's former telephone monopoly restructured in July into two
domestic fixed-line subsidiaries, NTT East and West. It did more
restructuring in November, announcing plans to cut 21,000 jobs from
the two subsidiaries over three years.
</P>
<P>
   But the company is still facing a sharp decline in demand for
fixed-line, voice-transmission services, its basic business, while
consumers clamor for the mobile phone and high-speed data
transmission services that fall under the purview of its big
affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Including Internet services that are provided over mobile
terminals, Japanese use of the Internet will surpass that of the
United States by March 31, 2001, company officials said on
Wednesday. Japan is now second only to the United States as the
world's largest user of the Internet, and NTT DoCoMo is outfitting
all its mobile phones with Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The company also continues to wrestle with its labor force,
which remains bloated and overpaid by Japanese standards. On
Wednesday, it pledged to replace the traditional, seniority-based
compensation system with a more merit-based plan.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would reallocate 27,000 employees from NTT
East and NTT West to other subsidiaries where growth is higher.
``Mobility of people, this is a must,'' Miyazu said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts who follow NTT said they were paying little heed
to any of the company's plans because of the highly politicized
atmosphere surrounding the telecommunications industry in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is threatening to take Japan to the World
Trade Organization, contending that government regulation favors
NTT and demanding a reduction in the fees that NTT competitors pay
for phone connections in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take anything the company says right now with anything
more than one grain of salt,'' said Makio Inui, a
telecommunications analyst at Nikko Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
