<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-ART-NYT &LR;      04-12 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SELLOFF IN TECHNOLOGY PUSHES NASDAQ INTO BEAR MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors jettisoned technology stocks Wednesday,
driving the Nasdaq composite index down 7.06 percent, or 286.27
points, to 3,769.63. The slide was the sixth largest in percentage
terms and the second largest in points in the index's history.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money being pulled out of technology shares shifted
into old economy stocks during the day, but the buying was abruptly
halted in the final hour, transforming a 1.22 percent advance in
the blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average into a 1.43 percent
decline. The Dow closed down 161.95 points, at 11,125.13. And the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index plummeted 33.42 points, to
1,467.17.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq has now fallen 25.3 percent from its peak on March
10, sinking into the territory of a 20 percent or greater retreat
that Wall Street designates as a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are fleeing the tech sector and throwing the money at
what they were castigating two weeks ago,'' said Thomas Rath, a
vice president and portfolio manager at Safeco Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   No development stood out as a cause for the latest wave of
selling. But analysts said contributing factors may have been the
slide in Microsoft's shares after a leading stock analyst lowered
his revenue expectations for the company; a battering of Motorola's
stock on Tuesday, and again Wednesday, after the company warned of
slower growth; some unusually pointed comments by a Federal Reserve
governor about the need to keep raising interest rates; uncertainty
over upcoming government reports on inflation, and some investors
raising cash to meet Monday's deadline for paying their 1999 income
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were also pressured by margin calls, with some traders
giving up on losing positions and others selling stocks to raise
cash to maintain their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long overdue re-evaluation in the new-economy stocks,''
said Alfred E. Goldman, chief strategist at A.G. Edwards in St.
Louis. But it's not a bubble being burst, he contended, just a
fairly normal downturn that ``reduces excesses and complacency''
and should prove generally beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   After the close, Advanced Micro Devices announced first-quarter
profits that surpassed the most optimistic forecasts, and its stock
climbed sharply in late trading. Wall Street has been expecting
strong profits, especially for technology companies, during the
reporting season that is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this week's carnage, analysts said some stability might
emerge in coming days if technology stocks are seen as bargains and
earnings reports, like that of Advanced Micro Devices, meet or
exceed expectations. Some, in fact, said that the stock-market
declines would slow the economy and reduce the Fed's inclination to
raise interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, ``is obviously achieving his
goal of compressing price-earnings ratios and bringing down prices
of technology'' shares, said Paul McManus, senior vice president of
Independence Investment Associates in Boston. ``There might be the
outside possibility that he might not have to raise rates again.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the Dow sank 161.95 points Wednesday after being up as
much as 138.37 points, its technology components accounted for
virtually all of it. Hewlett-Packard, Intel, and IBM were its
biggest drags while Microsoft was the fifth biggest.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen of the Dow's 30 components ended with gains, paced by
American Express, one of the many winners among financial stocks in
the session.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final-hour slump in the blue chips and other
old-economy stocks, some portfolio managers who had favored those
over technology were hoping that the playing field was becoming
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers who are suffering with good-quality stocks can
finally breathe again,'' said Hersh Cohen, a value-oriented
portfolio manager at Salomon Smith Barney. ``The laggards have
picked up. It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen added that he thought relatively few investors,
especially those in mutual funds, have yet to realize the severity
of the damage to their portfolios and that he would be ``amazed''
if there was much of a rally in the market generally within the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of a possible shift in emphasis was that a PaineWebber
analyst began coverage of Ford and General Motors, calling the
former a ``buy,'' the latter ``attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Turnover was heavy, with 1.9 billion shares traded on Nasdaq and
1.18 billion on the New York Stock Exchange. Advancing issues on
the Big Board beat declining ones by a slim margin, 1,526 to 1,481,
with 56 issues making new 52-weeks highs and 45 new lows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
