<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES EDITOR'S NOTE FOR THURSDAY, APRIL 13
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: This editor's note will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT (moved on Sunday, April 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, April 9,
reported that The New Leader, the 76-year-old political journal,
was cutting its issue schedule to every two months, from every two
weeks, and starting a Web site to fill the gap, despite the
misgivings of its editor. The headline, affixed in editing, said,
Socialist Realism Moves to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the magazine, a voice of liberal anti-Communism,
formally broke with the Socialists in 1936 and in the heyday of
Stalinism provided an outlet for Eastern European writers defying
Stalinisms decreed fashion in arts and literature - Socialist
Realism.
</P>
<P>
   The headline's attempted wordplay could only have struck the
magazine's audience as unreal.
</P>
</TEXT>
