<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-MARKET-NYT &LR;      04-12 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT STARTS NASDAQ'S DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a day, blame it on Richard Sherlund, Wall
Street's leading Microsoft analyst. He trimmed his first-quarter
revenue estimates for the big software maker, and Microsoft's stock
price fell sharply on Wednesday, taking the Nasdaq market and the
shares of most technology shares with it.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund, an analyst at Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., did not reduce his
earnings estimate for Microsoft, and he kept the company on
Goldman's recommended list.
</P>
<P>
   But his warning of lower-than-expected revenue for the quarter _
results that Microsoft will report on April 20 _ was seen as a
signal of a general slowing in the growth of the personal computer
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund revised his revenue estimates for Microsoft to $5.75
billion during the first three months of this year, down about 3
percent from his previous estimate of $5.95 billion. The slippage,
he said, was attributable to slower-than-expected growth in
Microsoft's mainstay personal-computer software products _ the
Windows operating system and Office suite of productivity
applications.
</P>
<P>
   He said Microsoft's revenue in those basic lines appeared to
have grown in the 8-to-10 percent range in the first quarter
instead of the 10-to-12 percent range that the Goldman analyst had
earlier predicted. His revision, he said, came after consulting
with his firm's other computer analysts and studying corporate
buying trends.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in the quarter, Sherlund said, was largely
attributable to the lack of purchases of new software by
corporations, which account for more than 35 percent of the overall
PC market. A key reason for the corporate slowdown, Sherlund said,
was the ``lingering lockdown'' in computer purchases related to
concerns about Year 2000 problems. The Y2K hangover, he added,
extended through February, though he added that things did seem to
have picked up in March.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate demand for servers, the hub computers that serve
up Web pages, e-mail messages and data on computer networks was
still brisk, as Internet-driven demand remained strong. And
Microsoft's fast-growing server business, Sherlund said, should be
up sharply for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the corporate market, from desktop PC's to
mainframe computers, appears to have been sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   The industrywide implications? ``Look to PCs and mainframes for
problems,'' Sherlund said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the industry is giving off contradictory signals. On
Wednesday, Advanced Micro Devices, which makes microprocessors,
chips that determine a computer's power, announced earnings that
were almost double Wall Street's expectations, along with record
revenue that topped $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The slow-growth picture, Sherlund admitted, may be contradicted
on April 18 when Intel reports its quarterly results. Its sales of
chips in the PC market for the quarter may be up 15 percent or
more. Yet, more than an indication of robust PC sales, Sherlund
said, that may be attributable to PC makers, who suffered from chip
shortages at the end of last year, adding to their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see is a Microsoft-centric view of the PC industry,''
Sherlund said.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst has had that view for some time. He was the analyst
assigned to cover Microsoft for Goldman in 1986, when the
investment bank handled Microsoft's initial public offering. His
career and reputation on Wall Street hinge on his astute analysis
of Microsoft. Last year, Sherlund was selected by Institutional
Investor magazine as the ``first team'' PC software analyst for the
sixth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlund did not reduce his quarterly earnings estimate of 41
cents a share because he says the earnings reduction of 2 cents a
share from lower revenues will be offset by increased income from
Microsoft's sizable investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the first quarter, Sherlund remains optimistic about
Microsoft. New product sales should fuel higher growth, he said,
and Microsoft's antitrust case should shift to the appeals stage by
the second half of the year. And, he added, Microsoft's prospects
on appeal can only improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've focused on for the quarter is a transient issue that
seems mostly behind the company,'' Sherlund said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft shares closed down $4.50 a share, at $79.375. Its
shares are down 32 percent from its recent high on Dec. 30.
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
