<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT PUSHES GUN CONTROL MEASURE
</HEADLINE>
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With the anniversary of the shootings at Columbine High
School a week a way, President Clinton came here on Wednesday to
intensify his public campaign for tighter gun restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any future president to have to go to Columbine
or to Springfield, Ore., or to Jonesboro, Ark., or to any of the
other places I have been,'' Clinton said at a downtown rally,
rattling off some of the sites of recent shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tough enough to comfort the families of our servicemen
and women who die in the line of duty,'' he said. ``Children have
no duties, except to their studies and their families. Our duty is
to protect their lives and give them futures.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also appeared in a televised town meeting organized by
MSNBC in which the sharp divisions on the issue of guns became
clear. The president made his pitch for more regulation, while
local politicians, police officers and prosecutors weighed in on
both sides of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Kirklin, a student who was wounded in the school shooting
in the Denver suburb of Littleton on April 20, 1999, was one who
spoke against more restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see guns jumping off the table and shooting
people,'' Kirklin said, urging more of a focus on troubled people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lent support to a proposed ballot measure in Colorado
that would require unlicensed dealers at gun shows to run
background checks of gun purchasers within three days. Clinton has
been pressing for similar legislation in the Congress to close the
so-called gun show loophole, but it has become mired in gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally staged by gun control advocates, Clinton said on
Wednesday that Colorado could send a strong message to the rest of
the country by endorsing such legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do this, you will give so much energy to people who
have been sitting around in other states like yours, thinking it
was a hopeless battle, thinking they couldn't win,'' he said. ``If
you do this, you will give enormous impetus to our efforts in
Congress to try to provide national protections.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in both parties are seeing next week's anniversary
of the Columbine shootings as an important marker in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, seeking to show that they also are moving on
a politically powerful issue, rushed a measure to a vote on Tuesday
that would reward states that adopt tougher sentences for gun
violators.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican National Committee chairman,
accused the Clinton administration of ``campaigning on the backs of
national tragedies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at ground zero of the gun debate,'' said Arnie Grossman,
a leader of a Colorado group called Sane Alternatives to the
Firearms Epidemic that is pushing for the ballot initiative. ``We
did not choose to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the president's speech, gun advocates protested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this society, everyone needs to be armed,'' said Kyna
Cheek, a college student who joined about 100 others. ``The
teachers should have been armed in Columbine. As a woman, I need to
be armed in case I'm on the wrong side of town and some guy bothers
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, there appears to be little likelihood of a quick
compromise. Different proposals passed by the House and Senate have
yet to be reconciled in conference, and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, has said that there was
no use in convening such a meeting with parties so far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and John Conyers Jr.,
D-Mich., urged Hatch in a strongly worded joint letter on Tuesday
to convene a conference meeting to resolve the dispute. But by
Wednesday, that apparent harmony was gone and Hyde, chairman of the
House Judiciary Committee, and Conyers, the committee's ranking
Democratic member, were sniping at each other.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Clinton, Hyde criticized House Democrats for
avoiding ``any compromise on gun safety legislation.'' Hyde offered
a proposal that Bruce Reed, the president's domestic policy
adviser, dismissed as a step backward.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers issued a press release accusing Hyde and his House
Republican colleagues of capitulating to the National Rifle
Association in making his latest legislative offer.
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
