<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SHEPPARD-SUIT-NYT     04-12 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPPARD-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY REJECTS INNOCENCE OF SHEPPARD IN 1954 MURDER
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ohio, Calif.)  By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than four decades after a Cleveland jury convicted Dr. Sam
Sheppard of murdering his wife in a case that transfixed America,
another Cleveland jury rejected his son's efforts to prove that his
father was innocent and had been wrongfully imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Wednesday was a victory for prosecutors who
argued that Sheppard was an adulterous playboy who bludgeoned his
wife to death to get out of an unhappy marriage. The prosecutors
belittled DNA testing that pointed to a window washer as the real
killer.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was also a setback for Sheppard's son, Sam Reese
Sheppard, who has been trying for 10 years to clear his father. The
doctor was originally convicted in 1954 and served 10 years in
prison. In 1966, he had the case overturned by the U.S. Supreme
Court on the ground of prejudicial pre-trial publicity. Sheppard
was found not guilty in a second trial but died four years later.
He always contended that a ``bushy-haired'' intruder had beaten his
wife to death in her bedroom before knocking him unconscious. The
case became the basis for the television series ``The Fugitive''
and the movie of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Reese Sheppard said that the prosecutors had been
``venomous'' in their portrayal of his father and that their
motivation was political, calling them ``a younger generation of
prosecutors trying to protect the honor of its elders.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard's lawyer, Terry Gilbert, said the prosecutors' strategy
had clearly been to turn the case into another trial of Dr.
Sheppard, attacking him ``even more aggressively'' than in the
first two trials, even though this was a civil rather than a
criminal proceeding and the roles were reversed, with the son as
the plaintiff and the prosecutors as the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   A major difficulty for Sheppard was that he had to prove to the
jury, in Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Court, that his father was
innocent, a task that requires a higher burden of proof than simply
showing that he was not guilty of murder.
</P>
<P>
   If the jury had found the father innocent, his son planned to
file suit and seek damages in the Ohio Court of Claims for wrongful
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated less than three hours after a trial that
lasted more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard, 52, of Oakland, Calif., maintained his composure as
the verdict was announced, but Gilbert, his lawyer, cried openly.
</P>
<P>
   At a short news conference after the verdict, Sheppard said,
``The Sheppard family may be bloodied, but we are unbowed. We've
been unbowed for 45 years. We'll be unbowed for all time.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, William Mason, stressed evidence that the father
had been having an affair with a laboratory technician, telling the
jury in closing arguments on Tuesday that Sheppard was a ``playboy
of the Western world'' who killed his wife, Marilyn, to get out of
an unhappy marriage, particularly after he learned she was
pregnant. ``He humiliated her in public,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason theorized that the murder weapon, which in the earlier
trials was said to be one of Dr. Sheppard's surgical knives, was a
bedside lamp. The police did not find a lamp in the bedroom, and no
murder weapon was ever introduced at any of the three trials.
</P>
<P>
   Mason also raised questions about Sheppard's motivation in
bringing the case, suggesting he was only interested in the money
he could win. ``It may just be,'' Mason said to the jury, ``that
you are being asked to award the killer's son for the killer
bludgeoning his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   The basis of Gilbert's case was that DNA testing of bloodstains
found in the bedroom of the suburban Cleveland home where Sheppard
was killed clearly showed that they did not belong to either Dr.
Sheppard or his wife, and therefore there must have been a third
person in the room who committed the murder. That person, Gilbert
argued, was Richard Eberling, a window washer who was later
convicted of the murder of a wealthy widow, Ethel Durkin, and who
was found with a ring that belonged to Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor dismissed the DNA testing as ``mumbo jumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert then pointed out to jurors that the DNA expert under
attack by the prosecutors, Dr. Mohammed Tahir, was the same expert
the Cuyahoga County Coroner's office had hired as a consultant to
help set up its own DNA laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Eberling died in 1998 in prison, where he had been serving a
life sentence for the unrelated murder. A witness who had once
worked with Eberling, Kathleen Dyal, testified that he had
confessed to her that he killed Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   One of the abiding mysteries is why the prosecutors fought so
hard. Privately, some of them had said earlier that they now
believed Sheppard was innocent and that Eberling was the real
killer. But decades after the murder, the case still divided
Cleveland, and Sheppard and his supporters maintained that some of
the earlier generation of prosecutors had brought pressure on the
current team of prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Francis Sweeney, who was an assistant prosecutor in
Sheppard's second trial, is now a justice on the Ohio Supreme
Court. He voted unsuccessfully last year to block Sheppard's
lawsuit from going forward in court. Despite his involvement in the
earlier case, he declined to recuse himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
