<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES PLAN FOR 11 SCHOOL DISTRICTS SEEKS LOCAL CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a move intended to increase local control of
education and improve student performance, the sprawling Los
Angeles Unified School District has voted to reorganize itself into
11 semiautonomous subdistricts, each with its own superintendent,
as part of a broader effort to head off more radical proposals for
breaking up the nation's second-largest public school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting here in a situation in Los Angeles where if we
don't turn around this system within the next 18 months, we're
going to be looking in the face at vouchers or breakup,'' said
Caprice Young, one of the seven school board members who voted
unanimously on Tuesday for the reorganization, which was proposed
by the district's interim superintendent, Ramon Cortines.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which officials hope to have in place by the
start of the new school year on July 1, the system's 790 schools,
35,000 teachers and 700,000 students would be reorganized into
subdistricts of 60,000 to 77,000 students that would have wide
latitude over most decisions. In addition to being under the
supervision of a general superintendent, each district would have a
local parent-community advisory council, but the elected citywide
board would still set overall policy.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for shrinking the district's 2,000-person central
office by more than 800 positions, and transferring many of these
employees to the new local districts, each with 50 to 75 schools.
About 300 jobs would be eliminated through retirements, voluntary
departures and elimination of vacant jobs. Officials project
savings of $46 million from the district's $7.7 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles schools have been plagued by a variety of
problems, including severe crowding, dismal test scores, disputes
over bilingual education and polls showing a widespread lack of
public confidence. At the same time, the system is facing
contentious contract negotiations with its teachers union, and on
Tuesday the board voted to approve a 6 percent raise, with merit
pay for teachers who improved their students' scores on
standardized tests. The union is seeking a 21 percent raise and
bitterly opposes merit pay.
</P>
<P>
   Cortines, a former schools chief in New York City and San
Francisco, was chosen last year to head the district temporarily,
pending a nationwide search for a permanent superintendent. But
since taking control in January, he has moved aggressively to
reorganize the district and has placed new emphasis on improving
reading skills. Cortines will appoint the district superintendents
from a list of finalists recommended by local community panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan gives local district superintendents the authority
to make decisions by giving them control of their budget,''
Cortines said in proposing the plan last month.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders of groups advocating a formal breakup of the
district said Cortines' proposal fell short.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Thomas, co-chairman of Finally Restoring Excellence in
Education, a citizens' group that is backing a ballot initiative to
create two new independent districts in the San Fernando Valley,
said: ``Local control would still be at the whim of every new
school board. It's a nice try, but it doesn't go far enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
