<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-GORE-PARDON-1STLD-WRI     04-12 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PARDON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT WILL NOT REQUEST OR TAKE PARDON, GORE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Tightens lead, adds Bush quote at end of story) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON President Clinton will neither request nor accept a
pardon from his successor for any possible crimes committed in
office, Vice President Al Gore said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question at an appearance before the American
Society of Newspaper Editors, Gore said Clinton had made his views
on the matter clear during the impeachment investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton is way ahead of you on this,'' Gore said.
``He said publicly some time ago that he would neither request nor
accept a pardon, so that's the answer to that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's remark Wednesday morning, Clinton has never
publicly addressed the question of a pardon. The White House said
the issue was raised in the House Judiciary Committee's impeachment
hearings in December 1998. Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, asked Charles
Ruff, the White House counsel, if he could assure the committee
that Clinton would not pardon himself or accept a pardon from a
successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Ruff replied.
</P>
<P>
   The question of a presidential pardon arose after recent
statements by Robert Ray, the independent counsel, who said he had
hired additional prosecutors and was considering whether to indict
Clinton after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Ray replaced Kenneth Starr last October as the investigator for
matters relating to Whitewater and Monica Lewinsky. The independent
counsel's office reported to Congress in 1998 that it believed
Clinton had committed perjury, obstruction of justice and witness
tampering in the Lewinsky affair. Most scholars contend that there
is no legal or constitutional bar to pursuing criminal charges
against Clinton when he is no longer protected by the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said earlier this
week that Clinton would not pardon himself before he left office to
escape prosecution by Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the president and vice president said today that they
did not know of any conversations between the two men about a
possible pardon.
</P>
<P>
   There is some debate among legal scholars over whether a
president can pardon himself. Some say that he cannot, on the
principle that a judge cannot preside over his own trial. Others
say that the pardon power in the Constitution is absolute and
extends to a president granting himself a pardon in advance of any
criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   But mindful of the political firestorm that followed President
Gerald Ford's pardon of President Richard Nixon after Nixon's
resignation in 1974 _ and Ford's defeat at the polls two years
later _ several scholars and commentators said it was unlikely that
Gore would risk such a move to protect Clinton from any legal
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not proper to do it,'' said Akhil Reed Amar, a law
professor at Yale Law School. ``Yu can't be a judge in your own
case. It's a long-standing principle of Anglo-American
jurisprudence.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Amar added, ``it just doesn't pass the smell test.''
</P>
<P>
   Amar and other scholars said that if Clinton was to pardon
himself, Congress could find that action an impeachable offense,
although he would likely do it in the final days of his term in
office.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore did not absolutely rule out granting Clinton a
pardon, such a prospect is remote, several observers said. And even
if he did offer Clinton a pardon, Clinton could refuse it because
it would imply an admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said he understood that Nixon's acceptance of his pardon as
a confession of sorts, but Nixon said it meant no such thing and
maintained his innocence after his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Lacovara, who served as counsel to the Watergate special
prosecutor in 1974, said he took the statements of Gore and
Clinton's lawyers and spokesmen with a bit of skepticism. No one
can predict the political climate after the November election or
the public reaction should Ray charge Clinton with crimes next
year. Gore's statements Wednesday could quickly become, to use the
Watergate-era word, ``inoperative,'' Lacovara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were signals by Ford and Nixon, right up to the time the
pardon was issued, that neither of them had an interest in a
pardon,'' Lacovara said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility of a pardon for Clinton, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, the likely Republican presidential nominee, said
through a spokesman Wednesday that ``President Clinton has already
said he will not seek a pardon, and I take him at his word.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
