<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-LANNY13-COX     04-12 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LANNY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lanny Wadkins recalls key moments on Champion Course at PGA
National
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ If you want a quick primer on the
history of golf on the Champion Course at PGA National, just spend
a few minutes with Lanny Wadkins.
</P>
<P>
   Wadkins serves as a walking time line for the two most
significant events played on this course _ the 1983 Ryder Cup and
the 1987 PGA Championship. He was a central character both weeks
with decidedly different results.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, he hit a sand wedge to within 1 foot on the 18th hole
to ensure the Americans would not become the first team in Ryder
Cup history that failed to win on home soil.
</P>
<P>
   How memorable was that shot? ``I remember I kissed the divot,''
said Jack Nicklaus, who was the United States' captain.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Wadkins was walking down the adjacent 10th
fairway in a playoff with Larry Nelson for the PGA title. That
finish wasn't as memorable for Wadkins as he missed the green with
an 8-iron, then a 6-foot par putt to lose to Nelson in the
highest-scoring (and hottest) PGA ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it as a good result and a bad result,''
Wadkins said. ``They were both pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadkins gets one last chance to play The Champion, starting
today, before the PGA Seniors' Championship leaves PGA National
after this week. But before looking ahead, here's a look back:
</P>
<P>
   THE 1983 RYDER CUP
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup matches didn't figure to provide much drama when
they were held Oct. 14-16. The Americans had won six matches in a
row and hadn't lost the biennial competition since 1957.
</P>
<P>
   But the '83 Ryder Cup was competitive from opening day, with
Europe taking a 4 1/2-3 1/2 lead. The Americans tied it at eight
points after Day 2 heading into the 12 singles matches, supposedly
the U.S.'s strength.
</P>
<P>
   With Nick Faldo and Bernhard Langer winning their matches early
and Seve Ballesteros earning a tie with Fuzzy Zoeller after a
brilliant 240-yard, 3-wood from a bunker on the 18th hole, it
became obvious to Wadkins his match with Jose Maria Canizares _
they were the day's third-to-last pairing _ was going to play a key
role in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Canizares had a one-up lead through 15 holes when he hit his
approach shot at the par-4 16th hole into the water and Wadkins had
a 12-foot birdie putt. Canizares hit his ball out of the edge of
the lake and holed a 30-foot par putt, then Wadkins missed his to
keep the Spaniard in front. At No. 17, Wadkins made a 6-foot par
putt to keep his match alive.
</P>
<P>
   After Wadkins hit his second shot at No. 18 came word that Tom
Watson had beat Bernard Gallacher, meaning the United States had
clinched at least a tie to retain the cup with the
Wadkins-Canizares match the lone one remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we would have tied if I lost, but that's kind of like
kissing your sister when she's ugly,'' Wadkins said.
</P>
<P>
   With teammates and the captains from both squads lining the 18th
fairway, each player prepared to hit their vital approach shots.
Canizares, playing first, hit his wedge a little fat and it landed
on the front edge, about 30 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad at myself, because I knew how important that shot
was,'' Canizares said. ``I always aim at the flag, but there I just
hit it on the green.''
</P>
<P>
   With the hole 72 yards away, Wadkins reached for his sand wedge.
The notorious fast player didn't allow much time for the pressure
to build any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of on automatic at that point,'' he said. ``One of
the best things I do is play quick when I get that much pressure, I
don't have a lot of time to think about what the consequences are
if I screw up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably as nervous hitting that shot as any shot in my
life. It was not just for me, it was for a lot of other guys, I
know Nicklaus didn't want to be the first captain not to win on
American soil.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball went directly at the pin and plopped a mere 12 inches
away as the American players started hugging and kissing each other
in a wild celebration scene that was so uncommon for professional
golf at the time. Wadkins pumped his right fist, then later used
that hand to congratulate Canizares after he missed the long birdie
putt and the Americans had clinched another Ryder Cup victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the highlights of my career,'' Wadkins said.
</P>
<P>
   THE 1987 PGA
</P>
<P>
   Every player remembers the 1987 PGA Championship for two things:
Sweltering temperatures and awful greens that conspired to produce
the highest winning score (287) in the 42 years the PGA has been
contested by stroke play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly wasn't a putting contest,'' Nelson said. ``Except for
the last hole.''
</P>
<P>
   A Wadkins held the first-round lead after a 68, but it was
Bobby, Lanny's younger brother. Lanny shared the halfway lead with
Raymond Floyd before he shot 74 and entered the final round a shot
behind Mark McCumber and D.A. Weibring.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than a half-dozen players with a chance to win
on the back nine Sunday, with Nelson, both Wadkins, McCumber,
Weibring, Scott Hoch, Don Pooley and Ben Crenshaw in the mix. Lanny
Wadkins
</P>
<P>
   moved into a share of the lead with a birdie at the par-3 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was one shot back until he appeared to get a huge break
at the par-3 17th, according to Wadkins. ``Nelson had about a
25-footer at 17 and he asked Crenshaw to move his coin,'' Wadkins
said. ``He pulled his putt, it hit the coin and went into the
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly true, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never pulled it,'' he said. ``The greens were so bad, I told
my caddie I needed to roll it right over his dime. It was one of
those putts that actually went right where I aimed it. The ball
rolled right over the coin, It stayed right on line and it didn't
knock it off line.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Wadkins came to the 18th fairway tied with Nelson for
the lead, knowing a birdie would earn him his second PGA 10 years
after he had defeated Gene Littler in a playoff at Pebble Beach.
This time, there would be no 18th-hole magic. Wadkins' sand wedge
landed 25 feet from the pin and he two-putted for the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have had the replay of the '83 shot.'' Wadkins
said.
</P>
<P>
   The playoff started and ended on the 10th hole, which at the
time was a nondescript par-4 (it has since been changed to a
par-5). Both players hit the fairway and had short irons to the
green.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's approach ran through the green and finished in the
rough. Wadkins punched an 8-iron that hit on the edge of the green
and it kicked into the rough. Nelson's chip rolled about 12 feet by
and Wadkins was faced with a 6-footer before the putting contest
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry made and I missed,'' Wadkins said. ``It was pretty
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
