<SLUG> BC-EBOND-ENTREPRENEURS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIR UNITE TO SELL BONDS ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They are 26 and 28, friends since their undergraduate
days at MIT. One is a bond guru. The other has already built and
sold a Web company, for $100 million. Together, they're taking on
Wall Street's bond giants, in a bid to become the eBay of
fixed-income trading.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Robertson and Sam Choi are launching their company,
Visible Markets, in downtown Boston, with big-name venture backers.
Fresh from Amazon.com and Lehman brothers, they are the first in
the business to try to bring complex mortgage-bond trading to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the realm of day traders. Visible Markets will be an
auction site for big investors, like mutual funds, banks and
brokerage firms _ not for individual investors. The institutions
that deal in mortgage securities trade $16 trillion of them a year.
That's about the size of the equity markets combined. And it's more
than the outstanding debt of the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The sector is as arcane as it is big.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage-backed securities are bonds that banks and mortgage
companies create when they sell home mortgages in the secondary
market, for example. The biggest reason they're not yet traded on
the Web, bond experts say, is because of their complexity.
</P>
<P>
   But big investors seem ready to make the leap _ as long as
there's enough activity on the site that they can get good prices
on their trades.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Feeney, who oversees $1.6 billion as a partner and senior
fixed-income portfolio manager with Boston Partners Asset
Management, said online bond trading is becoming a valid option.
``The name of the game is to obtain the best price for a
security,'' he said. ``As pricing, trading and execution improve,
the client benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, if a big investor wants to buy a $20 million bond, calls
are made to several brokers. The buyer waits to hear back, then
picks the best price, makes the trade and files paper trade slips.
</P>
<P>
   Visible Markets says it can reduce the transaction time
significantly, and ease the paperwork. The buyer would go to the
site and set a time for an auction that day. Potential sellers
would then have time to research the bond for sale and log in for
the auction. The transaction gets done with the click of a button
and all the accounting paperwork would be sent electronically to
the parties involved.
</P>
<P>
   Visible Markets has hired 45 people, among them some well-known
bond veterans. Stephen Boxer, a bond manager for State Street
Global Advisors, joined the firm as marketing chief after hearing
the founders' pitch to lure State Street as a client. Other new
hires hail from ABN Amro, Merrill Lynch and Boston's Independence
Investment Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a recruiting machine,'' said Bill Kaiser, a general
partner with Greylock Management, the Boston venture capital firm
that's putting $9 million into Visible Markets, in its first formal
round of financing. The sense of urgency is key, he said: ``If you
don't move fast, you're roadkill.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, who is chief executive of Visible Markets, couldn't
get venture funding from Greylock for his first business. When he
started PlanetAll in Cambridge _ an online datebook and address
book _ in 1996, he said, ``We had to go to about 100 VC firms.''
Ultimately CMGI Inc.'s (at)Ventures fund gave him the nod.
</P>
<P>
   With PlanetAll's success under his belt _ he sold the company to
Amazon.com for $100 million in stock, which is now worth about $500
million _ Greylock was happy to comply this time. Robertson stayed
in touch with Kaiser from his last go-round, and the venture
capitalist admits to a soft spot for his fellow MIT alumni.
</P>
<P>
   And Robertson did something unusual. He put up $3 million of his
own money in this round of financing.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kaiser, ``A lot of guys wouldn't necessarily be putting
their money where their mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has a dozen employees out taking their broker's
exams. The firm is awaiting approval for its own broker/dealer
license and hopes to be live by the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They need to move fast. The top Wall Street shops got together
in 1998 to back TradeWeb.com, an online exchange for Treasury
bills, notes and bonds. The biggest bond traders in the business,
Salomon Smith Barney, Merrill Lynch, Goldman Sachs and and Credit
Suisse First Boston, have done $1 trillion of trades on the site
since. The group is testing government agency bonds now. But
they've not yet ventured into mortage-backed bonds. Bloomberg,
whose system is widely used by bond investors, also recently
launched an online bond trading program.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kaiser, ``If you can be known first, then it's that much
harder for the next one to be successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
