<HEADLINE>
RANGERS YANKED BACK TO FAMILIAR REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This time, at least the plot was better, filled with
twists and intrigue in almost every inning. Unlike six months ago
in the playoffs, the Rangers did battle the New York Yankees and
did score runs.
</P>
<P>
   But the ending was still the same. The Rangers still die in the
end, but this time it was more their own doing than because of the
Yankees' vaunted pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Having failed early to pummel struggling Yankees pitcher David
Cone, the Rangers saw a fifth-inning breakdown by Darren Oliver and
a seventh-inning breakdown by their left-handed relievers cost them
in an 8-6 loss at Yankee Stadium yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had a 2-0 lead in the fifth and a 6-5 lead in the
seventh, but a three-run homer by Bernie Williams and a two-run
triple by Tino Martinez allowed the Yankees to prevail in their
home opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same old New York,'' Rangers second baseman Luis Alicea said,
shaking his head. ``Seems like every time we get close, we can't
put them away.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss makes the numbers more gruesome. The Rangers are 11-33
against the Yankees since Game 1 of the 1996 divisional playoffs
and 8-29 in New York since the start of the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very well today,'' first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro said. ``We had some chances to score some runs and didn't,
and we didn't play very good defense. We gave 'em some runs, and
that probably cost us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver was probably as frustrated as anybody in the Rangers'
clubhouse, trying to figure out afterward how a well-pitched game
turned into such a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to hold a 2-0 lead, Oliver gave up a leadoff single to
Roberto Kelly to start the bottom of the fifth inning. He got
Alfonso Soriano to pop out, but Chuck Knoblauch hit another high
pop that dropped for a single in short left, and Derek Jeter
followed with a bloop single to right, scoring Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill popped out, but Oliver left a changeup over the
plate to Williams and saw it smacked over the left-center-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver had his way with us before Bernie hit that home run,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A flare here, a flare there,'' Oliver said. ``Just long enough
to keep the inning alive and bring Bernie up. I felt fine. I was
making good pitches all day and doing what I wanted to do. Even the
pitch to Bernie. I wanted to throw a changeup there, it just
drifted back over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run aroused the crowd and brought the playoff
atmosphere back to Yankee Stadium. But, temporarily at least, the
Rangers refused to give in.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer hit a two-run double in the sixth to tie the score,
and, after Greer dropped a fly ball to give the Yankees a run, the
Rangers scratched home two more runs in the seventh with the help
of Ruben Mateo's surprising sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   But the bullpen couldn't hold the 6-5 lead. Manager Johnny Oates
brought in Mike Munoz to face the Yankees' big left-handed hitters,
and it didn't work. O'Neill and Williams singled off him, Tino
Martinez smacked a two-run triple, and Ricky Ledee later hit a
two-out single to right off Mike Venafro to give the Yankees an 8-6
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching wasn't sterling, but the Rangers, despite scoring
six runs, were still lamenting afterward about their inability to
hammer Cone early. Cone allowed 10 of the first 20 batters he faced
to reach base through four innings, but the Rangers managed only
two runs in that span. They hit into two double plays, Gabe Kapler
was thrown out trying to steal, and Mateo struck out with the bases
loaded to end the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just something we have to overcome,'' Greer said.
``The past history is we usually play solid baseball against these
guys, but we haven't been able to put them away. We don't get a hit
at the right time. The only way to change that is to go out and win
a few games.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
