<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-DOMINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND LEAD IN COLLEGE DOMINANCE SLIPPING, SURVEY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New England's dominance in US higher education is
eroding, as the region's share of both college students and federal
research money declines, compared to other booming regions,
according to a survey by the New England Board of Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   The region, long a national center for higher education, can
still boast one dubious distinction: It continues to be home to the
nation's most expensive public and private colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which will be released later this month, says
enrollment at New England's nearly 280 colleges has dropped from a
peak of 827,293 students in 1992 to 795,317 in 1997, and board
officials believe that number has dropped further in the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The six states' share of the nation's total college enrollment
has fallen from 6.4 percent in the mid-1980s to 5.5 percent in 1997
and is estimated to be below that today. (About 5 percent of the US
population lives in New England.)
</P>
<P>
   The decline is partly due to the region's slow population
growth, board officials said. That's the same trend that has cost
Massachusetts two seats in Congress since the 1980s, while states
such as California and Florida have gained seats.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, schools in other parts of the country increasingly
offer cheaper alternatives, officials stressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a historical view of opportunities in America, there are
just more people going to schools in the South and West,'' said
John Harney, executive editor of the board's Connection magazine.
``Students now have more choices in going to schools in other parts
of the countries. It's also usually less expensive to go to school
there.''
</P>
<P>
   New England is also losing its share of research and development
money from the federal government, though the region continues to
lead the nation in such grants. According to the report, New
England institutions' share of research and development money from
Washington has fallen from 10 percent in 1983 to 8.1 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   However, even with a boom in scientific programs at schools in
states such as Florida, Texas, and California, the region received
$2 billion in academic research and development projects. That
leads the nation, at $153 per capita, compared to $96 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   New England colleges and universities are still attracting
record numbers of applicants. But a history of low public support
for higher education has made New England's colleges and
universities the nation's most costly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite five years of tuition cuts for state residents at
Massachusetts public colleges, New England's public four-year
universities charged state residents $4,619 in average tuition and
required fees between 1999 and 2000, compared to a national average
of $3,356, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year private institutions in Connecticut, Maine,
Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island, and Vermont charged
students $19,710 in average tuition and fees, while universities
around the country on average charged $15,380, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, according to the board's ``Facts 2000'' report,
the average tuition and fees have increased by $1,800 at public
campuses and by more than $7,800 at the region's private
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Although there may be a variety of reasons why New England's
colleges and universities are more expensive, the clearest
explanation comes from the region's historical lack of state
support for higher education, Harney said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the 1997 fiscal year, the six New England states
all ranked in the bottom 10 in higher education appropriations as a
share of state tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   While state support for higher education in New England exceeded
$2.2 billion in fiscal 2000, the money amounted to only $169 per
capita, compared to a national average of $209, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, for better or worse, New England has chosen
that higher education not be a taxpayer burden and that the burden
should instead fall on the shoulders of students,'' Harney said.
</P>
<P>
   New England's scientific preeminence and consistent ability to
attract federal funds arises from its role as a center of
expertise, which the government has drawn on since World War II,
Harney said.
</P>
<P>
   New England's universities still depend on Washington for
research money, according to the report. Sixty-nine percent of the
region's university research dollars come from the federal
government, compared to 58 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much of the population has moved to the West and to the
South, so has much of the political representation,'' Harney said.
``That helps those regions draw more of the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the region's eroding lead in other areas, New England
continues to attract students from elsewhere. According to the
report, 25 percent of freshmen enrolled at New England campuses
come from other states, up from 20 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 5 percent are international students, many from
Pacific Rim Countries, the report said. Foreign enrollment
reportedly has jumped 45 percent alone in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   New England's colleges and universities, however, have had less
success in attracting minority enrollment. New England's
approximately 78,000 African-Americans, Latinos, and Native
American students represent 10 percent of the region's student
population, though they account for 14 percent of the region's 18-
to 24-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, African-American, Native American, and Latino
enrollment has increased significantly, rising 38 percent, 41
percent, and 54 percent respectively in New England from 1990 to
1997, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means, I think, is there's still a lot of cachet
that goes along with going to college in New England,'' Harney
said. ``But we also haven't done as good a job as we could in areas
such as recruiting minorities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
