u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-RENO-NYT     04-12 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-RENO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO MAKES CUBAN BOY CASE A PERSONAL CRUSADE 
</HEADLINE>
 (With CUBAN-BOY) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The custody battle over Elian Gonzalez has thrust
Attorney General Janet Reno into what is most likely to be one of
her last starring roles as she returned to her hometown of Miami on
Wednesday in a gesture that transformed a Justice Department legal
fight into a one-woman crusade.
</P>
<P>
   The case has seemingly energized the 62-year-old Reno in the
final year of her stewardship at the Justice Department. At
considerable risk to her credibility and reputation, she began a
personal mission Wednesday to reunite Elian with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Associates said that Reno went to Miami because she feels
comfortable in the fiery politics and passions that have swirled
through Miami's Cuban-American community since 6-year-old Elian was
pulled from the Atlantic Ocean off of Florida on Thanksgiving after
fleeing Cuba with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, they said, Reno made the trip to show that she is
willing to take every conceivable step to resolve the issue
peacefully. They added that she wanted to underscore the point that
she had tried every reasonable approach, in case a subsequent law
enforcement action by the immigration service is necessary to take
custody of the child.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the associates said, Elian's case, in contrast to
seemingly endless partisan squabbles with Congress, has presented
her with a powerful issue to demonstrate that she can be what she
hoped to be from the start _ a forceful advocate for children.
</P>
<P>
   But her trip remains a gamble. If she succeeds in returning to
Washington with Elian without provoking an outburst from Miami's
Cuban-American community, it would represent an achievement for the
Justice Department. But it would be an even bigger boost for Reno's
standing, seriously depleted after years of bloody battles with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   However, if she returns without the boy, or if her presence
sparks demonstrations that frustrate legal efforts to transfer
custody of the boy to his father, it would serve as a stunning
personal blow to the attorney general, leaving her perhaps
irreversibly damaged as she enters the final months of her tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dangers, her associates said she has thrown herself
into the case with a vigor _ deciding nearly a week ago that she
would fly to Miami if the opportunity arose. They said she has
worked on the case like an entry-level lawyer, poring over briefs
and carefully monitoring the negotiations involving the Justice
Department, Cuban officials and representatives of the Elian's
Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Her working style has shifted to accommodate her interest in the
case. Reno, who has often annoyed her aides by her inability to
turn over even minor issues to subordinates, in recent days has
delegated much of her workload. That has allowed her to concentrate
on Elian, sometimes spending entire days riveted on the legal
strategy in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, even her public demeanor has loosened up, in
contrast to her often pinched and uncommunicative presence at her
weekly news conferences. Instead, she has been a forceful and
voluble advocate for the Justice Department, pressing for what she
has said the law unequivocally requires, the speedy reunification
of Elian and his father.
</P>
<P>
   She told reporters that she had been deeply moved by her meeting
last week with Gonzalez, a session that aides said had confirmed in
her mind the wisdom of granting the father custody, even if it
meant sending the child back to Cuba, whose government Reno has
been careful to criticize as a dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's aides said her expression of such sentiments reflect her
confidence that she has stayed in touch with the Cuban-American
community and the politics that shaped her and Miami during the 15
years she prevailed there as a local prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   She still reads The Miami Herald daily and has kept up with
rising and falling fortunes of local politicians. She remains
fearless that her personal presence will calm a potentially
volatile population, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reno has experienced first hand the violence that can
erupt in the cross hairs of law and politics. In 1980, as the state
attorney for Miami-Dade County, Reno watched as the city erupted in
a riot after prosecutors in her office failed to win a conviction
against four white police officers charged with the beating death
of black insurance salesman.
</P>
<P>
   But her decision to go to Miami reflects a deeper longing that
has stirred her ever since she became attorney general, her
associates said, a desire to demonstrate that federal law can be
used on behalf of children and families _ a promise that her
critics have complained has resulted in better speeches than
programs at the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's efforts in behalf of children have sometimes gone awry.
Early in Reno's career at the Justice Department, she gave the
final go ahead for the tear gas assault in April 1993 at Waco _ in
part because of reports of child abuse inside the Branch Davidian
compound.
</P>
<P>
   But the tear-gas operation, which was supposed to allow those
inside to flee, instead ended in a deadly fire in which some 80
people, including many children were killed _ a disaster that Reno
once said she thinks about every day.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's case has provided Reno with a clear-cut example of how
the attorney general can exercise power to improve the life of a
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always talking about wanting to save a one child a
time,'' one government official said. ``Here's a real chance to
save one little boy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
