u s BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     04-12 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD GUARD LIFTS SLUGGISH YANKEES TO HOME OPENER VICTORY OVER
RANGERS, 8-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The new championship banner climbed the flagpole at
Yankee Stadium, curling in the frigid gusts of spring, and the
Yankees stood along the first-base line for a few moments Wednesday
and could reflect on the accomplishments of last summer. Then they
dispersed to their dugout for the first home game of the 2000
season, a revised roster facing new problems and obstacles,
starting all over.
</P>
<P>
   The solutions remain the same for the Yankees. One week into the
season, they aren't playing like a juggernaut that has won
consecutive championships; they are grasping for hits and runs and
pitching consistency. But it's a team capable of willing itself
into victory on days when it has the look of a loser, and Wednesday
the Yankees played poorly before pulling out an 8-6 victory over
the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, the center fielder, slammed a three-run homer
in the fifth inning and the first baseman, Tino Martinez, had a
double, single and triple. A crowd of 48,487, diminished by
no-shows who likely would have filled Yankee Stadium Tuesday if not
for the postponement of the home opener, waited in 44-degree
weather through a game of 3 hours 33 minutes. Wrappers and bags
loosely showered the field, swept by a cold wind. It was a nasty
day, a long, ugly game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play long, ugly-looking games,'' said David Cone, the
Yankees' starting pitcher, who was charged with four runs in
five-plus innings. ``But we win of lot of games like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no subtle mastery, no acute opening day strokes to be
admired in memory by middle-aged fans two generations from now.
This was strictly paint-by-the-numbers with thick crayons. Cone
required 40 pitches to get through the third inning, after his
catcher, Jorge Posada, took off his mask, turned and argued
face-to-face with the home plate umpire, Tim Timmins. The Yankees'
bullpen was charged with two blown saves in two innings. A Yankee
third baseman made an error for the third consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   As they often did in the first week of the season, the Yankees'
hitters worked themselves into favorable ball-strike counts before
squandering opportunities: In the fourth inning, Williams grounded
to short with the count 3-1, Shane Spencer popped out on a 3-0
pitch and Posada hit a weak bounder on two balls and no strikes.
</P>
<P>
   These flaws are not isolated, a few mistakes on one bad day. The
Yankees have not played well in their first seven games, their
defense erratic, their offense sporadic, the starting pitching
responsible for an epidemic of base runners. Cone, Clemens and Andy
Pettitte have started five games collectively and none has been
credited with a victory. ``We're not clicking on all cylinders
where we are into the swing of things,'' said Derek Jeter.
``Hopefully, we'll get something going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees looked inert in the early innings, and felt the same
way, as if they all needed a good dose of caffeine. It was cold and
windy, the bunting on the facade whipping in the wind and breaking
free of the long ropes used to tie it down. It was a perfect day to
hibernate, and for four innings, the Yankees looked dormant. ``It's
like when you're feeling lazy,'' said Ricky Ledee, the left
fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Something almost always pushes them through the sluggishness,
however, a collective will or a sense of responsibility, and time
and again over the last few years, they have revived themselves to
win games like this. As they returned to the dugout to bat in the
bottom of the fifth inning, trailing 2-0, somebody yelled ``Let's
go!'' _ words echoed by others, Ledee said, until they were all
yelling, all contributing to a din.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Kelly, who had 1 hit in his first 11 at-bats this
season, singled to center field off the Rangers' Darren Oliver, and
two batters later, Chuck Knoblauch lifted a looper over the head of
shortstop Royce Clayton and in front of the outfielders, the ball
falling into a triangle of Rangers. First and second, one out.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter was next, trying and failing to check his swing at one
pitch over his head. He fouled off a two-strike pitch, worked the
count to 3 balls and 2 strikes and dumped a single into right
field. Kelly scored, Knoblauch stopped at third. Jeter later spoke
of the at-bat with seeming embarrassment, but he kept the inning
going.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, who drove the offense in the first week of the
season, popped high in the infield, and carried his bat with him as
he trudged toward first, appalled. Two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Williams followed O'Neill to the plate; they are playing
together for their seventh season. ``We've got such a close-knit
group,'' said O'Neill, ``and a lot of that is because we've been
together so long. Everybody knows what it feels like to not come
through. Everybody knows what a great feeling it is to pick up a
teammate after that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver meant to throw Williams a fastball over the outside
corner, to the target set by the Texas catcher, Ivan Rodriguez, but
his pitch drifted over the middle of the plate and Williams
hammered it, the ball landing in the netting over the fence in
left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way to pick me up,'' O'Neill said to Williams in the Yankees'
dugout, but in fact, Williams had lifted all of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   They were ahead, 4-2, but blew that lead, and after
re-establishing a lead of 5-4, they blew that as well, falling
behind, 6-5, in the top of the seventh inning. Mike Munoz, who is
part of a Ranger pitching staff rebuilt with left-handers almost
specifically designed to combat the Yankees' left-handed hitters,
entered the game to pitch to O'Neill in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill pulled a single to right, however. Williams smacked a
single to center, O'Neill pausing as neared second, and then
speeding around the bag, taking third. Martinez came to bat,
already with two hits against left-handed pitchers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   When he faces a succession of left-handers, Martinez tends to
keep his front shoulder tucked in, rather than jumping out
anxiously. He had 2 hits in 10 prior at-bats against Munoz, but
this time, he lined a ball into the right-center field gap. O'Neill
scored, Williams sprinted around third and scored, and Martinez
slid into third, the Yankees leading again, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, a blast of wind hit the upper deck and
littered the field with a blizzard of paper, drawing a cheer from
the crowd. The temperature dropped rapidly, Posada said, ``like 20
degrees.'' Mariano Rivera took the mound in the ninth, froze out
the Rangers and the Yankees escaped to the clubhouse, somehow
taking a victory with them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
