<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take flag off Statehouse, S.C. Senate says
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A new era in remembering the old Confederacy
emerged Wednesday as the South Carolina Senate approved 36-7 a bill
to remove the controversial Confederate flag from atop the
Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which still must be approved by the state House,
came on the 139th anniversary of the attack on federal troops at
Fort Sumter in Charleston that started the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, worked out by pro-flag and anti-flag forces in the
Senate, would move the battle emblem to a Confederate soldiers'
monument in front of the Capitol. It looks destined to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our flag got abused,'' Sen. Glenn McConnell (R-Charleston)
told colleagues Wednesday evening. ``It got taken by politicians
and got used for racial causes. It got taken by hate groups who
stained it with their hands by taking it for their causes. But
that's not the long-term legacy of that flag. It doesn't belong for
that. And it communicates negative things to part of our population
because of those who misused it.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, who runs a Civil War memorabilia shop, has been a
crucial player in the apparent compromise. Senators applauded his
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Another key player was Sen. Darrell Jackson (D-Columbia), a
member of the black legislative caucus. He kept members of the
NAACP, whose push for an economic boycott brought embarrassment to
the state, apprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had not been for the NAACP,'' Jackson said, ``maybe we
would not be here and it would be another generation 10 years from
now who would be fighting this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of flag supporters, many from Charleston, sang
``Dixie'' while waiting to get in the Senate gallery after a lunch
recess.
</P>
<P>
   Looking up to the lobby balconies from below, Sen. Arthur
Ravenel (R-Mount Pleasant), who had called the debate
``Armageddon'' for the dignity of the battle emblem, waved to
supporters and urged a reprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of his favorite songs,'' said Jacqueline Lear of
Charleston, who helped start the singing of ``Dixie.'' ``He keeps
telling us, `I'm for you. You be for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
