<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUJIMORI APPEARS TO FALL SHORT OF FIRST-ROUND VICTORY IN PERU
ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ President Alberto Fujimori on Wednesday fell just
short of reaching a first-round victory in his re-election bid,
meaning that a runoff will be held by early June, a surprise
development that elated the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The government announcement set off euphoria in the streets,
where news of a Fujimori victory was awaited. Such a victory would
probably have brought violence and made his administration an
international pariah and the source of constant instability, given
the criticism of the election's fairness at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   With 97.68 percent of the official vote counted, authorities
said on Wednesday night, Fujimori's total official vote count rose
a bit, to 49.84 percent, tantalizingly close to the needed 50
percent. But election officials said there were too few uncounted
votes outstanding and that Fujimori could only hope to add at most
five-hundredths of 1 percent to his result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The democratic forces have triumphed!'' Alejandro Toledo,
Fujimori's leading opponent, shouted from a balcony overlooking
tens of thousands of supporters in the San Martin Plaza in downtown
Lima. Waving a flag and flashing a victory sign, he added, ``Our
people have won despite all the games and tricks. On to the second
round!''
</P>
<P>
   Election officials said on Wednesday night that Toledo won 40.31
percent of the vote, in the latest count. A candidate needed more
than 50 percent to win outright in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement of victory for Fujimori would have put Peru on a
collision course with the United States and the Organization of
American States, both of which said that quick counts after
Sunday's election indicated that neither candidate had won, and
that a second round would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   When the results trickled in this week, and election monitors
raised many charges of improprieties, diplomats at the Organization
of American States already had begun discussing economic and
political sanctions to reverse the vote, and if necessary to strip
the government of its recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a business school professor, this week said he would
accept nothing short of a runoff and promised to lead nonstop
demonstrations culminating in a national strike on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori had no immediate comment on Wednesday night. Toledo
boasted that it was the two days of demonstrations that stopped
Fujimori from stealing the election, and that the mostly peaceful
marches across Peru had moved the international community to back
democracy here.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Portillo, the head of the national election commission,
dismissed that claim, telling the news media that reports of
computer and vote fraud were proved false by the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can think what you like,'' Portillo said. ``It was
impossible to falsify or adulterate the results.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo repeated his demand on Wednesday night that all the
networks open their airwaves to the opposition, and that dirty
campaign tricks be halted.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics, like microphones that went dead at opposition
rallies, egg-throwing mobs meeting opposition candidates, and smear
campaigns orchestrated in the press, came under intense criticism
by the Organization of American States and the Atlanta-based Carter
Center and several international election observer teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we will show the world that Peru can hold a clean
process,'' Toledo told the throng in downtown Lima on Wednesday
night, one of many that gathered expectantly in cities across Peru.
``I want to be clear that I will be respectful of the institutions
of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   International pressure on Fujimori to hold a second round of
voting rather than declare an outright majority in the first round
mounted through the day.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Pickering, the U.S. under secretary of state for
political affairs, telephoned Prime Minister Alberto Bustamante to
say that U.S. relations with Peru would be seriously strained if a
second round was not held.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conversations have been stark but decent,'' a State
Department official said. ``There is no doubt in our minds they
know the way we feel.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambassadors of France, Britain and several other European
nations also said there was enough evidence of voter fraud _
including pre-marked ballots and a series of unexplained counting
delays _ to require a second round to ensure the credibility of the
next government.
</P>
<P>
   But senior Latin American diplomats here expressed concern that
the tough language by Pickering and other American officials might
be having a negative effect. Several Cabinet officials complained
openly of blatant interference in Peru's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The United States stand ``has triggered a very nationalistic
reaction,'' one Latin American diplomat said, adding, ``There is
very strong resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lima government appeared to be testing a nationalist
response to the international pressures when Fujimori's running
mate, Francisco Tudela, scolded foreign governments and media on
Tuesday night for conspiring to ignore the will of the Peruvian
people and push an election result to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had this kind of international intervention in our
political process before,'' Tudela said in a television interview,
which was repeatedly broadcast on a pro-government channel on
Wednesday. ``We are not a banana republic. We Peruvians need to
defend our national sovereignty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
