<HEADLINE>
LEFT-HANDERS WEREN'T RIGHT SOLUTIONS FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rangers expect to have a strong bullpen, mainly
because they have two All-Stars in right-handers Jeff Zimmerman and
John Wetteland, and two other hard-throwing right-handers in Tim
Crabtree and Francisco Cordero.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handers, however, are expected to do their part, and
that didn't happen yesterday in the Rangers' 8-6 loss to the New
York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were 0-for-9 against Cordero, Crabtree and
Zimmerman. They were 5-for-5 off left-handers Mike Munoz and Mike
Venafro in their decisive three-run seventh inning rally. So much
for the theory the Yankees are vulnerable to left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got a job to do,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``That's why we have those left-handers out there, to get
left-handed hitters out.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz took over in the seventh with the Rangers leading 6-5. He
was given the daunting task of retiring Paul O'Neill, Bernie
Williams and Tino Martinez. He couldn't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bit rusty,'' said Munoz, who hadn't pitched in a game in
eight days. ``I didn't have a real good feel for what I was doing.
It's been awhile. I don't want to make excuses, but it's been
awhile since I've been out there.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, a left-handed hitter, started the rally by lining a
first-pitch breaking ball into right field for a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``We noticed he was hacking at first-pitch fastballs all day,''
Munoz said. ``So, we tried a first-pitch breaking ball and he still
swings at it. It's one of those situations, you throw a first-pitch
fastball and you may hear a lot of questions. So, you throw a
breaking ball first pitch, and he hacks at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz managed to jam Williams, a switch hitter who was 0-for-11
against left-handers coming into the game. But Williams fought it
off and blooped it into right-center for a single, moving O'Neill
to third. That brought up Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the kind of situation where you hope something will go
right at someone, a line drive or a fly ball, and get you out of
the inning,'' Munoz said. ``It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Martinez ripped a 2-0 pitch into right-center for a
two-run triple that gave the Yankees a 7-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Oates brought in Crabtree to face right-hander Shane Spencer and
switch hitter Jorge Posada, and he got both on weak ground balls,
keeping Martinez at third.
</P>
<P>
   But Oates then went with Venafro to face Ricky Ledee, a
left-handed hitter who normally sits when the opposing team starts
a left-hander. Ledee answered the challenge with a single up the
middle to drive home Martinez with the Yankees' final run.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0408 </DOCNO>
