r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JOHNSON-T     04-12 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JOHNSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEED LED COWBOYS TO PURSUE GALLOWAY OVER JOHNSON, JONES SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ So, you like the thought of receiver Joey
Galloway in a Cowboys uniform this season.
</P>
<P>
   And never mind that the Cowboys traded two first-round picks to
Seattle for him and will be idle for the first 48 selections of
this weekend's NFL draft, you still like Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Well, how about Keyshawn Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever consider the possibility of Cowboys quarterback
Troy Aikman throwing Johnson the ball?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones did.
</P>
<P>
   And he traded for Galloway, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said yesterday that Johnson, the former New York Jets
receiver who was traded to Tampa Bay for two first-round draft
picks, was the subject of considerable discussion at the Cowboys'
Valley Ranch training complex the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   And Jones said he knew Johnson might by available when he
acquired Galloway in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did know he might be available,'' Jones said. ``I had
visited with \Rformer Jets coach\S Bill Parcells about a trade last
year. It didn't go anywhere. But I had the sense that Keyshawn
might have been available \Rfor the Cowboys this year.\S But in our
opinion, we just liked what Joey brought to the table and how it
went with what we were trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the situations weren't exactly the same. The Cowboys
traded the 19th pick in Saturday's draft, along with next year's
first-round pick, to Seattle, while the Jets got two picks in
Saturday's first round (No. 13 and 27.)
</P>
<P>
   Also there were different deadlines. The Cowboys needed to act
fast with Galloway because several teams were bidding for his
services. Actually, the Cowboys' megabucks deal with Galloway
prompted Johnson to squawk about a holdout if he didn't get a new
contract, forcing the Jets to move him.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway's contract, which is worth $42 million over seven years
and included a $12 million signing bonus, set the market value for
Johnson, who got $56 million over eight years, including a $13
million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   To Jones, the decision was not about timing but about the skills
of the two players, both 28, and how they fit with Aikman's skills
and the Cowboys' new stretch-the-field offensive philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   And never mind that the 6-foot-3 Johnson has seemingly been more
productive, catching 305 passes for 4,108 yards and 31 touchdowns
with two Pro Bowl appearances in four seasons. Galloway (5-11) has
caught 283 passes for 4,457 yards and 37 touchdowns and has been to
the Pro Bowl once in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys liked Galloway's blazing speed, which is the reason
he has more yards and more touchdowns, over Johnson's size and sure
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it,'' Jones said. ``It was debated long and
hard about which was better with Aikman's skills _ someone who
would go up and get the ball like Alvin Harper vs. laying under it.
We went the speed route. That was the difference. We made the
decision to go with the speed in Galloway.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his goal during the off-season was to build the
Cowboys into a Super Bowl contender. He said getting Galloway was a
step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Jones will carry that same line of thinking into the draft,
despite having only five picks, none in the first and third rounds.
The Cowboys have one pick in the second, fourth, fifth, sixth and
seventh rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jones believes there is enough quality in the draft that he will
be able to get a good player with his second-round pick. The
Cowboys' philosophy is to take the best available athlete, although
they plan to focus on linebackers and cornerbacks early.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jones, who has made 25 draft-day trades since he bought
the team in 1989, also will listen to trade offers to move down to
acquire additional picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this long enough that you get some interesting
opportunities on draft day,'' Jones said. ``In the ideal situation,
we'd consider moving down and picking up another pick. It'd have to
be a high third pick. I could see scenarios where that could
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the quality depth in this draft puts the Cowboys in a
good situation. And if there are still good picks available when
it's their turn to pick in the second round, then more teams are
likely to call them for a trade. This gives them a choice of
drafting a good player or trading down to get an extra pick and
still get a good player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a year for us to not have a pick in the first
round,'' Jones said, ``this is the year.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
