<HEADER>
A5101 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPOR     04-12 1785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLADEGA LOOMS AS ANOTHER NO-REPEAT CUP WEEKEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somehow, a NASCAR Winston Cup season that began with
back-to-back-to-back ``boring'' races has produced a series-record
eight different winners.
</P>
<P>
   Incongruous, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Only if you are Dale Jarrett, Bobby Labonte, Jeff Burton, Dale
Earnhardt, Ward Burton, Rusty Wallace, Dale Earnhardt Jr. or Mark
Martin. Only if you have been trying to become the first repeat Cup
race winner of 2000, a scenario that carries absolutely no
guarantee heading into NASCAR's longest and fastest racetrack this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The high-banked, 2.66-mile Talladega Superspeedway is a sister
track to the 2.5-mile Daytona International Speedway. Since 1988,
Daytona and Talladega are the only tracks where NASCAR requires use
of a carburetor restrictor plate to keep speeds from routinely
topping 210 mph.
</P>
<P>
   While the plate has sucked approximately 300 horsepower out of
the equation, it hardly has reduced the level of competitiveness at
the Alabama racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Like Daytona, Talladega features a trioval down the
frontstretch, perfect for last-lap heroics heading toward the
checkered flag. Unlike Daytona, Talladega's turns are banked at 33
degrees, two degrees steeper than DIS.
</P>
<P>
   Talladega is an interstate-style four lanes wide track, easily a
full lane wider than Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Talladega's backstretch is nearly 4,000 feet long, and at times
freight trains of cars seem to occupy every inch of available
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, Talladega has been the site of seven of the 10 most
competitive races in Cup history. The 1984 Winston 500 produced 75
lead changes in 188 laps before it was won by Cale Yarborough.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the season-opening Daytona 500 was a study in
single-file racing, with only nine lead changes among seven drivers
before Jarrett emerged as the winner _ under caution. NASCAR
shouldered most of the blame for how its Super Bowl played out. The
sanctioning body's new uniform shock and spring package widely was
lambasted by drivers and crew chiefs struggling to find an
aerodynamic balance for their cars.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``government issued'' shocks and springs were
mandated in the name of safety and reducing costs. But the aero
compromise was significant enough that NASCAR has allowed the teams
to use shocks of their choice at the front of their cars for
qualifying and race-day setups leading into Sunday's DieHard 500.
NASCAR-issued shocks and springs, however, again will be in place
at the rear of all cars.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the diameter of the four holes in all NASCAR-issued
carburetor restrictor plates has been reduced by a thirty-second of
an inch, to seven-eighths of an inch, to further control speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Total effect of the revised rules remains open to debate,
beginning with Martin, a two-time winner at Talladega who never has
hidden his dislike for plate racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say the Daytona 500 was boring this year, and I'm sure
the only reason they say that is because there were no big
wrecks,'' said Martin, driver of the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus.
``The fans want the cars in a wad, therefore NASCAR wants the cars
in a wad, and they weren't in a wad at Daytona, so they're gonna do
something to get 'em in a wad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the fans will enjoy what they see Sunday. I'm sure of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more diplomatically, Mike Skinner said he left a recent
test concerned about how good the racing would be on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put every shock we ran for the last four years on the
front of the car,'' said Skinner, driver of the No. 31 Lowe's
Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``And without putting the rear shock package
to go with it, it was basically useless. And you've got a smaller
restrictor plate, which is basically going to bunch the cars up
even more, if that's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, who finished fifth and sixth at Talladega as a
rookie last year, said the revised package should make the cars
more comfortable in 195 mph rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given some stability back to the cars,'' said Stewart,
driver of the No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac Grand Prix. ``But there's
only about four guys who have figured it \Rplate racing\S out and
really know how to do it right. Dale Earnhardt, Jeff Gordon, Dale
Jarrett and Bobby Labonte.''
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, only Gordon, a three-time series champion, has
yet to win a Cup race in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into NASCAR's longest and fastest racetrack, that's
incongruous, isn't it?
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON Brack set to rediscover his road-racing
skills Before he became Indy Racing League champion and
Indianapolis 500 winner, Kenny Brack was a road racer with Formula
One aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I got ticked off with the way the European racing system
works,'' said Brack, a native of Sweden. A 10-time winner in 37
road/street starts in developmental formulas, Brack is finding the
hoopla surrounding his debut in CART's Toyota Grand Prix of Long
Beach this weekend a bit overdone.
</P>
<P>
   Because he really does know how to turn right.
</P>
<P>
   Brack's road-racing resume includes series titles in the Renault
Clio Scandinavian Championship (1992) and Barber Saab Pro Series
(1993), as well as third- and second-place finishes in Formula 3000
in 1995 and 1996, respectively. Brack's last road-racing start was
in a FIA F3000 race in Hockenheim, Germany, on Oct. 13, 1996. Brack
was leading the race when he was disqualified for rough driving.
</P>
<P>
   His last road-race pole and victory were scored at Silverstone,
England, on Aug. 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In his last 11 Formula 3000 races, Brack won four times, not
including that controversial DQ in Germany. In three years of
Formula 3000, Brack posted five poles, 11 top-three and 14-top five
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Formula 3000, that's a step below Formula One,'' said Brack,
34. ``Well, you would think you'd earned yourself a position in
Formula One with a good team, right? But what happened was I got a
test drive in a junk team \RArrows\S and drove that car a few
times. And I just couldn't see myself going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of that, if I wanted to race, I had to bring like $10
million. Well, OK, fine, you can have your Formula One. I'm out of
here. I want to race to win. I couldn't see \Rfor\S myself a bright
future in Formula One. I don't have that kind of money. Secondly,
even if I had it, I wouldn't put it in a junk Formula One team,
because they rip you off.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, then I took the decision to go to America and look for an
Indy-car ride. I eventually ended up in the IRL, but it could have
been CART.''
</P>
<P>
   During his three-year stint in the all-oval IRL, Brack won the
1998 series championship and 1999 Indy 500 for Indy-racing legend
and team-owner A.J. Foyt of Houston. Brack joined Team Rahal at the
end of last season, fully intent on rediscovering the joys of road
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 82-lapper through downtown Long Beach will be the 17th
edition of America's most successful street race. Ironically, the
LBGP began life as a Formula One race, before pricing itself out of
the market after 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about Long Beach,'' said Brack, driver of the
No. 8 Shell Reynard/Ford-Cosworth. ``I watched the race in person
in 1996. It's a spectacular event, one I always wanted to drive.
Now I'll get the chance.''
\Nsubheds:PIT STOPS \Nsubheds:Bernstein ends skid Kenny Bernstein
will roll into Houston Raceway Park in Baytown this weekend having
ended the longest winless streak of his multi-championship National
Hot Rod Association career.
</P>
<P>
   Drag racing's ``King of Speed,'' Bernstein snapped a 27-race
winless streak dating to 1998 when he captured the Top Fuel final
of the inaugural Summitracing.com Nationals at The Strip at Las
Vegas Motor Speedway on Sunday. Bernstein defeated Joe Amato in a
tire-smoking matchup of former champions to record his 23rd Top
Fuel victory, and 53rd overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a-year-and-a-half drought and the pressure was
starting to build for the team,'' said Bernstein, who debuted a new
Hadman chassis version of The Budweiser King at Vegas. ``We've been
saying for five months that we just need to win one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein stands third in Top Fuel points after four events, 56
behind Schumacher, heading into qualifying for the 13th annual
O'Reilly Nationals at HRP tomorrow. For ticket information, call
(281) 383-7223 or Ticketmaster. \Nsubheds:CART eyes Europe CART
can't sell out any of its oval races in the United States, but that
hasn't prevented series organizers from targeting Europe for its
next global expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Craig, chief executive officer of the Championship Auto
Racing Teams, confirmed yesterday that the open-wheel series plans
to make its European debut in 2001 in either England or Germany.
Craig told The Associated Press a European race probably would be
run in the fall and that a second European venue could be added in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   The English site is the 1.5-mile Rockingham Motor Speedway in
central England near Corby. The German candidate is the Laustizring
circuit, a 2-mile oval, 60 miles south of Berlin. Craig said
putting on a European race would cost about $6 million _ about the
same as an American venue.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said the 2001 CART schedule will remain at 20 races, with
one U.S. event almost surely to be dropped. Reports have suggested
that Gateway International Raceway outside St. Louis would be the
casualty, although speculation also surrounds the Nazareth (Pa.)
Speedway. \Nsubheds:Last laps Reigning Winston Cup champion Dale
Jarrett will be honored as Driver of the Year at the International
Motorsports Hall of Fame induction ceremony at Talladega
Superspeedway tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Plano's Greg Ray, the reigning Indy Racing League champion, is
scheduled to ride in an F-15 jet at Nellis Air Force Base tomorrow
morning. The base is located right across the highway from Las
Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Already celebrating his 25th season in the Winston Cup series,
Bill Elliott will mark his 600th career start in the DieHard 500 at
Talladega Superspeedway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, the 1999 Winston Cup Series Raybestos Rookie of
the Year, has yet to lead a lap after eight races in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Jacques Villeneuve earned five Formula One championship
points for his fifth-place finish in the San Marino Grand Prix on
Sunday. The 1997 World Driving Champion, Villeneuve did not score a
point for British American Racing in 1999. \NsubhedsThe last word
``You can't win the Indy 500 if you're not in the field, and it'll
be nice to hopefully have a shot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ CART driver Jimmy Vasser, on returning for the 84th
Indianapolis 500
