<HEADLINE>
FORMER TCU COACH TOHILL DIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When former TCU football coach Billy Tohill died in a
Birmingham, Ala., hospital late Tuesday, the scene was familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fought hard,'' his wife, Bobbie, said. ``He really didn't
want to give up ... but it was time. His body finally just shut
down on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tohill, 61, will be buried at 11 a.m. tomorrow at Jefferson
Memorial Gardens in Hoover, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew him during his coaching career at TCU (1971-73)
and afterward remembered him yesterday as a ``man's man'' who never
quit on a friend _ or a foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be the toughest guy I ever knew,'' said former TCU
athletic director Frank Windegger, recalling that 27 years ago,
Tohill ``walked away from death.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in the spring of 1973 when a badly mangled Tohill was
pulled from the wreckage of his car on the South Freeway in Fort
Worth after he lost control, flipped ``over'' a cement truck, and
landed on the access road. One leg was eventually amputated below
the knee, but Tohill survived, vowing to return and coach the
Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one believed it at the time, but by the time we started
two-a-days, he was back, with a prosthetic leg,'' said Gerry
Boudreaux, one of Tohill's assistants at the time. ``It was truly
amazing, but that was Billy. He was a man's man and very blunt and
outspoken. There were people he rubbed the wrong way, but you
always knew where you stood with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a tremendous will. And anytime you had to go to battle,
you wanted Billy on your side.''
</P>
<P>
   Tohill arrived in '71 as an assistant on the staff of new head
coach Jim Pittman, and suddenly became the head coach when Pittman
died of a heart attack on the sideline at Baylor at midseason. When
TCU finished 6-4-1, the two were named co-coaches of the year in
the Southwest Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an eventful era, and a lot of guys left because it was
a tough regime,'' former safety Harold Muckleroy said. ''We lost
about 40 players, including the group \Rof five black players\S who
left because of a racial controversy. It was a sad thing, because
those guys didn't do anything wrong; they just objected to the rule
\Rno facial hair\S. They considered it a cultural thing and coach
Pittman considered it a matter of obeying the rules regardless of
whether or not you agreed with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy was like that, too. He certainly wasn't politically
correct, and you couldn't say that everyone liked him. But those
who stayed, loved him. When he came back after that accident, he
refused to use the cart they provided for him, because he wanted to
walk the field. You could see blood oozing out of that wound, but
he kept walking. To me, Billy Tohill was a king.''
</P>
<P>
   After 5-6 and 3-8 seasons in '72 and '73, Tohill was replaced by
Jim Shofner. He moved to Birmingham to coach the local World
Football League entry, then coached at two high schools and as an
assistant at Alabama-Birmingham before going into private business
with a string of fast food restaurants. He had been in poor health
in recent years, partly from hepatitis contracted from blood
transfusions after his accident, in addition to various other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He suffered a lot,'' Bobbie said. ``He fought a lot of
battles, and he won some and lost some. But he had a full life ...
and he lived it right up to the end.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
