<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-PALFFY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ABOUT TIME: PALFFY GETS PLAYOFF CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Pain? Real pain? For Ziggy Palffy, it is not the
sprained right shoulder that has sidelined him the past month.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the thought of Detroit strongman Darren McCarty
crashing him into the boards tonight in Game 1 of the Kings
first-round playoff matchup with the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going home every April when everyone I knew was still
playing,'' Palffy said Wednesday at Joe Louis Arena. ``It was the
feeling that no matter how well you played it was never good
enough. Nobody cares how many goals you score, just how many
playoff games you've won.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects the Kings to win many against the mighty Red
Wings, but it clearly has been a breakout season for Palffy and his
new team.
</P>
<P>
   During his first four full seasons in the NHL, Palffy scored
more than 40 goals three times for the New York Islanders. But the
once-proud Islanders never even got close to the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd see him in the summers and he always seemed down about
that,'' said teammate Jozef Stumpel, a fellow Slovak and a friend
since grade school. ``A guy that good is going to get his chance
one day, but it took a long time for him. Now he has his chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity nearly was derailed in mid-March when he took a
vicious hit by the Mighty Ducks' Vitaly Vishnevski and missed 12
games. For a player who had been sidelined just three games before
this season, it was a reality check.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy also spent much of the season battling lower-back
soreness. The Kings' first line of Palffy, Stumpel and Luc
Robitaille each missed extended playing time due to injuries and
played only 50 games together.
</P>
<P>
   But the time in the trainers' room may have strengthened more
than his back and shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he surprised some people,'' trainer Pete Demers said.
``He took this very seriously. He did what had to be done. He is an
elite athlete, but that can make it tougher to dedicate yourself to
the other things. He was outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy finished with 27 goals and 66 points despite missing 18
games. But he also impressed the hard-to-please Murray with his
playmaking and defensive ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed that from him almost more than we needed the
scoring,'' Murray said. ``We needed him to play within our system
for us to be successful. All he had to do before was score, which
is hard enough. But sometimes it can be even harder to get an
offensive player to play the total game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although those were the fringe benefits this season, Palffy was
brought here to score.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, out of the playoffs five of the previous six years,
were looking to upgrade their offense when they moved into the new
Staples Center in October. Palffy was their man, coming over last
summer with Bryan Smolinski for Olli Jokinen and prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy also brought some baggage.
</P>
<P>
   As the only true scorer on a poor team, he had a reputation for
being quirky and a little selfish. Winning and qualifying for the
playoffs has tapered those edges.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few days, he has been standing up in the
players-only meetings,'' Murray said. ``He has things to say and he
wants people to know just how important this is for the
organization. He is saying never take this for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, 28, said he never expects to become a team leader. He
carried the offensive load with the Islanders and that was enough.
Here, there is captain Rob Blake and other veterans.
</P>
<P>
   But he also learned a lot about expectation playing in New York.
The Nassau Coliseum was not Madison Square Garden, but he saw how
fans and media could turn quickly on players.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I scored I knew I was going to be OK,'' Palffy
said. ``If they saw it slip that might have changed, but I was the
go-to guy. The only time I saw a little trouble was with my
contract (last season). But I think people understand that that
wasn't about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy held out for half a season before receiving a five-year,
$26 million contract. But the Islanders were losing a bundle and
played before sparse crowds. They had to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him carry a great weight on the Island,'' Smolinski
said. ``Not only was it a struggling team, he was the only player
people could look to. Here he is surrounded by better players and
it has made him more well-rounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the challenge is the Red Wings. Earlier this season, Palffy
was flattened by McCarty along the boards and stayed down for
almost a minute. The Kings did not retaliate, but won 3-2. That
game, played Feb. 18 at Joe Louis Arena, was considered a turning
point in the team's maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a marked man and he knows it,'' said teammate Bob Corkum,
who often defends the other team's best player. ``We'll be trying
to move Sergei Fedorov off the puck the same way. Sometimes you hit
them, some times you miss. Those are special players.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0413 </DOCNO>
