<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-12 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: CAPITALIST ADVICE
</P>
<P>
   An independent-minded pro-capitalist economist will serve as
adviser to President-elect Vladimir Putin, Putin's spokesman said.
Putin has yet to outline a detailed economic program. But his
selection of Andrei Illarionov, 38, is a sign he will follow a
program of free-market reforms. Illarionov has criticized Russian
dependence on the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PUTIN TO MEET QUEEN
</P>
<P>
   Russia's president-elect, Vladimir Putin, will meet Queen
Elizabeth II at Windsor Castle during his trip to Britain next
week, Prime Minister Tony Blair's office said. Blair's spokesman,
Alastair Campbell, said the prime minister and Putin would discuss
the Russian economy, the Chechnya conflict, the Balkans and
cooperation in fighting crime and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: U.S. TO SKIP EXPO
</P>
<P>
   The United States will not take part in Expo 2000, opening in
Hanover on June 1. A statement issued in Berlin by the United
States commissioner for Expo, William Rollnick, said he had been
unable to raise sufficient funds from the private sector. The mayor
of Hanover, Herbert Schmalstieg, said ``nobody will miss the United
States.'' More than 190 other countries will take part.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: KOSOVARS EXPELLED
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland has expelled the first group of Kosovo Albanians who
sought refuge during the fighting in Kosovo last year. The 60
people flown to Pristina are the first of up to 30,000 Kosovars who
officials plan to return forcibly by the end of this year. A
full-scale effort is set to begin in June, when financial
incentives being offered for returning voluntarily expire.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: U.S. TALKS SET
</P>
<P>
   China said it would resume talks with the United States on
limiting the spread of nuclear weapons, ending a suspension that
followed the bombing of China's embassy in Belgrade. The policy
reversal follows China's rejection of a formal American explanation
that the bombing was accidental. Resumption of the talks leaves
human rights as the only area in which Beijing has so far refused
to resume talks with Washington since the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: GOVERNOR REPLIES
</P>
<P>
   Facing growing criticism, Gov. Shintaro Ishihara of Tokyo said
he was not referring to Korean residents of Japan when he used a
derogatory term commonly used to disparage Koreans and other
foreigners at the end of World War II. While he expressed regret
that Koreans were offended, Ishihara said he still considers
foreigners who enter or stay in Japan illegally ``very
troublesome.''
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF APPEALS
</P>
<P>
   The ousted prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, convicted last week of
hijacking and given a life sentence, has appealed the verdict. A
two-judge panel will hear arguments in the case, though no date has
been set. Sharif's six co-defendants, all of whom were acquitted,
remain locked up, each under investigation on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SETTLERS EXPANDING
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, Jewish settlers in the West Bank
started an expansion project without government approval to protest
a government freeze on approving new construction. They began
bulldozing near Efrat on Tuesday and continued near Har Hilo, where
they said they plan to build 230 homes. The police acted when a
Peace Now protest threatened to lead to a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: UNIVERSITY HIT AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Dissident students closed seven departments or schools at the
National Autonomous University of Mexico in what they announced as
a 24-hour strike. An attempt to re-open talks with the dissidents
failed Tuesday after only one session. The students, who led a
nine-month strike that ended Feb. 6, are demanding the release of
about 30 protesters still in jail after the strike.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: POLICE VERDICT VOIDED
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court in the Amazonian state of Para has overturned
the acquittal of three commanders of a police detachment that
killed 19 unarmed peasants four years ago. The original verdict in
last August's trial set off outrage in Brazil because of reports of
bribed jurors and what rights groups called procedural
irregularities. A retrial was ordered, after which the 147 men the
officers led are also expected to be judged on the same charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
