<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5114 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBA-BOY-BOS &LR;      04-12 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO MEETS WITH ELIAN'S MIAMI RELATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Taking a dramatic step to end the custody standoff over
Elian Gonzalez, US Attorney General Janet Reno traveled to Miami
Wednesday night to meet with the great uncle who has refused to
hand the boy over to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision to intervene personally came after a reunion
between father and son was canceled, apparently after Elian
expressed reluctance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's planning to work out a resolution, trying to meet with
the parties concerned to seek a cooperative settlement,'' Justice
Department spokesman Myron Marlin announced in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   While Elian's father waited in Washington, Reno and her small
entourage met with the relatives at the Miami Beach home of Sister
Jeanne O'Laughlin, the Barry University president who earlier
hosted a reunion between Elian and his grandmothers. It was not
known whether Reno would meet with the 6-year-old boy who has
sparked an international tug of war.
</P>
<P>
   One change was clear: the Miami clan headed by great-uncle
Lazaro Gonzalez seemed for the first time to accept that Elian and
his father would return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the family is becoming more reconciled and facing what
perhaps could be pain . . .,'' said O'Laughlin, who was initially
neutral in the dispute but now wants to see Elian remain in Miami.
``It is my hope and prayer that as the child becomes acquainted _
reacquainted _ with his father there will be peace in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   A transfer of custody was tentatively set for Thursday morning
at the Opa-locka airport outside Miami, where security was being
tightened. But in a battle that twists and turns daily, it was
uncertain whether Elian would actually be leaving, whether his
father would be arriving, or whether any resolution would be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   With demonstrators vowing to form a human chain to protect him,
federal officials want to avoid having to use force to remove Elian
from his great-uncle's house in Little Havana. Lazaro Gonzalez's
earlier announcement that Elian was not headed to Washington met
with cheers.
</P>
<P>
   As about 100 demonstrators gathered outside the Miami Beach
mansion, a stark contrast to the modest home where Elian has been
staying since he was found floating at sea Thanksgiving Day, the
much-anticipated meeting began around suppertime. Joining Reno were
Immigration and Naturalization Commissioner Doris Meissner and a
few other federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez and his daughter Marisleysis, who left the
hospital where she is once again being treated for stress-related
ailments, represented the family that has been fighting for custody
of Elian. They are appealing a federal court ruling that upheld
Reno's right to return Elian to his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
and to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Gregory B. Craig, the attorney representing the
father, demanded anew that the Justice Department order the
relatives to bring or send Elian to his father, who arrived in the
United States last week. ``Every day of delay does enormous damage
to Elian,'' Craig said. ``It is time for the Justice Department to
instruct Lazaro Gonzalez to follow the law and do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Mas Santos, chairman of the Cuban American National
Foundation, had announced Tuesday night that the reunion would take
place Wednesday. But that event fell through, and Wednesday Santos
stressed that it was never intended as a handover of Elian.
Instead, he said, it was meant to provide a forum for the family to
decide the boy's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez proposed O'Laughlin's house as a neutral site
for a meeting between the Miami relatives and Elian's father, who
chose to remain in Washington and meet with officials at the Cuba
Interest Section Wednesday night. The Cuban government, however, no
longer considers her neutral, since she has made clear her
preferences about where Elian should live.
</P>
<P>
   Family spokesman Armando Gutierrez called Reno's trip to Miami,
her hometown, a ``good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Miami, where she served as state's attorney for 15
years, Reno also planned to meet with exile community leaders but
did not plan to deliver the government letter outlining the
specifics of the custody transfer. That letter had not been
delivered by Wednesday afternoon, although even Elian's most ardent
Miami supporters are starting to accept the inevitability of his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I expect to see and all that Americans demand to see . . .
is that whatever happens happens the American way,'' said Miami
Mayor Joseph Carollo, who, like many of the Cubans in the
800,000-strong exile community in Miami, opposes returning Elian to
Cuba until the federal court case is settled, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials expressed frustration at Wednesday's events and
that the boy has not been returned to his father a week after Juan
Miguel Gonzalez arrived in Washington from Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time the (US) government do what it is legally obligated
to, return the boy to his father,'' Ricardo Alarcon, president of
Cuba's National Assembly, said on national television Wednesday
night. ``What has happened shows the moral bankruptcy of the
kidnappers in Miami who are doing everything they can to delay
this, and that they're desperately running out of options.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
