   (NYT42) FAIRBURN, Ga. -- April 12, 2000 -- FOOD-EGGS-1-COX --
Recent studies have shown eggs aren't nearly as hard on the
arteries as once believed. Dave Califf of Puck's Farm gathered eggs
(from his free-range chickens) to be delivered to some of the
Atlanta's finest restaurants. (Phil Skinner/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- April 12, 2000 --
LUXURY-BOATING-COX --Don't be fooled. At the high-end of a
mega-boat show, it's all about sex. And the 100-foot Tarrab, a
drop-dead opulent yacht, is sexy. The Tarrab was among 1,000 boats
on display at the 15th annual Palm Beach Boat Show this spring. It
took German and Italian craftsmen in Buenos Aires more than a year
to build the 25-foot-wide yacht, which is made with all U.S. parts.
The master bedroom, top; the master bathroom, or ``head,'' below.
(Jean Hart Howard/The Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- HOUSEBOATS-2-COX -- With
the robust economy, houseboat sales are soaring - from $25,000
entry-level used boats to high-end models in the mid-six figures.
``The economy has a direct impact on the houseboat industry,'' said
Steve Smede, editor of Houseboat Magazine, who has seen
subscriptions to his publications double during the past five
years. ``People have money to spend and they're buying nicer
things.'' (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) ON LAKE TRAVIS, Texas -- April 12, 2000 --
HOUSEBOATS-1-COX -- With the robust economy, houseboat sales are
soaring - from $25,000 entry-level used boats to high-end models in
the mid-six figures. Jeff Walker and his cat Razz are the new new
owners of a two-month-old houseboat on Lake Travis. ``I found out
it was so much fun that I just decided to live out here,'' said
Walker. ``And I have a much bigger swimming pool now.'' (Ha Lam/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) LITHONIA, Ga. -- April 12, 2000 -- SPAS-TRENDS-COX --
Health spas offer nearly every convenience, and the Cox News
Service staff gladly lent their bodies to science - the science of
relaxation - in the pursuit of the best spas in the Atlanta area.
Jacqueline DaCosta was massaged by Sharon Brathwaite in preparation
for her facial at Spa Daweeds Hair Design &AMP; Fitness in Lithonia.
(Louie Favorite/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- NY-SCHOOLS-GIULIANI --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and his son, Andrew, took in opening day at
Yankee Stadium on Wednesday. Giuliani adopted a conciliatory tone
Wednesday toward Harold O. Levy, the interim schools chancellor who
has told the Board of Education that he wants to be considered for
a permanent job. The mayor's gentle remarks were in contrast to his
initial harsh opposition to Levy, and seemed to signal that
Giuliani was backing off from another fight over the management of
the city's schools. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- OBIT-DLUGOSZEWSKI -- Lucia
Dlugoszewski, a composer and the artistic director of the Erick
Hawkins Dance Company, was found dead on Tuesday in her Greenwich
Village apartment. She is believed to have been 68. She died of
natural causes, said Ellen Borakove, spokeswoman for the New York
City medical examiner. (Lucia Dlugoszewski/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- ECONSCENE -- Is democracy
valuable on economic grounds alone? Amartya Sen, an economist, says
democracy should be sought as an economic end in itself. Freedom is
essential, he argues, to a full life. (James Estrin/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- April 12, 2000 -- TERAYON -- Zaki
Rabib is the chief executive of Terayon Communication Systems, a
company with a market valuation of almost $4 billion. Terayon is
growing exceptionally fast and establishing itself as a leader in
the burgeoning market for advanced cable modems and other
communications equipment. (Steve Castillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- CAREY-MUSIC-REVIEW --
Mariah Carey seemed adrift during her live performance at Madison
Square Garden on Tuesday night. Her celebrated high notes suffered,
perhaps because she still hasn't learned to preserve her voice
during a tour. Without those heady vocal lightning flashes to
distract, Carey's problems finding her new style's emotional core
became evident. Her skilled but overly precise band didn't help;
the mix made it sound like a backing track. (Michelle V. Agins/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- ROSE-THEATER-REVIEW --
Olympia Dukakis in Martin Sherman's play ``Rose,'' at the Lyceum
Theater. Directed here, as in London, by Nancy Meckler, the
production has a finger-wagging quality. It comes through in the
writing of Sherman, an American who lives in England, and in the
performance of Ms. Dukakis, who doesn't seem to have inhabited the
character of Rose so much as seized on her to make a point: Listen!
This is good for you. (ara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 12, 2000 -- PROUST-POPULARITY --
The increased availability of Marcel Proust's letters has fostered
new scholarship on his life. At Caffe Proust in San Francisco, P
Segal, center, the owner, led the first meeting of a reading group
devoted to Marcel Proust (Thor Swift/The New York Times), depicted
at right in an 1893 painting by Jacques-Emile Blanche (University
of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign/The New York Times).
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- NAZI-ART-MUSEUMS-2 --
Manet's ``Monet Family in Their Garden at Argenteuil,'' one of 393
paintings owned by the Metropolitan Museum of Art that have gaps in
their Nazi-era ownership history. The paintings were listed on the
Web on Wednesday. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- GEEK-NOTES-4 -- A new robot
may look a lot less fetching than R2-D2 - it's actually a tractor
retrofitted with water cannons, cameras, and remote-controlled
attachments - but firefighters may be very glad to see it, anyway.
The new machine is meant to go where no firefighter has gone,
investigating factory floors, for instance, for explosive chemicals
and removing them with a remote-controlled grapple before people
enter to tackle the blaze. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) DEARBORN, Mich. -- April 12, 2000 -- GEEK-NOTES-3-B&AMP;W --
After World War II, R. Buckminster Fuller founded a company to
mass-produce Dymaxion houses - aluminum structures shaped like
flying saucers and supported by a central shaft, somewhat like an
umbrella. Among other amenities, there were shelves that rotated
behind the walls at the touch of button. But the venture fell apart
in 1946 and only one such house was ever erected. The Henry Ford
Museum is restoring it and has devoted part of its Web site to the
project (www.hfmgv.org/dymaxion/). (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- GEEK-NOTES-2 -- The makers
of the popular Blackberry pager - a small, wireless e-mail device
with a keyboard - unveiled a larger sibling this week. The new
Blackberry 957 is roughly the size and shape of a Palm device but
is closer in spirit to the original Blackberry pager, the 950, than
to a personal digital assistant. The two products will appeal to
different people for different reasons,'' said David Werezak, vice
president for marketing at Research in Motion, the Canadian
manufacturer of the device. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- GEEK-NOTES-1 -- La-Z-Boy
worked with Microsoft's WebTV Networks division to create the
ultimate throne for mouse potatoes who want to surf the Net, send
and receive e-mail and watch TV at the same time. The left arm of
the Explorer recliner has a keyboard tray that folds and swivels.
The chair also includes a power outlet with surge suppression and a
modem jack, and a storage compartment in the right arm for
essentials like a remote control and the user's beverage of choice.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W -- The
most popular powe tool for professionals and do-it-yourselfers,
after the portable electric drill, is the circular saw. It can make
most of the cuts done by table or radial-arm saws, and it has the
added advantage that it can be carried to the job site. Fitted with
the right blade, a portable circular saw can cut through almost any
material, and obviously, faster than a hand saw. (Edward R.
Lipinski/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- SURVIVORS-HAGGADAH-B&AMP;W --
The pages of ``A Survivors' Haggadah'' resonate with bitter sarcasm
toward the God who was a spectator to the Holocaust. A spectral
woodcut commemorating bondage to Hitler is one of seven invoking
the Jews' bondage to Hitler. Most are accompanied by traditional
text. (Woodcut by Miklos Adler in ``The Survivors' Haggadah''/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- UNILEVER-BEN&AMP;JERRYS -- In
a complex end to a four-month odyssey, Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, the
quirky Vermont ice cream company, said Wednesday it had agreed to
be acquired by Unilever, the global consumer-products giant that
makes Breyer's ice cream and Good Humor bars, for about $326
million in cash, or $43.60 per share. Blanca Parajon serves the ice
cream at a Ben &AMP; Jerry's store in Manhattan in 1997. (Don Hogan
Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- MARKET -- Pradip Duria, a
day trader, on the phone as the Nasdaq market dropped in value,
Wednesday. Investors stepped up their jettisoning of technology
stocks Wednesday, driving the Nasdaq composite index down 7.06
percent, the second-worst slide since August 1998 when various
Asian economies seemed on the verge of meltdown. (Chang W. Lee/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- April 12, 2000 -- IMF-PROTESTS-3 --Worried
that doing business with China will crowd American workers out of
the global economy, thousands of union men and women flocked to
Capitol Hill on Wednesday to condemn the idea of normal trade
relations with Beijing. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) HIGH POINT, N.C. -- April 12, 2000 -- HOME-FURNISHINGS
-- The furniture being shown this week at the High Point
International Home Furnishings Market embraces the classic.
Clockwise from upper right: Mario Buatta's button-tufted sofa
($7,000) invoked the glamour of Syrie Maugham and Elsie de Wolfe;
Michael Vanderbyl's outdoor furniture designs in teak, aluminum and
cloth webbing include this lounge chair, for McGuire ($1,520); the
dark chest from Lane offers French influences at mid-market prices
(i.e. $1,799). (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- DESIGN-BOOKS -- Bookstore
shelves are groaning under the weight of ever more design titles.
And whether they're coffee-table fluff, scholarly analyses or
plain-spoken how-tos, they find buyers. (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- OPEN-CURTAINS -- Trend
watchers, take note: It's curtains for drapes. Say farewell to the
billowing swathes of fabric. The vogue for curtainless windows is
making every building a Cineplex. (Barbara Alper/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- April 12, 2000 -- TEST-PROTESTS --
Brushfires of civil disobedience flared in classrooms across
Massachusetts Wednesday, as several hundred 10th-graders, and
dozens of fourth- and eighth-graders, boycotted the first of 11
days of statewide standardized testing. A high school student
protested the test Wednesday. (Evan Richman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- April 12, 2000 -- TEST-PROTESTS --
Brushfires of civil disobedience flared in classrooms across
Massachusetts Wednesday, as several hundred 10th-graders, and
dozens of fourth- and eighth-graders, boycotted the first of 11
days of statewide standardized testing. High School students
protested the test Wednesday outside their school. (Evan
Richman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE -- The
Nasdaq composite stock index dropped as much as five percent
Wednesday after more bad news on some of its major technology
components, but technical analysts say the index is groping for a
bottom near term. A man looked into the window at the Nasdaq
Marketsite which displayed market activity, Wednesday. (Chang W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-2 -- Mel
Stottlemyre in the dugout during the New York Yankees home opener
against the Texas Rangers, Wednesday. The Yankees opened the home
portion of the 2000 season in familiar fashion, with Stottlemyre in
the dugout and a win over the Texas Rangers. Texas lost 8-6.
(Barton Silverman//The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-RANGERS -- Hall
of Famer and former New York Yankee catcher Yogi Berra throws the
ceremonial first pitch at the start of the Yankees home opener
against the Texas Rangers Wednesday. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LOS ANGELES -- April 12, 2000 -- CIR-BROWN-ANIMATION --
For the last seven months the computer wizards of Digital Domain, a
company that has made special effects for films like ``Apollo 13,
``True Lies'' and ``Titanic,'' have been trying to create a
convincing, animated double of the self-proclaimed Hardest-Working
Man in Show Business. Mark David Brown worked on a digital James
Brown while Andre Bustanoby, left, and Joshua Kolden looked on. The
image, below, is from animation software. (Marissa Roth/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- CIR-POSTMORTEM-EMAIL --
Todd Michael Krim started FinalThoughts.com as a one-stop source of
information on death and dying. The Web site also offers its users
a place to store e-mail messages online so they can be sent to
family members and friends after each writer has died. Think of it
as e-mail from beyond the grave. (Norman Y. Lono/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 12, 2000 -- CIR-THINGS-THAT-THINK --
Today, dozens of appliance manufacturers are betting that some sort
of pervasive-computing devices will come to be considered as
necessary as a telephone. The trick, for them, is to figure out
which ones. Front to back, Jeff Miller, Eric Chen and Russell
Robertson at ECCO Design have studied the feasibility of smart
appliances. (Frances Roberts/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- CIR-THINK-VIDEOPHONE-B&AMP;W --
If any product demonstrates the gap between what can be created and
what people actually want, the videophone may be it. ``It's been on
the verge of happening for nearly a hundred years but hasn't yet,''
said Paul Levinson, a professor of communications and media studies
at Fordham University and the author of ``The Soft Edge: A Natural
History and Future of the Information Revolution.'' (AT&AMP;T
Archives/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- April 12, 2000 -- FUNDS-ROLLERCOASTER-BOS -- In
the last few days, for mutual fund investors, it's meant hanging on
while tech-heavy portfolios were pummeled - and seeing that a
euphoric ride up can be grim on the way back down. ``It's been a
very active quarter because the changes in the market have been so
drastic,'' said Gary Craven, manager of Evergreen's successful
Small Company Growth fund, who has been standing up to the pressure
admirably. (John Blanding/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- April 12, 2000 -- NEWBALANCE-JUMP-BOS -- Jim
Davais, head of New Balance, puts his feet up to show his company's
product during an interview earlier this month. Davais has set out
to to diversify his line of running shoes and broaden his market
beyond male baby boomers after he saw too few people using the
company's products in the 1990 Boston Marathon. (Janet Knott/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- April 12, 2000 -- TAX-RUSH-BOS -- John Danehy
is spending about 80 hours hunkered down inside his office lately.
He's besieged on all sides by the tools of the season. The
52-year-old Danehy is no undertaker, but if death is indeed one of
life's only two certainties, he represents the other: taxes. He's
an income tax preparer, one of the uncounted tens of thousands of
paid professionals assisting roughly half of the country's 126
million individual taxpayers with their 1999 returns. (Suzanne
Kreiter/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- April 12, 2000 -- NAZI-ART-MUSEUMS -- On
Monday, the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston said that it found more
than 200 paintings in its collection with gaps in provenance
between 1933 and 1945. But the museum decided to post on its
website only seven paintings that are ``of most concern'' because
of their association with people implicated in World War II era
looting or because of the timing or location of transactions in
their history. One of the seven paintings posted is this one,
``Portrait of a Man and a Woman in an Interior about 1675'' by
Eglon van der Neer. (Museum of Fine Arts/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- April 12, 2000 -- IMF-PROTESTS-2 -- Labor
union activists swarmed the Capitol Wednesday in an offensive
against a landmark trade agreement with China. Union members bow
their heads in prayer during the rally at the U.S. Capitol.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- April 12, 2000 -- IMF-PROTESTS -- Labor
union activists swarmed the Capitol Wednesday in an offensive
against a landmark trade agreement with China. Pat Buchanan, left,
running for the Reform Party presidential nomination, and Rep.
Bernard Sanders (Ind.-Vt), right, look on as Chinese dissident
Harry Wu holds up an image of Chinese prisoners facing execution
during the rally. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- April 12, 2000 -- MEDICARE-DRUGS -- House
Speaker Dennis Hastert puts his arm around Lillie Miller, 87, of
Alexandria, Va., after addressing reporters Wednesday on the
Capitol steps. House Republicans on Wednesday unveiled the outlines
of an election-year plan to make prescription drug insurance
available to senior citizens, with the government subsidizing
low-income individuals as well as those with unusually high
expenses for medication. (Carol T. Powers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- April 12, 2000 -- GORE-EDITORS -- Vice
President Al Gore waits to be introduced before the American
Society of Newspaper Editors, Wednesday. The day after Republican
George W. Bush jumped into the health care debate, Gore accused his
rival of ``political malpractice'' and prodded newspaper editors to
give Bush's proposals a close examination. (Stephen Crowley/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
