<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NUKE-WORKERS-COMPENSA     04-12 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-WORKERS-COMPENSATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S OUTLINES PLAN TO SETTLE CLAIMS OF BOMB WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., N.M., Wash.)  By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flanked by members of Congress and a woman whose
father is dying of a disease he contracted assembling atom bombs,
the energy secretary on Wednesday announced a plan to compensate
3,000 nuclear weapons workers for sickness or death caused by
exposure to radiation or chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary, Bill Richardson, said that under the plan, which
requires congressional approval before it can begin, the Department
would evaluate claims filed by families of workers or the workers
themselves and decide the compensation on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects that many of the cases would be filed by
families on behalf of workers who were already dead, in some cases
dead for many years. Half, he estimated, would be for workers with
cancer, a quarter for workers with lung problems caused by
beryllium, a toxic metal that in the '50s and '60s was used almost
exclusively in nuclear weapons manufacture, and the remainder for
workers sickened by asbestos or suffering from assorted other
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates for workers contended that the Energy Department
was a poor choice of agencies to advocate for workers, after
decades of poor safety and health processes and denial of problems.
Within the Energy Department, said Robert Alvarez, a former
official there and expert on nuclear weapons manufacturing,
compared the choice to putting tobacco companies in charge of
compensation to smokers.
</P>
<P>
   About 600,000 people have worked to produce nuclear weapons
since late 1943, when the Manhattan Project, the World War 2 effort
to build an atom bomb, began. The number of claims anticipated by
the department is one half of one percent of that number, although
others suspect there will be far more.
</P>
<P>
   The workers were almost all employees of contractors, not the
federal government itself. For years the contractors, on orders
from the Energy Department at the Atomic Energy Commission that
preceded it, routinely fought all claims of injury; as a result,
officials say now, many of those who died early or lived for years
with devastating illnesses never bothered to file claims.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the compensation program would cost about $400
million _ an average of about $67,000 per case.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday officials stressed that the new policy, which has been
in the works for about a year, was a historic and compassionate
shift, after five decades of denying that anyone had received
enough exposure to be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remembered the important lesson, that statistics are people
with the tears washed off,'' said Dr. David Michaels, the assistant
secretary for environmental safety and health.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress gives its approval, the Energy Department would
weigh claims by considering a worker's years of employment and the
maximum exposure to radiation or dangerous chemicals that was
possible in that job. It would then apply a formula to o determine
the payment. Depending on the amount, a worker or survivors would
receive a lump-sum payment or reimbursement of all medical costs
and partial compensation for lost wages.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does not go along, then the Department will simply
change its policy on workmen's compensation claims brought against
it, telling its contractors to drop opposition in cases that met
its new, relaxed criteria, and not asserting the statute of
limitations as a defense. That approach could still provide
compensation but probably at a lower amount, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the eight representatives and three senators who joined
Richardson, all with active or defunct weapons plants in their
districts or states, pledged to try for quick action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a proud generation,'' said Sen. Patty Murray of
Washington, ``They had a right to be proud, but they also have a
right to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep.Tom Udall, a Democrat, whose district includes the Los
Alamos National Laboratory, Wednesday introduced a bill that would
pay all medical expenses or a $200,000 lump sum, double the
administration's proposal. He said that the package proposed by
Richardson was just a starting point.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims and their relatives expressed gratitude for the
government's action.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Dietz, of Brooklyn, N.Y., a psychotherapist whose
father, Frederick, died of leukemia in 1969, at 57 years old, after
working as a research chemist at the Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory, said, ``It's a relief to me, it's substantiating a
reality that we always had a little bit of a hunch about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very nice to have someone say, yes, there was a reason
for his death that really is related to what he was doing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Vikki Hatfield, of Kingston, Tenn., appearing Wednesday with
Richardson, said her father Leon Meade, a machinist, had done
weapons work from 1949 until his retirement in 1985, and had later
developed diseases from beryllium and asbestos he was exposed to on
the job. Now 69, his weight has dropped from 190 pounds at
retirement to 120 now. ``He's six feet tall so you can imagine
there's not much there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The family has spent $400,000 on medical care, selling acreage
from the farm where they formerly kept dairy and beef cattle; there
is no longer anyone able to do that work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get this disease on the farm,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield said her mother could not leave her father even
briefly. ``He doesn't want to be alone; he's afraid of dying and he
doesn't want to do it by himself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give him back what he's lost, you can't stop the
pain he's going through,'' she said. ``But we have to move forward
and we have to do the right thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
