<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5126 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HEART-PUMP-HNS &LR;      04-12 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-PUMP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE MAY LEAD TO PERMANENT ALTERNATIVE TO HEART TRANSPLANT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Doctors at the Texas Heart Institute announced
Wednesday they have implanted a miniature pump inside the heart of
a patient, the first device of its kind to be used on a human in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by batteries, the Jarvik 2000, about the size of a wine
cork, fits directly into the heart's left ventricle and the tiny
turbine pushes oxygenated blood throughout the body when the heart
is no longer able to pump properly.
</P>
<P>
   The historic operation brings scientists a giant step closer to
a goal they have pursued for decades: a permanent alternative to
the heart transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major advance. We're all looking forward to it,'' said
Dr. Patrick McCarthy of the Cleveland Clinic in Ohio, commenting on
the landmark procedure. McCarthy is director of the heart
transplant and artificial heart pump programs at the renowned heart
research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope (it) will be better tolerated than larger
pumps,'' added McCarthy, who hopes to test the device.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Heart Institute doctors declined requests for interviews
about the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The Jarvik 2000 was developed by Dr. Robert Jarvik, the pump's
New York-based inventor, and Dr. O.H. Frazier, chief of
cardiopulmonary transplantation at the Texas Heart Institute at St.
Luke's Episcopal Hospital in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier interview, Jarvik said this device puts inventors
close to achieving a ``forgettable heart,'' an artificial pump that
allows people to resume normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Heart Institute said the device has been implanted as
a ``bridge to transplant,'' meaning a way to buy time for a dying
patient until a donor heart is available. One of the pump's
developers said a second device will be tested in Oxford, England,
as a permanent booster to keep a heart going for the rest of a
patient's life.
</P>
<P>
   A similar device pioneered by Dr. Michael DeBakey of Baylor
College of Medicine in Houston has been implanted as a bridge to
transplant in 28 people in Europe. DeBakey said nine of the
patients have been successfully transplanted with donor hearts and
are ``leading a good life. In general, the results are quite
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Both pumps are descended from a category of pumps called left
ventricular assist devices, or LVADS. But the Jarvik and DeBakey
devices are the tiniest yet, completely internal except for a
single wire that extends outside the body. Risk of infection is
minimal, and the pumps will fit into women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Jarvik 2000, DeBakey's device is a miniature axial flow
pump, but it is inserted into the aorta. DeBakey expects to begin
testing his device, which he calls an ``auxiliary aorta,'' in the
United States this year after receiving approval from the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very enthusiastic about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Heart Institute received permission from the FDA to
implant the Jarvik 2000 in a limited number of patients, the
institute said. Houston is the only site of the pilot study.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands could benefit from the technology. About
40,000 people have end-stage congestive heart failure, meaning
their hearts have gradually degenerated into weak, flabby organs
that do not pump strongly enough. The ideal therapy is a
transplant, but the number of donor hearts has leveled off at 2,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, patients whose diseased hearts get a chance to
``rest'' while on the artificial pumps may actually recover much of
their natural heart function, and have the pump removed. In this
case, the mini-pump will function as a ``bridge to recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping the chronically ill, the devices could
save people who suffer sudden damage through a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   DeBakey said many patients implanted with his device have been
able to rise from their hospital beds and resume some normal
activity. He said he recently had dinner in a restaurant with two
of his implant patients in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvik's name is associated with an earlier artificial heart,
the Jarvik-7, which was first implanted in a Utah patient named
Barney Clark 1982. Four others would get the Jarvik in the next two
years but only one lived beyond a year. It is still in use as a
bridge to transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Heart Institute said the Jarvik 2000 has been 10 years
in the making. Early research on the pump was supported by funds
Frazier set aside from money he was paid to remove hearts from
donors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
