<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING RESOLUTION, RENO MEETS WITH ELIAN'S MIAMI RELATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs to add 7 grafs at end)  
(See also CUBAN-BOY-RENO) 
 By RICK BRAGG and LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno arrived in
Miami on Wednesday evening and met face to face with Elian
Gonzalez's relatives here to try to persuade them to hand him over
peacefully, hoping that she might bring an end to a volatile
custody fight that has smoldered since November.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, the country's highest law enforcement official, met with
the boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, and other family members at
a neutral site _ the , gated Miami Beach home of Sister Jeanne
O'Laughlin, president of Berry University.The Roman Catholic nun
opened her home to a January meeting between the 6-year-old boy and
his grandmothers from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Reno ``is planning to work out a resolution,'' said Myron
Marlin, a spokesman for Reno, in a meeting with reporters in
Washington, D.C., Wednesday afternoon. ``She realizes it is a tall
order, but believes she may be the one who can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared to be a true last-ditch attempt at winning
cooperation from the family, which has resisted previous appeals
from Justice Department officials to work out a peaceful plan for
handing over the boy. Doris Meissner, the U.S. immigration and
naturalization services commissioner, accompanied Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was expected to offer to use her plane to fly Elian's Miami
relatives to meet with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, in
Washington and arrange an eventual reunion.
</P>
<P>
   As Reno and Gonzalez family members met behind closed doors,
Justice Department officials held off delivering a letter to the
family that would have required them to hand the boy over to
federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said Wednesday night that if there
was no progress in the talks between Reno and the family, she was
prepared to hand the family that letter Wednesday night. Before the
talks, officials had said the letter demanded the handover of the
boy as early as Thursday morning. .
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear, as they talked, if the child's reunion with
his father would take place soon, perhaps later this week, or if it
the meeting would turn out to be just one more delay.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to have Elian and his Miami relatives travel to
Washington to meet with the boy's father Wednesday morning fell
through late Tuesday night when the boy said that he did not want
to go, said Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Miguel Gonzalez came to the United States expecting to be
given custody of his son,'' said Gregory B. Craig, a lawyer for
Elian's father. ``He has been here for seven days and Elian is
still in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   The custody standoff has grown more tense almost from the minute
Elian stepped on dry land. He was found floating on Thanksgiving
Day in an inner tube in the Atlantic after his mother and 10 others
drowned in a failed crossing from Cuba. The boy's Miami relatives
and much of the Cuban exile population in South Florida have
refused to send him back to a communist dictatorship that his
mother died to escape. But the boy's father has insisted on his
son's return and many people, especially outside Miami, agree that
he has the right to speak for his child.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez requested that he, his wife, Angela, their
daughter Marisleysis and Elian leave their house in Miami's Little
Havana on Wednesday _ and the throngs of demonstrators and dozens
of reporters and camera crews _ for the less stressful atmosphere
of O'Laughlin's waterfront home on Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sensed a need to have some space,'' said O'Laughlin,
later adding that Elian seemed much at ease there. Elian and his
Miami relatives apparently planned to stay the night, if not
longer.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the family seemed resigned to handing over Elian,
she said: ``I think the family is becoming more reconciled and
facing what, perhaps, could be pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said Elian's relatives were not talking about handing
over the boy Thursday, and would wait to hear what Reno had to say.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the family was joined at the nun's house by two of their
lawyers. As of late evening, Reno had not spoken with reporters
about what was said in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   If family members expected to be free of the demonstrators who
have gathered outside their home for months, they were
disappointed. '
</P>
<P>
   Police stood in front of demonstrators as Reno arrived and
police cars lined the streets and surrounding areas. Two police
boats patrolled a canal behind the house.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening, the crowd swelled to about 400 and became
more agitated. Demonstrators chanted a rhyme in Spanish, ``Reno,
you coward! Miami is on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   In Little Havana, the demonstrators had been just steps away,
but on the beach, demonstrators were much farther from the house.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the demonstration, Ramon Saul Sanchez, staged a
sit-in on one of the main causeways linking the beach to the
mainland when rafters from Cuba were sprayed with a water cannon by
the U.S. Coast Guard last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanchez said only that ``the plan is that we pray. We pray
that the family can come together and work it out among themselves.
That would be the best thing for for them, for the boy, and the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said she hoped the change of scenery would help, no
matter when and how the boy's transfer would come about.
</P>
<P>
   The government-appointed psychiatrists and psychologists who
spoke to Lazaro Gonzalez about the best way to hand the boy over
said that Elian has the love of two families, but their
disagreements are hurting the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family in Miami needs to solve this in a positive and
constructive way,'' said Jerry Wiener, emeritus professor in
residence at psychiatry and pediatrics at George Washington
University School of Medicine. ``They are blaming the kid for
something they just don't want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiener said the meeting between the boy's father and the Miami
relatives, which was canceled late Tuesday, had offered promise,
``but it was very discouraging the meeting was called off.''
</P>
<P>
   That meeting, arranged by Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., was
not intended as a handover of the boy but as a chance for both
sides to meet and try to come to a compromise, in the boy's best
interest, said Jorge Mas Santos, who heads the Cuban American
National Foundation in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But at midnight, Lazaro Gonzalez said Elian had told him he did
not want to go, and that the meeting was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way you deal with a 6-year-old,'' Wiener said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
