<HEADLINE>
DESPITE INJURY, SMOLINSKI WILL PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Not only will Bryan Smolinski play tonight, just 11
days after suffering an apparent season-ending knee injury, he will
be a major player in the Kings' offensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski, diagnosed with a partially torn medial collateral
ligament in his right knee, skated with the team for the second
consecutive day and will play in his usual spots on the power-play
and penalty-killing units when the Kings meet the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty amazing,'' said Smolinski, who is wearing a
heavybrace on the knee. ``Something definitely happened down there,
but it never seemed quite as bad as it sounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski knew he was hurt when Phoenix's Travis Green rolled
over on his right leg with just 16 seconds remaining in a 2-1 loss
April 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wasn't a pop, it was more of a tweak,'' he said. ``The
next day the swelling wasn't so bad and I had good range of motion.
It wasn't like I couldn't sleep at night. They said I'd be out six
weeks, but I had a good feeling I could come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski's return adds depth to an offense that on paper does
not match up well with Detroit. It allows enforcer Ian Laperriere
to return to the third line where he is better suited. Smolinski
also has 40 games of playoff experience from his days in Boston and
Pittsburgh. Laperriere has 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told him we weren't going to use him unless he could
give us what he did before,'' coach Andy Murray said of Smolinski,
who was tied for fourth on the club with 56 points. ``If he
couldn't do that, we didn't want him. His situation has really
improved in a short amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THAT SPELL? Murray had only one word on the blackboard
Wednesday: Composure. Winger Bob Corkum said lack of composure
undid his Phoenix Coyotes two years ago after they defeated Detroit
in the first game of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just beside ourselves,'' he said. ``After we won
thatgame we said, `Hey, we're going to beat these guys.' Hockey is
a game of not getting too high or too low. Yet they were in the
dressing room acting like it was over. That did more to hurt us
than anything they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit went on to win the series in six games and took their
second consecutive Stanley Cup title. Corkum confirmed his status
as one of the game's toughest players by finishing the series after
breaking his foot in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum was struck on the foot by a Nicklas Lidstrom slap shot
but continued to play after receiving pain-relief injections.
</P>
<P>
   FISET IN: Stephane Fiset is the Kings' starting goaltender for
the series based on his strong finish (5-0-1 in his last six games)
and his record (2-0-1) against the Red Wings this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tremendous confidence in both our goaltenders, but
Steph has really stepped up,'' Luc Robitaille said. ``The team
really has rallied around him.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that way two years ago when Fiset dropped the first
two games in round one against St. Louis. Kings coach Larry
Robinson pulled Fiset in favor of Jamie Storr, but the club was
swept in four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was two years ago, I don't even want to think about
that,'' Fiset said. ``We have a much different team and the
attitude is great. We're not ruling anything out just because we
are playing the Red Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   MODRY IN, BERG OUT: Defenseman Jaroslav Modry wanted to make it
tough on the Kings to keep him out of the lineup. He scored two
goals in the final week that helped cement their playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Modry, who appeared in just 25 games, will play tonight in
place of Aki Berg. Modry faced Detroit three times this year and
the Kings were 2-0-1. The knock on him was he played
inconsistently, but the added playing time down the stretch seemed
to eliminate the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see Aki in this series,'' Murray said. ``But Modry has
earned his shot. He plays very well against the Red Wings.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
