<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK POISED TO REQUIRE LESS FLAMMABLE CIGARETTES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WINNIE HU and RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ State Senate leaders say they will pass a bill
early next week that will make New York the first state to require
that tobacco companies modify cigarettes to lower the risk of
smokers accidentally setting fires.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed the assembly on Monday. Passage by the Senate
would put the bill's fate in the hands of Gov. George Pataki. The
governor's spokesman, Michael McKeon, would say only that the
governor would ``take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   But several legislators and anti-smoking advocates predicted
that he would sign it, if for no other reason than not to be seen
as the Capitol's only defender of tobacco industry interests.
</P>
<P>
   If it becomes law, the bill will represent a major, long-sought
victory for anti-smoking advocates and some firefighters' groups,
who contend that it will prevent hundreds of fires set by careless
smokers each year. They also argue that it will jump-start the
issue in Congress, where it has languished for years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would strike yet another blow to a besieged tobacco
industry, which has lost its aura of invincibility in the last few
years, agreeing to pay the states $246 billion to compensate for
tobacco-related health care costs, seeing several states raise
tobacco taxes, and fending off a growing rash of lawsuits from
smokers, some of them successful.
</P>
<P>
   The New York bill would require that a cigarette go out rather
than keep burning when no one puffs on it for a mandated period of
time; that period of time has yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The change would cut down on sales, anti-smoking advocates and
sponsors of the bill said, because a smoker who walks away from a
lighted cigarette for a few minutes would come back and, rather
than finding only ashes, would find a stub that could be lighted
again.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies began test-marketing less flammable cigarettes
in the 1980s. They have taken several approaches, including
changing the chemical composition or the thickness of the paper.
Several brands are on the market now, including Merit, Virginia
Slims, More and Eve Lights.
</P>
<P>
   The companies say they are not yet convinced that those products
meet their customers' standards for taste, though anti-tobacco
lobbyists maintain that smokers do not notice a difference. The
changes do not affect the cost of making the cigarettes, industry
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision has been made that we will pass the bill early
next week,'' said state Sen. Frank Padavan, a Republican from
Queens who has sponsored the measure for four years. ``There is
widespread support for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Padavan said he smokes More cigarettes, made by R.J. Reynolds,
and has not noticed a difference in taste since they were altered
to stop burning.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, confirmed
that a vote would be held on Monday or Tuesday. Given that the bill
is likely to have unanimous support among the 25 Senate Democrats
and has been sponsored by 15 of the 36 Republicans, its passage is
assured.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan McCormick, a spokesman for the Philip Morris Cos., the
world's largest cigarette maker, said the industry's opposition was
not motivated by a fear of lower sales, but rather the desire for a
single national standard for flammability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this should be addressed at the federal level,'' he
said. ``We're going to continue to fight this.''
</P>
<P>
   The requirement that all cigarettes sold in New York meet a fire
safety standard would go into effect on Nov. 1, 2001. The bill
provides for heavy fines for failure to comply.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides that if the federal government establishes a
national standard, the New York law will automatically be voided.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes are the leading cause of fatal fires in New York,
resulting in 48 fire deaths statewide in 1997, the most recent year
for which figures are available, according to the state Office of
Fire Prevention and Control.
</P>
<P>
   Congress began considering fire safety standards for cigarettes
in the 1980s, but the idea met with fierce opposition from tobacco
companies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Each year he has introduced the bill, Padavan has won a few more
Republican co-sponsors. But not until this week did Bruno indicate
that he was willing to permit a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Legislature was deeply embarrassed by revelations
that a lobbyist for Philip Morris had paid for expensive meals and
other gifts for more than 100 legislators _ often apparently in
violation of the state's ethics law _ and then had failed to report
the spending, as required. Eager not to be seen as under the
influence of an increasingly unpopular industry, lawmakers in
December approved new lobbying restrictions and an increase of 55
cents per pack in the cigarette tax, to $1.11, the highest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But Padavan maintained that a more prosaic factor had changed
the minds of his colleagues on the fire safety bill. He said they
no longer feared that the industry would be unable to comply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
