<HEADLINE>
JETS CONSIDERING MORE DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see FBN-JETS-TRADE) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No team in the National Football League has ever been in the
position in which the New York Jets currently find themselves:
owners of four first- round picks in the college draft, which takes
place this weekend. Oh, so many choices; oh, so little time.
</P>
<P>
   After trading the star wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson to Tampa
Bay for the Buccaneers' two first-round selections, the Jets now
hold four No. 1 picks: 13, 16, 18 and 27. The Jets have the power
to completely manipulate the direction of the draft and amazingly,
are working the telephones to discuss making more trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's the Jets' world,'' said one general manager on
a division rival team, ``and that makes me a little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   It is making everyone nervous. Now the question is this: What
will the Jets do with all of that draft-day firepower? The answer
is, not even the Jets know, or at least right now they do not know.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that the Jets have contacted at least a
half-dozen teams _ maybe more _ in the past 48 hours about a
possible trade, according to one of the teams the Jets have spoken
with. The man doing most of the dialing is Bill Parcells, who is
clearly directing the Jets' draft, probably his last before he
rides off into the television analyst sunset.
</P>
<P>
   The main theory making the rounds now _ and these theories
change hourly _ is that the Jets are considering moving up between
Baltimore's fifth spot and Pittsburgh's eighth spot to draft
Michigan State's Plaxico Burress, a 6-foot-5{-inch, 229-pound
player with grace and size. He reminds the Jets of another player _
guess who? _ Keyshawn Johnson. The Jets are also looking at the
defensive linemen Corey Simon of Florida State and Shaun Ellis from
Tennessee. They may also covet Bubba Franks, the Miami tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells spoke to the Ravens on Tuesday and asked if they would
be interested in a possible trade, and the Ravens said they would
be, depending on their own circumstances. In addition to the fifth
pick, Baltimore also has the 10th pick in the first round. The two
teams may talk later this week or on draft day.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has spoken to other teams with selections in the top 10
of the first round, including Philadelphia, Arizona and Pittsburgh,
team executives said. Parcells has also called Cincinnati to
inquire about the disgruntled Pro Bowl wide receiver Carl Pickens,
who wants to leave the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not work out a trade with Baltimore or another team
with a top-five pick, there is the possibility that the Jets might
use a combination of their second and third-round picks to entice,
say, Tennessee to give up the 30th pick in the first round. Thus,
league executives say, do not be surprised if the Jets end up with
five first-round selections by the time the draft gets under way on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells may be taking the approach of the former Dallas Cowboys
Coach Jimmy Johnson, who was constantly stockpiling picks. Johnson
was like a magician, turning one first-rounder into two.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are telling teams they have ruled out packaging the
picks and moving up to the No. 1 overall spot, which Cleveland
owns. But the Jets once said they were not going to trade Johnson,
either.
</P>
<P>
   When a team has four No. 1 picks, it can almost say, or do,
anything it wants. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-3RDLD-WRITE     04-12 1149
</HEADER>
