<HEADER>
A5141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RESEARCH-AD-COLUMN-NY     04-12 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW RESEARCH METHODS SEEK TO LEARN WHAT YOU REALLY
THINK 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An executive at Media Direct Partners in New York
noticed the problem in a focus group of several dozen balding men.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, which was developing direct response advertising for
a surgical hair replacement company, heard nearly all the men in
the focus group say they were not bothered by hair loss _ yet many
were wearing hats during interviews that took place indoors on a
warm day in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the people in the focus groups weren't
necessarily saying what they felt or thought,'' said David
Reinbach, Media Direct's new business manager. ``They were saying
what they thought we wanted to hear or what they wanted us to
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   It is probably the worst-kept secret in the advertising research
business. Much of the research measuring advertising effectiveness
relies on verbal responses to questions about what consumers think
and feel. But what people actually think and feel is not
necessarily what they tell researchers, for reasons that could
include anything from not wanting to appear critical to perhaps not
being fully conscious of their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an estimated $87.5 billion was spent on advertising,
but no one can say with absolute certainty what actually works.
Advertisers typically use long-established tools like focus groups
and quantitative surveys to judge advertising _ and about $120
million is spent in advertising research _but the process is at
best an inexact social science.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem is that advertisers cannot read the consumer's
mind _ yet. But they are working on it. In the last several years,
new research methods have been developed that could make it easier
to gauge that ultimate wild card _ the emotions. Several of the
tools, like brain-wave tracking or measurement of the skin's
reaction, rely on physiology to get at what consumers really want _
whether they know it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Such research is valuable to advertisers because _ as in a lie
detector test _ reactions typically cannot be consciously
controlled by the respondent. Companies want to know how consumers
feel so they can create advertising and products that resonate with
the public and better predict their success.
</P>
<P>
   Research to measure emotional response has existed for decades.
What is new is that computers, video and other technologies have
made the research less expensive to conduct and less invasive for
the consumers who participate in the tests, typically for a nominal
fee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the methods at this point are hardly in the mainstream,
and there is skepticism. One problem with physiological measurement
is that it is hard to interpret what the results mean, said Jim
Spaeth, president of the Advertising Research Foundation in New
York. The body or brain can signal arousal at a certain point in a
commercial, but it may not be clear whether the response is
positive or negative. Does the heightened interest mean the person
likes what he sees or is irritated by it?
</P>
<P>
   Inner Response, a consumer research firm in Charlotte, N.C., is
marketing a new tool called MindView that tracks basal skin
response to a television commercial or other stimuli. The
measurement is taken by tiny sensors placed on the upper palm of
one hand, which are wired to equipment that tracks the skin's
subtle reactions, 10 times a second.
</P>
<P>
   What MindView is tracking is the automatic responses that the
skin has to stimuli. Jack Shimell, president of Inner Response,
compared it to the way muscles automatically tense in reaction to
potential danger. Such a response can be seen in cats when they
unconsciously arch their backs in fear, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you're a trained spy or something, you're not able to
control it,'' Shimell said. ``It's revealing what you're
unconsciously feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The MindView data is combined with data from other sources to
come up with a ``viewer involvement profile,'' he said. Inner
Response has been working with skin conductance measures for 11
years, for clients that have included Miller Brewing, McDonald's
and Coca-Cola. Company But last year it perfected the MindView
system, which Shimell said was cheaper, easier and achieved results
faster. Ten years ago, a test would have required renting studio
time and costly equipment at a price tag of about $100,000, or
about 10 times today's price, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Capita Research Group has created a system based on
electroencephalogram brain-wave measurements that NASA uses to
gauge the alertness of commercial airline pilots. The consumers
being tested wear headsets while watching commercials. Their
engagement levels, or attention levels, are picked up five times a
second and graphed like an EEG, then overlaid on the television
commercial for the client's use.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called engagement index graphically shows the ebb and
flow of attention, but it does not answer why engagement levels
vary. The index is usually used as a diagnostic tool in conjunction
with other data, said David B. Hunter, Capita's founder and
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can measure eyeballs watching, but that doesn't tell you
if it's sinking in,'' said Hunter, who sold his direct response
agency to invest in Capita, which he took public. ``And that's what
our system addresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Another measure to determine what consumers feel uses pictures
instead of words. Marketed by AdSAM Emotional Response Modeling,
this system was developed over six years by Dr. Jon Morris, a
professor at the University of Florida in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said his system does not rely on physiological response.
It asks consumers to check off pictures representing their feelings
after watching a commercial. For instance, the pleasure scale shows
emotions ranging from smiling to frowning.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of using visual cues is that it measures emotion
without the biases of language. It is also cross-cultural, which is
increasingly important for companies trying to reach a broad
market, he said. And like the other methods, the research has
applications far beyond measuring advertising impact. AdSAM was
used recently to determine whether consumers wanted a cosmetics
counter to become self-service, Dr. Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising industry, though intrigued, has yet to embrace
new ways, critics say. Robert F. Lederer, publisher of Research
Business Report, an industry newsletter, said one reason might be
because the research industry is a bit stodgy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Market researchers are a very conservative lot and can be
difficult to adapt and accept new ways of doing things,'' Lederer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, advertising agencies have long investigated the idea of
measuring emotion, Spaeth said. Several major agencies already have
their own techniques to measure emotions. And researchers have
tried many other ways to get at consumers' feelings, from
psychological testing to hypnosis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem with using physiological data is determining
what it all means, he said. ``It could all be tremendously
valuable,'' he said, ``if we could really understand how to use
those measures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
