<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CASINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO ALLOW INDIAN CASINO MAY BE WEIGHED IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Republican leader of the State Senate said
Wednesday that he might take up a measure that would allow an
Indian casino to be opened in the Catskills, potentially moving the
state closer to approving the contentious plan.
</P>
<P>
   The comments by Joseph L. Bruno, the Senate majority leader,
come nearly a week after the U.S. Department of the Interior
granted the St. Regis Mohawk tribe permission to open a $500
million casino in the Catskills, provided that the state also
approves the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, a strong proponent of casino gambling, has
maintained that he has the authority to approve such a plan on
behalf of the state. But he has also proposed a bill seeking
approval from the Legislature to open a casino in resort areas like
the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's comments are significant because he has been extremely
reluctant to consider such gambling measures in the past, given the
intense opposition that such proposals face from antigambling
groups like the Roman Catholic Church and the state's Conservative
Party.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, Bruno had been adamantly opposed to the
governor's bill for constitutional reasons. He took exception to a
provision in the bill that would permit slot machines in Indian
casinos, saying that the State Constitution forbids slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday afternoon, Bruno reiterated his
opposition to the provision in the governor's bill that would allow
slot machines on Indian reservations. But he said he would consider
taking up the measure as long as that provision was removed. ``I'm
looking at it because we may take some action,'' Bruno said, adding
that ``the biggest question we have is the constitutionality'' of
allowing slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department's decision last week helped clear the
way for the Mohawks to operate eventually a $500 million casino in
the Catskill community of Monticello, where government officials
and business leaders have hoped that gambling might bolster the
economy of a fading resort area that was once commonly known as the
borscht belt.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for the Mohawks to operate the casino on a
30-acre parcel that was put in trust for the tribe, whose
reservation is on the Canadian border. The casino, which would be
only 90 miles from New York City, is expected to employ 3,000
people and draw 9 million visitors a year. In 1997, a measure that
would have legalized casino gambling statewide was defeated in the
Senate amid intense opposition from antigambling groups. The
Democratic speaker of the Assembly, Sheldon Silver, has repeatedly
said he favored opening casinos in the Catskills and other resort
areas, and he has pushed legislation through his chamber that would
permit casino gambling in the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
