<HEADLINE>
KANSAS EDUCATION BOARD EXPLAINS SCIENCE STANDARDS DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KATE BEEM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Kan. _ A year after they first appeared before the Kansas
Board of Education, the state's new science standards were back
Wednesday, at least in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   One board member asked to start a dialogue on the standards in
Kansas newspapers and to sponsor ``informative debates'' to explain
the board's intent when it passed them.
</P>
<P>
   That motion failed. But the board did approve 6-3 a cover letter
for the standards, which will go out soon to the state's 304 school
districts. The letter will explain the board's efforts to
``strengthen'' the standards and clarify what students in Kansas
schools should learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the calls and e-mails I've received, the public
doesn't understand what the board did,'' John Bacon, a conservative
board member from Olathe, said in proposing the public relations
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What the board did in August was approve science standards that
contain microevolution, or variation within a species, but not
macroevolution, or change from one species to another.
</P>
<P>
   The standards, which are curriculum guidelines for school
districts, also do not mention the age of the earth or the big-bang
theory of the universe's origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of those items in the standards does not prevent
schools from providing instruction in those areas,'' the cover
letter says. ``While it is the hope and intent of the state board
that all schools will teach up to the standards, each school also
has the ability to teach beyond the standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the cover letter were moderate board member Harold
Voth of Haven and conservative board members Bacon, Linda Holloway
of Shawnee, Mary Douglass Brown of Wichita, Steve Abrams of
Arkansas City and Scott Hill of Abilene. The same six board members
voted in August for the revised science standards.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon's public relations motion was challenged by moderate board
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has any elected body made a decision and then had to go out
and debate the decision made?'' Janet Waugh asked. ``The board took
action. Now the consequences are to be followed through.'' Waugh is
a moderate board member from Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Waugh also questioned why Bacon would suggest publicly defending
the board's decision eight months after the fact. The education
community already understands the magnitude of the board's
decision, and the ball has been rolling for a few months now on
writing new tests based on the standards, she said. School
districts soon will receive copies of the new standards.
</P>
<P>
   The time to speak was last fall, Waugh said. Now, with an
election cycle under way, any public campaign would be
inappropriate, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this board table is the proper platform for an
election campaign,'' Waugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the six members who supported the science standards are
up for election this year: Holloway, Brown, Abrams and Hill, of
Abilene .
</P>
<P>
   Holloway has announced her intention to run, and Brown and
Abrams said they planned to. Hill has said he will not seek a
second term.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill supported Bacon's suggestion to engage in discussions
with the public about the science standards. Hill said the issue
was one of the most emotional he had ever encountered.
</P>
<P>
   And it's frustrating for the board to continually be attacked by
the Kansas science community, Hill said. At least one speaker each
month has addressed the science standards at the board's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sat here for six months, listening to the science
community rant and rave,'' Hill said. ``Do we ever get an
opportunity to say what we actually passed? Or do we have to listen
to this one-sided diatribe forever and ever?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown seconded Hill. She said she didn't understand why members
of the science community continued to pester the board when the
decision was ``over and done with.''
</P>
<P>
   Waugh explained: ``It's not over and done with, because I do
think it probably will be a re-election issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon's motion failed 5-4, with Voth and fellow moderates Waugh,
Val DeFever of Independence and Bill Wagnon of Topeka voting
against it. The board must have six votes to pass a motion.
Moderate Sonny Rundell of Syracuse was not at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The board met Wednesday at Troy High School in northeast Kansas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
