u f BC-AMDEARNINGS-NYT     04-12 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE MICRO POSTS STRONG EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 EARNINGS-NYT By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Driven by strong sales of its Athlon
microprocessors, Advanced Micro Devices Inc. posted first-quarter
earnings on Wednesday that were nearly double even Wall Street's
revised estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Although Advanced Micro said last week that it expected to
report sales of more than $1 billion for the quarter, a record, the
strength of its financial results still surprised many analysts.
Advanced Micro's growth was all the more startling on a day when a
key analyst reduced his estimates for the Microsoft Corp., citing
slower than expected personal computer sales.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter that ended April 2, Advanced Micro reported
earnings of $189.3 million, or $1.15 a diluted share, compared with
a loss of $128.4 million, or 88 cents a share, in the period a year
earlier. Sales rose 73 percent, to $1.09 billion from $631.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Advanced Micro to report earnings of 58
cents a share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. In
February, before Advanced Micro first revised its outlook for
first-quarter results, analysts expected profit of 32 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Before Advanced Micro reported the results, its shares closed at
$68, down 31.25 cents. In after-hours trading, they surged as high
as $76.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Advanced Micro's strong results could help
stabilize the Nasdaq and technology stocks in general, especially
if it is followed by other companies meeting or exceeding
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMD had the best quarter in its history,'' said W.J. Sanders
III, the company's chairman and chief executive. ``Each of our
product groups reported significant growth in the first quarter.
With a stronger product portfolio than at any time in our history,
we look forward to continuing growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Advanced Micro was fielding for the first
time in years a product line that can compete with the Intel Corp.
In the past, Advanced Micro either lagged behind in performance or
was unable to produce its fastest chips in high volumes, but these
problems appear to have been addressed with Athlon.
</P>
<P>
   Although a handful of companies produce microprocessors
compatible with those made by Intel, Advanced Micro has been the
most aggressive in terms of meeting, and at times beating, Intel in
absolute performance and has the broadest product line of all the
competitors. During the quarter, Advanced Micro shipped the
industry's first 1-gigahertz microprocessor. Although Intel rapidly
matched it, the symbolic value was significant.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway began using Advanced Micro chips again in January after
a long hiatus and Compaq, IBM and CyberMax have announced products
using Athlon processors. And last week, Dell Computer, which is the
only one of the top 10 computer makers that has never used Advanced
Micro processors, confirmed that it was in talks with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Although Advanced Micro's strong results seem at odds with news
of a weak quarter for computer makers, that is not really the case,
said Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock
Letter. ``The talk that you're hearing out of Microsoft and Micron
about weak PC sales entirely relates to the corporate market,''
where purchases were deferred until the release of Windows 2000 on
Feb. 17, he said. ``The retail market, which is AMD's primary
market, was just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The other factor was that Advanced Micro finally appears to have
its manufacturing house in order. ``We heard their yields went
through the roof,'' Murphy said. ``Give them credit. They've done a
great job of getting even with, or even a little ahead of Intel.''
</P>
<P>
   Although primarily known as a maker of microprocessors
compatible with those of Intel, Advanced Micro benefited from
strong sales of cellular phones and electronic devices, which
increased demand for its flash-memory chips. At $327 million, sales
for Advanced Micro's memory division were up 150 percent over those
in the quarter a year earlier. The company said it expected that
demand for flash-memory devices would continue to exceed supply for
the rest of the year and into 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
