<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5150 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-12 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW NOT TO CONDUCT LABOR TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the reams of U.S. labor and employment
law, there is a glaring omission. Somewhere there should be a law
that requires a third-party transcription of every labor
negotiation-related phone call, casual restaurant discussion and
formal bargaining session.
</P>
<P>
   The result couldn't be any more expensive or troublesome than
the we-said, they-said explanations and finger pointing that follow
failed labor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since things fell apart between Associated Wholesale
Grocers and Teamsters Local 955 in Kansas City, Kan., area grocery
customers and curious observers have begged the media to ``just
tell us the truth.'' Consumers are weary and suspicious of the
competing full-page ads and TV commercials battling for their
sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I heard detailed explanations from Doug Carolan,
president and chief executive of Associated, and Bobby Davidson,
president of the Teamsters local, about the impasse that occurred
when the union contract expired April 1. Listening was both a
privilege and a pain, given the animosities and economic fallout
for so many.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, both men came with allies and attorneys to sit at
conference tables at The Kansas City Star. Both were pleasant and
passionately concerned about protecting the interests of their
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   But the end result of a couple of hours of listening is this:
There are two versions of ``the truth,'' and only a very busy fly
on the wall _ which also would have to have been buzzing around
(BEGIN ITALICS)inside(END ITALICS) some key participants' heads _
could stitch the two versions together into ``the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   I was not that fly, so my hindsight is based on hearsay, but
here are some of my, no doubt, imperfect perceptions:
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, metaphorically speaking, the union still was playing
a neighborhood softball game when the company was winding up with a
hard fastball pitch in a whole new ball game. It's impossible to
say whether the signals were sent and missed or never sent.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the union negotiators thought they'd still be able
to play ball even after Mama called them home to dinner; instead,
they were thrown off the field before they realized it was getting
dark.
</P>
<P>
   Union reps contend they are not ``at an impasse,'' as the
company states. The Teamsters say that they will go back to the
bargaining table at any time and that they repeatedly and
specifically tried to address every issue the wholesaler brought
up. The offer seems to be too late; Associated has no intention of
listening.
</P>
<P>
   Associated says the union's proposals ``didn't go far enough''
to help them control costs. The union counters that it offered to
make changes but that the company refused to give them specific
targets to hit. Every company has the right to shave expenses, but
it seems it could have shared specific cost-cutting goals and
planned procedures earlier in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Associated says the Teamsters ``failed to grant'' them
negotiating sessions when they wanted them last fall to avoid
down-to-the-wire problems. It's clear the union reps didn't
understand that Associated was treating last October with the same
urgency as if it were March.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, by the way, acknowledged canceling or postponing a
few negotiating sessions because of family illnesses or scheduling
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters say Associated failed to bargain in good faith, as
the law requires, right up to the end of the contract. That does
seem to be so. In many collective bargaining cases, even if new
terms weren't agreed to by the contract expiration date, extensions
were received and bargaining continued. That's the model the
Teamsters assumed still existed. It obviously did not.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty days in advance of the contract expiration date, an
Associated human resource officer asked the local union presidents
from Kansas City and Springfield to meet him at a Bob Evans
restaurant in Springfield to discuss the status of the
negotiations. At the restaurant, the officer gave the union reps
Associated's notice of intent to contract out the warehouse and
delivery jobs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same moment, other Associated managers were announcing
the decision on bullhorns, standing in the warehouses. The union
officers asked for a delay in the announcement so they could talk
to their members first. It looks to me as if the company was
begging for a wildcat strike (which didn't happen) and was
disingenuous in setting up the restaurant meeting with the union
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale company is being patently ridiculous when it
attempts to separate the grocery stores it supplies from the labor
strife. Owners of the grocery stores are members of Associated's
board of directors. They are Carolan's boss. Any board,
particularly of a cooperative organization, that does its duty
knows exactly what the corporate policy and intent is.
</P>
<P>
   It seems clear to me that Associated decided well in advance of
the contract expiration date that it would turn over operations of
its warehouse and delivery operations to nonunion subcontractors.
Regardless what language Associated used, union workers were locked
out when the contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   The new employment offers extended to the warehouse workers are
superior financially to the re-employment ``opportunities'' offered
the truckers. It's impossible to judge the pros and cons of the
re-employment offers in the same breath.
</P>
<P>
   A loyal union member would say it's heresy to suggest accepting
the nonunion re-employment offer from CSI, the subcontractor chosen
by Associated to take over warehouse operations. I certainly
couldn't counsel either way.
</P>
<P>
   But it does appear that the re-employment offer on the table for
warehouse workers is financially comparable to their current union
wages and benefits. Provided the CSI offer is in good faith and
stays in place, it is a way for warehouse workers to keep their
jobs and maintain their current standards of living.
</P>
<P>
   The re-employment offer to the truckers is a mess. The
late-breaking offer from Associated was that the truckers may
``lease to own'' their tractors over two years _ at $100 a month _
if they choose to go to work for, and stay employed with, Perryman
Refrigerated Lines, the delivery subcontractor chosen by
Associated.
</P>
<P>
   A tractor for $2,400? Sounds good, right? I don't think so. The
expenses of owning and operating your own tractor, dependent on the
delivery hours the company will give you and the government will
allow, make a good living nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, some of the tractors that would be sold already
have hundreds of thousands of miles on them. Maintenance needs are
staggering. Again, I couldn't counsel anyone, but I wouldn't leap
at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I'm saddened by a pitiful lack of communication,
lack of understanding and seeming lack of good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Who is most at fault?
</P>
<P>
   Ask the fly that wasn't there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
