<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5151 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-VIRGIN-SUICIDES-2TAKE     04-12 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGIN-SUICIDES-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFIA COPPOLA'S SECOND CHANCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   Graham Fuller is the movie columnist for Interview magazine and the
editor of ``Loach on Loach,'' about the director Ken Loach.  
 By GRAHAM FULLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Virgin Suicides,'' the dreamy first feature film
written and directed by Sofia Coppola, five sisters, ages 13 to 17,
who live in a leafy Michigan suburb in the 1970s inexplicably and
matter-of-factly kill themselves. Their story, an unsolved mystery
laced with lust, obsession, longing, fantasies and gilded memories,
is recounted 25 years after by a neighborhood boy, now a rueful
adult, who worshiped Therese, Mary, Bonnie, Lux and Cecilia Lisbon
from afar.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Jeffrey Eugenides' lyrical 1993 novel, the movie
might have been a prurient wander through the bedrooms of its
lovely nymphs, an exploitative riff on teen-age angst, or a
cautionary drama _ think ``Five American Beauties, Interrupted'' _
with an earnest social message. But what Coppola has made of it is
a haunting metaphysical celebration of adolescence with the aura of
a myth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on the surface, there is something wrong with this picture:
how can a film in which a quintet of apparently normal girls commit
suicide possibly be a celebration, and why would a filmmaker
attempt to make it so unless she is uncommonly perverse? Not that
Coppola omitted all the details of societal decay and cosmic
malaise that Eugenides wove into his novel _ although anyone who
speaks at length with her would doubt she possesses an ounce of
perversity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, David Lynch, for one, has carefully hidden his
penchant for all-American degeneracy under a boyish ``Gee whiz!''
persona. But Coppola is apparently guileless, or so it seemed to me
when we met to talk about her remarkable debut.
</P>
<P>
   While she recently married the director Spike Jonze, whose film
``Being John Malkovich'' suggests a Dada-like weirdness in his
world view, Coppola comes across as an unassuming woman a good deal
younger than her 28 years. She talks eagerly about her film, but
answers must be coaxed from her and we will to get to those later.
First, like the unseen narrator, who with his friends tried to
unravel the irresolvable riddle of the legendary Lisbon sisters, we
need clues.
</P>
<P>
   Delving into Coppola's career immediately prompts another
mystery: why would she even want to make movies? Her initial forays
into the film business as an adult were thankless. At the age of
17, she designed the costumes and opening credit sequence of and
co-wrote Francis Ford Coppola's segment of ``New York Stories''
(1989). It was a precious tale about a privileged little girl, and
Coppola was suspected of diverting her father, the director of
``The Godfather'' and ``Apocalypse Now,'' from his auteur's vision.
</P>
<P>
   Worse was in store. Shortly after, she agreed to play Mary
Corleone in her father's ``Godfather Part III'' (1990) when Winona
Ryder pulled out of the film at the last minute. Coppola's
performance was as mannered as it was plucky, but it scarcely
warranted the critical mauling it received.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely painful,'' she recalled. ``If it had been my
dream to be an actress and that's what I'd been training to do, I
think it would have hurt so much more, but I didn't have all my
hopes wrapped up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola said: ``A lot of people thought Sofia was pursuing an
acting career and that I gave her a big break because I was her
father. But I'd gone to her when she was about to go back to school
and said, `Look, I'm in a spot _ can you help me?' If you compare
her so-called bad performance with the work of seasoned actresses,
then it's clear she had no training, but I thought her awkwardness
as a non-professional was touching. As so often happens, the
criticism was a way people could punish me through her.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola avoided movies for the next few years and, by her own
admission, became a dilettante. After leaving the California
Institute for the Arts in 1991, she was the co-host of Comedy
Central's short-lived talk show ``High Octane,'' took photos for
magazines, designed her own clothing line and modeled.
</P>
<P>
   She felt the absence of a vocation. ``I could do a little of
this and a little of that, but I never had the patience to study
one thing and become an expert at it,'' she said. ``I was mixed up
about what I was supposed to do and afraid I would wake up one day
not having done anything with my life. I realize now it helps to be
a generalist if you want to make films.''
</P>
<P>
   She never consciously decided to become a filmmaker, but in 1995
became fixated on adapting ``The Virgin Suicides.'' At the time it
was a fool's errand, given that Muse Productions, an independent
company run by Chris and Roberta Hanley, owned the rights and had
signed another filmmaker to direct his own adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   Going against her father's advice to adapt a book for which the
rights were available, Coppola says she wrote down the word
``opening'' and started highlighting scenes from the novel. ``I
didn't think about plot because the book jumps around so much in
time,'' she said. ``And I didn't realize until after I'd written my
script that at the end of each act there's a party scene, but
that's because I didn't think in terms of acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Muse Productions passed on the first adaptation and
invited Coppola to direct her script. Her father, who said his
daughter had been a visually oriented child with little interest in
literature, was impressed with the clarity of her script _
``Although it was an odd subject from my point of view,'' he said _
and came on board as one of the film's producers.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola, meanwhile, proceeded to direct a 14-minute
black-and-white film she had written with a friend. A deft moral
fable about a smug high school ringleader whose plan to poison some
of her fellow students ends in her ostracism, Coppola's ``Lick the
Star'' revealed her particular taste for images of bland suburban
landscapes and of adolescent girls caught in a state of dreamy
self-absorption.
</P>
<P>
   One overhead shot of a girl submerged in a bath, reminiscent of
John Everett Millais' painting ``Ophelia,'' was echoed in the
opening moments of ``The Virgin Suicides'' when Cecilia Lisbon
attempts suicide for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola now dismisses ``Lick the Star'' as ``like an old term
paper,'' but it demonstrated her facility for storytelling through
the use of tableaus and montages, rare in Hollywood filmmaking with
its reliance on uncluttered frames and sequential cutting. She got
the chance to give full rein to her impressionistic style when she
filmed ``Virgin Suicides'' on location in Toronto in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although Coppola suggested some key crew members to his
daughter, his involvement during shooting was minimal. ``I visited
the set for three days,'' he said. ``The rest of the time I was
available on the phone and Sofia did call me with a couple of
problems _ for example, when one of the young actresses broke out
in a rash and Sofia was getting pressure to fire her. So I was a
kind of a Yoda.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Turner, who plays the Lisbon sisters' dowdy and
obsessively controlling mother opposite James Woods as their weak,
ineffectual father, said she ``required Sofia to help me stay
brave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agreed to the body padding, to the brown polyester dresses,
to wearing no makeup _ and every time I stepped in front of a
mirror, I shuddered,'' she said. ``But Sofia constantly told me
that my work was good and that what I was doing was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Dunst, who gives an iconographic performance as the
sexually precocious 14-year-old Lux, had her own concern. After Lux
is seduced and unaccountably abandoned by her smitten beau, Trip
Fontaine (Josh Hartnett), on the school football field after the
homecoming dance, she begins to smuggle random males onto the
family rooftop for sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first movie in which I've played a promiscuous
character,'' Dunst said, ``and I was worried it wouldn't be done in
a classy way, but Sofia knew exactly how to handle my scenes. I do
think, though, that this would have been a completely different
movie if a man had directed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola uses the suicides bookending the film as a framing
metaphor for the passing of the teen years _ of which the Lisbon
sisters, frozen for all time by their deaths, are idealized
symbols. Coppola is also fascinated by what she describes as the
``epicness'' of teendom.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the most calamitous event in the movie is not
Cecilia's fatal plunge from her bedroom window, which ignites the
story, or the concluding suicides of her sisters, but Trip's
callous desertion of Lux. The close-up of Lux traveling home alone
by taxi in the blue light of dawn after her sexual humiliation is
the bleakest image in a film that otherwise luxuriates in
epiphanies of post-pubescent girlhood _ not that it shrinks from
realities like menstruation or one sister's capacity for meanness
to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought `The Virgin Suicides' was about suicide at
all,'' Coppola said. ``The reason I got involved in the first place
was that I didn't want to see a film of this book that was going to
be morbid, violent or sexual. What I loved about it when I first
read it was that it's like a celebration of first love and how that
haunts you forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its real theme is loss and the idea that things happen in life
that you have no explanation for. The story is made up of memories
and fragments of memories, and the feeling I got from it is that
you can never figure out what they all mean until you stop trying,
and then you just remember the essences of people _ and of the time
when they were suddenly gone and how it changed everything.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Everyone goes through something like that.'' In May
1986, Gian-Carlo Coppola, the older of her two brothers, was killed
in a speedboat accident at the age of 22. ``That was my experience
of loss,'' she said, ``although I didn't consciously realize its
connection to the story until after I'd started filming. But even
if someone's life is very short and you can't find a logical
explanation for it, you do end up with the feeling that their life
wasn't lived in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Eugenides' novel nor Coppola's film probes the
psychological or sociological reasons its heroines kill themselves.
The book cites, with calculated half-heartedness, some statistics
about teen suicides. Coppola, not remotely interested in whys, has
fun satirizing a predatory, narcissistic television newswoman who,
after Cecilia's death, stalks her grieving sisters on their
doorstep and is given to trite analyses of the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tragedy at its core, the film is driven by idylls
and reveries. There is an intensely feminine pastoral interlude _
complete with a unicorn and glowing images of the sisters _
inspired by the boys' reading of the dead Cecilia's diary and its
revelation that the libidinous Lux had a crush on a hunky
garbageman.
</P>
<P>
   There are the exotic ``vacations,'' depicted as a series of
snapshots, on which the boys imagine accompanying the sisters
(including the resurrected Cecilia). Lastly, we witness the boys'
``rescue'' of the four surviving girls in which they drive the
sisters away from their doom seconds before we see what has already
come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola clearly intuited how to evoke cinematically the mythical
aura in which the novel enshrouds the Lisbon girls, turning them
into phantoms in the boys' minds _ the kind of phantoms of
long-gone love objects most of us harbor.
</P>
<P>
   However, when asked if he felt the film enhanced this mythic
quality, Eugenides said he always believed that having live actors
play the girls, while unavoidable, ``would rob them of some of the
mysteriousness or unknowability I tried to give them in the book.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My own feeling is that the point of view in the movie comes
more from the girls than is the case in the book,'' he said. ``The
audience is constantly reminded that the story is being told by the
boys, that all this information is therefore suspect, but it's hard
to keep that in mind when you're watching a 20-foot-tall Kirsten
Dunst on the screen. She seems very real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he added, ``I always knew that the film would be
Sofia's vision of my book. What else could it be? Some translation
had to take place. The book was never written to be a movie. Many
people thought it couldn't be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Having been the one to pull it off, Coppola admitted it was a
relief to find a career. ``I like the idea of directing another
film,'' she said. ``But there's something to be said for going into
something when you're completely naive and don't know what you're
getting yourself into. I felt so strongly about `The Virgin
Suicides' that I never stopped to think about the end result or
that people would actually watch it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
