<HEADER>
A5154 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-L     04-12 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON ENJOYING `GOOD FORTUNE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Underachieving a year ago, unstoppable this season, the Lakers
have undergone an amazing transformation in a short period, but
coach Phil Jackson _ the favorite for coach of the year _ isn't
ready to declare this his best coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   But as he deflects credit for the Lakers' 65-13 record (with
four games to go), Jackson does take pride in the dominant run they
put together from just before the All-Star break to last week _ a
period in which the Lakers won 30 of 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game-to-game thing, I think,'' Jackson said of coaching
success. ``It's just like some days you hit them right and your
intuition's good, and the coaching staff are in sync, and other
times you're not.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one of those situations where we were in sync for
a couple months. That run we had that was a 30-something-game run,
31 games that we played together that were well done, was as well
orchestrated as any teams I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is saying something, considering that as Chicago Bulls
coach, Jackson won 72 games in 1995-96, 69 games in 1996-97 and 67
games in 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan had a lot to do with those numbers, of course.
But Jackson dismisses the notion that he takes pride in winning
without Jordan's assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the fact that Michael was maybe the most
competitive player I ever coached in my life, and one of the great
players,'' Jackson said. ``And I think it's quite obvious that
playing without him one year we had a really good record (55-27 in
1993-94), the other year (47-35 in 1994-95) we struggled a little
bit as we changed our lineup and our roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have the horses to win in this game, and it's
great to coach a great season without talent, beating your head
against a wall in many situations, and feeling like every play is
critical to your odds. It's another to have talent and to measure a
season and measure a team and the process of how you want to teach
and coach in a long-term aspect. That's been my good fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that fortune repeats, and Jackson rides Shaquille O'Neal
and Kobe Bryant to a title, will be known soon enough. The playoffs
begin in nine days.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we do in the playoffs is altogether different,'' Jackson
said. ``Michael was a big-time playoff player. And so were the
players that grew up with him in the '90s, and they learned how to
do it in critical situations. We're going to have to find out about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   KNIGHT TIME: O'Neal's recent two-game absence gave the Lakers'
backup centers a chance to make an impression. The final tally:
Travis Knight averaged 3.0 points, 4.0 rebounds, 1.5 blocks and 4.0
fouls in 19.0 minutes. John Salley averaged 4.0 points, 4.5
rebounds, zero blocks and 3.5 fouls in 15.5 minutes. They combined
to make 6 of 22 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, they won't be rusty if needed in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good just to get out and kind of feel comfortable,''
said Knight, who is averaging just 6.4 minutes in 59 games.
``Sometimes, if you get in there for five minutes, it's tough to
really relax and get into the flow of the game. But you get in
there for eight, 10 minutes, you can kind of feel it a little bit
and relax.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY-A     04-12 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: with me.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But they've become critics' darlings and their recent tour,
their first, went so well that even they were surprised by the
turnout. ``We'd look at all these people and think, `Is someone
else coming on after us?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Millers' modest visibility doesn't exactly put them at the
sales level of the Dixie Chicks or Garth Brooks, but like Lucinda
Williams, who had huge success with her 1998 album ``Car Wheels on
a Gravel Road,'' the Millers are a reminder that alt.country acts
can occasionally find recognition outside the Nashville machine.
</P>
<P>
   But the Millers' story is also a reminder of just how hard it is
to be heard. Alt.country acts don't get played on country radio or
have videos on country music television. Their labels tend to be
small, scrappy independents like HighTone, where the Millers
record, Sugar Hill, Vanguard, E-Squared, Compass, Rounder,
Bloodshot, Philo, Lucky Dog, Oh Boy or the Nashville artists'
collective Dead Reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's enough talent and critical mass in the alt.
country world that a lot of people are trying to figure out how to
make it work. There's the alternative country press, online and
off. There are Internet lists, like one called Postcard2
(topsoil.net/postcard2.htm), where the faithful debate fine points
of alt.country minutiae like obsessive honky-tonk Trotskyites.
</P>
<P>
   There's an Americana record chart, kept by Gavin, the trade
magazine of the radio industry. The chart is based on reports from
93 stations, most of them small, which usually mix some of the
alternative country artists with mainstream country, a format known
as album adult alternative or TripleA.
</P>
<P>
   Shows on the Public Broadcasting System like ``Austin City
Limits'' and National Public Radio take the music much more
seriously than country radio does, and an Americana live showcase
and radio show, the ``Western Beat Roots Revival,'' graduates to
Country Music Television this summer. There's even a fledgling
trade group, the Americana Music Association
(www.americanamusic.org) formed in March to promote the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much talent there, it deserves a hearing,'' said
Jessie Scott of Gavin, which has had an Americana chart for five
years. ``This could be the next big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Next big thing might be a bit much to ask for. The alt.country
cast of characters is considerably short on the glitz and sex
appeal that dominates the music business from country to pop to
soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the alt.country folks are a little straggly,'' said
Miller, whose Circle of Dust baseball cap and Neil Young couture
give him all the glamour of a guy who should be fixing the
transmissions on old Chevys. ``I'm an old hippy. I'm too old to try
to put on a suit and play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And if much of the music is terrific, some comes across as
good-natured amateurism or roots rock weirdos in funny outfits
trying to sound like music a half century out of date. ``It's like
any other alternative music,'' he said. ``A lot under that umbrella
is just an excuse for playing medicore songs out of tune.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet country has always veered between the mainstream and the
backwoods, usually swinging back toward its roots when it got too
bland and homogenized. It's pretty darn bland right now, and
country radio is seeing its audience melt away, shrinking by 25
percent since 1994. The most talked-about song on country radio is
``Murder on Music Row'' by George Strait and Alan Jackson, which
rails against Nashville's long day's journey into pop.
</P>
<P>
   And, if it's not likely to attract the hot young mass audience
Nashville is lusting after, the Millers' music _ smart, evocative,
technically proficient, lyrically inventive _ at least has the
potential to reach a sophisticated audience, from college students
to the NPR/PBS constituency, that's a quiet, but sizable hunk of
the populace.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out how to link the music with the audience is the hard
part. ``I don't care too much about what label they put on it,''
Miller said. ``Americana's fine. I'm just glad there's a place for
us. I'm so out of it; when I made my first record, I thought I was
making a country record. Then I found out it was alternative
country or whatever it is. Like Julie says, `I like to think what
we do is country and what they play on the radio is the
alternative.' But that's the way it's always been. Radio is
basically like McDonald's _ you know, a billion customers served.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, after a lifetime of scuffling around the edge of
solvency, he's not complaining. Their next project is their first
record together, a series of country duets a la Dolly Parton and
Porter Wagoner, and Miller is booked with projects for the rest of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I never could have foreseen this,'' he said. ``When I
lived in L.A. I spent the end of every month trying to figure out
which guitar I had to sell to pay the rent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
