<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5158 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SISKEL-EBERT-FILMS-$A     04-12 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISKEL-EBERT-FILMS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOT AT THUMB-WRESTLING WITH ROGER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   Franz Lidz, a senior writer at Sports Illustrated, is the author of
``Unstrung Heroes,'' and writes frequently about film.  
 By FRANZ LIDZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching ``Siskel and Ebert at the Movies'' was a bit like being
fed intravenously: you never tasted anything, but eventually you
felt a kind of ghostly satiation.
</P>
<P>
   The show's appeal derived less from its film snippets and
critical insights than from the banter between the cheery, chubby
Roger Ebert and the diffident Gene Siskel, a dour presence with the
silhouette of a roll-on deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, these two Chicago newspapermen lacked the easy
rapport of, say, Hope and Crosby, or the bittersweet camaraderie of
Laurel and Hardy. What they shared was a chafing testiness _ a
novelty among TV co-hosts. Throwing up their arms with evident
dismay, they bickered and bellyached like Beckett tramps trapped in
some Movie Theater of the Absurd. You sensed they could barely
stand each other, an impression reinforced every time Siskel
snapped ``Roger, that's ridiculous!'' and unleashed a laugh that
was pure triumphant scorn.
</P>
<P>
   Siskel died at the age of 53 in February 1999. Since then, his
chair has been warmed by the rumps of reviewers drawn from a
defective Gene pool. Sessions have tended to play out like first
dates: guest critics seem more intent on pleasing Ebert than on
engaging him.
</P>
<P>
   So when Ebert invites me onto the show to play Siskel, I ask,
``Which would you prefer _ a courtship or a marriage?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it best when the other critic acts as if it's his
show,'' he says, ``and he doesn't know what the hell I'm doing on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be a cinch, I think. After all, how hard can talking
about films be? Some of the most prodigiously dim people I know are
on the tube, filling air time with blab.
</P>
<P>
   Before blowing into the Windy City, I screen the five films
under discussion, and consult a television boxing commentator for
tips. Be playfully pugnacious, he suggests, and act like you hate
Ebert. ``Nobody cares what you say on TV, it's how you say it,'' he
advises. ``Lean forward and pounce. Begin your arguments with `Yes,
Roger, but. ...' or `Roger, have we seen the same film?'''
</P>
<P>
   What if we agree?
</P>
<P>
   ``Agree! You (italics)never(end italics) agree. What do you
think this is, a symposium? People tune in to see you duke it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   I arrive a day early for a sparring session with one of Ebert's
producers. ``A dry run,'' he says. We face off in a make-believe
movie theater erected on the same sound stage on which Nixon
debated Kennedy and sweated away the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   I play Nixon. Nervous under the lights, I step steadily into an
opinion, then, in my mind, hear a playback of what I've just said.
It sounds idiotic. I stop uncertainly, scold myself for goofing up,
collect myself and move forward before collapsing on the far side
of a not-terribly-coherent thought. ``You'll be fine, tomorrow,''
the producer assures me. ``Just relax and ad-lib.''
</P>
<P>
   This is perhaps not the best counsel. The last time I ad-libbed
on television was on a Stupid Pet Tricks segment of David
Letterman's show. ``My parrot is learning to speak Waring
Blender,'' I cracked. ``But I can't let him get too close to mine.
He thinks it's a Jacuzzi.''
</P>
<P>
   As I was hurriedly ushered off the sound stage, I noticed how
Letterman's eyebrows were set in perplexed diagonals. I didn't
achieve instant stardom, nor did my parrot.
</P>
<P>
   So the next morning I approach the Ebert show with determined
intrepidness. In the production office, I spy a chubby man
gathering up a dozen DVDs and videos in his arms. ``Ah!'' he
announces. ``Freebies.'' It's Ebert, and I can't follow the advice
to hate him. He's too darn cheery. We stroll to the sound stage,
chatting amiably about everything except the movies we're about to
critique. Ebert says he doesn't want to lose the edge of
spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Our first film is ``Mission To Mars.'' Ebert opens with a flurry
of praise for its special effects and elegant camerawork. Like
Groucho Marx in one of the early Marx Brothers features, I feel a
strange interlude coming on. When Ebert gives the picture a
``marginal thumbs down,'' I lean forward, curve my lips into a
smirk and say: ``Yes, Roger, but. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Awarding the movie seven enthusiastic Martian thumbs down, I
brand it yet another paean to product placement: ``The Earthship is
saved by gravity-free Dr. Pepper, and human DNA turns out to be
composed of M &AMP; Ms. I don't know about you, Roger, but this film
critic is 60 percent Goobers and 40 percent Raisinets.''
</P>
<P>
   I look at Ebert, whose brows are set in Letterman-like
diagonals. ``Sit up straight,'' someone shouts at me. ``Your voice
is scratchy. Drink some water.'' Spread your hands on your knees,
says somebody else, and keep still. I try to do both, but can't:
I'm too busy drinking.
</P>
<P>
   We start again. ``Don't keep your legs apart.'' We start again.
``Don't look at the TV monitor.'' And again. ``Don't. ...'' And
again. And again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   Several Martian Ice Ages later, we get around to ``Ghost Dog:
The Way of the Samurai.'' Sitting stiffly, legs together, eyes
straight ahead, I raise my thumb to this fairy-tale fusion of Mafia
movies and samurai epics. A Spaghetti Eastern, I call it.
Alarmingly, Ebert raises his thumb, too. When the cross talk
bridges back to me, I growl, ``Roger, have we seen the same film?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought we both liked it,'' he says, brows now
permanently perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, (italics)I(end italics) liked it more.''
</P>
<P>
   We blunder on. When Ebert cheers the flimsy whimsy of Anjelica
Huston's ``Agnes Browne,'' I rally. ``Roger, as Tom Hanks said in
`Apollo 13': `Huston, we have a problem. ...''' Somebody cuts in:
``You can't say that. It sounds scripted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scripted. Too bad the movie wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   After three rounds of film talk, I'm gabbed out. My conversation
is all preoccupied pauses and hesitations, a soft fluttering of ums
and ahs. I feel like Annie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   I try to snap awake before jabbing at ``The Ninth Gate,'' a
wannabe thriller set in the always exciting world of rare book
collecting. The plot _ if that's the word for it _ has something to
do with a Satanic text illustrated and autographed by Lucifer
himself. (It's a limited edition.)
</P>
<P>
   I put on a waxy smile as I sense my TV career waning. Gamely, I
begin: ``My idea of hell used to be four blank walls and a radio
that only picked up `A Prairie Home Companion.' ... Ebert turns his
thumb down, too. I briefly consider reversing myself and giving
``The Ninth Gate'' its only favorable review. While I consider,
Ebert jabbers on and time runs out.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember the name of the final film. I have a feeling
Ebert liked it, and I didn't. Or maybe it was the other way around.
I do remember a producer hurriedly ushering me off the sound stage,
out the studio and into a waiting taxi.
</P>
<P>
   He called me at home the next day. ``Sorry, but we can't run the
segment,'' he said funereally. ``It's way too ... disjointed.''
</P>
<P>
   I think the footage ended up thumbs down in Lake Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
