u f BC-TV-FOX-MAKEOVER-NYT &LR;      04-12 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-MAKEOVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER `MILLIONAIRE' DEBACLE, FOX MAPS PROGRAMMING CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping a last official hand-rinse eliminates any lingering tar
left by the ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire'' fiasco, the
Fox Network is moving away from violent pets, crashing trains and
deadly swarms of insects and toward ghosts, UFOs and Egyptian
mummies.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, Fox executives put word out Wednesday about the results
of the internal investigation the network commissioned into how
Rick Rockwell, the bridegroom at the center of the marriage show,
had managed to hide the fact that he had been the subject of
restraining orders.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, Fox executives said, absolved both Fox and
the production company responsible for the show, Next
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by a law firm that has often worked for Fox's
parent company, News Corp., , essentially blamed Rockwell for not
fully disclosing his past.
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives expressed hope that this would close the book on
the special, which displayed 50 women vying for the hand of a
supposed multimillionaire, which set ratings records for Fox before
blowing up in a surge of bad publicity over Rockwell's background.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the effort to slam that book closed are the
changes that Sandy Grushow, the president of Fox Entertainment, has
ordered in Fox's programming, changes that will be most apparent
starting in two weeks, when the May ratings sweeps month begins.
</P>
<P>
   For the first sweeps month since announcing a policy eschewing
``exploitative specials,'' Fox has announced a list of specials
that include ``Ghosts, Fact or Fiction,'' ``Paranormal: Do You
Believe?'' ``UFOs The Best Evidence Caught on Tape 2'' and
``Opening the Tombs of the Golden Mummies _ Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening the Tombs'' is the special Fox is exhibiting as an
indication of its new direction in sweeps-month programming. It is
the second special Fox has produced in conjunction with the
Egyptian government, both based on the live opening of ancient
tombs. This one, however, is being planned with a consciously more
serious intent, starting with the host, the former ABC News anchor
Hugh Downs.
</P>
<P>
   One element of the show will involve the investigation of a
so-called prophecy, issued, Fox executives say, by several seers.
The seers predicted that an official hall of records, which might
house items like the blueprint for the pyramids, might be in a
chamber under one of the Sphinx's paws.
</P>
<P>
   The ghosts special will purport to display videotape evidence of
``allegedly ghostly phenomena.'' The paranormal special will
include psychics and seances.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such tabloid touches, these shows are a far cry from
what Fox was offering in the last May sweeps, which included ``When
Good Pets Go Bad.''
</P>
<P>
   They also represent a sharp departure from some of the specials
that might have showed up in May had Grushow not ordered them
canceled in the aftermath of the multimillionaire scandal, like
``Plastic Surgery Nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Grushow said Fox would no longer be in the business
of offering ``exploitative material.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Fox executive also said the one remaining weekly series
that seemed to fit the genre of crashing vehicles, ``World's
Wildest Police Videos,'' was ``heading for changes in the future.''
At the least, those changes are expected to include a title change
to ``Police Videos.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-CROWN-MEDIA-KAN &LR;      04-12 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROWN-MEDIA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLMARK'S CROWN MEDIA POSTPONES STOCK OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Hallmark Cards Inc. subsidiary that had
been set to sell stock today in one of its companies on the Nasdaq
has put the offering on hold after that exchange's composite index
fell 7.1 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the initial public offering gets the green light, it
will be the first time that people outside the greeting card giant
can own a little piece of Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   The planned IPO is for Crown Media Holdings Inc., an Englewood,
Colo., company that owns three cable television channels with
almost 55 million subscribers around the world. In 1999, Crown
Media lost more than $103 million on revenue of close to $50
million.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Media could not say Wednesday when it would reconsider
making the offer. The company is hoping to sell up to 20 percent of
its outstanding stock, or 12.5 million shares. The company is owned
by Hallmark Entertainment Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of
Hallmark Cards.
</P>
<P>
   The company consists of three cable channels _ Hallmark
Entertainment Network, the Odyssey Network and the Kermit Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Media's cable channels license programming primarily from
a division of Hallmark Entertainment, which includes the Hallmark
Hall of Fame library, the Jim Henson Co. and other third-party
entities. Hallmark Entertainment and the Jim Henson Co. each own
half of the Kermit Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday, when the Nasdaq continued its recent sell-off,
Crown Media expected to offer the stock at $19 to $21 a share. If
the stock sold out at those prices, it would give Crown Media
between $237.5 million and $262.5 million in new capital.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it planned to use the proceeds for a variety of
purposes, including:
</P>
<P>
   $30 million earmarked to pay accrued and unpaid licensing fees
to Hallmark Entertainment Distribution, a subsidiary of Hallmark
Entertainment, for the use of television programs it owns.
</P>
<P>
   $50 million set aside for additional licensing programming,
including about $25 million to license programs from Hallmark
Entertainment Distribution.
</P>
<P>
   $20 million to enhance technical facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The rest for expanding distribution and advertising sales staff
and financing other unnamed general corporate expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark will retain 100 percent of Crown Media's class B, or
``supervoting,'' shares, which have 10 votes for each share of
class A stock, the type being sold to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark ``is raising capital without giving any control up,''
said Mark Minichiello, a principal with Spin-Off Advisors in
Chicago. ``Because of the way the deal is structured, there is no
shareholder voice.''
</P>
<P>
   So who would want to buy the stock?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question,'' Minichiello said. ``Probably people
in that industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Minichiello said, is that Crown Media is losing
money, ``and they don't want to pay for those losses out of their
pocket, so they want to raise the money this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall Roth of Renaissance Capital Corp. in Greenwich, Conn.,
said the timing for any IPO was bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``All IPOs are going to be a tough sell right now,'' Roth said.
``There is going to be a tremendous liquidity problem with some of
those stocks, even if the fundamentals remain intact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
