<P>
   THIRD PARTIES
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN WOOS HOFFA: Patrick Buchanan, who is seeking the Reform
Party's presidential nomination, suggested Wednesday that he might
give James P. Hoffa, the president of the Teamsters' union, an
important position in trade negotiations if Buchanan is elected
president. Appearing at a Teamsters' rally in Washington, where
more than 3,000 union members protested a China trade bill,
Buchanan had kinds words for Hoffa, who shares many of Buchanan's
hard-line views on trade. In a reference to the U.S. trade
representative, Buchanan said, ``If I get there, it won't be
Charlene Barshefsky sitting down in Beijing, it'll be Jim Hoffa.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Steven Greenhouse
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN TO BOYCOTT FUND-RAISER: Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said
Wednesday that he would boycott an enormous Republican fund-raising
gala to be held here on April 26 in honor of the party's presumed
presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush. But the reason cited by
McCain, who was Bush's main rival in the primaries, was not sour
grapes. It was ``soft money,'' the unregulated donations to
political parties that McCain has been trying for years to banish.
Much of the $15 million that the event is expected to raise falls
into that category, and for that reason, McCain said, he will be
taking a pass.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Frank Bruni
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AD ON YAHOO!: For months, Gov. George W. Bush has had a
link on his Web site (www.georgewbush.com) called a tax calculator.
You put in your marital status, number of children, annual income
and percentage of income from a second earner, and it tells you how
much you would save under Bush's proposed $483 billion tax cut.
With tax returns due on Monday, the Bush campaign has begun to
advertise the tax calculator on Yahoo!, the popular Internet
portal. A caution: The calculator only accepts income up to
$100,000; more than half the savings under the Bush plan would go
to taxpayers with incomes above that.
</P>
<P>
   _ By David E. Rosenbaum
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS RUNOFFS
</P>
<P>
   IN LINE FOR ARCHER'S SEAT: Since the creation of west Houston's
7th Congressional District in 1965, the seat has been held by only
two men _ both Republicans _ former President George Bush and Rep.
Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, who is
retiring this year after 30 years in office. The third person to
hold the seat will very likely be state Rep. John Culberson. In a
Tuesday night runoff, Culberson crushed his well-financed opponent,
Peter Wareing, to capture the Republican nomination. Wareing, a
Houston businessman, reportedly spent more than $3 million, four
times what Culberson spent. But the big money was not enough to
overcome Culberson's grass-roots organization, as he collected 60
percent of the vote to Wareing's 40 percent. In one of the most
reliably Republican districts in the country, Culberson is expected
to win easily in November.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Jim Yardley
</P>
<P>
   PERENNIAL CANDIDATE WINS: A perennial statewide candidate with a
famous name but a failed political track record easily won the
Democratic nomination to oppose Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas.
In a runoff on Tuesday, Gene Kelly, who has lost six previous
races, easily defeated a former state legislator, Charles Gandy, 58
percent to 42 percent. Hutchison, the Republican incumbent, is
considered a heavy favorite in November.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Jim Yardley
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE
</P>
<P>
   MISSTEP FOR FLORIDA SENATE HOPEFUL: In going after the
Republican nomination in this year's contest for Florida's open
Senate seat, Rep. Bill McCollum, who was one of the House managers
of President Clinton's impeachment trial, has raised more than $3.5
million, three times as much as the other primary contender, state
Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher. But McCollum is paying a
price for one of his most recent cash-raising efforts _ a letter to
Spanish-speaking voters in which he wrote about the international
custody battle over Elian Gonzalez, accusing Fidel Castro of
``politically manipulating the life of this small 6-year-old boy.''
That pitch struck Bob Poe, the chairman of the Florida Democratic
Party, as political manipulation on the part of McCollum, and he
accused the congressman of seeing ``dollar signs in Elian's
tragedy.'' Then the editorial writers of The St. Petersburg Times
weighed in, accusing McCollum of ``breathtaking cynicism'' and
adding, ``Castro should send a letter complaining that the
congressman has stolen his idea.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   HOT ISSUES IN VIRGINIA: Taxes and education are the latest hot
issues in the Virginia Senate race, in which George Allen, the
state's former governor, is trying to unseat Charles S. Robb, the
two-term incumbent Democrat. Last Friday, Allen, a conservative,
proposed a 10-year, $345 billion education package, whose
centerpiece is a $1,000-a-year tax credit for such educational
expenses as computers, books and tutoring. Then on Monday, Allen
proposed a 10-year, $278 billion tax package that would end the
so-called marriage tax penalty and the inheritance tax and also
provide a tax break for long-term care of the elderly. Robb said he
had already proposed or endorsed each of those forms of relief and
that Allen was becoming a ``political kleptomaniac.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RACES
</P>
<P>
   INCUMBENT LEADS IN INDIANA: Gov. Frank O'Bannon of Indiana would
easily defeat either of two Republicans running to unseat him, a
recent poll showed. The survey, published in The Indianapolis Star,
shows that O'Bannon, a Democrat, leads his most likely opponent,
Rep. David M. McIntosh, by 53 percent to 36 percent, and is ahead
of the other Republican candidate, John Price, a lawyer, 67 percent
to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Dirk Johnson
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Austin, Texas, and Houston
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
