<HEADLINE>
COST OF HANFORD CLEANUP COULD DOUBLE, SAY OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ The already astronomical cost of treating
millions of gallons of radioactive waste at the Hanford Nuclear
Reservation could nearly double, threatening to again delay the
long-awaited cleanup, federal officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   BNFL, Inc., the lead contractor at the former nuclear weapons
production facility, recently told the U.S. Department of Energy
that it seriously underestimated the cost of cleaning up decaying
underground tanks that hold most of the world's high-level nuclear
wastes.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the company estimated the cost at just under $7
billion. Now, it says the price go as high as $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't justify the original cost estimate,'' said Mike
Lawrence, BNFL's Hanford waste treatment project manager. ``It was
flat wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy officials, meanwhile, said BNFL officials are flat wrong
if they think the agency and Congress will accept that kind of
price hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing it at the numbers we have now is pretty heavy lifting,''
said Richard French, manager of Energy's Office of River
Protection. ``Doing it at these new numbers is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   French said the Energy Department will decide how to proceed
after it gets a detailed proposal from BNFL on April 24. If it
rejects the proposal as too costly, the department has other
alternatives, including finding another contractor, French said.
</P>
<P>
   But that could mean missing deadlines recently set by the state
Department of Ecology, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts them in serious jeopardy,'' French said. ``It's not to
say it's impossible, but it would take extraordinary action on the
part of the Energy Department.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials and members of Washington's congressional
delegation Wednesday expressed concern about the cost increase, but
said they would withhold judgment until BNFL presented its
proposal. Lawrence said the company could trim the price to about
$9 billion by restructuring the financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary concern has been not on how it was funded or
financed, but with getting the (treatment) plant in the ground and
running,'' said Mike Wilson, manager of the state Ecology
Department's nuclear waste program.
</P>
<P>
   Hanford has 54 million gallons of radioactive waste in 177 large
steel-and-concrete underground storage tanks, and 67 tanks are
suspected to have leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden jump in the cost of treating tank waste is the latest
impediment in the decade-long Hanford cleanup effort. It also
renewed criticism of Energy's approach in removing dangerous
liquids that threaten groundwater supplies and the Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Energy opted for privatization. BNFL would invest about
$400 million and secure private financing to build and operate a
treatment facility, with the promise of returns of 35 to 40
percent. The federal government would not have to pay the company
until the start of treatment, which turns the waste into glass for
long-term storage.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is scheduled for full operation in 2009, with cleanup
completed in 2028.
</P>
<P>
   BNFL in 1998 estimated the cost at about $6.9 billion, and
launched the design of the facility that will encompass four major
buildings on 67 acres. The company also was to refine its estimates
and present a firm price. Energy officials said the approach would
avoid cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, the BNFL manager, said the company realized its
original estimate was too low as it developed the technology and
the design became more detailed. The process of turning volatile
waste into stable glass has been used before, but never on the
scale required at Hanford, Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most technical, challenging job in the country,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   BNFL estimates that about half the $13 billion would come in the
cost of interest on longterm financing. By paying down the debt
earlier, the cost could be cut to about $9 billion, Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   BNFL already has invested some $300 million on design and
testing, Lawrence said. Come April 24, he said, the company will
propose a facility that can do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with Energy, the federal government will
have to pay BNFL for its costs so far, regardless of whether it
accepts the BNFL proposal. French, the Energy Department official,
said his agency will thoroughly test the cost figures before
deciding whether to move ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the privatized approach said Wednesday the huge jump
in the estimated price has proved they were right two years ago
when they branded it a boondoggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no surprise we're looking at a failure and a mess,'' said
Tom Carpenter, nuclear oversight director of Government
Accountability Project, a citizens' watchdog group. ``I just wonder
if this company knows what they're doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
