<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Earnings Sharply Exceed Forecasts
</P>
<P>
   Driven by strong sales of its Athlon microprocessors, Advanced
Micro Devices posted first-quarter earnings that were nearly double
Wall Street's recently revised estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro reported earnings of $189.3 million, or $1.15 a
share, sharply exceeding Wall Street expectations of 58 cents a
share. Before Advanced Micro reported the results, its shares
closed at $68, down 31.25 cents. In after-hours trading, they
surged as high as $76. Analysts said the results could help
stabilize the Nasdaq and technology stocks in general, especially
if other companies meet or exceed estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro's growth was all the more startling on a day when
a key analyst reduced his estimates for Microsoft, citing slower
than expected personal computer sales.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's Denies It Fixed Prices
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's denied conspiring with its rival auction house
Christie's to fix commissions for buyers and sellers and asked a
federal judge to dismiss civil suits filed against them.
</P>
<P>
   Telstra to Acquire Wireless Stake
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century CyberWorks, which is acquiring Cable and
Wireless HTK, Hong Kong's local telephone company, said it would
sell 40 percent of the company's mobile phone business to Telstra,
the dominant phone company of Australia, for $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan Has a Record Profit
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan said that its first-quarter profit rose nearly 5
percent, to a record $628 million, thanks to robust investment
banking, trading and money management revenues.
</P>
<P>
   NTT Aims to Bolster Profits
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, the Japanese telecommunications
giant that has reorganized over the last year to become more
adaptable and profitable, announced further plans to better
position itself for an explosion in demand for Internet-related
services. The company acknowledged that the plan was long on vision
and short on details. ``There is nothing of substance here written
in this report,'' said Junichiro Miyazu, the company's president.
``But it shows we must start thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Union Members Oppose China Deal
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of steelworkers, truck drivers, auto workers and other
union members rallied on Capitol Hill and swept through the halls
of Congress in a show of muscle intended to block a trade agreement
with China.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund forecast that the global
economy, led by the persistently robust growth in the United
States, would expand at a 4.2 percent rate in 2000, its fastest
pace since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Offering Set for China Web Portal
</P>
<P>
   Sina.com, China's most popular Internet portal, is set to go
public in the United States later this week. But investors who buy
the stock will not own a stake in the company. Instead, they will
have a piece of Sina.com's offshore Web sites, a fraction of its
core business.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade Reports $23.2 Million Loss
</P>
<P>
   ETrade Group, the Internet brokerage firm, said that it lost
$23.2 million in its most recent quarter, reversing a profit in the
comparable period of 1999, but the results beat forecasts. Its
revenue more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Posts Quarterly Loss
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner reported higher earnings in most of its businesses
but still posted a net loss for the first quarter, mainly because
of a write-down for Columbia House.
</P>
</TEXT>
