<HEADER>
A5292 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CSECTION-RATES-TWOTAK     04-12 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSECTION-RATES-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALUE OF ELECTIVE CAESARIAN SECTIONS UP FOR DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Overland Park, Kan., obstetrician James
Mirabile has been getting requests from some pregnant patients
lately to have Caesarean deliveries, even though they have no
medical need for the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, the idea would have been medical heresy.
The nation's obstetricians were performing far too many Caesarean
sections, public health experts and insurance companies agreed. The
numbers had to come down.
</P>
<P>
   But Mirabile says he'd be willing now to entertain patients'
requests for elective C-sections.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they're aware of the risks associated with surgery
_ and this is major surgery _ you have to advocate for your
patient,'' he said. ``I think as more women become vocal about
their health care, as they look at alternatives, this is going to
become more popular.''
</P>
<P>
   What Mirabile's patients have asked for is becoming a topic of
impassioned debate among parents and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, the wisdom of elective Caesareans will be
debated at a two-day conference sponsored by Truman Medical Center
that will draw obstetricians from around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that women should be offered the choice of Caesarean
section is an extreme position for which there is no scientific
basis and no precedent in medical history,'' said Marsden Wagner, a
Washington perinatologist and former World Health Organization
official.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue in publications like the New England Journal of
Medicine that efforts to lower the Caesarean section rate may be
seriously injuring mothers and babies.
</P>
<P>
   Others even say an elective Caesarean is now no more hazardous
than a normal vaginal delivery and ought to be a woman's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other medical condition we give the patient the options
to deal with it. This is the only area where we deny the patient
the choice,'' said W. Benson Harer Jr., president-elect of the
American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of the procedure, it's the principle of a
woman's right to control her body,'' Harer said.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents say this idea is preposterous. Caesareans remain
risky operations that ought to be done only to maintain the
well-being of mother or infant. In most situations, vaginal
deliveries are far safer.
</P>
<P>
   Harer, chief of staff of Riverside County Regional Medical
Center in California, brought the elective C-section issue to the
fore in a front-page editorial in the current ACOG Clinical Review.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed that the risks, benefits and costs of Caesarean
section and vaginal delivery were so balanced that perhaps it was
time to give women the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Harer said recent research suggests vaginal deliveries could
cause pelvic damage that makes women more prone to urinary and
fecal incontinence, sexual problems and to a downward slippage of
the uterus called prolapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an enormous problem with older women with organ
prolapse and incontinence,'' he said. ``This frequently doesn't
show up until after menopause. The incidence is vastly higher in
women who have given birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said these kinds of risks, however, are most common among
women who have delivered four or more children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They exaggerate the possible risk of vaginal birth and they
underestimate the risk of Caesarean,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   In a Caesarean section, the baby is delivered through incisions
in the mother's abdominal wall and uterus.
</P>
<P>
   Common reasons for a Caesarean section include prolonged labor
in which the baby does not progress through the birth canal;
infections, such as herpes, that a mother can pass to her baby
during a vaginal delivery; and multiple births that make vaginal
delivery risky.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
