<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5295 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CSECTION-RATES-2NDTAK     04-12 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSECTION-RATES-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALUE OF ELECTIVE CAESARIAN SECTIONS UP FOR DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... make vaginal delivery risky.
</P>
<P>
   Woman who have C-sections run the usual hazards of major
surgery: infections, injury to internal organs, neurological damage
from anesthesia. The risk of death is significantly higher than for
a vaginal delivery.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to 1988, the rate of Caesarean sections in the United
States rose from 5 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors attributed the rise to fears of malpractice
lawsuits and to the frequent use of fetal monitors, which can
inaccurately indicate that a baby is in distress.
</P>
<P>
   As one of its Health People 2000 goals a decade ago, the
Department of Health and Human Services included lowering the
Caesarean section rate nationwide to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With Caesareans running an extra $3,000 in surgical costs per
delivery, the estimated savings by reaching that goal were $1
billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, the Caesarean rate inched steadily lower,
declining to 20.7 percent of all births in 1996. But new federal
statistics show the decrease may have bottomed out. By 1998, the
rate had crept up a bit to 21.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the efforts to lower the C-section rate may be harming
both mothers and babies, Harvard Medical School obstetrician
Fredric Frigoletto said.
</P>
<P>
   In an article last year in the New England Journal of Medicine,
Frigoletto and other health experts looked at relatively rare, but
potentially disastrous complications that may be occurring more
frequently as doctors perform fewer Caesareans.
</P>
<P>
   One potential risk is vaginal deliveries by women who have had
prior C-sections. Although vaginal births after Caesareans are safe
for most women, in about 1 percent of cases they can cause the
uterus to rupture along the surgical scar. The rupture could prove
fatal to the baby and require a hysterectomy for the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Frigoletto studied data from hospitals in four states and found
that uterine ruptures increased during the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   While the data don't include injuries to babies, Frigoletto said
that could be significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the fetal mortality rate is greatly understated,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frigoletto also found evidence that obstetricians are performing
more vaginal deliveries with forceps or vacuum extraction. The
stress can cause skull fractures and bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many babies need to be permanently damaged or lose their
life, how many women need to lose their reproductive capabilities
before the pendulum has swung too far?'' Frigoletto said.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner took issue with Frigoletto's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   In vaginal deliveries after Caesarean, the risk of uterine
rupture is significant only among women whose labor is induced by
drugs that cause intense contractions, Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   The risks of forceps and vacuum extraction, he said, have become
a problem because doctors use them too often.
</P>
<P>
   An issue rarely raised by physicians is the psychological effect
of Caesareans, said Anita Woods, president of the Kansas City
chapter of the International Caesarean Awareness Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of women come to ICAN because they are devastated.
They feel confusion, anger, disappointment,'' Woods said. ``Some
women use the word rape, feeling violated by so many interventions.
There is a complete loss of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' first child was delivered by Caesarean. Since then she
has had two vaginal deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not feel I gave birth to my first child,'' Woods said.``I
had my son surgically removed.''
</P>
<P>
   After 12 hours of labor, Woods had not completely dilated. Her
doctor told her she needed a C-section.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I was cheated,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Women who have asked obstetrician Mirabile about having a
C-section ``think it's an easier way to have a baby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The women usually lose interest in elective Caesareans after
learning insurance probably would not cover the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City, for example, will not
pay for a Caesarean section unless there is a medical reason for
it, said Frank J. DiTirro, the company's chief medical officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To proceed with Caesarean as a choice doesn't meet the
standard of medical care,'' DiTirro said. ``I would suspect the
majority of managed care companies and physicians would have a hard
time justifying it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
