<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO, ELIAN'S RELATIVES FAIL TO AGREE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Attorneys met late into the night Wednesday and the
letter from federal officials ordering the Miami relatives of Elian
Gonzalez to hand over the boy Thursday morning went undelivered for
a second day.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno traveled to Miami Wednesday to
personally seek cooperation in reuniting the 6-year-old with his
Cuban father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the father's lawyer to end the 4{ month
custody battle, Reno and U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service Commissioner Doris Meissner met for three hours with
Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, his attorneys and other
family members but ended the talks apparently without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Meissner left the meeting without issuing a statement.
But Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, at whose Miami Beach home the meeting
was held, said afterward that there had been no resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would like Juan Miguel to come here to meet with them and
to become reunited with each other,'' she said of the relatives'
bargaining stance. ``There was no letter handed over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no deadline but she (Reno) had made suggestions that
the family might travel to Washington tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Reno was continuing meetings late Wednesday with
the family's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said Elian, who was given over to his uncle after he
was rescued at sea on Thanksgiving Day, was present at the meeting.
Elian's mother was fleeing Cuba for the United States with Elian
when the boat they were in sank and she drowned.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington the father's lawyer, Gregory Craig, told
reporters: ``It is time for the Justice Department to instruct
Lazaro Gonzalez to follow the law and do the right thing. This son
needs his father.'' He said that while Juan Miguel Gonzalez had
come to the United States expecting to take custody of his child,
he had now been here for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Reno came to Miami with a letter instructing the family to bring
the boy to Opa Locka Airport north of Miami at 9 a.m. Thursday for
the trip to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they come to a cooperative agreement, then there might not
be a need for the letter,'' said Maria Cardona, U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   If no agreement could be reached, Reno was expected to
personally deliver the letter. Reno met with Gonzalez and his
daughter, Marisleysis, at O'Laughlin's home where they had sought
refuge and where a meeting between the boy and his two grandmothers
was arranged last January.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome of the meeting, U.S. immigration
officials expect the boy to be reunited with his father as early as
Thursday afternoon, perhaps in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's visit came after a bizarre turn of events Tuesday night
when U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., brokered a deal between
Craig, the attorney representing the boy's father, and the Cuban
American National Foundation, an anti-Castro group based in Miami.
At a Washington news conference late Tuesday, Jorge Mas Santos,
foundation president, announced that the great-uncle, two other
family members and Elian would travel to Washington Wednesday to
meet with the boy's father.
</P>
<P>
   Then, less then two hours later, Lazaro Gonzalez emerged from
his Little Havana home to announce to the small crowd of supporters
that he was canceling the trip because the boy did not want to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were certainly trying to facilitate this meeting happening
but we were not expecting to find Lazaro Gonzalez come out late
last night and call off the meeting,'' Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was greeted with shouts of ``Liberty for Elian'' from about
300 demonstrators who had gathered outside O'Laughlin's home. The
crowd was not overly hostile to Reno, though one woman held up a
sign that read, ``Janet Reno how can you decide Elian's future when
you killed so many children at Waco, Tx.``
</P>
<P>
   One demonstrator, Moses Delval, had mixed feelings about Reno's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very courageous for her to accept,'' Delval said. ``And
we are thanking her for that. I believe she is applying justice and
applying God's wisdom in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Saul Sanchez of the Democracy Movement, which has led a
campaign of civil disobedience in support of Elian remaining in the
United States, reiterated that Miami's Cuban exile community will
abide by the family's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have consistently asked the people that we must respect
what the family wants to do regardless of whether that is something
that is not what people have been advocating will happen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also faulted Elian's father for not coming to Miami to
meet with his relatives, and suspects that he has not done so
because of orders from Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
