<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5300 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PLANETRX-STOCKDROP-SF     04-12 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANETRX-STOCKDROP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PLANETRX SCARES INVESTORS  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR;   &LR; When PlanetRx said Wednesday it would have an
announcement after the markets closed, jittery investors assumed
the worst and hammered the online pharmacy's stock to an all-time
low.
</P>
<P>
   But the news turned out to be benign: The company said its
president, Michael Beindorff, would become chief executive, while
the current CEO, William Razzouk, would remain as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The stock's plunge _ it was down 20 percent on a day when Nasdaq
slumped 7 percent _ reflects Wall Street's increasing distaste for
e-tailers after weeks of hearing that various Internet stores are
on life support. Exacerbating Wednesday's reaction, earlier in the
day Web site Redherring.com reported that Healthshop.com, a San
Francisco holistic health site, was shuttering its e-commerce
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``B2C is dead on Wall Street,'' said Caren Taylor, vice
president at E-Offering, an online investment bank in San
Francisco. ``In this sort of market, people will believe the glass
is half empty, not half full.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor and others said that PlanetRx has some encouraging
developments coming up, while the CEO of Healthshop said he still
hopes to salvage his firm by finding a buyer or merger partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``PlanetRx is being painted with the same brush as other B2C
companies, even though it is an exceptional company with good
strategy and management,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at its current burn rate, the South San Francisco,
Calif., firm's money could dry up this year, she said. In the
fourth quarter, PlanetRx lost $52.17 million on $5.1 million in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Beindorff said the firm will work to moderate
its spending rate without sacrificing growth. ``We're not going to
take a machete and slice and dice everything we're doing,'' he
said. But even with belt-tightening measures, ``we're going to have
to deal with the financing issue sometime during the course of this
year,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Beindorff said the company's first-quarter results, to be
announced Tuesday, would reflect ``significant ramp-up'' from its
relationship with Express Scripts, a pharmacy benefits manager that
acts as the HMO middleman for prescriptions for 40 million
individuals. Express Scripts bought 20 percent of PlanetRx in
October and made the company its exclusive Internet pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   Beindorff also said PlanetRx is in ``intense negotiations'' with
potential brick-and-mortar partners. ``We have concluded a physical
distribution network is important to us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After falling $1 to $4, PlanetRx edged up 3 cents in after-hours
trading. Since hitting $26 the day after its October IPO, the stock
has fallen steadily. Rival Drugstore.com closed Wednesday at $8.25,
down $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   At Healthshop.com, CEO and founder Glenn Zweig said the board
had decided to discontinue selling products and lay off a
substantial number of its 70 employees.
</P>
<P>
   It is continuing to operate as a content site, offering
articles, personalized health programs and community services,
while it searches for a buyer or merger partner. ``We didn't want
to get to a point where there was no cash in the bank and we had to
file Chapter 11,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the site, initiated in January 1999, had attracted $31
million in backing _ including an investment by drug giant
Warner-Lambert _ running an e-tailer ``is an incredibly expensive
proposition,'' Zweig said. ``You have to look in the mirror and
say, `Are we there?' We decided it would be wiser to focus on
strategic alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
