<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-QACOLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: ENCRYPTION IS BEST BET FOR SENSITIVE DATA FILES  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: &LR;  I'm the ethics chairman at a local psychological &LR; 
 &LR; association. A psychologist's laptop, with case notes in it, &LR;   &LR; was
stolen. with case notes in it. It was password-protected, &LR;   &LR; thank
goodness. We, rightfully, have very strict codes &LR;   &LR; concerning
client confidentiality. But I'd like to know whether &LR;   &LR; the thief
can get into the protected material. And are there &LR;   &LR; other ways to
enhance security? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: You didn't mention what kind of password protection
you're using. If it's just the log-on password that comes with
Windows, I'm afraid I have bad news for you. That password is just
for individual settings so that more than one person can have a
personal desktop on the same computer. You can bypass the password
and access the desktop _ and the files _ simply by clicking cancel
in the log-on dialog box.
</P>
<P>
   To really protect your data files, you should encrypt them, just
like they do in the spy movies. There are lots of encryption
programs out there, ranging from shareware to industrial-strength
commercial products such as Network Associates' PGP, which stands
for pretty good privacy. (There's a free version of PGP, but it's
only for noncommercial use.) Once a file is scrambled with a good
encryption program, only the person who has the software ``key''
can decrypt it. And, trust me, a garden-variety laptop thief won't
be able to break the encryption.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Q: My company recently installed Office 2000. In each program
within the suite, the pull-down menus are truncated to show only
the most recently used functions. At the bottom of the menu, a
little, double-down arrow allows me to expand the menu and see all
the functions, but it's annoying. I want all of the available
functions in each pull-down menu to be shown at all times. Can I do
this?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Can you do this? Is Paris a city? To make expanded menus
the default, do this: Go to the Tools menu in any Office 2000
program and choose Customize. Now tab over to the Options page. In
the section on Personalized Menus and Toolbars, uncheck the box
labeled ``Menus show recently used commands first.'' Now click
Close. From now on, you'll see nothing but long menus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My PC at home is unable to play some of the more
graphics-intensive CDs like the new Disney ``Toy Story 2 Action
Game.'' I was told that my video card has only 2 megabytes of
memory, and the game requires 4. Does this mean I need a new video
card? If so, where can I get one, and can I install it myself? My
system runs on a Pentium II chip and Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: Video memory is just like regular computer memory. Every
time you think you have enough, somebody comes up with a product
that gobbles up more. Many of today's shoot-'em-up action games can
use 16 or even 32 megs of video memory.
</P>
<P>
   The video memory in your PC may be embedded on the motherboard,
or it may be on a removable video card. Either way, it may be
possible to simply add video memory, so the first thing to do is
contact the PC maker about that. If it's not possible to upgrade
the video you already have, then it's time to buy a new 3-D card _
which you can easily install
</P>
<P>
   Before you go shopping, though, open up your PC to make sure
there's a place to put the card. You'll need an open PCI or AGP
expansion slot (if you already have a video card, you can use its
slot. The PCI slots are the white ones, which all newer PCs have.
The AGP slot is smaller, usually black or brown, and it's located
just above the PCI slots. You may or may not have an AGP slot. If
you do, consider getting an AGP card, because they're designed for
high-speed graphics.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Don't like your keyboard? Why not replace it? Keyboards are a
snap to install _ you just plug them in and maybe load a little
software _ and a good one with the right ``feel'' to the keys can
make working on the PC a lot more comfortable. You can get
keyboards with special keys for quick access to the Internet and
your computer's entertainment features, such as the volume. And
there are several ergonomic keyboards on the market that may help
reduce the risk of stress injuries to your hands and arms. Basic
keyboards start at under $25 and go up from there.
</P>
<P>
   David Einstein is West Coast bureau chief of Forbes Digital
Tool. Got a question about computing? E-mail it to
 &LR; computers &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
