<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      04-12 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON CAMPAIGNS UPSTATE AS GIULIANI CATCHES YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHILI CENTER, N.Y. _ ``Rudy decided to cancel today,'' a News 10
television reporter, microphone in hand, shouted to Hillary Rodham
Clinton at a crowded news conference outside a diner here five
miles southwest of Rochester on Wednesday afternoon. ``Is it a
coincidence that you decided to come to Rochester?''
</P>
<P>
   It was not, though Clinton did not quite say that to the
reporter, Elizabeth Chernack of WHEC-TV in Rochester. Instead, the
first lady settled back to swing at this hanging curveball of a
question about Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's abrupt decision to scrap an
upstate campaign swing so he could attend the home opening game of
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm happy to be here,'' Clinton said. ``I have enjoyed
coming to the Rochester area talking about the issues. I'm going to
keep doing that. Traveling all over the state and as many places I
can, as many different settings, talking about what I would do in
the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady never quite stated it, but pretty much everything
she did here on Wednesday _ her fourth upstate visit in six days _
was intended as a reminder of which candidate for the U.S. Senate
had not shown up as promised. She fit in an interview with a
Buffalo News reporter who found himself with unexpected free time,
since Giuliani was not going to be around to interview.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly every opportunity, Clinton managed to slip into her
remarks the number of times she had been upstate and the places she
had visited. And Tuesday night, Clinton, who was supposed to visit
only Buffalo on this trip, added a quick trip to Rochester, which
was the second of two cities Giuliani was supposed to visit. She
stayed just long enough for a glass of iced tea and a sit-down chat
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   At Yankee Stadium, Giuliani brushed off questions about his
absence upstate, saying he had ignored the advice of political
advisers to do what he loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're just talking about raising money, we can raise money
anytime,'' Giuliani said. ``The Yankees don't open every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's schedule was to have included both fund-raisers and
lunches with women who support him.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady on Wednesday avoided a question about whether
she, too, wished she had been at the Yankee opener.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
