<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JDN-REALTY-2TAKES-NYT     04-12 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JDN-REALTY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS OF MANAGEMENT DOG JDN REALTY
</HEADLINE>
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First the founder was in charge. But then came an accounting
scandal, and he stepped aside _ sort of. Replacing him were two
executives: his wife and the man who oversaw accounting. But then
another accounting scandal became public on Wednesday, and they
stepped aside, too _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Who's running the company? A member of the board of directors
who has supposedly been overseeing the company's executives since
the day it went public in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   This is JDN Realty, an Atlanta real estate investment trust that
was one of the industry's most respected firms. It is also one of
the prime developers for Wal-Mart Stores. But in the last two
months, JDN disclosed that it had been making under-the-table
payments to its own executives, that it improperly billed its two
largest clients, that it defaulted on its loans and that it would
have to restate all of its earnings for five years. Law firms have
filed class-action lawsuits. Its stock has dropped 43 percent since
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you look into this, the stranger it gets,'' said
Patrick S. McGurn, a vice president at Institutional Shareholder
Services, which advises large investors on corporate governance
issues. ``There is so much wrong with this that it's almost the
plot for a satire.''
</P>
<P>
   Management experts say JDN's travails offer a case study of the
problems that can befall a public company that continues to operate
like a private one. And at a time when companies are going public
at a record rate, and many are flouting widely accepted management
guidelines, the lessons are particularly relevant. At the core of
JDN's troubles, corporate governance specialists say, is a board
that is too closely aligned with management to be an effective
advocate for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The directors are a small inbred group _ mostly men who have
business ties to JDN or personal ties to J. Donald Nichols, the
founder, and his wife, Elizabeth. Most have been board members
since the company went public in 1994. The board lacks a nominating
committee.
</P>
<P>
   JDN executives and board members declined to comment. A lawyer
investigating the company on behalf of the board said the directors
had responded aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interests of the shareholders have been paramount in their
minds,'' said John Latham, a partner at Alston &AMP; Bird in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   To analysts and investors, however, JDN's problems _
jeopardizing almost every relationship the company has and
undercutting its financial statements for five years _ are deep
enough that an independent board would have discovered them sooner.
Even after they become public, the company has reacted in ways that
have ensured bad news will continue to dribble out, the critics
say.
</P>
<P>
   In February, for example, Nichols was one of two JDN executives
on a conference call to analysts in which she emphasized that her
husband did not seem to have benefited personally from the
off-the-books payments. And Wednesday, the company said it would
not publish its 1999 earnings by the end of this week, violating a
two-week extension it had received from the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The company also acknowledged that the billing ``discrepancies''
with its two largest customers, Wal-Mart and Lowe's, a home
improvement retailer.
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed on Wednesday, Nichols resigned as
chairman, having already stepped aside as chief executive in
February, Latham said.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, as one of the two companies JDN wrongly billed for the
construction, leasing and sale of shopping malls, is concerned
about the latest disclosures, said Les Copeland, a spokesman for
the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime we have to pay something we shouldn't, we take that
very seriously,'' he said. If anything, Copeland added, ``We're
going to overreact to it and manage it very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   After setting up his own firm, Nichols got his first break by
helping Wal-Mart build a store near his boyhood home in Franklin,
Tenn. His real estate business expanded in the 1980s, thanks in
part to Wal-Mart's rise as the nation's biggest retailer. JDN went
public in March 1994, and its stock consistently outperformed other
real estate investment trusts, giving shareholders a 79 percent
return between January 1995 and January 2000. Real estate indexes
returned about 50 percent during that same period.
</P>
<P>
   JDN ``had a superior growth rate and a predictable earnings
stream,'' said Andrew Jones, a real estate analyst at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   The executives did it by establishing solid relationships with
retailers like Wal-Mart, Lowe's and Home Depot. JDN won a
reputation for finishing its projects on time and, seemingly, on
budget. Retailers, Jones said, ``will pay a little bit more for
predictability.'' In the highly leveraged real estate business, a
small amount of additional cash flow makes a big difference to
profits.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, JDN continued to operate with largely the same
board. Until Nichols resigned on Wednesday, it included him and his
wife, along with William B. Green, a bank and real estate executive
who knew the Nicholses from Tennessee, where the couple continue to
live; Craig Macnab, a Nashville financial executive who also once
worked at J.C. Bradford, where Nichols got his start, and one of
the underwriters of JDN's first stock sale; and Haywood D. Cochrane
Jr., a Nashville health-care executive who says he met Nichols
shortly before JDN's initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of the two directors who have joined in the last six years, one
is William G. Byrnes, a retired Alex. Brown executive whom Nichols
has praised for the role he played in JDN's public offering. The
other, Philip G. Satre, is the president of Harrah's Entertainment
and also has a Tennessee connection.
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence of the coziness between the directors and
executives, critics say, is the lack of a nominating committee.
Without one, the choice of directors often falls solely to the
chief executive. ``That in itself ends up leading to a lot of
cronyism on boards,'' said Ann Yerger, the director of research at
the Council of Institutional Investors.
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters of public companies in the United States have
nominating committees, according to a study by Korn/Ferry
International, a recruiting firm.
</P>
<P>
   But executives of many public real estate investment trusts,
known as REIT's, often continue to run them more like the private
firms they once were, governance specialists said. As REIT's have
stumbled, investors have turned more attention to their management
structures.
</P>
<P>
   At JDN, management experts said, a more independent board may
not have been able to prevent the off-the-books payments, but it
probably would have responded more forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 14, the company announced that two executives, Jeb L.
Hughes and C. Sheldon Whittelsey, had received $4.9 million in
payments that JDN's earnings statements did not reflect. Many of
the payments, the company said, were approved by Nichols. The
payments, which analysts said could have come in the form of cash
or real estate, ranged from 4 percent to 20 percent of JDN's annual
earnings between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols may have made the payments, Jones at Morgan Stanley
said, in an attempt to retain the executives at a time when private
real estate firms were doing much better, and paying more, than
public REIT's.
</P>
<P>
   The company offered no explanation, however. It did announce
that Nichols was stepping aside as chief executive but that he
would remain chairman, in charge of maintaining ``tenant
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   McGunn, the shareholder adviser, said the company should have
dismissed Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   Latham, the board's lawyer, said the directors chose to weigh
Nichols' mistakes against the importance of his ties to clients.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols' wife and chief financial officer, William J. Kerley,
then took over as co-chief executives, and the board began
investigating the payments, as well as searching for a chief
executive. On Wednesday, Kerley resigned, Nichols returned to her
job as company president, and the board named one of its members,
Macnab _ the former J.C. Bradford employee _ to the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors, meanwhile, are trying to figure out when
the next piece of news will come and what it will contain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5312 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DESKTOP-WEBSITES-SFCH     04-12 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESKTOP-WEBSITES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TAKING THE DESKTOP WITH YOU  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How many times have you gone on a business trip
and forgot to transfer some crucial files to your portable? Or
needed to look up a phone number or appointment time but lacked
access to a computer?
</P>
<P>
   A rapidly multiplying class of Internet sites aims to free you
from the constraints of traditional PCs and software by putting
office applications on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The names give the concept away _ nearly all include the word
``desk.'' Desktop.com, MyInternetDesktop.com, FreeDesk.com,
MagicalDesk.com, Visto.com and MyWebOS.com are just a few of the
entries.
</P>
<P>
   These sites typically offer online hard-disk space, e-mail,
calendar, address book, to-do lists and Web bookmarks. Some also
provide full office suites with word processors, databases and
spreadsheets. The key attraction for all is being able to access
your personal data anywhere you can connect to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While you might assume that since they are Web-based, these
sites are platform-independent, that is not quite true. You can
access most of them from any Windows, Mac or Linux computer, but
most require Windows to get full functionality, such as
synchronizing data with your desktop organizer. The truly versatile
sites also let you look up certain data from cell phones and Palms.
For example, Visto.com's address book, calendar and e-mail can all
be accessed from Web phones.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect that sales of information appliances will
overtake those of PCs within a couple of years, so the ability to
store personal data on the Web will grow rapidly in importance. To
allay concerns about sensitive information residing on a central
server, most of these services provide strong security safeguards
and privacy policies. However, their nature is such that anyone
with your password can access your data, so it's important to
change it frequently and not use common words.
</P>
<P>
   While these sites are usually supported by advertising, many
charge for premium services, such as disk space beyond the usual 10
or 20 megabytes, or a small monthly fee. MagicalDesk charges $5 a
month after a free trial period, which includes 20 MB of storage,
or $10 a month for 50 MB of storage. Visto.com, one of the oldest
and largest desktop sites with more than 800,000 users, offers 15
MB of free space and charges $25 per year for each additional 25
MB.
</P>
<P>
   How well do these sites work? It's hard to argue with the
concept of replacing PC-based application software with Web
equivalents that are always up-to-date, cost practically nothing,
and can be accessed anywhere. However, Bill Gates is in no danger
of losing his day job. The reality of the present offerings is that
they won't displace your application software any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Why? For starters, it usually takes many times longer to
accomplish a task on one of these sites than with regular software.
Just entering a contact or appointment requires clicking through a
bunch of forms, and having to log on to a site and go to the
bookmark page to add one bookmark to your list is just plain silly
when you can accomplish the same task with one click in your
browser. Furthermore, aggregating a wide variety of tasks (from
reading news to storing files) on one page generally means that
none of them are really done well. The Web applications are
rudimentary compared to their PC counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that it is unlikely that you will want to
integrate these sites into your daily routine until they improve in
performance and usability.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the best way to use them is to enter everything in your
usual computer-based personal information manager (PIM), such as
Microsoft Outlook or the Palm Desktop, and synchronize with the Web
version. You can then use the sites for reference while you're on
the road, without the hassles of entering data directly into the
Web site, or dealing with slow Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if there should be an Internet outage or slowdown
just when you need to look something up, you will be out of luck.
But on the whole, data stored on secured Web sites is probably
safer than on your PC (unless you are among the few who actually
back up files!).
</P>
<P>
   Here's an overview of some of the key players.
</P>
<P>
   Desktop.com
</P>
<P>
   Desktop.com is probably the most ambitious undertaking. Founded
by the team behind Four11 and RocketMail (since sold to Yahoo), it
aims to aggregate features of popular Web sites, such as shopping,
search, news and e-mail, with Web-based applications, all on one
platform. Third-party developers can also add applications to the
core set, extending its functionality.
</P>
<P>
   Users can customize their Desktop.com home page by choosing the
search service that will be attached to the search button, the
shopping and news sites that interest them most and so on. Any
needed passwords are stored for you _ a big convenience.
Desktop.com comes in two versions, an ``Express'' version that uses
only HTML for access from any platform, and a full version for
Windows only.
</P>
<P>
   MyInternetDesktop.com
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, MyInternetDesktop.com's claim to fame is that
it works with all major platforms and browsers, and soon on cell
phones and Palms. It doesn't require Java, ActiveX or plug-ins, the
technologies that usually cause compatibility problems. And it also
lets developers add on to its capabilities, like Desktop.com.
</P>
<P>
   That said, MyInternetDesktop's interface is among the least
visually appealing and most cumbersome to work with. The main page
has lists of applications, like e-mail, calendar and address book.
Clicking on these opens each in a separate window, which are easy
to get drowned in.
</P>
<P>
   Visto.com, MagicalDesk
</P>
<P>
   Our favorite sites were Visto.com and MagicalDesk. Both require
Windows to sync data, but they are relatively mature compared to
most sites in this category, and have the best user interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Visto.com emphasizes workgroup collaboration features, such as
file sharing, conference call setup, calendar sharing and so on. It
also offers cell phone access to your address book, calendar, to-do
list and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   MagicalDesk's applications are limited compared to those on most
of the other sites, but they are easy to get at, not to mention
easy to look at. The calendar is by far the easiest to read of all
the sites, and you can customize the display of the home page and
applications to suit your needs.
</P>
<P>
   MagicalDesk also offers MagicalViewer ($5 per month), a program
for Windows and Mac that lets you view 250 different file formats,
even if you don't have the original applications. This is great for
sharing files with others.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; FreeDesk, MyWebOS
</P>
<P>
   FreeDesk and MyWebOS are the two sites we looked at that offer
full office suites. Again, it is hard to imagine using these sites
for everyday work, as opposed to occasionally when traveling. For
example, printing a document in FreeDesk currently requires
downloading and then opening it with Microsoft Word or Excel. And
since both use their own document formats, exchanging files with
others requires importing and exporting, usually to Word or Excel.
</P>
<P>
   FreeDesk and MyWebOS are working hard to add features, but it
will be a long time before they can compare to mature PC-based
office applications.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest challenge for the office suite sites is probably
the coming competition from Microsoft and Sun. Sun's StarPortal
will offer Java-based apps, and Microsoft, of course, will have the
enormous advantage of file format compatibility.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that desktop sites are a great idea that has
yet to be well-implemented. The nature of the Internet is that
sites are thrown up before they are ready for prime time in order
to stake out the territory. They want to grab users before the big
portals, like MSN, AOL, Yahoo and Excite, get into the act.
</P>
<P>
   But the kitchen sink approach of the portals means that there
will still be a need for full-featured, well-designed desktop
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Waring (becky(AT)waring.org) is a Berkeley technology
free-lance writer and former editor of New Media magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
