<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-ZDNET-SFCH     04-12 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-ZDNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES: ZDNET SEES BLUE SKIES, DESPITE BREAKUP WITH
CORPORATE  PARENT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The newest Internet media powerhouse looks an
awful lot like an old one. San Francisco's ZDNet, cut loose in the
breakup of tech publishing titan Ziff-Davis, is now on its own.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost inevitable. Ziff-Davis had been lumbering along
with nearly $1.2 billion in debt. It was one of the first so-called
old media firms to issue a tracking stock for its Internet
property, and ZDNet immediately started outperforming its parent.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis then sold off its research division, its magazines,
its ZDTV cable channel and its trade shows (including Comdex), and
what was left was ZDNet: 400 employees around the world, including
160 in San Francisco, publishing one of the top 15 Web
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet will still license content from the former Ziff-Davis
magazines _ such as PC Magazine and SmartBusiness (formerly PC
Computing) _ that built its popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ZDNet faces questions about how it will survive without its
close ties to much of that content, as Shelby Bonnie _ newly
installed CEO of crosstown archrival Cnet _ is quick to point out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of advantages to the integrated Ziff-Davis
company,'' Bonnie said. ``It had publishing assets, online assets,
television assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The ZDNet team had excellent access to other parts of
Ziff-Davis, Bonnie said, and ``the lack of doing that has to be not
as advantageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rosensweig, the CEO of ZDNet, disagreed. ``I don't think
we've lost any of the benefits,'' he said. ``To me, we get the best
of all worlds under this scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does ZDNet keep the Ziff content, but ``what we get is
clarity,'' Rosensweig said, adding, ``clarity breeds a plan. A plan
breeds confidence, and confidence breeds success.''
</P>
<P>
   He proudly points out that ZDNet has already toted up six
consecutive profitable quarters, and he has no plans to follow
Cnet's move to dip into profits for a $100 million ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers on the Net can always be manipulated to make any
argument, but Bonnie makes a persuasive case for Cnet's lead in
traffic over ZDNet. Rather than looking to Media Metrix, which uses
a ranking methodology that rankles many Webmasters, Bonnie looks to
Securities and Exchange Commission filings. After all, the
companies have to stand behind their own numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In their most recent filings, which cited figures from December,
ZDNet boasted 371 million page views for the month, which worked
out to about 12 million per day. Cnet claimed 14.7 million page
views per day, which works out to 455 million for the month.
</P>
<P>
   Rosensweig declined to discuss the competition with Cnet
(although ZDNet Vice President Dan Farber notes that even with
Cnet's advertising blitz, ZDNet still posted 40 percent audience
growth from the fourth quarter over the third quarter).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rosensweig said ZDNet will focus on hammering away at
its mission of serving all tech audiences, from newbies to systems
professionals, and will continue to expand internationally.
</P>
<P>
   I met with Rosensweig last month in a borrowed office at ZDNet's
headquarters in the cavernous former fashion center at Eighth and
Townsend streets. ``This was my office at one moment in time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's based in New York, although he prefers to put it in a
more cyberspace-coy kind of phrasing: ``I am everywhere. I am a
piece of data, traveling over the transom.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means: He gets to San Francisco every couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL ITEMS, BIG DEMANDS: As a father on paternity leave, I
often must bring my baby, Harry, with me on assignment. The folks
at ZDNet were quite accommodating, taking turns holding the
6-month-old little guy while I interviewed Rosensweig.
</P>
<P>
   Rosensweig kept a cell phone the size of a cigarette lighter on
his desk, and it rang several times, interrupting us. Finally I
said, ``Isn't it funny how something so small can run your life?''
</P>
<P>
   Rosensweig pointed at Harry, and said, ``You tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   IMAGINE A SANDY BEACH: Brisbane, Calif.'s Imagine Media, the
publisher of Business 2.0 magazine, is on a major expansion drive.
Not only is Business 2.0 doubling in frequency and putting on
conferences, but the company is also launching five new magazines
starting this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to find people, like its competitors at magazines and
dot-coms throughout the Bay Area, Imagine decided that its best
corporate headhunters would be its own employees. It ran an
in-house contest, with the top prize being a trip for two to
Hawaii, for those workers who could recruit the most qualified
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were much more successful than we expected,'' said Steve
Leibman, vice president of human resources. The contest yielded 325
referrals in the first three months of this year, and 48 of those
people were hired. (All told, Imagine hired 105 people in the first
quarter.) New hires came at all levels, from entry level marketing
folks to the vice president for Business 2.0's online business
(that's Nicole Brown, who jumped from Red Herring).
</P>
<P>
   Although Imagine isn't publicly traded in the United States, its
parent company, the Future Network Plc, is on the London Stock
Exchange, and Imagine is thereby able to offer stock options _ a
crucial currency in today's mad recruiting world.
</P>
<P>
   The person who brought in the most applicants was herself a new
hire, Anika Cunningham, who started in December as marketing
manager for the forthcoming Revolution magazine. Revolution will
cover dance culture and technology and will launch July 5 (and is
not to be confused with two other new magazines of the same name _
one from Britain's Haymarket Group that will cover the digital
economy, and one that will serve nurses).
</P>
<P>
   With the zeal of a new convert, Cunningham referred 25 people to
Imagine recruiters; about half were interviewed and four were
hired. Three more are still in the interview process, and she
believes two are on the verge of getting offers.
</P>
<P>
   She's one of five employees who won the Hawaiian trip, and she's
heading there next month to celebrate her boyfriend's birthday. One
of the best perks of the prize: the week away doesn't count as
vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   The contest worked so well that Leibman is keeping it going in
the second quarter. The top five prize-winners will be finalists in
a drawing for a new lime-green Volkswagen Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE CONFERENCE: Red Herring does it. Industry Standard does
it. So, maybe to prove its chops as a New Economy magazine,
Business 2.0 is going to do it, too: Put on a conference.
</P>
<P>
   The conferences are generally wildly profitable, drawing hefty
fees from attendees as well as substantial sums from sponsors. But
do Internet economy execs need one more schmooze fest? ``You can go
to one conference a day and never work,'' concedes Michela O'Connor
Abrams, president of Imagine Media's Business Division.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, of course, believes her conference will be worth
attending. Attendance will be limited to 500 people, at $2,495 each
(that's $1.25 million right there), and Abrams plans to sign up 10
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the conferences can pose some ethical
quandaries for journalistic outfits, Abrams said Business 2.0's
October confab in Monterey will draw strict lines: Sponsors won't
get the right to speak or make presentations at the conference, and
the editorial team, led by magazine editor Jim Daly, will speak at
the conference and help determine the content of the panels.
</P>
<P>
   GROK THIS: A popular newsletter among media junkies is the
Industry Standard's Media Grok, which gives pungent critiques of
tech news from various outlets. On Monday, the Grok skewered ``old
media'' for awaiting ``the boom's bust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the sky falling yet?'' The Grok wondered. ``That's not a
story you'll find on new-media sites ...''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, really? Wired News on Tuesday led its page with the
headline, ``Why the Bubble's in Trouble.'' And doesn't the Grok
read the Industry Standard, which had a photo of a roller coaster
on its latest cover with the headline: ``The End of the Beginning:
After a gravity-defying run, the Internet business is falling back
to earth ...''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at fostd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
