u s BC-OLY-FUNDING-NYT     04-12 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FUNDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OLYMPIC SPORTS FACING CUT IN FUNDS 
BY RICHARD SANDOMIR  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A plan proposed by the new head of the U.S. Olympic Committee
would redeploy funds to sports that traditionally produce the
highest medal counts, while paring funds to less successful sports.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Blake, the chief executive and secretary general of the
USOC since February, will tell the organization's transition
committee of his plan. If it approves the proposal, Blake is
expected to present all or part of it to the 19-member USOC
executive committee on Friday. ``We have to look at the sports
where the payoffs would be the greatest,'' he said from Boston,
where he will outline his 30-page plan to the committees.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We're not cutting off any sport at the knees. This
is not a cold turkey situation. This will be phased in, and we've
done a lot of homework to understand the infrastructures that will
be needed to keep the sports viable. Some sports will get less
money, but it doesn't mean they won't get enough to survive or
sustain themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake refused to say which sports would endure financing cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ``Generally about half would benefit, half would
get less support.'' The USOC provides money to 45 national
governing bodies, 39 of which sanction Olympic sports. For the 1997
to 2000 Olympic quadrennium, the USOC will distribute grants
totaling $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get this money out of thin air,'' he said. ``We're
accountable to our sponsors to show we're spending the money
prudently.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake said there will be degrees of budgetary additions and
cuts, depending on an assessment of where the money would be better
spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've ranked sports by capability and medal potential,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He then added that he was looking at the national governing
bodies as ``business partners and the USOC as an investor in them.
We have a portfolio of sports to evaluate in terms of how best to
serve the American public's interest in terms of winning at the
games.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the intention was not to eliminate financing to any
sport, but to redistribute money ``without throwing the baby out
with the bathwater.'' He said the USOC will provide those national
governing bodies with less money with some help in improving their
fund-raising capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is destined to stir debate and rouse criticism. Blake
scoffed at a suggestion that by taking funds from underperforming
sports to enhance the medal potential of already strong sports, he
is fostering a front-runner view.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Williams, a 1968 Olympic biathlete who is the lawyer for the
U.S. Biathlon Association, said, ``We're hoping the leadership of
the USOC will support all sports on the Olympic program including
the sports that are underdeveloped so they'll come to achieve the
success of the developed sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake was hired with a mandate to provide broad change to the
USOC. Since February, he has reviewed the organization's operations
and management, looking to streamline the bureaucracy to make
decisions more timely and eliminate redundancies. As a result, he
is also expected to dismiss employees, most of them in middle
management.
</P>
</TEXT>
