<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYING-STUDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE LESSON AT COLUMBIA: NO LYING TO PROFESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wasn't quite the end of Western Civilization, but
when a Columbia University student lied to get out of his homework,
it did turn into a federal case.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the student is losing.
</P>
<P>
   According to a court ruling published on Wednesday, the student,
Puneet Bhandari, was taking Contemporary Civilization, a required
survey of Western thought from Plato to Marx. It is a demanding
course with lots of reading. Bhandari apparently found the pace
rough.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1998, he came to his professor, Gregory J. Downey
Jr., to ask for more time, wrote Judge John G. Koeltl of the
Southern District Court in a March 24 ruling that was printed
Wednesday in The New York Law Journal. The student told his
professor that he and his brother, Parag, had been in a car that
was struck by a drunken driver. Parag was on life support, the
student said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, he told his teachers that his brother had died.
</P>
<P>
   Downey gave Bhandari all the time he needed, and ultimately he
finished the course. His misfortune brought teacher and student
closer, the judge said, and when Bhandari began applying to medical
school last year, he asked Downey for a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The professor said on Wednesday that he was happy to oblige and
wrote a glowing letter that spoke of how well this good student had
coped with his brother's difficult death. It was the letter that
finally unraveled what the judge called Bhandari's ``egregious''
and escalating lies.
</P>
<P>
   A medical school interviewer asked about his brother, and
Bhandari said he was doing well as an investment banker. Puzzled,
officials at the unnamed medical school inquired at Columbia.
Bhandari acknowledged that he had lied, the judge wrote, and he was
ordered expelled. He appealed to the dean of Columbia College, who
reduced the punishment to a two-year suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Still unhappy, Bhandari _ by now a senior only months from
graduation _ asked the court to block the suspension with a
preliminary injunction. The judge sided with Columbia. ``Mr.
Bhandari's conduct reflected substantial dishonesty over a
prolonged period in dealing with a professor,'' Koetl wrote in a
ruling that dealt only with the injunction.
</P>
<P>
   Bhandari's lawyer, Arthur R. Block, said on Wednesdayy evening
that he could not discuss the case without speaking to his client,
who was not available. A Columbia spokesman said that Bhandari was
no longer registered but that the university could not comment on
the case because it was still in litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Downey said on Wednesday that he was still unnerved by the
experience, which has made him more suspicious of students and
their excuses. ``Some students will fudge, and some students will
ask for extensions with no story, but I've never seen anything like
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was still not sure if Bhandari has a brother. ``I
have no idea what parts of the story he made up,'' the professor
said. ``It's an amazing case to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000412.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5318 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-12 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET MIGHT BE KEY TO KINGS' SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their last playoff memory was the lowering of a broom that swept
them into summer. But they bristle at the notion it could happen
again. Not this year, with a new coach and a new system that a lot
of the same players have embraced like religion.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Los Angeles Kings are a lot like the Lakers, only minus
the tsunami-sized expectations. Never mind that Stephane Fiset has
been as dominant as Shaquille O'Neal down the stretch, no one is
conceding the Stanley Cup trophy to the Kings, who open the
playoffs today at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, first-year coach Andy Murray's minions aren't even
favored to skate into the second round. On paper, the best-of-seven
series against the Red Wings shapes up as a mismatch on par with
Erin Brockovich vs. PG&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit is so deep it has a former league MVP, Sergei Fedorov,
centering its third line. Detroit is so deep the Kings may have to
split up their dynamic defensive duo of Rob Blake and Mattias
Norstrom to try to adequately cover the Red Wings' giant of an
offense.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Kings' claim to fame is they've made the playoffs
in two of the past three years, Detroit can boast of winning two of
the previous three Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit may have history and His Coaching Excellency, Scotty
Bowman, on its side. But we like the Kings' chances because of
Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   He was a nail in the Red Wings' wheel during the regular season,
posting a 2-0-1 record against them. In those games, Detroit
outshot the Kings 102-72 but was outscored 10-6. Fiset's .941 save
percentage against Detroit was proof of what he is capable when he
gets into a tread-sized groove.
</P>
<P>
   A bad wheel took Fiset out of circulation for two weeks in
March. But since returning to action March 23 from a left groin
strain, Fiset has been like cellophane wrap around the goal mouth.
</P>
<P>
   In his last seven appearances, he stopped 185 of 198 shots for a
.934 save percentage. Not coincidentally, the Kings were 4-0-3 in
those games on their way to a momentum-making 5-1-3 finish.
</P>
<P>
   When Fiset makes a stop, it has the same effect as O'Neal
swatting an opponent's shot. It sets the offense in gear and wears
on the opposition. Not to take anything away from Chris Osgood, who
tended the net nicely for Detroit during its 1998 title run, but
the Kings like their goaltender in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two weeks is probably the best I've seen him play,''
said Kings defenseman Rob Blake of Fiset, a member of the Colorado
team that won the 1996 Stanley Cup crown.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Fiset's final seven starts came on the road, so it's
doubtful a jolting Joe Louis crowd will unnerve him much. As
focused as Fiset looked Tuesday during the Kings' final practice
before departing L.A., live octopuses couldn't faze him.
</P>
<P>
   The way Fiset was snaring pucks, it appeared he was the one with
eight arms. ``There wasn't a shot he wasn't trying to get out
there,'' Blake said. ``It didn't matter how out of position he was,
he was trying to make the stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``You respect guys who give their all like that every time
they're on the ice,'' Blake added. ``When you see that, you don't
want to let the guy down.''
</P>
<P>
   We're counting on Blake playing much better than he did two
years ago against St. Louis. He contributed nary a goal in that
four-and-out first-round series. It says here he's primed to show a
network audience that Nicklas Lidstrom isn't the best blueliner on
the ice and in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Norstrom, we're not worried about. He's the Kings' answer to the
Red Wings' Chris Chelios: Smart, steady and with stamina to spare.
He was the only player on the team to appear in every game this
year, and he led all the Kings' defensemen in plus-minus at
plus-22.
</P>
<P>
   We're expecting a Kevin Elster-like hat trick from Ziggy Palffy,
who should be nice and rested after sitting out the last 12 regular
season games with a sprained shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope his shoulder is healed because he's going to have to
carry the weight of the Kings' scoring load. Of course, after four
full and (futile) seasons of trying to get to the playoffs with the
New York Islanders, Palffy, 27, ought to be able to do double
shifts on adrenaline alone.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille is no stranger to the playoffs, but the 14th-year
veteran does need to re-acquaint himself with the back of the net.
After collecting 24 points during a torrid 15-game point-scoring
streak that ended March 2, Robitaille mustered just four goals in
the final 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille is the franchise leader in postseason game-winning
goals with eight, so he has the muscle memory to make Osgood's life
miserable. If he can't, it may not matter in the end how well Fiset
plays in the net.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this is not the same Fiset whose confidence was
shaken two years ago, first by the St. Louis skaters and then by
then-Kings coach Larry Robinson, who benched him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we can beat them,'' Fiset said, speaking of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings can steal one of the first two games in Detroit,
it's not at all a distant possibility. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
