</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SEXCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSEMBLY ASKS TOUGHER PENALTIES IN SEX CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A proposal that would toughen penalties for
sexual assaults and provide more relief for victims was unveiled on
Wednesday by Assembly leaders, six years after the Senate first
tried to muster support for similar legislation and four years
after Gov. George Pataki joined the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by advocates for victims' rights, the speaker of the
Assembly, Sheldon Silver, outlined a plan that basically addresses
the same issues as those earlier efforts. Both versions would
increase mandatory sentences for a range of sex crimes, including a
maximum life sentence for a person convicted a second time of
sexual relations with a minor, and would eliminate the option of
bail after conviction for a sex-related felony.
</P>
<P>
   But the Assembly's plan also goes a step further by calling for
such costly measures as specialized training for nurses who examine
victims, guaranteed financing every year for rape crisis centers,
more treatment in prison for sex offenders and closer supervision
after their release. It also seeks to increase penalties for people
who entice their victims on the Internet
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a comprehensive bill that goes far beyond what
passed the Senate in terms of its treatment of the Internet, in
terms of its treatment of victims, in terms of its reaching out for
all aspects and all people involved in this field,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has submitted sexual assault legislation every year since
1997, and the Senate has passed it every year. In addition, the
Senate passed its own bills on sexual assaults in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the governor has proposed several minor amendments,
and Senate leaders said they expected to pass it again.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Quartararo, a spokeswoman for Pataki, said they were
pleased that the Assembly leaders had decided to take action.
``We're looking forward to seeing the Assembly bill,'' she said.
``We're hopeful the legislature is serious about comprehensive
sexual assault reform, because it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Senate aides cautioned that the Assembly had not yet
finalized its plan in a written bill, they said the differences
between the two proposals appeared to be minor and could be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will agree to a bill before the year is out,'' said
Sen. Dale Volker, a Republican from the Buffalo area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
