<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLEAN-BUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TO SPEED CONVERSION OF BUSES
</HEADLINE>
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Metropolitan Transportation Authority and New
York state lawmakers struck a deal on Wednesday that will move the
city's bus fleet _ by far the largest in the country _ much more
quickly away from diesel power and toward cleaner-fuel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The deal represents the most sweeping environmental change in
the history of New York City's transit system, a change long sought
by legislators and clean-fuel advocates and one that many other
U.S. cities have already made.
</P>
<P>
   It came after Democrats in the State Assembly, joined later by
Republicans in the Senate, pressured Gov. George Pataki and the MTA
to make greater strides to clean up emissions from buses, which are
believed to contribute to asthma and other health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said that disagreements over how many compressed
natural-gas buses and so-called electric hybrid buses the MTA would
buy over the next five years had become a major sticking point in
negotiations over how to divide $3.8 billion from a transportation
bond act that will be presented to voters in November. About $1.5
billion of that amount is to go to the MTA.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, about 44 percent of all buses bought in the
agency's next capital plan will be powered by natural gas or
hybrid-electric technology, in which the wheels are driven by
electric motors that draw their current from a small diesel engine
on board.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement raises the total number of buses the MTA will buy
over the next five years to 1,257 from 1,056. In all, the purchases
will expand the fleet by a little fewer than 100 buses, after buses
are retired and replaced. Officials say the overall capacity of the
bus system will increase about 11 percent, because of plans to buy
more of the large express buses, which provide service between
Manhattan and Staten Island, Brooklyn and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the 11 percent increase in seats, overcrowding
will probably continue to plague the system because bus ridership
has increased 38 percent from 1996 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement does not move New York nearly as far as many other
large cities, like Los Angeles, Atlanta and Tempe, Ariz., which
have stopped buying diesel buses. Even so, environmentalists hailed
the changes because of the influence New York City's huge fleet has
on bus manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a clear message to the entire diesel industry that it
needs to eliminate its toxic soot emissions or it will be out of
the bus business in New York,'' said Richard Kassel, a senior
lawyer for the Natural Resources Defense Council, which has been
pushing for an end to diesel buses.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also agreed to install special pollution traps, by
2003, on the exhaust pipes of every diesel bus in its fleet _ more
than 3,000 vehicles _ and to use very low-sulfur fuel in the tanks
of all diesel buses. MTA also promised to speed up the retirement
of older diesel buses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
