<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BARAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BARAK'S PATH TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, April 13:
</P>
<P>
   Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, is engaged in an intricate
balancing act involving the three main elements of his quest for a
Mideast peace settlement. As negotiations with Syria have stalled,
and with Israel's July deadline for withdrawal from Lebanon
nearing, Barak has sensibly shifted his attention to reaching
preliminary agreement with the Palestinians on a peace deal. His
four-hour meeting with President Clinton Tuesday night should help
energize this new negotiating push.
</P>
<P>
   The two men agreed on an accelerated meeting schedule and a
stronger American presence at the bargaining table. Next week
Clinton will meet with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat. Barak
returns to the United States in late May, shortly before the target
date for an agreement outlining settlement terms on boundaries,
Palestinian statehood, provisions for Palestinian refugees and
Jewish settlements and the future status of Jerusalem.
Working-level talks on these issues are going on outside
Washington. Direct American participation will make it easier to
bridge some of the gaps between the two sides. But the hard
decisions must come from Barak and Arafat. Clinton should use his
meeting with Arafat to press for direct talks between the two
leaders next month.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Clinton also discussed ways to smooth Israel's
departure from Lebanon, which now appears likely to take place
without a Syrian agreement. Barak hopes to minimize the risks by
following the withdrawal provisions of a U.N. resolution that the
Arab world has long endorsed. Israel deserves U.N. cooperation,
including an enhanced role for U.N. peacekeepers in the border zone
Israel will be vacating.
</P>
<P>
   As the Palestinian talks quicken and the withdrawal date from
Lebanon approaches, Israel will be counting on strong support from
the United States. If a peace agreement is eventually signed with
Syria, considerable new American financial aid will be required to
carry out its provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Israel is now needlessly complicating its relations with the
White House and Congress by persisting in its plan to sell an
advanced AWACS airborne radar system to China. The Pentagon rightly
worries that Beijing may one day use this system to support
aggressive military action across the Taiwan Strait. Conceivably,
the airborne radar could be used to track and target American
fighter planes patrolling the strait. Israel should defer to
American objections and freeze delivery of the Awacs-equipped
planes. Barak needs to concentrate his energies on negotiating
peace, not courting unnecessary conflicts with Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-00 2356EDT &QL; 
